<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITEMS ON KLEINFIELD'S COURTING PATRICIA LOTT, TIFFANY DUBIN LEAVING
SOTHEBY'S FOR INTERNET IPO, AND GIFT GIVING IN THE FASHION
INDUSTRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patricia Lott, the wife of the Senate majority
leader, Trent Lott, is not known in Washington circles as an
omnipresent social force. This seems of little concern to the new
owners of Kleinfeld's, the Brooklyn wedding-gown emporium, which
has asked her to become a paid consultant to the company.
Kleinfeld's, which specializes in bridal wear and has long
attracted the great cross-section of those about to wed _ from
teenage Hasidic girls in Williamsburg to late-marrying lawyers
occupying TriBeCa lofts _ is seeking to expand to the nation's
capital and wants Mrs. Lott to help them to better understand the
city's evening-wear scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a lot of knowledge of special-occasion dressing,''
said Mara Urshel, Kleinfeld's president and a partner in the KBC
Operating Co., which owns the business. Mrs. Lott was introduced to
Kleinfeld's by another member of the partnership, Clay Hamner, a
North Carolina-based real estate developer. ``Through Clay, we've
met a lot of the Republicans,'' explained Ron Rothstein,
Kleinfeld's chief executive. (Another partner in the venture is the
actor Wayne Rogers.)
</P>
<P>
   John Czwertacki, the senator's press secretary, said that Mrs.
Lott is seriously considering the offer and that she may well begin
her duties in January. A few weeks ago, she toured Barneys New York
on Madison Avenue with one of the store's buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Fran DeWine, the wife of Sen. Mike DeWine of Ohio and a good
friend and former neighbor of Mrs. Lott, said that Mrs. Lott has
``always had a real flair for fashion.'' Mrs. Lott used to make
porcelain dolls and dress them, Mrs. DeWine recalled, adding that
Mrs. Lott has some retail experience: she sells dressy suits, of
the sort a Washington spouse might wear, out of her home. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHIFT AT SOTHEBY'S  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ Tiffany Dubin, whose tenure as the first head of
Sotheby's fashion department helped to confer a new status on
clothes once simply thought of as old, has abandoned her post. Ms.
Dubin, the stepdaughter of Sotheby's chairman, A. Alfred Taubman,
has taken a job as a vice president of the Auction Channel, a
planned cable television channel that, as its name suggests, will
hold auctions. The channel is an offshoot of an existing Internet
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has chic IPO potential,'' Ms. Dubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubin, who resigned from Sotheby's last week, raised
$140,000 in her last sale of vintage cocktail wear.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubin, who was given no advertising budget to promote her
sales and used what she called ``guerrilla tactics'' to gain
attention for them, said that Sotheby's will now give the fashion
department such a budget. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOLIDAY GIFT-GIVING  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This week messengers who work the orbit of the
fashion world may find themselves especially busy. In the coming
days, fashion houses will begin sending their holiday gifts to
select fashion editors, ``a chance,'' as one publicist put it, ``to
say thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Rowley, who in the past has sent gifts like cashmere
sweaters, is sending editors Champagne and horseshoes (for good
luck, evidently). Last year, Michael Kors sent silk sweaters, but
he is keeping this year's gift a secret. Jil Sander, as she did
last year, is sending donations on behalf of the editors to a
German children's charity.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion editors invariably say that the industry's lavish gift
giving, with items often valued at $100 or more each, has no
bearing on future news coverage. (The New York Times' policy for
reporters and editors is that gifts valued at more than $25 are to
be returned.)
</P>
<P>
   The trend for sending charitable contributions as opposed to
liquor or clothing was popular earlier in the 1990s, a publicist at
a major fashion house said, but has since fallen out of favor. ``It
is my general perception that people aren't into it,'' she added.
``They want trinkets.''
</P>
<P>
   Prada is one company that does not indulge in holiday
gift-giving, on the grounds that the company displays its
generosity throughout the year, said Jennifer Pinto, a spokeswoman.
After its spring show in Milan a few months ago, it presented some
editors with handbags from the new line. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
