<SLUG> BC-LEAKES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAKS HAUNT ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GONDERINGER  
 and CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leaks from more than 3,000 underground gasoline storage tanks
continue to haunt Arizona, despite years of work and an investment
of $127 million in taxpayer money.
</P>
<P>
   Suspected or known causes of cancer have found their way into
Arizona's groundwater in at least 600 cases, but rarely have they
contaminated the state's drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   So Arizonans face the question: Is the cleanup worth even higher
taxes? The state auditor general is calling for the Legislature to
raise a tax on gasoline to hasten the effort. At the same time, a
governor's committee is looking at whether the taxpayer-funded
cleanup program should even remain in existence.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Quality says it is making
steady progress, and is drastically reducing the chances that more
leaks will occur.
</P>
<P>
   Leaking underground storage tanks are an American legacy of the
automobile. They're near homes, schools, restaurants, lying beneath
gas stations and auto shops, even dairies and orchards.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has confounded state agencies from California to New
York. So far, few lives have been threatened, causing some critics
to question the need for so many cleanups. But other experts worry
that so many leaks have affected so much groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is tremendous,'' said Joseph Gonzalez, appointed
several years ago to then-California Gov. Pete Wilson's committee
on underground storage tanks. ``You don't know where it is, where
it goes. I think the agencies are just overrun. I was flabbergasted
at the amount of chemicals out there contaminating potential
sources of drinking water.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider metropolitan Phoenix: At Indian School and 40th Street,
contamination lurks below three corners of the intersection.
Similar plumes were found beneath a Unocal station on West Broadway
Road in Tempe. &QL; 
OTHER HAZARDS FOUND &QL; 
Other hazards were found years ago, yet still haven't been removed.
In Mesa, for example, contaminants seeped into the groundwater at a
city service yard near Mesa Drive and Sixth Street in 1990 and
1991, eventually spreading at least 800 feet to the east.
</P>
<P>
   A state audit released in November says the backlog of unpaid
claims for cleanups rose to $55 million at the end of June 1999
from $48 million in October 1997 _ suggesting the Department of
Environmental Quality is falling farther behind in its effort to
fix the mess. The audit urges legislators to increase an existing 1
cent per gallon tax on gas that has raised money to pay for the
cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Republic'' reported in 1988 that at least 200
underground storage tanks and pipes had leaked more than 700,000
gallons of gasoline, oil and other petroleum products into the
Phoenix area's soil and groundwater. Since then, the number of
known leaks has increased steadily _ partly because of better
methods of detection and partly because tanks continued to leak. &QL; 
COMPLEX, COSTLY PROBLEM &QL; 
In Arizona and other states, dealing with the problem has turned
out to be more complex and costly than anyone could have predicted.
Arizona officials initially thought they'd have the problem under
control by Dec. 31, 1999. But hundreds of leaks continue to be so
severe that several feet of gasoline float atop groundwater.
Sometimes, it's the same groundwater tapped by wells for drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
   Added to that, new research shows that chemicals in gas can
``evaporate'' through the ground and penetrate concrete,
potentially leading to a health risk in the air inside a building
that sits over contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only takes a trace amount over a long period of time to
constitute an unacceptable health risk,'' said Patrick Wilson, a
toxicologist for the EPA in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   RISK STILL SLIM &QL; 
The good news is that the chances of coming in contact with the
dangerous chemicals remain small.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of MTBE, gasoline spills don't move as fast
or spread as far as other hazardous chemicals. Also, gas floats, so
even a sizable spill can sit atop groundwater and not taint water
tapped by a well a bit deeper. It also makes gas easier to clean
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as nasty substances that leak into the environment go,
gas is very forgiving,'' said Phil McNeely, manager of the
Department of Environmental Quality's program that works to clean
up underground storage tank leaks.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean it's safe. In Fountain Hills, one benzene
and MTBE-filled leak seeped into the groundwater and into a
neighborhood wash where children played.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, an underground garage at an office building at
Central Avenue and Camelback Road became flooded with water that
emitted noxious fumes. Builders didn't realize a gas station that
occupied the site before them had left a legacy of contaminated
soil and groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   Near Tuba City, in northeastern Arizona, residents of a Hopi
village worry that a creeping spill threatens sacred springs and
other water sources they rely on for survival and religious
ceremonies. &QL; 
CONTAMINATED WELL &QL; 
In the central Arizona community of McGuireville, Dave and Virginia
Womack turned on their kitchen faucet in 1997 to make tea. They
stopped when they noticed a funny smell and taste. Turns out the
well they'd been drawing drinking water from for 20 years had
become contaminated by leaking tanks at two nearby convenience
stores. Tests found unacceptably high levels of benzene.
</P>
<P>
   Though neither got sick, they worry someday they might.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows whether we drank any of those chemicals before they
got so bad we could smell them,'' Womack said. The couple is suing
for $500,000 in Yavapai County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   McGuireville is the only place in Arizona where drinking-water
wells have been shut down over contamination. But with the sheer
number of leaky tanks, it might not be the last.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Department of Water Resources estimates there are
50,000 drinking-water wells across the state, mostly in rural
areas. Permits for 3,500 new ones are expected to be issued next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Underground tanks became such a problem because for decades,
they were made of steel, which corrodes easily. Spills sat
unchecked for years. It wasn't until the mid-1980s that the EPA
began requiring states to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we can't see something, we often don't know about it
until it becomes a severe problem,'' said Lester Kaufman, chief of
the underground storage tank program for the EPA's regional office
in San Francisco. &QL; 
TANKS REGISTERED &QL; 
Arizona began the laborious task of registering the 26,860 tanks in
the state, and began making inspections every few years. Tank
owners were asked to report any leaks and start costly cleanups.
They then would be reimbursed for some of the costs _ today, as
much as 90 percent _ with money generated mostly from the gasoline
tax.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, there have been 7,500 reported leaks in the state.
About 4,400 have been cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   That's about 58 percent, close to the national average, Kaufman
said. He applauds the work of the Department of Environmental
Quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their program really is a good one, especially on the
prevention side. They have some of the best inspectors around,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's environmental groups have not rallied to the cause of
cleaning up underground storage tanks. The risks pale next to more
sinister problems, such as state Superfund sites and air pollution,
said Sandy Bahr, conservation outreach coordinator for the local
chapter of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are bigger public health threats out there. But still,
you don't want to be drinking gasoline,'' she said. &QL; 
MANY INEFFICIENCIES FIXED &QL; 
And despite the auditor general's criticisms, the report last month
says many inefficiencies in the underground storage tank program
have been fixed. New rules are in the works that will ensure less
money is spent on sites that don't pose as much of a threat. Sen.
Rusty Bowers, R-Mesa, estimates that a third of cleanups in the
state haven't really been necessary to protect human health.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the sheer number of these leaks, you just can't monitor
every single one, clean up every single molecule,'' the EPA's
Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, tank owners around the country were required to
upgrade their equipment to more leak-proof standards as of Dec. 22,
1998. Arizona has checked on 775 tanks so far, and has found 95
percent in compliance. The agency ruled 900 leaks officially
cleaned up this year, but 450 new ones were added to the stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, we dramatically decrease the likelihood that
future leaks will happen,'' said Al Johnson, ombudsman for
Arizona's underground storage tank program.
</P>
<P>
   That's welcome news to Dave Womack, who hasn't enjoyed hauling
water ever since he and Virginia were forced to close their
contaminated McGuireville well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that you just take for granted, that
you turn on your faucet and good water will come out.'' &QL; 
Lisa Gonderinger can be reached at &QL; 
lisa.gonderinger(at)azrepublic.com or at (602) 444-7967. Chris
Fiscus can be reached at &QL; 
chris.fiscus(at)azrepublic.com or at (602) 444-7942. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
