<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUCCANEERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNGY AND BUCCANEERS KEEP THEIR COOL, AND KEEP ON WINNING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ It was the third quarter in the Detroit
Lions-Tampa Bay Buccaneers battle here on Sunday and John Lynch was
on the bench, gasping for air, squelching the pain. Lynch injured
his left knee two games earlier, against Seattle, and it had nagged
him since. Now it seemed ready to blow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing with it hurting for a while, but then I got
caught in a pile and twisted it and it hurt so bad,'' said Lynch, a
persistent playmaking safety now in his seventh Bucs season. ``I
did not have the full range of motion for a minute. They were
checking me to make sure it was just a strain. I really didn't
know, but I did know I had to get back out there. There was so much
at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   First place in the National Football Conference Central was at
stake. So was a chance to earn a 9-4 record and trail only the St.
Louis Rams (11-2) in the NFC/ It was a chance for Tampa Bay to win
six straight in the regular season for the first time in team
history. An opportunity to gain respect, confidence, momentum, all
of the ingredients that a team yearning to make a playoff sprint in
January must exhibit in December.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch would play through the pain. His team crept within range.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs trailed Detroit, 16-9, early in the fourth quarter.
Then the offense scored a touchdown. And then Lynch, with 5 minutes
7 seconds left, made an interception and returned it 28 yards to
the Detroit 24 to set up the winning score.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay won, 23-16. No, actually, in trailing for all but the
final 4:18, Tampa Bay persevered. Kept in range. Then overcame.
</P>
<P>
   That was the theme that helped save the Bucs' season _ keep in
range and stay in view. After their first seven games, they were a
3-4 team apparently heavy on defense, light on offense and in a
confused state at quarterback, where Trent Dilfer had labored. They
opened the season with a loss at home to the Giants, beat
Philadelphia and Denver, and then lost consecutive division games
at Minnesota and at Green Bay. They beat Chicago, lost at Detroit
and _ it seemed to happen so quickly, so suddenly _ they were an
ugly 3-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year Minnesota was 15-1 and nobody in our division could
catch them,'' Tony Dungy, Tampa Bay's head coach, said. ``This year
was not like that. Everybody was close and we felt like after
starting 3-4 that if we could just get in range that it would pay
off later. We knew that the teams ahead of us in our division _
Minnesota, Detroit and Green Bay _ would all have to come to our
place in December. We took the mind-set that the next game was the
most important game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dungy did not panic. He could have benched players, cut players,
thrown out schemes and ripped his team to shreds.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said: ``A lot of times you take on the personality of your
leader. Rather than complicate things, coach simplified things,
emphasizing what we do well. When you see the leader not panic and
just chip away at being successful, you follow that. Personally,
this season I concentrated on my abilities, on my confidence, and
then tried to make that jump from being a good player to becoming a
great one by just trusting my instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay trusted its instincts as a team.
</P>
<P>
   Dilfer returned from a benching before Week 8 to start the
winning streak with better play, but then he was injured in the
Seattle game. Shaun King, the rookie quarterback from Tulane,
entered, helped beat Seattle and then in the last six days, in his
first two pro starts, beat Minnesota and Detroit. Both games were
against teams that entered tied with Tampa Bay for first place in
the NFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept grinding through the rough spots early in the
season,'' King said. ``We were 3-4, but we knew among ourselves
that we had a good team. Coach Dungy has a quiet confidence about
him, and it is easy to buy into the fact that he knows what it
takes to win. He said: `Follow our system, do what we do, don't
worry about the outside. Keep all 58 on the ship, nobody hanging on
a rope overboard.' He was right.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tampa Bay is now ripe. King gives the Bucs a winning
presence and more athleticism at quarterback. The defense is nasty,
sometimes dominating. ``It is hard not to excel in this defense
because so many guys are making plays and you want to be a part of
it,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay plays at Oakland on Sunday, then plays host to Green
Bay and ends at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year late in the season we had to win and hope somebody
else would lose so we could make the playoffs, which we didn't,''
Dungy said. ``This year we can win a playoff spot if we beat
Oakland. We can win the division if we win our last three games.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a long way from being a sour 3-4 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an electric atmosphere in the organization and in
the community over what has taken place, but we are keeping our eye
on the ball,'' Lynch said. ``During this winning streak, something
different but good has happened to us every week. We're winning
games with different people and in a different style from week to
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning instinctively. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
