u s BC-BOX-IBF-PRESIDENT-NYT     12-14 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-IBF-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDICTED HEAD OF THE IBF STEPS ASIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVE STRUNSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ The International Boxing Federation said Monday
that its president would take a leave of absence to attend to his
ailing heart and his indictment on corruption charges, a move that
the sanctioning body hoped would let it avoid federal monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   The president, Robert W. Lee Sr., was among four federation
officials indicted Nov. 4 on charges that they took $338,000 in
bribes in exchange for advancing fighters' rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The other indicted officials were Lee's son, Robert Lee Jr., the
federation's liaison to his father; Donald William Brennan,
chairman of the federation's ranking committee; and Francisco
Fernandez, an international commissioner who lives in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   After the indictment, the U.S. attorney's office in Newark,
which brought the criminal charges, sued the federation under
federal anti-racketeering laws and sought to install a
court-approved monitor over the organization. That would be the
first instance in which a monitor oversaw a sports organization. A
hearing is scheduled for U.S. District Court in Newark on Dec. 22.
The government has asked to install Zachary Carter, a former U.S.
attorney in Brooklyn, who is now in private practice.
</P>
<P>
   In granting Lee a leave, the federation's acting president,
Hiawatha Knight, said the organization was moving to lift the cloud
of suspicion from its daily operations, and therefore there was no
more need for the government to seek a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The office can run without an overseer,'' said Knight, a
federation vice president normally based in Detroit, who arrived at
the sanctioning body's headquarters in East Orange on Monday. The
federation's board of commissioners voted to grant Lee leave last
week, said James Cecchi, a lawyer for the group.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Drewniak, a spokesman for Robert J. Cleary, the U.S.
attorney for New Jersey, said Lee's leave had no bearing on the
monitoring issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed in our minds,'' Drewniak said. ``The
motion for the monitor is still pending before the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Krovatin, the lawyer representing the elder Lee in the
indictment, said his client had an operation Monday at Beth Israel
Hospital in Newark to unclog an artery in his heart. He said Lee,
65, who lives in Fanwood, has a history of heart disease that
included a triple-bypass operation eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fine,'' Krovatin said of Lee Monday. ``He's resting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
