<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-XEROX-INVESTORS-NYT &LR;      12-14 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XEROX-INVESTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS BUY XEROX DESPITE ANALYSTS' DOWNGRADES AND PRICE
INCREASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As shares of the Xerox Corp. regained a modicum of what they
lost late Friday, a market truism was reaffirmed Monday: investors
are simply contrarians these days.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the market closed on Friday, Xerox dropped a
bombshell, warning that fourth-quarter earnings, which it had
already said in October would be poor, would be even worse. Xerox's
shares continued to fall in after-hours trading after closing at
$20.0625, down 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, analysts flooded First Call/Thomson Financial with
downgrades. They reduced their estimates for Xerox's fourth-quarter
earnings to 40 cents from 66 cents, and they lowered their
estimates for next year's earnings to $1.91 from $2.29.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went from estimating a 3 percent rise in earnings next
year to a 3 percent decline,'' said Charles L. Hill, director of
research at First Call. ``Clearly, the analysts see some
long-lasting problems at Xerox.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet neither Xerox nor investors were acting as though the
company was in serious trouble on Monday. Conventional wisdom
normally dictates that a company fight an upstart competitor by
dropping prices. Although Xerox has been steadily losing market
share to Canon, which has introduced a slew of new digital products
this year, Xerox announced price increases Monday of 3 percent to 5
percent on some of its highest-end and lowest-end digital products.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are products where we can still sell everything we
build, and that makes a price increase sustainable,'' said Jeffrey
J. Simek, a Xerox spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, despite their reaction late Friday, had calmed down
by Monday. Instead of plunging further in response to the analysts'
downgrades, Xerox's shares rose $1.0625, to $21.125.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xerox has a tremendous customer base, and those customers will
give them time to get their act together before they switch to
competitors,'' said Hadley Reynolds, director of research for the
Delphi Group, a document processing industry consulting firm in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Monday whether investors were simply bargain
hunting or whether they agree with Reynolds rosy prognosis. If it
is the latter, it is based more on hope than on tangible signs of
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Xerox's problems are beyond its control, of course.
Brazil, once Xerox's hottest growth market, is besieged with
economic trouble. And the strong dollar has damped the numbers
Xerox can report from still-healthy sales in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But it is in the United States that Xerox is suffering the most.
It still derives 75 percent of its sales from slow, low-margin
copiers whose markets grow less than 10 percent a year. Sales
remain disappointing for Xerox's most profitable product line, the
high-speed copiers used by publishing houses for print-on-demand
applications and by corporations in their central copier
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox attributes the shortfall to jitters over potential Year
2000 computer problems. But if that were the case, both the company
and analysts would be predicting a big bounce from pent-up demand
during the second quarter of 2000. No one is making such
predictions.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Year 2000 seem to be an industrywide problem. Canon
USA, which is emerging as Xerox's hottest competitor for high-speed
digital copiers, insists its sales continue to boom. To be fair,
Canon does not yet offer the kind of super-expensive high-speed
copiers that Xerox says were the hardest hit by Year 2000 problems.
But, the company intends to offer its first 110-page-a-minute
digital copier in January, which means it will be approaching
potential customers just as their Year 2000 fears are abating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If companies really are holding back on purchases because of
Y2K, then we're going to have one real blowout first quarter,''
said a Timothy Andree, a Canon vice president. Six months ago,
Canon was ranked fourth in the copier industry, behind Xerox, Ricoh
and Sharp. Now, many analysts say Canon may well end the year as
No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hottest products win the day, and Canon's products are the
hottest right now,'' said Benjamin A. Reitzes, an analyst at
PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox's sales people are in poor shape to fight back. They are
grappling with a reorganization, effective in January, that makes
them responsible for specific industries and companies, not
geographic territories. On top of that, Xerox recently cut its
administrative staff, figuring that it could easily consolidate 36
administrative centers into three.
</P>
<P>
   The result was chaos. Billing errors and uncollected receivables
skyrocketed, and sales people spent their time placating angry
customers instead of cultivating new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've bungled this entire restructuring at a time when there
are just too many copier companies chasing too little business,''
Reitzes said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Xerox has not lost all its fans. Gibboney Huske, an
analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston, is sticking with her buy
recommendation on Xerox stock. In fact, she predicts the share
price will hit $41 within the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xerox is still a good buy from the perspective of
risk-return,'' she said. ``Granted, in the last month you've seen
all the risk and none of the return, but ultimately these are
short-term issues that will be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Simek said that Xerox already had a senior management task force
working on ``more than 25 countermeasures to help us heal more
quickly and sustain earnings growth.'' For now, Simek offers no
details, other than to say the countermeasures range from
generating demand to reducing costs. He promised greater detail on
Jan. 25, when Xerox will announce its fourth-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
