<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMMS-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALLY TIMMS: A SWEET, LONELY SADNESS, BOTH PAINFUL AND ARTFUL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANN POWERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Sometimes I flap my wings like a hummingbird just
to remind myself I'll never fly,'' Sally Timms cooed at Maxwell's
on Friday in a song written by her fellow Chicago-based urban
rustics, the Handsome Family.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Timms was the first artist on a bill representing that
tight-knit community, and right now, she's the most exciting
member. Her new album, ``Cowboy Sally's Twilight Laments for Lost
Buckaroos'' (Bloodshot Records), flawlessly expresses her lonesome
sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Timms blends rapture and disenchantment in a way that
recalls those old cliches about why caged birds sing. Her voice, a
secretive murmur refined by her native English accent, is the stuff
of lullabies. But her knowing stance pulls back from that intimacy
with a sweet sadness.
</P>
<P>
   At Maxwell's, singing ``Down from Dover,'' Dolly Parton's stark
tale of a stillbirth all alone, and ``In Bristol Town One Fine
Day,'' a contemporary Celtic ballad written for her by Robbie Fulks
(another Chicago luminary), Ms. Timms made the music painfully
immediate and artful. Her band was equally subtle. Jon Rauhause,
playing Dobro and mandolin, and Chris Mills, on acoustic guitar,
carved out their parts like latticework, never obscuring her voice.
The fiddler Andrew Bird gracefully bowed in step with her soft
croon.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Timms broke the music's spell with the sarcastic onstage
patter that she has perfected in the veteran rock band, the Mekons.
She joked about turning 40 and needing to retire to folk music
because ``I can do it until I'm extremely old.''
</P>
<P>
   With typical self-deprecation, she declared, ``You're seeing the
pinnacle of my musical career.'' The funny thing was, so far that's
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Bird played next with his own band, Bowl of Fire. The quartet
showed off its skill at the rock-influenced swing, also explored by
the better-known Squirrel Nut Zippers, with whom Bird often
performs.
</P>
<P>
   The players, especially the drummer Kevin O'Donnell, approached
the music athletically, stressing speed and force. Bird sang in a
deadpan Hoagy Carmichael-style slur, but the band's best twist on
history evoked a different era. The new song ``Go Down Slow''
sounded like 1960s surf music, and watching Bird play power chords
on his violin was the set's high point.
</P>
<P>
   Well past midnight, the Waco Brothers clambered onstage and
turned the evening into a real blowout. The six-man band features
the singer-guitarist Jon Langford and the drummer Steve Goulding,
also Mekons members turned Chicagoans, alongside assorted
Englishmen and Midwesterners, playing raging honky-tonk.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing Marxist cowboy songs like ``Plenty Tough Union Made''
with country classics like Roy Acuff's ``Wreck on the Highway,''
the Waco Brothers showed that Americana can be as hot as whiskey
going down the throat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 0014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
