<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      12-14 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The winter meetings will have come and gone
without the Astros making a deal, but plenty of groundwork will be
in place by the time general manager Gerry Hunsicker boards a
flight back to Houston this morning.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A proposed trade with the Boston Red Sox involving center
fielder Carl Everett is still alive, although it may have hit a
snag Monday.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, the Astros would receive top shortstop
prospect Adam Everett and at least one other player, probably a
pitching prospect, in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say the Red Sox would like to be able to negotiate a
long-term contract with Carl Everett before acquiring the
27-year-old switch hitter, who can become a free agent after the
2000 season. However, they would need the Astros' permission to
talk financial terms with Carl Everett's agent _ otherwise it would
be considered tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker, who has been tight-lipped on the subject, declined
comment on any matters regarding specific trade speculation,
although his policy generally is to deny other teams permission to
negotiate with any of his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it makes any sense for the club to do that,'' he
said. ``It gives the player all the leverage. The player has
everything to gain and nothing to lose. The team has everything to
lose and nothing to gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Major League Baseball rules, a team can't talk to a player
on another team who is under contract unless a deal already is in
place and the negotiating team has written permission from the team
holding the contract.
</P>
<P>
   If permission is granted, the negotiating team has 72 hours to
strike a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not involved in such a situation at this time,''
Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Carl Everett nor his agent, Larry Reynolds, was
available for comment. Carl Everett spent most of the day at a
hospital with his wife, Linda, who gave birth to a baby boy.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, teams don't like to allow other clubs to
negotiate with their players when a trade is in place because it
potentially could be a deal-breaker if the negotiating club
concludes it won't be able to secure the player's services for a
long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners have taken a similar stance in their trade
discussions involving Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if permission is granted and the negotiating
club reaches an agreement with the player, the trading club might
be able to get more value in return.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Red Sox's apparent inability to negotiate with Carl
Everett, there still is a chance the deal will be completed.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are desperate for a run-producing outfielder, and
Carl Everett fits the bill. It's conceivable the Red Sox could pull
the trigger on the trade and take their chances on re-signing Carl
Everett prior to the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the ball still appears to be in the Red Sox's
court.
</P>
<P>
   If the trade does go down, it clearly would be a move aimed at
the future from the Astros' perspective. No one will argue that
trading Carl Everett _ he hit .325 with 25 home runs and 108 RBIs
in 1999 _ makes the Astros a better team in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But shortstop is a weakness in the organization, and many
baseball observers believe Adam Everett is the real deal _ his
defense, in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox can afford to part with the 22-year-old shortstop,
who likely needs another year in the minors, because they are set
at shortstop with Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   One player who surfaced in speculation as a possibility to head
to Houston in the trade is lefthanded pitcher Greg Miller, 20, who
was 10-6 with a 3.10 ERA and 146 strikeouts in 137 innings last
season for the Red Sox's Class A affiliate in Augusta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is the fact the Astros eventually hope to
make room in their outfield for younger players such as Richard
Hidalgo, Daryle Ward and Lance Berkman.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it's important for the club to keep an eye on the budget,
especially since Moises Alou and Derek Bell will tie up almost $12
million in 2000 and the arbitration-eligible Carl Everett could
make as much as $5 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The fact the Astros are considering trade possibilities for
players such as Carl Everett and Cy Young Award runner-up Mike
Hampton speaks more to the economic state of the game than it does
the club's evaluation of the players.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker is quick to point out that both are key players for
the three-time defending National League Central Division
champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy when you have to make personnel decisions based
on factors other than baseball talent,'' Hunsicker said. ``But
that's the nature of our business. In our present situation, the
worst thing that could happen is to have three quality players
leave us (Everett, Hampton and Bell can be free agents after the
2000 season) and we get nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``To not get anything back for them is not a pleasant thought.
The flip side is when you're trading players of this quality, while
you may not get players back that make you better the next year, it
might make you better in years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the flip side of the Randy Johnson trade. You have to
evaluate trades like that based on the goal of the team at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his final day of work at this year's annual gathering of
baseball officials, Hunsicker said: ``I had some very interesting
conversations that could eventually lead to a trade, but we're not
there yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
