<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-RINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS GET CHAMPIONSHIP RINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dan Marino. Charles Barkley. Ted Williams. Brett
Hull.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, this had been the core membership of the elite
fraternity of The Best Players Never To Win Rings.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can scratch Hull's name off the membership list. Hull
and the Stars received their Stanley Cup championship rings in a
private ceremony Monday night at Las Colinas Country Club, 161 days
after winning the Cup in a not-so-private, triple-overtime, Game 6
thriller against Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the ring) is the symbol of it. But actually winning
it, they kind of go hand in hand,'' Hull said. ``You've got the
ring. You're a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   The ring has come to symbolize the ultimate achievement in pro
sports. Fans and players alike talk in terms of rings, not
championships. As in, does he have a ring?
</P>
<P>
   ``(Champio) is only a word. The ring is definitely the thing
that makes it official,'' said Stars forward Guy Carbonneau, owner
of three Stanley Cup championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   Said Stars general manager Bob Gainey: ``The ring has become
just that, a symbol of team success, of a group of players, of a
season.''
</P>
<P>
   So how much does a little symbolism cost nowadays?
</P>
<P>
   Stars owner Tom Hicks spent just under $1 million on the almost
175 rings given to players, coaches and staff. There are three
varieties of rings. The one the players received Monday night has
five interlocking green diamonds in the middle of a gold star
surrounded by 100 pave diamonds. The players, coaches and
management also received pendants like the tops of the rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it was, I'd spend twice as much,'' Hicks said. ``I
would spend twice as much to do it again. This is a celebration,
but this is also closure. ... They're warming up. I'm really
confident the guys will be more like Detroit was than New Jersey or
the Rangers or Colorado. We may not win it this year. I think we'll
give it a tough run. We're going to be in the thick of things. They
are going to play like the defending Stanley Cup champs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why, while the ring is nice, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said he didn't plan on wearing his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come over to the house, you can come look at it in the drawer.
I don't need to show off with it. I don't need people to say `Wow,
what did you win that for?' I don't need it,'' Hitchcock said. ``I
already have all of the feelings that happened. To me, nothing is
ever going to take place of watching a team come together. No
money, no ring, no trophy, no picture, nothing. The feeling of what
it was like, it is going to stay with me the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some of the players from that team aren't around
anymore. Wingers Pat Verbeek and Dave Reid signed with other teams
during the off-season. But 16 of the players from that team were in
attendance Monday night, and for them there was nothing quite like
the ring _ for memories, for validation but mostly for what it
symbolized.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are with you the rest of your life, and nobody
can take it away from you,'' Stars' Conn Smythe winner Joe
Nieuwendyk said. ``It's a great reminder of what special bond you
have with 24 other guys. Those are the things you take with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars forward Mike Modano said as good as holding the Cup was,
the ring was better. ``The Cup comes and goes, but the ring always
stays,'' Modano said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
