<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS REGROUP AFTER INJURIES TO ELLIS, SMITH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Somewhat sobering the mood at Valley Ranch on
Monday, the day after a 20-10 victory against the Philadelphia
Eagles, was the realization that the Cowboys must finish the season
without blossoming defensive end Greg Ellis and the uncertain
status of star running back Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who suffered a fractured tibia when teammate Alonzo
Spellman rolled over his leg in the first quarter, underwent
surgery Sunday night to place a rod in his leg. Not only will he
miss the final three games _ starting Sunday against the New York
Jets _ but he is expected to be sidelined through training camp
next year. The Cowboys are targeting his return for the start of
the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said Ellis, the team's top pick in
1998 and sack leader this season with 7.5, was playing at a Pro
Bowl level and his play and attitude will be missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was having an exceptional year,'' Gailey said. ``He was a
guy that gives you everything he has. We will lose some intangible
factors not having him on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who strained his groin on the first play of the game
against the Eagles, is listed as questionable for the Jets. Gailey
doesn't know if Smith will be able to practice this week, saying
his status will be evaluated daily.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gailey and Cowboys are confident in backup Chris Warren,
who replaced Smith on Sunday and gained 92 yards on 25 carries,
they are looking at the final three games as must-wins. And they
need Smith, the league's third all-time leading rusher and second
all-time leading touchdown scorer, in the lineup. Gailey said he
has no idea if Smith will be able to play against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to wait and see how he feels in the next two
days,'' Gailey said. ``It will depend how much he can do on the
practice field.'' Allen could return No matter who is running the
ball, the Cowboys could be boosted by the possible return of
All-Pro guard Larry Allen, who has missed the past four games with
a sprained knee. Allen is listed as questionable. Chan Gailey said
the team will get a better idea of Allen's status in practice
Wednesday and Thursday. NOW AT LEFT CORNERBACK ...
</P>
<P>
   It continues to be a revolving door at left cornerback. Kevin
Mathis, who started Sunday against the Eagles, suffered a sprained
knee on a kickoff return and is expected to be sidelined at least
one game.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis was starting in place of Kevin Smith, who missed the past
three games with a strained hamstring. Smith, who has started seven
games at the position, is expected to return Sunday. Reserve
cornerback Charlie Williams, who has started three games there,
will start if Smith can't. REPLACING ELLIS
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman seems to be the logical choice
to replace Greg Ellis at end.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman played end for the first six years of his career before
being moved to tackle in training camp to replace Leon Lett, who
was suspended for the first eight games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   With Lett seemingly returning to his Pro Bowl form, the Cowboys
are considering moving Spellman to end. However, Chan Gailey said
its not an easy decision because Spellman is playing at a Pro Bowl
level at tackle and they are hesitant about moving a player who is
dominant at one position to take a chance on him not being dominant
at another.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also like the production they are getting from their
standout tackle rotation of Lett, Spellman and Chad Hennings and
are reluctant to disrupt it.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Cowboys have gotten solid production from backup
tackles Brandon Noble and Michael Myers, and the need is greater at
end, where rookies Ebenezer Ekuban and Peppi Zellner are the other
possible choices to replace Ellis and start opposite Kavika
Pittman.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the Cowboys will make a decision on Spellman before
practice Wednesday but admitted they might not reveal their plans
this week in attempt to keep the Jets guessing. COWBOYS VISIT
HOSPITALS
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case all season, the Cowboys get an extra day
off after a victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys players spent their free time after Sunday's victory
against the Eagles visiting children at several area hospitals,
namely Children's Medical Center, Parkland Memorial Hospital,
Scottish Rite Hospital, Medical City Hospital, all in Dallas, and
Cook Children's Medical Center in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Raghib Ismail, linebacker Dat Nguyen and defensive end
Ebenezer Ekuban were among a group of 20 players who visited the
children's hospital in Fort Worth. Community relations director
Emily Robbins said the hospital visits, which also include the
Cowboys Cheerleaders, are an annual event for the Cowboys. She said
the players signed autographs and presented the children with
stockings stuffed trading cards, pictures and other gifts. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
