<HEADLINE>
DR. SEUSS CHARACTERS COLORED HIS EDITORIAL CARTOONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 (STORY also moved in ``K'' category) 
 TITLE: ``Dr. Seuss Goes to War: 
 The World War II Editorial Cartoons of Theodor Seuss Geisel''  
 Text by Richard H. Minear  (The New Press, $25)
 &HT;     By DAVE WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cat in the Hat's red-and-white-striped leaning tower of a
stove-pipe has become an American icon only slightly less
recognizable than the Disney mouse ears,'' contemporary cartoonist
Art Spiegelman (author of ``Maus'') writes in the introduction to
this eye-opening picture book for adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing the slightly battered lid on the Seuss bird that
represents the United States,'' Spiegelman writes, ``is
disorienting enough to bring on an epiphany: the prototype for the
cat's famous headgear is actually an emblem deployed in countless
political cartoons: Uncle Sam's red-and-white top hat! The Cat in
the Hat is America!''
</P>
<P>
   The long-necked ``Seuss bird'' is everywhere in this collection
of political cartoons, and so are prototypes of nearly all of the
other familiar Dr. Seuss characters, including Lorax and Yertl the
Turtle, the circus fish and the ubiquitous whale, but here they are
pressed into service as characters in single-panel political
satires.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Seuss, it turns out, began his career as a cartoonist for
the famous experimental daily newspaper of New York in the 1940s,
``PM,''perhaps the last left-wing paper in the country of any
circulation before it turned toes-up in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   Who could have known, as we read these books to our kids and
grandkids through the decades of the Cold War, that the long-necked
Seuss bird probably made his first appearance on Sept. 22, 1941,
with a sign, ``I am part Jewish'' hanging from his beak! For it
turns out that Theodor Seuss Geisel, son of German immigrant
Republicans, was an ardent anti-fascist and critic of
America-Firsters, anti-Semites and non-interventionists of every
stripe.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't remember America First, it was a group of
both conservatives and liberals who opposed getting into the war in
Europe, and among its leading members was Charles Lindbergh,
against whom Seuss directed volley after withering volley, as in
the cartoon of July 16, 1941, that featured the familiar whale with
the big eyes. Here the whale is presented as a fish out of water,
an ``isolationist'' whale who lives way up on top of a mountain:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(EDITOR: QUOTED LINES:) Said a whale, ``There is so much commotion,
</P>
<P>
   Such fights among fish in the ocean,
</P>
<P>
   I'm saving my scalp
</P>
<P>
   Living high on an Alp . . .
</P>
<P>
   (Dear Lindy! He gave me a notion!)''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Eight years after his death, Dr. Seuss still has more than 50-plus
titles still in print, and, in fact, ``Green Eggs and Ham'' is said
to be the third-largest selling book in the English language.
</P>
<P>
   This collection, with commentary by Richard H. Minear, is an
illuminating look at the politics of the early 1940s from an oddly
familiar voice, and it may even provide some clues to the deeper
meanings of the good doctor's less obviously political children's
tales. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 0107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8237 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     12-14 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By DALE ROBERTSON 
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
IN theory, the guy who changed his mind was a perfect fit for the
University of Houston. Bob Pruett had the coaching credentials and
the right demographics in his corner. At 57, he already was much
too old to use UH as a stopover en route to a more prestigious
posting.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, so much for theory. Pruett held the Cougars job for just
long enough to, no doubt, finagle a sweeter deal for himself at
Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   It's always risky business to attempt to steal a man from his
alma mater, where blood runs thicker than Gatorade. However, since
Chet Gladchuk left his _ Boston College _ to tackle the many
challenges UH presents, the Cougars' athletic director had no
qualms about giving it a go. Fortunately, he was ready with a Plan
B. (A Plan C and a Plan D, too, but no matter now.)
</P>
<P>
   Dana Dimel comes to us from that well-established cradle of
coaches nestled among the Rocky Mountains _ the University of
Wyoming _ with an impressive resume he's not bashful about
reciting. The most salient fact is that Dimel won 11 more games
than he lost in three seasons while recruiting about as many kids
out of Texas as Kim Helton persuaded to play for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   If Dimel can survive the culture shock of moving from Laramie _
he resided in Manhattan, Kan., before that _ to the Big City, he
should do fine by the Cougars. He promises a wide-open, exciting,
points-galore offense, although it's hard to imagine a new coach
anywhere admitting he intends to be dull and plodding.
</P>
<P>
   He also promises to sell tickets, and considering his new town
has about 10 times as many people as his previous state, you can
see whence his boundless optimism springs.
</P>
<P>
   The former goal is achievable from the get-go, with
strong-armed, clear-headed Jason McKinley returning for his senior
season and bubbling over with enthusiasm after hearing how Dimel
intends to ``spread the field.'' The latter objective, alas, will
prove far more problematic, certainly at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Dimel may set the Cougars on a course for national prominence.
He may put a sufficient number of fannies in the Robertson Stadium
seats to justify his five-year, $3 million deal. But it's rather
unlikely to happen overnight, a la Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Osborne or perhaps Dimel's former boss at Kansas State, Bill
Snyder, the glam rumors du jour of last week, might _ might _ have
induced Drexleresque hysteria, but Dimel will find Houston to be
very much a ``show-me'' kind of place. It's impossible he will
generate more fireworks than Jugular John Jenkins did a decade ago,
and remember how poorly attended most of those games were.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are nobody woke up Monday morning, saw the Chronicle
headline ``Dimel takes UH coaching reins'' and immediately pulled
on a scarlet sweatshirt, then headed to the telephone to order
season tickets. Rather, most folks asked, ``Who?''
</P>
<P>
   Although a known commodity in football circles, Dimel will have
to prove himself, something Helton never fully accomplished. And in
the process of doing so, odds are he will attract the attention of
other universities with higher profiles, more imposing stadiums and
deeper pockets. At 37, he is exactly what Pruett wasn't _
figuratively and, as things turned out, literally.
</P>
<P>
   A coach who's going places.
</P>
<P>
   Should Dimel prove as solid a choice as the university needs him
to be, he probably won't be here long. He left Wyoming two seasons
before his contract expired there, costing Houston $200,000 for the
buyout. If he can't cut the Cougars' mustard? That's not to be
cheered either, obviously, because UH is about out of opportunities
to make its program viable.
</P>
<P>
   Gladchuk is banking heavily on college football coming to its
senses and instituting a playoff system three or four years down
the road. In same, Conference USA would have guaranteed entree,
meaning its champion could compete on equal footing with the ``big
boys,'' at least in the sense that its dreams could be dashed only
on an actual playing field, not by some geek's computer.
</P>
<P>
   Dimel spoke of whupping TCU, SMU and Rice while at Wyoming and
coaxed a loud rise out of the packed house of boosters attending
his news conference Monday by saying he intends to add a Bevo skin
to his collection next season. Toward that end, his mission is
clear: He has to convince the local high school heroes they need to
stay here instead of going to Austin or College Station.
</P>
<P>
   While you're tempted to say, ``Fat chance,'' he somehow lured 18
Texans to Laramie, which never has been confused with Maui.
</P>
<P>
   Gladchuk should be commended for making his decision with an
open mind, and for having options after Pruett's bizarre U-turn.
After Drexler, there was tremendous pressure on him to stay ``in
house'' with this hire, giving rise to the ludicrous speculation
that either Andre Ware or David Klingler would land the job, never
mind their conspicuous lack of coaching experience.
</P>
<P>
   The AD insists he got a man he really wanted, even if the man _
or men, assuming the Osborne-Snyder talk had an iota of validity _
he most wanted got away. ``I don't know anything but winning,''
Dimel bragged, adding he fully expects the trend to continue
despite this latest drastic change of scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Except, as they say, it ain't bragging when you do it, and Dana
Dimel has.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 0108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0020 </DOCNO>
