<SLUG> BC-SOCC-AKERS-HONOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AKERS ENSHRINED IN ``SEATTLE WALK OF FAME'' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MEREDITH BAGLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The lines to see Santa got a little shorter at
Nordstrom Monday afternoon as World Cup and Olympic champion soccer
star Michelle Akers was inducted into the store's ``Seattle Walk of
Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers joins 28 other notable Seattle figures, from Jimi Hendrix
to Bill Gates, whose footprints have been bronzed into the sidewalk
outside the downtown store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of ties in Seattle,'' Akers said. ``The fans here
have been incredibly supportive and excited about my success, and
this award is part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers, who was recently named the CONCACAF 1999 Female Player of
the Century, is a 1984 graduate of Shorecrest High School. Akers
attended the University of Central Florida, where she was a three
time All-America selection.
</P>
<P>
   Akers is the all-time scoring leader in Women's World Cup
history and one of only four players, male or female, to score more
than 100 goals in international competition. She scored two goals
in the 1999 World Cup and had to be helped off the field after her
effort in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of the World Cup was beyond my wildest dreams,''
said Akers, who also played on U.S. teams that won the inaugural
women's World Cup and the 1996 Olympic gold medal. ``It's just been
a whirlwind since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Sports Illustrated named Akers and her teammates
Sportswomen of the Year. The award is for those who symbolize in
character and performance the ideals of sportsmanship. They are the
first female team to win the award in its 45-year history and join
the 1980 men's Olympic hockey team as the only teams so honored.
</P>
<P>
   Akers was not scheduled to take part in the World Cup team's
Victory Tour games due to a chronic knee injury that required
physical therapy. She was released for play in early December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had 12 or 13 surgeries on that knee,'' Akers said. ``It's
pretty thrashed, and my release was contingent upon me not being
stupid out on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers has had to deal with serious family illness since the
World Cup. In August, her father was diagnosed with colon cancer
and underwent surgery. Akers was on vacation at the time, but flew
back to Seattle to be with her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I planned to have some rest time, but I really haven't had a
break yet,'' Akers said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the original members of the U.S. National Team, Akers has
said she will retire after the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   As for her future, Akers has many ideas but no firm plans. One
thing she is sure of is that soccer will continue to be a part of
her life. Akers is the founder of Soccer Outreach International, a
program that works with youth teams to help develop leadership
skills through service projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with kids who are underprivileged or sick, and giving
them hope and something real to base their life on, that's what I
love to do,'' Akers said.
</P>
<P>
   Akers also has dreams of buying land for a ranch, and recently
purchased her second horse. She also is considering coaching and
wants to stay involved with the national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Olympic gold is great,'' Akers said. ``But you've got to
look at what's really important and base your life on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8239 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      12-14 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT EXPECTED BACK IN LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sonics center Horace Grant is almost always content.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are NASA will hear from Mars before you see Grant in a
cranky mood. It took a strained ligament in his left knee to change
Grant's disposition the past week, somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   However, Grant is apparently off the emotional roller coaster
he's been riding lately.
</P>
<P>
   While Grant's knee is not 100-percent healthy, the 6-foot-10
center will take the court Tuesday night against the Denver Nuggets
after sitting out three of the past four games.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Grant is more certain he can be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Grant did not play last Saturday in the Sonics' 92-88 win
against Miami. The day before, Grant took himself out of a loss at
Utah after playing the first quarter _ the knee was weak and left
him ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been getting treatment twice a day, and I went out and
tested it (Sunday),'' Grant said. ``Dwight (Daub, the team's
strength coach) took me through some good drills. There's a little
pain still there. But it's nothing I can't play with. ... Against
Utah, there were things I couldn't do, like jump off my feet
quickly and cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I went up and down (the court) with the guys (Monday). I
had some contact. I was able to twist and turn. I'm still not 100
percent, but I can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the Sonics have resembled Grant: Up and down.
</P>
<P>
   They lost at home to Charlotte, beat Minnesota, dropped a game
at Utah, then beat the Heat last week. Suddenly, the factors that
helped the Sonics throughout their 15-6 start are working against
them.
</P>
<P>
   On average, opponents are shooting and rebounding better than
the Sonics. Opposing teams have fared better at the foul line and
beyond the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Sonics have yet to lose two games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's competitiveness ... finding a way to win games. That's
the No. 1 statistic. The rest of them are clues,'' Sonics coach
Paul Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics must play fast and tenacious basketball. Rebounding,
running and scoring in transition are key, as is exhibiting a
decent defensive presence down low with or without Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Against Miami, the Sonics took advantage of mismatches in the
lineup to prevent Alonzo Mourning from dominating the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets (10-10) are a much-improved team, well-known to the
Sonics because Seattle struggled _ losing two of four _ against
Denver last season. Forwards Antonio McDyess and Ron Mercer and
guards Chauncey Billups and Nick Van Exel make up as talented a
group as any other in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest difference in Denver can be seen away from
the Pepsi Center. The Nuggets are no longer a bargain-basement
bunch. They finished last week's five-game East-Coast trip with a
3-2 record, including wins against the New York Knicks and
Philadelphia 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   Denver had won just two road games in each of the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're dangerous,'' Westphal said. ``They're starting to get
wins on the road this year. They have a lot of balance and creative
players when everything breaks down. They've got a lot of players
capable of keeping you from doubling their stars because they can
hit the 3. They're just a real dangerous team that can score from a
lot of different positions.''
</P>
<P>
   One could make the argument that the Sonics are just as
dangerous, because recently it is difficult to figure them out.
</P>
<P>
   With Grant on the floor, the team at least should find
equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of (the inconsistency) was Horace being out. He's such a
consistent player that played a big part,'' Westphal said. ``The
other part is some of these teams are pretty good. If they're
having a hot game when we're not having a good game, we can get
beat. That's what happened in the Lakers game (Nov. 30), the
Charlotte game (Dec. 5). ... Not having Horace, we didn't adjust
right. And the same thing in Utah (Dec. 10). The Miami game and the
Minnesota game (Dec. 8), we hit on a way that we can play and be
effective. That's how we have to play all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
