<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIDDING SEAHAWKS SEARCH FOR SOLUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Chad Brown wore the Seahawks' three-game
losing streak like a hair shirt Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As the team's leading tackler entered the locker room, his eyes
were fixed on the floor. His face was sullen. His gait was
deliberate. He looked as if he hadn't slept well, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and he was perturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not a good day,'' Brown said. ``Three in a row at
this point in the season when we need to try and separate ourselves
from the rest of the AFC West opponents and seal up this playoff
thing. December is when you want to play your best football.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for his anger is obvious. The once 8-2 Seahawks have
lost three in a row to squander their three-game lead in the AFC
West and allow themselves to be caught by the Kansas City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a three-game season. The Seahawks still control their
destiny. They're still in first place. Win two straight, and they
win the division.
</P>
<P>
   The optimistic words flowed from the players' mouths again
Monday, less than 24 hours after they had dropped a disheartening
and potentially disastrous 19-16 decision to the San Diego Chargers
at the Kingdome. They were the updated assessments of what had been
offered after the losses to the Oakland Raiders and Tampa Bay
Buccaneers the previous two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the looks on the players' faces and their body language
while reiterating the party line betrayed them.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks are blowing an opportunity that this franchise has
longed for during 10 playoff-less seasons, the past eight without
so much as a winning record. Their three-game lead with six to play
is now a no-game lead with three to play _ starting with their game
against the Broncos in Denver this week and then the Dec. 26
rematch with the Chiefs at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Three consecutive losses, each worse than the previous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still right there for us to take, but we've definitely
dug ourselves a deep hole that we've got to get out of,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have kind of exposed ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That they have. Opponents now know the way to beat the Seahawks
is to stop the run and blitz quarterback Jon Kitna, and do things
offensively that make it difficult for the defense to communicate
in the din of the Kingdome _ such as the no-huddle approach the
Chargers used Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to fix some things,'' Brown said. ``Because teams
are going to come in and do these things against us because we
haven't stopped them.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown says it's a matter of every player on the team looking in
the mirror and asking what he can do to improve and help the team
shake its slump. He said it after the game Sunday. He said it in
the locker room Monday. The last time he had used that analogy was
last November, after a tough-to-swallow loss to the Raiders at the
Kingdome. It was the game that marked the beginning of the end for
coach Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be a coaching change at the end of this season. But
if coach Mike Holmgren doesn't find a way to apply the breaks to
this skid, the season will end well short of everyone's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest problems that must not only be addressed but
corrected are the defense's sudden inability to pressure or contain
opposing quarterbacks and the offense's self-destructive tendencies
once it gets near the red zone.
</P>
<P>
   First, the defense. After collecting 30 sacks and 21
interceptions in their first 11 games, the Seahawks have one sack
and two interceptions in the past two games. Raiders quarterback
Rich Gannon and the Chargers' Jim Harbaugh have combined to
complete 66 percent of their passes while compiling a QB rating of
88.4 _ after the Seahawks had held their first 11 opponents to 53.8
percent completions and a 62.6 rating, among the lowest in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Brown says it's a matter of being aggressive. Or in the case of
the defense the past two weeks, a lack of aggressiveness. Holmgren
points out that aggressive is tied to the secondary being able to
play man-to-man coverage, and to do that the defensive backs must
he healthy. That was not the case Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you force the offense to think about what you're going to
do, instead of focusing on what they are trying to do to you, it's
a different mindset,'' Brown said. ``It's a different mentality
when they're reacting to you instead of you reacting to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like teams to watch film and look at our defense and
go, `Wow, what are we going to do with those guys? How are we going
to stop those guys?'''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case earlier this season, when the Seahawks were
among the league leaders in forcing turnovers and creating big
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people are watching film and probably saying, `We can do a
lot to these guys,''' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the offense, the Seahawks turned the ball over only twice
against the Chargers _ after having 10 in the losses to the Bucs
and Raiders. But each was costly, for a different reason.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna threw a pass in the first quarter that was intercepted at
the Chargers' 12-yard line to waste both a 42-yard kickoff return
by rookie Charlie Rogers and another scoring opportunity inside the
opponents' 20. Ricky Watters lost a fumble in the fourth quarter at
the Seattle 26 to set up John Carney's game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly it's been turnovers,'' Holmgren said when asked for
the difference between the team's five-game winning streak and
three-game losing streak. ``You could make a strong case that
turnovers cost us all three games.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
