<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-STRETCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' MOTTO DOWN STRETCH: DON'T LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 RUN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dave Campo has cut to the chase.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys' defensive coordinator has reduced the
``goals'' posted in the team's locker room from a dozen categories
to one:
</P>
<P>
   ``Win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken all the goals off our board. All we're doing now
is turning the opponent's helmet belly-up when we beat 'em,'' Campo
said. ``We've stopped keeping track of all that other stuff like
rushing average, passing average, getting at least two turnovers
per game, holding (the opposition) to 17 points or less ...
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're doing now is bellying-up the other team's helmet
whenever we win.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo uses 3-inch magnetic helmets to depict wins and losses
across a metal board. The Philadelphia Eagles' helmet was
ceremoniously turned upside-down Monday morning at Valley Ranch
after the Cowboys' 20-10 victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys found out late Sunday night (as soon as Minnesota
lost to Kansas City, 31-28, on the final play of the game) that if
they can turn the remaining three helmets on their schedule
belly-up, they are in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Cowboys control their own destiny in terms
of advancing as an NFC wild card, just not in terms of making the
postseason as the NFC East champion.
</P>
<P>
   With three games remaining, Washington (8-5) leads the division.
The Cowboys and the New York Giants are tied for second at 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal: St. Louis (11-2) has the best record in the
conference. Tampa Bay is next is next at 9-4, followed by Detroit
and Washington at 8-5. Four other teams, including the Cowboys, can
also win 10 or more games by winning out.
</P>
<P>
   But because of two remaining games that involve four teams
currently 7-6 _ Green Bay at Minnesota on Monday night and Giants
at Cowboys on Jan. 2 _ two of the four are assured of not finishing
with 10 wins.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the list of possible 10-game-or-more winners is
reduced to six, matching the number of playoff teams (three
division winners and three wild cards) from each conference.
</P>
<P>
   In Campo's way of thinking, defense is the best way to count on
getting the job done down the stretch because of the nature of
must-win games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the playoffs, and even down the stretch, just about every
play of every game is a potential difference-maker,'' Campo said.
``So coaches tend to be more conservative, and scores tend to be
lower. (Offensive) coaches are a little more reluctant to take a
shot downfield on third-and-two or third-and-one than they are
earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the teams that have a better defense have a better chance
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey approaches the New York Jets game at Texas
Stadium on Sunday as ``must-win,'' just as he will approach the New
Orleans road game Christmas Eve and the Giants game Jan. 2 the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I believe we are (taking each of these remaining games
as must-win),'' Gailey said. ``That may not necessarily be the
truth, but we're playing it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offense showed improvement Sunday in attacking
downfield in the passing game with six pass plays of 16 or more
yards. The Cowboys also scored as two offensive touchdowns in a
game for the first time in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey acknowledged that Sunday was merely a step in the right
direction for the offense. Penalties must be eliminated. The
passing game must function on a more consistent basis.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been outperforming the offense most of the
season, evidenced by the fact that the Cowboys have lost four games
this season in which the opponent was held to 13 points. The last
time that happened _ three weeks ago at Arizona (13-9) _ Campo
chucked all the goals except for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find a way to win,'' he said. ``All we're talking about now is
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys can still win the division title. In the case of a
tie between two or more teams within the same division, the first
tiebreaker is head-to-head results. The Cowboys own that tiebreaker
against the Redskins, having defeated them twice, just as the
Redskins own that tiebreaker against the Giants (2-0), while the
Giants (1-0) and Cowboys have a second meeting Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The second tiebreaker involving two or more teams from the same
division is best divisional record. The Redskins are 5-3 against
NFC East opponents, the Cowboys 4-3, and the Giants 3-4.
</P>
<P>
   Only the NFC East and AFC West do not have a team that can
clinch a playoff berth this week.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty four of the NFL's 31 teams are in contention for a
playoff spot with three weeks remaining. Only Atlanta, Cincinnati,
Cleveland, New Orleans, Philadelphia, Pittsburgh and San Francisco
have been elimininated. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
