<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-FINLEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' FINLEY PUTTING TOGETHER ALL-STAR SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Michael Finley is in a zone. Maybe even ``the'' zone.
</P>
<P>
   During the past seven games, the Mavericks' leading scorer is
averaging 23.7 points, 9.4 rebounds, 5.9 assists, and 1.9 steals
per game. In the Mavericks' three victories during that span,
Finley is averaging 31.6 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   And he's playing hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaching staff expects all three of those categories to be
high on the stat sheets every night for me, and I like that
responsibility,'' Finley said. ``Confidence comes with hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the type of hard work that I put in this summer to put me
in game conditioning and put me in game situations where I know
what to do and what my strengths are. I'm just stepping up to the
plate and doing those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditioning seems to have helped Finley overcome plantar
faciatis _ inflammation in his right foot. That's the same injury
that has ruined many careers, and the same injury that sidelined
Phoenix Suns guard Penny Hardaway last week.
</P>
<P>
   Finley hurriedly ices his foot after every game, and said his
foot feels ``all right.'' But those that know him know better and
know of Finley's high tolerance for pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just kept the intensity going,'' Cedric Ceballos said of
Finley's game Saturday against Phoenix, which included 33 points,
14 rebounds and 10 assists. ``We'd have dropoffs and relax, but he
just kept going and kept playing and doing everything for us.
That's what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley scored 30 points in a victory at Chicago on Dec. 2 that
followed a triple-double (14 points, 11 assists and 12 rebounds) in
a loss to Cleveland on Nov. 30, the start of the seven-game hot
streak. He had 32 in a victory at Minnesota on Dec. 4 and 29 in a
loss to Milwaukee the next night.
</P>
<P>
   Ever humble, Finley tries to downplay his importance to the
Mavericks. But they'll likely need another All-Star-like
performance from the Chicago native when they play host to the
defending NBA champion San Antonio Spurs on Tuedsay night at 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately for me my shots were falling down,'' Finley said
of his dominating output against the Suns, who drafted him No. 1 in
1995. ``I had good opportunities to rebound, and I was doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I was getting guys the ball they were knocking down
shots. It was just whatever it took for my team to win.''
</P>
<P>
   What Finley has accomplished the past two weeks is what the
Mavericks need in their go-to guy. And he said he still has a ways
to go to be the player he wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game is improving,'' Finley said. ``My game is still not to
a point where I want it to be. The coaching staff is putting the
ball in my hands and giving me opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson has been basking in
the glow of Finley's all-around game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been playing well lately, and we really need that from
Fin,'' Nelson said. ``He's been playing like an All-Star.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's numbers are coming at a time when opponents know he's
going to get the ball. He also is facing all sorts of gimmick
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teams try to play me one-on-one, and some teams would
rather go to a double-team situation,'' Finley said. ``They try to
mix it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they double-team me I'm unselfish enough to find the open
teammates. And when they're knocking it down, it just makes us an
even tougher team.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's effort coincided with the end of the coaching reign of
Danny Ainge, who resigned as the Suns coach Monday. After
Saturday's curtain-closing loss to the Mavericks, Ainge said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael hurt us bad. I think his eyes light up when he plays
against Phoenix sometimes. The basket got big and he was knocking
down things from everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley said he doesn't worry about the added minutes he's
playing, which included the full 48 minutes four times the past two
weeks. He also is not concerned that he leads the NBA in minutes
played at 41.6 per game.
</P>
<P>
   More important for Finley is to get the Mavericks pointed in the
right direction. And he points out that there's no better time than
this five-game homestand, which finishes with games against the
Spurs, New York, Minnesota and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to win games at home,'' Finley said. ``Coming off the
grueling road trip that we had _ with the losses _ our confidence
may have been shaken up a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to come here and play the way we did at home (against
Phoenix), it sets a good tone for our homestand. When we usually
come out of the box good early, it's a good indication that things
are going to go our way.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
