<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8244 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-TRADE-TEX     12-14 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TRADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ACQUIRE CHAD CURTIS FROM YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Todd Zeile is gone and Aaron Sele is unsigned
but the Rangers did accomplish one goal before leaving baseball's
winter meetings.
</P>
<P>
   They picked up a fourth outfielder and possible leadoff hitter
when they acquired World Series hero Chad Curtis from the New York
Yankees on Monday for minor-league pitchers Brandon Knight and Sam
Marsonek.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gritty type of player,'' Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin said. ``He gives us versatility and depth. He also brings a
personality to our ballclub. He's got a couple of championship
rings, hopefully that will rub off on our ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, taking over Roberto Kelly's role, gives the Rangers a
veteran backup for rookie center fielder Ruben Mateo and right
fielder Gabe Kapler. A right-handed hitter, Melvin said Curtis
should also see time as a designated hitter against left-handed
pitchers, particularly while batting leadoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he had a .400 on-base percentage against
left-handers,'' Melvin said. ``That's a role we're looking to fill.
He's batted at the top of the order before, we know he can do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, 31, hit .262 with five home runs and 24 runs batted in
in 195 at-bats for the Yankees last season, playing 72 games in
left field, six in center and three in right. He also stole eight
bases, giving him 202 in his eight-year major-league career. He had
21 in 1998 and a career-high of 48 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He also has some power as he showed in Game 3 of the World
Series this year. The Yankees were trailing 5-1 in the fifth inning
when Curtis started the comeback with a home run off Braves pitcher
Tom Glavine. He also finished it with a 10th-inning game-winning
homer off reliever Mike Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial response was looking at what I was leaving,''
Curtis said. ``I had a pretty good time in New York. We won a
couple of championships, and I established relationships with some
good people. My first reaction was I will miss those things. But if
I was going to list the top-10 teams I wanted to go to, Texas would
have been among them. And probably at the high end.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis was a starter for the first five years of his career with
the California Angels and Detroit Tigers before being used as a
fourth outfielder with the Yankees. He has wanted the opportunity
to be a regular again but said he understands that he will be a
reserve with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going in there to try to win as much playing time as
possible and help the team win,'' Curtis said. ``If there are three
guys out there who have a better chance of helping the team win,
I'd like to have them out there. But I'm still going to try and
show the manager that I want to play as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis is signed for two more years at $1.9 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   Marsonek, 21, was one of two first-round draft picks for the
Rangers in 1996 but his progress was slowed considerably by
injuries. He needed reconstructive elbow surgery in 1998 and
appeared in just four games. He was 3-9 with a 5.54 earned-run
average in 15 games for Class-A Port Charlotte this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the toughest part of the deal,'' Melvin said. ``A
first-round pick could come back to haunt you. He's someone we feel
could pitch in the big leagues but he's a little farther away. He
wasn't going to help us immediately and we needed a fourth
outfielder.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight, 24, was 9-8 with a 4.91 ERA for Triple-A Oklahoma last
season and wasn't expected to compete for a major-league job in
spring training. But Melvin heard the Rangers might lose him for
$50,000 in Monday's Rule V draft and pressed to get the trade done.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
