<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PITCHERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHERS FIND FREE-AGENT MARKET SLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Greg Vaughn, the best hitter on the free-agent
market, signed with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley, the best pitcher on the market, continues to look
for a job.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's winter meetings were supposed to produce a flurry of
activity, with agents shopping their players to the assembled
general managers. The setting did land new jobs for Vaughn, who
received a four-year, $34 million deal from Tampa Bay, and Todd
Zeile, who got $18 million over three years from the New York Mets.
But there has been absolutely no movement among free-agent
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been less activity this winter on the free-agent
market front than I've seen in years,'' Indians general manager
John Hart said. ``I don't remember it being this slow.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not likely to speed up before the meetings wrap up Tuesday.
Some general managers left town Monday night, and most of the rest
are departing Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   At this time last year, Randy Johnson had signed with the
Arizona Diamondbacks and Kevin Brown with the Los Angeles Dodgers.
This year, Finley, Aaron Sele, Kenny Rogers and the rest of the
pitching class of '99 remain unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to shed any tears. They won't be showing up on
the welfare rolls or in the soup kitchens. Eventually, the will all
get their millions.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe, just maybe, they won't get the millions they want.
</P>
<P>
   For once, the GMs aren't playing the game. That would be the
game where the agent says I want $10 million a year for my client,
and the GM says no one day, maybe the next and OK the third.
</P>
<P>
   Not this year, though, and not for these pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is slow, it's because of the lack of available
superstars on the marketplace,'' said agent Jeff Moorad, who
doesn't represent any of the unsigned pitchers. ``There are a
number of quality players available; however, this class lacks
luster. As a result, you're not going to have the bang-bang-bang
signings right out of the chute.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: teams aren't willing to spend superstar money for
non-superstar talent.
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame the agents for asking. After all, Moorad
engineered the trade between the Dodgers and Blue Jays for two of
his clients, right fielders Shawn Green and Raul Mondesi, and then
got LA to sign Green to a six-year, $84 million extension. The
Yankees gave David Cone a one-year, $12 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers gave out that $14 million contract and the Yankees
gave out that $12 million contract, so everyone is going `Fine, I
might not be worth $15 million, or $12 million, but $10 million is
looking pretty good,' '' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   It looks pretty good to Finley's agent, Tim Shannon. That's what
he wants for each of the next three seasons for his client.
</P>
<P>
   But although Finley generally is considered the best pitcher
available, he's also 37 years old, and he's not seen as a player
who can take a team to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon spent the past four days working the hotel lobby and
meeting with GMs, telling everyone who listened that his client was
prepared to sign with the first club that produced the magic
number. He tried to force the issue with a campaign of
misinformation, saying the Yankees, the Dodgers and the Rangers are
interested. They're not, at least not at anything close to the
asking price.
</P>
<P>
   He did receive offers from the Mariners, Orioles and Indians
that, according to the rumor mill, began at $22 million for three
years and crept closer to $27 million. No one, though, hit the
magic number, and Finley remains unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be any day now,'' Shannon said. ``It could take a
day, it could be a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the rest of the free-agent pitchers remain on hold,
waiting for a Finley signing that could ignite bidding wars for
their services.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the GMs refuse to play the game, it could be a long
wait. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
