</P>
<P>
   WALLSTREET-PAYDAYS (New York) _ Wall Street is overflowing with
holiday cheer: Investment banks have set aside $13 billion to pay
bonuses, up 20 percent from last year. Pay packages above $10
million are no longer rare. Yet among Wall Street professionals
whose incomes still astound the rest of America, the mood has
changed. One top trader bemoans the ``opportunity cost'' of
remaining a financier in the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLISHING-TALKS (Undated) _ Less than a year and a half after
buying the nation's premier publishing house, the Bertelsmann media
conglomerate is poised to form a partnership with an American icon
of popular literature, Time Inc.'s Book-of-the-Month Club. By
Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-AUTO-TRENDS (Paris) _ Clogged cities, astronomical gas
prices and a tradition of compact cars would seem to make most of
Europe less hospitable than the United States to the sport utility
vehicle. But Europeans _ to the delight of auto industry executives
and the dismay of environmentalists and traffic planners _ are
taking to the vehicles in a big way, moving up from their midget
Fiat Cinquecentos and Renault Twingos. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-GLITCHES (Undated) _ In the first few days of next year,
hundreds of thousands of Americans are likely to discover that they
cannot get cash from a teller machine. Others will suddenly lose
power, or be greeted with silence when they pick up their
telephones. Although many people who encounter such difficulties
will blame them on Y2K computer problems, they may well be wrong.
By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ After several high-profile shootings
in schools this year, lawmakers, parents and educators have been
looking for ways to help curb youth violence. Madison Avenue has
traditionally tried to support such efforts by creating public
service advertising. But one advertising executive has taken a
different approach. By Westray Battle.
</P>
