</P>
<P>
   SCI-STONEAGE-FASHIONS (Undated) _ According to three
anthropologists, it is time to toss aside the hidebound cliches of
Paleolithic woman. Researchers have found evidence that the women
of the so-called upper Paleolithic era were far more accomplished,
economically powerful and sartorially gifted than previously
believed. By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-POLIO (Undated) _ It is a turn of events that might have
delighted Dr. Jonas Salk: nearly 40 years after the United States
abandoned his injectable polio vaccine in favor of the oral version
created by his rival, Dr. Albert Sabin, the pendulum has swung back
the other way. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SLOAN-SKY-SURVEY (Undated) _ Using a technique akin to
overlaying thousands of faint X-ray images to create one sharp
picture, astronomers have discovered that typical galaxies may be
twice as large and contain twice as much mass as suggested by
previous measurements. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME (Undated) _ Biologists cannot yet synthesize a living
cell from the appropriate chemicals. But in the light of recent
research findings, the project has at least become conceivable. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RUSSIAN-LAKE (Undated) _ Russian, American and French
scientists are closing in on the secrets of a Lake Vostok, which
lies beneath a nearly two-mile thickness of ice covering the South
Polar Plateau _ a lake thought to resemble similar bodies of water
elsewhere in the solar system, and beyond.  &QL; 
By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GULF-DEADZONE (Undated) _ There has been a significant
increase in the expanse of the Gulf of Mexico's ``Dead Zone,'' an
area spreading from the Mississippi River too overrun with
pollution to support any marine life.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEDICAL-CASES (Undated) _ All the talk about medical errors
in Washington these days leaves the impression that now that the
problem is finally acknowledged, a solution is already in sight.
Would that it were so. Unlike aviation or any other industry,
medicine is a world etched in perilous shades of gray. By Abigail
Zuger, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GEORGE-WASHINGTON (Undated) _ Two hundred years ago Tuesday,
on Dec. 14, 1799, the first president of the United States died at
the age of 67 in his bed at Mount Vernon. Washington's doctors said
the cause was ``inflammatory quinsy,'' a severe infection of the
throat, but to this day controversy has surrounded his death. Did
Washington die because of medical malpractice? By Herbert Mitgang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREATHE-CDC (Undated) _ A respiratory virus that often
overwhelms pediatric clinics in winter has arrived in force, the
Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta says, and is causing twice
the hospitalization rate scientists expected. By Kenneth B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PERSONAL-TRAINERS (Undated) _ These days, personal training
is often not so personal. Around the country, growing numbers of
trainers are offering the benefits of one-on-one fitness to small
groups of people who would prefer to sweat together. By Linda
Villarosa.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Second of two columns on
bereavement. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Science notes and news: Items on coral
around oil rigs, tiny tweezers and birth of giant planets. By Henry
Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Can you reinfect yourself with an infectious
disease from which you are recovering, perhaps through exposure to
residual germs on your hands? By C. Claiborne Ray.
</P>
