<HEADER>
A8269 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-GRIZZLIE     12-14 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-GRIZZLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS END LOSING STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Clippers' lottery positioning was
horribly sabotaged Monday night when they were goaded into a 102-90
victory by the high-draft-pick hoggin' Vancouver Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   As the showcase event of the NBA's evening (it happened to be
the only game scheduled opposite ``Monday Night Football'' and
``Ally McBeal''), two of the best 4-16 teams the league had to
offer reinvented the sport in front of 9,303 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the reactionary cartwheels were preempted when guard
Derek Anderson limped off the court with 16 points and a bad ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The signature culprits in helping end the Clips' convincing
nine-game losing streak were point guard Troy Hudson (18 points, a
season-high 11 assists), center Michael Olowokandi (16 points, 10
rebounds) and power forward Maurice Taylor (a season-high 26
points, 8 rebounds), who admitted his team's recent trail of woe
prevented looking ahead to tonight's house party with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to go out and get a win first,'' said Taylor, who made
9 of 12 field-goal attempts in the first half. ``If I knew what was
wrong with us, I'd have told everybody a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody already knew. The Clips didn't pass the ball, rarely
moved without the ball and offered scant resistance when the other
team had the ball. And the schedule faced by the league's youngest
team has been a bit sinister.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, they finally were picked on by somebody their
own size. For ailing teams, the Grizzlies are the antibiotic of the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Despite getting thumped in an earlier trip to Vancouver, the
Clippers realized that _ on paper _ the Grizzlies represented a
nice opportunity for victory.
</P>
<P>
   So, with Hudson resurrected as the starting point guard, they
shared the ball enough to finish the first half with 17 assists and
a field-goal percentage of 60 percent. (They average an
unreasonably cold 41 percent.) Against the slacker defense of
Vancouver's Mike Bibby, Hudson had 11 points and 8 assists by
intermission. While Hudson demonstrated signs of life, rookie Lamar
Odom was behaving as the altruistic decoy. Odom responded to his
recent slump by only squeezing off only 3 field-goal attempts in
the first half (he made 2), while picking off 4 rebounds and
handing off 3 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson's 3-pointer at 3:33 in round two gave the Clips a 49-36
advantage, their largest of the half. The Grizzlies trimmed that to
8, but Tyrone Nesby's swooped in for a dunk to end the half in a
59-49 Clipper lead.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dickerson had 14 for Vancouver, which was treated to a
3-point half by point guard Mike Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   Shareef Abdur-Rahim went to work (nine points) in the third
quarter, but Olowokandi had 7 for the Clips, whose margin was nine
(84-75) entering the fourth period.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: During the Clippers' 9-game march of doom, they only
managed to outscore the opposition in 8 of 36 quarters. ...
Olowokandi, who averaged 18 points and 12 rebounds during last
week's 3-game road swing, admits he feels a lot more comfortable
playing away from Staples Center. ``There's no doubt about it,''
Olowokandi, the first pick in the 1998 NBA Draft said of his
comfort level away from the scrutiny of the home crowd. ``And
that's a shame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 0153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8270 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-ANALYSIS-     12-14 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SAY THEY AREN'T DONE YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Southland, and baseball, continued to
shake their heads Monday about the Los Angeles Dodgers' unloading
of salary the day before.
</P>
<P>
   But before everyone is done piling on and saying the Dodgers
were absolutely robbed in the trade that sent pitcher Ismael Valdes
and second baseman Eric Young to the Chicago Cubs for reliever
Terry Adams and a pair of minor-league pitchers, general manager
Kevin Malone wants everyone to understand the offseason moves
aren't completed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have no natural leadoff hitter, but by April 3 when
the season begins in Montreal they may. They have no solid
major-league second baseman, but by April 3 they may. The Dodgers
may need another starting pitcher, or help in the bullpen, but they
have time.
</P>
<P>
   The dumping of Young's and Valdes' combined $10.5 million
contracts next season put the Dodgers in position to make other
moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're saying, `This is the team,''' Malone said.
``We're in the middle of a process. Opening day is not tomorrow,
it's months away. We have a few more things to do. This trade puts
us in better position to strengthen our club and be able to make
other moves. Opening day is not today.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers brass doesn't dispute the financial implications of the
deal. The Dodgers claim to have lost close to $20 million last
season, and they had to slice from somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Dodgers are already committed to approximately $80
million of salary, and that's expected to escalate to $86-$89
million by spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Malone points out the Dodgers went 77-85 with the group that
included Raul Mondesi, Young and Valdes. He also said this isn't
the first move, but rather the latest in a series of moves that
began with the acquisition of Shawn Green for Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, we think we can get better without (Valdes and Young),''
Malone said. ``Two, we created some financial flexibility to
address our bullpen and bench weakness and, three, we think we can
improve the overall makeup and chemistry of the club. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The public may be waiting for the Dodgers to sign or trade for
another marquee player, but that's not the plan. Instead, they are
looking into signing second- and third-tier free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore free agent Arthur Rhodes remains a long shot, but
Malone talked with his representatives Sunday. Rhodes wants a
four-year contract, a major deterrent for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The club is also looking into signing either Steve Avery or Jeff
Fassero to fill the left-handed void in the bullpen and perhaps
challenge for the lefty spot in the starting rotation. While
sources said Malone spoke with representatives for both players,
two sources said the Dodgers would prefer to sign both players to
minor-league contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are also looking to strengthen their bench, and
utility player Shawon Dunston is a possibility. Dunston, a close
friend of Dodgers center fielder Devon White, said, ``I wouldn't
mind coming to Los Angeles, I'm not going to lie to you.'' But
Dunston, who can play shortstop, third base or outfield, said he
thought he would wind up back with the Mets or in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Malone is slated to talk to Kurt Abbott's
representatives today, though an offer for the former Colorado
infielder isn't expected.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, much of the Dodgers' plans remain on hold while the
Adrian Beltre saga drags on. A source familiar with the talks said
the decision would be announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, executive vice president of baseball operations
for the Office of the Commissioner, said the fact-finding portion
of the investigation is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``His potential free agency has not been a factor in the pace of
this inquiry,'' Alderson said. ``The fact that the possibility
exists has been a burden on both the player, reportedly, as well as
the club. That's unfortunate in both cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to do, from a conceptual standpoint, I think
aside from this case ... we have to make sure there's an interest
on the part of everyone involved to comply with the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The case could leave Beltre, and the Dodgers, in limbo until
late January. If Beltre isn't declared a free agent and a grievance
is filed, it could take more than a month to sort out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 0157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
