<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MEETINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS MAY NOT BE AN ANGEL FOR LONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ As of Monday night, Jim Edmonds was still an Angel.
But how long that remains true could be counted in days, even
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels and Oakland A's are on the verge of making a
deal that would send the 29-year-old center fielder, a one-time
American League All-Star and two-time Gold Glove winner with a .290
career batting average, to the A's for a package of minor-leaguers
and possibly second baseman Scott Spiezio.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the deal would be pitcher Brett Laxton, a 26-year-old
right-hander who went 13-8 with a 3. 46 ERA in 25 starts for
Triple-A Vancouver last season. He also pitched in three games for
the A's, going 0-1 with a 7.45 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The others expected to be involved in the deal are outfielder
Mario Encarnacion and third baseman Adam Piatt. Both players split
time last season between Double-A Midland and Vancouver. Piatt hit
.345 with 39 homers and 135 RBIs in 129 games for Midland.
Encarnacion hit .309 at Midland.
</P>
<P>
   If he's involved in the deal, Spiezio would likely become the
Angels' starting second baseman, but he's hardly the leadoff-type
hitter they've been looking for. Last season, Spiezio, 27, hit .243
with 8 homers and 33 RBIs in 89 games for the A's, and also played
28 games for Vancouver, where he hit .390. It's possible the Angels
prefer a second baseman from the A's minor league system instead.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams were believed to be close to finalizing the trade
Monday afternoon, but Oakland GM Billy Beane checked out of his
room at the Anaheim Marriott, site of the Winter Meetings, before
nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stoneman awaited word from the A's, and set a 7 p.m.
deadline - when he left to attend a baseball dinner function.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds' agent, Paul Cohen, was in touch with Edmonds all
afternoon, keeping his client up to date on the day's events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a good place for him,'' Cohen said of Oakland. ``He
loves hitting in that ballpark and he likes the guys on that team.
He's torn by the fact he's from here. But if the Angels decide to
move him, that's a place he'll like playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds is eligible for free agency after the 2000 season and
has a list of nine teams he said he will not sign an extension with
if traded. The A's, Cohen said, are not one of those teams. But
whether or not the A's could afford Edmonds - who could command
anywhere from $6 million to $9 million per season - remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at it logically you say one year and out,'' Cohen
said. ``But I don't necessarily know that to be the case. It's my
understanding that with new ownership coming in, they can get
creative. And they don't come any shrewder than Billy Beane.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Edmonds is not talking to the media until a deal is
made, but said the former Diamond Bar High standout is feeling good
about his situation and is working out three to four hours a day
and getting in great shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mind is set now because of the way events have unfolded,''
Cohen said. ``He has a 10-month window that will determine his
future. Last year at this time, he was anxious. Now, it's a relaxed
curiosity. He believes he's going to have an MVP-type season.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman was typically tight-lipped about the situation and
would not mention names or even the team involved. But he admitted
he expected something to happen soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anything else, it's just a matter of making things
work,'' he said. ``There's an offer there that should make things
work. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Edmonds deal will be consumated, Stoneman
said he'll continue to talk with a number of teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've dealt with a lot of things today and there are still
other possibilities,'' he said. ``We've had some very productive
discussions. We know a lot more now than we did coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman will check out of his hotel room this morning and
conduct business from his Edison Field office. He came into the
meetings hoping and expecting to get something done, but he said
Monday it wasn't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a trading deadline tonight at midnight,'' he said.
``It's nice everybody's here, but phones still work.''
</P>
<P>
   If Edmonds is traded, it would end a bittersweet 12 years in the
organization, a time when many believe his potential for greatness
was overshadowed only by the perception of wasted talent.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds' best season came in 1995, when he hit .290 with 33
homers, 107 RBIs and 120 runs scored. In 1997, he made what some
have called the greatest catch ever, making a diving, over-the-head
catch of a long drive hit by the Royals' David Howard in Kansas
City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
