<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERCIVAL TORN ABOUT WANTING TO LEAVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Agent Paul Cohen had lunch with three of his
clients Monday, Jim Edmonds, Troy Percival and Mike James. Cohen
said Percival continues to ``welcome'' a trade to a contender, but
isn't necessarily in a hurry to leave the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where it stands right now is he's torn between playing at home
in front of the home fans vs. being in a situation with a team that
can win right away,'' Cohen said. ``He realizes it will be an
uphill struggle in Anaheim and he wants to pitch for a team that's
going to be in it at the end. In the past it was not even something
he would look at. But he's not 25 anymore. He's 30 and he's only
got so many years left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had conversations with Mr. Stoneman and expressed Troy's
issues. But obviously, it would take a tremendous trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival is signed through next season with club options for
both the 2001 and 2002 seasons. His 139 career saves is the most in
franchise history, with a single-season career-high 42 saves coming
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Two picked: The Angels selected two players Monday in the Rule V
Major League draft, taking pitcher Derrick Turnbow, 21, from the
Phillies organization and catcher Jaime Escalante, 22, from the
Orioles organization.
</P>
<P>
   By rule, the two were placed on the Angels' 40-man roster. If
they are not on the 25-man roster on opening day, they must be
placed on waivers and be available to any team. If no team claims
them, the Angels must then offer them back to their original club.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman said he thought there was a good chance Turnbow, a
hard-throwing right-hander, could make the major league club as a
reliever next season even though he pitched at the Single-A level
last season, going 12-8 with a 3.35 ERA in 26 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's interesting,'' Stoneman said of Turnbow, who has a
fastball clocked at 94-95 mph. ``We did something different than
most teams did. We reached way down to Class-A to find a player,
and not even a high-A league. Our reports on this pitcher are that
he's a special pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also lost a player in the Rule V draft, as outfieder
Marcus Knight, who played at Double-A Erie last season, was
selected by the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Talks continue: Tim Shannon, agent for ex-Angels pitcher Chuck
Finley, continues to talk with a number of interested teams but is
in no hurry to get anything done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several teams want him real bad,'' Shannon said, adding that
he believes there will be a flurry of other free-agent signings
after Finley signs. ``I think everybody's waiting on us. He seems
to be the marquee player right now. Usually it behooves the No. 2-
and 3-tier guys to wait until the top tier guy goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
