<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WINNING MAKEOVER FOR SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took Sandy Koufax eight seasons before he learned the
rudiments of his craft and became the most dominant pitcher of his
generation. He was 26.
</P>
<P>
   It took Michael Jordan seven seasons before he understood fully
the nuances of his sport, and his Chicago Bulls suddenly became
perennial NBA world champions. He was 27.
</P>
<P>
   It took Wilt Chamberlain eight season before he realized that
50-point games were meaningless if your team kept losing, and his
Philadelphia 76ers responded to his changed outlook during the
1966-67 campaign by winning a league-record 68 games and the NBA
title.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I went out to Staples Center the other evening, and saw a
similar transformation in the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal, who put on
the kind of sterling clinical basketball exhibition that John
Wooden would have applauded.
</P>
<P>
   I kept rubbing my eyes thinking I was witnessing a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   At 27, Shaquille O'Neal played with a maturity, a purpose, a
resolve Sunday night against the Detroit Pistons that I've never
witnessed during his seven previous seasons in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, this wasn't the same Shaquille O'Neal I had become
accustomed to watching the past three years with the Lakers, the
plodding O'Neal who'd huff and puff listlessly up and down the
floor, content to grab a few rebounds, negotiate the usual gaggle
of rim-thundering dunks, expend modest amounts of energy, and do
absolutely nothing to enhance the play of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But against the Pistons, O'Neal was a sight to behold, going
after rebounds with uncharacteristic abandon at both ends of the
court, swatting away Piston shots, and methodically taking command
of the entire proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it without a rest.
</P>
<P>
   He played the first 40 minutes of the game - Phil Jackson took
him out for good early in the fourth quarter when the Lakers had a
commanding lead - and never seemed to tire.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics reflected his dominance - 24 rebounds, 22 points,
four blocks - but they didn't reflect what an intimidating factor
he was throughout the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you saw out there tonight was a great player at the peak
of his skills,'' said an interested observer, Jerry West, the Laker
executive who was responsible for O'Neal signing with the team
during the summer of 1996. ``Actually, Shaquille has been playing
like this all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got himself in tremendous shape in the off-season, and he's
been totally committed from the first day of training camp. I know
he believes totally in Phil's system. I think without a doubt he's
been the best player in the league. No one's been able to handle
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, if only Shaquille O'Neal could shoot free throws.
</P>
<P>
   If he could, the Lakers would breeze to a world title.
</P>
<P>
   They'd never lose one of those close games they have so often in
the past because of O'Neal's shortcoming in this category.
</P>
<P>
   But such a deficiency might not make that much difference this
season because the Lakers figure to be holding commanding leads
late if O'Neal continues his ferociously effective work.
</P>
<P>
   I can't believe how different O'Neal's approach has become on
the court.
</P>
<P>
   When he gets the ball, his first instinct now is to pass to an
open teammate instead of trying to score.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, he no longer lolls around the middle, but gets
actively involved in double teams and contests almost every shot an
opponent attempts inside.
</P>
<P>
   He would have lengthy moments of inertness in the past, but now
he never stops hustling.
</P>
<P>
   I've never seen a man of his immense size - he's listed at
7-foot-1 and 315 pounds but probably weighs closer to 350 - move
with such quickness and agility.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, I saw Wilt Chamberlain often, even covered him
full-time for a few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain could maneuver well also, but he'd have had serious
problems containing O'Neal, who simply can maneuver better.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as promising as this latest incarnation of Shaquille
O'Neal is, there are questions looming over the Lakers, who are
tied with Portland at 17-5 for the league's top record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a very favorable early-season schedule with most of
our games at home,'' says West. ``We still have to prove we can win
on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   And Shaquille O'Neal and the abundantly exciting, vexingly
undisciplined Kobe Bryant still have to prove they can function
smoothly together.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant still might be five or six years away from reaching the
maturation level that O'Neal seemingly has attained.
</P>
<P>
   He led the Lakers with 26 points and elicited the usual oohs and
aahs from the fans against the Pistons, but he also threw up 24
shots in a mere 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant still doesn't have the foggiest notion of what
constitutes team basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But, if there is a coach capable of teaching him, it is Phil
Jackson, whom Jerry West credits for O'Neal's remarkable turnabout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil Jackson just has a terrific rapport with the players,''
says West. ``He has a presence about him, and the players seem to
have great confidence in him. He has a nice way with them. And he
doesn't care who he gets on. If a player needs scolding, Phil will
do it. And, most importantly, the players will listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is listening more attentively these days than Shaquille
O'Neal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 0217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
