<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA MORE AT HOME THAN WASHINGTON IN KEYARENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After what took place on the hardwood in KeyArena last
March, it was inevitable what happened Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga won the opening tip from the University of Washington.
Axel Dench tapped the ball back to guard Matt Santangelo and before
you knew it, Casey Calvary was throwing down a two-hand jam.
</P>
<P>
   These names are familiar. The kind of basketball they play is,
too.
</P>
<P>
   And before you knew it, the Bulldogs were running off a lead,
fueled by their defense.
</P>
<P>
   Down 6-0, Huskies senior Deon Luton found himself trapped at
half court. A double-team forced a turnover that allowed an outlet
pass to Santangelo, who knew exactly what he was going to do.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo all but strutted unscathed to the basket, where he
delivered a 180-degree, midair spin that finished with a
back-handed, two-hand dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, it was Gonzaga 8, Huskies 0. Time out,
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   After last March, something like this was to be expected _ all
the way down to the 76-66 Gonzaga victory that head coach Mark Few
called better than Gonzaga's win Saturday over 11th-ranked UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way (my team) executed.'' Few said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Coach (Bob) Bender would find a way for them to take us
out of our primary option, and they did. That we were able to go to
our third and fourth options and be successful is a sign of
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The college basketball season kicked off in earnest Monday with
the Huskies' home opener.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's home court for the Huskies felt every bit as
much a homecoming for the Bulldogs. At least that's how the
Bulldogs seemed to treat the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   The cheers before the opening tipoff were split between the two
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The logos on sweatshirts and ballcaps throughout KeyArena
boasted allegiance to both the Zags and the Dawgs, proof that what
went down in this town last spring was not forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga became college basketball's newest darlings.
</P>
<P>
   And they were born here.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Bulldogs were a force to be reckoned with all last
season, when they scorched the West Coast Conference on a hell-bent
mission not to be denied an invitation to the NCAA tournament. The
Bulldogs were hot before setting a sneaker in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But essentially, Gonzaga's coming out party came to a rocking
crescendo right here.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that the Bulldogs knocked off Minnesota and Stanford
in the sub-regional of the 1999 NCAA tournament before rolling to
the Elite Eight and coming excruciatingly close to a trip to the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   If only Santangelo had hit one or two of those jumpers in
Phoenix, where the West Regional Final was within a fingernail of
the Bulldogs' possession ...
</P>
<P>
   If only UConn's Richard Hamilton weren't so silky smooth and the
Big East big dogs weren't on a mandate to win coach Jim Calhoun's
first national championship ...
</P>
<P>
   If fate had twisted a little more in Gonzaga's favor, then the
little school from the other side of the mountains would have been
dancing big at the big dance.
</P>
<P>
   So, it was inevitable what happened Monday, really, given this
bit of history.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that set up the inevitable question: Whose court
is this?
</P>
<P>
   The Zags had a right to stake a greater claim, beating the
Huskies as they should, considering their No. 22 national ranking
and their desire to repeat this season what they did last.
</P>
<P>
   The young Huskies and Bender understood what they were facing,
which probably explained the energy the Dawgs expended trying to
win back the bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they didn't like to come out as the underdogs against
us, being a Pac-10 team,'' Calvary said, understanding the Huskies'
mindset.
</P>
<P>
   And for a few flashes, the Huskies tried to bite back.
</P>
<P>
   Thalo Green stole the ball just before the first half ended and
went in for an underhanded scoop to pull the Dawgs within one.
</P>
<P>
   But Santangelo seemed destined to suck back any Husky momentum.
The senior guard nailed a long 3-pointer at the buzzer to give the
Zags a 37-33 lead _ which was challenged only once in the second
half when the Huskies tied it at 47.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long ago that the Huskies were one of those college
basketball darlings. One year before the Zags almost blew into the
greatest show in college athletics, it was Bender's Huskies who had
their fun run to glory.
</P>
<P>
   College basketball relies on its darlings.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga and Washington can both count on having seasons that
make the local college hoops loyalists swoon.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer scholarships being offered across the board by all
Division I schools and with more big-time programs losing top
recruits to the pros after one or two seasons, it is more and more
likely that schools like Washington and Gonzaga can lure impact
players to their programs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Luton is about all the Huskies have this season, with his
ability to elevate and score. But he needs a Donald Watts and/or a
Todd MacCulloch around him to make him as good as he can be. Bender
won't stop until he gets another solid squad to take the Huskies to
the dance again.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Zags rely on Santangelo. He was the kid that got
away from Stanford, which made Arthur Lee a priority. Now look at
Santangelo. He was back in town Monday to put a little footnote on
what he and the Zags started.
</P>
<P>
   It was a perfect way to begin a season, perhaps even for Huskies
fans, who know a darling when they see one.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
