<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8287 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BKC-UW-GONZAGA-SPI &LR;      12-14 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UW-GONZAGA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLDOGS WIN NORTHWEST DOG FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This is where the tale of the overachieving underdog
began, in KeyArena featuring Gonzaga in the 1999 NCAA tournament.
Unfortunately for Washington, Monday night looked like last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies battled until the final horn, but the Bulldogs
emerged with a 76-66 victory in what was supposed to be
Washington's first home game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't seem that way for two reasons. It was the Huskies'
first game in KeyArena, where they will be playing all season while
Hec Edmundson Pavilion is being renovated. Secondly, there were
plenty of Gonzaga fans in the crowd of 8,637, creating an
environment of mixed company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was wonderful,'' Bender said, referring to the
new home, not the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was different,'' said UW point guard Senque Carey. ``It's
not Hec Ed, but at the same time, it has a roof over it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was his best line of the night. The one in the box score
showed 4-for-16 shooting and four turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always found that Senque bounces back pretty well,'' said
UW coach Bob Bender. ``Tonight was a tough one for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey, who hit 7 of 7 threes in his last game at Old Dominion,
is just like the team he plays for, filled with potential and heart
but prone to inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, Gonzaga won, taking advantage of an
assortment of Washington mistakes. Missed free throws and field
goals resulted in a missed opportunity because the Bulldogs, for
all of their talent and experience, could have been had Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   For the past nine days, Gonzaga has ping-ponged across the
country from Cleveland and Spokane to Chicago and Spokane to Los
Angeles and Seattle. This was their fourth game on the road.
Compared to Cincinnati, Temple and UCLA, the Huskies could have
been lightly regarded. But they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, this was the state championship game for us,'' said
Richie Frahm, the smooth-shooting forward from Battleground who led
Gonzaga with 19 points. ``A lot of us weren't recruited by them.
We've all got chips on our shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies were motivated, too, realizing the caliber of the
competition after watching Gonzaga become one of the best eight
teams in the country last year. And then seeing the Bulldogs on TV
against the nation's elite this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of hype,'' said Michael Johnson, who scored 10
points and distributed eight assists. ``We all knew it was a big
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies were out of sorts in the beginning, as if they felt
uncomfortable in this kind of company. Gonzaga bolted in front 8-0,
combining steals with jams and layins, running circles around their
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Bender called a timeout and admonished the Huskies right after
sophomore guard Bryan Brown blasted his teammates himself.
</P>
<P>
   A blowout appeared imminent until Deon Luton showed up, giving
Washington stability and a remarkable dose of accuracy. The senior
shooting guard made his first five shots, from every angle on the
floor. Luton keyed an 11-0 run that put Washington ahead 18-14. He
scored 15 points in a little more than four minutes and finished
with 23.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga recovered, first getting a lift from its standout point
guard, Matt Santangelo, who will be running someone else's offense
on this floor next year at the next level. After making just one of
his first seven shots, Santangelo drilled a three at the first-half
horn, right when it appeared Thalo Green had given momentum to
Washington with a steal and a layin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the scrappiest team we've played this year,'' Frahm
said. ``Washington played a lot tougher than UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed, over and over again, the Huskies taking charges and
pursuing loose balls. The problem was, Washington hit the floor
more frequently than the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga appeared to be in control with a 66-52 lead with 6:40
remaining. But Luton, Carey and Johnson sliced the deficit to 68-64
after Johnson converted a 3-point play from the lane. A Johnson
banker kept Washington within 70-66 with 53 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The heroic ending never materialized, Gonzaga closing it out
with free throws in an appropriately ironic development. If
Washington had been more proficient at the line _ Luton was 4 for
11 unguarded, 8 for 12 with hands in his face _ the verdict could
have been reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically just missed,'' Luton said. ``I'll be shooting them
in practice every day (this week).''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies feel like they're not that far away from being as
competitive as Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually think we're pretty close,'' Johnson said. ``We're
getting used to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs know what it's like to be in Washington's position,
with doubters outnumbering believers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people don't expect much from them,''
Santangelo said. ``That's good. It got us to where we are today.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, which fell to 3-4, will try to get back to .500 on
Friday when it hosts Wichita State.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
