A8289 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SUN-WIND-SFCHRON &LR;      12-14 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-WIND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY THE SUN LOST ITS WIND  
 
 

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ A mysterious disturbance in the magnetic forces
that link Earth and the sun has puzzled _ but also delighted _
space scientists who are still pondering the event more than seven
months ago when the sun virtually ran out of wind.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Normally, the sun's outermost corona sends out a constant,
violent ``solar wind'' of electrically charged particles that speed
in all directions at a million miles an hour or more, holding
Earth's magnetic field in check.
</P>
<P>
   Those particles _ mainly electrons, protons and the nuclei of
helium _ wash Earth constantly, causing the lovely auroras that
shimmer in the night sky near the poles when the particles interact
with gases high in the upper layers of Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   During a 24-hour period around May 11, however, the solar wind
suddenly and unexpectedly died away almost completely, leaving only
a sparse and gentle rain of particles to reach Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Without resistance from the solar wind, Earth's magnetic field
stretched as far as the moon. And the auroras, normally visible as
curtains of green and yellow light, instead turned into a steady
circular glow around the North Polar region.
</P>
<P>
   The event was witnessed, recorded and its details radioed to
Earth by no fewer than 10 orbiting satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, at the annual fall meeting of the American Geophysical
Union at Moscone Center, dozens of physicists who study solar
phenomena and their effects on Earth's atmosphere confessed they
are still puzzled by the virtual disappearance of the wind.
</P>
<P>
   But they are also fascinated. Earlier satellites had seen
similar but far less conspicuous events over the past 35 years, but
never anything remotely like this sudden calm in a storm that is
normally most intense at Earth's poles.
</P>
<P>
   One of the satellites recorded a 99 percent drop in the density
of the wind's charged helium particles. The electrons, sparse as
they were, reached Earth at temperatures of a million degrees _ 10
times hotter than normal.
</P>
<P>
   To Keith Ogilvie, a space physicist at NASA's Goddard Space
Flight Center, the event gave him and his earthbound colleagues ``a
rare window to see the sun's corona directly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, our view of the corona from Earth is like seeing the
sun on an overcast, cloudy day,'' said Jack D. Scudder of the
University of Iowa. ``But on May 11, the clouds broke and we could
see it clearly. It was a very unusual opportunity, and it was very
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Scudder and Don Fairfield of the Goddard center had predicted
that this kind of event might happen, and indeed it did, with the
rain of electrons producing a steady glow over the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists who discussed the May 11 event so heatedly Monday
could not offer an explanation for its cause, but as Ogilvie said,
``it strengthens our belief that we're beginning to understand how
the sun-Earth connection works.''
</P>
<P>
