<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8371 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FLA-AFFIRM-CONTROVERS     12-14 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-AFFIRM-CONTROVERSY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Political storm brews over affirmative action
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There is a whispered urgency to the
conversation. A chat where the senior adviser to a black political
leader is so worried about what she is saying that, well, it just
can't get back to her boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We jumped on his One Florida idea because it was the first
opportunity for blacks to jump on Jeb,'' she says. Privately, she
wonders whether they are doing the right thing. Publicly, she
questions the validity of Bush's plan to do away with affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   A bit more than a month has passed since Gov. Jeb Bush offered
his idea for getting rid of affirmative action in Florida
universities and in the awarding of state contracts, saying he
wants to replace those programs with ones that help the
disadvantaged regardless of race.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed responses are not uncommon among the state's black
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush announced his plan on Nov. 9, he tried to show that he
had significant minority support: He picked popular state Sen.
Daryl Jones of Miami, who is black, to lead the effort. University
Chancellor Adam Herbert, who also is black and a friend of Bush's,
heartily endorsed the plan. On that first day, Bush seemed to have
done what he has done best since taking office this year _ forming
coalitions comprising differing factions.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, some of Bush's support began to unravel. Jones, who
would like to run for Congress after he leaves the state Senate,
suddenly announced that he didn't understand what he was getting
into, had never committed to taking a leadership role and had
developed grave doubts about Bush's plan.
</P>
<P>
   While Herbert stuck with Bush, other black leaders, such as U.S.
Rep. Corrine Brown and most of the members of the state
legislature's black caucus, opposed One Florida. During a recent
caucus, some black lawmakers complained that Bush left them out of
the planning for One Florida and then dumped it in their laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying not to be overly critical of the governor on this,
but I think what he has done is insulting,'' says state Rep. Addie
Greene. ``He's doing this just to try and make us feel good, but
when you look at the nitty-gritty what is he really doing? I think
he's just trying to help his brother win the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he intended it or not, Bush wedged himself into the
middle of a raging controversy over one of the most difficult
social issues in the nation. A controversy that could have enormous
political consequences for Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was prodded to act, in part, because California businessman
and activist Ward Connerly is trying to pass an amendment to the
Florida Constitution that would eliminate all forms of affirmative
action. Bush told Connerly to stay out of Florida, but Connerly
ignored him. And even with a setback that means Connerly may have
to wait until 2002 to get his issue before voters, the debate is
certain to have an impact on next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is already acrimonious. Connerly, a black
conservative, said Bush's plan is a weak imitation of his. U.S.
Rep. Carrie Meek, the matriarch of liberal black Democrats,
condemned the plan, saying it is an attempt to take away the
hard-won gains minorities have made since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plan, the top 20 percent of students in each high
school will be guaranteed admission to one of Florida's
universities. Bush says his plan will increase the number of
minority students in college. He also promises to improve the
process for awarding state contracts to minorities, without using
quotas.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans fear that if Connerly's amendment manages to
get on the ballot this November, huge numbers of blacks and other
minorities would go to the polls in an effort to defeat it, and
while there they will vote for Democratic candidates. Among those
who could get hurt would be Texas Gov. George W. Bush, should he
become the GOP nominee for president. Polls have indicated the
Connerly's initiative would pass easily.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeb Bush remains undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with the support we have received on the One
Florida initiative,'' Bush said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has a Mexican-American wife, worked hard in the 1998
campaign to win minority votes. Exit polls show that he got 61
percent of the Hispanic vote and 14 percent of the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   That 14 percent shook the Democratic Party, which in past
elections could count on getting nearly 95 percent of the black
vote. After the election, Bush and the Florida GOP continued to
court black support, hoping to solidify their gains. Now, with
Bush's One Florida plan and Connerly's anti-affirmative action
amendment, Democratic leaders see an opportunity to bring black
voters back to the party. Connerly will address the Forum Club in
West Palm Beach on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans for the first time in this century controlling
the governor's office and both houses of the legislature, Democrats
are looking for issues that clearly separate them from the GOP.
Affirmative action is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the things the Republican Party has tried to
do over the years, I think it becomes very clear which party has
been there for minorities,'' says Charles Whitehead, state
Democratic Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   For many black Democratic leaders, any changes to existing
programs, especially those suggested by Republicans, are suspect.
In their districts, they are reminding black voters that
Republicans do not have a history of looking out for their
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make sure that you are doing the right thing by
your constituents,'' said Greene. ``That means you have to spend
time in my district getting to know the people before you try and
do things that might affect their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to allay their fears, Bush appointed a 24-person
committee to evaluate inequities in Florida's schools. The
committee includes 12 blacks, including the chairman, Castell V.
Bryant, president of Miami-Dade Community College's north campus.
The only white man on the committee is state Sen. Jim Horne.
</P>
<P>
   ``More important than reaction to the plan is whether what we
are doing is right,'' says Bush. ``I believe improved opportunities
in purchasing and admissions is a good thing, and I will fight for
implementation of our plan.''
</P>
<P>
   With Meek, Brown and other leading black Democrats watching for
any misstep and ready to take him on, Bush could find himself in a
fight that lasts well beyond next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats have just begun to fight on this issue, I promise
you,'' said House Democratic leader Les Miller of Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: briancrowley(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
