<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8377 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX     12-14 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilot's protest justified
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Airline food has a history of being lousy. I
think it has to do with the fact that lukewarm casseroles were not
designed to be taken internally above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's been 40 years since I earned a meager living
pounding the carpeted aisles of a Martin 404 in three-inch heels,
I've never forgotten the mixed emotions elicited by an airborne
mealtime. Passengers were less sophisticated in those days and
still agog over the idea of dining in the clouds so they didn't
complain a lot. Crew members were less enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   And apparently still are. Have you heard about the Northwest
pilot who held up a flight for an hour because he didn't like the
meal he was served? Walked off the airplane, past the airport
jiffy-junk food establishments, got into a cab and went to get
himself some real food.
</P>
<P>
   The airline had a little surprise for him when he got back. They
fired him.
</P>
<P>
   These days I'm no longer a crew member but I am a frequent
flyer, and I hate airplanes that run behind schedule just as much
as the folks at Northwest do. Too many times I've been stranded in
airports at odd hours when the bookstores are closed and coffee, if
available at all, has to be prodded from the pot.
</P>
<P>
   HOWEVER. . . In the case of this 22-year veteran of airline
abuse, I would have thrown my discomfort to the winds and cheered
the hero who risked it all to protest his company's practice of
serving food that, unless you've seen a third-world dumpster for
yourself, cannot be aptly described.
</P>
<P>
   This pilot deserves a medal for bravery for all of the years he
survived on airline food and still managed to pass a first-class
physical twice a year. And if I weren't holding a ticket on
Northwest for next Friday, I'd be organizing a protest against the
firing of this man and suggesting the airline be forced to erect
statues of him in major airports around the world. I see him done
in living-color bronze, fully uniformed and caught mid-stride as he
passes
</P>
<P>
   baggage claim, remnants of his crew meal spilling to the ground
from the tray in his lowered left hand as he hails a cab with the
right.
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you folks, the sickest minds among us could never
envision food like the breakfasts Atlanta used to load on our
Constellations back in '59. Granted, it was only 14 years after the
end of WWII, but wasn't that a little beyond the sell-by date for
surplus powdered eggs? No foolin', these eggs were so green they
had to have been the inspiration for Dr. Seuss's best seller. When
we complained, the caterer got a little huffy and serviced our
flight with cold rubber pancakes for the rest of the month. We
asked if it would cost extra to vulcanize them so at least they'd
be hot.
</P>
<P>
   There were crew members who actually bid trips according to
where the airplane was to be catered. Atlanta and Miami were
definitely out. Chicago wasn't bad because we lived there and knew
where the ``slop-shop'' folks parked their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Raleigh-Durham, N.C. was the best place to lay over. Real nice
caterers there who'd let the crew stop in the kitchen and shmooz
with them over the next day's menu. Sometimes we had filet mignon
with mushrooms and real vegetables that never saw the inside of a
can. Once we had lobster.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before RDU layovers were first choice on crew bid
sheets. Senior captains who could have been flying San Juan and
earning over-water pay, flew Raleigh for the food. It was a dog
trip but we ate well _ at least until the company got the bill for
it and sent a nasty memo TO: All Flight Crews. FROM: Company. RE:
Surf 'n Turf.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, in protest, a couple of pilots showed up for work
with Batman lunchboxes strapped to their flight bags. It didn't do
any good. The company paid no attention and pretty soon their kids
wanted the lunchboxes back.
</P>
<P>
   The way I see it, Northwest got off lucky with just a ground
delay. What if the airplane had been at 30,000 feet when the pilot
got a gander at his crew meal and decided to take a hike?
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
