<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8378 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN15-COX     12-14 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Light breaks through tunnel of misdiagnoses
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tennis court lines are not supposed to
be wavy, so my wife's first reaction was, ``That's odd.''
</P>
<P>
   During a pause in a clinic she was teaching, she experimented,
closing each eye in turn. Slight problem in the left eye. Time for
an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   She remembered an ad for a free eye exam at an eye surgical
center and made an appointment for Oct. 29. After dilation and an
hour of charts and lights, the doctor offered this somber finding:
Cataracts in both eyes, beginning of glaucoma in both eyes, and a
``wet'' retina, indicative of bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned, Nellie asked: ``What can I do?''
</P>
<P>
   The glaucoma, of course, was treatable, and cataract removal is
an outpatient procedure. The doctor's upbeat observation was that
for $2,500 an eye, Nellie could get corrective laser surgery, which
would, at the same time, take care of the cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't have to wear glasses anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   First, of course, he added, she would want to get a specialist
to look at that retina.
</P>
<P>
   Our HMO pushed buttons and got her an appointment with an
ophthalmologist in three days. The new doctor was most reassuring.
He had trained at Yale, worked between two offices and had his own
surgical eye center. Like the earlier examination, the procedure
was very thorough. Different results, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first doctor was way off base,'' the HMO's doctor said,
evidently perplexed. He found no cataracts. As for glaucoma, the
readings were only ``suspect.'' And, he told Nellie, she did not
have a wet retina.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a macular hole in your left eye.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't sound good. And it wasn't. The macula is the lining
of the retina that contains the photoreceptive cells necessary for
vision. ``You will slowly lose sight in that eye,'' the doctor
informed her.
</P>
<P>
   How could this happen? Bad luck, the doctor said. What about
drops, surgery, anything? How could she teach tennis?
</P>
<P>
   Even as the doctor shook his head, he saw that she was
panicking. ``You can still play your tennis,'' he assured her.
``Babe Ruth played baseball with one eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Nellie broke down. She didn't want to believe that there wasn't
at least some particle of hope of saving her vision. ``I'm going to
get another opinion!'' she blurted out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get as many opinions as you want,'' he replied. ``But that's
the story.''
</P>
<P>
   It was raining as Nellie sat in her car and cried.
</P>
<P>
   Then she did seek another opinion, an opinion she paid for
herself because she wrongfully concluded that the HMO had taken her
as far as it would go. The next day she went to an optometrist,
desperate to hear someone, anyone tell her that she would not lose
vision in her left eye.
</P>
<P>
   The optometrist asked if she had seen a retina specialist. No,
she replied, she had seen the ophthalmologist on the HMO list, and
he had told her that it was pointless to go farther.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were my eye,'' the optician said, ``I would see a
specialist and get his opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Nellie went back to her primary care physician and insisted
that the HMO send her to a retina specialist. Dutifully, the HMO
obliged, getting her an appointment in three weeks. Nellie saw the
retina specialist, and this time the exam was exhaustive. She was
injected with dyes and dozens of pictures were taken inside her
eye. With his results spread before him, the doctor said:
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not have a macular hole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Swear it,'' Nellie said, fervently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear,'' the doctor said. ``You do not have macular
degeneration,'' he pointed out. ``You do not have cataracts. Years
down the road you might have glaucoma. What you do have is a
membrane that's grown over the macula, a puckered film that
distorts your vision.''
</P>
<P>
   He showed her the pictures. She saw the wrinkled membrane that
explained the wavy lines on the tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   ``And something can be done?'' my wife wondered hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, how bad is this problem?'' the doctor asked. ``Can you
live with it? There is a surgery that can remove the membrane, but
in 60 percent of the cases, a cataract forms within the year which,
of course, must be removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the specialist assured her that the condition will not get
worse or affect her reading or driving, Nellie has decided that she
can put up with the occasional wavy line on the tennis court
</P>
<P>
   My wife is grateful. Grateful for the optician who said if it
were his eye, he would consult a specialist. Grateful for our HMO,
which moved on her request even though its own ophthalmologist said
it would be pointless. Grateful for a doctor who correctly
diagnosed her condition. Grateful enough to want their names known
_ optometrist Dr. O.K. Haugen for the referral, Health Options for
honoring her wishes, and retina specialist Dr. Randy Katz for going
the extra mile.
</P>
<P>
   I see no reason to name others who offered what I am sure were
defensible opinions, given their limitations. I'll leave the final
words to Nellie. ``When it's your health or your life at stake,
insist on a second or third or even fourth opinion. Remember that
doctors aren't Gods, they're fallible human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: ronwiggins(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
