<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crusade for clean language good fit for mean times
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Chick Lewis is doing everything in her power to
make Waco known worldwide for something other than an inferno on
the prairie.
</P>
<P>
   She's doing everything in her power from this base to make the
world something more than a spinning swirl of expletives and
put-downs.
</P>
<P>
   The world needs this. Regardless of what gaseous pollutants have
done to the atmosphere, the spewing of thoughtless words degrades
us all and raises global temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   We've become so casual about callousness. We have so
institutionalized the profane and perverse.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the children _ lean, mean and obscene. They know not
what they do, what consequences words can carry. We must again
teach them to look before they bleep, and remind ourselves as well.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Chick Lewis' mission has been since she retired as a
nurse at the Department of Veterans Affairs Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   She was inspired to make it her cause while sampling the
language of female inmates in a jail ministry which she continues
weekly with a group called Nurses for Christ. She made it a point
to make inmates think about what they were saying, what it said
about them. Success in that venue encouraged her to ask everyone to
think about what they say.
</P>
<P>
   She's been mentioned on Paul Harvey and in lots of news stories.
She's distributed bumper stickers, T-shirts, ball caps. She speaks
to civic groups. Recently Waco Transit stuck her insignia on a bus.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem like a one-woman movement, but one woman's constant
motion can cause a swirl that unites, like the blades of an
ice-cream crank.
</P>
<P>
   In September two new elementary schools opened up in Waco.
Realizing this, and not wanting to miss an audience, Lewis hustled
over to Provident Heights Elementary to see if it would like to
post her decals. They were already up.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis isn't about playing censor or writing laws telling people
what they can't say. She's simply asking people to be more
thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 we've seen over and over the ravages of unkindness.
We've seen children so estranged from friends and the world that
they would take a weapon into a school and kill indiscriminately.
We've tossed social theories and zero-tolerance notions about. The
only thing that we know would have made a lick of difference is
what Chick Lewis is advocating. Just be nice to one another. Watch
what you say. Know that words hurt. Words degrade.
</P>
<P>
   Bullets only finish what words start. Chick Lewis did not
discover this. She's only reminding people of it, this
world-changing advice.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to help, write Lewis at 5831 Caldwell, Waco,
Texas, 76710.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung (at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
