<HEADER>
A8382 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-JANE-POWELL15-COX     12-14 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANE-POWELL15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MGM songbird takes flight again in movie, TV shows
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jane Powell, the ingenue songbird of the
golden era of the MGM movie musicals, doesn't mind talking about
the past, but she would much rather look ahead. After all, at 70,
the still perky Powell has a new movie waiting to be released and a
couple of television projects to be aired. ``Just a few things to
keep me off the streets,'' she says. And she is taking computer
lessons to get ready for the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, she is in town to introduce a screening of 1954's
``Seven Brides for Seven Brothers.'' Although virtually absent from
films since 1958's ``Enchanted Island,'' a movie Powell groans at
the mere mention of, she is anything but bitter about her
inactivity. ``Well, my life has just changed. I've done a lot of
plays and lectures and that kind of thing,'' she says by phone from
her New York apartment. ``Y'know, you have your moment in the sun
and then something else happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those were a Broadway debut in 1973 in ``Irene,'' filling
in for MGM colleague Debbie Reynolds, and a few Polident
commercials. She wrote her autobiographies (''The Girl Next Door''
and ``How She Grew'') in 1988, and, for the past 11 years, has been
busy enjoying life with her fourth husband, former child
star-turned-publicist Dickie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   While she once told interviewer Rex Reed, ``I didn't quit
movies, they quit me,'' you won't catch Powell spouting regrets.
``Well, there haven't been that many offered, because of my age and
because they think of me as just being a singer or a dancer,'' she
says evenly. ``And they stopped making musicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Of her classic musicals _ merry production number-filled romps
such as ``Royal Wedding,'' ``Hit the Deck'' and ``Nancy Goes to
Rio'' _ she says, ``It's just wonderful that people still remember
them and that they're still popular.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven Brides for Seven Brothers,'' considered one of the best
movie musicals of all time, was made with low expectations by the
studio. ``Ours was a sleeper,'' concedes Powell. ``They even took
some of the budget away before they even made it,'' diverting the
money instead to Vincente Minnelli and Gene Kelly's ``Brigadoon.''
To widespread surprise, including Powell's, the lively Western,
about seven marriage-minded siblings who kidnap their prospective
mates and take them home to the avalanche-prone mountains, proved
far more popular and enduring.
</P>
<P>
   To Powell, it was just one more assignment. ``I was under
contract, so I just did what it was they told me.'' She singles out
``Seven Brides'' as the movie whose success surprised her the most,
finally sensing it had box office potential when it was booked to
open at Radio City Music Hall. ``That meant it was kind of a
shoo-in for it being successful,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   She gives prime credit to choreographer Michael Kidd, rather
than director Stanley Donen. ``He really made the movie what it
was. He was really the star of the show, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, viewers of the movie can see where the corners were cut.
``Because they cut the budget, we did not go on location. So we had
to use backdrops, and some of the backdrops are really terrible,''
Powell says with a laugh. ``They're just awful. They even chose
ones that weren't painted well.'' The avalanche scene is certainly
effective, but as she notes, ``That was stock footage. Even with
all that, it still surmounted all of its problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell expects to reminisce today about her studio days, to drop
a few names of stars, answer audience questions and introduce
``Seven Brides.'' Just don't ask her to sit and watch it. ``I don't
watch my movies. They make me too nervous,'' she says. ``I don't
live in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, her present and future are so active. Still to come,
she's unsure when, is the release of the movie ``Picture This.''
``Oh, it's just a little vignette in an independent movie,'' she
insists at the mention of it. ``I'm just a visitor at the art
gallery. I just made her a very Chatty Cathy kind of character.''
</P>
<P>
   She enjoyed the experience, but feels that virtually everything
has changed in moviemaking since the '50s, whether for a low-budget
independent or a studio release. And not for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that there's the protection that you had with
the studios, when you were under contract. There isn't the
protection for the producer, for the director, the writer, for
anybody,'' she says. Powell disagrees that the studio system was
needlessly restrictive to contract players. ``No, I think it was
very positive,'' she says. ``I'm sure people long for those days
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned for Powell on a couple of made-for-television movies
that she has already shot. ``One is called 'Sandy Bottom
Orchestra.' It's not a very good title, but it's taken from a book.
It will probably be out in the spring,'' she announces. ``And I
just did a part in the Jon Benet (Ramsey) epic that will be coming
out later. I play the dancing teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   As challenging as those roles were, they were a piece of cake
next to Powell's current task _ learning to use a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``Just to understand it,'' she replies. ``I don't know that
I'll ever use it, but I just feel so illiterate that I don't know
what people are talking about. I have no idea what I'm going to use
it for, but I really want to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell sounds ready for what lies ahead for her. She currently
has future film plans, but remains eager to see what will develop
from this recent burst of activity. ``You just never know,'' she
says brightly.
</P>
<P>
   Hap Erstein writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: haperstein(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
