<HEADER>
A8383 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN15-CO     12-14 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scale back wedding, get jump on the nest egg
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About 15 years ago, I got to attend one of those truly
astonishing weddings _ hundreds of guests, a generous open bar,
three kinds of caviar and flower arrangement 8 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   All that was before the wedding and the dinner dance that went
on until 2 a.m. That event in a posh Chicago hotel must have cost
more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   That blowout comes to mind as I look ahead to the next batch of
June weddings, only six months away now.
</P>
<P>
   I keep thinking there's a better way to do this. Not eloping,
but scaling back the monstrous costs of these affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of a wedding in 1997 was slightly more than
$19,000. That includes the reception, rings and some of the small
stuff. (Invitations and other correspondence averaged $327; the
bride's headpiece added another $166.)
</P>
<P>
   All this ceremonial profligacy takes place around a young couple
who may well be carrying college loan debt and who probably have no
way to buy a house or otherwise start moving their joined lives
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you rearrange your wedding budget? First you cut back on
things like the number of guests invited, the grandeur of the
reception and a few other costly items.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you divert the savings into a fairly aggressive stock
fund and leave it there for a long, long time. The chart indicates
some possibilities. Bear in mind that your investment return would
be much larger if you funneled the money into tax-deferred savings
programs, such as an individual retirement account.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the trade-off: less pomp now for more circumstance later.
Do you want a big party for hundreds of people now or, say, an
earlier retirement later for the two of you?
</P>
<P>
   There are other prudent alternatives, of course. A friend of
mine started preparations for his son's wedding by arranging the
down payment for the couple's first house. He put in several
thousand dollars, as did the bride's father and several other close
family members.
</P>
<P>
   Frugality at the altar is not a new idea. People are marrying
later these days, and it is more common for the bride and groom to
split expenses with their parents. That certainly encourages
careful budgeting and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is that more people are appalled by the huge
costs involved. Annual spending on weddings now comes to about $45
billion a year. There's enough money involved that one wedding Web
site (www.theknot.com) has announced an initial public offering of
stock.
</P>
<P>
   I am told that there are at least 20 Web sites that sell
containers of live butterflies, to be released during the nuptials.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet also reflects growing interest in
cost-conscious wedding plans. There are dozens of sites that deal
with budgeting, inexpensive alternatives and tips on keeping down
costs. One good one is rachel.itgo.com. For numerous penny-pincher
stories, both newspaper and first-person, look at
weddings.about.com/home/weddings/msub29.htm.
</P>
<P>
   A good book on the subject is ``Bridal Bargains: Secrets to
Throwing a Fantastic Wedding on a Realistic Budget,'' by Denise and
Alan Fields.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that we're talking about a two-step process. The first
is making an acceptably lean budget and sticking to it. The second
is seeing that the savings indeed go to investments or other
accounts that will serve the new couple's future needs.
</P>
<P>
   The whole process will be a lot easier if all the family members
agree to do it. An engaged couple will have a hard time controlling
expenses if her mom insists on a showy event or his dad must invite
tons of business associates.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the problem, then the question becomes one that a lot
of new couples must struggle with: Whose wedding is it, anyway? And
whose future?
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WEDDINGS COST
</P>
<P>
   (Average spending in 1997)
</P>
<P>
   Reception $7,635
</P>
<P>
   Rings $4,060
</P>
<P>
   Photography $1,311
</P>
<P>
   Bride's dress $823
</P>
<P>
   Music $830
</P>
<P>
   Bridesmaids' dresses $790
</P>
<P>
   Flowers $756
</P>
<P>
   Rehearsal dinner $698
</P>
<P>
   Men's formalwear $449
</P>
<P>
   Other $1,752
</P>
<P>
   Total $19,104
</P>
<P>
   A CALCULATED ALTERNATIVE
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you cut spending by half just for the three most
expensive items _ the reception, rings and photography. Now suppose
you invest the $6,500 savings and make a 10 percent return. Here's
what happens:
</P>
<P>
   Year Balance Return Taxes Year-end balance
</P>
<P>
   1 $6,500.00 $650.00 $221.00 $6,929.00
</P>
<P>
   10 $11,553.89 $1,155.39 $392.83 $12,316.45
</P>
<P>
   20 $21,892.75 $2,189.27 $744.35 $23,337.67
</P>
<P>
   30 $41,483.20 $4,148.32 $1,410.43 $44,221.10
</P>
<P>
   40 $78,603.94 $7,860.39 $2,672.53 $83,791.80
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
