<HEADER>
A8385 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ISAAC-STERN15-COX     12-14 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISAAC-STERN15-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Stern looking forward to musical life after 79
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Passy
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Isaac Stern would love to talk, but he's
got a more pressing matter at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you call me back in five minutes?'' the violinist asks,
speaking by phone from his New York apartment on a Saturday
morning. ``I'm just getting the shaving cream off my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from a man who is unquestionably one of this century's
greatest musicians _ and musical advocates _ it seems a
particularly humbling remark. But, as Stern jokes, even legends
have to shave. ``Let's just say the daily routines are not changed
by age or place,'' he explains good-naturedly. ``They're necessary
to continue living.''
</P>
<P>
   And the art of living _ in all its mundane and majestic glory _
is the subject of Stern's newly released autobiography, ``My First
79 Years'' (Knopf), written in collaboration with novelist Chaim
Potok. The title says it all: No matter what the age, life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any sense of being elderly,'' says Stern. ``I
have the same instincts I had 20 years ago. . . I see myself
continuing at the same pace that puts a lot of young people gasping
in the wake. I take it for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My First 79 Years'' chronicles the fruits of Stern's
extraordinary labors, starting with the Russian-born violinist's
early years in San Francisco, where he made his recital debut in
1935 and his orchestral debut with the San Francisco Symphony a
year later. Friends and family pushed the prodigiously talented
teenager to perform in New York. When his first appearance was
greeted with critical jabs, he remained undeterred. ``I had
invested so much of my life in music, I couldn't quit now. I would
keep trying. I would give the career another year, another two
years. I would go back to San Francisco and practice, practice,
practice,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Practice indeed made perfect. By his 20s, Stern was under
contract with Columbia Records and playing concerts worldwide. His
circle of friends included the budding young conductor Leonard
Bernstein, veteran impresario Sol Hurok and cellist and
humanitarian Pablo Casals. His life is no less charmed today: His
discography has grown to more than 150 recordings and he's
considered one of a handful of musicians whose mere presence turns
a concert into an event. When the Kravis Center hosted its
inaugural gala in 1992, he was inevitably asked to perform. (He has
since been back several times, thanks in part to his friendship
with Palm Beach cultural philanthropists Leonard and Sophie Davis.)
</P>
<P>
   But the story of Stern goes far beyond the fiddle. In the 1960s,
he started a one-man crusade to save New York's beloved Carnegie
Hall from the wrecking ball _ a luxury apartment building was
slated to rise in its place _ and he still guides the hallowed
hall's programming and operations as president of its board. He's
also been a tireless champion of human rights, traveling to China
in 1979 for a series of highly publicized concerts (captured in the
documentary From Mao to Mozart) and donning a gas mask for a
special performance in Israel during the Gulf War. His friend and
colleague, cellist Yo-Yo Ma, once joked that ``when he (Stern)
thinks the world needs saving, it's hard to keep his mind on
practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   The autobiography dutifully captures both sides of Stern's life
_ as musician and global citizen _ and gives a tiny peek into his
private world. Stern insists he doesn't separate one aspect from
another. ``The music comes out of the total person,'' he explains,
noting that what might be seen as unrelated _ say, his return to
China this year _ is quite connected. ``It may seem political, but
it always revolves around the centrality of music to the art of
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern is the first to admit that the book wasn't an especially
labor-intensive project. He leafed through old papers and
correspondence _ ``We fortunately have a very large archive in my
office,'' he says _ and spoke his mind into a tape recorder. The
material was passed on to Potok, a prize-winning Jewish novelist
(''The Chosen,'' ``The Promise,'' ``The Gift of Asher Lev''). ``Out
of that would come 8 to 12 very pointed questions (from Potok), and
that triggered another opening,'' recalls Stern of the process.
While Stern credits Potok with making ``order out of the chaos of
our conversations,'' he insists it's still very much his book.
``It's my voice you hear, not his,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the anecdotes Stern tells in the 306-page tome reveal a
great deal about the pleasure-loving man behind the music. There's
the lazy summer day he spent in the company of flutist Jean-Pierre
Rampal, scavenging for sea urchins on the island of Corsica. ``We
ate the fresh oursins with the small spoons and drank the Pernod in
the boat on the water. We were there for hours,'' he recalls
contentedly.
</P>
<P>
   Other incidents speak of an individual of liberal conscience who
clearly feels the pain of the world. He describes how he learned of
the assassination of John F. Kennedy while he was waiting to make a
connecting flight in Dallas of all places. ``We looked across the
airfield from the window of the cafe where we were sitting, and
there was Air Force One . . . Only later did I learn that on it was
the president's body,'' he writes. (He concluded that night with a
concert in San Antonio, where he played the Bach Chaconne in place
of the Sibelius Violin Concerto in D Minor: ``I chose Bach because
there is in his music a pervasive sense of balance, a continuity of
deep belief.'')
</P>
<P>
   The book does stint on some details, including those involving
the breakdown of Stern's 45-year marriage to Vera, with whom he
fathered three children. (He has since remarried a younger woman,
Linda Reynolds, an arts administrator.) And it's hard to accept the
off-handed way he dismisses critics of his playing, which has been
notoriously sloppy of late. ``So I missed a few notes sometimes,''
he writes. ``Was that really a big deal?''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Stern's problem, however, has been physical. He's been
hampered by a disabling hand injury _ carpal tunnel syndrome _ in
recent years. He ends the book with something of a question mark,
noting that he's going for surgery to correct the problem, but he's
not sure how far it will take him.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, Stern is happy to report that he's almost up to
speed _ and he's looking forward to ``one other small procedure
that would bring me back to 98-percent normalcy.'' He's been forced
to take a sabbatical from heavy-duty playing during the past year,
and he's eager to get back on stage for concerts in New York, San
Francisco and Los Angeles in February.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he's got the next 79 years ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Passey writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
