<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8390 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CYSTIC-FIBROSIS15-COX     12-14 2074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYSTIC-FIBROSIS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life for Cystic fibrosis kids a struggle, but it hasn't shaken
their parents' faith
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Every night, Bill and Jerri Chesney tap
their children's chests, over and over again, to keep them from
drowning.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney, 8, and Taylor, 5, have cystic fibrosis, a disease that
tricks the body into producing excess mucus, which coats the
pancreas and the lungs, inhibiting digestion and breathing. The
phlegmy superflux must be expelled daily, or the children will be
left gasping for air, like fish on dry land.
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 people in the U.S. have the disease, which is
incurable, though its symptoms can be dramatically alleviated with
vitamins and enzymes to enhance nutrition, inhalants to clear the
lungs, as well as physical therapy, like the chest-tapping the
Chesneys perform each night, doctoring their children. The couple
have been married 12 years and live in Stuart, Fla. Bill, 37, works
at Florida Power &AMP; Light's nuclear power plant. Jerri, 34, works
part-time at a Christian bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have an evening out with another family, and they'll
call afterward and say: `We got home, put the kids in bed and had
two hours to ourselves.' That never happens with us. We've got the
inhaling and the tapping to do, every night,'' Bill Chesney grins
ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   Faith and the fellowship of their church sustain them. The very
malady itself has strengthened the Chesney family, knit them
together with a powerful bond. The children themselves are
extraordinarily close to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in Philippians 4:13: `I can do anything through
Christ which strengtheneth me.' There's a reason God has given us
this opportunity. It may be a ministry for us to their lives,''
Bill goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the reason is for other children to see them and think:
'Those kids have CF and they've overcome it. If they can overcome
it, I can overcome whatever life sends me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The disease is drawing nationwide compassion and attention. This
Jan. 8, the 33rd annual ``65 Roses'' gala charity ball for CF will
be held in Palm Beach. Last year's event drew singer Celine Dion,
who performed for the audience at Donald Trump's Mar-a-Lago. Dion's
niece died of the disease, and she is the spokesperson for the
Canadian CF Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   CF used to mean certain death, often before the child's age
reached double digits. It is transmitted by a defective gene,
isolated and identified in 1989. The gene must be present in both
parents and even then, the disease afflicts only one child in every
four births. More than 10 million Americans _ one in every 31
adults _ have the defective gene and don't know it. Caucasians are
especially at risk: 28 of every 31 people who have the gene are
white.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers lead perfectly healthy lives, until they meet and marry
another carrier and have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no CF on either side of our family,'' Jerri Chesney
says. ``Bill and I both had the gene and didn't know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, gene therapy and powerful new medicines such as
Pulmozyme, and ingenious delivery systems, via benign viruses and
tiny liposomes, have increased life expectancy to 40 and beyond _
by which time there may be a cure, perhaps through gene therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Jerri is a lively, cheery woman who nonetheless has a catch in
her voice as she recalls how her daughter was first diagnosed with
CF:
</P>
<P>
   ``She was 8 weeks old. She had a terrible cold, and her stomach
was hard, and she was crying all the time. She was so tiny! She
never gained weight easily. She coughed a lot. We took her to the
doctor on Christmas day, and he thought it was just a bad cold. He
said: `Babies' immune systems are very strong. She'll get over the
cold without antibiotics.' So we went home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then she went into pneumonia. One lung collapsed, and the
other was full of congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``She spent 10 days in the hospital, and they still didn't catch
it. They did CF tests, and it didn't show up. But they sent us down
to St. Mary's hospital in West Palm. They did a follow-up test.
</P>
<P>
   ``They caught it. She tested positive. She had CF. I can still
remember us holding hands in the emergency room. We were just so
baffled by it. We don't know anybody on either side of the family
that has CF. We didn't know a thing about it. We'd never heard of
it, in either of our families.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, with one child already having CF, did the Chesneys choose
to have another child?
</P>
<P>
   ``We prayed over it a lot, believe me,'' Jerri says. ``We wanted
a bigger family. The odds were three to one in our favor, that the
child would be normal. But we knew we were taking a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got pregnant with Taylor, we knew we were taking a
chance. But we did ultrasounds, and he seemed to be developing
normally. We didn't do amniocentesis, because we knew we would keep
him no matter what. We don't believe in abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was also this thought,'' Bill adds delicately, ``that if
we lost one child, we would still have another with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Taylor was born and was immediately diagnosed with CF.
</P>
<P>
   The Chesneys accepted the fact stoically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked ourselves: 'Why us? Why two? What's the deal here?'
'' Bill says. ``But our church family and our relatives have helped
us get through it. They've been wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were better prepared the second time,'' Jerri says. ``In
some ways, it's almost easier to have them both having it. That way
one doesn't feel singled out. And we believe the Lord has a plan
for them to lead a wonderful life.''
</P>
<P>
   The two children, Courtney and Taylor, come bouncing into the
living room, giggling and only a little shy. They are remarkably
beautiful. Taylor is blond, Courtney is somewhat darker haired,
with a fine oval face and high cheekbones. The illness has
shortened their breath, but in return it has given them an almost
ethereal beauty, chiseled away pudginess and baby fat, modeled
their faces handsomely. They are active, cheerful and only very,
very slightly pale, because their lungs don't absorb quite as much
oxygen to redden their blood.
</P>
<P>
   They seem good children, sitting comfortably side by side in a
soft armchair, watching TV, with nebulizer masks on their faces,
inhaling Ventalin and Intol, two powerful anti-asthma medicines.
Quivering mists of vapor form and flee on the inside of the masks
as they inhale the cool, phlegm-loosening fog.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our daily routine,'' Jerri says. ``The kids take
multivitamin pills with every meal, every snack, and enzymes too,
to help them digest. Every morning and evening they do breathing
treatments with a nebulizer. They also take antibiotics and
steroids. Without Blue Cross, the pills would cost $2,500 every
three months. With Blue Cross, it's only $15.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be extra careful in the winter, with all the
northern visitors in the season. They bring down their colds and
flus with them, and you have to keep a sharp eye out for that and
jump on a cold the minute a red flag goes up,'' Bill says.
``Otherwise it can get really bad, really fast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most Courtney has missed is eight days of school. She had
a hard time with a cold this year and had to go on antibiotics for
15 days,'' Jerri says.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for the percussion treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Daddy!'' Courtney exclaims and hops on his lap, lying
across his knees face up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, Jerri does this far better than I do. I still have
to use this thing,'' Bill says, showing a doughnut-shaped rubber
O-ring he attaches to his fingers. Jerri needs no such aids; she
has mastered the percussion, cupping her hand just right so that a
soft ``pop'' of air gently explodes each time she taps Taylor's
chest. The young fellow looks dreamily peaceful, enjoying the
rhythmic, gentle blows, watching the television through eyes that
are getting sleepier.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hit them, you sort of tap them with your hand
cupped, to set up a vibration. Sometimes they nod off while we're
percussing them. Sometimes they use it as an excuse to stay up
later. We say: `Time for bed!' And they say: `Oh no, mom! We've got
to do our treatments!' So they get an extra half hour up.
Rascals!''' Jerri says.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time I was at a ballgame giving Taylor a treatment, and
some man turned around in the bleachers and asked: `What's that
hammering noise? What are they building back there?' '' she laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Pop, pop, pop, pop, pop! The tapping has to be done on the upper
and lower side, both lungs, four quadrants of the chest, in turn.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is not contagious. The children pose no danger to
their playmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because we have decided to raise them as normally as
we can and not leave them out, they've adjusted very well. When her
girlfriends come over, they'll ask: `Let me tap Courtney,' '' Bill
says.
</P>
<P>
   One day Courtney came home crying from preschool. Gently, her
mother asked if the other children were being mean to her. She
nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the illness. I thought it was that she was
being set apart. I asked her what exactly was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it turned out she was having to take the pills in
applesauce, and the other kids thought that was babyish. So she
wanted to learn how to swallow pills without applesauce, and I
showed her. Now the two kids have this competition. Courtney will
swallow her medicine, and Taylor will challenge her. He'll say:
`Look: I can do two pills!' ''
</P>
<P>
   When the insidious mucus comes up, it looks clear and runny,
like thick saliva. The two children cough a bit more than other
children do, and have to carry tissues with them wherever they go.
Sometimes, they have a salt-ring around their forehead where
they've sweated. Salty skin is a symptom of CF.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the odd rewards of the malady is being able to eat
lots of fat and lots of salt. A CF child's body doesn't absorb fat
or salt as quickly as normal, so Courtney and Taylor can eat things
the rest of us can only look at longingly: rashers of bacon,
sizzling eggs, hamburgers, french fries, cake and ice cream _
practically as much as they like.
</P>
<P>
   ``We even give them their own salt shakers and tell them to use
them. We also supplement their diets with Ensure,'' their mother
says.
</P>
<P>
   Discipline: ``Yes, we spank them,'' the father says. ``They
don't get off the hook just because they have CF. You've got to set
limits and let them know when you have gone beyond the limits, or
they will grow up with no idea of what the rules are. Sometimes I
just say: `Go to your room and we'll talk.' And that's enough, I
don't have to spank them.''
</P>
<P>
   The children enjoy Disney World and Six Flags over Georgia as
much as any children their age would. Taylor is crazy about Batman
and has a Bat-Plane in his room. Courtney likes kickball; Taylor
likes soccer and swimming. They are both looking forward to seeing
Toy Story 2. Buzz Lightyear is a favorite with both. The children
have arguments, mostly over who gets to sit up front in the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to the First Baptist Christian School,'' Courtney says.
And Taylor?
</P>
<P>
   ``I go where she goes,'' Taylor says loyally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lifestyle as parents and children is pretty doggone
normal,'' Jerri Chesney insists. ``Neither one of them has ever
been hospitalized again. We've maintained them at home with
treatments. Every three months we go to St. Mary's. Our next visit
is in February.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are really struggling with this thing. We consider
ourselves comparatively lucky. We're getting by. I've got a good
job, with good insurance. Our church family has backed us up
wonderfully. We have prayer chains, one praying for another who
needs it. We get a lot of energy from prayer,'' Bill Chesney says.
``Our hope is that one day, through science, or through the will of
God in a miracle, they will be cured.''
</P>
<P>
   At night, the children say their prayers while their parents
listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courtney prays to God to make her well, to cure her soon. She
has a lot of faith,'' her father continues. ``We actually learn a
lot from the children. Sometimes I hear their prayers at night and
they are so sincere, so confident, so faithful that I think to
myself, `I've got to learn from that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: michaelbrowning(at)pbpost.com
</P>
