   NATIONAL NEWS (''a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINE-LABEL (San Francisco) _ The federal government's decision
to temporarily halt a program that lets the wine industry tout the
health benefits of wine on its labels has left some in California's
powerful wine industry with a slight taste of sour grapes. Yielding
to pressure from Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms for the time being put the cork on
the 10-month-old practice of permitting wine labels to allude to
wine's health benefits. The agency plans hearings on the labeling
next year. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-WESTWING-REVIEW (Undated) _ The great American soap opera
that is ``The West Wing'' could never have made it post-Watergate
but seems absolutely essential post-Monicagate. The days of
trusting a Jimmy Stewart style candidate and living in a world of
Frank Capra dreams are over. Even Bill Clinton's bar-lowering
antics in the White House failed to raise much of a ruckus among
the general population. The last 25 years have been a textbook
example of jadedness grown to exponential levels. Maybe that's why
``The West Wing'' is a hit, why it casts such a mysterious trance
over cynics. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
