   SPORTS (''s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ The San Francisco 49ers' win
over the Atlanta Falcons ended the 49ers' miserable losing streak
ended at eight. The 49ers defense swarmed ball-carriers, batted
down passes, knocked Atlanta quarterback Chris Chandler out of the
game and surrendered no offensive points. By JEFFRI CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (''k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ What we're up against with mental
illness is a huge, unofficial ``Don't tell, don't talk about it''
policy. The surgeon general, Dr. David Satcher, is trying to end
that policy. He has issued a report saying that 22 percent of the
population has diagnosable mental disorders, but two-thirds don't
seek treatment. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ An old Albany joke: Kids in this
town don't wear masks on Halloween. Instead, they dress up as state
legislators, knock on the doors of lobbyists and demand presents.
And get them. Which means it's possible that the governor and both
houses of the Legislature will reach agreement this month on
toughening New York's lobbying law before it dies Dec. 31. It's
also possible that O.J. Simpson will find the real killer, that
Bill Clinton will enter a monastery and that Rudy Giuliani will win
the Nobel Peace Prize. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ There is something so darkly
comic about the U.S. Department of State's holiday terrorism
warning. One might suspect the late film maker, Stanley Kubrick, of
having scripted it. After all, the irony is already close to the
``Dr. Strangelove'' level. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   PERSON-OF-CENTURY (San Francisco) _Time magazine's Man of the
Year _ later changed to Person of the Year _ has always generated
lots ofpublicity. The hype machine is in full swing to anoint the
one person who has most influenced human affairs over the past
hundred years. By BOB ARMSTRONG.
</P>
