<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8426 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-KOSOVO-RETURNEE-$ADV1     12-14 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RETURNEE-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALBANIAN REFUGEE FINDS RETURN TO KOSOVO IS BITTERSWEET
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For locator map purposes, Gnjilane is in south-central
Kosovo province, just north of the Macedonia border.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Dec. 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GNJILANE, Yugoslavia _ Alongside a two-lane road that winds
through the hills in southern Kosovo sits a walled farmyard with a
cinderblock house at its center.
</P>
<P>
   The steep, forested hills rising all around could be mistaken
for those of north Georgia. Skender Rahimi couldn't get this place
out of his mind even while he was in the safety and relative
serenity of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The house by the road is Rahimi's home. By local standards, it's
no palace, but it's a good solid house and a cause for pride. It
pained Rahimi (pronounced: ``ra-HEE-mee'') to leave it eight months
ago to escape advancing Serb forces. With seven family members, he
made his way to neighboring Macedonia and a refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   His story is a familiar tale of exile and return that is common
among the 800,000 Kosovar Albanians who fled their homeland last
spring during the brutal conflict between the Serb-led Yugoslav
military and ethnic Albanian separatists. The conflict came to an
end after NATO's 78-day bombing campaign forced the Yugoslav army,
police and paramilitaries to withdraw from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   When Rahimi fled in April he left behind his parents, whose
memory haunted him for the months he was away.
</P>
<P>
   Parents hold a special place in Albanian society: Children,
particularly sons and their wives, are duty-bound to care for them.
The idea of sending parents off to a nursing home or even a
retirement village is an unheard of absurdity, particularly here in
the deeply traditional
</P>
<P>
   countryside.
</P>
<P>
   But Rahimi's parents _ both in their 60s, an advanced age in
Kosovo _ were not up to the long journey south to Macedonia. Also,
it seemed unlikely that Serb soldiers would harm them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived with them more than 40 years,'' Rahimi said a on
recent day in the house's sitting room over cigarettes and cups of
strong Albanian tea. ``I must care for them now.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the effort to transfer refugees out of overwhelmed
Macedonia, Rahimi's family was airlifted to the United States and
ultimately to Atlanta. America wasn't his first choice _ he had
requested Sweden or Norway to remain closer to home _ but he was
intrigued when he saw the destination on a list in the refugee
camp.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is an odd fantasy to people in this part of
the world. Few have visited it, but America is always with them in
movies, sitcoms, music and endless stream of consumer products.
Yet, it remains a distant place. ``It is somewhere for other
people, that's what we always thought,'' he said. ``Before, I
couldn't have an impression. The biggest impression I had was that
Albright and Clinton were helping us to get freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, after a brief stay in New Jersey, the family arrived in
Atlanta and were housed in an apartment complex near Hartsfield
International Airport. Rahimi spoke not one word of English, and
his children had learned only a little more in school. None had
been to a city as big as Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In time, they made a life. From some Bosnians he met, he learned
where he could get familiar food (he didn't care much for the
American fare he sampled, with the exception of pizza). From
Vietnamese emigrants he met at work, he learned survival skills.
</P>
<P>
   But his most powerful memory of Atlanta is a thousand little
generosities given by an American named Mike _ Rahimi can't recall
the odd sounding last name. ``I still think of Mike and walking
around Atlanta,'' Rahimi recalls, first with a smile and then with
a waver in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gaertner, a Catholic Social Services volunteer, assisted
the Rahimis in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm thinking if I could ever help him as I was helped,''
Rahimi says, pausing without ending the sentence. ``They were very
good people in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he loves his native Kosovo deeply, Rahimi would have
liked to have stayed in America. He harbored a powerful desire to
see his five children educated _ a difficult challenge in the
uncertainty of a war-torn province. His younger son, Flamur, caught
the computer bug but has returned to a place where he has no access
to one.
</P>
<P>
   And at 41, Rahimi was prepared to embark on a new life in the
strange but promising land.
</P>
<P>
   Then he received a phone call. He was told that his mother was
sick, perhaps mortally ill. His father was despondent, perhaps
losing his mind. His house in Gnjilane has no telephone and it had
become virtually impossible to get reliable information on his
parents' conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In September he decided it was his duty to return to Kosovo.
However, his eldest son, Mentor, wanted to stay in America. Mentor
turned 18 on Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me 'You're sending me to Kosovo. Where I can't
study, where I can't make a life,''' Rahimi recalls.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife agreed to let their son stay. ``So, he will
finish school there (in Atlanta) and maybe he can work there.''
Rahimi says, smiling. ``Now Mike is his second father.''
</P>
<P>
   After saying this, Rahimi looks at his younger son and one of
the three daughters who returned with him to Kosovo and then to his
wife. Briefly, they seem to share in the emptiness of Mentor's
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' Rahimi says after a minute or two. ``But now
he's grown up and he's living his life. It would be harder now to
have him here and to be unable to give him the school he needs now.
That would be too much for me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned home in September, Rahimi was overjoyed to find
the house undamaged. About 100,000 houses in Kosovo were damaged in
the fighting, half of them beyond repair. He had assumed the worst.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Bathie, will never forget his return. She was
standing on the front porch. ``I looked at the gate open,'' she
recalls. ``And then I saw Skender's face, the face I never thought
I would see again. I thought I was dead before and now I'm alive.''
</P>
<P>
   He was relieved to find his parents alive and reasonably
healthy. It was all he had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   While his home and immediate family was spared, things weren't
so good for everyone. Five cousins were dead. Many houses were
destroyed. The mosque down the road was a pile of rubble.
</P>
<P>
   And with winter coming on hard, there will be plenty of misery
to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Rahimi thinks a lot about Atlanta and his son. He wonders if he
will ever see either again. When he wants to talk to Mentor, he
walks about five miles to use a telephone. But it's not the same.
</P>
<P>
   He hands a visiting American a handwritten note and a shopping
bag of cassette tapes to take to Atlanta. ``These are his
favorites.''
</P>
<P>
   Life in Kosovo doesn't allow much time for reverie. He and his
wife have four children and two parents to care for.
</P>
<P>
   Rahimi says he's ready for winter. Firewood is stacked neatly
against the wall. The family tractor is parked near the chicken
coops on the front wall.
</P>
<P>
   It is cold the morning Rahimi's wife, Vahide, cooks ``fli-a'' _
a special dish with layers of yogurt and a pasta-like bread _ in a
pan over the open fire. She's in constant motion, stirring the
coals and adjusting the pan to get the heat right. She says very
little.
</P>
<P>
   Rahimi sits on his haunches smoking and warming his hands on the
fire. His mother gazes at him from a few feet away. He wonders if
he was right to leave Atlanta, but he doesn't allow himself to
drift into regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to find the house and the tractor weren't
damaged,'' he says, squinting as the smoke stings his eyes. ``But
life is more important than anything else. This is what I think
now.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
