<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8451 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-COLUMN16-CO     12-14 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flowers speak prayers if you know how to listen
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Dec. 16.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sally Ann Giray has lost control, and her life's all the better
for it.
</P>
<P>
   A poet, storyteller, playwright, actress and gardener, Giray
last year gave in to the pulls of words and flowers and
spirituality, combining the three to produce a book of poems,
``Prayers From the Flowers.'' She self-published the 63-page volume
soon after a friend who lay dying urged her to do so, to become the
way she had been as a child _ when she talked to flowers in her
native England. And listened to them.
</P>
<P>
   As a young girl, she says, she spent much time alone. And
flowers ``became my people. They gave me spiritual strength.''
</P>
<P>
   After her friend (he was married to her best girlfriend) died,
Giray, who also has lived 13 years in Jamaica, began writing the
poems, recalling the magic of her grandparents' Sussex garden, the
prayers she heard from the daisy, orchid, dogwood, morning glory,
sunflower, evening primrose and more.
</P>
<P>
   The poems ``just came,'' she said on a welcome wintry day, as we
enjoyed a lunch of homemade vegetable soup, salad and corn bread in
her Decatur home. ``As if someone was guiding my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, her guidance, her loss of control, is like
gardening itself. After a certain point, something beyond the
gardener takes over; there is a flow of energy between the plant
and the person that relies less on how well we work the garden than
on how well we connect with it.
</P>
<P>
   This guiding force has many faces, many names. And, just as
Giray notes that ``Prayer is like love; there are so many ways of
making it,'' and that she is still on ``the long journey toward
finding my own way to prayer,'' we all are seeking ways to get to
the garden of peace.
</P>
<P>
   During her journey, Giray has met and written about some
thoughtful, moving plants and the prayers they have uttered. Listen
to the rose:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Lord of all
</P>
<P>
   have You seen how
</P>
<P>
   here along my stem
</P>
<P>
   You have set thorns?
</P>
<P>
   Even my leaves
</P>
<P>
   are often prickly
</P>
<P>
   I am a mess!
</P>
<P>
   Dear Lord of all
</P>
<P>
   is this Your will
</P>
<P>
   Your secret blessing
</P>
<P>
   to have this thorny stem
</P>
<P>
   push the bud
</P>
<P>
   reminiscent
</P>
<P>
   in amaze of glory
</P>
<P>
   to a flowered beauty
</P>
<P>
   of heavenly grace
</P>
<P>
   And, in the last of four stanzas, the iris says:
</P>
<P>
   In tongues of blue
</P>
<P>
   unsealing, the bud
</P>
<P>
   unfurls its bloom
</P>
<P>
   and all's at peace
</P>
<P>
   and all is You
</P>
<P>
   At the end of her book, Giray lists a floral vocabulary, passed
down since ancient times. Among various plants and their meanings:
</P>
<P>
   Aster: elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Camellia: constancy and steadfastness.
</P>
<P>
   Laurel: victory and glory.
</P>
<P>
   Thyme: spontaneous emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Violet: modesty.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, flowers speak _ and teach _ volumes. ``Everything in
nature grows; it doesn't ask how,'' Giray says. ``It springs. I've
learned to allow things to spring. Flowers have given me the
ability to lose control, a new sense of being one with everything.
If you unlace, you expand, and your spirit is free to recognize
what beauty is.''
</P>
<P>
   Giray sells and ships ``Prayers From the Flowers'' for $11.95.
Call 404-486-8886 or e-mail SallyGiray(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May is a regular columnist on gardening lifestyles for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.. E-mail him at leemay
</P>
<P>
   (at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
