<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8452 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOLIDAY-TABLE16-COX     12-14 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-TABLE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grand ideas for impromptu entertaining
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Dec. 16.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It may be the last minute, but all of a sudden you're
in the mood to throw a holiday dinner party. You:
</P>
<P>
   a) Call your caterers on the off chance they can work you in,
within a week of Christmas;
</P>
<P>
   b) Take a hard look at Happy Meals;
</P>
<P>
   c) Have another drink and forget the idea;
</P>
<P>
   d) Go for it.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta event planner and caterer Tony Conway thinks you should
choose ``d.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep the food and drink simple but the presentation grand,''
he said during a demonstration at the Atlanta Decorative Arts
Center's recent Designers Holiday Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Food as basic as mashed potatoes can be served in something as
elegant as martini glasses, he said, which is bound to get the
chatter going.
</P>
<P>
   Presentation centers on the table. But rather than spending a
small fortune on flowers, linens and glassware, look around the
house for alternative uses for items you already have _ a throw
becomes a tablecloth, a small Christmas tree makes a centerpiece _
and rent the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Then leave the ``entertaining'' to the guests. ``You're getting
your friends together, and they will take care of the
conversation,'' said Teresa Day, Conway's partner in Legendary
Events. ``You provide the drama.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 15-minute demonstration, the two pulled together a holiday
table for an impromptu cocktail party. Here are their pointers:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Table the idea: Don't have a long table for making a
presentation? An 8-foot folding one can be had at rental shops for
as little as $20.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Show a little leg: On the other hand, if you have a nice
table, don't hide it. ``One of our most expensive things in the
home is the dining room table, but we drape over it completely with
cloths,'' Day said. ``Let the table show.'' Place the cloth off
center or toss a throw on it so that parts of the tabletop show.
Gather the throw at one end and tie it with a ribbon. If you want
to dress things up, rent skirting, which can be attached with clips
around the edge of the table or with duct tape to an undercloth. Or
you can make a simple skirting with a nice piece of fabric and add
a shirttail hem.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Center of attention: Who says a centerpiece has to be a floral
arrangement? And who says whatever you choose has to be
``centered''? Decorate a small potted Christmas tree and place it
at one end of the table for instant height as well as light. Lay a
wreath in the center of the table around a punch bowl or soup
tureen and decorate it with cut roses stuck into water-filled
picks. Or stack identically wrapped gift boxes in the center,
building-block fashion. Use collectibles, such as ornaments, dolls
or music boxes, to decorate a theme table. ``Look around the house,
in the closets, the china cabinet,'' Day said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Create height: One means for creating a dramatic table is
different levels for giving objects height. Consider stacking
Styrofoam blocks, books or gift boxes and hiding them under the
tablecloth to draw attention to a centerpiece or even a stack of
serving plates. For a contemporary look, place glass blocks, which
sell for under $10, on top of the cloth. ``Blocks also make great
reflections for candles,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shed light on it: Like artwork, no table presentation is
complete without proper lighting. Use small lanterns or lots of
small votives to highlight the tabletop. If the skirting is
interesting, clamp a light under the table.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Go unconventional: One of Conway's favorite serving pieces is
the martini glass, which he collects. Because of its wide bowl and
narrow stem, a 9-ounce glass is practical yet elegant for serving
everything from tomato bisque to frozen yogurt, for both seated
dinners and stand-up affairs. ``They're so sexy and fun to use,''
Conway said. If you don't own any, rent them, or, if you want to be
really practical, go with plastics.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it's the ideas, not the materials, that make
entertaining grand.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
