<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8453 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PARTY-STEMWARE16-COX     12-14 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-STEMWARE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glassmakers uncork vault of new wine stems perfect for gift
giving and festive entertaining
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Dec. 16.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time to shatter another myth: To set a festive dinner table,
matching china, matching glassware and matching napkins are musts.
If only guests would wear uniforms to complement the color scheme!
</P>
<P>
   Professional party planners will tell you their most fun and
exciting affairs result from breaking the rules.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to selecting wine glasses, why not let your guests
help?
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks really neat when you set a table to let everybody
pick out their own special one,'' said Trisha Puls of City Art
Works, an Atlanta gift gallery.
</P>
<P>
   And with the array of designs in stemware these days _ from
whimsical conversation-starters to elegant art glass _ the choices
are endless.
</P>
<P>
   Both mainstream retailers and art galleries are toasting a hot
commodity among those grown weary of the same old, same old of
homogenous ``sets.'' Consumers are drawn to colors, shapes and
sizes that allow them to mix and match to suit their personalities,
their guests' and the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Prices run the gamut, from less than $5 for mass-produced stems
at houseware havens such as Pier 1 Imports to thousands for
handblown, artist-signed pieces at high-end galleries. Stems priced
less than $100 typically are purchased as functional pieces, while
those above usually are sold to collectors, said David Alfrey of
Vespermann Glass Gallery, which is showing goblets by glass artists
across the country through December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people collect the one-of-a-kind goblet, while some just
want something a little unusual,'' said Ellie Mueller of
Vespermann.
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons, wine stems can be both a fun and practical
gift idea. You can build on someone's collection or start them on a
new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are viewing glassware more as pieces of art these days,
so they're going beyond just being functional,'' Puls said.
</P>
<P>
   But remember: If the glass is to be used, not just viewed, its
shape, texture and color can affect the taste of the wine it holds.
``We eat and drink with our eyes as much as our mouths,'' said
Atlanta wine expert Jane Garvey, so choose your stems carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you thought size was one of those myths worth
shattering ...
</P>
<P>
   P I C K I N G A S T E M
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a wine glass isn't just about art. There's a science to
it as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recently served a friend the same wine in two different
glasses,'' said Jane Garvey, wine columnist for the The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's Food section. ``He said, `I liked this one
but not that one.'''
</P>
<P>
   She rests her case: ``The shape of the glass determines how wine
is thrown back into your mouth and what parts of the palate it
hits, affecting the way it tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid altering the taste, Garvey recommends:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stems slightly flared at the the hip (for swirling) and
slightly closed at the lip (for focusing aroma). Lips should be
plain, not curled.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stems with generous bowls for swirling more complex red wines
and smaller ones for basic whites as well as roses. Typically, reds
should be served in a 20-ounce or larger glass, pouring only 6 to 8
ounces so there's room for swirling; whites should be served in a
10- to 12-ounce glass, by the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bowls without a surface design or color. A heavily cut surface
affects how the wine rolls over the palate, while dark shades
obscure the wine's color, which psychologically can alter the
taste.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Flutes or tulip-shaped glasses slightly closed at the top for
champagnes. White wines should not be served in flutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Holding all glasses by the stem and all flutes by the base so
the hand doesn't affect the wine's temperature. ``Hold it by the
bowl only if you want to warm it up,'' Garvey said.
</P>
<P>
   S O U R C E S
</P>
<P>
   City Art Works, 2140 Peachtree Road N.W., 404-605-0786
</P>
<P>
   Crate &AMP; Barrel, two metro locations (404-239-0008, Lenox Square)
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Deluxe, 1034 N. Highland Ave. N.E., 404-892-9337
</P>
<P>
   Pier 1 Imports, 14 metro locations (404-881-6549, Ansley Mall)
</P>
<P>
   Pottery Barn, three metro locations (404-812-9726, Lenox Square)
</P>
<P>
   Sidewalk Studio, 1050 N. Highland Ave. N.E., 404-872-1047
</P>
<P>
   Twelve, 976 Piedmont Ave. N.E., 404- 897-5511
</P>
<P>
   Vespermann Glass Gallery, Brookwood Square, 404-350-9698
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Wine Glasses Ltd.: www.wineglassesltd.com/
</P>
<P>
   Wine Glasses from TR Christian:
</P>
<P>
   www.trchristian.com/wineglass.htm
</P>
<P>
   Lenox: www.lenox.com/stem/stem.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
