<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8454 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SECURITY-HOLIDAY16-CO     12-14 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECURITY-HOLIDAY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't let thieves steal the holiday
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Dec. 16.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't let a grinch steal your Christmas. Or your Kwanzaa, for
that matter.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday season is supposed to be a time of good cheer, but
it's also a time when home burglaries are at their highest,
according to law enforcement experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, burglaries are a bit higher in July and August, the
heavy vacation months, and then again in December,'' says Jean
O'Neil, director of research for the National Crime Prevention
Council in Washington. ``Based on what I hear from police
departments, the increase in December is concentrated around the
holidays ... especially in suburban areas or neighborhoods with a
lot of new families who might be going home for the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Burglary is a crime of opportunity, where the objective is to
get in and out of a home as quickly as possible. Most burglars
won't spend more than a couple of minutes trying to break in,
experts say. That's why one of the most effective ways of
protecting your home is to discourage unwanted intruders from ever
attempting to get in. Here are some things you can do, whether
you're going out of town or just planning to be away for several
hours:
</P>
<P>
   Inside the home
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Put interior lights on a timer. Rotate the on and off times to
discourage any would-be intruders. If possible, put stereos and
televisions on a timer, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Turn the radio to a talk show program so it sounds as if
conversations are taking place.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Turn the ringer on the telephone down or off, so an unanswered
ring can't be heard from outside.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Close the drapes when you're not at home, so burglars can't
see your valuables from a window.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Move important papers and expensive belongings to a
safe-deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Do an inventory of your home. Take good-quality photographs of
items that are hard to describe. Write down item serial numbers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure locks on windows are sturdy. Replace thumb latches
on windows with keyed locks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Install double cylinder deadbolt locks on doors with glass
panes. Make sure all exterior doors are sturdy and secure,
including patio doors and doors that lead from the garage to the
house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If firearms are in the home, make sure they are stored in a
safe place and properly secured. Store ammunition in a separate
location. Firearms and ammunition are among the most frequently
stolen items in home burglaries.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Purchase a security system and make sure it is turned on when
you leave home. When shopping for a system, look for companies that
provide 24-hour monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the home
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Trim hedges and shrubbery on the exterior of the house, so
there are no areas in which to hide. Make sure the perimeter of the
home is well lighted.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Walk around your home and determine how you would get in if
you locked yourself out. If you can find an easy way inside, it's a
good chance a burglar can, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure there are no tree branches or outside structures
that would give someone easy access to the upper level.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Do not leave expensive tools, equipment, toys or bikes in an
unlocked garage or shed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Do not hide keys outside.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't advertise expensive gifts by leaving empty boxes on the
curb for the garbage collector. Tear down boxes or take to a dump.
</P>
<P>
   In your community
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ask a trusted neighbor or friend to park his car in your
driveway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure delivery of mail and newspapers is either stopped or
items are picked up by a friend or neighbor. Give neighbors a key
and a telephone number where they can contact you if an emergency
arises.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ask a crime prevention officer if your local police can put
your home on a surveillance list.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
