<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8487 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-DESSERTS-TO-DIE-FOR-L 1stadd &LR;    12-14 2300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESSERTS-TO-DIE-FOR-LADN, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOCOLATE ORBIT CAKE 
 

</HEADLINE>
 1st add  
UNDATED: ... some of these. 1/2 pound (2 sticks) butter 
12 ounces bittersweet chocolate 
6 eggs 
1 cup sugar 
Creme anglaise (optional)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Position oven rack in center of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 9x2-inch round cake pan and line inside with a round of
parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Set a large bowl over a pan of simmering water to create a
double boiler. Cut butter and chocolate into small pieces and place
in bowl to melt, whisking occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together eggs and sugar in another bowl. Thoroughly whisk
in melted chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Pour chocolate batter into cake pan. Place in a large baking pan
and pour in warm water to reach halfway up sides of cake pan. Cover
tightly with foil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 1 hour and 15 minutes, until
cake appears to be set and when you touch center, your finger comes
away clean.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cake from water bath and cool completely before serving,
plain or with creme anglaise. Makes 1 (9-inch) cake, 12 to 14
servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
From ``Room for Dessert'' by David Lebovitz (HarperCollins). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PERSIMMON CAKE
</P>
<P>
   For this dense, moist cake, use very ripe persimmons that are
completely soft and translucent. The larger, elongated Hachiya
variety is best for baking, although the other common persimmon,
the Fuyu, will do. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 very ripe, medium-size persimmons &QL; 
1 cup walnuts, toasted &QL; 
8 tablespoons (1 stick) butter, at room temperature &QL; 
1 1/4 cups granulated sugar &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
2 eggs, at room temperature &QL; 
1 3/4 cups flour &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1 teaspoon baking soda &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
3/4 cup dried currants, soaked in 1/4 cup Cognac OR brandy &QL; 
Powdered sugar for dusting cake &QL; 
Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Cut persimmons in half and scoop out pulpy flesh with a spoon.
Puree pulp in a food processor or a blender, or pass through a food
mill. You will need 1 cup puree for the cake. (You can freeze any
leftover puree and use another time.)
</P>
<P>
   Position oven rack in center of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Line a 9-inch round cake pan or a 9 1/2-inch springform pan with
a circle of parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Finely chop walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Cream together butter and granulated sugar until light and
fluffy, 3 to 5 minutes in a standing electric mixer. Add vanilla
and beat in eggs, one at a time. Stop and scrape down sides of bowl
and beat until eggs are completely incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together flour, salt, baking soda and cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Stir 1/2 of persimmon puree into creamed butter mixture, then
thoroughly mix in dry ingredients. Stir in remaining puree, walnuts
and currants with their liquor. Pour batter into prepared cake pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven about 45 minutes, until a
toothpick inserted in center comes out clean. Remove from oven and
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cake from pan and peel off parchment paper. Dust with
powdered sugar and serve with whipped cream. Makes 1 (9- or 9
1/2-inch) cake, 10 to 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Room for Dessert'' by David Lebovitz (HarperCollins). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE MACADAMIA CAKE
</P>
<P>
   This recipe has only four ingredients. It can be assembled in
minutes, and it produces a cake so intensely chocolate-flavored
that the only thing you will want to serve alongside it will be
softly whipped cream. Use the very best chocolate you can find. If
you want, substitute walnuts or pistachios for the macadamias _ or
leave out the nuts altogether. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
3/4 pound (3 sticks) unsalted butter &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds bittersweet chocolate (see Note) &QL; 
1 cup macadamia nuts, toasted &QL; 
8 eggs, at room temperature &QL; 
Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Position oven rack in center of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 9 1/2-inch springform pan and line bottom with a round
of parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Cut butter into small pieces and chop chocolate into small
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl set over hot water, melt chocolate and butter
together. Coarsely chop macadamia nuts.
</P>
<P>
   With an electric mixer, beat eggs until a ribbon forms when you
lift beater.
</P>
<P>
   Fold eggs into melted butter and chocolate, then rapidly fold in
nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer batter to lined springform pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 400-degree oven 45 minutes. If cake appears to
be getting too dark on top, drape a piece of foil over it and
continue baking until cake begins to feel firm in center.
</P>
<P>
   When cake has cooled, loosen cake by running a knife around
sides of pan, then remove sides of springform pan. Invert cake onto
a serving plate, lift off bottom of springform pan and peel away
parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Turn cake onto a serving plate. Serve with whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 (9 1/2-inch) round cake, 10 to 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Because this cake has no added sugar, use a chocolate that
is not overly bitter.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Room for Dessert'' by David Lebovitz (HarperCollins). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PANFORTE
</P>
<P>
   This is my version of the classic holiday confection from Siena,
Italy. I like my panforte quite spicy (in Siena they call highly
spiced panforte panpepato), so I added a brisk amount of black
pepper. This makes it ideal for after dinner: sweet, but not too
sweet, with a spicy bite to it. Panforte can be made well in
advance and kept on hand for serving after dinner, sliced into
small wedges, with strong coffee or with vin santo. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
5 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa, plus 2 teaspoons more for dusting
pan &QL; 
3 ounces bittersweet chocolate &QL; 
1 cup hazelnuts, toasted and loose skins removed &QL; 
1 1/2 cups almonds, toasted &QL; 
3/4 cup flour &QL; 
3/4 cup chopped candied citrus peel (preferably candied citron) &QL; 
1 tablespoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
2 teaspoons ground ginger &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
Pinch grated nutmeg &QL; 
Pinch chili pepper &QL; 
1 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
3/4 cup honey &QL; 
Powdered sugar for dusting
</P>
<P>
   Position oven rack in center of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 9 1/2-inch springform pan. Dust pan with 2 teaspoons
cocoa and tap out any excess.
</P>
<P>
   Chop chocolate and melt in a dry bowl set over simmering water.
</P>
<P>
   Very coarsely chop hazelnuts and almonds, leaving a few whole.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, stir together hazelnuts, almonds, flour,
5 tablespoons cocoa, candied citrus and spices.
</P>
<P>
   In a small heavy saucepan fitted with a candy thermometer, mix
granulated sugar and honey and heat to 240 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Stir chocolate into chopped nut mixture. Stir in honey syrup. At
this point, batter will begin to stiffen, so work rapidly. Transfer
batter to prepared pan. Dampen your hand or back of a spoon and use
to spread batter evenly and smooth surface of panforte.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 300-degree oven 50 minutes. Remove from oven
and let stand about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While panforte is still warm, loosen edges from pan with a
knife. Remove springform and remove bottom from panforte with help
of a metal spatula. Cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle top of panforte with powdered sugar and rub in with
your hands. Do same to bottom and sides. Wrap panforte lightly in
plastic wrap and store in a cool, dry place until ready to serve.
It will keep 1 year and improves with age. Makes 1 (9 1/2-inch)
cake, 16 to 20 servings.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Traditionally, panforte is baked in a pan lined with a
disk of edible rice paper, which makes it much easier to remove
panforte from pan. Edible rice paper is available by mail order
from Sweet Celebrations, (800) 328-6722.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Room for Dessert'' by David Lebovitz (HarperCollins). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLASSIC LINZER TART
</P>
<P>
   This Austrian specialty, associated with the city of Linz, is a
tart filled with raspberry jam. Modest, perhaps, by Austrian
standards (for starters, there's no whipped cream on or in it), the
linzer tart is nonetheless a beloved tradition. Criss-crossed with
strips of rich nut pastry, the diamonds of ruby-red jam peek
through like jewels. Although usually made with almonds, this
pastry is delicious when hazelnuts are used instead. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2/3 cup hazelnuts (filberts) &QL; 
1 1/4 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/3 cup packed light brown sugar &QL; 
6 tablespoons butter OR margarine, slightly softened &QL; 
1 large egg &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
3/4 cup seedless raspberry jam &QL; 
Powdered sugar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Place hazelnuts in a 9x9-inch metal baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 15 minutes, or until toasted.
Wrap hot hazelnuts in a clean cloth towel. With hands, roll
hazelnuts back and forth to remove most of skins. Cool completely.
Turn off oven.
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor with a knife blade attached, or a blender,
pulse nuts with 1/4 cup flour until nuts are finely ground.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, with a mixer at low speed, beat brown sugar and
butter until blended. Increase speed to medium-high; beat until
creamy, about 3 minutes, scraping bowl with a rubber spatula.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce speed to medium and beat in egg and vanilla until smooth,
about 1 minute. Reduce speed to low. Add ground nut mixture,
cinnamon, salt, baking powder and remaining 1 cup flour; beat just
until combined.
</P>
<P>
   With floured hands, press 2/3 of dough into bottom and up side
of a 9-inch tart pan with a removable bottom (1/4 inch below edge
of pan). Wrap tart shell and remaining dough in plastic wrap and
refrigerate 30 minutes, or until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Spread raspberry jam over bottom of tart shell to 1/4-inch from
edge. Divide remaining dough into 10 equal pieces. On a lightly
floured surface, with floured hands, roll each piece into an 8
1/2-inch long rope. Place 5 ropes, about 1 1/2 inches apart, over
filling; do not seal ends.
</P>
<P>
   Make a lattice top with remaining 5 ropes. Trim ends of ropes
even with edge of tart; press ends to seal. With any remaining
trimmings, make rope for tart shell and press around inside edge of
tart. Make decorative edge with a fork, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 35 to 40 minutes, until
filling is hot and bubbly and crust is lightly browned. Cool on a
wire rack at least 1 hour. Sprinkle tart with powdered sugar. When
cool, carefully remove side of pan. Makes 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Good Housekeeping Baking'' (Hearst Books). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MARBLED POUND CAKE
</P>
<P>
   We love this versatile cake. If you double the recipe, you can
bake it in a 10-inch bundt pan. We've baked it in a loaf pan,
cupcake tins and a bundt pan, and all have turned out beautifully.
In the bundt pan, baking time is about 1 1/2 hours, the cupcakes
bake in 20 to 25 minutes, and in the loaf pan baking time is about
1 hour. This is great with a glass of cold milk. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
1 teaspoon baking soda &QL; 
1 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
4 ounces (1 stick) unsalted butter, at room temperature, cut into
small pieces &QL; 
1 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
2 eggs &QL; 
1 cup buttermilk &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa powder, sifted &QL; 
1/2 cup semisweet chocolate chips &QL; 
Chocolate Glaze (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Position rack in center of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Butter or coat with vegetable spary an 8 1/2x3 1/2x2 1/2-inch
loaf pan.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together flour, baking soda, baking powder and salt. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl of an electric mixer fitted with a paddle or
beaters, beat butter on medium speed. Gradually pour in granulated
sugar, increase speed to high and beat until fluffy. Add eggs, one
at a time, beating just to combine. Reduce speed to low and
alternate adding flour mixture (3 additions of flour and 2 of
buttermilk). Add vanilla with last addition of buttermilk.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape 2/3 of batter into prepared pan. Add sifted cocoa to
batter remaining in bowl and beat until well blended. Fold in
chocolate chips.
</P>
<P>
   Drop large spoonfuls of chocolate mixture over batter in loaf
pan and swirl through batter with a metal spatula or flat knife,
resulting in a marbled effect.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven about 1 hour, until a cake
tester gently inserted into center of cake comes out clean. Set on
a rack to cool.
</P>
<P>
   When completely cool, release cake from pan by running a sharp
knife around inside of pan, separating cake from pan. Invert cake
onto a rack. Place a pan below rack and drizzle Chocolate Glaze
over cake. Let set. Slip a long heavy spatula under cake and
transfer cake to a flat surface.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, cut a thin slice off both ends (end pieces are for
family consumption, see Note) and cut cake into 8 slices. No
garnish is needed for this cake, but for color, place a strawberry
or a sprig of mint alongside each slice. Makes 1 loaf, about 8
servings.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Since there are no ends when baked in a bundt pan or
cupcake tins, this may not apply.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Spago Chocolate'' by Mary Bergin and Judy Gethers (Random
House). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE GLAZE
</P>
<P>
   A glaze differs from a frosting in that it is poured over a
cake. It has a shiny glassiness when it sets. A glaze has many
uses. Before frosting a cake that's not completely smooth, we pour
the glaze over, let it set and then frost. The frosting then will
be much smother and give the cake a more professional look. When
the glaze becomes slightly firm it also can be rolled into small
truffles or piped between two cookies as a filling. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
8 ounces bittersweet chocolate, cut into small pieces &QL; 
3 ounces (3/4 stick) unsalted butter, cut into small pieces &QL; 
1/3 cup light corn syrup &QL; 
1/3 cup brandy
</P>
<P>
   In a medium heatproof bowl, combine chocolate and butter and set
over a pan of simmering water. Do not let bottom of bowl touch
water, or chocolate may burn. Let melt almost completely, turn off
heat and let mixture continue to melt, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk in corn syrup and brandy until smooth. Pour through a
fine-mesh strainer into a clean medium bowl and reserve, covered,
in a warm spot until needed. Makes about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   TO PREPARE AHEAD: Glaze can be made 2 to 3 days ahead,
refrigerated, covered and remelted over simmering water when
needed. Let stand over warm water until smooth, stirring
occasionally. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MORE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1307EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
