<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8490 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-DESSERTS-TO-DIE-FOR-L 2ndadd &LR;    12-14 1908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESSERTS-TO-DIE-FOR-LADN, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 2nd add  
UNDATED: ... smooth, stirring occasionally. CLASSIC CHOCOLATE TRUFFLE CAKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is one of the most frequently requested recipes at Spago.
If you want to save time, or don't want to make your own truffles,
good-quality chocolate truffles from a reputable chocolate shop
will work almost as well. When raspberries are not at their best,
eliminate them from the truffles and pipe plain chocolate mounds
instead. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRUFFLES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces bittersweet OR semisweet chocolate &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons heavy whipping cream &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ounce (1 tablespoon) unsalted butter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flavoring of choice (Grand Marnier, Framboise,
Chambord OR vanilla) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 fresh perfect raspberries (optional) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE CAKES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces bittersweet chocolate, cut into small pieces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces (1 1/2 sticks) unsalted butter, cut into small pieces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, at room temperature &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 yolks, at room temperature &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons plus 1 teaspoon all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   For Truffles, in a small heatproof bowl set over a pan of
simmering water, combine chocolate, cream and butter. When almost
melted, remove from heat and stir mixture until smooth. Stir in
flavoring of choice and refrigerate until thick enough to mound on
a spoon, stirring occasionally, about 30 minutes. Do not let it get
too hard, since you want to pipe it.
</P>
<P>
   Line a baking tray with parchment or wax paper. Scrape chocolate
mixture into a pastry bag fitted with a No. 3 plain tip. Pipe 8
(1-inch) mounds onto prepared tray. Place 1 raspberry in center of
each chocolate mound and pipe a little more of chocolate mixture on
top to enclose completely. It will resemble a chocolate beehive.
Refrigerate until firm, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For Chocolate Cakes, position rack in center of oven. Butter (or
coat with vegetable spray) 8 oversize muffin cups (4 inches wide
and 2 inches deep) or 1 1/4-cup custard cups. Line bottoms with
rounds of wax paper. (To cut rounds, place 1 cup on wax paper and
trace around bottom with a pencil. Then cut out 8 circles and
place, pencil-side down, in cups.) Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a small heatproof bowl set over a pan of simmering water,
melt together chocolate and butter. This should be very liquid.
Cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a large bowl of an electric mixer fitted with a
paddle or beaters, on high speed, beat eggs, egg yolks and sugar
until tripled in volume, about 5 minutes. Scrape in chocolate
mixture and, on low speed, beat just until combined. Remove bowl
from mixer and fold in flour, using a rubber spatula. Spoon a
little of batter into each of prepared cups and set 1 truffle on
top, but do not push it down; cover with remaining batter. Arrange
cups on a baking tray.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 12 to 13 minutes, or until
edges of cakes begin to pull from sides of cups. Let stand 10
minutes, then invert onto individual dessert plates and carefully
peel off papers.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm. Dust with sifted powdered sugar and spoon softly
whipped cream or ice cream next to each cake. If desired, garnish
with a few fresh raspberries or chocolate curls. Serve immediately.
Makes 8 (4-inch) cakes, 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   TO PREPARE AHEAD: Arrange filled cups on a baking tray and
refrigerate until serving time. This can be done one day ahead.
About 30 minutes before baking, preheat oven, remove baking tray
from refrigerator and continue with recipe.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Spago Chocolate'' by Mary Bergin and Judy Gethers (Random
House). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COOKIES AND CREAM CHEESECAKE
</P>
<P>
   The chocolate crumble is used not ony as a crust but also as a
layer and a topping. The result is a creamy cheesecake with a
crunchy texture.
</P>
<P>
   I find the easiest way to melt the white chocolate is to break
it up into small pieces and place it in a small cup or bowl. Place
the cup in the microwave oven, cover with a paper towel and heat
chocolate 30 seconds at a time, stopping oven and stirring
chocolate, continuing to heat until melted. It shouldn't take more
than two or three 30-second periods. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE CRUMBLE: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsweetened cocoa powder &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces (1 stick) unsalted butter, chilled and cut into 1-ounce
pieces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons heavy whipping cream &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAKE: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds cream cheese, at room temperature, cut into 2-inch
pieces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup dairy sour cream &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces white chocolate, melted (see above)
</P>
<P>
   Position rack in center of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Butter or coat with vegetable spray bottom of a 9- or 10-inch
springform pan. Line a baking tray with parchment paper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For Chocolate Crumble, sift together flour, cocoa, sugar and
salt and transfer to bowl of a food processor fitted with a steel
blade. Process with on and off turns until blended. Arrange pieces
of butter around flour mixture and process until mixture resembles
coarse meal.
</P>
<P>
   In a small cup or bowl, whisk together egg yolks and cream. With
processor running, pour mixture through feed tube, making certain
you scrape out all liquid from cup. Let machine run until dough
begins to come together, about 1 minute. (You should have about 4
cups.)
</P>
<P>
   To make crust, spoon 2 cups crumble into prepared pan and press
evenly over bottom of pan. (Rounded bottom of a 1-cup measuring cup
is perfect for leveling crust, ensuring smooth edges.)
</P>
<P>
   Spread remaining crumble on prepared baking tray. Place
springform pan and baking tray in oven.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 10 to 12 minutes, or until
crumble is lightly toasted. Transfer to a rack to cool. When
completely cool, wrap heavy-duty foil _ or 2 layers of regular foil
_ around bottom and halfway up outside of springform pan, pleating
foil to tighten. Break up crumble on parchment paper, using your
hands or a fork; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For Cake, place cream cheese, sugar and salt in a large bowl of
an electric mixer fitted with a paddle or beaters. On medium speed,
beat until smooth, stopping often to scrape down sides of bowl and
under blade with a rubber spatula. Turn speed to high and continue
to beat until nice and creamy.
</P>
<P>
   Stop mixer and add sour cream, eggs and vanilla; beat 3 minutes
longer, again stopping mixer and scraping down sides of bowl and
under blade as necessary. Scrape in melted chocolate and continue
to beat until well combined and smooth. You should have about 6
cups of mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 1/2 of mixture (3 cups) into springform pan. Sprinkle 1/2
of crumble (1 cup) over; pour in remaining 3 cups mixture and cover
entire surface with remaining 1 cup crumble.
</P>
<P>
   Set springform pan in center of a slightly larger baking pan
with sides. Pour enough hot water into larger pan to reach halfway
up sides of springform pan, but not above foil. Carefully place
both pans in oven.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 1 hour. Cover cake loosely
with foil and continue to bake 20 minutes longer, until center of
cake is slightly firm. (Check water level after 30 minutes, making
certain there is enough water in pan.)
</P>
<P>
   Carefully remove both pans from oven and transfer springform pan
to a rack to cool. Fold foil down sides of pan, helping cake to
cool. When cake has cooled remove foil and allow cake to cool
completely. Cover pan loosely with a clean piece of foil and
refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, remove cheesecake from refrigerator. Dip a
long sharp knife in warm water and run knife around inside of
springform pan, loosening cake from pan. Remove outer ring.
Continue to dip knife into warm water as necessary for neatly cut
slices.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, arrange one slice of cake on a cake plate and garnish
with fresh berries of choice _ raspberries, blueberries or sliced
strawberries. Makes 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   TO PREPARE AHEAD: Crust can be made two days ahead; the cake
must be made one day ahead.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Spago Chocolate'' by Mary Bergin and Judy Gethers (Random
House). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUDGY CHOCOLATE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   This wonderfully moist, fudgy cake can be made in a 10-inch
bundt pan, as below, or in two (9x5x3-inch) loaf pans (baking time
will be 35 to 40 minutes). We first tested this cake when Jean-Paul
DeSourdie, a caterer in New York, brought it as a gift. We liked it
so much we decided that, with our minor additions, it belonged in
the Spago repertoire. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces bittersweet chocolate, cut into small pieces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces (2 sticks) unsalted butter, cut into small pieces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cold brewed coffee &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Grand Marnier OR Kahlua &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grand Marnier Sauce (optional, recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Position rack in center of oven.
</P>
<P>
   Butter (or coat with vegetable spray) a 10-inch bundt pan,
making certain you coat all ridges plus center tube. If pan does
not have a nonstick coating, dust with flour, then tap out excess.
Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together flour, baking soda and salt. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium heatproof bowl set over a pan of gently simmering
water, melt chocolate and butter, stirring occasionally. When
almost melted, turn off heat and let melt completely.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl of an electric mixer fitted with a paddle or
beaters, whip eggs. On low speed, gradually pour in sugar and
continue to beat well until mixed in, increasing speed when all
sugar has been mixed in. On low speed, scrape in melted chocolate
mixture; add vanilla and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Alternate adding flour mixture and coffee, starting and ending
with flour mixture (three additions of flour and two of coffee). Do
additions on low speed and then turn speed to high. Stop machine
occasionally and scrape around bowl and under beaters. Add Grand
Marnier and beat just until combined.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape batter into prepared pan, distributing evenly around pan
(tap pan to level batter).
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven about 1 hour, until a cake
tester inserted in middle of cake comes out clean. Cool on rack 15
minutes, then invert onto a 10-inch cardboard round and return to
rack to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, cut cake into slices and serve with a dollop of
whipped cream. Scatter a few fresh raspberries or sliced
strawberries around cake. Or spoon a little Grand Marnier Sauce
around center of each plate and set a piece of cake on sauce. Makes
1 (10-inch) cake, 8 to 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   TO PREPARE AHEAD: Cake cam be made one day ahead.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Spago Chocolate'' by Mary Bergin and Judy Gethers (Random
House). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRAND MARNIER SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   This sauce can be spooned over ice cream, to accompany cake or
chocolate crepes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups orange juice &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Grand Marnier, Triple Sec OR other orange-flavored
liqueur &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   In a medium heavy saucepan, combine all ingredients. Over
medium-high heat, bring to a boil and continue to heat until 1 3/4
cups remain, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Sauce thickens slightly as it cooks, and foam will form on top,
but it will subside.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm or at room temperature. Makes about 1 3/4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   TO PREPARE AHEAD: Sauce can be made 1 day ahead and does not
need to be refrigerated. Just keep covered. If serving warm, reheat
over low heat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MORE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
