<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESSERTS-TO-DIE-FOR-LADN, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 3rd add  
UNDATED: ... reheat over low heat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLOURLESS BITTERSWEET CHOCOLATE CAKE WITH MILK CHOCOLATE DRIZZLE
</P>
<P>
   Prepare this cake, and you can promise your guests the ultimate
experience; they will not be disappointed. A simple but
straightforward exercise in sweet surrender, this flourless cake is
glazed with dark chocolate and further drizzled with milk
chocolate. The raspberry jam and kiss of cognac add intriguing
flavor notes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FLOURLESS CHOCOLATE CAKE: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces bittersweet chocolate, coarsely chopped &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, cut into 1-inch pieces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cognac &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 large eggs, separated, at room temperature &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 2 tablespoons granulated sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE GLAZE:
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces bittersweet chocolate, coarsely chopped &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy whipping cream &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR ASSEMBLY AND GARNISH: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup seedless raspberry preserves &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces milk chocolate, melted
</P>
<P>
   For Flourless Chocolate Cake, position a rack in center of oven.
Butter bottom and sides of a 9-inch springform pan. Line bottom of
pan with a round parchment or wax paper; butter paper.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, combine chocolate and butter. Cook over
low heat, stirring constantly with a wooden spoon, until chocolate
and butter are melted. Gently whisk until smooth. Remove from heat
and stir in cognac. Let cool.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, whisk together egg yolks and 1/2 cup sugar
until well blended. Stir in melted chocolate mixture.
</P>
<P>
   In a 4 1/2-quart bowl of a heavy-duty electric mixer, using a
wire whip attachment, beat egg whites at medium speed until frothy.
Increase speed to medium-high and beat egg whites until soft peaks
start to form. One tablespoon at a time, beat in remaining 2
tablespoons sugar. Continue beating until egg whites are stiff but
not dry.
</P>
<P>
   Using a large rubber spatula, gently fold beaten egg whites into
chocolate mixture in 3 additions. Do not overmix. Pour batter into
prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven until cake is puffed and a
tester inserted into center comes out with moist crumbs attached,
about 30 minutes. Transfer pan to a wire rack and cool 10 minutes.
Using a small, sharp knife, cut around sides of cake to loosen.
Release pan side. Invert cake onto wire rack. Peel off parchment
paper and cool cake completely. Wrap in plastic wrap and
refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   For Chocolate Glaze, place chocolate in a medium bowl. In a
small saucepan, bring cream to a gentle boil. Using a wire whisk,
stir in honey. Pour hot cream mixture over chocolate and let
mixture stand 30 seconds to melt chocolate. Whisk mixture until
smooth. Cover surface of glaze with plastic wrap and set aside at
room temperature 30 minutes or until slightly thickened.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble cake, remove cake from refrigerator and remove
plastic wrap from cake. Place cake on a wire rack set over a baking
sheet. Using a metal spatula, spread raspberry preserves evenly
over top and sides of cake. Pour Chocolate Glaze over cake,
covering completely; spread evenly with a metal spatula. Drizzle
top of glazed cake with melted milk chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Serve cake immediately, or refrigerate. Bring cake to room
temperature before serving. Makes 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Chocolate Passion'' by Tish Boyle and Timothy Moriarty,
(John Wiley &AMP; Sons). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GIANDUJA TRUFFLE TART
</P>
<P>
   This is a chocolatey, decadent, rich dessert. Serve small slices
with a cup of coffee. Gianduja is a specialty item, a flavorful
blend of hazelnuts and chocolate that comes in block form like
regular baking chocolate (I use Callebaut brand). Look for it in
specialty food stores. For this recipe, use a milk chocolate
gianduja. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRUST: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 (9-ounce) box Nabisco Famous Chocolate Wafers, roughly
crumbled by hand &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup hazelnuts, skinned and toasted &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons (3 ounces) unsalted butter, melted &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILLING: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces gianduja, finely chopped &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups heavy whipping cream &QL;
</P>
<P>
   11 ounces bittersweet chocolate, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Spray an 11-inch loose-bottomed fluted tart pan with nonstick
cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   For Crust, grind cookies and nuts in a food processor, fitted
with a metal blade, until fine.
</P>
<P>
   Pour in melted butter and pulse machine on and off to combine
well. Press crumb crust over bottom and up sides of prepared tart
pan. Use a flat-bottomed glass to facilitate pressing crumbs along
bottom and to help with edges. Keeping glass flat, move toward
edges; it will press crumbs along sides, creating an even layer all
around.
</P>
<P>
   Place tart pan on a parchment-lined sheet pan.
</P>
<P>
   Blind bake crust in preheated 375-degree oven 10 minutes. Set
tart pan directly on a wire rack to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   For Filling, melt 6 ounces gianduja with 1/4 cup cream in a
double boiler or microwave. Whisk until smooth and pour into cooled
tart shell. Refrigerate 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Melt bittersweet chocolate with remaining 1 1/4 cups cream in a
double boiler or microwave. Whisk until smooth and pour over
chilled gianduja layer.
</P>
<P>
   Melt remaining 2 ounces gianduja, place in a parchment cone and
make a random design over bittersweet ganache. Refrigerate until
firm, at least 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   This tart may be refrigerated up to 2 days; cover with plastic
wrap after it has chilled for the initial 3 hours. Serve cold, in
thin slices. Remove tart from pan before serving. Makes 1 (11-inch)
tart, 10 to 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   BAKE IT TO THE LIMIT: Serve above tart with creme anglaise (any
recipe), flavored with hazelnut liqueur if you like. Have creme
anglaise made, cooled and poured into a squeeze bottle. Have
luncheon or dinner-sized plates ready for this.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 8 ounces bittersweet chocolate, finely chopped, in a double
boiler or microwave and place in a parchment cone. Make a large
star design on each plate, about 7 inches from point to point, with
melted chocolate. Refrigerate plates until chocolate sets, about 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Fill in chocolate star outline with creme anglaise. Then place a
slice of tart slightly off-center. You should be able to see star's
points radiating beyond slice. Dust plate's edges with sifted Dutch
process cocoa. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Bake It to the Limit'' By Dede Wilson (William Morrow). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
END &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
