<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNING ISSUE ISN'T THE COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Barely one-third into the NHL season, the Bruins
returned to work in need of shaking off their second troublesome
winless streak of the season and turned in an impressive 2-0 win
over the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not get too depressed,'' said Pat Burns, surrounded by a
larger-than-normal media pack after the day-of-game skate at the
FleetCenter. ``Let's not be talking suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns's reaction was in obvious response to words written in
this space Sunday that noted that winless stretches _ no matter
their causes or justifications _ often prove to be coach-killers.
The Bruins opened this season with an 0-5-4 skid, the worst they've
come out of the gate since going 0-8-1 at the start of the 1964-65
season. Headed into Monday night's go-round with Phoenix, they were
0-3-3, a stretch that included a humiliating 9-3 pasting on home
ice _ the worst on Causeway Street in Burns's tenure _ at the hands
of the dreadful Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of divots in an 82-game season that get
coaches sent packing. The most recent example is Pittsburgh, which
last week tossed Kevin Constantine overboard after two-plus seasons
and brought in gold-medal makeover artist Herb Brooks to revive
playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't stick a fork in us yet,'' proclaimed Burns, noting that
he had read Sunday's report. ``The fork's getting ready to stick in
me. We're not dead yet. This is early in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Would the Bruins give Burns the gate now? Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Would it necessarily be the right move? No.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, what we've seen of the Bruins thus far in 1999-2000
is a far, far cry from what we expected. The young core talent of
the club, expected to take off and fly after two years of
seasoning, has been overwhelmingly underwhelming. Joe Thornton is
the exception. Jumbo Joe finally is beginning to play like the
impact player that the league's Central Scouting Bureau projected
he would be before his being drafted in 1997. He's not exactly a
Hart candidate yet, but it's at least feasible to think that he
could be a franchise center in a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   But what of the rest of the young, ready-for-prime-time bunch?
</P>
<P>
   To wit:
</P>
<P>
   --Sergei Samsonov _ Only tiny flashes of brilliance. Often seems
confused, unsure whether to try to beat someone one-on-one, dish
it, or shoot it. Sixty points or more was a reasonable expectation
for this season. He had 14 before picking up a goal Monday night.
At that rate, he will be challenged to match his rookie output of
47. He looked sharper vs. the Coyotes, performing with some zip,
but has to prove he can do it consistently.
</P>
<P>
   --Jason Allison _ Burns thinks he's really in a rut, and adds
that is why Dave Andreychuk has gone cold (no goals in the 0-3-3
stretch). Allison thinks he's playing OK and that he can't be
fingered as the reason for the recent malaise. The truth here:
Allison is skilled but has a tendency to let his game go soft. He
has to apply some grit, and in a hurry, or this could be one wicked
winter on Causeway Street.
</P>
<P>
   --Anson Carter _ He is the club's No. 2 point-getter (22 vs.
Thornton's 28). So why are we not impressed? Because Carter had a
very impressive second half in '98-99 _ a pair of late-season hat
tricks and that thrilling OT playoff goal vs. Carolina immediately
come to mind _ but he hasn't come close to returning to that form
yet this year. He was defining his career. Now, he too often looks
like he's coasting, waiting, looking for his game to find him.
</P>
<P>
   --Byron Dafoe _ He was a franchise goalie when the playoffs came
to an end. Now? He's still in the process of getting it together
after waiting a month to sign, but before Monday night he had a
mundane .887 save percentage. He was second in the league last year
at .926. That's like a .340 hitter in baseball dipping down to
.276. Just OK, nothing special. If Monday's performance (32
shots/32 saves) is the real thing, then that could change the
club's dynamic significantly.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, instead of building on last year's momentum, this
club is struggling just to get back the beat. Yes, they did rattle
off six straight wins (Oct. 23-Nov. 6). Yes, they were four games
over .500 by Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   But virtually across the board, the offense has been
disappointing and Dafoe's goaltending mostly mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Equally troublesome has been the minuscule contribution from
Providence. The best of the Baby B's this year has been netminder
John Grahame, but he was hauled back down Route 95, his contract
sweetened slightly, soon after Dafoe came in for the cash. A couple
of times each week, a kid or two gets called to Boston, only to be
hustled back to Providence after barely getting a glimpse of Quincy
Market. Convinced the Baby B's can't cut it here, the Bruins in
recent weeks have added graybeards Joe Murphy and Marty McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk was a brilliant offseason acquisition, but this many
911 calls to the Salvation Army speaks to a dysfunctional feeder
system. These are jobs that young prospects should be filling.
Where are the kids? Where is the future? Two-plus seasons after
finishing dead last in the NHL and noting the obvious need to
replenish the pipeline, it's just not there.
</P>
<P>
   Who next in the spoked B? Kirk Muller? Brian Bellows? Vladimir
Krutov?
</P>
<P>
   Here's where your faithful correspondent believes this is going
if the core fails to get it going: The front office soon will
mandate that Burns adopt two or three orphans from Providence and
force them into game action with real minutes. They may not cut it.
They may be worse than what he's got, but it will be up to him to
turn them into players.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is an excellent coach. He'd be even better if he had a
better lineup under his thumb. He'd be even better if the lineup he
does have were to play up to capabilities. Thus far, that's more
their fault than his, just as the playing stock is far more
management's charge than his.
</P>
<P>
   But we have heard and seen all that before here in the Hub of
hockey. Go ask Butch Goring, Rick Bowness, Brian Sutter, Steve
Kasper, et al. As loyal and financially willing as the fan base is,
this is not a franchise that can afford to be stagnant, risk
slipping back to where it was before Burns's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Early? Not on a clock that has been running now for almost 2 1/2
years. The truth is, it's time _ for better effort, better results,
and a better return for a town that hasn't seen a Stanley Cup for
going on 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
