<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-FOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORPIONS, MADAM? A LIVE, AUTHENTIC CHINESE MENU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   XI'AN, China _ The table had been set out with a savory-smelling
and artistically presented banquet: shish-kebabbed cicadas with
green peppers; black ants sprinkled on hard-boiled eggs; sauteed
scorpions layered on shrimp chips; French-fried larvae and
silkworm; and the piece de resistance _ live scorpions crawling up
a 10-inch pagoda carved from a turnip.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that dinner at the Three Brothers Scorpion
Restaurant is more than just a meal; it's an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   The vast panoply of Chinese cuisine proudly embraces many things
that American cooking does not, from chicken feet to snake, from
seaweed to dog. But like birds'-nest and sharks'-fin soup,
scorpions have never been everyday fare; they were a delicacy
believed to have originated in the celebrated reign of the
18th-century Qianlong Emperor, when a single fried scorpion was
served to each diner as an end-of-meal treat.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a food that doctors of traditional Chinese medicine,
and some scientists, believe has powerful health benefits. The Liu
brothers _ who claim to be the first in China to have reintroduced
scorpions to their menu _ say a visit to their restaurant offers
both a novelty and a cure.
</P>
<P>
   As Chinese society becomes more prosperous and cosmopolitan,
wealthy and adventurous Chinese are seeking ways to experiment with
food, just as they have with music and fashion. China has
mind-boggling regional variety in its cuisine, but relatively few
foreign restaurants. In the same way that American yuppies have
embraced Ethiopian or Burmese cuisine _ foods that seemed strange
even a decade ago _ well-heeled Chinese are flocking to try exotic
foods from their own gastronomic history.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese feel the same delight mixed with horror that a
daring foreigner might experience in eating a live bug. But even as
they revel in the exotica, diners also hail the connection to
Chinese medicine.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent evening, Wang Hao, 31, a Beijing manager visiting
this central Chinese city on business, expertly used his chopsticks
to pluck a squirming scorpion off its pagoda and dangle it
theatrically over his mouth while his friends downed shots of
scorpion-infused wine and egged him on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come for the experience _ for fun,'' he shouted over the
din. ``It's in the Chinese character _ we want to try something
new.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that tasty, but it's really good for the health,''
Wang said enthusiastically, biting off the body and waiting three
seconds for the once-lethal tail to stop wagging before he placed
it on his tongue. (The scorpions undergo a 13-step, 6-month process
to extract most of the poison and sterilize them.) ``The more
poisonous, the more healthy it is for the body.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite that simple. But Chinese medicine follows the
homeopathic principle that something toxic can, in small doses,
cure the very ailments that a large dose would cause. Scorpion
venom is thought to cure a range of ailments from fever, chills,
convulsions and anxiety to arthritis, skin problems, immune
disorders, and kidney problems. Some even claim that eating the
bugs cures cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Kong Tianhan, director of a team that conducted an eight-year
study of the medicinal uses of scorpion at Henan Medical Science
University, said a polypeptide extracted from scorpion venom is
effective against human tumors, relieves pain of cancer patients,
and boosts the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   That was old news to the three Liu brothers. They had trained as
chefs and studied nutrition, and for years they pored over Chinese
food literature to come up with a recipe that would combine health
food with creative dining. Finally they hit upon scorpions, which
had died out as food after Qianlong's time, and which are native to
this region of Shaanxi province. Voila _ a gourmet novelty was
born.
</P>
<P>
   ``By now, China has pretty much solved its food problem. People
have enough food, so now they can consider food `culture,' instead
of just eating to satisfy their hunger,'' said Chen Dan, the
restaurant's manager. ``We call it `future food' or `21st-century
food.' In the 21st century, people will be more and more concerned
about healthy food.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But first the more timid will have to recover from the
shock of facing a tableful of fried, roasted, and sauteed bugs.
</P>
<P>
   The insects and arachnids are artfully arranged on beds of
lettuce and garnished with broccoli, maraschino cherries, radishes
carved into flowers, and sugar-coated potato chips. The seasonings
are a tasty, subtle combination of cayenne pepper, cumin, and soy.
The dishes have evocative names such as ``Golden cicadas on sticks,
Scorpions rolled in the snow, Fresh blossom worm and five-flavored
silkworm larvae, or Drunken scorpions climbing the pagoda.''
</P>
<P>
   Fried scorpions are crunchy on the outside and sandy inside. The
fried rice worms taste like oily French fries. The toast stuffed
with minced chicken and embedded with a scorpion is sweet and
delicious _ though it's hard to avoid eye contact with the topping.
The cicadas have a chewy, meaty taste. The ants are crunchy and
vinegary and could almost pass for cheap caviar.
</P>
<P>
   The raw, live scorpions, once bitten, don't bite back. There is
a definite adrenaline rush to the experience, but the taste is
unremarkable: crunchy, but bland.
</P>
<P>
   To round out the meal, there's scorpion soup and sorghum wine
steeped in 20 herbal medicines and six scorpions.
</P>
<P>
   Chen trumpeted the benefits of each dish. Ants smooth wrinkles,
turn white hair black, and counter diabetes, she said. Silkworms
are high in protein, though their history is sadder; they were
eaten out of desperation by people banished to the barren
countryside during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution. Cicadas are
good for hearing, anxiety, and male virility. The wine is good for
kidneys, migraines, and cancer prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the diners on a typical night were Chinese tour groups
and out-of-town businessmen, but there were some locals so sold on
the reputed curative properties that they have become regulars. One
woman who was diagnosed with breast cancer comes here every other
evening with her husband. The pair eat 30 live scorpions, and at 45
cents each, it's a very expensive dish by Chinese standards. But
the woman believes the scorpions have kept her disease in
remission.
</P>
<P>
   At $17, the most expensive dish was the poisonous tree ants
imported from France. The other insects are collected in the wild
and raised on a nearby farm.
</P>
<P>
   Chen won't share the secret of extracting enough poison to make
the stinging creatures edible, but leaving enough to make them
potent. But she revealed one trick of the live pagoda dish: the
scorpions are soaked for a few minutes in alcohol to anesthetize
them _ but ``not too long or they faint.''
</P>
<P>
   Some didn't seem very drunk as they performed acrobatics on the
chopsticks. But Chen reassured that only about one diner a year
gets bitten, and insists there is no real danger thanks to the
detoxification process.
</P>
<P>
   China's president, Jiang Zemin, has dined here and liked the raw
scorpions best, Chen says. Owner Liu Kaijun, a former chef at the
Chinese Embassy in Washington, thinks other enlightened diners will
agree, and hopes to open a branch someday in the United States
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreigners may be very interested,'' Chen said, ``because they
are concerned with their health and also like exciting things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
