<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL _ THE PERFECT GIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still trying to find that perfect gift?
</P>
<P>
   Why not give the gift of travel? Many folks would certainly
appreciate a cruise or airplane ticket somewhere, but price-wise
that's out of the question for most of us. But, why not give a gift
certificate for a portion of a trip or a getaway?
</P>
<P>
   Travel gift certificates are easy to get, can be quite
inexpensive, and always fit, no matter what the person's size or
interests might be. For example, cruise lines offer a variety of
bon voyage gifts from wine to on-board credits to use in the shops
or for a shore excursion. Gift certificates can be purchased to be
used toward a trip or for a hotel stay.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott Hotels is offering gift certificates that can be used
for weekend getaways at their properties. And, if you order one and
pay for it with a Visa card, you'll save $10 on each certificate.
For details, call 800-813-GIFT.
</P>
<P>
   Bass Hotels (Inter-Continental, Crowne Plaza, Holiday Inn,
Holiday Inn Express, and Staybridge Suites by Holiday Inn) offer a
Prepaid Guest Card, which can be used toward any charge at their
hotels. The cards, similar to a credit card, are available in
amounts of $25 and up. For details, call 877-994-8378.
</P>
<P>
   Some other ideas:
</P>
<P>
   What could be better for an inexpensive gift than a calendar,
especially one that lists many fun events in New England for the
year 2000? For 20 years, Kanin Press (PO Box 1174, Portsmouth, NH
03802; 603-433-4775) has made New England Weekenders calendars. For
2000, it's as informative as ever, and even more colorful with
wonderful paintings of favorite locations throughout the region.
Not only will you be able to plan great weekend getaways, but
there's also room for your notations. The calendars are available
in stores or from the publisher at $13.95 a copy, plus $5.50
shipping. Kanin also produces a Weekenders Calendar for the
Mid-Atlantic states, and three lighthouse calendars: New England,
the Cape Cod area, and one for the Southeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   While it may seem a strange gift, the new paperback edition of
``The Merck Manual of Medical Information _ Home Edition'' ($7.95)
could be the perfect antidote for a medical problem on a trip. The
book is the same one doctors have used for years, only this one is
in everyday language. In its hardcover edition, it has already sold
more than a million copies, but the paperback is lighter and easier
to carry.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is to give a book about a place where your traveler
is going or has been. ``Great Lodges of the Canadian Rockies'' by
Christine Barnes (WW West, $35) will certainly evoke memories of a
visit there. Not only are the photos stunning, but also the stories
about these lodges are fascinating. Most of these grand hotels were
built to lure Easterners west, and give the Canadian Pacific
Railroad business.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe your travelers raved about a food treat from the last
trip. If they've been to the Cayman Islands, a rum cake from there
is perfect. Try the original one from Tortuga Rum Cake
(800-444-0625) or from Blackbeard's Liquors (888-947-2253), which
makes its own ``award-winning rum'' for the cake. For other Cayman
Island ideas, call the tourist board at 800-346-3313.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are hundreds of items made just for travel _ some
for comfort, others for convenience. Two of the best sources for
travel needs are the catalogs of Magellan's (800-962-4943 or
www.magellans.com) or TravelSmith (800-950-1600 or
www.travelsmith.com).
</P>
<P>
   And, with so many shopping on line these days, here's an idea
for finding the right gifts and rewarding yourself. At
www.clickrewards.com you can shop at all the top on-line retailers
and earn ClickRewards, which can be redeemed for airline miles, or
for other gifts. If you use a credit card that earns frequent flyer
miles, you'll get double miles, and some merchants on the service
are offering double miles on their own, which means you could earn
triple or more miles. Should you be embarrassed by these riches,
with a click you can donate these extra miles to a favorite
charity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Holiday stroll
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take a stroll along Boston's famed Freedom Trail this holiday
season and you just might meet Paul Revere, Mother Goose, Abigail
Adams, and James Otis. The Freedom Trail Players will be leading
walking tours along the trail beginning Dec. 18 through Dec. 21
between 2 and 3:30 p.m. There will be carolers, refreshments, and
gift shop discounts for those who purchase tickets. Tickets are
available at BosTix booths ($10 adult, $5 children) or from
Ticketmaster at 617-931-2000. Tours begin at the Boston Common
Visitors Center. For more information, call the Freedom Trail
Foundation at 617-227-8800.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 96th anniversary of the Wright Brothers First Flight at
Kitty Hawk will be held on Dec. 17 at the Wright Brothers National
Memorial in Kill Devil Hills. For information, call the Dare County
Tourist Bureau at 800-446-5106.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
New Year's Eve stroll
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Adventure on a Shoestring will be running five
walking tours of Chinatown on Dec. 31. The tours will be led by
Howard Goldberg, who has been doing these walks ($10 a person) for
years. For information, call 212-265-2663.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meet Mrs. Astor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, visitors have toured the Astors' Beechwood home in
Newport, R.I. Never has Mrs. Astor been present, tourgoers have
usually been ushered out of the mansion before she appears. Now,
Mrs. Astor (Newport resident Peg Kieman) will welcome visitors to
her home  &UR; today &LR;  and Dec. 17-18. For details and to check on
reservations, call 401-846-3772.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tour to Cuba
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A different way to welcome in the new century is by a visit to
Cuba. The Global Exchange _ a nonprofit organization that works for
global political, economic, environmental, and social justice _ is
featuring a tour to Cuba Dec. 27-Jan. 4. ``Cuba is one of the few
modern countries that likely will not be greatly inconvenienced by
any Y2K bugs because the country is not as computer-reliant as
other nations,'' said Malia Everette, director of the program. The
trip costs $2,000 and includes air fare from Mexico City. For
information on this and other trips, write Global Exchange, 2017
Mission St. 303, San Francisco, CA 94110; call 415-255-7296.
</P>
</TEXT>
