<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HARVARD-COUNSELORS-BO     12-14 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-COUNSELORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD TO ADDRESS STUDENTS' MENTAL HEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Recognizing that more students are suffering
from mental disorders, from typical adolescent stress to depression
and schizophrenia, Harvard University is planning a large-scale
effort to help identify and treat students before their conditions
become life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations outlined in the executive report circulated
last week include hiring more young psychologists in the
university's health service, offering training to resident advisers
and professors on how to identify and refer students who may be
struggling with serious problems, and setting up ``safe spaces''
for severely stressed students in each of the 12 undergraduate
residence houses.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard is hardly alone in its concern about student mental
health. While there are few studies, many universities and national
organizations of college health counselors say they are seeing more
and more students coming on campus with serious mental health
problems, or developing problems, especially depression, while
there.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard and other challenging schools may be particular
pressure cookers: the university's report talks about students who
have never failed before, and fear that conceding even the
slightest struggle is admitting defeat; in other cases, it says,
students don't confide in resident advisers or tutors out of fear
they might not be able to get good recommendations for graduate
school or jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the years of young adulthood are the years of the
onset of many psychological illnesses, and on top of that they are
a time of significant stresses,'' said Paul Summergrad, associate
professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the head of
the committee that wrote the report. ``There's just a lot of
pressure on kids, coming into the university, and given the value
families are placing on elite university degrees. We have kids
coming in and taking their SATs in 5th and 6th grade. . . . Hitting
the wall becomes a pretty big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes the consequences can be extreme. A Harvard
undergraduate four years ago stabbed her roommate to death, then
hanged herself. At Johns Hopkins University, one student shot
another while they were leaving a campus club meeting. And after
the suicide of a graduate student last year, the chemistry
department at Harvard hired a psychiatrist whom students can see
free.
</P>
<P>
   While the university is acting in hopes of preventing another
tragedy, it also wanted to act in the absence of any crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately (the murder-suicide) is the most serious failure of
the system,'' said Harvey Fineberg, provost and former dean at the
university's School of Public Health, who commissioned the report.
``One of the reasons I was very determined to undertake this
assessment now is that there is not an immediate tragedy or crisis.
You can look objectively, dispassionately, unemotionally,
critically, at what's going on. If you do it in the aftermath of a
tragedy, everyone's defensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Health professionals say the anecdotal increase in the incidence
of mental problems on campus could be because diagnosis has become
better. In addition, students whose mental illnesses once might
have prevented them from advancing through school are getting
better treatment and medication, allowing them to flourish in high
school and eventually attend top schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they succeed in school, you may be enriching your pool of
college age students with a lot of talented individuals who
nevertheless are psychologically vulnerable,'' Fineberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, identifying or dealing with mental disorders can be
particularly difficult on campus, given the age of the students,
and the intersection, as the Harvard report notes, of ``residential
life and the life of the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, the report notes, becomes deciding, ``Is a
student's inability to finish a paper due to poor study habits,
changing academic interests . . . or an obsessive compulsive
disorder? Is difficulty living with roommates a cultural adjustment
or a manifestation of social phobia? Is change in behavior or
appearance a struggle for a new sense of self or a reflection of
incipient schizophrenia?''
</P>
<P>
   The report, based on eight months of interviews, found
administrators at each of Harvard's graduate and undergraduate
divisions emphasizing the ``increasing fragility of students and
apparent higher incidence of depression and serious mental
illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Students complained that resident tutors were chosen without
consideration of how well they interact with undergraduates. While
many students seek help from the university's Health Services, some
students wait as long as a month to be seen by a psychologist, and
many of the psychologists do not have training in dealing with
young adult issues. The student who killed her roommate, for
example, had been seen in the health services, but by someone with
training in education, and not in recognizing or dealing with
mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to more staff and the establishment of ``safe
spaces,'' the university has already taken steps to set up a
coordinating council to oversee the delivery of mental health care
on campus. Each house has been newly assigned a liaison to the
university health services. The university also wants each of its
academic departments to offer faculty training in recognizing when
they should refer students to mental health services. Ultimately,
administrators say, they want to make sure that no student is more
than two steps away from getting needed help.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of us, what's important is where we live, who our
friends are, how our community works, and what happens at work,''
said Michael Jellinek, chief of child psychiatry at Massachusetts
General Hospital, who specializes in establishing systems of
support. ``All of those things interact, and push more of us over
the edge, or fewer of us over the edge. You have to think through
all of those things, from soup to nuts, take an emotional and a
developmental perspective, and see if there are things you can do,
which will not mean that everyone's going to go through it fine,
but it does mean that more people will go through it fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
