<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-PULLOUT-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARISTIDE'S SILENCE ADDS TO UNCERTAINTY IN HAITI 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ All of Haiti awaits him.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000 prisoners held without trial.
</P>
<P>
   The mother superior who grieves for the nun shot to death
outside her convent.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher who lacks a light at night to prepare his lessons.
</P>
<P>
   And the country's elected officials, all nine of them.
</P>
<P>
   They wait for Jean-Bertrand Aristide.
</P>
<P>
   They wait for the slender former president to say something, to
show himself outside his compound, at the end of a lane of
flowering trees and fragrant, white-blossomed Old World gardenias.
</P>
<P>
   Aristide, 46, is expected to run for president again next year,
and to win easily. But his silence on public matters over the past
18 months has contributed to a growing uncertainty about him, and
about Haiti's future.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery has deepened: What is Aristide doing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to keep silent and work,'' he said at his private
residence, in his first extensive interview with an American
journalist in a year. ``I want to educate the poor and work in the
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, behind two well-guarded metal gates in the
lowlands near the international airport, he is Haiti's shadow
president. He is the unelected but widely acknowledged national
leader, the first in nearly 196 years of torturous independence to
act on behalf of the poor, a priest-turned-president overthrown
early in his term who then returned to power on the heels of an
invading force of 20,000 US troops.
</P>
<P>
   Now he serves as Haiti's political godfather, receiving
businessmen, US and foreign leaders, competing parliament
candidates seeking his support in March elections, and groups of
street children arriving on the weekends to eat lunch and swim in
his pool.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned the children time and again. He knows it is
paradise for them; there is not a single public pool in Haiti. And
for him? Well, for one thing, they are essentially his only contact
with the poor, for whom he put his life on the line in helping
destroy 30 years of Duvalier family dictatorship. The last count is
nine attempts on his life.
</P>
<P>
   But the longer he remains out of sight, the more tenacious the
rumors become, snaking around Haiti, slipping into the White House,
penetrating the large expatriate communities in Boston, New York,
and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In those places, people whisper that some of his aides profit
from drug traffic; that Aristide has directed supporters to disrupt
political rallies, including one in which people threw urine at a
crowd; that Aristide lives as a king, with a second swimming pool _
this one on his roof.
</P>
<P>
   To that, Aristide laughed, the stiffness leaving his body as he
leaned forward in his home office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that,'' he said. ``Because in Haiti there is a saying,
`twou manti pa fon.' It means the hole of the lie is not deep. The
best way for me to fight against those liars is to let them lie and
the truth will come. It is a free country, you are free to say the
truth, free to lie. I choose the truth, you choose the lie, go
ahead, and I should pray for you to lie more often. Because I do
not need to defend myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While he lives behind walls with his wife, the former Mildred
Trouillot, and their daughters, Christine, 3, and Micaele, 1, his
opponents in Washington and elsewhere have helped turn the Clinton
administration away from Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Clinton's extraordinary commitment of troops and
funding followed many months of internal administration squabbling
over how to oust the military coup leaders and reinstate Aristide.
Many raised doubts about him, most notoriously in a widely leaked
CIA profile that questioned his mental stability. (The CIA refused
a Globe request for a background briefing on Haiti this month.)
</P>
<P>
   There were also questions in Washington about the effectiveness
of an invasion. But after Jimmy Carter negotiated the deployment of
troops in September 1994, the US force arrived without major
incident. Aristide returned a month later, and the coup leadership
scattered to the United States, Panama, and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   By prior arrangement, Aristide served only the last 14 months of
his five-year term, handing over power to his former prime
minister, Rene Preval, in Haiti's first peaceful transition from
one elected president to the next. Preval remains president of a
skeleton government until a successor is chosen in November.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy, though, has stumbled badly. Infrastructure has not
supported development. Corruption has remained rooted. Parliament
has fought with Preval, and after legislators could not meet a
constitutional requirement to set a new date for elections, Preval
dissolved the body last January.
</P>
<P>
   Without a functioning government, Haiti cannot legally receive
direct foreign funds, and now between $500 million and $800 million
is in limbo, much of it perhaps lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament elections are set for March 2000, and a presidential
vote for November next year, but there are no guarantees either
will take place as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the US troop presence has dwindled over the past five
years to 450. The permanent US mission ends Jan. 1, although
rotating troops will arrive for the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon planners are relieved to pull back from a mission that
has cost an estimated $2 billion. They had long worried about the
safety of the troops, who were divided in Haiti into a group that
built schools and clinics, and a group that guarded the builders.
Often, the security detail outnumbered by 2 to 1 the troops doing
the work.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress also are happy. They have criticized the
US Haiti policy ever since eager Clinton aides called the work
there a victory in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, US Representative Porter Goss, a Florida Republican
and a former CIA agent who chairs the Select Intelligence
Committee, testified at a congressional hearing that ``if there was
a case study of the failed foreign policy of the Clinton
administration, Haiti would probably be the first example.''
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``The passion for brutality hasn't changed there.
There's a question now whether we're headed toward more violence
there, whether we're headed toward a new Tontons Macoute'' _ the
dreaded militia created by the dictator Francois ``Papa Doc''
Duvalier and continued under his son, Jean Claude.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier hearing, Goss focused on Aristide: ``You can't do
much of anything in Haiti without the blessing of Aristide. . . .
When we talk of authoritarian government, (it's) soon to be the
authoritarian government of Aristide.''
</P>
<P>
   Haiti's problems, as cited by Goss and other Republicans, seem
endless. The government does not function, people do not feel
secure, police killings are on the rise, judges are corrupt, about
80 percent of those in Haiti's jails are still awaiting trial, and
drugs from Colombia flow easily through the nation.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt about the depth of Haiti's problems, or that
US policy makers see only one major strategic interest in Haiti: It
sits 550 miles south of Florida, making the United States
vulnerable to a flood of refugees in a time of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Absent that threat and with the intractibility of Haiti's
problems, US interest is bound to slide. ``We can't continue to
keep Haiti in tutelage,'' the US ambassador, Timothy Carney, said
from his second-floor office, which overlooks the waterfront Harry
Truman Boulevard. ``It's self-defeating to continue in the present
mode, because Haiti, any country, will eventually react to the
presence of foreigners who are in positions of seeming control or
are too numerous.''
</P>
<P>
   But the distancing from Haiti also has been accelerated by
Aristide himself _ mainly by his decision to cloister himself from
most of his country, according to several US officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haiti is floating off our radar screen,'' a senior US official
in Washington said on condition of anonymity. ``Aristide's friends
in Washington are dwindling. It's not that Aristide has become the
devil, but that he hasn't become more of a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
