<HEADER>
A8553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-HAITI-PULLOUT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     12-14 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-PULLOUT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 PORT AU PRINCE, Haiti: ... a leader.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where does a leader begin in Haiti?
</P>
<P>
   Just an hour's drive around Port-au-Prince shows the vast needs
of the country: smelly open sewage, roads chewed up by runoff water
from the surrounding hills, people bulging out of the zany-colored
Haitian buses known as ``tap-taps,'' bearing names such as
Temperance, Grace, Dignity, and I Love You My God.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only an hour at the Aristide Foundation for Democracy, which
Aristide started about three years ago, shows the hand of a leader.
The foundation, run out of a new warehouse, auditorium, and office
complex, includes a grocery store, a 14-hour-a-day radio show run
by street children, literacy training workshops, a cooperative
farm, and a program that has given out more than 12,000 loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundation is not Haiti,'' Aristide said by his desk at
home, sitting beneath a portrait of his dear friend, assassinated
priest Jean-Marie Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only part of Haiti. But how to broaden the picture and
make it clearer to the whole country? I think this is an issue of
speaking the truth, and I'll explain.''
</P>
<P>
   He took a deep breath and returned to what he called the
country's structural injustices. For example, 1 percent of the
population controls 45 percent of the wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the same group of people who led the coup against me,
who now are behind a huge campaign of disinformation. They are
fighting against their own people. We had and still have an
apartheid society. We don't call it racism, but that is what it is.
. . . As we say in Creole, `Anal fa bet pa bet,' which means, `They
are illiterate but they are not dumb.' They can see what is going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   His answer on how to lead, though, was to first lower
expectations on behalf of the poor. The poor, he said, first need
dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Aristide and hundreds of his Fanmi Lavalas party activists have
written issue papers for the elections in March. One pledge is to
build many schools; only an estimated 50 percent of Haiti's
children attend school.
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy also carries into his talks on business deals
for the country, although it is unclear what, if any, commitments
Aristide can make while out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about new projects, Aristide said nothing about basic
improvements but instead highlighted plans for a $33 million
seaport and four new international airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome foreign investors,'' he said. ``We want the public
and private sector to work together. In Haiti, that means not
allowing anyone to use weapons or money or their positions to
unfairly benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Haiti drifts, and even Aristide's friends
wonder whether he understands what is happening outside his gates.
</P>
<P>
   People are so poor that a man recently killed a nun for money.
Inside the convent of the Sisters of the St. Louis Charities, the
mother superior, who would not give her name because of her fears,
told the story of Sister Marie Geralde Robert being shot in her
left cheekbone at 9:40 p.m. Nov. 17 as she rang the convent bell.
``The sister who died died with her protector, but her protector
doesn't carry a gun,'' the mother superior said.
</P>
<P>
   Educators cannot even teach the struggle for democracy.
</P>
<P>
   At a 12th anniversary commemoration at the site of a November
1987 election day massacre, few of the hundreds of schoolchildren
present knew about the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know why I am here!'' shouted Belane Azor, 17, a
sentiment echoed by his classmates. As an Aristide activist yelled
at pupils that they must know their history, teacher Rodnay
Debcieux, 42, said he was embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a country where most of the people are
illiterate,'' he said quietly. ``There is so much to do. So many
problems. I cannot prepare my lessons because there is no
electricity at night. And if I go outside and stand under a lamp, I
might never make it home because someone could shoot me.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Haiti, at least by Western standards of free press and
speech, has made some strides toward democracy in the past five
years. One is simply the absence of the army, which Aristide
disbanded in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Aristide said he needs to preach peace among Haitians. ``We need
not to say yes to impunity, but not to encourage violence,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing will come easily. The rumors are proving hard enough to
beat back. Aristide volunteered an example, another one about his
pool. One day, a street child asked him whether he could get AIDS
from swimming there. Soon, all the children told him they had heard
the same story, that if you swam in Aristide's pool you would come
down with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they lie like that, they don't help themselves,'' he
said, a hint of anger rising in his voice. ``It's so stupid, so
cynical, to tell a kid of the streets such nonsense when we know
how difficult it is for Haitians to find clean water.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will continue to lie,'' Aristide said, ``and I will
continue to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
