<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS ON THIN ICE FOR PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots are at the mercy of other
forces. They could win their last three games and still not make
the playoffs. They could finish 9-7 and still make the playoffs.
The calculations are endless this time of the year, and the
complicated AFC playoff picture likely will not be clear until the
final week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unsual time of the year,'' said Patriots coach Pete
Carroll. ``You can't predict how it will go. Teams get a second
life, and hopefully we're one of them. The only way to do that is
to win them out. That means trying to get a win in Philly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wade (Phillips in Buffalo) is fighting it, Jimmy (Johnson in
Miami) is fighting it. If Minnesota had pulled the game out (over
Kansas City Sunday night), we had tremendous opportunity to gain
all around and we didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With their 20-15 loss in Indianapolis Sunday, the Patriots did
not gain any ground, but they didn't lose much, either, because
Miami and Buffalo also lost.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll does the figuring and the calculating. He does it
because he needs to tell his team, as he did Monday, that there is
hope of making the playoffs. He has been in this position before,
as an assistant coach with the Jets and Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year the Jets were 8-8 (1991), we got big-time help the
last game of the season,'' said Carroll. ``In Minnesota (in 1989),
St. Louis beat Dallas in the last game. St. Louis was struggling
and Dallas was playing real well so it was quite a surprise. It put
us in the playoffs and we made a pretty good darn run.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalls that his wife had given up hope for the Vikings in
1989 and decided to complete her Christmas shopping at a local mall
on the final Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was walking through a section where the TVs were _
furniture section _ and she saw the game on TV and she stopped and
watched, and that's where she found out we were in the playoffs,''
said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has happened. It always happens to somebody. It needs to be
us. We have to get it done this weekend. It has to start this
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Patriots have an easier schedule than any of the
teams they are vying with for a playoff spot. New England's last
three opponents _ Philadelphia, Buffalo, Baltimore _ have a
combined winning percentage of 42.5 (17-23).
</P>
<P>
   While Carroll is aware of that, he also knows the speculation
and guesswork is just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look for a sea of hope, you look at the schedule and
see what's going on,'' he said. ``You can't tell. You try to figure
this team has done that and this team has done this, but you don't
know. You think you might know but you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though they are still alive, Carroll and his players know
that, in the words of linebacker Ted Johnson, they ``blew it'' by
losing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys are pissed off today,'' said tight end Ben
Coates. ``After watching the film, we had so many chances to win
the game. All we can do is just keep on winning and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In reflecting on the game, Carroll said the Patriots could have
done more than the obvious to win. Beyond the red zone problems,
Carroll thought his defensive backs missed a couple of
opportunities to pick off passes. There also were penalty problems.
And a costly Drew Bledsoe interception just before the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew had a chance to hit Shawn (Jefferson) one time in the
corner,'' said Carroll. ``Drew had the chance to get the ball to
Ben. I'm not putting it on him because I thought he threw the ball
like crazy. He was hitting everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll also pointed out that Lamont Warren busted inside for a
7-yard gain to the 1 on a failed third-quarter drive where ``one
block would have sprung him for the touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   He also half-kiddingly lamented the bye week coming when it did
_ when the Patriots were 6-2 and coming off a decisive win in
Arizona _ though everyone at the time said it came at a perfect
juncture. Since the bye, they've gone 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we didn't have the damned bye,'' said Carroll. ``I
don't know what it is, but we got back into games with our division
after it and we knew that would be a dogfight. We haven't been able
to survive our division. The break in the action . . . I don't know
. . . the timing of it was excellent in that it allowed us to get
healthy. I'm saying this tongue-in-cheek, but we haven't answered
it like we need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, all of the could-have-beens are huge, and all the
reflection won't do any good.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's in someone else's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a lot of heart from us and a lot of help
from other people,'' said Carroll. ``We can play with all the heart
we want to play with the next three weeks, but if nobody loses,
we're dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
