<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING AT A GAME OF CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Fear is in the eyes of some Patriots today.
Resignation is in the eyes of others. Blankness is in the eyes of
nearly everyone.
</P>
<P>
   They are shell-shocked this morning, reeling from having lost
four of their last five games, stunned at their inability to solve
the offensive problems that week after week keep them out of the
end zone just often enough to lose again.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, at the 11th hour plus 57 minutes, they finally seemed to
understand the predicament they have created for themselves. It is
simple. Their destiny is out of their hands now.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots no longer control their fate, unless they keep on
losing, in which case they would seal it. They must count on others
to save them from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't done yet,'' said Troy Brown, who is pound for pound
the toughest guy on this team, mentally and physically. ``We're
still alive. You're still alive until you're dead. We're going to
need a lot of help, but it ain't done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown can talk that way because he majored in computer science
at Marshall, so he understands math, and math is the only thing the
Patriots have going for them. But even if they have begun to play
like cadavers, Brown's point of view is the only one you can take
now. It is the only way you can look at them and still talk of
playoff chances. They do remain viable, but reality enters into
these things eventually, even in New England, a region whose view
of its football team so often seems to stray far from reality. And
the reality of their situation can be summed up in one word.
</P>
<P>
   Dire.
</P>
<P>
   There are seven AFC teams ahead of the Patriots fighting for six
playoff slots, and every one of them has the advantage in all
manner of tie-breakers because of New England's dismal division and
conference records. Because of that, you can say only one thing if
you play football in New England. You can say only that you are
still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that you are on life support must be ignored. The
Patriots' playoff life could not appear frailer, yet all week you
will hear only of how they know they need help and help has come in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   They know they are playing just terribly enough to lose four
times since the return of the Parcells Effect, yet they talk of
help as if they were Tonto waiting for the arrival of the
ever-reliable Lone Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   This collapse began when New England was beaten by Bill
Parcells's staggering Jets five Sundays ago. They have gone 1-4
after losing to him for the third straight year. They can say all
they want in Foxborough about how there is no longer anything
between Parcells and his old team, but the fact of their annual
collapse puts the lie to that.
</P>
<P>
   Three straight years. Three straight losses to Parcells's team,
followed by three straight collapses and three straight 1-4 runs.
Whether that is because Parcells and defensive assistants Bill
Belichick, Al Groh, and Romeo Crennel keep devising the blueprint
for others to follow to beat the Patriots or simply because the
annual loss reminds too many people in Foxborough of what has been
lost is impossible to know.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that the collapse dropped a haughty 6-2 team
into fourth place in the division, bringing it closer to the
last-place Jets than the first-place Colts.
</P>
<P>
   But where there are games left, there is always hope.
</P>
<P>
   They know this, just as they know they are in deep trouble, and
so they chose to focus on the positive Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unusual time of year,'' coach Pete Carroll said.
``Teams seem to get a second life. Look what happened Monday. We
had a tremendous opportunity to gain ground across the board and we
didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   No they did not, and that brings to mind a sad thought. What if
they've already gotten all the help they're going to get?
</P>
<P>
   New England lost on a day it could have tied the floundering
Dolphins, slipping Bills, and fading Seahawks, who all lost to drop
to 8-5. Only Kansas City, which has a win over New England and thus
the tie-breaker advantage, won, but it is also only 8-5. So New
England had help but gained no ground.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, when the Patriots lost to Buffalo, Miami lost the
same day. So did Seattle. So New England had help but gained no
ground.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, when the Patriots lost to Miami, Buffalo was
losing. So was Kansas City. So New England had help but gained no
ground.
</P>
<P>
   When this slide began back on Nov. 15 with the Jets loss, it was
on a day when Miami and Kansas City also were defeated. So the
Patriots had help that day even before they realized they might
need it, but gained no ground.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, how much more help can New England expect to receive?
</P>
<P>
   Even the normally upbeat Carroll acknowledged that sad reality
for a moment Monday when asked if perhaps they'd gotten all the
help they could hope for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be,'' he said. ``This was a tremendous weekend for us to
cash in and we didn't. We'll have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   His players were saying much the same thing. They were talking
hopefully while knowing hope is all but gone. Extinguished as much
by their own hands as by anything that had been done to them.
Extinguished by penalties at the worst of times and dropped balls
at the worst of times and receivers running routes from Mars and
not getting open and linemen standing after running plays when the
only things on the ground are their running back and the 1,000
pounds of defenders on top of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not scoring touchdowns, man,'' Brown said. ``Your guess
why is as good as mine. Our execution is hurting us. Now it will
take a lot of heart from us and a lot of help from other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand our situation. We've got to win out, but even if
we do, if nobody loses we're dead. When we were 6-2 we were flying
high. I couldn't have imagined being in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few naysayers did, and they were hooted down. Now there
is nothing more to say. It is time to watch and wait in New
England. Wait for help that already may have come and gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
