<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO REGROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FIFA and the European Football Union should reevaluate the
criteria for qualifications. They have scheduled three meetings
between England and Germany in the next few months: home-and-away
World Cup 2002 qualifiers, and a European Championships 2000 match
in Charleroi, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   And World Cup champion France was placed in the toughest Euro
2000 group, along with the Czech Republic, Denmark, and Holland.
</P>
<P>
   England and Germany were assigned to Group 9 along with Greece,
Finland, and Albania in the World Cup draw. They join Portugal and
Romania in Group A in Euro 2000. The security arrangements for
England-Germany matches are prohibitive; the last time the nations
were to meet for a ``friendly,'' they mutually consented to cancel
it out of fear of neo-Nazi groups. It did not help that the game
unwittingly was scheduled for Hitler's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The problems started when England, France, and Italy _ three of
only four European nations that have won the World Cup _ were
placed in the second grouping. The matchups were based on results
in qualifying for the France '98 World Cup and Euro 2000, scheduled
in Belgium and Holland June 10-July 2. So France received no credit
for its World Cup title, since it did not play any qualifiers as
host nation.
</P>
<P>
   Italy was fortunate. The Azzurri have Belgium, Sweden, and
Turkey in Euro 2000 and meet Romania, Lithuania, Hungary, and
Georgia in World Cup qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's coach, Dino Zoff, was taken by surprise during the World
Cup draw in Tokyo. Since Romania was designated No. 1 seed, the
Romanians took the initiative in scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, it is we who host these meetings,'' Zoff told the
Romanians, according to La Gazzetta dello Sport reporter Sergio Di
Cesare. ``Why don't you come to Rome and we can talk about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Mircea Sandu, president of the Federatia Romana de Fotbal,
replied: ``Those days are finished, times have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandu then turned and winked at his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dubious alliances
</P>
<P>
   Diego Maradona has seldom been concerned with political
correctness. Nor have many others from his neighborhood in Villa
Fiorito on the outskirts of Buenos Aires, where survival is the
primary concern. But Maradona should not be perceived as
politically naive. He is among the few prominent athletes who have
expressed consistent support for Fidel Castro. Maradona recognizes
his roots and is true to them. He would never be accepted on his
terms in the sporting world's mainstream, so he has found his place
among similar renegades. In Naples, where Maradona played for seven
years, he found an entire race of people with similar sentiments.
Now Maradona is being courted by Libya. His younger brother and
Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson were to arrive in Tripoli Tuesday to
begin a 90-day training program for national team striker Al-Saad
Khadafy, son of Moammar. Both Johnson and Raul ``Lalo'' Maradona
have played for soccer teams in Toronto. ``Al-Saad will see if
Johnson can teach him, and this will benefit the whole team,'' said
Libya's Italian coach, Eugenio Bersellini. The Johnson-Maradona
team, which also includes a masseur and another coach, are being
paid about $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Revved up
</P>
<P>
   The New England Revolution's strike force is going strong in
South America. Eduardo Hurtado scored the only goal as LDU Quito
defeated Nacional in the first game of the Ecuadoran finals.
``Thank God I have teammates who supported me when I shot badly on
two good balls they gave me in the first half,'' Hurtado said. ``I
felt their support and I dedicate the goal to them.'' Giovanni
Savarese's Caracas FC lost to Independiente Santa Fe of Bogota in
the semifinals of the Copa MercoNorte. Meanwhile, Ariel Graziani,
who played three times for the Revolution before moving to Dallas,
was named Ecuadoran player of the week after leading Emelec to two
victories and qualification for the Copa Libertadores tournament .
. . Former Revolution striker Joe-Max Moore made his debut for
Everton FC as a 75th-minute substitute in a 0-0 tie at Exeter City
in an FA Cup match. The return game is scheduled in Liverpool
Sunday. Likely, Everton president Peter Johnson will continue to
keep a low profile after receiving a death threat over the Internet
from a group called Direct Everton Action . . . Moore is being
allowed to concentrate on his club career by US national coach
Bruce Arena, who invited 34 players to training camp starting Jan.
5 in Claremont, Calif. Revolution midfielder John Harkes, who has
89 US appearances, is headed to the camp in preparation for the
Jan. 16 friendly against Iran in Pasadena. The US meets Chile in
Coquimbo Jan. 29, then plays in the Gold Cup starting Feb. 12
against Haiti in Miami . . . Hector ``Bambino'' Viera, Bolivia's
Argentine coach, announced plans to use two naturalized Brazilians
in World Cup qualifying, which starts in Uruguay March 28. Viera,
who earns a bonus of $1 million if the Bolivians qualify, plans to
use Julio Cesar Baldivieso (Japan), Marco Etcheverry (D.C. United),
and Erwin Sanchez (Benfica) in the tournament, but will not likely
call up the Revolution's Mauricio Ramos . . . Lothar Matthaus,
billed as the successor to Franz Beckenbauer with the MetroStars,
has agreed to join the MLS team in March. But he will likely be
called to Germany for Euro 2000 and five pretournament friendlies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
