<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8597 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-JERUSALEM-SYNDROME-BO     12-14 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERUSALEM-SYNDROME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERUSALEM INSPIRES DELUSIONS ALONG WITH FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Lost souls wander the ancient pathways of the Old
City here convinced they are the Son of God, or at least one of his
prophets.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe they are John the Baptist, others the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   All of them suffer from the ``Jerusalem Syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   As the millennium approaches, the number of people afflicted
with the psychological disorder is growing, said Dr. Yair Carlos
Bar-El, who is called the world's leading expert on it.
</P>
<P>
   In his office at Kfar Shaul Mental Health Center on the
outskirts of Jerusalem, he treats on average 30 acute cases a year
of travelers who become overwhelmed by the religious significance
of Jerusalem and descend into a delusional state in which they
assume the personalities of biblical characters.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming year, he expects that number will triple.
</P>
<P>
   Already, he said, he is up to 50 cases this year, and the flood
of 3.2 million tourists expected to visit the Holy Land for the
millennium is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Victims of the syndrome exhibit well-known signs, such as
purification acts, obsessive bathing, or wrapping themselves in
white sheets (typically taken from the hotels where they are
staying). Often, they end up disrupting prayer services at one or
another holy site, screaming about the wages of sin.
</P>
<P>
   Only a fraction of one percent of the tourists who come will
experience psychiatric problems brought on by the emotion of
visiting the holy sites, he said. But that will add up to roughly
3,000 cases of emotional distress among religious travelers in the
city over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   He said sufferers usually fit into one of three broad
categories:
</P>
<P>
   --Some are are mentally stable at home but develop emotional
problems triggered by something in the experience of visiting the
Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   --Some arrive intent on bringing about a specific biblical
prophecy. They are typically passive but feel that they are called
to come.
</P>
<P>
   --Those in the third group, which most precisely fits the
clinical definition of ``Jerusalem Syndrome,'' typically come as
normal religious tourists, often travelling alone. During the
journey, they develop a belief that they have been called to take a
role in a prophecy or, in some cases, that they are the
reincarnation of a biblical character, often the Virgin Mary or
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Although occasionally people of other faiths develop such
symptoms, Bar-El said, it is mostly a phenomenon among Christians,
especially those in evangelical Protestant denominations.
</P>
<P>
   Bar-El has been helping Israeli police and tour guides
understand what to expect in the way of mental aberrations among
the pilgrims, but he said their training has been limited and
insufficient to deal with the coming onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be capable of detecting these cases, to find them
early,'' he said. ``We have told authorities loudly that more needs
to be done, but our protests have gone unheard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1350EST &QL; 
