A8598 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-MILLENNIUM-OLD-BUSINE     12-14 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-OLD-BUSINESS-RESEND-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORA'S STORY: MILLENNIUM-OLD SWEDISH COMPANY PUTS ON A NEW FACE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Desks...RESENDING from Nov. 29)   (This 975-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' financial news and ``a'' general news files.)  
  
 By ALINE SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Once upon a time'' is the stuff of fairy tales, not corporate
histories. But that is how Stora Enso Oyj introduces its saga, and
for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish company is as old as the millennium. That makes it
one of the oldest companies in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock is also well worth buying, industry analysts say.
Stora joined forces a year ago with Enso Oyj of Finland to create
Europe's biggest paper maker.
</P>
<P>
   The combined group is taking advantage of record-low inventories
around the world and raising prices. At the same time, it is
divesting itself of 2 billion ($2.04 billion) worth of utility
assets in a bid to overtake International Paper Co. and become the
top paper maker in the word.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite a story, not only because Stora is so old but also
because its history so well illustrates the ongoing struggle in
Europe between public and private enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Stora traces its origins to Stora Kopparberget, or the Great
Copper Mountain, in Falun, Sweden. The mine was first worked at
some time between 850 and 1080.
</P>
<P>
   A Deed of Exchange dated 1288 and signed by the king bequeathed
an eighth part in the mine to the diocese of Bishop Peter of
Vasteras in exchange for a farm complete with mills, fields,
pastures, fishing rights and forests.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a great success, at least not at first. In 1347, King
Magnus Eriksson issued a charter following a disappointing visit to
the mine. The charter, which is one of the oldest surviving
documents of its kind in Sweden, details the poor conditions in and
around the mine and outlines a new management and wage structure.
</P>
<P>
   In 1360, a few years after the Black Plague struck the mine in
force, the king supplemented the charter with a Mining Statute.
This allowed master miners to mine ore in proportion to the number
of smelters they owned.
</P>
<P>
   It also determined the sequence of work. At this point,
according to Stora research, the mine emerges as a truly corporate
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   This was obviously a success _ so much so that in 1396 Queen
Margareta reasserted the crown's right to the mine.
</P>
<P>
   Stora Kopparberget thrived through most of the 15th century. A
guild was formed, with St. Orjan as the patron saint. By this time,
the miners probably mined more than 2,000 ship's pounds of copper a
year, according to preserved Lubeck accounts. That is about 300,000
kilograms. Almost all of Swedish copper was sold through Lubeck and
through the Hanseatic League.
</P>
<P>
   The invention of a pump driven by a water wheel gave the mine a
new lease on life in 1556. King Gustav Vasa was enthusiastic about
the new technology but had trouble with master miners who refused
to abandon their traditional working methods.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, by the beginning of the 17th century, all the
mine's chambers were being worked as one, systematically utilized
unit, enabling Sweden to surpass Germany in production and refining
and dominate the European copper market.
</P>
<P>
   A copper mint was the next step, just in time for Sweden's move
to a copper monetary standard. For more than 200 years, all of
Sweden's copper coinage was minted in nearby Avesta. The biggest
coin was the 10 daler piece, which weighed almost 20 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
   Mining copper ore required enormous amounts of wood. In 1648, a
trading company was formed to transport wood to Falun, which by
this time had become a town.
</P>
<P>
   The mining thrived and work went on all day and night. The pits
went deeper and deeper and the walls between the chambers became
thinner and thinner.
</P>
<P>
   In 1687 they caved in. Extraordinarily, no one was hurt. All of
Stora Kopparberget's miners were above ground, celebrating
Midsummer. Indeed, the cave-in exposed hidden ore and created a
tourist attraction, the Great Pit. It was a stroke of great luck in
what were otherwise bleak lives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1734 the Swedish scientist Carl von Linne visited the mine
and called it the greatest marvel in Sweden but ``as terrible as
hell itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Forestry became increasingly important and, by the late 1800s,
generated more than half of Stora's income. Associated works also
produced silver, sulfuric acid, newsprint and red paint (which,
according to legend, followed the discovery of iron deposits by a
Finnish shepherd boy when his billy-goat, Kare, returned home with
red horns).
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish crown's direct authority over the mine came to an
end in 1862 and the mine and the various individual works were
combined into one company, Stora Kopparbergs Bergslag. In 1885,
Stora became a limited company. The nominal capital was 9.6 million
kronor.
</P>
<P>
   A century later, Stora was a rapidly growing company with
interests in market pulp, sawn goods, newsprint and electricity as
well as mining. But in 1990, the company decided to focus
exclusively on its most profitable sector, forest products, and in
November 1998 it completed its merger with rival paper maker Enso.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Stora Enso has 40,000 employees around the world. It is
listed on the Helsinki and Stockholm exchanges and has market value
of about 6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Stora seems to have made the right choice. Chile, which now
produces most of the world's copper, has been forced into recession
by low copper prices.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, forest products and paper in particular are ripe
for significant growth, industry analysts said. Pent-up demand from
the recovering economies of Asia and the need to replenish low
inventories in Europe and North America will enable Stora Enso to
boost both prices and supply over the next few years, they said.
</P>
<P>
   There could even be a sudden, sharp surge in demand from
magazines and newspapers that want to mark the millennium with
features, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
