<HEADLINE>
FOX TEAM WAS ON ITS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox had a well-rounded NFL pregame show Sunday, with highlights
and zany antics as usual, but also news and solid commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Bradshaw had the scoop of the weekend. According to him,
Redskins owner Daniel Snyder told six veteran players to do
whatever it took to win against the Arizona Cardinals, even if it
meant not listening to their coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's wrong,'' Bradshaw said. ``That's not how you lead a
football team to victory. That's not good for Norv Turner, and if I
were Norv, I would drag Snyder in a room and have a few words with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Host James Brown and analyst Cris Collinsworth had an
interesting discussion about race, prompted by an interview of
Kerry Collins, the New York Giants quarterback who has been accused
of making racist comments in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Collinsworth told viewers, ``Race relations are one thing that
no one wants to talk about, but it can destroy a football team
faster than any other thing I know.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times a coach doesn't even know what's going on in
the locker room. One problem is that sometimes black players can
say things to each other that if a white tries to say the same
thing, it's over. That team is finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds a little bit like blaming the victim. Brown picked up on
that theme, saying, ``I think your point is well taken. Often times
you will hear black players say some things to other black
ballplayers. It's my belief that no matter what, if it's racial in
nature it's not to be said by a black to a black, much less a white
to a black. I think you ought to just stay away from it, period. No
matter who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the usually lighthearted crew moved beyond the world of
sports and tried to deal with a serious topic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Channel surfing
</P>
<P>
   HBO is expected to unveil a new sports magazine program hosted
by Bob Costas . . . Andre Aldridge is leaving ESPN's ``NBA
2Night,'' to join CNN/SI as an anchor . . . The Patriots-Eagles
game at Philadelphia Sunday will be on Channel 4 at 1 p.m., with
Gus Johnson, Brent Jones, and Beasley Reece. Channel 25 has the 4
p.m. Tampa Bay-Oakland game, with Curt Menefee and Brian Baldinger
. . . ESPN's ``SportsCentury'' picks Jesse Owens as its
sixth-greatest athlete of the century. Wayne Gretzky is No. 5. Late
Los Angeles Times writer Jim Murray said of Owens, ``This was the
guy that tweaked Hitler's mustache. This is the guy that showed the
master race they were the minor race. Jesse Owens was an authentic
American hero from then on.'' On Gretzky, actor Alan Thicke said,
``He was in another league. He was in another universe as far as
the other players were concerned. I remember an opposing center
lining up against him, and just before the referee would drop the
puck saying, `Could I have your stick after the game?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy-duty program
</P>
<P>
   Bud Greenspan's ``Kings of the Ring,'' debuts Jan. 3 on Showtime
at 10 p.m. Greenspan takes a look at four of the greatest
heavyweights this century: Jack Johnson, Jack Dempsey, Joe Louis,
and Muhammad Ali . . . ESPN examines the America's Cup in a
one-hour show Sunday at 4 p.m. The cable network reports on the
recently completed challenger round-robin series and previews the
semifinals. There will be nightly same-day coverage of the
semifinals from New Zealand on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
