<HEADLINE>
THEY ALWAYS STICK THEIR NECKS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With their amazingly long necks, spindly legs, and spotted
exteriors, giraffes are curious creatures indeed. Here, from
Classic Encounters, which conducts safaris and other travel to
southern Africa, are some fascinating facts about giraffes:
</P>
<P>
   --They are the tallest land mammals, averaging 10 feet high with
8-foot necks.
</P>
<P>
   --When born, they average 6 feet tall and weigh about 130
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   --They sleep (standing up) for about five minutes at a time and
average a mere 20 minutes a day.
</P>
<P>
   --Adults can eat up to 140 pounds of foliage a day.
</P>
<P>
   --Their markings are as unique as human fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   --If water is nearby, they'll drink it. But they can go for
weeks without water.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information on Classic Encounters and its ``Dream
Safaris,'' call 888-808-1999.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Name the landlocked country in the Pyrenees in which
Catalan is the official language. (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``When the captain has turned off the overhead seat belt
light you may move your seat to a recline position. If you cannot
figure out how . . . ask the person in front of you whose head will
be resting in your lap once they're in a reclining position'' _
from Brutally Honest Flight Attendant Announcements in Mad
magazine. &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The name of Macao, which reverts to China this month, is
derived from that of the Taoist Ma Temple, which in Cantonese is
``Ma Gau.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
O Christmas lake: For a decade now, kayakers have been gathering on
Seattle's Lake Union to sing carols. About 50 kayaks, each an arm's
length from another kayak, participate. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Museum of the month: Baltimore's new American Dime Museum is a
two-story throwback to the many ``dime museums'' of the 19th
century _ places where for a mere 10th part of a dollar you could
see such curiosities and wonders as a monkey woman or a devil man.
They were fakes, of course, but the crowds loved them, and the
museums gave rise to circus sideshows. In addition to the
``preserved'' devil man and monkey woman, the museum contains
hundreds of ersatz oddities, including the ``Lip of a Lion Shot by
Teddy Roosevelt'' (in reality a scrap of cooked liver) and the
9-foot-tall Peruvian Amazon (under glass).
</P>
<P>
   One thing, though: This dime museum will cost you 30 dimes to
enter. The American Dime Museum is at 1808 Maryland Ave.,
Baltimore. For more information, call 410-230-0263. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: In New Hampshire, it's illegal to tap your feet,
nod your head, or otherwise keep time to music in a tavern,
restaurant, or cafe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
They're walkin', yes indeed: More people walk to work in Alaska
than in any other state. (With thanks to faithful contributor Mike
Schuster of Foxborough, Mass.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gizmos at sea: Now you can get your amazing gizmos and gadgets at
sea: Royal Caribbean Cruise Line has opened a Sharper Image store
on its Monarch of the Seas. This is the first seagoing outlet of
the electronics and gifts chain. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Andorra.
</P>
</TEXT>
