<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAIT-AND-SEA-CHANGE IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The conventional wisdom is that the collapse of World Trade
Organization talks last week was a grave setback to hopes for
further expansion of global trade. It seems unlikely that this is
the case. But the real direction of march won't be clear for at
least another year.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the five-day bout of street theater in Seattle, most
trade professionals had concluded that the talks were unlikely to
go forward in 1999 in any public way, owing to two uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   One was obvious: the coming US election. The other is slightly
less so: the advent of the Internet, with all its uncertainties for
the conduct of global business.
</P>
<P>
   Why an administration that won two mighty trade liberalizations
early in its first term didn't make that same calculation and
scuttle the talks _ or at least not fan the tinderbox flames _ is
one of those riddles that awaits the next high-level insider book
by Bob Woodward of The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, it was some combination of political paralysis and
battle fatigue. The desire to give Al Gore's candidacy a boost
clearly contributed to the debacle, in which President Clinton
seemed to throw his weight behind sanctions demanded by American
labor unions against nations violating arbitary labor and
environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
   But the snappy answer Clinton gave after the fact at a White
House press conference packed more persuasive power than anything
he said to the delegates or the newspapers in Seattle:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years from now, we'll all take it for granted that we've
come a long way in integrating trade and the environment and labor.
That's what I think and what I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   That next round of negotiations _ when it comes _ will not bear
Clinton's name.
</P>
<P>
   That's because of the sea change that occurred in Seattle. It
had less to do with the hundreds of bottom-up nonovernmental
organizations whose members converged on the city than it did with
the top-down sentiments of the trade ministers who witnessed the
``battle in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the United States has been the leading proponent
of a fair global trading game. This year, ``the inchoate feeling of
many developing countries became a little more sharp, their sense
that somehow we were trying to capture it for our own advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the judgement of Columbia University professor Jagdish
Bhagwati. He spent five days in Seattle, jousting with various
critics of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the emphasis we put on services, agriculture, where we
are exporters, they saw the US as increasingly trying to caputure
markets for its own producers. Meanwhile, we were essentially
unwilling to give up anything on the import side.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, European nations hestitated to support
American bargaining positions, at least partly because they feared
subtle attempts to stack the deck in favor of e-commerce trading
practices. The Internet was for the most part developed in the
United States, and American manufacturing and software companies
possess considerable advantages.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wanted is a clearer signal of American intentions in
the years to come _ in the form of a 2000 election that clarifies
the nature f the consensus under which the United states is to be
governed.
</P>
<P>
   All four major candidates _ Bill Bradley, George W. Bush, Al
Gore and John McCain _ are deeply avowed free-traders, though Gore
probably is more beholden to union wishes than the others. Somewhat
less clear is the position of each on the landmark issue of
taxation of Internet transactions.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is what kind of Congress will arrive in
Washington with the new president. The loss of as few as five seats
by the Republicans would give the Democrats control of the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party resistance to the North American Free Trade
Agreement and the ratification of the Uruguay Round _ both
championed forcefully by President Clinton _ contributed to the GOP
landslide and the loss of the House in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder, then, that the rest of the world is unwilling to
follow the US lead down a road whose route markings are not yet
clear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
