<HEADLINE>
BLESSED BE OUR LITTLEST BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the God of Materialism looked down upon the world at
Christmastime and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   He saw the world's children glued to their television sets, the
glow of action-packed advertising washing over their eager little
faces.
</P>
<P>
   He heard them thinking: ``I want that! I want that too! I want
that! And that! And that!''
</P>
<P>
   And he knew that his creative disciples in advertising offices
around the globe had been hard at work this holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   The God of Materialism knew that to hook customers for life you
had to brainwash them very young.
</P>
<P>
   You had to hit them hard and hit them again.
</P>
<P>
   How else could you ensure that they would pester mom and dad for
the hottest kiddie creature, game, or device?
</P>
<P>
   And don't just give them kids' advertising. Hit them with the
adult ads. Then they'll be sure to badger dad until the old man
buys the cool car they saw streaking across the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   The God of Materialism had recently called upon professor James
McNeal, the guru of kid advertising at Texas A&AMP;M University. McNeal
explained that parents are giving their children ever greater
influence over family buying decisions, to assuage their guilt for
their time-starved schedules. McNeal estimated that kids ages 4 to
14 have a decided impact on the brand, size, color and style of
cars purchased.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he discovered that the average 10-year-old has
memorized as many as 400 brand names. When kids beg their parents
for a product, he said, they name the item by its brand 92 percent
of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The God of Materialism was most gratified to learn that
advertising targeting children had grown 15 to 20 percent a year
for the past six or seven years.
</P>
<P>
   When the God of Materialism left McNeal, he smiled again.
</P>
<P>
   But as he surveyed his world from his perch on high, his eye
fell on a troubling sight. In parts of Europe, he saw kids seated
cross-legged before their television sets _ but sin of sins! _ no
glow of advertising lighted up their little faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of humans are these?'' He cried. ``Certainly not
created in my image!''
</P>
<P>
   The God of Materialism summoned the Angel of Advertising for an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please forgive me, your highness,'' the angel began. ``But I
have discovered an unsavory fact: It is against the law in Sweden
to run TV advertising targeted at children who are less than 12
years old.''
</P>
<P>
   The God of Materialism swallowed hard. ``Go on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets worse, I'm afraid,'' the angel said. ``It's the same
in Norway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And Christmas still comes to these places?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Belgium, advertising to kids is banned in some parts of the
country near the time of children's programming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A crime against humanity!'' the God of Materialism huffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denmark, Poland and Ireland are also thinking about cracking
down on kids' advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to bring this before the International Tribunal in
the Hague!'' cried the God of Materialsim.
</P>
<P>
   The Angel of Advertising continued:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Swedish government did a study several years ago that
showed children who were 7 or younger could not distinguish between
ads and programming. It also showed that older kids didn't
understand the intent of commericals. Do you want to know what the
head of Sweden's consumer agency said about TV advertising?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I must.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `It is considered that it is not a fair way of
dealing with very small consumers, because they are being
exploited.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The God of Materialism fell silent. Then, in a weak voice, he
said: ``I'm depressed. I'm going shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
