<HEADLINE>
WHO'S THE NEXT EMC? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chances are you didn't have EMC stock in your portfolio when the
decade began. Why would you?
</P>
<P>
   The Hopkinton, Mass. high-tech company was small and struggling.
A year earlier, its chairman and president had vowed to go without
pay until the money-losing operation returned to profitability.
EMC's chief competitor was IBM Corp., then and now the world's
biggest computer company. Its business, computer storage, wasn't
even recognized as a distinct market.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad for you. If you had invested in EMC Corp. back then, you
would be one very rich individual today. A dollar invested in EMC
on Jan. 1, 1990, is worth nearly $700 today. Put another way, an
investment of $1,500 would have translated into just over $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Take that, Regis Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   EMC was the top-performing Massachusetts stock in the 1990s. It
had some serious competition for the number one spot, however. CMGI
Inc., the Andover Internet incubator, went public at the beginning
of 1994, and a dollar invested in it at the beginning would be
worth more than $600 today.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of our top ten stocks aren't in that league. In the
past 10 years, they increased in value between 16- and 34-fold.
Even in this age of wildly heightened expectations about the stock
market, that's still a pretty fair performance.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of our top ten companies are in electronics. Biogen Corp.
is in health care, Staples Inc. is in retailing and Oak Industries
Inc. is a traditional manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   What else can you say about the top companies? Either through
luck or foresight, they were in position to take advantage of some
of the key trends of the decade. For EMC, it was the explosion of
data storage; for CMGI, the mushrooming of the Internet. For Analog
Devices, it was the boom in communications; for Staples, it was the
enormous growth in small business and home offices.
</P>
<P>
   But just being in the right business wasn't enough. In many
cases, these companies had to be willing to drop what they were
doing and reinvent themselves. Some had to do it more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Take EMC. In 1990, the company canceled most of its products to
concentrate on one market: computer storage for mainframe
computers.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of the decade, EMC owned the business. But chief
executive Michael Ruettgers wasn't content to rest on his laurels.
``Mike saw that mainframes were not going to be a growth area,''
says Mark Fredrickson, the company's director of corporate
communications.
</P>
<P>
   The action was moving to personal computers, and Ruettgers
pushed EMC, reluctantly at first, to head in that direction. More
recently, he has engineered another midcourse correction, away from
hardware and toward software. Judging by the stock price, his
creative destruction was just what the company needed.
</P>
<P>
   At Analog Devices in Norwood, the early '90s was a time of
soul-searching. The once high-flying company had crash-landed. The
main customers for its specialty chips _ the military and industry
_ held limited promise for future growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have to do,'' chairman Ray Stata told his troops, ``is
change everything we do and how we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Analog did just that. Communications, a tiny fraction of sales
in 1990, is the biggest and fastest-growing part of Analog's
business today; military sales are far less important than they
once were.
</P>
<P>
   Analog's stock is up 20-fold in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Teradyne also started the decade on a low note.
Teradyne sells test equipment to the semiconductor industry. In the
early 1990s, much of that industry was moving to Japan _ and buying
equipment from Teradyne's chief competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Teradyne couldn't do much about that. ``But we decided we had to
stop thinking of ourselves as victims,'' says Thomas Newman, a
Teradyne vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The company embraced total quality management in a big way, a
decision that led to a raft of new products and a change in
corporate culture. When the American semiconductor business snapped
back, Teradyne was in perfect position to ride the wave.
</P>
<P>
   The stock was up 16-fold in the 1990s, missing the top 10 list
by a hair.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the top group, the stock of State Street Corp. was up
more than sixfold during the decade, a very impressive performance
for a company that did fabulously in the 1980s. Gillette stock was
up more than fivefold, even though it has lost ground over the past
year. Again, over the long haul, it has been a heck of an
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, after a column of ours about EMC appeared, we
heard from a curious reader. She told us she had not had much luck
in the market and was looking for one good investment. ``Could you
please tell me what stock is likely to be the next EMC?'' she asked
in a letter.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great question. When we figure out the answer, you, our
readers, will be the first to know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
