<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING `AFFAIR'? HAVE IT YOUR WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gentle readers, you did your best. We were hoping you could help
settle the debate between two friends over whether an affair
necessarily implied adultery, and you responded. But unlike last
year's survey on bring vs. take, this question brought nothing like
consensus.
</P>
<P>
   On the basic question of whether adultery was part of the
definition of affair, respondents _ whose ages ranged from 27 to 79
_ were evenly divided. But almost everyone felt the need for
further footnoting.
</P>
<P>
   ``An affair implies a situation with a short lifespan,'' wrote
28-year-old Jonathan, one of those who said adultery wasn't
necessarily part of the deal. ``A relationship is a stable
situation of indefinite duration. Affair implies an adventure from
which you return, like a vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   But 64-year-old Joel thought a fling could also be too brief to
meet the definition: ``Many relationships are so transitory as to
hardly merit being called an affair.'' If you can't remember it, in
other words, it doesn't qualify.
</P>
<P>
   And when marriage is impossible, love affairs can go on for
years, becoming monuments to romance lived respectably: Look at
Katharine Hepburn and Spencer Tracy. Thus Sarah, who's in her 50s,
calls her relationship with another woman a love affair, using love
as a declaration of exclusivity and commitment.
</P>
<P>
   For 34-year-old Mary, an affair involves deceit, but not
necessarily a marriage: ``It could be any relationship with an
implied commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the question of parity. ``When I confided to my
therapist that I was having an affair with a married man, she
corrected me by saying that `it is his affair, but your
relationship,' '' wrote 56-year-old Jean.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Technique of the Love Affair,'' a 1928 guidebook for women
just reissued by Pantheon, shows that the definition has been
shifty for quite a while. In this precursor of 1995's ``The
Rules,'' the affair is not just about sex. Caution and coquetry are
essential on the road from ``flirtation' to ``light affair'' to
``serious affair,'' one that might even lead to marriage. But how
light is light, and what constitutes a ``lover''? Though the
liberated young flappers aren't saving themselves for marriage,
these terms remain open to interpretation. To fog the windshield
further, ``Technique'' was written in an era when ``making love''
could still mean simply flirting.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently words of love _ and sexual involvement _ are just too
culture- and context-bound to be pinned down. We use affair for
affairs both sordid and sweet, short and long, secret and public.
No wonder dictionaries keep it simple, with entries like ``an
amorous relationship between two people not married to each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing has changed, though: We're less likely now to call an
event an affair, often substituting the unlovable function. We can
still describe a wedding reception as ``a grand affair,'' it's
true. But no longer do we see hotels issuing the invitation Durham
Caldwell saw on a billboard board decades ago: ``Have your next
affair at the Schine Inn!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
