<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAKA-KHAN-MILLENNIUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAKA KHAN CAN'T WAIT FOR Y2K FESTIVITIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients. Fact box at bottom.) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For most performers, New Year's Eve is a priority
booking. For r&AMP;b diva Chaka Khan, Universal Studios Hollywood's
Millennium Dance Party represents the start of an unusually full
year.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 31, the studio will play host to the gala millennium
event, which also features such musical acts as electro-pop group
Berlin, new wavers Missing Persons and salsa star Yari More
performing in themed party areas topped off by a choreographed
display of fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Guests will go footloose in the park with four dance areas _ a
high-energy Rio carnival, a masquerade ball, a red-carpet Hollywood
movie premiere and a romantic escape area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just enjoy performing _ period,'' says Khan, who sang with
r&AMP;b group Rufus from 1972-78 before going solo. ``If the sound is
good, the vibes are there and people are into it, I don't care
where I sing.''
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 will be heralded at Universal with explosions,
confetti cannons and party favors while the celebration continues
until 2 a.m. to allow guests to keep dancing or enjoying such
attractions as Terminator 2: 3D, Jurassic Park _ The Ride, Back to
the Future and Backdraft.
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Eve has long been a favorite night in the Khan
household, and the vocalist plans to catch some of the other acts
on the Universal lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say there's competition on a night like Dec. 31,
but we all want to do our best,'' she said. ``We want to give our
all for a crowd that wants to have a night to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1978, the Grammy-winning Khan has released a series of
solo albums and cut vocals with Prince, Steve Winwood, David Bowie
and Quincy Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to hear a selection of familiar tunes from Khan on New
Year's, including the Top 40 hits ``Tell Me Something Good,'' ``You
Got the Love,'' ``Sweet Thing,'' ``Once You Get Started,'' ``I Feel
for You'' and ``I'll Be Good to You.''
</P>
<P>
   You see, the Illinois-born Khan says she never tires of singing
her hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those people that's just happy to do music for the
love of music,'' she says. ``If there's someone out there who wants
to hear me perform something in particular, I'll always be happy to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Released this summer, Khan's 20th album, ``Come 2 My House''
(New Power Generation Records), includes 10 songs written or
co-written by Prince.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prince financed the entire project,'' Khan said. ``He's really
a lovely human being. He's a little shy and misunderstood, but he's
lovely. There was no pressure. It was the perfect partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Khan plans to release a new album and will launch a
year 2000 tour, perhaps with a visit to Europe or Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love what I do,'' she insists. ``That's what keeps me going,
no matter how busy or tired I might get. I just love the music.'' &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: Millennium Dance Party. &QL; 
Who: Chaka Khan, Berlin, Missing Persons and Yari More. &QL; 
Where: Universal Studios Hollywood. &QL; 
When: 9 p.m. Dec. 31. &QL; 
Tickets: $99 and $250. &QL; 
Information: (800) 959-9688. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
