<SLUG> BC-PERSON-OF-CENTURY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WILL CHOOSE THE WRONG MAN OF THE CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOB ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The race is on at Time magazine to select the
Person of the Century. Time's Man of the Year _ later changed to
Person of the Year _ has always generated lots of publicity.
</P>
<P>
   The hype machine is in full swing to anoint the one person who
has most influenced human affairs over the past hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the magazine's editors will make the final decision,
Time has an on-line poll to measure public reaction on the
contenders. Journalists have hammered away on Bill Clinton for
allowing political decisions to be driven by polls, but that didn't
stop Time from doing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Christians are upset because Jesus is not a contender in this
particular millennium. Jews, appalled that Adolf Hitler was leading
in the on-line poll, started clicking for Yitzhak Rabin, the
Israeli prime minister assassinated four years ago by an
ultranationalist Jew trying to staunch the peace process with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent tally, that helped. Rabin was in second
place with about 600,000 votes. The Third Reich's superstar settled
into third place with slightly more than a half million clicks. In
first place with 620,000 fans is the man who certainly did shake up
the planet: Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   As a parlor game, this is lots of fun. If we take it seriously,
other contenders like Einstein, Gandhi and Mother Teresa stand tall
on the horizon beyond the Heartbreak Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Time admits the poll is far from scientific. Some effort has
been made to stop on-line programs that automatically launch
thousands of votes for a candidate. But the on-line poll leaves
lots of room for ballot stuffing. You can vote early and often.
</P>
<P>
   In my view, and putting on-line popularity polls aside, one
person knocks out all the other contenders in a single hard blow:
the aforementioned Adolf Hitler. The key word in Time's choice is
``influential,'' not loved or admired. The magazine acknowledged
this when it chose Hitler as the Man of the Year in 1938, Josef
Stalin in 1939 and 1942, and Ayatollah Khomeini in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   St. Augustine said the function of the bad was to make the good
stand out more strongly. Hitler certainly fills the bill. In 1934,
a year after gaining power, the maniac bellowed, ``We may be
destroyed, but if we are, we shall drag the world with us _ a world
in flames.'' This shows not only hatred toward his enemies, but
toward the German people too.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing this non-drinking, non-smoking, vegetarian _ in
some ways he was way ahead of his time _ ever came to power. The
iron leader spent most of the day sleeping, then conducted business
into the wee hours of the night while sweating racial hatred and
popping pills administered by a quack doctor for his chronic
flatulence.
</P>
<P>
   Like a monster rising from the ninth circle of Hell, Hitler's
ideology was based on little more than mass murder and total war
designed to coat every square inch of ground with blood.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Meaning of Hitler,'' historian Sebastian Haffner wrote:
``There is no doubt that Hitler is a figure of world political
history; there is equally no doubt that he belongs to the annals of
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine will reveal its choice in the Dec. 27 issue. There
will be an hour-long special on CBS devoted to the Person of the
Century.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea who Time will choose, but I predict it will not
be Hitler. Time editors won't want to take the heat and the
subscription cancellations that would follow. Instead, the editors
will write an essay on why they did not choose Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. Hitler would enjoy that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Armstrong is a free-lance writer in San Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
