<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8635 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-14 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING THE NEW YEAR IN A BUNKER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There is something so darkly comic about the
State Department's holiday terrorism warning. One might suspect the
late filmmaker, Stanley Kubrick, of having scripted it. After all,
the irony is already close to the ``Dr. Strangelove'' level.
</P>
<P>
   Never before in the history of the United States have so many
people been so well off and willing to spend plenty to commemorate
the last Hanukkah, Christmas and New Year's Eve of a century and a
millennium. While most Americans will do their partying in the
States, thousands have planned once-in-a-lifetime pilgrimages to
the Holy Land, long weekends in Paris or luxury cruises half-way
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two weeks before Christmas and three weeks before the
biggest celebration in the Western world, along comes the State
Department to pour a big old ice bucket of freezing cold water on
everybody's head.
</P>
<P>
   Because of ``credible information that terrorists are planning
attacks,'' U.S. citizens living or traveling abroad during this
holiday season have been put on what may be the scariest _ and most
ridiculous _ alert of the last 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where might these attacks occur?
</P>
<P>
   State Department: ``Locations throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In what sort of situations might these acts occur?
</P>
<P>
   State Department: ``Where large gatherings and celebrations will
be taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What precautions against such possible attacks can be taken
by U.S. citizens living or traveling abroad?
</P>
<P>
   State Department: ``Avoid large crowds, keep a low-profile,
review security practices, remain alert to the changing situation
and exercise caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, thanks for sharing. You forgot to tell us to have a good
time.
</P>
<P>
   OK. OK. Nobody wants to see another Pan Am Flight 103. And ever
since that 1989 mid-air bombing over Scotland, any ``credible, but
not counterable'' threat of murder or mayhem must be passed along
by the State Department in the form of a public warning.
</P>
<P>
   But, if the best the folks at State can do is tell us what most
U.S. citizens already know _ somewhere out there, insane ideologues
hate us and, as a holiday surprise, are plotting to make some of us
dead _ why did they even bother warning us?
</P>
<P>
   Short of abandoning all travel plans and eating big bucks in
cancelled airfare and hotel deposits, how can anyone seriously
respond to such a non-specific, all-encompassing warning?
</P>
<P>
   Should you go ahead but stay in your hotel room the entire time?
Cancel all planned visits to such sites as the Wailing Wall, the
Place de la Concorde, Piazza San Marco, Trafalgar Square, Plaza
Colon, the Brandenburg Gate?
</P>
<P>
   How about hiring bodyguards and asking for an armored car when
you check in at Hertz? Or cleverly festooning your clothing with
shamrocks, Celtic crosses and buttons that say, ``Kiss me _ I'm
Irish''?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe somebody in the State Department, maybe even Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, feels better now that they have shared
their credible but not counterable information about possible
holiday terrorism abroad. Now, if something happens, they'll be
able to say, ``We told you so.''
</P>
<P>
   And, who knows? Maybe the worldwide warning will actually end up
saving somebody's life _ somebody, say, who was all set to sing
``I'm a Yankee Doodle Dandy'' at the stroke of midnight on New
Year's Eve in Red Square.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
