<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8642 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-14 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK NEEDS A LOBBYING LAW _ NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Here's an old Albany joke: Kids in this town
don't wear masks on Halloween. Instead, they dress up as state
legislators, knock on the doors of lobbyists and demand presents.
</P>
<P>
   And get them.
</P>
<P>
   Which means it's possible that the governor and both houses of
the Legislature will reach agreement this month on toughening New
York's lobbying law before it dies Dec. 31. It's also possible that
O.J. Simpson will find the real killer, that Bill Clinton will
enter a monastery and that Rudolph Giuliani will win the Nobel
Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Of all those possibilities, passing a tougher lobbying law seems
far and away the least likely.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there aren't proposals out there. Several Assembly
Democrats have offered new lobbying laws so tough that they enjoy
zero chance of passage. Senate Majority Leader Joe Bruno has a
proposal that the Democratic leadership is already bad-mouthing.
And, before long, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver is likely to
offer his own lobbying law suggestion _ one the Republicans will
trash as soon as the wraps come off it.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the holidays are coming. The state
Senate is in town to do something with health care financing _ and,
perhaps, with the lobbying law. But the Assembly isn't yet
scheduled to appear before the new session begins next month.
</P>
<P>
   If, after the Senate goes home, the Assembly does show up to
pass its own lobbying law, the Senate probably won't come back
before Dec. 31. Even if the Assembly passes a 30- or 60-day
extension of the current law, it's unlikely that the Senate will
return to ratify that extension before the new session begins Jan.
5.
</P>
<P>
   Which means, essentially, that even if both houses and the
governor do agree to pass a lobbying law next month _ or the month
after that, or the month after that, or the month after that _
there'll exist a glittering window of time between passage of the
new lobbying law and expiration of the old one.
</P>
<P>
   This will be some window. It will permit lobbyists to shower
expensive gifts on lawmakers and never have to make them public.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking BMWs here. We're talking tickets to Paris. God
knows what we might be talking about. The possibilities beggar the
imagination. No, no, no, say the Republicans; we can always make
any new lobbying law retroactive. After all, we do that with
funding bills, don't we?
</P>
<P>
   Sure. That's because the organizations receiving state money,
even if it arrives late, have no reason to sue. The lobbyists and
their clients would have every reason to sue. They won't want to
make public the gifts they've showered on lawmakers during the
window between the expiration of the current, woefully inadequate
lobbying law and passage of any new one.
</P>
<P>
   They'll argue that no law was in place when they decided to play
Santa Claus to the lawmakers, and that ex post facto laws violate
the U.S. Constitution, which they do.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming, that is, that any new law really is passed during the
next legislative session. Neither the lawmakers nor the lobbyists
who finance their campaigns and provide them with goodies want to
see a lobbying law in the first place. They never did.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the New York State Temporary Commission on Lobbying
has been ``temporary'' since 1977. Neither the legislators nor the
lobbyists who shower cash and presents on them really want to see a
tough lobbying law a permanent part of state government.
</P>
<P>
   So keep your eye on this. And remember it next November, when
all these people stand for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   What you're seeing, quite simply, is Albany at its slimy worst.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
