<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8644 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-WESTWING-REVIEW-HN     12-14 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WESTWING-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WEST WING' RESTORES CREDIBILITY TO WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great American soap opera that is ``The West Wing'' could
never have made it after Watergate but seems absolutely essential
after Monicagate.
</P>
<P>
   In the post-Nixon days, the country was reeling from its first
popular-opinion nightmare that citizens could no longer trust the
government. Now, as we near the post-Clinton days, our
disappointment long ago turning to unsentimental jadedness, how
many among us could stand up and say that politics is noble, that
politicians are representatives of the people and that clashing
political ideologies are set aside for the common good?
</P>
<P>
   The days of trusting a Jimmy Stewart-style candidate and living
in a world of Frank Capra dreams are over. Even Bill Clinton's
bar-lowering antics in the White House failed to raise much of a
ruckus among the general population. The last 25 years have been a
textbook example of jadedness grown to exponential levels.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is why ``The West Wing'' (9 p.m. EST, Wednesdays on
NBC) is a hit, why it casts such a mysterious trance over cynics.
There is no question that it is a superb bit of television, much
like ``ER'' used to be and how creator Aaron Sorkin's other show,
``Sports Night,'' often is.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if these characters were somehow wedged into a drama that
had nothing to do with the president or politics they would still
coalesce into a wonderful ensemble that riveted the nation. They _
and Sorkin _ are that good.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a show about the president of the United States, the
people who work in the White House and the day-to-day realities of
politics. And not cynical, irony-laden politics and situations
either. No, on ``The West Wing'' soapy do-gooderism is played up to
operatic proportions and somewhere Frank Capra is standing at
attention, saluting Old Glory, a tear in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written these days about anti-irony, the return of
honesty and real emotions. From a popular book on that very idea to
yuppies turning their backs on prosperity to seek a simpler life in
their own private Walden, there is a bubbling undercurrent in this
country that seeks the return of the good in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that more readily represented in pop culture than in
``The West Wing,'' a show that has become a hit across the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing'' is nothing if not modern fantasy, prime-time
wish fulfillment. First, a liberal Democrat (Martin Sheen) is in
the White House. He is surrounded not by political vultures and
cronies but by eager go-getters, aides filled to the brim with
righteousness and intellect and just enough smart-aleck savvy to
distinguish them from, say, ``Touched by an Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   That latter part is key if you want to hook former ``Seinfeld''
fans and those who consider themselves intellectual independents
who frown on mainstream pap. Perhaps this is the finest attribute
of ``The West Wing'' _ pulling in the cynics and wrapping them in a
warm flag before they knew what hit them.
</P>
<P>
   From the stirring music at the beginning, and throughout this
show, to the blurred flag waving gloriously in the frame to the
distant shot of the White House and then the 44 minutes of
pro-politics, pro-Constitution, pro-government dramatics that
follow, ``The West Wing'' is a kind of love poem to the Founding
Fathers or something to put in a time capsule so that 100 years
from now historians can say, ``They were a suspicious lot until
just before the new millennium, when they began to believe again.''
</P>
<P>
   What Sorkin and the writers of ``The West Wing'' do,
fundamentally, is get at the meaning of ``good politics.'' Civil
rights come up in virtually every episode. The kind and smart
president and his dedicated staff go through difficult,
gut-wrenching situations; they are overcome often with doubt, which
leads to much hand-wringing, head-shaking and personal reflection.
But in the end, as the music swells and the tears begin to well in
viewers everywhere, those decisions are made for the good of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The show is developing such true believers that Sheen _ a noted
liberal _ is said to be worried that people will confuse the show's
middle-of-the-road president (in Sheen's view) with him.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen has a point. ``The West Wing'' is making believers out of
people. It is restoring faith. Closer to the 2000 election someone
ought to study how a hit television show helped shape an election.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, we will have many more opportunities to soak in
Sorkin's warm bath of patriotism. We can follow President Josiah
Bartlet, a New Hampshire Democrat who just happens to be a direct
descendant of the one of the signer of the Declaration of
Independence. His chief of staff Leo McGarry (John Spencer), a good
man and recovering alcoholic who devotes his life above everything
(even his wife, who leaves him) to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Or deputy chief of staff Josh Lyman (Bradley Whitford), the
fiery, wily strategist with compassion for the people. Then there's
communications director Toby Ziegler and his deputy Sam Seaborn
(Rob Lowe), putting the best spin on the president's populist
message.
</P>
<P>
   Making sure the contentious press is kept at bay as much as
possible is press secretary C.J. Gregg (Allison Janney).
</P>
<P>
   They are all good people. Even political consultant Madeline
Hampton (Moira Kelly), who is a sheep in shark's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, we want to follow these people because they are
doing the nation's work, they are guiding us to greatness in a
world of madness. And even if, in moments, it all seems so corny
and unbelievable, you are dragged back in and reduced to tears or
pride before the dreaded jadedness can rise in your throat.
</P>
<P>
   When President Kennedy said, ``Ask not what your country can do
for you, but what you can do for your country,'' Aaron Sorkin must
have been all ears. He has created a great television show.
</P>
<P>
   In five or so years, it may not age as well as others, but it is
definitely of _ or slightly ahead of _ its time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
