 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Dec. 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The Security Council is expected to
vote Tuesday on a major new Iraq resolution, spelling out the
renewal of arms inspections and conditions for the lifting of
sanctions. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL (Panama) _ Jimmy Carter signs the document on the
turnover of Panama Canal, though control passes at midnight Dec.
31. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-ASSESS (Panama) _ A news analysis on the turnover of the
canal and the end of an era. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the opening of
Israel-Syria talks. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-LEBANON (Damascus) _ A look at Lebanon's role in the
Israel-Syria talks, and whether Israel would like Syria to stay in
Lebanon to police anti-Israel guerrillas. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-HAMAS (Jerusalem) _ In a rare admission, Israel's deputy
defense minister said that the two top Islamic militants killed in
an army raid of their hideout late Monday night had been targeted
for death by Israel; he says there is ``an automatic contract'' on
anyone from Hamas who kills an Israeli. Hamas vows revenge. By
William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in the fighting
in Chechnya. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECT (Moscow) _ With a mayoral election as well as a
parliamentary election on Sunday, the mayor of Moscow organizes a
big rally to boost his presidential hopes. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NKOREA (Tokyo) _ Japan said Tuesday that it would remove
the last of the sanctions it had imposed on North Korea after the
Communist country tested a ballistic missile last year, including a
ban on food aid to the impoverished country. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-U.S. (London) _ Treasury Secretary Summers gives a speech
outlining the U.S. proposal to narrow the mission of the
International Monetary Fund. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-REFERENDUM (Caracas) _ In a referendum on Wednesday
Venezuela has the chance to accelerate what its president, Hugo
Chavez, terms a ``peaceful revolution,'' or to reject what his
opponents say would be a constitutional dictatorship benefiting
Chavez at the expense of the millions of poor citizens he says he
represents. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-POLITICS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Developments after the
Sudanese president dissolves parliament, and the parliament's
speaker urges defiance of the president. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-HUANG (Washington) _ After four years of
investigations, Republicans in Congress will get their chance at a
hearing on Wednesday to publicly grill a Democratic fund-raiser at
the heart of the campaign fundraising controversy: John Huang. By
David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LAND (Washington) _ President Clinton announces a new
list of protected Western lands and monuments. By Marc Lacey
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-TRIAL (Ellicott City, Md.) _ The judge in the Linda Tripp
trial rules that she did not have immunity from state charges when
she taped phone calls with Monica Lewinsky. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   MONT-DRUGS (Fernie, B.C.) _ A busload of elderly people, led by
the Democratic candidate for the Senate from Montana, treks hours
from Missoula, Mont., to Canada to buy less costly prescription
drugs. Democrats across the board hope to make Medicare coverage of
prescription medicine a big issue in next year's election
campaigns. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TRANSIT (New York) _ Ledeall: A judge issues an injunction
barring a transit strike in New York City; negotiators work toward
a midnight strike deadline. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-HEALTH (Columbia, S.C.) _ Moving to capitalize on his
surge in the polls, John McCain on Tuesday is expected to set out a
far-ranging health care plan, including a new block grant to help
low income senior citizens with the costs of prescription drugs and
measures to give more children insurance. The speech is his attempt
to address some of the hottest issues on the campaign trail and
puts him on ground so far dominated by Democrats. He does it as he
steps up his presence in one of his must-win states and as the
campaign goes on the air here with three new radio spots. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-WHITMAN (Washington) _ Looking back at what Bill Bradley
calls his near-death experience, his close call with Christie
Whitman in 1990. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IOWA (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Lamar Alexander endorses George
Bush; other day developments. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RITALIN (Undated) _ In the largest such study yet, the drug
Ritalin is found to be more effective than behavior therapy in
treating attention deficit disorder. By Holcomb B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The outlook for interest rates grows
murkier after the government reports that consumer prices remained
tame in November but that retail sales rose much sharper than
expected. The Labor Department says the Consumer Price Index rose
0.1 percent _ somewhat less than expected and half the pace
recorded in the previous month. But an acceleration in housing
prices contributed to an increase of 0.2 percent in the core index,
which excludes the volatile food and energy sectors. Retail sales,
meanwhile, jumped 0.9 percent in November, posting the largest gain
in three months. Excluding the heavily weighted category of sales
at auto dealers, retail activity rose a more modest 0.4 percent, in
line with expectations. Treasury prices slump after the retail
sales report. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MONSANTO-SUIT (Undated) _ Some of the nation's most prominent
antitrust lawyers file a lawsuit against Monsanto, accusing the
company of cornering the seed market and of rushing genetically
modified seeds to market before they were tested adequately. The
suit seeks class-action status on behalf of farmers. By David
Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   AMR-SABRE (Undated) _ AMR, the parent of American Airlines,
confirms plans to spin off its 83 percent interest in Sabre
Holdings, in a transaction worth $6.2 billion. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were slightly lower in early trading.
European markets were modestly higher. The Nikkei closed down 0.22
percent; the Hang Seng, down 0.97 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   USED-CARS (Canton, Mich.) _ For most of the last century,
selling cars, particularly used cars, has been a gritty business in
which profits usually went to the entrepreneur who could negotiate
the highest possible price for each automobile, while spending as
little as possible on amenities like furniture, carpeting and
salaries. AutoNation and several other big, publicly traded
companies captured Wall Street's fancy three years ago by trying to
change all that. Now that strategy appears to be imperiled, as the
industry has been buffeted by the rise of the Internet, a decline
in used-car prices and by a renewed push by traditional car dealers
to improve customer services. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Oracle reports its second
quarter earnings after the market closes. The forecast is for
earnings of 22 cents a share. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   DAEWOO-GM (Seoul, South Korea) _ General Motors makes an offer
for assets of Daewoo Motor and asks creditors to write off billions
of dollars of debt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT-AS-PROCESS (Undated) _ Marshall McLuhan wrote 35 years
ago that the medium is the message. Today, a great many business
thinkers, in one way or another, seem to be saying something
similar: the process is the product. Puzzling or not, that thought
has become today's operating philosophy. Aside from electronic
gadgetry, the other things we buy _ the cars we drive, the shoes we
wear, the trips we take _ are not all that different from what they
were 10 years ago. But the ways they are produced have been
overhauled, as the awesome speed of the Internet forces every
business to reinvent its product as a process. By Fred Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   DOMINI-FUND (Undated) _ Amy Domini talks about why she runs a
socially conscious mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   William Safire's ``Essay'' and Bob Herbert's ``In America.''
</P>
