<HEADER>
A8659 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-14 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCH-22S FOR 22 PERCENT OF AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Imagine that 22 percent of the population had
disabling and mysterious disorders of a specific vital organ _ the
liver, say _ and couldn't get treatment. Imagine further that tens
of thousands of these people were lying in sickness and pain all
over the streets.
</P>
<P>
   There would be a call for a national war on liver disease.
Health plans would be forced to cover it. Scientists would work
overtime to invent medications to treat it.
</P>
<P>
   Quit imagining. It's true, except the organ in question is the
brain, and for some reason disorders of the brain are ignored,
denied, feared or considered a joke. Thus people don't seek
treatment for them, even though very effective medications exist.
</P>
<P>
   What we're up against with mental illness is a huge, unofficial
``Don't tell, don't talk about it'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon general, Dr. David Satcher, is trying to end that
policy. He has issued a report saying that 22 percent of the
population has diagnosable mental disorders, but two-thirds don't
seek treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The report's main recommendation is ``seek help if you
experience symptoms of mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   You bet, Doc. The Catch-22 is, if you're crazy, you don't think
you're crazy. And if you seek help, you're crazy to think you'll
get much from the average health plan.
</P>
<P>
   The late Joseph Heller, who invented Catch-22, the rule that
``anybody who wants to get out of combat duty isn't really crazy,''
would have a field day with the surgeon general's advice, as
well-meaning as it is.
</P>
<P>
   Think of all the Catch-22s there are for the 22 percent of
Americans with the highly stigmatized disorders of the brain. Seek
help? That's advice seriously out of touch with reality.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who is seriously depressed probably is too depressed to
get out of the house or pick up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody planning to commit suicide, as Kay Redfield Jamison
discusses in her new book ``Night Falls Fast: Understanding
Suicide,'' probably is concealing the fact.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who goes out and seeks help for mental problems probably
finds they aren't adequately covered in the health plan. There
aren't enough beds on psychiatric units for the seriously ill
either.
</P>
<P>
   The craziest thing of all is that medications exist to
effectively treat depression, manic-depression and certain other
disorders, yet people don't take them. It's understandable.
Consider the stigma.
</P>
<P>
   That's another Catch-22. You have to be crazy to tell an
employer, or a even a friend, you take drugs that keep you sane.
</P>
<P>
   Not telling and not talking about it are requirements of mental
illness, unless you're Woody Allen and using psychiatry as a
running (or lying down) gag for your own enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has done more than any single individual to make
psychiatry seem like a ridiculous waste of time fit only for
weak-willed narcissists _ even at a time when psychiatry has moved
away from the couch to effective and relatively inexpensive pills.
</P>
<P>
   But the disappearance of Woody Allen won't help much. The
stigmatization of mental illness is older than Bedlam, runs wide
and deep, and it isn't about to disappear quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Prozac and Zoloft are laugh lines, even though such new drugs
are effective in treating serious depression in many individuals.
They're also knocked by many social commentators as a means to lull
the non-ill into Stepford tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that they only work on the depressed, and have no
effect on those who are just looking for a high.
</P>
<P>
   In America, there are three strong streams of non-thought about
mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   One says, ``Buck up and pull out of it. It's all in your head.''
The problem is, it is all in the head, and sometimes those little
neurons need some chemical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Another says the mentally ill are violent. Newspapers never fail
to use the phrase ``He had a history of mental illness'' in murder
stories when they can.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that far more people are killed and injured by those
without a history of mental illness. And plenty of people who have
fought and beaten mental illness are working around you.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another disordered line of thinking is that mental illness
is strictly socially defined, schizophrenics have great insights,
and mental hospitals and psychoactive drugs are totalitarian tools
of social control. Those romantic, ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest'' illusions have been disappearing as large mental hospitals
have closed and their former patients have appeared on the streets.
Unfortunately, now we associate mental illness with a state of
hopeless degradation that can't be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon general is to be congratulated for making a
statement that mental illness is hazardous to the nation's health,
and should be treated as a health problem like any other.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't a health problem like any other if you're running
for public office, looking for a job or trying to keep a job.
That's another Catch-22 in the fight against mental illness and its
stigma.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be crazy to talk about having been crazy, and then
who's going to listen to you?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
