<P>
   &UR; FOCUS (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., Dec. 17) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO RETURNEE: Alongside a two-lane road that winds through
the hills in southern Kosovo sits a walled farmyard with a
cinderblock house at its center. The steep, forested hills rising
all around could be mistaken for those of north Georgia. Skender
Rahimi couldn't get this place out of his mind even while he was in
the safety and relative serenity of Atlanta. His story is a
familiar tale of exile and return that is common among the 800,000
Kosovar Albanians who fled their homeland last spring during the
brutal conflict between the Serb-led Yugoslav military and ethnic
Albanian separatists. The conflict came to an end after NATO's
78-day bombing campaign forced the Yugoslav army, police and
paramilitaries to withdraw from Kosovo.
</P>
