<HEADLINE>
GARCIA MAY BE IN LINE FOR QB OF 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. - Although nobody from the San Francisco
49ers has talked openly about Jeff Garcia's auditioning for a
future role with the team, his coach has finally suggested that is
the case.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief topics to come out of coach Steve Mariucci's
weekly news conference on Monday was the matter of Garcia, who
starts at quarterback for the 49ers but also remains a work in
progress. Garcia led the 49ers to their first win in two months
when the team beat the Atlanta Falcons and threw for 437 yards in a
loss to Cincinnati two weeks ago. He also played so poorly earlier
this season that he lost his job for three games.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia now seems to be set to finish the year as the team's
starter. By bestowing that responsibility on Garcia, Mariucci
acknowledged he is hoping to learn quite a bit about his
quarterback over the remaining three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know where we stand with Jeff by the end of the year,''
Mariucci said. ``I don't know about the other quarterbacks, but
hopefully, Jeff will continue to improve and we'll be able to see
where to go either in the offseason or the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's other quarterbacks are injured starter Steve Young
and reserve Steve Stenstrom.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing for more yards than any other quarterback this
season against Cincinnati, Garcia turned in a solid effort against
Atlanta. He completed 16 of 24 passes for 160 yards, and though he
didn't throw for any touchdowns, he also did not toss any
interceptions. He has appeared far more comfortable with the recent
game plans than earlier this season, when four of his five starts
ended in defeats.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason for Garcia's relaxed style of play is that the
49ers coaches have tailored their strategies to fit his strengths.
He is more accustomed to making plays on the fly than standing in
the pocket. So most of the plays Mariucci and offensive coordinator
Marty Mornhinweg called on Sunday required Garcia to move around
and first look to tight ends and running backs for his throws.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the kind of game plan that will appease wide
receivers Jerry Rice, Terrell Owens and J.J. Stokes, who combined
for four receptions for 38 yards against Atlanta. But that is how
the 49ers think they have to play with Garcia until he develops
into a more polished pocket passer. Of course, the question the
coaching staff is pondering is if that growth will actually happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to see Jeff making progress,'' Mariucci said. ``The
big thing was that we didn't turn the ball over. I think you saw
what he does best. He moves the ball around and gets it to the
backs and tight ends. He's very good at that. What he's being
coached on is staying in the pocket and throwing downfield to the
receivers. He's doing what he does best but he has to continue
improving on making plays in the pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Garcia does improve over the next three weeks, there are
no guarantees the 49ers will not pursue other options in the
offseason. Before Sunday's win, the team seemed to be plummeting to
the point where a high selection in next April's draft appeared to
be a given.
</P>
<P>
   If the 49ers do wind up in decent enough position to pluck a
highly rated prospect like Marshall's Chad Pennington or
Louisville's Chris Redman, they would have a hard time passing that
up. As for free agency, that is not going to yield much at
quarterback; Cincinnati's Jeff Blake and Tennessee's Neil O'Donnell
headline the upcoming crop. These are players the 49ers must
consider because Garcia may end up being nothing more than a solid
backup and the team has shown no indication that they expect Young
to be playing next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jeff is a backup, we're going to have to decide on a
starter still,'' Mariucci said. ``Is it Steve Young? A trade? Free
agency? Those decisions will have to be made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
