<HEADLINE>
ENSURE LOW RATES BY BUYING THIS YEAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If ever there were a time to buy life insurance, this
is the time.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the hype insurance companies are pitching to
potential customers about the dawn of the Triple X era of life
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry or get excited. Insurers aren't trying to make their
business sexier by giving away pornography with their policies.
</P>
<P>
   Triple X is the misnomer of a regulation adopted by the National
Association of Insurance Commissioners that requires life insurers
to keep more cash in the reserves they maintain for long-term
guaranteed premium policies.
</P>
<P>
   It gets its nickname from the association's alphabet-reliant
naming system.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners took this step out of worry that the fierce
competition to sell term insurance, which is estimated to have
premiums 40 percent lower than five years ago, might leave some
companies without enough money stashed away to pay future claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Triple X is meant to ensure that a promise made is a promise
kept,'' says Jack Dolan, a spokesman for the American Council of
Life Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RULE AFFECTS TEXAS POLICIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen states also have adopted the rule, which takes
effect in Texas and most other states Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   After that insurers will have to keep more money in accounts
that return less interest than if they were allowed to invest that
money in stocks and other securities.
</P>
<P>
   To make up for the loss in income and to get the additional
money to increase their reserves, insurance companies can either
make less profit, raise premiums and/or eliminate long-term
policies from their product line.
</P>
<P>
   Since stockholders aren't too inclined to see a drop in
revenues, many insurers are predicting premiums rates will rise 15
to 50 percent on term and universal insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Others are saying 30-year term insurance will no longer exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything is prohibited by the regulation, but
some products certainly will be harder to find,'' says Ted Becker,
chief life actuary for the Texas Department of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the mini-Y2K hype.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers wondering if they should boost their coverage before
the calendar fills up with zeroes need to consider a crucial
question: Do you need more life insurance?
</P>
<P>
   If someone depends on your income and you don't have any, then
the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   Those with some insurance need to sit down and figure out how
much money your loved ones would need if you died today.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, calculate your monthly expenses and think about what
future plans you want to fund. If you want the mortgage paid off, a
child's college education funded or your spouse to be able to stop
working, then you need to have enough insurance to cover all of
that.
</P>
<P>
   Rules of thumb, such as being insured for seven times your
annual income, really don't cut it. But you can use that to get
started if thinking about your bills, debts and mortality is just
too depressing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHOLE LIFE PRICES COULD DROP &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once you've determined your coverage level, you need to decide
what type of policy best suits your financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   Term insurance provides protection for a specific amount of time
and pays a benefit only if you die during that period.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent insurance gives lifelong protection and pays a death
benefit as long as your premiums are paid.
</P>
<P>
   The three types of permanent insurance are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Whole or ordinary life, which has fixed premiums that build up
cash inside the policy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Universal or adjustable life, which has flexible premium
payment schedules and a guaranteed death benefit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Variable life, which ties death benefits and cash values to
the performance of an underlying investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Although term and universal may see rate increases, don't
automatically choose term over whole life.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of the consumer-friendly Triple X rule is that it
used revised mortality tables to come up with the new reserve
requirements. That could have the unintended effect of lowering
whole life premiums.
</P>
<P>
   If all of this confuses you, talk to your insurance agent or a
financial planner about your current cash flow and your financial
goals. These professionals should be able to guide you to the best
type of policy for you.
</P>
<P>
   You can also use the Internet to research policies and check
rates. Visit Quotesmith.com or accuquotelife.com.
</P>
<P>
   But start searching soon. Getting life insurance is more
complicated than filling out an application.
</P>
<P>
   The underwriting process requires a medical exam, a credit
report, a driving record and other details of your health and
lifestyle. It typically takes life insurance companies 3 to 6 weeks
to set up a policy.
</P>
<P>
   And just like the other millennium bug, Triple X may prove to be
much ado about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan, of the life insurance council, says some companies will
be taking a wait-and-see approach to the rule for the first six
months of the new year. And if competition to write policies stays
strong, rate increases may not be as high as those predicted.
</P>
<P>
   But the bargain shopper in me says, if you need more insurance,
don't wait.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
