<HEADER>
A8688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      12-14 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS THAT GO BEYOND `RED WITH MEAT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wish Dr. Seuss were still around. I could make him still
another fortune and come off with a tidy little sum for myself.
How? Simple. Persuade him to write a how-to book about wine. You
know: big print, silly pictures, a 300-word vocabulary, mostly
one-syllable words like ``wine'' and ``vine,'' and a title like,
oh, how about ``The Ape That Ate the Grape''?
</P>
<P>
   It would be a smash! How do I know this? I don't, but year after
year at about this time, publishers pump out yet another batch of
wine primers. They are a brilliant lot, those publishers, so they
must know what they're doing. They have obviously tapped into an
insatiable demand for books that say yet again, and as cleverly as
possible, red with the meat and white with the fish.
</P>
<P>
   But concentrating on oversimplified, glossy gift books means
overlooking some less heralded but often intriguing things written
about wine that are not meant for neophytes. Some months ago, a
thoughtful reader put me on to a truly remarkable piece of American
social history, Madelon Powers' ``Faces Along the Bar: Lore and
Order in the Workingman's Saloon, 1870-1920'' (University of
Chicago Press, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   For the millions of immigrants to this country in the 19th and
early 20th centuries, the saloon was an indispensable source of
advice, education, information and relaxation. It took them out of
their fetid tenements, however briefly, and played a defining _ and
now almost forgotten _ role in shaping their new lives.
</P>
<P>
   With considerable skill, Ms. Powers steers a path through
sentimentalists like George Ade and Peter Finley Dunne and
reformers like Jane Addams and Jacob Riis, but uses them and a
hundred other sources to paint a vivid picture of both the
fellowship and the tragedy to be found in what has been called the
``poor man's club.''
</P>
<P>
   The illustrations are worth the price of the book. One shows a
map of a section of Manhattan's Lower East Side in 1894. The area
bounded by the Bowery and Hester, Essex and East Houston Streets,
is shown to have had a population of 49,359 people and 237 saloons,
or a saloon for every 208 residents. ``Ah, the Irish,'' one is
tempted to say. No, the map is titled, ``Jewish Quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   In a totally different vein, ``Wine From Sky to Earth'' (Acres
U.S.A., $24) by Nicolas Joly, the father of the biodynamic movement
among winemakers, explains how he left investment banking and
returned to his family's vineyards along the Loire, bringing with
him an entirely new way of looking at grape growing and winemaking.
He demystifies biodynamics, which calls for the abandonment of all
chemical fertilizers, pesticides and fungicides, as he argues that
the process involves a return to old ways, not a leap into
something new and untried.
</P>
<P>
   As David Ridgway, the sommelier at Tour d'Argent in Paris, says
in his preface to Joly's book, ``We acknowledge the influence of
the moon, sun and stars on the tides, but at present we deny that
the same effects extend to grapevines.''
</P>
<P>
   Biodynamics has been called extreme organic farming. But Joly
has imparted his enthusiasm and his methods to hundreds of
winemakers around the world, including some of the most famous.
Now, he has produced a highly readable and most valuable book for
anyone interested in the future of wine and the grapes from which
it is made.
</P>
<P>
   Most wine books, like many of the wine fan magazines, are
treacly encomiums to the industry and the winemakers. So, ``The
Wrath of Grapes'' (Spike, $13.50) by Lewis Perdue offers a
much-needed, unsugared view of the wine business and the people who
run it. Instead of giving lush descriptions of vineyards and rare
wines, he talks about overproduction, flat consumption, an
antiquated distribution system, unstoppable vineyard diseases and a
host of other problems besetting America's winemakers. At the same
time, he suggests some fascinating ways to capitalize on the
industry's problems, from investing in undervalued stocks to buying
good, undervalued wines. You will be intrigued by his lists of the
most underrated wines, like Shafer Vineyards, and overrated wines,
Dom Perignon. This is a good little book for counteracting wine
industry hype.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Sense of Place: An Intimate Portrait of the
Niebaum-Coppola Winery and the Napa Valley'' (Routledge, $24.95),
Steven Kolpan, who teaches wine studies at the Culinary Institute
of America in Hyde Park, N.Y., offers a discerning view of the
winery created and owned by Francis Ford Coppola. Much of the
material about the sad demise of the original Inglenook Vineyards
has appeared elsewhere, but Kolpan is particularly good on the
contributions of the Mexican laborers who quietly perform so much
of the work that goes into making Napa Valley wines.
</P>
<P>
   As for those easy-reading wine guides, two are worth a mention.
With the 14th edition of his ``Windows on the World Complete Wine
Course'' now out (Sterling, $24.95), Kevin Zraly is the grandfather
of wine-primer writers, and his book the McGuffy's Reader of wine
books. His never-flagging enthusiasm for wine bounces off every
page, just as Zraly bounces around the room during his wine
lectures. In a classroom, expounding on the glories of Burgundy _
or anything else _ he is a one-man Cirque du Soleil. But his book
is still the best of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there are also a couple of new kids on the block who
_ although I wouldn't swear to this _ seem to be fixing to
out-Zraly Zraly. Dorothy J. Gaiter and John Brecher, a
wife-and-husband team who write a popular weekly wine column for
The Wall Street Journal, have produced a lighthearted and
informative little book called ``The Wall Street Journal Guide to
Wine'' (Broadway Books, $25). Their enthusiasm for the grape, which
can border on the manic (they love the word ``wow''), is exceeded
only by their enthusiasm for each other. It spills over on every
other page. They are the Nelson Eddy and Jeanette MacDonald of
wine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
