A8693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-HOLIDAY-EATING-WELL-N     12-14 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. FEELGOOD'S EATING WELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pumpkin pie? ``You might as well put this right up there on the
food pyramid,'' said Dr. Eric Rimm, an associate professor of
epidemiology and nutrition at the Harvard School of Public Health,
getting into the spirit of this week's Eating Well column which, in
honor of the season, has been temporarily renamed Dr. Feelgood's
Eating Well column.
</P>
<P>
   Eggnog? Caviar? Help yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Regular readers of Eating Well, who may be certain I have taken
leave of my senses, can be assured that all I have done is come to
grips with reality. There is no sense in railing about fat and
calories during the holidays, because one or two days of
overindulgence are not going to kill anyone and are even unlikely
to cause weight gain.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the number of calories needed for weight
maintenance, a person would have to consume 5,000 to 7,000 calories
in a day to gain any weight at all, and it's not likely to be even
close to a pound, said Dr. Wayne Calloway, an obesity specialist
and an associate clinical professor of medicine at George
Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind I decided to look on the bright side of our
annual holiday orgy of eating, and I found all kinds of good stuff
for your body as well as your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked in between the cholesterol and the saturated fat, the
calories and the salt in the foie gras, the sausage stuffing and
the standing rib roast, there are dozens of nutrients that are
highly recommended by the food police. These are the vitamins and
minerals and phytochemicals that may prevent cancer and heart
disease and a host of other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone already knows that chocolate is a health food: Two
pounds of it, particularly dark chocolate, has the same
cancer-fighting antioxidants as a quart of tea.
</P>
<P>
   But did you know that each time you eat a three-ounce piece of
pumpkin pie you may well be reducing your risk of cataracts and
macular degeneration? The pumpkin in that small wedge of pie is
filled with carotenoids, almost 3,000 micrograms of beta carotene,
1,900 of alpha carotene and 400 of lutein, the carotenoid connected
with cataract prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Before dinner you might have some heart-healthy caviar: Its fats
are mostly mono- and polyunsaturated, and those are preferable to
saturated fat. Wait _ that's not all. Caviar is loaded with iron,
which helps the blood, and with magnesium and selenium. It has
reasonably good amounts of &UR;  &LR; B12 and folate, which reduces the risk
of birth defects. As for its levels of omega-3 fatty acids, which
protect against heart attacks, they are absolutely great. That
benediction comes from Bonnie Liebman at the Center for Science in
the Public Interest, not exactly a champion of wretched excess.
</P>
<P>
   How about the silken unctuousness of foie gras? Have a second
helping because liver is a significant source of copper, necessary
to make hemoglobin in the blood, and of iron, especially important
for women. And it is packed with selenium, as much as 22 times the
recommended daily allowance, which may reduce the risk of prostate
cancer. Foie gras is not bad in the B vitamin department either; in
fact it's got far more vitamin B12 than the recommended daily
requirement, and B12 helps to prevent neurological problems. Foie
gras also has a significant amount of vitamin A, a precursor of
those carotenoids.
</P>
<P>
   Standing rib roast is a must even though it is not exactly
perceived as health food. It is hard to get enough B12 in the diet
without eating meat. Team the foie gras with the rib roast, and you
get a double whammy: Three ounces of foie gras and a six-ounce slab
of beef provide 10 milligrams of iron, more than half the daily
iron requirement. Any other time of year, nutritionists recommend
three ounces of meat (about the size of a deck of cards) as an
appropriate serving size, but this is Christmas!
</P>
<P>
   Even fruitcake has its merits, although it is not everyone's
favorite. What with all those fruits and nuts. Three ounces has
three grams of fiber, which is about 10 percent of the recommended
daily amount. But that's not all. There are also about 20
micrograms of lycopene in that fruitcake, not a great deal, but
every microgram counts in efforts to reduce the risk of prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   You will also get some fiber from Granny's rich
sausage-oyster-cornbread stuffing, not to mention selenium, folate,
iron and tons of zinc. Zinc aids healing and immune function. Both
the cornbread and the oysters add some lutein.
</P>
<P>
   And this just in. All alcohol, not just wine, may be good for
you, providing a superb excuse for indulging in several well-spiked
cups of eggnog, a drink that also contains an excellent source of
protein. A study reported in this week's British Medical Journal
reaffirms the notion that distilled spirits are as effective as
wine or beer in reducing the risk of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   So now you know the little secret that nutritionists have kept
to themselves for years. Buried in the foods that may clog your
arteries and make you fat are nutritional treasures.
</P>
<P>
   If you insist on knowing the information that has been purposely
been excluded here, you can log onto the Agriculture Department's
Web site, www.nal.usda.gov/fnic/foodcomp/, and look it up for
yourself. I'm certainly not going to spoil this column by telling
you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1611EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8695 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-2NDT     12-14 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: most content.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other Internet start-ups are expanding their offerings by making
publishing as democratic as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Fatbrain.com is an online seller of technical and computer books
that started a few years ago in a Silicon Valley garage. Last month
it announced the infusion of $20 million in venture capital to
support a publishing program that allows authors to sell their
works online for a 50 percent royalty.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been the appearance of such works as Richard
Bach's ``Air Ferrets Aloft.'' A Fatbrain.com summary describes the
title as ``the first widely published disclosure of the remarkable
activities of the world's domesticated ferret community, told
through the stories of outstanding individual animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon to come: ``Philosopher Ferrets in the Wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   Already there is some uncertainty about whether this new
technology will produce a wider selection or simply digital slush.
</P>
<P>
   NetLibrary, for instance, will not accept any self-published
titles on its site. The company's view is that books have more
credibility when they are screened and filtered by professional
editors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not allowing people to post their titles,'' said
Melancon. ``If you do, it devalues the other books, because it
doesn't have credibility. Say I go to a Web site and I look up
books on low birth weight and prenatal care in developing
countries. I pull up a book by Sam Jones and I have no idea who Sam
Jones is.''
</P>
<P>
   The prices of netLibrary's books are the same as those of print
versions, but other companies are already starting to experiment
with e-book price discounts because of reduced costs for storage,
inventory and paper.
</P>
<P>
   Zero Heure, a French publisher founded two years ago, is able to
offer discounts for electronic titles that the Bertelsmann-owned
online bookseller Bol.Fr cannot match for printed versions because
of European rules regulating cover prices for conventional books.
</P>
<P>
   A minute after an order is placed, the electronic publisher will
e-mail some of the latest French best sellers at one-third off the
list price to American customers with no access to print versions
in stores here.
</P>
<P>
   Zero Heure is buying the electronic rights for print books, but
is also publishing its own original titles. Next month, for
instance, the company intends to publish ``Ici Kaboul,'' an ongoing
book about an Afghan woman's experiences in Kabul that will be
updated quarterly with new electronic chapters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's writing a chronicle of her life, and this could continue
as long as she wants,'' said Jean-Pierre Arbon, one of the
company's founders and the former managing director of Flammarion.
</P>
<P>
   This experimentation with literary forms has spread to nouveau
companies with no publishing experience such as CyberGold, an
e-commerce company that offers an array of digital products.
</P>
<P>
   This month, CyberGold featured its first electronic title,
``Dark Again,'' a thriller by David Saperstein, the author of the
book ``Cocoon,'' which inspired the movie of the same name. It is
available for $7.50 for the entire book or 50 cents a chapter. Each
chapter includes additional material _ from the assassin's
corporate memos to diary entries.
</P>
<P>
   One basic question that all these companies must confront is
whether readers will warm to the new forms.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, like netFind, are counting on a generation of
young readers, weaned on computers, who are ready to read on
screens. But as skeptics have pointed out, for years to come
companies will also have to reach the much larger group of older
readers to make the market viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 48, and for me I can't do it,'' confessed Dillon, who is
in charge of acquiring electronic titles for the University of
Texas. ``But my kids are in high school and they read books from
beginning to end on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his personal misgivings, he is betting on a generational
shift that will raise the popularity of e-books. He noted, for
example, that the library had expected that readers would be
interested only in electronic versions exploring computer topics.
But the taste in digital fare is far more eclectic, with readers
checking out titles from ``Art Ideology and Economics in Nazi
Germany'' to ``100 Years of Tomorrow: Brazilian Women's Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to put the money there, because we're guessing
that's what will happen,'' he said of student demand. ``It's
getting harder and harder to get them to go into their car to come
to the library.''
</P>
</TEXT>
