<HEADER>
A8698 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BOOKS-CHILDREN-HNS &LR;      12-14 1721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CHILDREN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO CULTIVATE A CHILD'S INTEREST IN READING, CHOOSE BOOKS THAT ARE
FUN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Pokemon) 
 
By JANE P. MARSHALL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagination and creativity are the wings of one's mind. On these
two wings, you will fly high and far.
</P>
<P>
   Jean and Mou-Sien Tseng used these words to explain how they
feel about illustrating children's books.
</P>
<P>
   But those two sentences also describe the essence of children's
books, and why so many work so hard to put books in children's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Give a book and you give a window, a magic carpet, a gift which
reaches beyond a single volume.
</P>
<P>
   To select a book:
</P>
<P>
   _ Get one the child will enjoy reading. That may not be the one
with the fancy cover. Or the one with a moral that a child
``should'' read. Remember, the book is not as important as the fact
that a child is reading.
</P>
<P>
   _ Select one with quality paper and a sturdy binding that will
withstand many little hands and readings.
</P>
<P>
   _ A picture book should be an artistic achievement. Children
appreciate nuance as much as adults. Pictures don't have to look
like the cartoons they see on TV, all brightly colored and cute.
</P>
<P>
   _ Books should fit a child's reading and interest level. But
age-appropriate labels are only guides. Some children can handle
``Bridge to Terabithia'' at 8, others not until 12.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put by Eden Ross Lipson, author of the ``New York Times
Parent's Guide to the Best Books for Children'' (Random House,
$15): ``... In choosing or giving books, remember to try to find
titles that children can embrace, not suffer; seize, not shove away
for the deferred or postponed gratification of something to `grow
into,' like a winter coat.''
</P>
<P>
   She tells the story of Beverly Cleary, author of the Ramona
series, who said, ``When I was a child, a relative gave me
`Ivanhoe' to grow into. I was so disappointed that I still have not
grown into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Books can be classics, they can be notable award winners, they
can be just plain fun. Fiction or nonfiction. Silly, sassy or
sweet.
</P>
<P>
   But they must speak to the child looking at the pictures,
reading or listening to the words.
</P>
<P>
   These, culled from hundreds of new books, are lively, quality
books, beautifully written and illustrated. They are delightful to
read aloud. They will capture hearts, imaginations and attention.
They will live longer in a child's mind than a Pokemon game and
Millennium Barbies. They will help instill a love of reading, the
most precious gift you can give a child.
</P>
<P>
   But they are only a place to start.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOR THE VERY, VERY YOUNG &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``First Night'' (G.P. Putnam, $15.99), by Harriet Ziefert,
marches along as Amanda Dade leads the parade. Others fill in the
New Year's event but Amanda Dade leads. The repeating verse helps
children learn words and sounds. S.D. Schindler's illustrations of
colored pencils and Magic Markers on midnight blue pastel paper are
stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Are You Peeling? Foods with Moods'' (Scholastic, $15.95)
takes an old theme and illustrates it with goofy personified
vegetables and fruit. An orange screaming. A silly kiwi.
Delightfully delicious!
</P>
<P>
   ``Tucker Flips!'' (Dutton, $9.99) is a pint-sized book for
pint-sized hands. Puppy Tucker dreams of playing with children. He
even practices ... and learns to flip! The bold, colorful drawings
will keep tiny eyes sparkling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOR AGES 4 TO 8 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Books for beginning readers can, of course, still be read aloud.
Author and reading-aloud advocate Jim Trelease writes that ``almost
as big a mistake as not reading to children at all is stopping too
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Night Iguana Left Home'' (DK, $15.95), by megan McDonald
with illustrations by Ponder Goembel, is at once loopy and sweet.
Even the most cherished pet dreams, and Iguana, who lives with her
``almost sister'' Alison, dreams of a warm-weather vacation by the
sea. She takes off on a well-planned but mishap-prone trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Make Me Laugh'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, $16) is by
the wonderful James Stevenson. Sorry, can't say much about this
because the story line is a secret. But here's a hint: You may feel
like laughing but you don't. No laughing allowed when reading this
book. None. Delightful read-aloud book for even the most solemn
child and curmudgeonly adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swine Lake'' (HarperCollins, $15.95) leaps from the famous
minds of author James Marshall (the prince who gave us ``George and
Martha'') and artist Maurice Sendak (the king who gave us ``Where
the Wild Things Are''). Their partnership is what is special about
this book. Pigs on pointe. Hungry wolf in a box seat. Getting
caught up in the moment. The power of a positive review. What a
tasty treat!
</P>
<P>
   ``Do You Want To Play? A Book About Being Friends'' (Dutton,
$15.99) has a simple story and a zany circus of characters that
keeps each page buzzing like a beehive. Learning to be a friend _
from sharing and fighting to apologizing to playing alone _ may be
a blatant message, but who cares? Bob Kolar's art is like romping
through a toy store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is the Apple Pie?'' (Philomel, $15.99) is best when read
aloud. The nonsense tale of a missing pie's journey around the
world is just plain fun from Ukrainian emigrant Valeri Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's A Wardrobe in My Monster!'' (Carolrhoda, $15.95) tells
about what happens when Martha, bored with ordinary pets, gets a
great big, ugly monster at the pet store. Original. Delightful.
Adrienne Geoghegan wrote, and Adrian Johnson illustrated, with
panache.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Piccolo's Easy Chair'' (DK, $15.95) will send kids into
fits of the giggles. One day Mrs. Piccolo's big chair follows her
to the grocery in search of its favorite snack _ cheese puffs.
Author Jean Jackson has an extraordinary imagination, as does
illustrator Diane Greenseid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma Fina and Her Wonderful Umbrellas'' (Cinco Puntos,
$15.95), from a small press in El Paso, is called a bilingual early
reader. Benjamin Alire Saenz's Grandma Fina is a kind feisty lady
who is loved by the whole community. Every person invited to her
birthday party decides what she needs most is a new umbrella. But
what's a grandma to do with all those umbrellas! Geronimo Garcia's
illustrations make you love Grandma Fina even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullfrog Pops!'' (Gibbs-Smith, $15.95) puts a cocky animal in
a pickle and watches what happens. Rick Walton's tale and Chris
McAllister's hilarious paintings fill this book with color, humor
and a big, fat, extraordinarily hungry and ornery bullfrog. Has
Bullfrog met his match in Ravenous Gulch? This is another to read
aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Escape from City Zoo'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux,
$16) is from Australian cartoonist Tohby Riddle. A band of unlikely
buddies do what few have dared _ they break out of city zoo. The
fugitives' quest for a new life puts them into some sweet and some
funny scenes. But they can't escape their past. Here's sweet
suspense, silly surprises and intriguing black and white
illustration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOR AGES 6 TO 10 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perfume of Memory'' (Scholastic, $16.95) is an original
tale by Michelle Nikly, illustrated by Jean Claverie in soft,
dreamlike watercolors. Yasmin dreams of becoming the Royal Perfume
Maker, but the law forbids it. Only boys can compete, according to
an ancient, unfortunate law. But when the queen's memory is taken
away by an enemy, only young Yasmin figures out how to save the
kingdom and restore tradition and hope. Doing what is right is a
powerful thing, and even the youngest can summon that power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ghost of Shanghai'' (Abrams, $16.95) takes Li on a journey
across Shanghai to deliver the wedding dress her mother has made
for the wealthy Ha family. She is hit by a bicycle. As she lies in
the street, a ghost assures her she will be all right. But he has a
request. Li learns about justice and honor in this charming story
of contemporary China and a little girl with big dreams. Claude
Guillot wrote the story, which Fabienne Burckel vibrantly
illustrates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAMILY READ-ALOUD BOOKS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland'' (Candlewick Press, $24.99)
was originally published in 1865. Lewis Carroll (Charles Lutwidge
Dodgson) taught mathematics at Christ Church College, Oxford
University, and wrote the story for his dean's daughters. The story
is as magical as ever. Try this on the Harry Potter fans in your
house. This new version is illustrated by Helen Oxenbury, who adds
modern charm and a bit of whimsy that don't remind you a bit of
Disney's characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fairies' Ring: A Book of Fairy Stories &AMP; Poems'' (Dutton,
$24.99) is collected and adapted by Jane Yolen and illustrated by
Stephen Mackey. Even in this day of space alien teen-agers on TV
and creatures battling each other in video games, fairies are
magical. Their age-old allure is presented in this rich collection
of the familiar and unfamiliar and beautiful illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince and the Pauper'' (Dial, $17.99) was adapted by
Marianna Mayer from the Mark Twain novel of switched identities.
This is a worthy introduction to a classic story, one of the best
of many new adaptations on book shop shelves. Gary A. Lippincott's
engaging paintings brim with detail and emotion.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Wings of an Artist: Children's Book Illustrators Talk About
Their Art'' (Abrams, $17.95), more than 20 celebrated children's
book artists, ranging from Maurice Sendak to David Small, each
contribute an illustration and an essay.
</P>
<P>
   Although some favorites are not here _ John Burningham, Jan
Brett, Jerry Pinkney, Floyd Cooper and others _ those included
explain their chosen career paths with childlike awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of children's book illustration is such a
kaleidoscope, offering imagination, creativity and artistic
ingenuity in a tangible, satisfying and enduring form _ a picture
book,'' Julie Cummins writes in the introduction.
</P>
<P>
   She emphasizes the importance of art literacy and picture books'
role in helping a child appreciate art.
</P>
<P>
   William Joyce, who has created many wonderful characters,
explains: ``I don't pretend to be from another planet anymore _ but
I get to make up characters who are. It's my job. And in some weird
way, it's like getting paid for recess.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1618EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
