<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Shara arrive in Washington
for a round of talks at President Clinton's urging. We look at the
peace talks that are scheduled to begin Wednesday at the White
House, the issues at stake, the role Clinton is likely to play,
what the United States must do to make any progress stick. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-LAWSUIT (Washington) _ Taking the next step in a threatened
federal lawsuit against gun manufacturers, senior administration
officials meet with 20 city and county officials to coordinate
their negotiations with the industry. Some local officials express
outrage at what they see as its intransigence. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
(Will update.)
</P>
<P>
   US-Y2K (Washington) _ The federal government plans to announce
that is ready for the year 2000. Uncle Sam's cost to handle the
so-called Y2K computer bug is estimated at more than $8 billion. By
DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS-POLICE (Washington) _ Police harassment of Hispanics
nationwide will continue largely unabated until law-enforcement
agencies recruit, hire and retain more Hispanic officers, leading
civil-rights and police organizations say. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   MILLION-MOM-MARCH (Washington) _ Outraged by incidents of gun
violence that have killed or wounded children, thousands of mothers
across the country are quietly organizing what they hope will be a
``Million Mom March'' in May aimed at pressuring Congress to enact
tougher firearm controls. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-ED (Washington) _ More schools are urging adolescent
students to wait to have sex, but information on safe sex and birth
control is still offered at most schools, according to a new study.
Some experts see political and religious conservatives as a threat
to classroom discussions on how to use a condom and where to go for
birth-control pills. By ANDREW BROMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL (Panama City, Panama) _ At the site of one of
America's greatest engineering feats, the United States
symbolically hands over control of the Panama Canal, marking the
close of a century-long presence on the isthmus that separates the
Atlantic and the Pacific oceans. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Des Moines, Iowa) _ On the heels of an energetic
debate exchange with chief rival John McCain, George W. Bush says
that he expects the race for the Republican presidential nomination
to heat up but hopes it will not turn ugly. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ If ever there were a time to buy life
insurance, this is the time. At least that's the hype insurance
companies are pitching to potential customers. By SHANNON BUGGS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Time magazine, elaborating on its
annual man-of-the-year cover, is searching for a public consensus
on a person of the century. The results will be in the Dec. 27
magazine. The pundits' favorite seems to be Franklin D. Roosevelt,
but a Time online poll leans toward Elvis Presley (honest).This is
an interesting exercise, but a case can be made for choosing many
people, not just one. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
