<HEADLINE>
ROMANCING THE NUT: FIRST, GET IT OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most kitchen equipment is purchased with the task in mind: You
want a tool that works easily and efficiently. So it is rare to
come across a tool like the nutcracker, which is used both for the
task and for the pleasure of breaking open a nut and retrieving the
meat.
</P>
<P>
   Nuts straight from the shell have much more flavor than those
bought shelled, so purist bakers want to shell nuts, and shell them
quickly. More often, though, nut cracking is an amusement for
people lounging by the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why few nutcrackers look serious. You know when you put
a walnut in the mouth of a wooden squirrel that this is not about
cracking 10 nuts a minute. (With most squirrel or soldier
nutcrackers you may never get a nut open _ it always slips out of
the mouth.)
</P>
<P>
   The seven nutcrackers I tried were wildly different in
appearance, and none of them were very efficient. By design, they
crack only one nut at a time, and most nuts will still require a
little peeling by hand.
</P>
<P>
   I began with the most recognizable nutcracker, the spring-action
pincer-type with narrow steel handles; this one came with four
picks.
</P>
<P>
   With practice, you can get this nutcracker to work well. It will
split a walnut up its sides, and then you can pick out the halves.
But this nutcracker is flimsy and thin, so you could just as easily
squeeze too hard and smash the nut _ or a finger. Next to
familiarity, its price may be its best asset. The Quackenbush brand
is $3.98 at Zabar's, 2245 Broadway (80th Street); (212) 787-2000.
</P>
<P>
   High design hasn't necessarily helped the nutcracker. Oxo's
version was the clunker of the group. With a handle made of zinc,
it feels like an anvil. I thought the weight and wide shafts would
help hold the nut in place and crack it forcefully but slowly.
Instead, once the handles were squeezed, the weight only compounded
the force.
</P>
<P>
   The shell didn't just crack, it exploded. A hazelnut shell hit
me in the head; when I tried an almond, it blew to smithereens. The
Oxo is $11.95 at A Cook's Companion, 152 Atlantic Avenue (Clinton
Street), Cobble Hill, Brooklyn; (718) 852-6901.
</P>
<P>
   You would expect the same results from the Rocket, which looks
like a contraption made by someone who spends too much time in a
tool shed. But it works splendidly. You hold the nut, end to end,
between two cupped receptacles, then pull a lever _ like a beer
tap. The cups clench the nut and it cracks according to how hard
you pull the lever; the meat stays mostly in whole pieces. The
Rocket is $12.98 at Zabar's.
</P>
<P>
   A similar concept applies to the Biesse nutcracker. The nut is
laid on a grooved rubber surface, under two overlapping levers.
When you lightly pound the top lever, the nut is cracked between
layers of rubber. The idea is fine, but the results inconsistent. I
was able to get whole meats from Brazil nuts, but walnuts broke
into large pieces, each of which had to be cracked.
</P>
<P>
   What I liked least about this tool, though, was the way it
removed you from the cracking. Nut cracking should be hands-on. The
Biesse is $7.99 at Chef Central, 240 Route 17 North, Paramus, N.J.;
(201) 576-0178.
</P>
<P>
   The Schmidt &AMP; Brendel nutcracker, a hand-held model, does manage
to break nuts gently. The nut is placed in a ridged cone. As you
squeeze the handles, the nut cracks and falls farther into the cone
and the handles crack at different points every time you squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the tool cracks the outer shell without crushing the
nut, then you have to peel away the shell and pick out the meat. It
is $14.99 at Chef Central.
</P>
<P>
   Zyliss recently introduced a nutcracker similar to the Schmidt &AMP;
Brendel but without the cone. It is the best design of the six
all-purpose crackers. A round cavity holds the nut; as you squeeze,
a ridged piece presses against the nut and cracks it. The cavity
contains the shell as it shatters, and you don't have to press too
hard and risk an exploding nut. The construction is solid and
hefty, with a comfortable matte surface, which helps you grip.
Every nut I cracked came out in one piece. It's $13.98 at Zabar's.
</P>
<P>
   One specialized nutcracker, the Mono walnut opener, is a silky
stainless-steel disk, shaped much like the Batman symbol and
attached to a thin leather string. Its surface has just a slight
indentation where your thumb is placed, but the depth is so perfect
and so comfortable that it fits right into your hand.
</P>
<P>
   It actually works, too. All you do is press the center point
into the base of the walnut, then turn it like a key. The nut
splits in half flawlessly, and you can use the other points to pry
up the meat. It's $19.50 at the MOMA Design Store, 44 West 53rd
Street; (212) 708-9669.
</P>
</TEXT>
