<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NURSING HOMES THAT HURT PATIENTS NOW SUBJECT TO STIFF FINES
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nursing homes that harm patients can be given steep
fines under new federal orders issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If those orders had been in effect last year, 12 percent of the
nation's 17,000 nursing homes would have been fined, said Nancy-Ann
DeParle, head of the Health Care Financing Administration, which
oversees Medicare and Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, nursing homes have received warnings and minimal
fines which gave them little incentive to make long-term
corrections to problems, DeParle said at a breakfast with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in what she described as a ``yo-yo effect'' of
homes complying with regulations for a brief period and then
violating them again without fear of significant sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to put that to an end by making a deterrent so
that it would not be in a nursing home's interest to wait it out,''
DeParle said, noting that thus far ``it has not been in their
interest ... to spend the money to fix the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Under DeParle's new instructions, states must impose sanctions,
which could range up to a $10,000 fine for each violation, whenever
a nursing home is found to have caused harm to a patient on two
consecutive inspections. The injuries do not have to have been
caused by the same violation for a home to be sanctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing homes are inspected by the states on a roughly annual
basis, but homes would be subject to more frequent inspections if
problems are identified or if there are complaints.
</P>
<P>
   A General Accounting Office study in June predicted that stiffer
federal sanctions would be effective in reducing harm to nursing
home patients. In its study of 107 nursing home inspections, the
GAO found 201 cases of harm to patients, including bed sores,
broken bones, severe weight loss, burns and death.
</P>
<P>
   DeParle's orders also give the states greater authority to
sanction nursing homes that don't meet certain health and safety
regulations by denying Medicare and Medicaid payments for new
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Homes that do not fix serious problems could lose their
contracts for Medicare and Medicaid payments entirely.
</P>
<P>
   DeParle's instructions are part of a broad effort by the Clinton
administration to make nursing homes safer for their 1.6 million
elderly and disabled residents.
</P>
<P>
   The federal budget this year includes more than $50 million to
enhance nursing home safety enforcement. Since the spring, federal
officials have trained more than 600 state and federal survey
managers.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Financing Administration has put a priority in
getting inspectors to focus on problems such as preventing bed
sores, malnutrition and physical abuse in nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also released a new pamphlet, ``Your Guide to
Choosing a Nursing Home,'' to answer questions about selecting a
nursing home. The guide is available by calling 1-800-MEDICARE
(1-800-633-4227).
</P>
<P>
   People interested in comparing local facilities can get data
related to residents' health status at Medicare and
Medicaid-certified nursing homes through the Health Care Financing
Administration's Internet site at www.medicare.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
