<HEADLINE>
WINE INDUSTRY FORESEES VINDICATION ON HEALTH ADVISORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's wine industry is not happy about
the federal government's decision to temporarily halt a program
that lets the industry tout the apparent health benefits of wine on
its labels.
</P>
<P>
   But industry experts and bottlers said Monday that they were
nonetheless confident that planned hearings on the program would
put the issue of labeling to rest for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think an educated public is better than an uneducated
public. The scientific community's research is really going to be
our response,'' said John De Luca, president of the Wine Institute,
a San Francisco-based association that represents more than 500
members in California.
</P>
<P>
   Yielding to pressure from Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms for the time being put the
cork on the 10-month-old practice of permitting wine labels to
allude to the apparent healthful benefits of wine. The agency plans
hearings on the labeling next year.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond, the liquor industry's most outspoken and powerful
congressional critic, has been fighting the wine industry over
labeling for years, introducing legislation to prevent the
marketing ploy and, at one point, accusing the Wine Institute and
senior government officials of conspiring to manipulate government
nutritional guidelines to promote the sale of alcohol based on its
health benefits. Thurmond's daughter was killed by a drunken
driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ill effects of alcohol are well documented,'' Thurmond
said in his response to the ATF's latest directive. ``The
government should not dilute the negative repercussions of alcohol
consumption by allowing labels which may confuse the public.''
</P>
<P>
   De Luca said the policy to allow the labels has been precarious
since the ATF approved it in February for the J. Lohr and Laurel
Glen wineries. Officials with ATF made clear at the time that they
intended to hold public hearings that could result in a change of
policy, De Luca said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the ATF has approved 98 labels for 17 wineries.
Those wineries will be permitted to use their labels, but what will
happen to future applicants will likely be determined after the
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Although studies show that moderate wine drinking is associated
with reduced risk of heart attack, the labels are not permitted to
make explicit health claims. Instead, they generally refer
consumers to their doctors or suggest they send away for the
government's ``Dietary Guidelines for Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The dietary guidelines, under lobbying from California's $6.3
billion-a-year wine industry, were revised in 1995 to become more
wine-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   They now include the point that ``alcoholic beverages have been
used to enhance the enjoyment of meals by many societies throughout
human history,'' as well as a reference to the health-benefit
claims.
</P>
<P>
   De Luca said he was unsure how many wineries were intending to
get label approval from ATF when the freeze was imposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
