<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEDERAL GOVERNMENT HAS BEATEN Y2K BUG, CLINTON SAYS
 &HT;    260&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton congratulated federal workers
Tuesday for ridding the government of virtually all Y2K computer
bugs that threatened operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done our job,'' he said, citing a new Y2K report by
the White House's Office of Management and Budget showing that 99.7
percent of ``mission-critical'' computers have been cleared of
bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton predicted the year rollover will produce only
``glitches'' that can be handled through backup plans now in place.
</P>
<P>
   The president's optimism was supported by the 11th and final OMB
quarterly report on the Y2K bug, a software flaw that could cause
some older computers to read only the last two digits of the date.
That seemingly small flaw could cause many computers to malfunction
or shut down on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   OMB said U.S. agencies have completed work on 6,159 computerized
systems critical to fulfilling the government's obligations. Only
16 systems are still being fixed, but that work will be completed
by the year-end deadline. A government computer that generates,
say, a holiday greeting to staff is not considered ``critical,''
while one that issues Social Security checks is.
</P>
<P>
   Also speaking Tuesday, the president's Y2K czar, John Koskinen,
told the National Press Club that because major industries ``are
basically done with their Y2K work ... we do not expect to see
major national failures'' in key sectors, such as power generation,
telecommunications or transportation.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen himself seemed amazed at the surge of good reports on
Y2K. ``Serious people, two years ago, maintained there was no way
we would finish the work in time'' to avoid nightmares caused by
malfunctioning computers, he said. When he started heading the
President's Council on Year 2000 Conversion in February 1998, many
members of Congress were critical of the administration's Y2K
preparations. ``The consensus was that the government wouldn't make
it,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the World Bank said at the time that three-fourths
of the world's countries had not even begun to think about Y2K
problems. ``In short, the problem looked too mammoth, too
complicated and too interconnected to be solvable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What changed was that ``top management'' in both government and
private businesses finally realized that the problem was serious.
By spraying the bug with about $100 billion in labor and equipment,
U.S. government and industry leaders made dramatic progress in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his optimism, Koskinen predicted that ``the transition
to the new century will not be perfect.'' Some small businesses,
health care facilities and schools have been too slow to fix
problems, he said. A number of developing countries also are not
prepared for the date rollover.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Americans to prepare for a few days of potential
disruptions in business routines. So, for example, families should
make sure they get their prescriptions up-to-date and have some
ready-to-eat meals on hand in case they have to stay home in the
early days of 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
