<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SLAVE-LABOR (Berlin) _ After months of bitter
negotiations, German industry and government officials agreed
Tuesday to establish a fund of roughly 10 billion marks or $5.1
billion to compensate slave laborers during the Nazi regime. Though
some details remained fuzzy Tuesday evening, German negotiators
reluctantly agreed to increase what they had insisted was their
final offer _ 8 billion marks. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL (Panama) _ Eighty-six years of American power and
presence along the shores of the Panama Canal symbolically ended
Tuesday when former President Jimmy Carter exchanged diplomatic
notes with President Mireya Moscoso and said simply, ``It's
yours.'' With those words began a new era in Panamanian life, a
journey that began in 1977 when Carter and Gen. Omar Torrijos
signed the controversial accords that would give Panama full
territorial sovereignty and total responsibility for the canal.
Moscoso pledged to meet the immense challenges that come with the
treaty, which she praised a model for the peaceful resolution of
international conflicts. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Washington) _ Israelis do not stand on ceremony
or bow to courtesy. But, in an unprecedented show of support, 21
out of 22 of Prime Minister Ehud Barak's often squabbling Cabinet
ministers saw him off at Ben Gurion Airport when he flew here
Tuesday to resume Israel's negotiations with Syria. There couldn't
have been a clearer demonstration of how Israelis _ like many
others in the Middle East _ perceive the import of the moment. It
is a moment of truth, as they see it, and it can be felt in the
air. A news analysis by Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photos (NYT6, 8)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, trying to
bolster support for his opposition movement in Russia's
parliamentary election on Sunday and for a possible run for the
presidency next year, roared defiance at Kremlin leaders today and
urged voters to reject candidates linked to them. By Celestine
Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Hours before the Security Council
was to vote on a new arms inspection system for Iraq on Tuesday,
France suddenly asked to stop the clock, calling for more talks
among council members on a resolution that has been under
discussion for more than six months. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NKOREA (Tokyo) _ In a move that could help North Korea
feed its hungry people this winter, the Japanese government said
Tuesday that it would lift restrictions on food aid to the
Communist country and begin formal negotiations to establish
diplomatic relations. In announcing the lifting of sanctions,
Japan's chief Cabinet secretary, Mikio Aoki, said Japan and North
Korea planned to hold preliminary talks by the end of the year. By
Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-WHITMAN (Washington) _ It once seemed that the word
failure was not a part of Bill Bradley's lexicon. He had been a
Rhodes Scholar, Olympic gold medalist, two-time NBA champion and,
on his first foray into politics in 1978, the winner of a Senate
seat from New Jersey. In 1984, he won re-election by one of the
largest margins in state history. So in 1990, when Bradley came
within 3 percentage points of losing his once safe bastion to an
unknown, poorly financed Republican named Christie Whitman, he was
devastated. To many of his critics and supporters alike, the
disastrous 1990 campaign _ both sides use the adjective _
represents the most important event in Bradley's political life. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-HEALTH (Charleston, S.C.) _ Sen. John McCain on Tuesday
set out a plan of ``tailored reforms'' of the health care system,
ranging from a federal block grant to help elderly people with
lower incomes pay for prescription drugs to a limited right to sue
health maintenance organizations. McCain's speech to the Charleston
Rotary Club marked an effort to capitalize on his surge in New
Hampshire by beginning to set out detailed positions on social
issues. Health care, and most particularly the soaring costs of
prescription drugs, has emerged as one of the hottest topics on the
campaign trail this year and it is a policy arena that so far has
largely been dominated by Democrats. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
