   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-TRIAL (Ellicott City, Md.) _ A Maryland judge on Tuesday
dealt a severe setback to Linda Tripp as she faces trial on
criminal charges for secretly tape-recording telephone
conversations with Monica Lewinsky that led to last year's
impeachment drama. Judge Diane O. Leasure ruled that the immunity
conferred on Mrs. Tripp by federal prosecutors in the independent
counsel's office investigating Clinton did not prevent Maryland
from bringing a prosecution for violating state wiretap laws. The
agreement only prevented the state from using information gathered
by the federal prosecutors after the immunity took effect. More
importantly, Leasure also ruled that immunity was not conferred on
Mrs. Tripp on Jan. 16, 1998, as she and the prosecutors believed.
That was the day that Mrs. Tripp turned over to the prosecutor's
office a handful of tape recordings of her conversations with Ms.
Lewinsky and received in exchange a letter from Jackie Bennett
saying she had immunity. Instead, the judge said that the immunity
did not make effect until Feb. 19, when a federal judge confirmed
the immunity agreement in a formal court order. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TRANSIT (New York) _ As union and transit officials
negotiated feverishly Tuesday in the hope of averting a shutdown of
New York City's buses and subways, the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority and the Giuliani administration obtained injunctions that
would impose draconian fines on the union if it strikes.
Developing. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
