<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILLENNIUM MOON WON'T BE MUCH
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Call it the Millennium Moon, but don't look for too
much.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual combination of orbital mechanics will bring a full
moon into one of its closest approaches to Earth on Dec. 22, a time
when both will be closer than usual to the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers say the effect, though rare, won't look particularly
impressive. If there were some way to put the Dec. 22 full moon
next to an ``ordinary'' full moon, they said, the human eye would
be unable to tell which was brighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not be a torch in the sky, lighting up the night,''
said Yale University astronomer Bradley Schaefer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people will not notice the difference,'' said research
scientist Ed Barker of the University of Texas's McDonald
Observatory in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the dates and distances:
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 winter solstice, the point at which the Earth's north
pole is tilted away from the sun at the greatest angle, will occur
at 5:44 a.m. EST on that day. Sixteen minutes later, at 6 a.m., the
moon's orbit will be at perigee, the point closest to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The distance between the two bodies at that time will be about
213,992 miles. The average distance is about 230,641 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The moon will be full a few hours later, at 12:31 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Earth-moon system, which also swings farther and
closer to the sun during the 365-day orbit, will be at
``perihelion,'' the point closest to the sun, on Jan 3.
</P>
<P>
   The three events _ moon perigee, Earth perihelion and a full
moon _ don't occur often, only once in about every 133 years.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the greater proximity to the Earth, the moon will
appear to be about 16 percent larger than normal that night.
</P>
<P>
   However, that happens several times every year, whenever the
full moon coincides with the moon's closest approach to the Earth
once every 27 days, Schaefer said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barker and Schaefer said they received a widely distributed
e-mail message describing the upcoming full moon in dramatic terms.
On a snow-covered terrain, the message declares, the moon will
appear so bright that car headlights will seem ``superfluous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, it's just trivia,'' Schaefer said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
