<SLUG> BC-WEB-JOURNALISM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I WRITE COPY FOR A WEB START-UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DEIRDRE SHAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, I abandoned the sinking ship of newspaper
journalism and hopped aboard a pirate vessel, the Internet. Instead
of writing news for a venerable newspaper, I'm now providing
content for a Silicon Alley start-up founded by two 20-somethings.
</P>
<P>
   My fellow reporters and I often grumbled about the long hours,
low pay and humdrum assignments at the Philadelphia daily where we
toiled on the suburban beat. Yet, when I told them where I was
going and added that, yes, at the tender age of 27, I'd be
receiving stock options, I saw sellout in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Sellout? Maybe. But in journalism, you have to work your way up
the ladder for years. Your bosses have worked their way up the
ladder. You put in time at newspapers in states like Iowa and
Louisiana, and then maybe you have a shot at a staff job on a
newspaper in New York or San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In the new economy, if you're smart and confident, you don't
have to wait in line. You can be whatever you want to be. There are
no ladders and no pigeonholes.
</P>
<P>
   My new bosses at InfoRocket, an online information-auction
company where users pay other users for answers to their questions,
seemed excited about my arrival. Experiment with the copy, they
told me. We trust you.
</P>
<P>
   So I admit it: I was probably rubbing it in when I told my
newspaper friends that InfoRocket's co-founder, Matt Cassin, 24,
was wearing shorts during my interview. And that irreverent
employees had scrawled site models and quotes like ``Revolt Against
Time'' in black ink on the office's white walls. (I later learned
this was because the walls were to be torn down.)
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just the casual atmosphere that struck me; what
bowled me over was the sheer energy of the place. People were
coming and going, banging away furiously at the keyboards, shouting
across rooms. At one point, Teo Montoya, 25, the other co-founder,
stumbled into the room unshaven and disheveled. He had been up all
night writing code, but that didn't stop him from sitting down with
me for an hour to talk about everything from my favorite movies to
the ``new information paradigms.''
</P>
<P>
   I hate to say it, but the hectic pace made me wonder if this
Internet start-up didn't resemble a newsroom back in the heyday of
newspapers. I belonged here, I told myself.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't have a computer or a desk for the first three days, and
it took even longer to get a telephone. But on my first day the
company ordered pizza and my 13 colleagues and I sat around the
conference table. ``OK, team,'' said Matt. ``How is everything
going? Do we need to discuss anything?''
</P>
<P>
   We really didn't, but we did anyway. I was forced to reveal my
most embarrassing moment. (Losing my bathing suit while
water-skiing, if you must know.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm hard at work planning the e-mail newsletter I'll
eventually be writing for our users. ``I have lots of ideas,'' I
say. ``We'll take 'em,'' my colleagues reply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-LATINOS-POLICE15-COX     12-14 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINOS-POLICE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LATINO GROUPS URGE ADDING MORE HISPANIC POLICE OFFICERS
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Putting more Hispanic police officers on the
streets could mean a drop in racial profiling and law enforcement
abuse of Latinos, Hispanic organization urged Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos remain severely under-represented in most major police
departments across the country, and not just within the top ranks,
but among the rank and file as well,'' said Adrian Garcia, national
president for the National Latino Peace Officers Association.
</P>
<P>
   A November study released by the National Council of La Raza
found that Latinos hold less than 8 percent of supervisory
positions in law enforcement in Houston, a city that is more than
one-fourth Hispanic. In Los Angeles, a city more than one-third
Hispanic, 22 percent of police officers and 14 percent of law
enforcement supervisors were Latino.
</P>
<P>
   The study also reported that the number of complaints received
by the National Council of La Raza on racial profiling and law
enforcement harassment of Hispanic Americans has nearly tripled in
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamental to stemming the dramatic increase in civil rights
violations against Latinos is restoring the trust between law
enforcement and the Hispanic community,'' said Raul Yzaguirre,
president of the National Council of La Raza.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Tuesday, the National Council of La Raza,
the Hispanic American Police Command Officers Association and the
National Latino Peace Officers announced a partnership to address
the issues of Latino- related racial profiling, police harassment,
and the lack of Latino law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership will also address the lack of statistical data
on the incidents of racial profiling against Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although racial profiling of African Americans has received a
great deal of media attention, its impact on Latinos has not been
as widely reported,'' said Rachel King, legislative council for the
American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the ACLU sponsored anti-profiling bills in 20
different states. King said that several statistical collection
bills and anti-profiling bills have been introduced in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   King said that people can report incidents of racial profiling
or police harassment to the ACLU's racial profiling national
hotline at 1-877-6-PROFILE, or on line at
http://www.aclu.org/profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schultz's e-mail address is sues(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
