<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WESTWING-2TAKES-NY     12-14 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WESTWING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: DOES THE MUSH KEEP BRAINS AFLOAT ON TV? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can a television series be uncompromising and successful at
once? Since its much-hyped premiere three months ago, ``The West
Wing'' has developed a distinct style that suggests the answer is a
chilling ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   With its acerbic sense of politics and its Mighty Mouse hero of
a president, the show is ``Wag the Dog'' meets Frank Capra. That
collision of styles has made it the smartest, most tantalizing,
most maddening new drama in a season full of them.
</P>
<P>
   And the series' split personality points to an issue about
television's possibilities and limitations. A solid though not a
spectacular ratings success, artistically ``The West Wing'' towers
over the junkier dramas that litter the television landscape,
including several that began the season with promise. Yet it
consistently undermines its own ambition, as if it doesn't dare
trust the audience to grapple with realism and ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   That seems self-defeating, since the show is most absorbing when
it is most complex and sardonic. There are a few fundamental truths
that the White House staff in ``The West Wing'' live by. As the
deputy communications director (played by Rob Lowe) put one of
them: ``There's two kinds of trouble here: actual trouble and PR
trouble.'' Everyone knows that a public relations disaster is the
most serious problem of all.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday night's episode (NBC at 9) the staff deals with
both kinds, debating the merits of a hate crime bill spurred by the
murder of a gay 17-year-old and dealing with the threat that a
Republican political opponent will reveal that the chief of staff
was once addicted to prescription drugs. They consider a little
pre-emptive blackmail. Maybe a helpful prostitute they know could
reveal the names of some Republican clients?
</P>
<P>
   But in case all this seems too cynically realistic, the
communications director goes to exceptional, unpublicized lengths
to arrange an Arlington funeral for a homeless veteran; the
president's secretary reveals she lost not one but twin sons during
the war in Vietnam; and as the show tosses realism aside
completely, the president goes Christmas shopping and refuses to
let the press tag along for a photo op.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way the series has evolved through the season. It
has enhanced its strengths, presenting a tough-minded sense of the
dizzying pace, the compromises, the high-stakes bluffs and
strong-arm tactics of politics. Yet in every episode there is the
big Television Moment when President Josiah Bartlett, played by
Martin Sheen with such windbag bluster it's a wonder he ever got a
vote, enters and makes a rousing ideological speech. He is a deus
ex president arriving from fantasyland.
</P>
<P>
   What the show says about politics is addressed to a smart
audience; yet its emotional mushiness suggests a fear that the
audience cannot deal with ambiguity unless it is countered by the
sop of inspirational uplift. And in strictly commercial terms, that
premise may not be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sorkin, who created ``The West Wing,'' also created
``Sports Night,'' the riskiest show on television. Freshly blending
drama and wit, ``Sports Night,'' set behind the scenes of a
television sports show, defies audience expectations and has
struggled in the ratings so severely that ABC now seems to have it
on life support. President Bartlett may exist to save ``The West
Wing'' from itself, making it palatable enough to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Even with its compromises, ``The West Wing'' has turned out to
be the best the season's new dramas. ``Once and Again,'' ABC's
40-something show about divorce, has become so earnest that
watching it is like enduring a therapy session. ``Now and Again''
on CBS offers some charm in the romantic plot about a middle-aged
man in a hot young body pining for his wife; yet he is asked to do
government spying that gives the series a hokey aura.
</P>
<P>
   And though CBS's ``Judging Amy'' is consistently engaging, its
aspirations are not as high as those of ``The West Wing.'' If ``The
West Wing'' is loaded with realism undercut by mawkishness, ``Amy''
turns that pattern upside down. As a judge with a small daughter
who returns to live with her own mother, Amy Brenneman is at the
center of many expected heart-tugging moments; but that formula is
undercut by the kinds of family squabbles that link the show to
reality and give it a bracing air.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing'' is ambitious enough to be measured against its
own aspirations rather than the low level of drama that surrounds
it. The show came closest to fulfilling its potential a month into
its run with an episode about a White House attempt to pass a gun
control bill. At the last minute the staff lost five crucial votes.
``How do we get five votes without giving away everything in the
store?,'' wonders Sam Seaborn (Lowe's character).
</P>
<P>
   Josh Lyman, the deputy chief of staff (played by Bradley
Whitford with such nuanced thoughtfulness that he has become one of
the show's most believable characters) begins manipulating
congressmen. He threatens to run another Democrat against one of
them in the next primary. In the end, the president's people win
but feel as if they've lost: they've spent too much political
capital; the arm-twisting will cause a backlash; it was a
watered-down bill anyway; the hated, distrusted vice president gets
credit on CNN for saving the bill. (There's actual trouble and PR
trouble.)
</P>
<P>
   The texture of the series works in smaller ways, too. When
Josh's assistant mentions that the Republicans want to give back
the budget surplus by lowering taxes, she asks, ``Why don't  &UR; we &LR; 
want to give it back?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cause we're Democrats,'' he says, delivering the line with a
deadpan look and a wry tone that reveals how subtly Whitford has
created Josh's character.
</P>
<P>
   This inside view makes the White House staff human, flawed,
intriguing. The chief of staff, Leo McGarry (John Spencer), is a
recovering alcoholic whose marriage has just broken up because he
is too absorbed in his work. The press secretary, C.J. Gregg
(Allison Janney), is breezily efficient but real enough to consider
dating a reporter despite the obvious conflict of interest. The
Lowe character can't seem to escape silly plot twists: first he
unknowingly slept with a hooker, then he arranged a doomed date
with the chief of staff's daughter. But even he is a more credible
character than the president.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When the president invites his staff to eat chili with him one
night, he offers a toast that invokes the days of John F. Kennedy
and the space race. ``What will be the next thing to challenge
us,'' he says, music swelling in the background, ``that makes us go
farther and work harder, as we did in the time when our eyes looked
toward the heavens and with outstretched fingers we touched the
face of God.'' That is typical presidential conversation in ``The
West Wing,'' though you'd think he'd save it for the State of the
Union address. It is an accident of timing that the swirl of
current pop cultural references includes Andy Kaufman (the subject
of a new film) lip-synching to the old Mighty Mouse theme, but that
is what comes to mind when this cartoon president steps in to save
the day.
</P>
<P>
   An episode about selecting a new Supreme Court justice begins
with acerbic wit when the Ivy League-educated Peyton Cabot Harrison
III accepts the president's offer to be nominated. ``You know what
we're finally going to have?'' an ecstatic Josh asks his assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``WASPy old man on the Supreme Court?'' she answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A smooth confirmation process,'' he insists.
</P>
<P>
   But despite a monthslong vetting process, Harrison is done in by
a 30-year-old, anonymously written footnote in a law journal that
suggests he might not protect privacy rights. In a flash he is
replaced by a Hispanic judge, Roberto Mendoza (Edward James Olmos),
who began his career as a police officer injured on duty and then
went to law school at night. The president hands Mendoza the
nomination with a dramatic flourish. ``Tomorrow evening at 5
o'clock I am naming you as my nominee to be the next associate
justice of the Supreme Court,'' he says. (What, no three-month
checks on him? Wouldn't they be doubly cautious this time?) ``Let
the good fight begin,'' the president says as Mendoza walks out of
his office and, of course, the music swells.
</P>
<P>
   And when a hurricane hits off the coast of Virginia and traps a
Navy fleet, the president leaves a state dinner and promises to
stay on the phone with a lowly radio operator named Harold ``as
long as the radio works,'' he says. (Or until Harold drowns,
whichever comes first.)
</P>
<P>
   The first lady (Stockard Channing) is there holding his hand,
reassuring him he can't stop hurricanes. Her character has not been
seen much so far, but she has a significant role. This is a
cultural moment when Gail Sheehy is promoting her biography of
Hillary Rodham Clinton by recounting how she reacted to news of her
husband's affair with Monica Lewinsky. The real first lady,
according to Ms. Sheehy, hauled off and hit the president, calling
him stupid. This may or may not be true (the book's research has
been widely challenged) but it suggests how much nostalgia and
fantasy is involved in the Bartletts, whose very names, Abigail and
Josiah, reek of America's Puritan past.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they are meant to be comforting, but audiences know
better. This season, one of the characters on ``Sports Night''
rejects a suggestion from an executive because it implies ``the
audience is not as smart as we are.'' If ``Sports Night'' has
trusted its audience, ``The West Wing'' seems to have taken all the
network advice it can. If the best parts of the series keep us
coming back, the mushy undercurrent keeps us tearing our hair at
the end, frustrated that a show with such ambition is so fearful of
its own brainy realism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1722EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
