<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8744 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MILLION-MOMS-MARCH-HN     12-14 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-MOMS-MARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROLS ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   MOMS PLAN MARCH TO TRIGGER NEW (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By JUDY HOLLAND   
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Outraged by gun violence that has killed or wounded
children, thousands of mothers across the country are organizing
what they hope will be a ``Million Mom March'' aimed at pressuring
Congress to enact tougher controls on firearms.
</P>
<P>
   They intend to arrive in the nation's capital for a march on May
14th, Mother's Day, a holiday that originated during the Civil War
to remind women to take care of each other's wounded sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want common sense gun laws in this country that make it
less easy for the criminally insane or for children to get guns,''
said the founder of the march, Donna Dees-Thomases of West
Caldwell, N.J., a part-time publicist for comedian David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that the mothers' march will mobilize enough mothers
to do for irresponsible gun ownership what the MADD mothers did for
drunk driving,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   MADD, the organization of Mothers Against Drunk Driving, has
raised public awareness about the issue. Many states have recently
lowered the level of blood-alcohol that defines drunk driving.
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases says the Aug. 10th shootings at the North Valley
Jewish Community Center in Los Angeles _ where a young man with a 9
mm Uzi killed a postal worker and wounded five people , including
three little boys _ persuaded her it was time to stand up to the
powerful gun lobby. She also cited the April 20th massacre at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., in which two teen-agers
shot to death 12 students and one teacher before the youths killed
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases said her campaign is intended to make gun policy
an issue in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about enlightenment,'' she said. ``Mothers are finding
out how their congressmen have voted on gun policy... We want to
put this right in their faces. The time for compromise is over.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the mothers are pushing for:
</P>
<P>
   _Extensive background checks and ``cooling-off periods'' of 14
to 30 days for people who want to buy guns.
</P>
<P>
   _Federal licensing of gun owners and registration of guns.
</P>
<P>
   _Safety locks on all handguns and loaded chamber indicators.
</P>
<P>
   _ A limit on handgun purchases of one per month.
</P>
<P>
   Leading gun control advocates in Congress such as Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., claim that their legislative agenda has been
thwarted by the political clout of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   One key part of that agenda, the Juvenile Justice Bill, was
approved last June in the House and the Senate. However, differing
versions of the measure have been mired in a conference committee
convened to merge the two bills.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation contains a ban on the import of high-capacity
ammunition clips, a provision to encourage gun manufacturers to
include trigger locks, a ban on juvenile possession of assault
weapons and a provision to require background checks for any
firearm sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases said her group welcomes others besides mothers,
but chose moms to start with because ``there's something safe and
comforting about mothers' getting together.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the ``Million Mom March'' is a word-of-mouth effort
financed by sales of baked goods and T-shirts and is gaining
members who visit her website www.millionmommarch.com or call
1-888-989-6667.
</P>
<P>
   Dees-Thomases has enlisted a fleet of volunteers such as Gail
Powers, a North Ridge, Calif., mother of two, whose then-4-year-old
son Nathan was at the North Valley Jewish Community Center during
the August shootings and emerged unhurt but badly shaken.
</P>
<P>
   Powers said after the shootings, her son ``was afraid of
everything. If there ever was a sound and he couldn't see how it
was being made, it was a trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was somebody who did not know the nature of gun violence,''
Powers said. ``We are hoping to open peoples' eyes up to what
people and children are doing with guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Another volunteer is Spring Venema, an Otsego, Mich., mother of
two whose father-in-law was killed in a robbery of his home.
</P>
<P>
   Venema, a graphic arts coordinator at a pharmaceutical company,
said she has never been involved in politics before but has taken a
public speaking class and spends three hours a night contacting
potential marchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could save one family from going through what mine went
through, it would be worth it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she has taken plenty of ``guff'' from gun owners who
have called her names, but she says she won't give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like confrontation,'' she said. ``I'm a peaceful
person. I am doing this because I love my children. I'm just going
to stand my ground because I think it's right. I'll never stop
working on this until this goal is set. It's a lifelong
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
