<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8750 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-SIMPATICO-REVIEW     12-14 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SIMPATICO-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PARTIAL REDEMPTION IN `SIMPATICO'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: fact box at bottom) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thin, fragile line between success and failure is one of
playwright Sam Shepard's career-long obsessions. So it's ironically
fitting that Matthew Warchus' movie version of Shepard's sly
horse-racing fable ``Simpatico'' should straddle that line with the
precarious balance of a nervous jockey on derby day, until at last
it slips clean off the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simpatico,'' which is making a one-week Oscar-qualifying run,
is a misfire. But it's an honorable, intelligent misfire from a
promising rookie director who hasn't quite found a way to fully
translate Shepard's lean, lyrical stagecraft into naturalistic
cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the film's awkward stretches are partially redeemed by its
gutsy if not always laugh-proof lead performances, by the jagged
poetry of John Tolls' cinematography, and by Stewart Copeland's
abstract country-western score, which almost single-handedly
elevates the stumbling screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough for you? Don't forget that in Shepard's mytho-poetic
America of fallen dreamers and ambitions that got off on the wrong
foot, partial redemption is about the best a body can hope for.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly more than what we first expect for Vinnie (Nick
Nolte), a broken-down barfly living out near Cucamonga, where's
he's been nursing a guilty conscience and a busted love affair for
decades. Seems that in the course of a generally reckless youth,
Vinnie, his erstwhile best friend Carter (Jeff Bridges), and Rosie
(Sharon Stone), the girl they both loved, hatched a get-rich plan
of switching slow racing horses for fast ones, then betting the
high odds.
</P>
<P>
   When a California racing commissioner named Simms (played with
raffish elegance by Albert Finney) caught onto the act, the trio
hatched a blackmail plan to shut him up, using Rosie as bait.
</P>
<P>
   But while their ill-gotten gains helped Carter grow up to become
a millionaire thoroughbred breeder, with a plush Kentucky homestead
and Rosie (now his wife) among his leggy trophies, Vinnie backslid
into alcoholism and depression. Simms also was driven from racing
by the scandal, the juicy Polaroid evidence of which Vinnie has
preserved in a cardboard box.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, as the movie begins, Vinnie has come up with
a payback scheme that involves luring Carter to California and
confronting both Rosie and Simms, who has managed to put his past
behind him and start a new life under an assumed name. By one of
several plot twists that make little dramatic sense, Vinnie's
scheming also inadvertently drags in his only friend, Cecilia.
Cecilia's a loopy but self-possessed supermarket checkout girl
(Catherine Keener), who despite being saddled with some horribly
awkward dialogue, gradually emerges as one of those intriguing
eccentrics in the Shepard mold.
</P>
<P>
   As the story tracks the men's disparate paths toward
self-discovery, the cunning, feral Vinnie and the smooth,
domesticated Carter seem to be swapping identities, like the rival
brothers in Shepard's ``True West.'' Warchus, a British theater
director best-known for helming the international hit play ``Art,''
has a sure feel for this cat-and-mouse dynamic, as do Nolte and
Bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Warchus and screenwriter David Nicholls also have come up with
the bright idea of reconstructing the circa-1970 flashbacks of the
horse-racing scam using youthful versions of Vinnie, Carter and
Rosie. The ardency of the three young actors who play the
principals' foolhardy former selves _ Shawn Hatosy, Liam Waite and
Kimberly Williams _ helps make these sequences among the movie's
most effective.
</P>
<P>
   The film's pictorial beauty, however, is nearly overwhelmed by
the tin-eared platitudes, as when Carter waxes to Cecilia about a
horse's ``rippling muscles'' as a thing ``beyond seduction, beyond
lust.'' The film slips into even more overstatement when Stone
makes her belated first appearance as the disheveled, boozing
Rosie, unleashing her inner demons with every slurred consonant.
It's not Stone's fault that she appears to have strolled in from a
Tennessee Williams play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simpatico'' is named for the beautiful, aging Triple
Crown-winning stallion that Carter is about to sell. As potentially
heavy-handed as that symbolism is, here it makes a potent metaphor
for Shepard's vision of the receding macho frontier, in which a
stud is usually another name for a former champion who doesn't know
his best days are over. &QL; 
____ &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR; !off! ``Simpatico'' (R; strong sexuality and language). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR; !off! Nick Nolte, Jeff Bridges, Sharon Stone, Albert
Finney. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR; !off! Directed by Matthew Warchus. Written by
Warchus and David Nicholls, based upon Sam Shepard's play.
Photography by John Toll. Released by Fine Line Features. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time:!off! &LR;  One hour, 46 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Playing: &LR; !off! AMC Century 14 in Century City for one-week Academy
Award-qualifying run. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR; !off! 2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
