</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-WEB _ LOS ANGELES _ The Western Show opens in Los Angeles
today and the show's theme is the convergence of cable TV
technology with the Internet. A growing number of cable TV
operators such as Cox Communications are using their new digital
networks to provide Internet access at high speeds. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BLINDSHOPPERS _ Crowded stores, long lines and short tempers _
it's another hectic holiday season. But if getting from one packed
department store to the next isn't already a challenge, shoppers
who need an extra set of eyes to help them navigate face an even
tougher situation. (Schatz, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   INNOVATION _ AUSTIN, Texas _ OK, they need to work on the name _
ToolBelt 98-11 _ but local software developer AMicuys has an
interesting way to keep securities brokers from saying things in
e-mails that will get them in trouble. Think ``this is a sure
thing'' and ``guaranteed to pay off.'' (Park, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CCE-CHANGES _ ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Enterprises announced more
management changes as President and Chief Executive Officer Henry
Schimberg prepares to leave the company. The Coke system's largest
bottler named four new senior vice presidents, including a new
special assistant to the chief executive officer. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-BUMPING _ Delta cut its involuntary bumping rates during
the third quarter but still led the industry for the first 9 months
of the year, according to the latest Air Travel Consumer Report
from the DOT. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   MOTIVE-DELL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Motive Communiations Inc. is
spinning off a new company that will focus on offering tech support
to small and home businesses. Dell Computer is putting an
undisclosed amount into the new company, called all.com Inc.
(Hawkins, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   AUTONATION _ AutoNation's management and overhead problems
doomed its used-car superstores, analysts say, but the company
still is far and away the nation's biggest auto retailer. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 1214 _ Saab, not content with making its 9-3 line
of cars one that wins praise for practicality, safety and pricing,
has moved squarely into the performance arena with its 2000 Viggen.
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 3-column color
photo of 2000 Saab Viggen and 1-column color photo of car's
interior dash.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 2000 Saab Viggen.
</P>
<P>
   THE MECHANIC _ Grandma's cars, her escape machines, carried her
through a century of adventure. (Carter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). Includes 1-column color photograph of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ The average cost of a wedding in 1997 was slightly
more than $19,000. That includes the reception, rings and some of
the small stuff. (Invitations and other correspondence averaged
$327; the bride's headpiece added another $166.) All this
ceremonial profligacy takes place around a young couple who may
well be carrying college loan debt and who probably have no way to
buy a house or otherwise start moving their joined lives ahead.
Suppose you rearrange your wedding budget? Frugality at the altar
is not a new idea. People are marrying later these days, and it is
more common for the bride and groom to split expenses with their
parents. That certainly encourages careful budgeting and spending.
Other tips and websites. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BE-AEROSPACE _ B/E Aerospace loses $66 million, or $2.66 a
share, in the third quarter. Its seating business has had
production problems that everybody knows about and the company has
been unable to correct. Still, its other aircraft component
businesses are sound, including its galley products group which has
a plant in Delray Beach, Fla. We're wondering if investors will
take the stock down another notch. (Pounds, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-KPN _ATLANTA _ BellSouth announced a clever deal last
week that will eventually give it a large stake in Dutch company
KPN Telecom _ without spending any money. The arrangement, praised
as savvy by analysts and the business press, was touted excitedly
by BellSouth as a way to boost its stock value. KPN stock has
soared, but investors stateside have yawned at BellSouth. Why? Did
BellSouth oversell this? Where does it leave the company? And where
does it lead? (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
