<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8765 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GUN-LAWSUIT-1STLD-WRI     12-14 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-LAWSUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL, LOCAL OFFICIALS VOW FIGHT AGAINST GUN MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Updates with NRA comment in 11th graf and fixes last graf,
updating status of lawsuits.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking the next step in a potential federal lawsuit
against gun manufacturers, senior administration officials met here
with 17 city and county officials Tuesday and vowed to fight for
safer firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo and Bruce
Reed, President Clinton's point man on gun policy, said at a news
conference that the meeting had produced the outlines of a unified
stance that local and federal officials will take to the gun
industry ``over the next days.''
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the threatened class-action lawsuit that HUD would
launch through 3,200 housing authorities across the country is to
force the manufacturers to produce safer guns and new business
practices that would guard against shady dealers.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco City Attorney Louise Renne expressed outrage at
the easy access many children have to guns and said she was buoyed
by the federal lawsuit threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who are here from California and have been very
actively involved in this ... wouldn't have traveled across the
country if we didn't believe that this administration and Secretary
Cuomo were serious,'' Renne said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``The time is now for the gun manufacturers to step
up to the plate and be serious because we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said the federal and local officials had ``agreed to stand
together ... to ensure that the gun industry takes responsibility
for its share of the violence'' that has wracked public housing
projects over the last few years. Flanked by the local officials
and a representative from the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, Cuomo said the group intends to
``reach our goals through negotiations'' but is ``wholly prepared
to go to litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who is also President Clinton's domestic policy adviser,
said he will meet with the state attorneys general from New York
and Connecticut on Wednesday about the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than seeking monetary compensation, HUD wants gun makers
to crack down on disreputable dealers and make safer guns that
can't be fired by children. The administration also wants gun
makers to agree to end practices such as marketing weapons that are
impervious to fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   James J. Baker, the National Rifle Association's top lobbyist,
said the municipalities and the White House ``are getting
desperate'' after judges recently threw out lawsuits brought by the
cities of Bridgeport, Conn., Miami and Cincinnati against gun
makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to threaten the full force of power of the
federal government to get from the gun companies concessions'' that
should be legislated by Congress, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal-local coalition effort is distinct from lawsuits
that 28 cities have filed against gun manufacturers seeking
monetary damages and changes in the ways guns are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Although judges have dismissed the Bridgeport, Miami and
Cincinnati lawsuits, another judge has allowed one filed by Atlanta
to proceed and has ordered the industry to open its files.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
