<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8788 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-SPOT-BJT15-COX     12-14 1733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, Dec. 15,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds. Adds: REACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL _ PANAMA CITY, Panama _ The Panamanian government
holds a celebration, with Latin American leaders in attendance,
commemorating the hand-over of the Panama Canal. But Panamanians
are bothered by the fact that neither President Clinton nor
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright saw the event as important
enough to attend. Bad enough the United States lorded it over them
for decades, now this insult. Developing. (Williams, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 6 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ WASHINGTON _ A walk-up to the first round of
talks between Israel and Syria in nearly fours years. Once again,
the United States has stepped to the forefront in negotiating a
peace in the Middle East by hosting this high-level meeting. Will
the investment pay off? What's at stake for President Clinton,
global peacemaker? What do they hope to accomplish? U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright has described it as just an
ice-breaking meeting. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move 6 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-HOMES _ WASHINGTON Nursing homes that harm patients,
either through abuse or neglect, may be fined under new rules
issued by the federal government Tuesday. If those rules had been
in effect last year, 12 percent of the nation's 17,000 nursing
homes would have been fined, said Nancy-Ann DeParle, head of the
Health Care Financing Administration. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   LATINOS-POLICE _ WASHINGTON _ Representatives of the National
Council of La Raza, the National Latino Peace Officers Association
and the Hispanic American Police Command Officers Association
announce a partnership to address racial profiling, law enforcement
abuses and the number of Latinos in law enforcement. (Schultz, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-MOON _ WASHINGTON _ Call it the Millennium Moon. An
unusual confluence of orbital dynamics will produce the brightest
full moon of the 20th century on Dec. 22, the day after the winter
solstice. Because the moon on that night will be near its
``perigee'' _ the closest its slightly out-of-round orbit brings it
to the Earth _ it will appear slightly larger than normal. However,
the earth-moon system will also be near the ``perihelion'' point,
the orbital position that takes the Earth closest to the sun,
sunlight reflected by the moon will be slightly more intense. The
confluence of the three factors occurs about once every 133 years
and will not occur again during the next century. But astronomer Ed
Barker of Austin's McDonald Observatory said the difference will
hardly be noticeable to the average observer. (Nesmith).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-VOTING _ WASHINGTON _ Jim Adler, founder and CEO of
Votehere.net, holds a briefing on how companies are working to
ensure security for voting via the Internet. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-VOICE _ WASHINGTON _ The National Museum of Natural
History previews ``African Voices,'' a permanent exhibition on
``the people, culture and dynamic history of the African
continent.'' The exhibit opens to the public Wednesday. (Dart, Cox
News Service). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (l) lifestyle and (t) travel categories.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ WASHINGTON _ The White House's Y2K czar, John Koskinen,
will appear at a National Press Club luncheon Tuesday to answer
questions about the nation's readiness for the date rollover.
(Geewax, Cox News Service). 22. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CUBANS _ As U.S.-Cuba diplomatic relations continue to strain
with the weight of the custody battle over 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez, the longstanding issue of Cuban detainees in U.S. jails
flared today with negotiators working for armed Cuban detainees to
release two deputies and a warden taken hostage at the St. Martin
Parish jail in Louisiana. One of the Cubans has been held for 13
years and is frustrated at the lack of progress in his case. The
Cubans are among a group of 60 in jail for the INS pending
deportation or other action. (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (i) International
categories.
</P>
<P>
   REACTOR _ The one-year warranty has expired on the nuclear
reactor UT bought in 1992 and shut down last month due to a welding
defect. That's right, one year is all you get for a plutonium
container. Because reactors are supposed to last 40 years and the
company that made this one has never had such a problem since it
began, the factory rep is coming to Texas next week from the
headquarters in San Diego to check out the problem. Although
there's no safety danger, officials from the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission came to Austin this week to take a look. Though it's a
lot of red tape for UT, the shutdown's greater impact is on
graduate students who had planned to get their degrees in May and
were counting on the reactor for their experiments. (Jayson, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ Checking on what other law enforcement officials and
local residents think about outgoing ATF director's comments that
Olympic bombing suspect Eric Rudolph is probably dead. (Manuel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WATERWAR _ ATLANTA _ Georgia will find out Tuesday whether
Florida will abandon the water war negotiations, or agree to a
deadline extension to keep the talks alive. Representatives from
Georgia, Alabama and Florida are meeting at a negotiating session
in Atlanta on Tuesday, and Florida will reveal whether it will
stick to an earlier announcment that further talks may be futile to
divide up the waters of the Chattahoochee and other rivers. If the
talks fail, the water war most likely will end up in the Supreme
Court. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-LOTTO _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ If you miss buying a ticket
for Wednesday's $70 million Lotto jackpot, don't fret. It will
probably hit that level at least once more in the next 10 months.
And if $70 million isn't enough to make you part with a buck, just
wait 2.8 years, by which time it will likely have hit $134 million,
according to Lottery estimates obtained by The Palm Beach Post
through the public records law. (Date, Palm Beach Post). 16.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-TEXAS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As of Jan. 1, under-age girls
will have to notify their parents before they get an abortion in
Texas. The law takes effect amid grave concerns about the
confidentiality requirements of a provision allowing a girl to go
to a judge instead of her parents. The new law requires the court
proceedings _ not just the girl's name _ to be confidential. Some
say that could violate the Texas Constitution's ban on secret court
proceedings. Some judges are worried about not having access to the
court cases that will enable them to know what the standards for
awarding the bypass are. There's also a question of making public
the actions of elected judges so people can determine whether they
are judging such cases fairly or on the basis of their own pro- or
anti-choice views. One Houston judge has been jailed for
anti-abortion protests. (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman).
25.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-AFFIRM-CONTROVERSY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Gov. Jeb Bush's
plan to end affirmative action in state government is beginning to
lose what bipartisan support it had. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN-SHOPPERS _ SAN MARCOS, Texas _ Like millions of other
visitors to San Marcos, Araceli Trevino emerged from a day of
serious shopping at the outlet malls with a fistful of receipts and
a car full of bags to tell the tale. Shoes from Nike, dishes from
Pfaltzgraff, clothes from Tommy Hilfiger, Nautica and Liz
Claiborne, assorted gifts from the Disney Store. But instead of
heading home to Austin or San Antonio, Trevino drove more than five
hours to Monterrey, Nuevo Leon, Mexico. It's a trip she has made
twice a year for the past six years. She's hardly unique, however.
These days, more and more Mexicans are coming to Texas to shop.
(Pletz, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
