<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-KENTUCKY-CHRISTMAS-2T     12-14 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENTUCKY-CHRISTMAS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF KENTUCKY HOLIDAY COOKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Recipes appear in 2d take.)  
(DW) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRODSBURG, Ky. _ Coming down through Bluegrass Country from
Lexington to this bustling little farming town, it's not at all
difficult to envision central Kentucky as it must have been 150
years ago. The stately farm homes _ mansions, really _ the
well-kept barns and stables and the spotless white fences and
handsome stables are ample proof that Kentuckians are proud of
their land and their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   I was in search of another facet of that heritage, Kentucky
cooking, particularly in the bountiful holiday season. I was on my
way to visit two of the state's leading culinary landmarks, both
here in Harrodsburg: the Beaumont Inn and, a few miles east of
town, the historic Shaker Village of Pleasant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   At the Beaumont, Ken Dedman, representing the fourth generation
of his family to own and operate the inn, was putting the final
touches on his Christmas decorations. The imposing Greek Revival
inn, originally a finishing school for girls, has been a
destination for lovers of authentic Kentucky cooking for more than
80 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's Kentucky cooking,'' Dedman said. ``Or maybe
Kentucky Southern _ not just Southern cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Shaker Village, Christmas decorations were also up, for
parties. I dined by the light of candles and the last pale rays of
the setting winter sun. Everything, I knew, was much as it had been
when the Shakers lived here a century ago, because the hard-working
women of this religious sect recorded everything, especially the
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen was turning out its own version of Kentucky cooking.
There and at the Beaumont Inn were local favorites like country
ham, corn pudding, carrot casserole, biscuits and a plethora of
pies. But at neither stop did I find Kentucky's famous bourbon:
Mercer County, like about 75 percent of the state, is dry.
</P>
<P>
   Harrodsburg was the first permanent European settlement west of
the Alleghenies, in the 1770s. In 1805, the Shakers arrived. A
religious sect founded in England in 1747, they moved to America in
1774. Eventually, they established 19 Shaker villages from Maine to
Indiana, of which Pleasant Hill was the third largest, with some
500 members. All those settlers left their mark on the cuisine
here.
</P>
<P>
   Ronni Lundy, who lives in Louisville and has written extensively
about the food of her home state, explained how Kentucky cooking
differs from traditional Southern style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kentucky is a long state from east to west, and a short state
from north to south,'' she said. ``In the north it borders the
Midwest, and the cooking there shows that influence. Eastern and
central Kentucky are part of the mountain South _ the southern
Appalachians, western Virginia, West Virginia and parts of
Tennessee. Further south, where it's hotter, the tendency is to
cook for the moment. Here, where we have winter, we tend to
preserve things.''
</P>
<P>
   Like country ham, which is a specialty at both the Beaumont Inn
and the Shaker Village, as well as at other restaurants like Boone
Tavern, not far away in Berea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aging country ham is really a Kentucky specialty,'' Ms. Lundy
said. ``In the deep south, the pig is cooked and eaten right way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beaumont Inn's specialty, not surprisingly, is country ham.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my grandfather was the innkeeper, there were two items on
the menu, fried chicken and country ham,'' Dedman said. ``We've
expanded our menu, but they are still our most popular items,
served separately or combined with a side order of corn pudding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most good ham producers age them for about a year, and people
buy them and eat them right away,'' he continued. ``We hang them in
our own ham house for at least another year or until they are two
years old. The extra time really improves the flavor. At any given
time, we have about 6,000 pounds of ham aging here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooking a country ham begins with scrubbing it and then soaking
it overnight. At the Beaumont, the chef, Nick Sundberg, then boils
the ham for hours, removes the skin, rubs it down with a paste of
cornmeal and brown sugar and bakes it. Some Southern cooks have
been known to add a quart of Coca-Cola to the pan before baking the
ham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is what defines the quality in a good Kentucky ham,''
said John T. Edge, the author of ``A Gracious Plenty,'' a new book
on Southern cooking (Putnam, $30). ``The process is simple _ salt,
hang, smoke. But we live in a hurry-up time, where brine is
injected and water is added to hams, and they are barely aged at
all. Time is what makes the Kentucky hams so good.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything characterizes Kentucky cooking even more than
country ham it's the almost ubiquitous presence of corn bread.
``When I was a child, bread meant corn bread,'' Ms. Lundy said.
``The white stuff you bought at the grocery store was `sweet
bread.'''
</P>
<P>
   Corn was part of Kentucky life from Colonial days because it was
relatively easy to grow. It was a staple of the Native American
diet long before the first settlers arrived west of the mountains,
and many dishes like corn bread and corn pudding are variants of
dishes familiar to the original inhabitants of the region.
Kentuckians prefer their cornmeal and corn flour white and their
corn bread without sweetening.
</P>
<P>
   Country ham takes a back seat to fresh vegetables at the Shaker
Village at Pleasant Hill. The settlement was founded in 1805 and
disbanded in 1910. The Shakers, celibate, austere and withdrawn
from the world, reveled in nature's bounty and became successful
farmers, cattle raisers and traders. Eventually, here in Mercer
County, they owned some 4,500 acres in fields, pastures, gardens
and orchards.
</P>
<P>
   While the men, called brethren, tilled the fields, raised
livestock and made tools, the women, called sisters, produced
woolen goods, dried seeds and herbs, and cooked for the community
and guests.
</P>
<P>
   The last member of the Shaker community died in 1923.
Restoration of Pleasant Hill began in 1961. With the restoration of
the handsome Shaker buildings has come a revival of Shaker customs,
including the cooking. Thanks to well-preserved old journals, the
Pleasant Hill kitchens can prepare many of the dishes served to the
community and their guests, including hundreds of Union and
Confederate soldiers, more than a century ago. Now a nonprofit
educational corporation, Pleasant Hill welcomes travelers
throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the peak of the summer season, we serve up to 600 meals a
day,'' said Brian Bentley, the restaurant's assistant manager.
</P>
<P>
   In Pleasant Hill's 19th-century heyday, the community was
self-sustaining. Its gardens, orchards and pastures produced enough
surplus to permit the Shakers to trade and sell their plenty as far
off as New Orleans. There are still gardens and orchards, cattle,
sheep and poultry, but they are maintained principally to
demonstrate how the Shakers lived. Only the garden vegetables are
used in today's kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   A Shaker specialty often on the menu is a casserole made with
salsify, which is also known as oyster plant. It recalls the
salsify seeds brought from Britain to America by the first Shakers
in 1747. Once Pleasant Hill grew its own salsify. ``Now, we import
it from Belgium,'' Bentley said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Shakers were celibate, they bestowed their names on the
dishes that they created: Sister Amelia's Stuffed Onions, Sister
Abigail's Blue Flower Omelet, Sister Olive Wheeler's Ginger
Cookies, Sister Mary's Zesty Carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most popular dish is Shaker lemon pie, which has
been called the quintessential Shaker recipe because it embodies
two important ideals of the sect: simplicity (it's easy to make)
and thrift (because it uses every bit of the lemon, including the
rind). The secret is slicing the lemons paper thin.
</P>
<P>
   The Shakers had no stated objection to alcohol and made both
hard cider and fruit wines. Today, no alcohol is served at Pleasant
Hill or at the Beaumont Inn, although guests who bring their own
wine and spirits may drink in their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have guests from all over the United States and Europe who
are astounded to discover that they can't get a drink in the heart
of Kentucky bourbon country,'' Dedman of the Beaumont Inn said.
</P>
<P>
   A change in the county's drinking laws was voted down 2-to-1
this year. Will Rogers took note of the irony in that predicament
many years ago when he observed, ``Southerners will drink wet and
vote dry so long as any citizen can stagger to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPES FOLLOW)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ZESTY CARROT CASSEROLE  &QL; 
From Pleasant Hill Shaker Community &QL; 
Time: 35 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 medium carrots, peeled and thinly sliced lengthwise on a
mandoline
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons prepared horseradish
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced onion
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   { cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fine bread crumbs or cracker meal
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon melted butter
</P>
<P>
   Dash of paprika.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium saucepan combine carrots with 1 cup water. Place
over high heat. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low, and
simmer until carrots are just tender. Drain, reserving \ cup of
cooking liquid.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat oven to 375 degrees. Arrange the carrots in a shallow
6-cup baking dish. In a small mixing bowl, combine the reserved
carrot liquid, the horseradish, onion, salt, pepper and mayonnaise.
Pour the mixture over the carrots.
</P>
<P>
   3. In another bowl, combine bread crumbs, butter and paprika;
sprinkle over carrots. Bake until topping is golden, about 20
minutes. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.  &QL; 
BEAUMONT INN'S CORN PUDDING Adapted from the Beaumont Inn,
Harrodsburg, Ky. &QL; 
Time: 1 hour 10 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh white corn kernels
</P>
<P>
   { cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 cups milk.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oven to 450 degrees. In a bowl, combine corn, flour,
salt, sugar and butter. In a separate bowl, lightly whisk eggs,
then add milk. Whisk again until just blended.
</P>
<P>
   2. Transfer corn to a shallow 2-quart casserole, spreading
evenly. Pour egg mixture over it. Bake 10 minutes, then gently stir
bottom with a long-handle serving fork, disturbing the surface as
little as possible.
</P>
<P>
   3. Reduce oven setting to 350 degrees, and bake for 10 minutes.
Again stir bottom of dish. Bake 10 minutes more, and stir for a
third time. Bake again until surface is lightly browned and center
is firm, 15 to 20 minutes. Remove from oven, and allow dish to sit
for 5 to 10 minutes. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKER LEMON PIE Adapted from Pleasant Hill Shaker Community &QL; 
Time: 45 minutes, plus 2 hours standing and 30 minutes cooling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 large thin-skinned seedless lemons, sliced paper thin
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, well beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 unbaked 9-inch pie shell and crust.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a bowl, combine lemons and sugar. Allow to stand at room
temperature, mixing occasionally, for at least 2 hours or
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat oven to 450 degrees. Add beaten eggs to lemon mixture,
and stir well. Pour into pie shell, arranging lemon slices evenly.
Cover with top crust; crimp edges. Cut slits near center of crust.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bake pie for 15 minutes, then reduce heat to 375 degrees.
Continue to bake until a knife inserted near rim of pie comes out
clean, 20 to 25 minutes. Center of pie will continue to set as it
cools. Serve at room temperature or chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: One 9-inch pie (8 to 10 servings). &QL; 
 &QL; 
COUNTRY HAM  &QL; 
Adapted from Nick Sundbreg of the Beaumont Inn &QL; 
Time: About 6 hours, after overnight soaking  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 country ham, about 14 pounds
</P>
<P>
   { cup cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   { cup brown sugar.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash ham thoroughly. Place in large pot and cover with cold
water. Soak overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour off water and cover ham with fresh cold water. Place on
burner and bring to a boil, then cook about 3{ hours (15 minutes a
pound). Remove from cooking water and cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat oven to 400 degrees. Remove skin on ham. Place ham in
roasting pan, fat side up. Combine cornmeal and sugar and pat
evenly over fat side. Bake 45 minutes, or until top is brown. Cool
again before cutting into thin slices. Serve at room temperature.
Yield: 25 servings.
</P>
