<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8805 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV21-     12-14 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I FILLED OUT THOSE FORMS AND I LIED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, Dec. 21)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Janice, mother of a kindergartner, has a message for other new
mothers contemplating going on welfare: Make sure you do it
legally, she says, not the way she did it.
</P>
<P>
   Janice is in jail. She'll miss Christmas with her little boy.
She'll be behind bars for New Year's and spend the first two months
of the millennium in the El Dorado County Jail for committing
welfare fraud.
</P>
<P>
   This week she sat in her apartment, emptied of a number of
belongings she sold to get money in order to pay her bills ahead.
Someone had just purchased her vacuum cleaner and with that money
she was off to buy her son a Christmas present, perhaps a set of
Legos.
</P>
<P>
   He'll spend part of the holidays with Janice's parents and then
live with his father, Janice's estranged husband, until she's
released.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Janice will be in jail serving 60 days because, as
she explained to her son, ``Mommy did something I shouldn't have. I
broke the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Janice says, she is not unique. That is why she
wanted to pass on her warning. ``I know women who do this or think
about doing this all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And it commonly begins as it did for her.
</P>
<P>
   She met a man, fell in love, got pregnant and they moved in
together. He had a job and was capable of supporting them, but in
order to get AFDC and food stamps she told welfare authorities that
she was alone and that the baby's father was dead. That was six
years ago. Janice later stated in an affidavit that her boyfriend
pressured her to lie. He countered that he didn't. But in the end
it came down to she said/he said, and it was Janice's signature on
the welfare papers. This fall, sheriff's officers came to Janice's
house in Sonoma County, Calif., where she lives with her little boy
and arrested her for committing welfare fraud in El Dorado County.
</P>
<P>
   Janice knows all about how it was wrong and illegal and unwise.
``My friends are so mad at me for being so stupid and weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Her only defense, she says, is, ``I wanted to do whatever it
took to make him happy,'' meaning her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have left him and gone home to live with my parents.
Or I could have gone on welfare legally and lived by myself, taken
the harder route, the lonely route. But I felt at the time my only
choice was to commit the crime and keep the man.''
</P>
<P>
   She also admits, ``I liked having my own money. I knew it was
illegal and wrong but I filled out those forms every month and
lied.''
</P>
<P>
   She and the baby's father eventually married, and Janice went
off welfare and began working as a house cleaner. A year later,
Janice left her husband, moved to Sonoma County with her son and
turned herself in.
</P>
<P>
   0``I talked to the district attorney's office and told them who
the real father was and that I had lied on the original paperwork.
I turned myself in so I could get child support. They attached his
wages and that started the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it took years before anyone came after her for welfare fraud
and at first she hoped she could just pay it off. She'd begun
sending $25 a month to El Dorado County toward the $6,400 she owes
for 10 months of food stamps and AFDC, but that wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told just because you make restitution doesn't keep you
out of jail. I think they're disgusted with me. They think this
girl needs a wake-up call. I guess I agree.'' Janice is 36,
attractive and articulate. ``I was one of those kids who was
supposed to be gifted,'' she says, almost smiling. She plans to go
to business school next year when her son enters first-grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to think about educating the brain God gave me.''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't try to rationalize her acts nor paint her husband as
the bad guy but accepts her role in a bad decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you don't take the time to think about the future
because you're so wrapped up in the moment. You don't see that
things could change, that the boyfriend could leave or you'd want
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you get pregnant you need to make sure the child has a
father. You have to make the man responsible for his child. Put his
name down on that paper. Because six years later it can come back
full circle.''
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, Janice says she'd be married and have three
kids and ``be the mom picking up my kids at the bus stop.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead she's going to jail and trying to be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that after this, things can only get better.''
</P>
<P>
   First she has to say goodbye to her son for a while. ``That's
going to be pretty painful. He's such a lovable little guy.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
