A8808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RUDOLPH-COX     12-14 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rudolph's death exaggerated, say mountain residents
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At the Lake's End Grill in North Carolina's Nantahala
Forest Tuesday, Peggy Ellison grilled a hamburger for an FBI agent.
The two chatted about the latest twist in the saga of accused
bomber Eric Robert Rudolph: The outgoing director of the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms thinks he's dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here's just laughing about it,'' said Ellison, whose
restaurant sits smack in the middle of the prime search area for
the 33-year-old fugitive. The agent waiting for lunch told Ellison
``he didn't know where the (ATF chief) got his information.''
</P>
<P>
   During an interview published in Tuesday's USA Today, ATF
Director John Magaw said: ``My gut instinct is that he is still
there, in a cave, and he's dead. That's only my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Magaw leaves Monday to coordinate the Federal Emergency
Management Agency's response to domestic terrorism. The new
director, who remains unannounced, is scheduled to be sworn in
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the opinion of the director,'' ATF spokeswoman Tracy
Hite said. ``We still have resources dedicated toward finding Eric
Robert Rudolph and toward prosecuting him.''
</P>
<P>
   The carpenter and former resident of the Nantahala community is
charged with the July 27, 1996, bombing at Centennial Olympic Park
and the fatal bombing at a Birmingham abortion clinic Jan. 29,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the rugged Appalachians of western North Carolina,
Magaw's comments made the rounds in newspapers, on television and
on radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think he's dead? No, I just think he's smart,'' said
Ellison, whose marquee for months has read ``Rudolph eats here.''
Guests once gossiped regularly about Rudolph, but it's been two or
three months since anyone's mentioned him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's in a cave, I just don't think's he's out there without
any help,'' Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   John Wagner, a retired Florida auto parts salesman who moved to
Nantahala in 1973, is one of Ellison's regulars. He's been saying
the same thing as Magaw for almost two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I've said all along _ he dug a hole, climbed in
and blew his brains out,'' said Wagner, who's had fatigue-clad
agents trod on his property. ``It's hard for me to believe _ I
don't care how tough he is _ that he's been out there for two
winters eating nuts and berries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep asking about the reward,'' said Wagner, wondering how
to collect the $1 million FBI bounty if Rudolph is dead. ``They
tell me, `Just bring in his teeth.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Magaw's opinion, though, doesn't necessarily have teeth with the
Southeast Bomb Task Force, a multi-agency group stationed in nearby
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is entitled to their own gut theory, whether they be
the outgoing director of the ATF or any citizen in the Nantahala
forest, '' Task Force spokesman Patrick Crosby said Tuesday. ``But
the task force must always be diligent and assume nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even local law enforcement has placed little stock in Magaw's
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to look for him until it's proven he's
not here,'' said Roger Williams, chief deputy of the Cherokee
County Sheriff's Department in Murphy, N.C. ``The man's elusive. .
. . I try not to form opinions because when I do, I don't do as
good a job as I need to investigating.''
</P>
<P>
   Magaw noted no food's been reported missing, no cabins have been
broken into.
</P>
<P>
   That's true, as far as Elsie Lail knows. She rents cabins at the
Hideaway Campground in the Nantahala Gorge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to a few people'' who shared Magaw's opinion, Lail
said. ``Personally, I think he's somewhere else, and I think most
people think he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, the task force intensified its search when a
mountain acquaintance of Rudolph reported the suspect stole food
and his pickup. The truck was recovered nearby a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, it's been quiet. No forensic evidence has been
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a non-event,'' Wagner said. ``You don't see the
dark-tinted Suburbans, Blazers and Explorers or searchers in
fatigues. There are no helicopters, and they used to be a daily
occurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times Neice
</P>
</TEXT>
