<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPICE-GIRL-MELANIE-NY     12-14 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPICE-GIRL-MELANIE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SPICE GIRL MELANIE CHISHOLM, THE `SPORT' IS ALL IN THE MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BILL DeYOUNG  
The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask Melanie Chisholm, one of the most famous women in England,
how she deals with the constant presence of paparazzi, and the
artist som%times known as Sporty Spice chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I'm really lucky because they don't
really bother with me that much,'' she says. ``They tend to be more
interested in people's personal lives, and I haven't got one.''
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm has been one of the Spice Girls since the beginning,
and some 40 million records later, she is a 26-year-old
multimillionaire and an instantly recognizable celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   In Great Britain, the Spice Girls sell newspapers, and Fleet
Street likes nothing better than a juicy story about Victoria
``Posh Spice'' Adams and her new husband, soccer star David
Beckham.
</P>
<P>
   They like Emma ``Baby Spice'' Bunton and Melanie ``Scary Spice''
Brown, too. And even Geri ``Ginger Spice'' Halliwell, who's not in
the group any more, gets more press than Melanie Chisholm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because I favor work, and you always know what I'm up
to,'' Chisholm says good-naturedly in a telephone interview from
Liverpool. ``Victoria's got a famous husband as well, so obviously
they're a lot more interesting than me. They're only interested in
who you're sleeping with, rather than the music you're making.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the group took some time off while Adams and Brown
married their beaus and had babies. Chisholm, a self-proclaimed
workaholic, used the opportunity to record a solo album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northern Star,'' released under the name Melanie C, covers a
cross-section of musical styles, from electronica and industrial to
flat-out rock 'n' roll, and a few moments of Spice-like pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I like, and I never pushed myself in any
direction,'' Chisholm says. ``I just sort of wanted to see what
came naturally. I think it was always going to be different from
Spice Girls stuff, because as individuals we're very different to
who we are within the group, even.''
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm recently had her hair cut into a spiky blond 'do.
Because of her prolific tattoos, her gold tooth and the steel stud
in her nose, the first reaction to ``Northern Star'' was that she'd
gone, well, punk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love pop music, and lots of different styles of music, and I
do love to rock out and do pretty hard stuff. But I don't think I'd
ever make an album that was totally that,'' Chisholm says. ``I like
it being quite eclectic-sounding. 'Cause, you know, my emotions go
up and down, day to day. And I like to express that.''
</P>
<P>
   To promote the album, which includes production by Rick Rubin
(Tom Petty, Red Hot Chili Peppers) and William Orbit (Madonna's
``Ray of Light''), Chisholm played a few dates as a solo. Her
performance of the Sex Pirtols' ``Anarchy in the U.K.'' left a lot
of fans scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's finding it quite hard finding what
category to put me in,'' she says. ``The kids haven't really got on
to what I'm doing, and the older ones are a bit cynical about me
being a Spice Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of working-class Widnes, just outside Liverpool in the
north of England, Chisholm had designs on a performing career at an
early age. In 1994, she answered a trade magazine ad for an
all-girl band.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Monkees and Menudo, the Spice Girls didn't come
together organically but were created for a purpose; in this case,
a production team and a financial backer set out to put five very
different singer-dancers together to tackle the British charts.
</P>
<P>
   They succeeded beyond anyone's wildest dreams. The quintet got
along famously and charmed the world. And most of the group's hits,
including ``Wannabe,'' ``When 2 Become 1'' and ``Too Much,'' were
co-written and arranged by the Spice Girls themselves.
</P>
<P>
   However, because the Spice Girls were ``manufactured,'' they've
taken some hard knocks from the music press.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one saving grace we've always had is that we truly do
believe our music's great,'' Chisholm explains. ``As much as people
can knock us _ and they can say whatever they like _ we've always
believed in the music that we've made.
</P>
<P>
   From day one, even the Spice Girls' harshest critics agreed that
Spo2ty, she of the Nike sweats and athletic stage moves, was ``the
real singer'' in the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wd're all very capable vocalists,'' she says. ``I think the
girls in the band would all agree that I'm probably the most
determined out of everybody, and I do work the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, each to their own. Everybody's got their
favorite Spice Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spice Girls were nearly knocked off the rack by the sudden
departure of Haliwell in 1998, on the eve of the group's two-month
debut American tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we could keep the show together,'' Chisholm says.
``We had to go out and do a couple of dates in Europe like the day
after she left. But I think our biggest fear with America was just
if people would want us as a four-piece, without Geri.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let everybody know, and thank God the promoters and
everybody in America, they didn't have any problem with it being
just the four of us. But it went great.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she has exchanged ``the odd card and letter'' with
Haliwell, and intends to read her ex-mate's autobiography one of
these days.
</P>
<P>
   But Chisholm didn't care for ``Schizophonic,'' Haliwell's
post-Spice solo recording. ``I would've thought she could have made
a better album, and I think vocally it is very weak,'' she says.
``And if people don't think so, they must be deaf.''
</P>
<P>
   The four Spice Girls are back in action this month, playing a
series of Christmas shows in their home country. Each show was a
near-instant sellout. A new album is due in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   And no, the group does not intend to split up any time soon. For
Melanie Chisholm, it's possible to be a Spice Girl and a solo at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really funny, because as time goes by more and more
things become apparent to me,'' she says, ``especially being back
with the Spice Girls over the last few weeks and doing live shows.
When I'm part of the band, the Spice Girls, I am completely
different. It is really, really strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I'm up there on stage I really act the part, I do. I
really act Sporty Spice. It's a part of me, you kno{, but it's not
the way I would be on my own on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
