<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8811 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GWTW-MUSEUM15-COX     12-14 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GWTW-MUSEUM15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Gone With the Wind' museum near the Margaret Mitchell House in
Atlanta
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANT _ Fans of ``Gone With the Wind'' who have been looking in
vain for Margaret Mitchell's fictional Tara can now find a little
bit of the Hollywood version in Midtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The front door of the legendary plantation used in the movie set
and the portrait of Scarlett O'Hara that hung over Rhett Butler's
mantel are the main attractions in a new museum adjacent to the
Margaret Mitchell House at 10th and Peachtree streets.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,500-square-foot museum will open to the public Thursday
after a private gala tonight marking the 60th anniversary of the
film's premiere in Atlanta on Dec. 15, 1939 at Loew's Grand
Theater. Exhibits will include dozens of artifacts from the
collection of Herb Bridges, a retired Sharpsburg postal worker who
has been collecting GWTW memorabilia for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herb's collection is impressive,'' says Mary Rose Taylor,
executive director of the Margaret Mitchell House &AMP; Museum. ``This
is an opportunity to give the public a little more. Even for
Atlantans who think they're bored with the `Gone With the Wind'
story, this exhibit will allow them to see it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dramatic items in the exhibit is the
larger-than-life portrait of Vivien Leigh as Scarlett O'Hara,
painted for the movie by artist Helen Carlton. On loan from the
Atlanta Public Schools (it normally hangs at Margaret Mitchell
Elementary School), the portrait still bears the marks of the
whiskey glass that Clark Gable hurled against it in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it's a liquor stain, but Bridges speculates it was just
colored water. ``I'm sure they had to shoot several takes, and they
wouldn't have used alcohol. Although,'' he adds, ``in the scene
where Rhett is giving Mammy (Hattie McDaniel) a drink, Clark Gable
actually used real whiskey as a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The white wooden Tara doorway and casement is owned by Gene
Talmadge, son of Betty Talmadge, former Georgia first lady who
bought it for $5,000 in 1979 and spent $8,000 restoring it.
Everything else is from Bridges' extensive collection, from an
assortment of Scarlett and Rhett dolls to the striped pants Clark
Gable wore in the film.
</P>
<P>
   What is surprising is the enormous array of merchandise tied-in
to the movie. In a way, Bridges says, it was the ``Toy Story'' or
``Star Wars'' of its time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had Scarlett perfume, Scarlett dolls and various other
things,'' Bridges says. ``Rich's sold the first Scarlett dolls. A
jeweler made Belle earrings _ named for Belle Watling (the madam of
the local brothel) _ in the shape of little bells and sold those.
Scarlett hair bows sold for five cents at the dime stores and there
were beautiful paper doll books.''
</P>
<P>
   Other items of note include mimeographed film scripts, aisle
lights from Loew's Grand Theater, the green bonnet that Rhett
brought Scarlett from Paris, and original movie posters in English
and foreign languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``One movie poster went for $71,000 at an auction,'' says
Bridges. ``I started collecting this stuff when nobody wanted it. I
bought it a piece at a time. I had three children and a house
payment. There was no way I could pay any big money for it.'' Now
Bridges, who owns the largest private collection of ``Gone With the
Wind'' memorabilia in the world, is glad to have found a permanent
place to exhibit his treasures. ``I am thrilled to be able to do it
at a reputable place like the Mitchell House and Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a wonder the Mitchell House even exists. It was
on the verge of demolition when Taylor launched efforts to save it
in the 1980s. It finally opened in 1997 after a series of financial
setbacks and two cases of suspected arson _ one in 1994 and another
in 1996 when the renovation was nearly completed.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was saddened by the near-destruction of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not sorry to see the Margaret Mitchell House burn to the
ground,'' novelist Pearl Cleage wrote in the Atlanta Tribune at the
time. ``I was, in fact, delighted that someone had taken direct
action against what I consider to be an insult of monumental
proportions to African-American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all African-Americans share Cleage's view, however. One of
the Margaret Mitchell House board members is Dr. Otis Smith, a
former president of the Atlanta branch of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   As Smith frequently points out, Mitchell quietly gave
scholarship money to at least 40 Morehouse College graduates to
enable them to attend medical school.
</P>
<P>
   This little-known side of the author is emphasized during tours
of the Margaret Mitchell House, Taylor says. At the end of each
tour, a short video describes Mitchell's anonymous contributions to
the black community.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, attendance has grown steadily from 45,000 in 1997 to
65,000 this year. Taylor expects those numbers to rise with the
addition of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been self-supporting since the house opened,'' says
Taylor, ``but we do it by having fund raisers. We are looking for
an endowment.''
</P>
<P>
   A non-profit organization, the Margaret Mitchell House acquired
the $1 million-plus building, a former NationsBank branch, through
a grant from the Woodruff Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   During a pre-exhibit tour, public relations director Heather
Hjetland explained that the museum will be divided into three
sections: The making of the movie, the movie's premiere, and the
movie's legacy.'' (The film, by the way, was shot in Hollywood _
not in Atlanta.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have records of the movie's music, the pants worn by Clark
Gable, and a corset worn by Vivien Leigh. You can see how tiny her
waist was,'' she says, holding the garment against her body.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items is a two-and-a-half-foot scale model of a
railroad boxcar used in the burning of Atlanta scene. ``They shot
that scene in Hollywood,'' Hjetland says. ``They burned the King
Kong set and other old Hollywood sets.''
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, there is the movie merchandise, from hair bows to
Lux soap. ``This is really the first movie that was so
commericalized,'' Hjetland says. ``The Hollywood publicity machine
kept `Gone with the Wind' alive in people's minds from 1936 to 1939
when the movie was released.''
</P>
<P>
   Six decter, Scarlett fever shows little signs of
subsiding. According to Publishers Weekly, the novel still sells
250,000 copies a year, second only to the Bible, and signed first
editions of ``Gone With the Wind'' are worth upwards of $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Mitchell House &AMP; Museum
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where:
</P>
<P>
   990 Peachtree St.; free parking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: 9 a.m.-4 p.m. daily. Closed Thanksgiving, Christmas and
New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Admission:
</P>
<P>
   $7 adults, $6 students and senior citizens; children under 5
free.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Web site:
</P>
<P>
   www.margaret
</P>
<P>
   mitchell.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  General information: 404-249-7015
</P>
<P>
   Evolution of `the Dump'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1889: Cornelius J. Sheehan builds the house for his family on
Peachtree.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1913: The house is moved back from Peachtree to 979 Crescent
Ave. and converted into a 10-unit apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1925: Margaret Mitchell and her husband, John Marsh, move into
Apt. 1 on the bottom floor. Mitchell, who dubbed the small
apartment ``the Dump,'' wrote most of ``Gone With the Wind'' here.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1932: Mitchell and Marsh move to the Russell Apartments on
17th Street. ``The Dump'' remains an apartment building until the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1977: Mitchell's brother, Stephens Mitchell, discourages plans
to revive the deteriorating building.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1981: Fire damages the roof and upper floors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1982: The Atlanta Bureau of Buildings cites the structure for
housing code violations. The Urban Design Commission agrees it
should be torn down.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1985: Trammell Crow Co. acquires the building. Deborah James
forms Margaret Mitchell Museum Inc. to renovate it. The Urban
Design Commission reverses its 1982 opinion and urges saving the
house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1987: Margaret Mitchell Museum Inc. abandons its efforts.
Mitchell House Inc. is formed and renews the drive to save the
house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1991: Mary Rose Taylor becomes chairwoman of Margaret Mitchell
House Inc. and launches a fund-raising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1994: Fire guts the building; arson is suspected.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1995: German automaker Daimler-Benz signs a $4 million
agreement to save and restore the burned-out building.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1996: The nearly restored structure is gutted by fire again;
once again, arson is suspected. Taylor adds security and vows to
rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1997: Margaret Mitchell House opens to the public.
</P>
<P>
   _Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
