<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATERWAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia amends water basin plan
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In an effort to salvage deteriorating water war
negotiations, Georgia officials put an altered proposal on the
table on Tuesday to keep Florida from pulling out of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials said they will study Georgia's new plan, but
they declined to say whether they will budge from their declaration
this month that a continuation of the talks beyond a Dec. 31
deadline appear to be futile.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, Florida and Alabama are locked in a battle over sharing
the waters of the Apalachicola, Chattahoochee and Flint river
basin, or the ACF. The basin's headwaters begin in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia wants to be sure it has enough water to allow for future
development. But Florida and Alabama are concerned Georgia's use of
the water from those rivers will leave less water for their own
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has proposed a water-allocation plan that would
guarantee certain minimum flows of water at the Georgia borders
during droughts, through the manipulation of dams along the
Chattahoochee, for the next 50 years. Tuesday, Georgia officials
modified that plan to allow for a changes to be made after only 10
years. Georgia officials also called for a study to determine if
minimum flow levels should be maintained along the Flint River, as
well as the Chattahoochee, during droughts.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether negotiators from Alabama and Florida will
agree to the Georgia plan, or the changes introduced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The three states are scheduled to meet in another negotiating
session in Tallahassee on Dec. 29. If they don't agree to extend
the deadline, the talks will fail and the squabble could head to
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials say chances of reaching a settlement in the
ACF fight are slim and perhaps unachievable because of Georgia's
refusal to agree to specific flow conditions in the Flint River.
They say they probably will not agree to a deadline extension if
Georgia remains unyielding. The Flint, which begins just south of
Hartsfield International Airport, meets up with the Chattahoochee
in southwest Georgia at the Florida state line to form the
Apalachicola. The Apalachicola flows across the Florida Panhandle
and nourishes oysters and other marine life in Apalachicola Bay on
the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For an agreement to be reached, Florida and Alabama also would
have to agree to other stipulations, such as limits on how much
they can withdraw from the basin for human consumption and
industry. In addition, Florida would have to agree to limits on how
much oysters and other commercial fishes can be taken from
Apalachicola Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's demands sparked visible annoyance among Florida's
negotiators. Bob Kerr, Georgia's chief negotiator, said that
Georgia wants to make sure that Florida properly manages
Apalachicola Bay in return for guaranteed volumes of water from the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
