<HEADER>
A8815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-GULFWAR-SYNDROME-NYTR     12-14 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULFWAR-SYNDROME-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS STILL HEALING FROM GULF WAR SYNDROME
WHISTLE - BLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Md.)   (bl)  
 By CARL HULSE   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group Washington Bureau   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ James Moss is a regular at the veterans medical
center in Gainesville, Fla., another casualty of Gulf War Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Moss was not a soldier in the conflict. Rather, he was a U.S.
Agriculture Department researcher whose work on insecticides
unexpectedly suggested a link between the chronic disorder
afflicting thousands of veterans and an experimental drug taken as
a nerve gas antidote by Gulf War troops.
</P>
<P>
   When he refused to halt what his superiors claimed was an
unauthorized study, he lost his job. He now works as a temporary
research technician at the VA center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a big irony,'' observed Moss, 48, still bruised from
his run-in with a hostile government bureaucracy. ``It is rather
amazing to be in there working among veterans, especially knowing
some are sick'' from the very problem he investigated.
</P>
<P>
   After years of government denials, a new Pentagon-funded study
has substantiated what Moss and another Florida scientist, Thomas
Tiedt of Bradenton, said all along _ pyridostigmine bromide, given
to troops to protect against nerve gas attacks, was a potential
culprit in the puzzling, debilitating malady. The cure, in effect,
caused the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``PB cannot be ruled out as a possible contributor to the
development of unexplained or undiagnosed illness in some PGW
veterans,'' said the authoritative Rand Corp. study issued in
October.
</P>
<P>
   While not conclusive on the link, the finding was a far cry from
the insistent Pentagon position that the PB tablets given more than
250,000 servicemen and women were no factor in the syndrome _ a
stance affirmed in two earlier government studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't rule it out, by definition you are ruling it
in,'' said Tiedt, who like Moss, is acknowledged in the Rand study
for his research on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Both men expressed a level of satisfaction in the release of the
Rand review, but they are still healing from wounds suffered in
their battle with powerful government forces.
</P>
<P>
   Tiedt, 49, a medical toxicology consultant, said he devoted
almost full-time to the controversy at his own expense between
1994-98 only to be treated like a pariah by some of his colleagues
in the research community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would show up at these things and I was just ridiculed all
over the place,'' said Tiedt, who said his personal finances also
took a beating. ``I will be forever behind the eight ball
financially.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact on Moss, recognized as one of the first to raise the
prospect of PB contributing to the disorder, was even more direct.
Ordered to quit his pursuit of how insecticides widely applied in
Gulf military installations might have interacted with PB, Moss not
only refused to stop but eventually took his findings to receptive
members of Congress in May 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his research contract later that year and had to go on
unemployment. He became a substitute teacher to support his wife,
Gail, a librarian, and their three children. His life was seriously
disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played a very pivotal role and he paid a very heavy price
for his citizenship and his advocacy on behalf of Gulf War
veterans,'' said Paul Sullivan, executive director of the National
Gulf War Resource Center.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent congressional hearing on the report, other
veterans advocates singled out Moss and Tiedt for their willingness
to step forward on the controversy when others shied away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have experts who have been on the veterans' side since
1993,'' said Denise Nichols, a retired Air Force nurse and
vice-chair of the National Vietnam &AMP; Gulf War Veterans Coalition,
in recognizing the work of Moss and Tiedt. Moss earlier received a
commendation from the state of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the personal turmoil, Moss is not sure he could have
done anything differently once his work with cockroaches pointed
him in the direction of a tie between PB and DEET, a popular
insecticide that the Agriculture Department helped develop in the
1950s in the same Gainesville lab where Moss worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't just sit on it,'' said Moss, about his decision to
publicize his research despite fierce resistance from his
superiors.
</P>
<P>
   Moss filed a complaint over his job loss, but a USDA
investigation reported that he was simply let go when his contract
expired and there was no other position for him, a decision upheld
by Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   Tiedt came to the subject via a different route. As a
postdoctoral fellow at the University of Maryland in the 1970s, he
did some of the original research demonstrating the toxicity of
compounds like PB even at low dosages.
</P>
<P>
   So he said he was shocked when, while channel surfing in June
1994, he came across C-Span's coverage of a congressional hearing
at which three government experts testified under oath that PB
posed no known toxic risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you at the time that threw me for a loop,''
recalled Tiedt, who _ after a few sleepless nights _ contacted Sen.
Jay Rockefeller, D-W.V., then head of the Senate Veterans' Affairs
Committee. Rockefeller was sympathetic to veterans' claims that PB
tablets had helped make them sick and had himself been looking for
Tiedt.
</P>
<P>
   Tiedt provided Rockefeller's staff with evidence of extensive
research on PB, material included in a searing 1994 Senate panel
report critical of the Pentagon's history of experimenting on its
own troops. Tiedt then considered the matter closed.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of continued Pentagon stonewalling on the research
surrounding PB, Tiedt pressed on. He testified before a
presidential advisory commission and then a House panel in 1997
about the existing record on the potential consequences of PB and
his view that it would not have protected the troops regardless.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seemed to finally turn the tide with the DOD,'' said
Tiedt, decrying the human anguish that arose out of the military's
decision to give troops PB when research indicated it would be
ineffective for its intended purpose. ``It should have never been
administered in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Tiedt nor Moss equate their own personal trials with the
suffering by the actual victims of Gulf War Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tiedt: ``It doesn't match 100,000 veterans who are sick and
hundreds of thousands of others and maybe millions of Americans who
are deeply offended at the lack of respect'' shown the veterans by
government skepticism toward their illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has motivated the veterans and the people supporting the
veterans is simply a yearning for respect,'' he said. ``For
somebody just to say, we believe you.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
