NYT-12-14-99 1823EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8817 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     12-14 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING HOLIDAY STRESS TO A MAXIMUM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to a three-year study done by the Center for Lifestyle
Management, an average of 10 hours on Christmas week are spent
arguing and bickering with family members about holiday-related
activities.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting statistic, to be sure, but what I want to know is
what these family members are doing the rest of the time?
</P>
<P>
   According to my cheap, matchbox-size pocket calculator
(Christmas gift, 1995), there are 168 hours in a week. Assuming
that family members do not quarrel during their eight hours of
sleep each night, that still leaves 102 hours that family members
are not arguing or bickering with each other about holiday-related
activities during Christmas week.
</P>
<P>
   The way I look at it, if you're not arguing with your family
members for more than 10 hours Christmas week, you're not really
trying. Ten hours of holiday-related bickering is nothing. Many
family-members can't even clear their throat in that short a time.
Heck, in my house we've done more bickering than that just hauling
the Christmas stuff down from the attic.
</P>
<P>
   What accounts for this woeful lack of bickering? My guess is
that the average American family is not engaging in nearly enough
holiday-related activities. Simply sitting down together and
agreeing on a Christmas-card message should be good for at least
five hours of bickering. You can add another five hours by
discussing who gets a card and who doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Families that are interested in getting their bickering time up
where it belongs should try engaging in the following
holiday-related activities:
</P>
<P>
   Buy a Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing gets the holiday bickering scene off to a ``bang'' than
a trip to the ol' tree lot. Begin by arguing over whether you want
a long-needle or short-needle tree. If everybody in your family
prefers one type, then you should demand they buy the other. Point
out that all the trees everyone else likes have lousy shapes, drop
needles and are hard to decorate. As soon as people start agreeing
with your point of view, change your mind. Insist on visiting at
least four lots on opposite ends of town before making a decision.
Forget to bring a rope to tie the tree down in the trunk of your
car. And, of course, always buy a tree that is too big to fit in
your tree stand.
</P>
<P>
   Play Christmas music nonstop for the entire week.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing brings families closer together, bickering-wise, then
back-to-back-to-back playings of the Jingle Dogs rendition of
``Away in a Manger.'' Even a brief playing of any Christmas albums
sung by Leonard Nimoy or Ringo Starr should accomplish the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Decorate the outside of your house with those trendy new icicle
lights.
</P>
<P>
   Icicle lights were specifically engineered for those people who
couldn't tangle the lights they had into a big enough knot. Icicle
lights are pre-tangled at the factory, thereby saving the busy
homeowner the trouble of doing it himself. To me, nothing says
''Christmas'' like trying to unravel a hopelessly snarled set of
icicle lights while balanced precariously atop a 30-foot extension
ladder on a windy day. Other family members can lend encouragement
to the person hanging the lights by telling him to hurry-up or,
after he's finished, by telling him they wish he'd bought a
different color.
</P>
<P>
   Go shopping at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas shopping is plenty stressful what with the traffic,
the joust for a parking space, the mobs of desperate shoppers and
the surly and/or confused and/or unresponsive salesclerks. Bring
the whole family along and the experience comes to resemble the
dizzy, nerve-stretching terror one normally associates with the
shower scene in the movie ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   While you're there, be sure to let the kids visit Santa. Few
things relax a small child more than being involuntarily hauled, in
front of a crowd of staring people, onto the lap of a huge,
strange, harshly lighted man in a wet, smelly red suit who bellows
``Ho! Ho! Ho!'' at odd intervals and for no apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   If you engage in just a few of these holiday-related family
activities, I'm sure you'll find yourself arguing and bickering a
lot more than 10 hours Christmas week. In fact, you might want to
start the week before, just to make sure you get it all in.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
