<HEADER>
A8820 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u a BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-NYTR &LR;      12-14 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS `REVUE' OF CHILDREN'S SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you plan to bring a computer home this gift-giving season for
Junior and Sissy, you might want to add something to help with the
experience during the coming year: A subscription to Children's
Software Revue.
</P>
<P>
   I've written about this bimonthly publication before, because
it's a reliable place to find impartial, kid- and parent-tested
software. Revue Editor Warren Buckleitner started the magazine
after years of evaluating children's software for an
education-based group.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Revue is supported by its subscribers; it does not
accept advertising from the publishers of software it evaluates.
(Yeah, yeah, I know. The other magazines all have policies saying
advertisers have no control over editorial content. But seeing the
full-page ad for Modem's Magical Dialtone Vacation across from the
glowing review of Modem's Magical Dialtone Vacation always gives
pause.)
</P>
<P>
   And I like a magazine where the ``Greetings from the Staff''
column says that computers are not the ultimate dream when it comes
to childhood development: ``Kids will always be kids, and
technology can not and should not replace experiences like riding a
bike or reading a book.'' It's an obvious viewpoint _ but one not
emphasized enough in computer magazines catering to families.
</P>
<P>
   When Junior and Sissy sit in front of the computer, they may as
well be exposed to quality software _ and the current issue of
Children's Software Revue has reviews of 164 new CDs, Internet
sites and computers for kids. (They even give a nod to some games
for the PlayStation and Nindendo 64.)
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for some games for the whole family to use on
the computer once it's up and running, CSR offers these
suggestions: Elite Darts is ``the next-best thing to being there.''
Patch Products Inc., 800-524-4263, www.patchproducts.com. Ages
10-up. About $20, Windows/Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyle Board Games 3.0. I've reviewed this title, too, and agree
that it's an all-time favorite program. Games include chess,
mancala, backgammon, parchisi, dominoes and backgammon. Sierra
On-line/Havas, 800-757-7707, wee.hasbo-interactive.com. Ages 8-up.
About $20. Windows/Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyle Word Games. In a word: Addictive. Eight games, including
crosswords, doublecross, anagrams and word searches. A good game
for anyone who likes to play with words. Sierra On-line. Ages 8-up.
About $30. Windows/Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Rubik's Cube. An electronic twist on the old hand-held favorite
and with variations added. Hasbro Interactive, 800-683-5847,
www.hasbro-interactive.com. Ages 8-up. About $20. Windows only.
</P>
<P>
   Scrabble CD-ROM Crossword Game. Play against the computer or
over the Internet. Computer's skill level can be adjusted. The game
provides hints and word definitions. Hasbro Interactive. Ages 8-up.
About $30. Windows only.
</P>
<P>
   Space Invaders. It's the arcade version brought home to the
computer screen _ with a lot of new multimedia features.
Activision, 800-477-3650, www.activision.com. Ages 8-up. About $30.
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   UpWords. A Scrabble-like game that uses tiles to build words,
but lets players earn points by stacking tiles to form other words.
Hasbro Interactive. Ages 8-up. About $20. Windows only.
</P>
<P>
   Subscriptions to CSR are $24 a year ($39 for two years), with
discounts available for multiple copies to the same address. For
information: 1-800-993-9499; online ordering,
www.childrenssoftware.com/subscribe.html.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
