<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-ATTACK (Mozdok, Russia) _ Russians step up their
pounding of Grozny, trapping thousands of civilians. Chechens
strike back, bringing down two helicopters and a fighter jet. By
David Filipov and Dmitry Shalganov. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CANAL-TURNOVER (Panama Canal Zone) _ The canal that Americans
built is turned over to Panama, with no current high-level US
official in attendance. Jimmy Carter does the honors. By Richard
Chacon. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MCCARTNEY (London) _ Paul McCartney returns to the small,
sweaty, Liverpool nightclub that launched the Beatles 36 years ago.
By Kevin Cullen. 1000 words. (i and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-TAPE (Washington) _ Judge decides Linda Tripp remains
vulnerable to charges of illegally taping her telephone
conversations with Monica Lewinsky. By Bob Hohler. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-INDEPENDENTS (Undated) _ Based on Globe/WBZ polling
data, a closer look at how the crucial independent N.H. vote is
swinging. By Walter V. Robinson. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-IOWA (Waterloo, Iowa) _ Labor's embrace of Al Gore has
somewhat frustrated Bill Bradley's efforts to cut into Gore's lead
in Iowa. By Curtis Wilkie.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN (Charleston, S.C.) _ John McCain unveils a
health care plan that provides increased prescription drug payments
and puts new money into Medicare and veteran's benefits, while
relying mostly on tax breaks to expand coverage to 44 million
uninsured. By Michael Kranish. 950 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-GORE (Nashua, N.H.) _ Bill Bradley and Al Gore battle
over health care, campaign finance and gays in the military. By
Jill Zuckman. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHULZ-RETIRE (Undated) _ Charlie Brown is retiring from the
funny papers. Creator Charles Schulz, who was recently diagnosed
with cancer, will retire Jan. 4, the day after the final daily
strip runs, his wife says. By Joseph E. Kahn. 1200 words. (a and e
coding)
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-HIRING (Boston) _ In a decision that spells the end of
affirmative action within the Boston Police Department, a judge
rules that race cannot be taken into account in promotions. By John
Ellement and Anthony Flint. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAREGIVER-STRESS (Undated) _ Caring for a loved one can be
hazardous _ even fatal _ researchers have found, in the first study
to document higher death rates among family caregivers. By Richard
A. Knox. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MA-HPHC-COPAYS (Boston) _ Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, New
England's largest HMO, has been ``secretly'' pocketing the profit
when its 1.5 million subscribers pay $5 copayments for prescription
drugs that actually cost the health plan $3 or even less per
prescription, class-action suit charges. By Richard A. Knox.
</P>
<P>
   MALDEN-SUIT (Boston) _ Malden Mills workers' file compensation
claim charging company negligence caused the fire that destroyed
the factory complex and severely injured them four years ago. By
Bruce Butterfield. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-DESIGN (Boston) _ Looking to boost its access to the
great minds of MIT, struggling Motorola is opening a consumer
product design lab in Cambridge. By Peter Howe. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
