<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8842 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-EXCHANGE-SFCHRON &LR;      12-14 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCHANGE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 THE EXCHANGE: Fruit Takes the Cake   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Never mind all the fruit cake jokes _
traditionalists among us still enjoy a slice of moist cake loaded
up with fruit and nuts with a holiday cup of tea or coffee.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gloria Silva wrote months ago that she'd like to treat her
husband to the fruit cake his late mother baked from an S &AMP; W label
recipe, but try as she might (she even wrote the company), she
couldn't find the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Well, surprise _ a reader just dug up that 40-some-year-old
recipe, and it sounds like a nice, old-fashioned cake.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Requests &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Judy Logan e-mails from Berkeley, ``I've never been able to
find a great pumpkin soup recipe that equals the one I had at San
Francisco's Silks restaurant over eight years ago . . . It was
about the consistency of cream and was full of subtle flavors that
didn't overwhelm the pumpkin flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ruby Cousnard of San Francisco is looking for a recipe she
lost for a lemon cake with crushed pineapple, topped with coconut
and marshmallows. Does that ring a bell with anybody?
</P>
<P>
   _ Norma Dresser of Lafayette wants a recipe for a
vanilla-flavored cornstarch pudding. She wrote to the Kingsford
starch company, who sent her recipes _ but not the one she was
looking for.
</P>
<P>
   _ Karl Wilson has fond memories of  &LR; gl &LR; u &LR; hwein &LR;  (hot spiced
wine) served in ski huts when he was an exchange student in
Austria. He has tried spice mixes for mulled wine but finds them
``too much like potpourri.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Send requests and contributions to ``The Exchange,'' Food &LR; 
 &LR; Department, The San Francisco Chronicle, San Francisco, Calif. &LR; 
 &LR; 94103-2988. Or, send e-mail to  &LR; food &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;  Include your &LR; 
 &LR; name, address, daytime telephone number and the source for your &LR; 
 &LR; recipe. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Recipes cannot be returned and have not been tested in &LR; 
 &LR; Chronicle kitchens. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
S&AMP;W TEMPTATION FRUITCAKE
</P>
<P>
   Marillyn Serrao of Stockton copied this from the label of a jar
of S&AMP;W cake mix that she saved about 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound glace fruit mix
</P>
<P>
   1 cup almonds, slivered
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raisins, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1 cup currants
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fruit juice (or brandy)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup molasses
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brandy flavoring or sherry (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon mace
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the fruit mix, nuts, raisins, currants, fruit juice or
brandy, the molasses, brandy flavoring or sherry and spices in a
large bowl. Mix well and let stand while preparing the batter.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the flour, salt and soda. Cream the butter and
sugar until fluffy. Beat in the eggs, 1 at a time. Stir in the
sifted flour mixture. Fold in the fruit/nut mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Pack the batter firmly into two 71/2 x 31/2 x 21/4-inch loaf
pans that have been lined with heavy white wrapping paper (or
bakers' parchment), well greased.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a preheated slow oven (300 degrees) for about 13/4
hours. (Use aluminum or bright tin pans. If dark tin or glass pans
are used, double-line with paper and slightly reduce baking time.)
Start testing for doneness with a toothpick at the end of 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Remove cakes from pans and let cool. When thoroughly cold,
remove the paper and store in an air-tight container.
</P>
<P>
   May be served immediately, but aging in a cool place for about 3
weeks will improve the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Serrao likes to soak cheesecloth in brandy and wrap the
fruitcakes in this for a month or so.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3 pounds of cake; about 14 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 415 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 72 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 13 g fat (5 g saturated), 63 mg cholesterol, 225 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
