<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8843 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GAYVOTE-COX     12-14 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYVOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley, Gore compete for gay vote
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last spring, when Bill Bradley was still a blip on
the political radar, Vice President Al Gore's campaign sat down
with two dozen gay and lesbian leaders in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the meeting, led by Gore's former campaign
manager, Craig Smith, was to build support for Gore in New York's
influential gay and lesbian community, according to Kevin Finnegan,
the president of a gay Democratic club and one of those who
attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became clear that what they really meant by 'support' was
money,'' Finnegan recalled. ``We said, 'Look, we don't know what
the vice president's positions are and where he's going to take
things.' Craig Smith didn't know anything. . . It was a very
disappointing meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Bill Bradley, who in the summer and early fall organized
several of his own meetings with New York gay and lesbian leaders.
Bradley's spade work paid off. Two weeks ago, he picked up
endorsements from several prominent gay and lesbian activists,
including Finnegan and two New York city council members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley reached out to the community in a way that Gore did
not,'' said Finnegan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is now doing some outreach of his own. On Monday, he issued
a three-sentence statement calling for an end to the
administration's ``Don't ask, Don't tell'' policy toward gays and
lesbians in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's opposition to the 1993 policy, universally decried by gay
and lesbian advocacy groups, ranks as one of his highest profile
breaks with the Clinton administration. The policy, which First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton last week also denounced, prohibits
superiors from investigating or asking about the sexual orientation
of military personnel. But it allows gay service men and women to
be discharged if they talk about their sexuality openly.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's decision to publicly abandon ``Don't ask, Don't tell,''
which aides say he privately opposed for years, underscores the
extent to which the vice president has had to jettison his
political strategy of focusing on the general election and the
eventual Republican nominee in favor of one that confronts the
threat Bradley poses for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is now having to fight Bradley for votes among a
constituency that, according to some gay and lesbian leaders, he
took for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The intensifying contest for votes among gay and lesbian
Americans also illustrates much about Bradley. While Bradley has
publicly disparaged the politics of playing to special interest
groups, privately he has waged an aggressive campaign to reach out
to key constituencies within the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In September, following several private meetings with gay and
lesbian leaders in New York, Bradley announced his support for
virtually every major initiative supported by the gay and lesbian
community, including opposition to ``Don't ask, Don't tell,'' and
support for full equality of benefits for domestic partners. He
remains opposed to government sanction of gay and lesbian
marriages, and as a New Jersey senator Bradley voted for the
Defense of Marriage Act, which defined marriage as a union between
a man and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's willingness to learn about issues important to gays
and lesbians won over Ethan Geto, a gay activist in New York who
became one of Bradley's state co-chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody at that level comes to you and solicits your
advice, then they take all of your advice in an aggressive,
committed fashion, how can you not support them?'' Geto said.
</P>
<P>
   Gay and lesbian voters are only a small percentage of the
electorate, but they comprise an influential block within the
Democratic Party, particularly in New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley and Al Gore have learned to count,'' said Keith
Morrison, managing director of the Stonewall Democratic Federation,
the gay and lesbian wing of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison described the behind the scenes push for gay and
lesbian votes as the most intense of any previous presidential
election. ``It's almost to the point where you wish they didn't
have your phone number,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Campaign, the largest gay and lesbian advocacy
group, hasn't endorsed either Gore or Bradley but plans to endorse
soon, said executive director Elizabeth Birch.
</P>
<P>
   Birch welcomed Gore's opposition to ``Don't ask, Don't tell''
and hinted her organization would back the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming majority of gay people out there are
supportive of the vice president because they have seen action,''
Birch said. ``The fact is that Bill Bradley was never a leader on
these issues. He was always a good vote, but he was never a
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Gore has picked up the endorsement of three of the
state's five openly gay and lesbian public office holders. Bradley
has the endorsement of the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also won the endorsement of Ronald Johnson, the city's
former AIDS administrator and an influential figure in the fight
against the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with our early meetings with former senator
Bradley and the degree to which and the way he addressed issues
that were important to gay men,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson and others announced their support for Bradley,
Gore's New York campaign elevated state Sen. Tom Duane, an
influential gay legislator, to the position of honorary co-chairman
and named Emily Giske, vice chairman of the state party, as a
senior advisor to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Giske said the Gore campaign ``probably miscalculated'' in not
reaching out to New York gay and lesbian leaders sooner. But she
said that Bradley had made a calculated effort to split the gay and
lesbian vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bradley campaign was very astute,'' she said. ``They took
a big chart and they put it on the wall and they said, 'What makes
up this primary vote?' You can still do that in this primary.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, the majority of the gay and lesbian Democratic
clubs have not endorsed either candidate yet, although the vice
president enjoys widespread popularity.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the Golden state, Gore can take nothing for granted.
The Stonewall Democratic Club of Los Angeles, the largest
Democratic club in the state, gay or otherwise, endorsed Gore in
January.
</P>
<P>
   But many members are now unhappy with the early endorsement,
according West Hollywood city council member Steve Martin, a former
club president. Martin, who is not committed to either Gore or
Bradley, said he is considering offering a motion to rescind the
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense that Gore could wrap this up in the gay and
lesbian community and take our constituency for granted,'' Martin
said. ``I don't see that it's in our community's best interest to
swear allegiance to one Democratic candidate, when there is another
candidate who is wooing us and who's record is very credible on our
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bauman, the club's current president, said the majority of
Stonewall members still support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been consistently the gay and lesbian community's
best friend in the White House,'' Bauman said. ``Bradley has made
some proposals that are very progressive on gay rights, but I
always urge people to look at someone's record.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the top issues for gay and lesbian issues in California
is a ballot initiative scheduled for March 7 that would make gay
and lesbian marriages illegal. Bradley was the first presidential
candidate to announce his opposition to the ballot question, and
Gore quickly followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bradley also support hate crimes legislation,
another important issue among gay and lesbian voters. Bradley has
gone one step further than Gore, saying he would seek to amend the
1964 Civil Rights Act to include gays and lesbians as a protected
group of citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
