<SLUG> BC-BOOKROUNDUP-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: Cookbooks Offer Gift-Givers a Stocking Full of  Great
Ideas   By Karola Saekel 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  So many books, so little time . . . If you tried
to make every recipe published in books in 1999, you'd still be
cooking when the clock strikes midnight in the year 2001.
<P>
   Here's a round-up of books we especially liked this year
(several have already received the full review treatment in this
section, and some may get complete reviews later). Any of them
would make a good gift for a cook on your holiday list _ especially
if that cook is a Francophile. This year, French cookbooks
dominated the best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Daniel Boulud's Cafe Boulud Cookbook: French-American &LR; 
 &UR; Recipes for the Home Cook,'' &LR;  by Daniel Boulud (with Dorie
Greenspan; Scribner; 400 pages; $35) is modeled after this New York
celebrity chef's restaurant. Menus are divided into the categories
of classic French, seasonal, international inspirations and food
from the garden, and the book encourages creative mixing. Many
recipes are for complete entrees, including side dishes, so a cook
can recreate the whole dining experience. And, true to the title,
these are recipes for home meals, with only a few extravagances
that veer into restaurant cooking.
</P>
<P>
   _ In  &UR; ``Parisian Home Cookiversations, Recipes and Tips &LR; 
 &UR; From the Cooks and Food Merchants of Paris'' &LR;  (William Morrow; 335
pages; $25), Michael Roberts goes to great lengths to point out
that the French insistence on fresh ingredients does not mean
purchasing budget-busting luxury items and that many splendid
French home recipes don't require hours of complicated preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is an entertaining writer, and his anecdotes and
descriptions of markets and people bring the Paris food scene to
life.
</P>
<P>
   _ Veteran food writer Georgeanne Brennan entices readers to
catch the cadence of eating  &LR; a &LR;  la Fran &LR; c &LR; aise &LR;  in  &UR; ``Savoring &LR; 
 &UR; France: Recipes and Reflections on French Cooking,'' &LR;  a
Williams-Sonoma book with stunning scenic photos by Steven Rothfeld
(Time Life Books; 256 pages; $39.95). The book is especially strong
on the kind of first courses common in France but rarely found in
French restaurants abroad.
</P>
<P>
   _ Straddling the French-Spanish border, San Francisco chef
Gerald Hirigoyen (Fringale and Pastis restaurants) recalls his
boyhood in  &UR; ``The Basque Kitchen: Tempting Food from the &LR; 
 &UR; Pyrenees'' &LR;  (with Cameron Hirigoyen, HarperCollins; 262 pages;
$35).
</P>
<P>
   He offers a wealth of recipes for true Basque cooking, which he
calls rustic in the best sense of the term: excellent ingredients
simply prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Other local chefs share their enthusiasm as much as their
recipes in books published this year.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Rose Pistola Cookbook,'' &LR;  by Reed Hearon and Peggy
Knickerbocker (Broadway Books; 276 pages; $35) is packed with
recipes for the wonderful food that distinguish this North Beach
hot spot. Hearon focuses on the dishes that Italian immigrants from
Liguria brought with them when they came to San Francisco looking
for gold _ and stayed to build a city.
</P>
<P>
   Hearon's fish dishes _ like roast whole fish with artichokes and
potatoes, one of the restaurant's signature dishes _ are especially
wonderful. A home version is simple to make and its presentation is
the height of rustic elegance.
</P>
<P>
   _ In &UR; ``The Tra Vigne Cookbook: Seasons in the California Wine &LR; 
 &UR; Country,'' &LR;  Michael Chiarello (with Penelope Wisner; Chronicle
Books; 215 pages; $35), chef of Tra Vigne restaurant in St Helena,
draws on his sumptuous culinary heritage _ his father's homemade
wine, his grandfather's home-cured prosciutto, his mother's
vegetable garden _ combines it with a Northern California larder
and creates a distinctive cuisine rich with a sense of tradition
and seasonality.
</P>
<P>
   Chiarello bases much of his cooking on master recipes suitable
for each season. And while perfecting these and other Chiarello's
recipes may require perseverance from a novice home cook, results
will leave holiday guests with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alice Waters and crew brought us another book whose visual
appeal matches its culinary merits.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; ``Chez Panisse Cafe Cookbook'' &LR;  (with David Tanis and Fritz
Streif and illustrations by David Lance Goines; HarperCollins; 267
pages; $35) is a must-have for admirers of Waters and her
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the upstairs cafe with its eclectic
California/Proven &LR; c &LR; al/ Tuscan melange, this is a more
light-hearted book than previous ``Chez'' volumes, with
reminiscences about the restaurant giving it a personal touch.
</P>
<P>
   Like previous books, it makes a strong appeal for using Northern
California's agricultural bounty. A few recipes push the envelope,
but even though few people will want to make their own head cheese,
it's entertaining to read how this old-fashioned, waste-nothing
concoction is handled at the cafe.
</P>
<P>
   _ One of the most user-friendly books in the current crop is
former Chez Panisse and Monsoon restaurant pastry chef David
Lebovitz'  &UR; ``Room for Dessert,'' &LR;  (221 pages; HarperCollins; $30).
This well-illustrated volume deserves a prize for clearly laying
out the basics of the craft, from utensils and ingredients to
techniques and, of course, recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Lebovitz admits in his introduction that he left out some great
recipes because they fall into the category of Things Nobody Wants
to Do at Home (spinning sugar, tempering chocolate). Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Those recipes he considered appropriate for home kitchens are
wonderful: flourless chocolate macadamia cake, butterscotch flan,
fig cookies and a plum huckleberry upside-down cake that lifts this
homey cake into the heavenly category.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``West Coast Seafood: The Complete Cookbook,'' &LR;  by Jay Harlow
(Sasquatch Books; 366 pages; $23.95) is a thoroughly researched
volume, offering information on species, their inherent qualities,
seafood seasonality and safety and, of course, excellent recipes.
This book is particularly useful for Northern California cooks
because, true to its title, it deals with the creatures of the sea
that we can purchase, not the catch of Nantucket or the Gulf coast.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Weir Cooking: Recipes From the Wine Country,'' &LR;  by Joanne
Weir (Time-Life Books; 208 pages; $27.50) is based on the Northern
California author's television series by the same name. Preaching
the modern mantra of fresh and seasonal, Weir has a happily
unorthodox approach, encouraging cooks to experiment: ``Forget
about white with chicken, red with meat,'' she writes. ``Follow
your nose and your taste buds and enjoy what tastes good to you.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; `'San Francisco Flavors: Favorite Recipes From the Junior &LR; 
 &UR; League of San Francisco'' &LR;  (Chronicle Books; 319 pages; $27.50) is
a collection gleaned from the kitchens of San Francisco's movers
and shakers, without being a fawninrity book. The volume is
especially strong on that rarely emphasized meal _ brunch.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Short &AMP; Sweet,'' &LR;  by Melanie Barnard (Houghton Mifflin; 238
pages; $25) delivers what it promises _ desserts in a hurry. One of
the author's strategies is to embellish purchased ingredients like
high-quality pound cake and ice cream. It's a very useful guide for
time-pressed cooks.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``A Spoonful of Ginger,'' &LR;  by Nina Simonds (Alfred A. Knopf;
320 pages; $30) guides Western cooks through a broad range of
Korean, Chinese and Japanese recipes. Extensive lists and sidebars
provide a glimpse at history and philosophy, along with good tips
for using Asian ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Pie and Pastry Bible,'' &LR;  by Rose Levy Beranbaum
(Scribner; 692 pages; $35) is a highly acclaimed, exhaustive
treatment of the subjects. There is no faulting the results but for
the most part the recipes are so demanding and time-consuming that
this is a book for perfectionists and professionals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
