<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Piedmont Beats Tuscany for Italian Title   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Italian wine fans are divided over the best region
for red wine _ Piedmont or Tuscany? The controversy is not unlike
the one that divides lovers of California Cabernet Sauvignons _
Napa Valley or Alexander Valley?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Measuring the best Italian red wine region by the number of
wines with DOC and DOCG status, the clear-cut winner is Piedmont.
Eight DOCG wines and 44 DOC wines account for 80 percent of
Piedmont's total production, the highest in Italy; the average in
other regions is about 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Denominazione di Origine Controllata  &LR; is the system of Italian
wine production governed by national and regional authorities, in
compliance with the European Economic Community. The DOC covers
approved vines, the winemaking process and the selling of the wine
but does not guarantee quality. DOCG _ DOC with  &LR; Garantita &LR;  _ does
guarantee the authenticity of wines of ``particular esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   So, why does Piedmont have so many more DOC and DOCG wines than,
say, Tuscany?
</P>
<P>
   The hills of Piedmont account for a part of the high quality.
General wisdom says that hills are the best spots for growing
quality wine grapes. Piedmont also has varied soils, especially in
such noted DOCG zones as Barolo and Barbaresco, where there's a
complex mix of calcareous and sandy soils with veins of clay marl.
Further, the climate of Piedmont is right for the leading red
grapes _ Nebbiolo and Barbera _ plus such valuable whites as
Moscato Bianco (Asti Spumante), Arneis and Cortese, the grape of
Gavi or Cortese di Gavi.
</P>
<P>
   Nebbiolo is one of Italy's great classic red grapes and one of
the top red wine grapes of the world. Barolo and Barbaresco,
arguably Italy's best red wines, are made solely from Nebbiolo.
Nebbiolo has an unusual but pleasing nose of ripe plums, violets
and anise, with fresh fruit flavors, sometimes with a trace of
chocolate. Nebbiolo is the grape for Barolo, Barbaresco, Gattinara
and Ghemme.
</P>
<P>
   Barbera is known for its considerable natural acidity and fresh
berry aromas and flavors. Barbera d'Alba and Barbera d'Asti are the
most popular, but producers of Barbera del Monferrato are
campaigning to elevate the reputation of their wines. Barberas from
great vintages, like 1998, are rated among the best of Piedmont
reds.
</P>
<P>
   Moscato Bianco, one of many in a large family of Muscat grapes,
is the highly aromatic grape of lightly sparkling Moscato d'Asti
and Asti Spumante sparkling wines. It is the most widely planted
white grape in Piedmont.
</P>
<P>
   Arneis, grown in the Cuneo province, is considered by some to be
Piedmont's best white grape. Elegant and perfumed, it has finesse
and personality. Cortese is the other Piedmont white grape with
character and personality. Cortese is the grape of Cortese di Gavi
or Gavi and is used for still and sparkling wines.
</P>
<P>
   Piedmont is blessed with excellent growing conditions for a
variety of wine grapes. While reds, like Barolo and Barbera,
continue to get better with each vintage, Piedmont whites are the
wines to watch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Year 2000 Calendar &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Atlas Peak Vineyards, the Napa Valley producer of Sangiovese
wines and owned by Tuscany's Marchese Piero Antinori, has just
published a four-color Year 2000 Calendar, depicting the seasons of
Atlas Peak's hillside vineyards, the winery's aging caves and
images of winemaker John Falcone. The calendars are $12.95
(includes tax and postage) and are available by sending check or
money order to: Atlas Peak Vineyards, c/o Allied Dome Wines, USA,
Public Relations Dept., 375 Healdsburg Ave., 2nd Floor, Healdsburg,
CA 95448.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
