<SLUG> BC-LEARN-COOKIE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 LEARNING TO COOK: Teach Them to Bake and They'll Eat For Life   By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; One of the best gifts you can give young children
is a lesson in baking cookies. We all know that Santa Claus doesn't
bake, so cookies make a welcome present that children can give.
<P>
   Many years ago I taught baking classes to Brownies and Girl
scouts in Southern California. This recipe for Christmas Nut Chews
was the best _ and easiest _ recipe to make.
</P>
<P>
   To begin, read the recipe entirely. Turn the oven on to 350
degrees. Put all the ingredients on your work counter. For baking
this recipe, I like to use an 8-inch Pyrex pie dish. (The proper
way to measure pie plates or pans is to measure across the bottom,
not the top.)
</P>
<P>
   Because these are soft, chewy cookies, often called ``bar''
cookies, you can also cut them into large pieces and serve them as
dessert with a little whipped cream on top.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CHRISTMAS NUT CHEWS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 cup walnuts, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Instruction: Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Have ready an
8-inch diameter pie plate or an 8-inch square baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Put the butter into a small saucepan and place over low heat.
Stand right by the stove and tilt the pan as the butter begins to
melt so it all melts evenly. Pour the melted butter into the pie
plate (or pan) and tilt and turn the plate until the bottom is
completely covered with butter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mixing the Batter:  &LR; Crack the eggs into a mixing bowl and using
a fork, beat them until they are all one color and look well
blended. Add the sugar, flour, baking soda, salt and vanilla. Using
a large spoon, beat the cookie batter until it is completely
blended and smooth. Stir in the walnut pieces. Pour the batter into
the buttered pie plate (or pan).
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 12 to 15 minutes. Because ovens vary in temperature,
check at 10 minutes by touching the center gently. If it feels
firm, double-check by inserting a toothpick into the center; if it
comes out clean and not damp and sticky, the cookies are done.
Better to bake an extra minute or two if you are in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and place on a wire rack to cool. Cut into
wedges or squares.
</P>
<P>
   These freeze well if wrapped in 2 or 3 layers of plastic wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 12 to 14 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 150 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 19 g carbohydrate,
8 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 35 mg cholesterol, 76 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1850EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-BUMPING-COX     12-14 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-BUMPING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta improves its bumping rate
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines cut its chronically high passenger
bumping rate during the third quarter but still led the industry
for the first nine months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The government's latest Air Travel Consumer Report also shows:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hartsfield International Airport had the lowest percentage of
on-time arrivals among major U.S. airports during October. Airline
officials blamed the delays on runway repairs and bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consumer complaints about big airlines tailed off in October
compared with the previous two months but continue to run well
ahead of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes as major airlines today enact a slate of
service-enhancement measures ranging from higher liability caps for
lost luggage to better information about delays and cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   The industry offered the measures _ some of which only formalize
existing procedures _ to avoid calls for congressional action that
followed a wave of airline service horror stories last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Involuntary bumping, which occurs when planes are overbooked and
some passengers are put on later flights, has been a stubborn
statistical problem for Delta for two years. In the third quarter
Delta had the seventh-highest rate among the 10 major airlines. The
airline denied boarding to 1,567 passengers, or 0.61 per 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   That was down sharply from 5,519 such bumpings and a rate of
2.07 during the second quarter, when Delta was 10th. For the first
nine months of 1999, Delta bumped 15,230 passengers for a rate of
1.98, highest in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The latest quarter was the first to reflect the changes we're
making,'' said spokesman John Kennedy. ``We're en route to where we
want to be.'' He said Delta expects a rate of around 0.30 for the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   While only a tiny percentage of passengers are involuntarily
bumped, a comparatively high rate suggests an airline is too
aggressive in overbooking to hedge against no-shows. Bumping
aggravates gate pileups and delays as agents sort things out.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said Delta _ after lengthy delays _ has installed new
software to better manage overbooking. He said it is offering
incentives earlier to volunteers when bumping may be necessary,
usually credit toward a future flight.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has had more success improving on-time ratings, which many
passengers rate as their biggest concern. For the 12 months ended
in October, it was fourth out of 10 major airlines, with 77.8
percent of flights arriving within 15 minutes of the scheduled
time.
</P>
<P>
   But in October Delta fell to seventh, which Kennedy attributed
to runway work and bad weather at Hartsfield, its biggest hub. Only
68.2 percent of all Hartsfield arrivals were on time during the
month, down from 77 percent in September. Kennedy said operations
rebounded in November.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints to the U.S. Department of Transportation about major
carriers dropped to 1,086 in October from 2,265 in September. But
in October 1998 there were only 485.
</P>
<P>
   There were 142 gripes about Delta for the month, down from 290
in September but more than double the 68 of October 1998. Delta's
complaint rate was third-best in the industry, the same rank as a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Travel Consumer Report is available on the World Wide
Web: www.dot.gov/airconsumer/
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
