<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Let Them Eat Cake _ If It's From Pillsbury   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Your holiday guests are arriving and there's no
time to whip up a homemade dessert. Will your guests know you took
a shortcut?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Depends on which brand of cake mix you've bought, according to
The Chronicle's tasters. Today's panel tasted five yellow cakes
made from mixes. The name brands were close in price, depending on
the store. One lesser-known mix and a store brand were
significantly cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   We prepared the cakes according to package directions and served
them without frosting.
</P>
<P>
   The panel overwhelmingly agreed on a favorite, finding most of
the rest too sweet and artificial-tasting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pillsbury Moist Supreme  &LR; (181/4 ounces, $1.89-$2.29 at many
supermarkets) took top honors. Three panelists particularly enjoyed
the texture. Most liked the flavor, which one described as
``clean.'' But one panelist thought the cake was a bit sweet. Four
would buy it; one might.
</P>
<P>
   Second place was a tie between  &UR; Betty Crocker Super Moist &LR; 
(131/4 ounces, 99 cents-$2.29 at many supermarkets) and  &UR; Duncan &LR; 
 &UR; Hines Moist Deluxe  &LR; (181/4 ounces, $1.99-$2.29 at many
supermarkets). Panelists didn't care for the overly sweet flavor of
Betty Crocker, and complained that the cake was so moist that it
was gummy. Two panelists said the cake tasted like coconut (coconut
is not one of the ingredients). Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Two panelists also detected an overwhelming coconut flavor in
the Duncan Hines (coconut is not an ingredient). Others disliked
the artificial flavor _ one compared it to butter-flavored
microwave popcorn. Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jiffy &LR;  (9 ounces, 65 cents at Safeway) came in fourth. Three
panelists disliked the dry, crumbly texture, which one likened to a
cotton ball. Others thought its flavor was too mild; another found
it salty. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lucky &LR;  (181/4 ounces, $1.19 at Lucky, now Albertson's) came in
just below Jiffy, putting it in fifth place. One panelist liked the
moist texture, but others found the cake sticky and gummy. Two
panelists noted an eggy taste; others were put off by the
pronounced artificial flavor. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna Katzl,
chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot,
chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and
Menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and Kirk Webber,
chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are tasted
blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
