<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKIES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 German Christmas Cookies Evoke Heartfelt Holiday Memories  &HT;        By Karola Saekel 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; No matter how avant garde we are the rest of the
year, the winter holidays _ Thanksgiving, Hanukkah and Christmas _
are times that evoke nostalgia. It's unlikely anybody wants fusion
gingerbread men. The season calls for the kind of cookies you'd
expect Clara's parents to serve in cut-glass dishes in their parlor
in the Nutcracker.
<P>
   Of all the nationalities that have culinary Christmas
traditions, few are more deeply rooted than Germany's Christmas
cookies. Many families of German heritage follow an annual schedule
for making the sweets that accompany afternoon coffee or tea and
are brought out for visitors who drop by, right up to Epiphany or
Three Kings' Day on January 6.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in early November, pfeffern &LR; u &LR; sse, lebkuchen and other
honey-based cookies that need to ripen are stashed in tins. Later
come the marzipan confections, the macaroons, the tiny jam tarts
and butter and sugar cookies, some of which can be eaten the day
they are baked.
</P>
<P>
   We were given some old family recipes for the kinds of Christmas
cookies that can be made now by a Berkeley baker of German
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Lenore Griffin retired from the marathon baking she
used to do before Christmas (just as her octogenarian mother, Wilma
Schenk of San Francisco, did before her) some years ago. But she
passed the mantle on to her grown sons and nieces, especially Dion
Griffin, 39, an Alameda business executive who now regularly brings
trays of cookies to his parents' North Berkeley home.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls how in his youth, after all the cookies were cooked
they would cool for a day and the next day he and his brother would
decorate whatever they and their dad hadn't already devoured.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, mom would store the cookies in various cookies
cans . . . I would ravage through all of the cans and take as many
as possible and try to cover my tracks by stacking the cookies in
such a way as to give the illusion that the cans were still full,''
he chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year, I went a bit too far and mom barely had enough
cookies to serve on Christmas Eve. . . from that point forward, mom
would hide the cookies throughout the house, and when we wanted
some, she would slip away and get a plateful at a time from her
secret hiding places.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother's own early recollections of holiday baking have all
the elements of a Christmas tale. Born in San Francisco to
German-American parents, she was taken to Germany as a small child
for a visit to her father's ailing mother. The visit turned out to
be ill-timed. As the clouds of war gathered over Europe, the Schenk
family was not allowed to return to the United States and ended up
spending the war years in Germany, first in her father's native
city of Ulm and, after bombing raids claimed the family home, in
the nearby village of Langenau.
</P>
<P>
   In Ulm, she recalls, their 17th-century house had the
convenience of ``running cold water _ that was all.'' In Langenau,
the family ended up in an old farm house of similar simplicity.
Neither house had an oven. ``You made an appointment with the
baker,'' she says. ``When he was done with his bread baking, you
carried your cookie pans there and later brought them home _
through wind and snow and storm.'' Children were enlisted to this
chore, and while it may have engendered some physical discomfort
(warm clothing was hard to come by in war-time Europe), it added to
the mystique of holiday celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, once the family returned to the United States after
the war and Lenore married, she started perusing German cookbooks
published in this country to translate her old family recipes into
more standardized terms. Her sons _ Dion and his brother _ are
among the beneficiaries of these efforts. Instead of calling for a
nice lump of sweet (unsalted) fresh butter and 250 grams of sugar,
the Griffin family recipes now specify cups of sugar and cubes of
butter _ though it still has to be fresh and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Try These Simple Tips and the Perfect Cookie is Yours &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Baking holiday cookies is an ancient tradition, and you need not
be a Houdini of the kitchen to produce wonderful results. But there
are a few do's and don'ts that will help assure success:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Use only top-quality ingredients.  &LR; For most Christmas
cookies, that means unsalted butter, preferably European-style. Be
sure eggs are fresh and of the size specified in the recipe. Use
only pure cane sugar (that eliminates most store-brand sugars),
since beet sugar does not react the same in baking. Use
high-quality flour _ if you are an infrequent baker and your bag of
flour has been languishing in your pantry for a year, purchase a
new bag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Be sure spices are fresh and fragrant.  &LR; If you bake with
two-year-old cinnamon or cloves or ground nutmeg, you might as well
be using sawdust. Baking powder needs to be used before the pull
date or the results will be decidedly flat. (To test, dissolve 1
teaspoon in 1/4 cup water _ if it doesn't bubble, it's lost its
oomph.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Grind your own nuts and almonds.  &LR; Unless they are extremely
fresh, preground nuts also tend to resemble sawdust. And always
taste nuts before using them. Stale nuts can spoil the finest
recipe. A nut grinder _ it resembles a small meat grinder _ is
ideal for grinding, but a food processor works fine if you don't
let the nuts liquefy. When possible, add a little of the sugar or
flour from a recipe to the nuts in the processor to help keep them
dry and fluffy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Make the dough ahead, if you like.  &LR; Most doughs can be made a
day or two ahead _ some, in fact, have to rest at least overnight _
and many can be frozen for up to a month. You can make the dough
when you have a little spare time, then bake cookies when needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Handle dough carefully.  &LR; Berkeley's Lenore Griffin, who has
passed her German cookie recipes on to her sons and nieces,
recommends a simple technique common in central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For buttery doughs, dust the rolling surface and rolling pin
with a mixture of 2 tablespoons sugar and 1/3 cup flour. The sugar
keeps the flour from clumping and facilitates handling delicate,
rich doughs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Use baking parchment.  &LR; Long used by European home bakers,
baking parchment is becoming increasingly available in the United
States. There are several brands available in cookware shops;
Reynolds now also makes one that is carried in many supermarkets.
It is the single biggest time saver and shortcut to success in
cookie baking. There is virtually no cleanup: Whatever might stick
to baking sheets _ bits of dough, spilled sugar, chocolate run-off
_ sticks to the parchment instead and can just be tossed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Handle cookie sheets properly.  &LR; If you don't own many cookie
sheets, grab the used sheet with a pot holder as soon as the
cookies are removed, discard parchment and run cold water over the
back of the sheet. It will cool it for almost immediate reuse
(never place cookies on a hot sheet) without getting the baking
surface wet. Just slap on another sheet of parchment, and you're
ready to bake the next batch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Avoid mixing cookie dough in a food processor.  &LR; The speed of
these machines means that little air is incorporated into mixtures,
which drastically changes cookie dough texture _ and final results.
Electric mixers are generally fine, but don't overmix, especially
when creaming butter and sugar. If you cream as thoroughly as you
would for a cake, the cookies will flatten out when they bake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GRIFFIN FAMILY GERMAN BUTTER COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   These cookies and the macaroons are a natural pair _ both in
terms of taste and texture contrast and because this recipe calls
for 10 egg yolks and the macaroons 8 egg whites.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   10 yolks from large eggs
</P>
<P>
   21/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   71/2 cups sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   1 pound unsalted butter (no substitutes), softened
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup flour mixed with 2 tablespoons sugar for rolling out
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Food coloring (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Beat the yolks until light and lemon-colored; beat in the sugar
until very creamy, about 5 minutes with an electric mixer at medium
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Mound the flour on a pastry board or in a very large bowl. Cut
the butter into thin slices and work into the flour with a pastry
blender or your fingertips, until the mixture is the consistency of
coarse meal. Add the yolk mixture and fold in, using first a
spatula and then your fingers. Knead until a smooth dough is
formed. Shape into a smooth ball, flatten slightly, wrap in wax
paper and refrigerate at least 1 hour or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to bake, preheat the oven to 375 degrees. Sprinkle a
board with a little of the flour/sugar mixture to prevent sticking.
Lightly coat a rolling pin with the same mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Using one quarter of the dough at a time, roll out to about
1/8-inch thickness and cut with cookie cutters to desired shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Reroll scraps with next dough quarter and proceed until all
dough is rolled out and cut.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cookies on ungreased baking sheets and bake for 8 to
10 minutes, until the edges just turn golden. Remove cookies to
racks to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the powdered sugar and lemon juice, adding enough
water to make a spreadable mixture. Divide between 2 or 3 small
bowls or cups and add different food colorings as desired. These
are delicate cookies, so pastel shades seem more suitable than
bright colors.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not wish to color the cookies, either brush unbaked
cookies with an egg wash made from 2 yolks mixed with about 1
teaspoon water, or sprinkle them with colored sugar crystals before
baking.
</P>
<P>
   Store cookies in airtight containers for a few days or freeze
for up to a month.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 8 to 12 dozen cookies, depending on size.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 65 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 9 g carbohydrate, 3
g &LR;   &LR; fat (2 g saturated), 22 mg cholesterol, 1 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GERMAN HAZELNUT MACAROONS
</P>
<P>
   These cookies should not be hurried. Don't skip either the
resting time for the unbaked dough and cookies or the ripening. If
you start them by this weekend, they'll be perfect at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 cups hazelnuts or filberts
</P>
<P>
   8 whites from large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   21/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 cup powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Grate 4 cups of the nuts, preferably with a European nut grater.
If using a food processor, use on/off pulse, making sure you don't
over-process to the point of creating nut butter.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg whites in a large bowl with an electric beater
until stiff, starting at low speed and switching to medium as soon
as whites start to mound. Gradually add the sugar and continue
beating until very smooth and glossy, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Fold in the vanilla and grated nuts. Refrigerate for from 2 to 6
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Drop the batter by heaping teaspoons onto ungreased cookie
sheets lined with parchment paper or foil, dull-side up, spacing
about 11/2 inches apart. Press a whole nut in the center of each
cookie. Let stand overnight in a cool room.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a 300 degree oven until the cookies are gently browned
and can be easily lifted from the paper with a spatula, about 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the cookies to racks. Have ready the powdered sugar mixed
with enough water to make a smooth glaze. Brush this over cookies
while they are still warm. Cool completely, then store in an
airtight container, adding 1/2 apple to retain moisture. Age in a
cool place for 5 days to 1 week, checking to make sure the apple
doesn't rot.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 6 dozen cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIES: &LR;   &LR; 100 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 9 g carbohydrate,
7 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 6 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VIENNESE CRESCENTS
</P>
<P>
   These Austrian cookies have become part of the holiday
repertoire all over central Europe. Some recipes call for almonds.
This one uses walnuts or pecans or a mixture of the two.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 pound powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 vanilla beans, broken into pieces
</P>
<P>
   The Dough
</P>
<P>
   1 cup walnuts or pecans, finely ground
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsalted butter (no substitutes), softened
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   At least 2 days before making the cookies, combine the powdered
sugar and vanilla beans in a tightly closed jar. Let stand at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all dough ingredients in a large bowl and mix into a
smooth dough. Shape into a ball, wrap in wax paper and refrigerate
at least 1 hour for easier handling. (If you refrigerate the dough
overnight, let it sit at room temperature 1/2 hour before shaping.)
</P>
<P>
   Break off pieces about 1 teaspoon in volume. Roll into balls,
then into ropes about 3 inches long, tapering ends. Place on
ungreased cookie sheets (covering them with parchment makes cleanup
a snap), bending them into a crescent shape.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a 350 degree oven until cookies just turn golden, 10 to
15 minutes. As soon as the cookies are cool enough to handle, roll
them in a bowl of the vanilla sugar. Place on a rack to cool. When
completely cool, roll in sugar again, then store in an airtight
container.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in a cool place for 5 days to a week, or freeze up to 1
month.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 4 to 5 dozen cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 80 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 10 g carbohydrate, 4
g &LR;   &LR; fat (2 g saturated), 8 mg cholesterol, 1 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COENEN FAMILY CINNAMON STARS
</P>
<P>
   This is a recipe handed down in my mother's family. While these
traditionally are baked in a star shape, there is no reason not to
use other cookie cutters.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup unsalted butter (no substitutes), softened
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons lemon zest (from about 1 large lemon)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon mace
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   Large pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   2 extra-large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup blanched almonds, finely ground
</P>
<P>
   1 cup walnuts, finely ground
</P>
<P>
   13/4 cups sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup flour mixed with 2 tablespoons sugar for rolling out
</P>
<P>
   Topping
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark rum or orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Food coloring and colored sugar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Cream the butter in a large bowl until light. Gradually add the
sugar, beating until the mixture is light and fluffy. Add the lemon
zest, mace, allspice and salt along with the egg yolks. Beat until
blended.
</P>
<P>
   Using a rubber spatula, fold in the nuts and flour. Briefly
knead to form a smooth dough. Shape into a ball, flatten slightly,
wrap in wax paper and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The dough will still be sticky, so cover a board with wax paper
or baking parchment and sprinkle it and the rolling pin liberally
with the flour/sugar mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Divide dough into 3 parts and roll the first one to 1/8 inch
thickness. Cut out with star or other cookie cutters.
</P>
<P>
   Reroll the trimmings with the second part of dough and proceed
to cut and roll until all dough is used up.
</P>
<P>
   Using a thin spatula, carefully move the cookies to ungreased
baking sheets covered with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a 350 degree oven until the cookies turn light brown at
edges, 8 to 10 minutes. Let cool a couple of minutes, then
carefully remove to racks.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the powdered sugar with the rum, adding enough water to make
the mixture a spreadable consistency. Add food coloring if desired.
Glaze cookies while they are still warm and sprinkle with colored
sugar if desired.
</P>
<P>
   When completely cool, store in airtight containers for at least
2 days and up to 10 days, or freeze for up to a month.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3 to 4 dozen cookies, depending on size.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 100 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 10 g carbohydrate,
6 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 17 mg cholesterol, 4 mg sodium, 0
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
