<HEADER>
A8859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-HISPANICS-POLICE-HNS &LR;      12-14 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-POLICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC GROUPS URGE POLICE TO HIRE MORE LATINOS AS WAY TO END
`RACIAL PROFILING' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police harassment of Hispanics nationwide will
continue largely unabated until law-enforcement agencies recruit,
hire and retain more Latino officers, Hispanic civil rights and
police organizations said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A greater Hispanic presence on police forces will reverse the
rising tide of instances when officers single out young Latino men,
they said. The victims are targeted for traffic stops and verbal
and physical abuse based on the invidious stereotype that all
youthful Hispanics are criminals, said Raul Yzaguirre, president of
the National Council of La Raza.
</P>
<P>
   This ``racial profiling'' of Latinos by police is symptomatic of
law-enforcement agencies that, while ostensibly serving Hispanic
communities, have few Latino officers, added Houston police Officer
Adrian Garcia, president of the National Latino Peace Officers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic groups' call for more Latino officers mirrors a
similar plea from the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, which has said young black men have also been
targeted by police based on the same nefarious stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread use of racial profiling has led Hispanic and
African-American rights groups to suggest jokingly that the police
have created a new traffic offense _ ``driving while brown'' or
``driving while black'' _ that allows officers to pull over
minority motorists summarily.
</P>
<P>
   Yzaguirre, while denouncing racial profiling, said officers who
harass minorities because of their race are an ``aberration'' and
threaten the reputations of the overwhelming majority of officers
who valiantly strive to protect all residents, regardless of their
ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Garcia, who directs Houston Mayor Lee Brown's anti-gang office,
added:
</P>
<P>
   ``Many officers don't come from the background of the community
they're policing. This could create an issue of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To increase the number of Hispanic officers, Yzaguirre and
Garcia said their groups will encourage young Latinos to consider
law-enforcement careers. The Hispanic American Police Command
Officers Association will join the groups in the recruitment
effort.
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia said the Latino groups ``have a lot of work to do''
to ensure the proportion of Hispanic officers mirrors the
percentage of Hispanics in the cities they serve. For example, the
Houston population is 26 percent Hispanic, but Latinos hold fewer
than 8 percent of the police force's supervisory positions, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Houston Police Department's 5,439 officers as of Dec. 1,
960, or 18 percent, were Hispanic, HPD reported.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the National Council of La Raza nor the police groups
had figures on the number of Hispanic officers nationwide. But the
council said other large-city police departments have staff
inequities similar to Houston's.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, which is 33 percent Hispanic, has a police force in
which Hispanics comprise 22 percent of the officers and 14 percent
of the supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   The Metro-Dade Police Department serves Miami and neighboring
Florida cities, a community that is nearly 50 percent Latino. But
fewer than 14 percent of the department's supervisors are Hispanic,
the council reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos are more and more (being) targeted by police abuse,''
Yzaguirre said. ``We need to have officers from our own
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal lawmakers are considering legislation that would protect
from retaliation officers who blow the whistle on colleagues who
harass people solely because of their race. Congress is also
weighing a bill that would require the Justice Department to
collect data on instances of racial profiling nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
