<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH EXPECTS TIGHT RACE FOR GOP NOMINATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ On the heels of an energetic debate exchange
with chief rival John McCain, presidential hopeful George W. Bush
said Tuesday that he expects the race for the Republican nomination
to heat up but hopes it will not turn ugly.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor also reaffirmed his support for the ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy of allowing homosexuals to serve in the
military, despite complaints from the White House and elsewhere
that it isn't working.
</P>
<P>
   Bush discussed those issues and received the endorsement of
former presidential contender Lamar Alexander in a news conference
the morning after turning in his liveliest debate performance so
far in his White House race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose earlier debate appearances had been criticized as
lackluster, said he liked the ``free-flowing'' format of Monday
night's televised forum in Iowa, which featured sharp exchanges
between him and McCain over ethanol tax breaks, tax cuts and
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed myself last night,'' Bush said. He said he liked the
opportunity to directly question his opponents and looked forward
to future ``interchanges'' in the nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the early Republican front-runner, is believed still to
have a large lead in Iowa, the state that holds the first
nominating contest Jan. 24, and one that McCain has virtually
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   But recent polls indicate that McCain, a senator from Arizona
and a former POW in Vietnam, has surpassed Bush in New Hampshire,
site of the nation's first primary Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he expected a ``tight'' race for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like a good fight,'' he said. ``I like competition. That's
what the primaries are about. The question is will the candidates
pledge not to let them deteriorate into mudfests, and I'm going to
keep it positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he hoped the other candidates would take time during
the upcoming holidays to ``reflect'' about positive campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK for someone to be feisty, but there is a difference
between feistiness and ugliness,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he still supported the ``don't ask, don't tell''
policy for gays and lesbians in the armed services, even though the
Defense Department has ordered a review of complaints that gay
service members are being harassed.
</P>
<P>
   And Vice President Al Gore, a candidate for the Democratic
presidential nomination, has called for the policy to be abolished
and homosexuals allowed to serve openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support don't ask, don't tell, and I think it ought to be
made to work,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the next commander-in-chief has got to send one
clear signal. We're not going to tolerate abuse. We expect people
to be treated with respect throughout the military,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, a former Tennessee governor who ended a six-year
quest for the presidency in August after finishing sixth in an Iowa
straw poll, said he was now backing Bush because his performance
has been ``solid'' and ``presidential'' and he had experience as an
elected, executive officeholder.
</P>
<P>
   When he dropped out of the race, Alexander had suggested that
Republicans were in too big a hurry to nominate Bush and said they
may discover later that he was too inexperienced to be president.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, with Bush standing nearby, Alexander said Bush had
``earned my respect the old-fashioned way _ he defeated me.''
</P>
<P>
   When reporters persisted in asking Alexander questions about his
apparent change of heart about Bush's qualifications, Bush stepped
in to end the news conference. ``Quit harassing the man,'' said
Bush, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
