<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8881 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-ATTACK-BOS &LR;      12-14 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-ATTACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
45,000 CIVILIANS TRAPPED AS RUSSIANS BLAST GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND DMITRY SHALGANOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ Thousands of civilians were trapped in
Chechnya's capital, Grozny, Tuesday after Russian forces launched a
fierce artillery assault on separatist militants holed up in the
besieged city.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of heavy fighting between Russian troops and Chechen
militia fighters cast doubt on the ability of up to 45,000
civilians in Grozny to reach safe corridors that Russia promised to
set up to allow them to escape the barrage.
</P>
<P>
   Facing international pressure to give people more time to get
out, Russia last week delayed an ultimatum that its troops would
kill anyone who remained in the city after Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few hundred civilians left the city following the
ultimatum. Refugees who did said that many of those left inside are
old or have small children and are afraid or unable to leave their
basement shelters and make the long trek to the Russian checkpoints
outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, reports from Grozny described constant artillery fire.
An Internet Web site run by a rebel leader said the assault on the
city by Russian forces ``is under way practically at full scale.''
A Russian Defense Ministry spokesman denied that report, but the
Interfax news agency quoted military sources as confirming that
clashes had taken place near the airport, on the eastern side of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders deny they will launch a head-on assault of
Grozny, a tactic that resulted in heavy Russian losses in Moscow's
failed 1994-1996 campaign against the rebels. Instead, the
commanders said, they will use special forces commandos, and
pro-Moscow Chechen irregulars to take the city bit by bit.
</P>
<P>
   The military Tuesday also acknowledged the loss of a Su-25 jet
and two helicopters in fighting in southern Chechnya. The rebel-run
Web site (www.Kavkaz.org) said Chechen fighters had shot down two
jets and three helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, about 100 refugees, many of them elderly women, left
Grozny on foot and made their way to a checkpoint established by
the Russians in Alkhan-Yurt, 2 miles southwest of the capital.
There, they were picked up by a bus and five trucks sent by Russian
Emergencies Minister Sergei Shoigu.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Shoigu said at a briefing that only about 2,200
civilians had been able to leave through the corridors. He said
8,000 to 30,000 more remained in the city. Moscow's senior envoy to
Chechnya, Nikolai Koshman, said on Saturday that 45,000 civilians
were still in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Shoigu, repeating Russian charges that the separatists are
preventing civilians from escaping, called on Chechen leader Aslan
Maskhadov to help get them out.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based organization Human Rights Watch said Tuesday
that Russian troops along the safe corridor were exacting bribes
from people wishing to leave Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Many refugees are like Taisa Shamkanova, who said she had been
living in a basement and was unaware of the ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have left earlier, but I really didn't believe it
would be so bad,'' Shamkanova told the Associated Press, referring
to the daily attacks on Grozny. ``And then I was just afraid to
leave the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   Elections for Russia's parliament will be held Sunday, and
opinion polls show most people approve of the campaign against the
Chechen rebels, who twice last summer invaded the neighboring
Russian region of Dagestan and whom Moscow accuses of bomb blasts
in Russian cities that killed almost 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders have criticized Moscow's tactic of pounding
rebel positions from afar with such weapons as antipersonnel
rockets. Such strikes, which cannot be aimed accurately, have sent
more than 200,000 Chechen civilians fleeing, destroyed entire
towns, and killed hundreds, perhaps thousands, all while largely
sparing the rebel fighters, who are better able to protect
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday Knut Vollebaek, the Norwegian foreign minister who is
chairman of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, visited Dagestan and called for an immediate cease-fire.
Russian officials rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, who attended the launching of a
new strategic missile in northern Russia Tuesday, used the occasion
to warn the West against criticizing its offensive in breakaway
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's popularity ratings in polls have soared during the
fighting in Chechnya, and few Russian leaders have dared speak out
against the campaign. Tuesday, a rare voice of concern was raised
by Adolf Shayevich, Russia's chief rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today in Grozny there are 50,000 people. Will the remaining
50,000 be exterminated to get rid of those three or four thousand
fighters? . . . The state should not act like this,'' the rabbi
said in Moscow. ``They are Russian citizens as well. . . . Why is
society so calm about what is going on there?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian General Gennady Troshev said his troops had
cleared Chechen rebels from Shali, the last major lowland town
apart from Grozny they had yet to seize. Russian forces have also
begun heavily bombing and shelling the foothills and mountains in
the south.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels there are well dug-in, according to the crew of a
Mi-8 helicopter that was shot down on Monday while on a mission to
find the pilot of the downed Su-25 jet.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels ``fought well,'' said the helicopter's commander, who
asked that only his first name, Slava, be used. ``They had an
entire firebase set up. They hit us with a heavy machine gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Slava managed to crash-land the aircraft safely enough for his
crew and nine Russian commandos to avoid serious injury. But as
soon as they dragged themselves from the wreckage, they came under
heavy fire from rebels.
</P>
<P>
   They held on for 30 minutes until they were rescued by two more
helicopters that chased away the rebels with rocket fire. Not far
away, two other helicopters were shot down, killing six Russians.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Filipov reported from Moscow, Shalganov from Mozdok.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
