<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA OPENS DESIGN LAB NEAR MIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Looking to tap into one of the nation's
hottest technology-development areas, Motorola Inc. says it wlil
open a $5 million consumer product design laboratory near the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be closer to where there's a lot of action,''
Motorola president Robert L. Growney said in an interview Tuesday.
``There's just lots and lots of ideas around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge is among eight sites chosen by the Schaumberg,
Ill.-based company for consumer product design labs. The others
include San Francisco, Milan, Seoul and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's stock and corporate reputation took a beating during
the mid-1990s amid stalled earnings and a disastrous investment in
the now-bankrupt $3 billion Iridium satellite-phone project.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last 16 months, a turnaround effort has boosted
Motorola stock from less than $43 a share to as high as $129, and
company officials hope to turbo-charge efforts to develop new
wireless communications devices by tapping in to the MIT and
Kendall Square tech communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a company with 70 years of history, and we've done some
fantastic things, and we've done some dumb things,'' Growney said.
``We've just exited one of our dumb periods.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola also will use its new office at Two Cambridge Place,
opening in February, as a field office for its venture-capital arm,
which has taken stakes quietly in more than 20 local startup
companies involved in communications, semiconductor research and
biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Growney would not identify local recipients of Motorola
investment, saying, ``My competitors would love to know the precise
direction we're headed in.'' But he said he sees ``significant
opportunity'' for more investments locally, aimed at supporting
Motorola product development and research.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Motorola designers have been demonstrating a
prototype Dick Tracy-style wristwatch phone and super-cheap phone
handsets that are activated by a credit card with a number keypad
built in. Wireless companies could sell calling time through the
cards and give away the matchbook-size handset.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola expects to employ 20 designers at the 8,000-square-foot
lab on the outskirts of Kendall Square, including people who now
work at its Advanced User Interactions Lab in Illinois. Motorola
has 1,000 Massachusetts employees now, chiefly at a Mansfield
plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really looking to capture the Cambridge buzz,'' said Dan
Williams, director of consumer design and innovation. One focus of
the new lab will be improving ``wearable,'' voice-controlled
communications devices that could be as small as a collar stay in a
shirt, a pendant or a cufflink.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones and related gear accounted for about 42 percent of
Motorola's 1998 net sales of $29.4 billion. Radio devices were 18
percent, and pagers and other information and media products
accounted for 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the Schaumburg, Ill., company has
sponsored a group of seven to nine ``Motorola Fellows'' associated
with MIT's Media Lab who have been developing new concepts for
wireless communication.
</P>
<P>
   Current fellow Rob Poor, an MIT PhD candidate, has been working
on a concept he calls the ``embedded network'' _ equipping a vast
array of objects, and even people's bodies, with devices that
communicate by low-power radio waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday there will be network connections in almost everything
in our world, not unlike the way there is printing on almost
everything in our world,'' said Poor, a Silicon Valley expatriate
whose past jobs include working for the Grateful Dead rock band and
George Lucas's film studio.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, Poor thinks wireless phone systems could be
developed that would use each phone to relay calls throughout the
system, eliminating the need for base stations with tall antennas
and sharply reducing power needs for each phone.
</P>
<P>
   Once radio transmitters become cheap enough, Poor also has ideas
for equipping individual Federal Express packages and FedEx drop
boxes with chips to communicate the location of packages. Lost
packages literally could tell carriers where they were to be
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Growney said the company also sees huge new markets in adapting
wireless devices for use in people's cars. ``The auto is going to
become like the office and the home. It is going to have an
enormous information content,'' Growney said. People must be able
to get at by voice-recognition systems or other options that
require minimal distraction from driving, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
