<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NKOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN RESTORES FOOD AID TO NORTH KOREA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a move that could help North Korea feed its hungry
people this winter, the Japanese government said Tuesday that it
would lift restrictions on food aid to the Communist country and
begin formal negotiations to establish diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the lifting of sanctions, Japan's chief cabinet
secretary, Mikio Aoki, said Japan and North Korea planned to hold
preliminary talks by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring food aid to North Korea, which is in desperate need
after years of shortages and famine, is seen as a necessary first
step toward diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo suspended all food aid after North Korea fired a
multistage rocket that flew over Japan and into the Pacific Ocean
in August 1998, setting off fears across East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the dire hunger situation in North Korea, it would be
difficult for Japan to come to the diplomatic table without at
least offering some help,'' said Hajime Izumi, a professor of
political science at Shizuoka University. ``Lifting sanctions is
important because it clears the way. The question now is what will
North Korea do with this new opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Aoki said the government would not immediately restore food aid
to North Korea but instead would ``make a comprehensive decision
after closely addressing the progress of the preliminary talks and
North Korea's responses.'' There was no immediate comment from
North Korea Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There is still strong opposition in Japan to providing food to
North Korea. Many Japanese are still upset that North Korea fired a
missile over their territory and that the country has not accounted
for the whereabouts of 10 Japanese citizens that intelligence
officials here maintain were abducted by North Korean agents in the
1970s and  &UR; ' &LR; 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has proposed that during the talks, the Red Cross
organizations of both countries hold discussions on issues
including food aid, visits to Japan by Japanese spouses of North
Koreans and the disappearance of the Japanese citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement underscores a remarkable improvement in
historically bitter relations between North Korea and Japan, which
only a few months ago appeared to be archenemies.
</P>
<P>
   In August, much of Japan was jittery after North Korea said it
planned to test a new long-range ballistic missile. In retaliation,
Japan threatened to bar Koreans living in Japan from sending cash
and goods to North Korea. The remittances, estimated to be as much
as $1 billion a year, are a major source of capital for North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   But the missile crisis came to an abrupt end when North Korea
agreed to suspend future missile launchings in exchange for
Washington's relaxing its own sanctions on the country.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea then began a major effort to improve its foreign
relations to gain economic assistance, holding talks with the
United States, Britain, Japan, other countries and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, political leaders from Japan and North Korea,
meeting in Pyongyang, the North Korean capital, reached an
agreement to ask their governments to return to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still considerable hurdles to overcome before
diplomatic ties are restored, and almost no one expects the
negotiations to be completed soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``With today's announcement we have basically returned to where
we were in August 1998 before the missile was fired,'' said Sadaaki
Numata, a spokesman for Japan's Foreign Ministry. ``This is the
start of what may be a long process.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development that also underscores the improving
state of relations with North Korea, the Japanese government said
Tuesday that an international consortium planned to sign an
agreement on Wednesday in Seoul, South Korea, to begin construction
of two nuclear power plants in North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium, which is led by the United States, was formed in
1994 to build two Western reactors and provide shipments of fuel
oil in exchange for North Korea's promise not to pursue its own
nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea, Japan and the European Union are shouldering the
bulk of the $4.6 billion project, and the United States is
supplying the fuel oil. The project ran into trouble last year
after North Korea test-fired its first missile and the Japanese
government immediately withdrew its $1 billion contribution.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan restored the financing several months later at the
urging of the United States and South Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
