<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BUGS BUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memo to: Vyacheslav Trubinokov, Director, KGB (now called SVR)
From: TLF.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Vyacheslav: This is a joke, right? You guys were bugging
the conference room of the State Department's Bureau of Oceans and
Environment? What were you thinking? You could bug the entire State
Department _ they could put a microphone on every floor and pipe
the conversations directly over to the Russian Embassy like Muzak _
and it wouldn't help you. What are you going to bug next? George W.
Bush's foreign policy library? The International House of Pancakes?
C-Span?
</P>
<P>
   People say that your bugging of the State Department means the
Cold War is still on. Wrong. It means the Cold War is truly over.
How else can one explain that you sent a Russian diplomat, in a car
with diplomatic license plates, to regularly park right in front of
State and then walk around suspiciously in a trench coat? Why
didn't he just wear a Sputnik hat and a sandwich board saying:
``Hi, I'm Boris. I'm spying for Russia. Could you please speak
louder?'' The KGB would  &UR; never &LR;  have been so sloppy if the Cold War
were still on.
</P>
<P>
   I feel sorry for you guys. You're making it too easy for the
FBI. So here's what I'm going to do. I'm going to give you a list
of the offices you should bug if you want to understand U.S. power
today.
</P>
<P>
   1. If you insist on bugging a Clinton cabinet member, then start
with Charlene Barshefsky, the top U.S. trade negotiator. She's got
real power. In this free-market age, she can shut down your steel
business with a stroke of her pen, if she accuses you of dumping
steel here at below market prices. What she thinks affects real
jobs and people in your country.
</P>
<P>
   2. If you can't get into Charlene's office, just go down three
blocks to that nice marble building next to the State Department.
It's the office of a guy named Alan Greenspan. Got that? Greenspan.
He's also known as ``The Master of the Universe.'' Trust me on this
one, what he thinks about interest rates and IMF loans to Russia
really matters.
</P>
<P>
   3. Do you know the way to San Jose? Go there, to 300 East Tasman
Dr., and bug the offices of Cisco Systems. It makes the routers
that connect the Internet, and the Internet is how we will
increasingly communicate, educate and do business in the coming
century. Yes, I know, missile size still matters _ if you plan to
launch a nuclear war with us that will obliterate your country,
too. But if you want to know what will drive day-to-day power, it's
bandwidth _ how much installed Internet capacity your country has
and how fast you can push stuff through it, which is Cisco's
specialty. Vyacheslav, you didn't lose the Cold War because you
didn't steal enough secrets from the State Department. You lost it
because you didn't steal enough secrets from Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bug the New Mexico home of the nuclear weapons engineer Wen
Ho Lee. This guy allegedly downloaded, from the Los Alamos nuclear
labs, America's most critical nuclear weapons secrets, then put
them on portable tapes and took them home. If the charges against
him are right, you could have downloaded more secrets from his home
computer than you ever would have found at the State Department _
and you wouldn't even have had to change the molding on his walls
to implant a bug. All you would have needed was a floppy disk.
</P>
<P>
   5. The most important thing you could bug would be any tour bus
that takes you around to the institutions and monuments of
Washington, D.C. I would recommend visiting the Supreme Court, the
Securities and Exchange Commission, the Federal Reserve, the
Federal Communications Commission, the FBI, the Jefferson Memorial,
the Lincoln Memorial and Congress. These offices hold the real
``secrets'' that Russia needs _ and they're all hiding in plain
sight. The secret of our strength is that we are a democracy and
free market built on the rule of law, with real oversight and
regulatory institutions. We're not built on corruption, arbitrary
rule and the smashing of Chechnya. Yes, I know Russia has real
elections, but your people don't have real democrats to vote for
yet, and even if they did, those democrats don't have real
institutions to operate. That's what you need to steal.
</P>
<P>
   You can catch the Tourmobile Sightseeing bus at 18th and
Pennsylvania. It's $16 for a narrated tour _ and the guides don't
even mind if you bring a tape recorder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
