presence along the shores of the Panama Canal symbolically ended
Tuesday when former President Jimmy Carter exchanged diplomatic
notes with President Mireya Moscoso and said simply, ``It's
yours.'' With those words began a new era in Panamanian life, a
journey that began in 1977 when Carter and Gen. Omar Torrijos
signed the controversial accords that would give Panama full
territorial sovereignty and total responsibility for the canal.
Moscoso pledged to meet the immense challenges that come with the
treaty, which she praised a model for the peaceful resolution of
international conflicts. By David Gonzalez.
