<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8890 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CAREGIVER-STRESS-BOS &LR;      12-14 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREGIVER-STRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY CITES STRESS HAZARDS OF CARING FOR ELDERLY LOVED ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caring for an elderly loved one can be hazardous _ even fatal _
researchers warned Tuesday in the first study to document higher
death rates among family caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly caregivers who reported feeling stressed by attending
for a disabled spouse were 63 percent more likely to die over the
next four years, compared to elders did not saddled with such a
burden.
</P>
<P>
   The study is part of a growing research effort to document
health effects of caregiver stress. Other recent studies have found
that family caregivers have more heart disease, high blood
pressure, impaired immune function, and metabolic abnormalities
than people the same age who don't have to attend to ailing family
members.
</P>
<P>
   The toll that family caregiving takes is an issue of mounting
importance not only to the invisible army of 15 million family
caregivers in this country, but to society, which often must pick
up the cost through Medicaid-paid nursing home care when family
care systems collapse.
</P>
<P>
   A survey last year by the National Alliance for Caregiving
estimated that family caregiving saves society from $113 billion to
$286 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, conducted by University of Pittsburgh scientists
and published in the Journal of the American Medical Association,
followed 392 elders who cared for their spouses and another 427
elders who lived with their spouses but did not have provide care.
</P>
<P>
   The study subjects, from 66 to 95 years old, were from North
Carolina, Maryland, California, and Pennsylvania. The caregivers
had spouses with diseases such as Alzheimer's, heart failure,
stroke, and cancer. However, many of the recipients of care were
not severely disabled.
</P>
<P>
   When the researchers took into account the levels of underlying
disease among the different groups of elders, they found that
something about the stress of caregiving imposes an additional risk
of death, irrespective of whatever underlying disease the caregiver
suffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have evidence that this group of strained caregivers had
higher levels of depression and anxiety, and reported higher rates
of not getting enough rest, not having time to exercise, not having
time to rest when they get sick,'' said Scott R. Beach, who did the
study with Richard Schulz. Both are at the University of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think being in this stressful situation prevents people
from being able to take care of themselves,'' Beach said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Beach and Schulz found that 13 percent over their total group of
819 elders died over a four-year period. Among those who were not
providing care to their spouses, the death rate was only 9 percent;
but among caregivers who reported being strained by the job, the
death rate was 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After adjusting for differing levels of underlying disease and
other factors, the stressed caregivers were 63 percent more likely
to die in four years compared to those not providing care for a
family member. The risk of death was not significantly higher among
caregivers who reported little stress, or those who had a disabled
spouse but were not providing care.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Vitaliano of the University of Washington said elders are
not equally vulnerable to the health-destroying effects of
relentless caregiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to be a caregiver,'' Vitaliano said. ``You
have to be vulnerable, and you have to have poor social supports''
to suffer ill effects. ``We need to find out which types of
caregivers are at risk,'' so additional resources can be targeted
to them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington State researcher hypothesizes that having high
rates of anger and hostility and low social supports lead to a high
risk of what is known as Syndrome X, a metabolic disorder the makes
people prone to heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Kiecolt-Glaser and her husband Ronald Glaser, from Ohio
State University, wrote in an accompanying editorial that
physicians should question caregivers about their health and stress
levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Glasers added that the new study ``is likely to fuel the
debate about the financing of long-term care'' since caregiving
``will become an increasingly prominent problem as the baby boom
generation ages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
