<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8891 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TOMASELLI-ART-$ADV19-     12-14 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOMASELLI-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE DROPPED OUT OF DRUGS, AND PUT THEM IN HIS ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19)  
 (af)  
 William Harris writes about avant-garde art, theater and dance.  
 By WILLIAM HARRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the painter Fred Tomaselli pulls out a drawer
from a flat file in his studio, a visitor gasps. Inside are
cardboard palettes with meticulously cut out photos of birds,
flowers and insects scavenged from field guides and arranged by
size, color and species.
</P>
<P>
   There are also pictures of lips and eyeballs clipped from
fashion magazines and palettes of pressed leaves and organic
narcotics likes hemp, datura and ephedra. These items, along with
scores of pills and tablets _ over-the-counter remedies as well as
prescription and recreational drugs _ are Tomaselli's primary
materials. The drugs are stored nearby, sorted in old aspirin
bottles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tomaselli is known for collaging these water-soluble bits on
dark backgrounds, then sealing them in several coats of resin.
Pictorially the work veers between the figurative and the abstract,
but the result is usually the same: eye-popping imagery that is
dense, decorative and witty.
</P>
<P>
   The latest and largest example, ``Gravity's Rainbow (Large),''
is now on view at the Whitney Museum of Art at Philip Morris on
42nd Street through Jan. 7. (It will soon be added to three other
Tomaselli works in the Whitney's permanent collection.)
</P>
<P>
   This piece, named for Thomas Pynchon's 1973 novel and
constructed out of five 4-foot-by-8-foot sections, is an exuberant
explosion of line and color with beaded swags sweeping across the
surface. It is remarkably seductive, yet some of its beauty is
derived from illicit drugs, which makes the work highly
provocative. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a dialogue about art heightening awareness
or modifying consciousness,'' said Tomaselli, who has never had
problems caused by his choice of materials. ``I started seeing some
interesting correlations between the rhetoric that surrounded
modernism _ of losing oneself in the sublime _ and the rhetoric
that surrounded drug culture.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about being bad or transgressive,'' he continued.
``Drugs were an aspect of my life. I don't take drugs anymore; I
just smoke cigarettes and drink coffee. What I'm really up to is a
giant act of sublimation. My work allows me to use drugs, to obsess
and be compulsive about them the way druggies are _ counting,
sorting, arranging, weighing. But the only way you can get their
psychoactivity is through your eyeballs, not your bloodstream.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tomaselli, 43, is at a key juncture in his career. Ten years
ago, when he first started incorporating pharmacological references
in his work, he also had to hold a day job to support himself.
(Back then, he was an installation artist, and one of his pieces
from that period remains on permanent view at the Hall of Science
in Flushing Meadow, Queens.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a waiting list for his work. His output is modest,
because his process is labor-intensive. A 2-foot-square Tomaselli,
purchased for $2,800 four years ago, since sold at auction for
$11,000. Meanwhile, he recently joined a new dealer, James Cohan,
after being courted by a dozen galleries.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred is a hybrid of several different sensibilities,'' said
Cohan, whose three-month-old gallery also represents, among other
artists, Ron Mueck, Richard Patterson and Bill Viola as well as the
estate of Robert Smithson. ``He has great conceptual ideas and also
makes remarkably convincing pictures. He really believes art has
the ability to transform and transcend the everyday.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The earliest drug works were whimsical drawings, goofing on
astrology. Tomaselli asked sitters to name their birthday and list
all the drugs they remember taking _ everything from aspirin,
alcohol and amyl nitrate to caffeine, chocolate or cannabis.
</P>
<P>
   The birth date would correspond to an astrological sign, which
in turn corresponded to an astrological chart. Tomaselli recreated
those charts and renamed the stars on them for the drugs consumed.
``They were portraits of inner space and outer space,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The paintings are much more elaborate and the process is
painstaking. With ``Gravity's Rainbow (Large),'' for instance, he
began by using an 18-foot-long beaded pull cord, creating
catenaries, or chains, on the wood surface that pleased his eye,
then traced them with a white pencil. Pills and cutouts were
arranged and rearranged, then glued to the surface. Next came the
resin, squeegeed on and blow-dried, before new catenaries were
etched into the surface, creating another layer to be filled in.
The piece took five months to complete.
</P>
<P>
   In a sly wink to one of Philip Morris' most controversial
products, Tomaselli experimented with using cigarette butts in the
garlands. Dissatisfied with the result, he ended up using cigarette
butts as stamps to create little circles of color.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep the viewer as off-balance as possible to
the reality of what they're seeing,'' said Tomaselli. ``I freely
mix the painted, the photographic and the real as seamlessly as
possible in the same picture plane. I like the textural contrast of
the hard geometric manufactured pills against the soft shape of
nature.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tomaselli grew up in Southern California in a working class
family, not far from Disneyland. His parents were Swiss immigrants.
By his own admission, he spent his high school years either stoned
or tripping on psychedelic drugs. ``The slippage of reality was
part of the way I grew up,'' he noted. But he also remembers being
exposed to Conceptualist artists like Bruce Nauman, Chris Burden
and James Turrell, and the pull they had on him as a rebellious
teenager interested in punk rock. He graduated from the California
State University at Fullerton in 1982 with a BA in painting and
drawing.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a Turrell show where there appeared to be a
black-painted rectangle on the wall in a dimly lit gallery,''
Tomaselli said. ``Me and my friends were laughing and saying,
`Stupid modern art.' I went over and touched it, and my hand went
into limitless space. I went from ridiculing it to going ooooh.
That was a critical moment for me. I loved being fooled, it was
like magic. That double take has been germane in my work.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tomaselli moved to New York 14 years ago, having never been here
in his life. Today, he lives with his wife, Laura Miller, and
20-month-old son, Desmond, in the Williamsburg section of Brooklyn,
where he also has his studio.
</P>
<P>
   He finds the recent feeding frenzy among dealers wanting to
represent him both flattering and unnerving. ``I never expected
that this late in the process I'd still have some juice left in my
career,'' he said. ``I've had a below-radar career for a long time,
and it's only in the last few years that things have escalated. My
stock seems to be rising. But I've also been around long enough to
know that this stuff goes away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
