<HEADLINE>
AN AIRPORT ARCHITECT'S GREAT LEAP FORWARD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Having designed 30 airport terminals around the world,
Paul Andreu can hardly escape being known as an airport architect.
Not that there is anything amiss with that.
</P>
<P>
   Airports today are what railroad stations were at the turn of
the century, gateways that every year provide tens of millions of
travelers with their first and last impressions of a city. And if
Andreu keeps being invited to build airports, it is because this
engineer-turned-architect enjoys a worldwide reputation for
designing visually striking and passenger-friendly terminals.
</P>
<P>
   Parisians above all have come to appreciate his work (without
necessarily knowing his name) as the designer of five elegant
modules for Air France's ever-expanding Terminal 2 at Charles de
Gaulle airport north of Paris. Elsewhere in France, he has built
new airport terminals in Nice, Bordeaux and Guadeloupe, while his
works abroad include terminals in Cairo, Jakarta, Shanghai,
Dar-es-Salaam, Bangkok and Athens.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, he also designed the high-speed train station
at Charles de Gaulle airport and the cross-Channel railroad
terminal in Calais.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, at the age of 61, this slim, bearded Frenchman would like
to be remembered for more. After all, every architect has his
vanity. And, let's face it, in today's architectural celebrity
circuit, airports are simply not as sexy as, say, museums or opera
houses.
</P>
<P>
   So last year, he took the plunge, entering a design competition
for a new national theater complex in Beijing, just the kind of
cultural building that would assuredly change his image. The
problem was that a Chinese architect was the logical choice. And if
not, several other foreign architects seemed like stronger
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Andreu was right about one thing. Having won the
competition in August, his image is already changing. And now, like
I.M. Pei with his glass pyramid at the Louvre Museum in Paris,
Richard Meier with the Getty Center in Los Angeles and Frank Gehry
with the Guggenheim Museum Bilbao, Andreu is destined to be
identified with a building that will leave its mark on Beijing for
generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   With construction scheduled to start in March, the $360 million
egg-shaped complex, with its opera house, concert hall and two
theaters, is set to open by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project has everything,'' Andreu said in an interview at
his office near Orly Airport outside Paris. ``It is in a great
country. It is at the heart of a great city. It's an immense
cultural project. It has an ellipsoid form that has fascinated me
for a long time and that I can now build. I can't think of anything
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for his gamble to pay off, he must eventually please
two quite separate audiences: the Chinese, both its government and
its theatergoing public, and Western architecture critics and
scholars. But those tests are still some time away.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Chinese authorities informed him that his design had
been selected, for instance, they have yet to announce the decision
at home. Similarly, though his design will soon start appearing in
specialist magazines, architecture critics tend to wait until
buildings are almost completed before pronouncing their verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the project has been mooted for so long that no one
was quite ready for it to go ahead. As far back as 1958, Prime
Minister Zhou Enlai sponsored the idea of an opera house in
downtown Beijing, and some foundations were even dug. Work stopped
during the famine that followed the disastrous Great Leap Forward
in 1960, and though digging resumed in the mid-1960s, the project
was again halted by the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, more buildings were razed to clear the way for the
complex, but the plan remained bogged down in political debate.
Then, after the student killings in Tiananmen Square in 1989, it
was considered risky to draw large crowds to an adjacent theater
district. Finally, President Jiang Zemin himself apparently
approved the project.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, the proposed site of the complex has remained
unchanged: a large near-abandoned lot with a few unseemly holes and
run-down houses, separated from Tiananmen Square by the Great Hall
of the People and catty-corner from one side of the Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1998, when the Chinese authorities in the shape of the
Grand National Theater Committee organized the design competition,
they not only spelled out where the complex should stand and what
it should contain but also required that it not be higher than the
Great Hall of the People. In terms of material and shape, though,
they made no recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Andreu learned of the competition by chance while visiting the
construction site of ``his'' new Shanghai-Pudong Airport, which was
inaugurated this fall during celebrations of the 50th anniversary
of China's Communist regime. It transpired that some big-name
architects had already been invited to participate, among them Jean
Nouvel of France, Carlos Ott of Canada, Hans Hollein of Austria and
Arata Isozaki of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Andreu, however, had to seek permission to be included among the
44 architects, more than half of them Chinese, allowed to present
designs and models for the theater complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Architects generally like very selective competitions, with
six or seven people, but this was perfect for me,'' Andreu said.
``I had no important references in the cultural area. I am building
Osaka's new Museum of the Sea in Japan, but people like to put you
in boxes, and I was the one who built airports. So a more open
competition suited me. At first, I didn't join with the idea of
winning. I viewed it as a way of getting new oxygen into my system.
So I entered the competition. There was the first round, the second
round and then suddenly I thought, perhaps I can win this.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
