<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8893 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AIRPORT-ARCHITECT-2ND     12-14 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-ARCHITECT-2NDTAKE-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PARIS: win this.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The selection process took 18 months, longer than usual in such
competitions. After the first round, the 44 models were displayed
at the Museum of Revolutionary History on Tiananmen Square. The
organizing committee then invited all 44 participants to make new
presentations that took into account criticisms and
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Retaining his original design of a massive rectangular building,
Andreu was chosen in May this year as one of four finalists, along
with Carlos Ott, Terry Farrell from Britain and the Architectural
Design Institute of Qinghua University. Only then did Andreu
radically revise his proposal, abandoning his ``shoe box'' for the
titanium-and glass-covered ellipsoid shell that was approved.
</P>
<P>
   As currently designed (things can always change), the
430-foot-long and 135-feet-high building will be surrounded by a
large, shallow lake and will be approached through an underwater
glass-roofed tunnel through which the complex should be
shimmeringly visible. The public will then arrive in a cavernous
lobby where, like a city within a city, the 2,500-seat opera house,
the 2,000-seat concert hall and the 1,200-seat theater will appear
as separate structures (the 520-seat minitheater is below ground).
</P>
<P>
   A transparent gilt metal netting will surround the opera house
to suggest something slightly ethereal, while the auditorium itself
will have dark red as its dominant color.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always attached to the idea that you don't enter an
opera house as you might push open the door of a supermarket,''
Andreu explained. ``You need time to enter the world of opera. The
Palais Garnier in Paris does that, it gives you time to breathe.
That's what I'm aiming for here. Going to the opera is a
processional process. Opera becomes ridiculous it you don't have
time to enter a world of dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Andreu hopes that the area around the theater
complex will become a park, not only for environmental reasons (he
has frequently integrated gardens into his airport terminals), but
also because trees will soften the impact of his unusually shaped
building on the surrounding neighborhood. While this is out of his
hands, however, he has been told that he will be responsible for
construction of the theater complex itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Shanghai-Pudong airport, we did the drawings but did not
intervene in the construction,'' he said. ``Here we'll have Chinese
associates, apparently the Institute of Beijing City, with some
role for Quinghua University. But they said: `You're in charge of
this project. You'll work with Chinese, but you're responsible. We
want you to be there.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, several thousand miles away, a team of
French architects are working on detailed drawings of the new
complex in the offices of Aeroports de Paris, the government-owned
agency that operates the Paris airports.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely location mirrors Andreu's unusual career: since the
late 1960s he has been an employee of Aeroports de Paris and, as
such, has been hired to build airport terminals around the world.
In Beijing, he is working in his own name, but even there Aeroports
de Paris is associated with the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incomprehensible,'' he admitted with a laugh. ``It's
unthinkable in any other country: Aeroports de Paris and Paul
Andreu Architect, together but separate.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Andreu knows that when the Beijing project is completed,
he alone will take credit or blame. And at this stage of his life,
this is the gamble that he is evidently eager to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have unanimity on such a project is impossible,'' he said.
``I expect quite a number of people in China will say they don't
like it. But a creation is bound to be something that disturbs. If
it is just a reproduction, it is handicraft. My purpose is to do
something original. I can only hope that it disturbs in a positive
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
