<HEADLINE>
THE BOOM IN STOCKS REVERBERATES IN COLLECTIBLES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As stocks soared this year, the New York market for
antiques, collectibles and 20th-century objects eclipsed even the
levels reached in the boom years of the 1980s. Auctions, fairs and
exhibitions at museums and galleries attracted new collectors and
dealers as well as a new art fair to Manhattan, heightening the
awareness of the decorative arts, especially in the Art Deco style.
</P>
<P>
   Why New York?
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty percent of our clients are American, and most of them
live in Manhattan,'' said Bob Vallois, a prominent Paris dealer in
Art Deco, explaining why he and his wife, Cheska, opened an annex
of their Left Bank gallery in Manhattan. The shop is a partnership
with Barry Friedman, a dealer in 20th-century works. On view now at
Friedman &AMP; Vallois are a 1930s silvery aluminum desk and chair by
Jacques-Emile Ruhlmann, priced at $420,000; a 1940 brass and glass
lamp with parts from a Ford V-8 engine by Jean Perzel, at $22,500,
and a 1930s Daum glass lamp, at $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Art Deco objects, as well as most decorative arts and
collectibles, have had a good year in galleries, fairs and flea
markets small and large, including the Pier Shows. But the best
gauge of the market's health are auctions, because there the prices
paid by buyers are published, unlike those at private sales.
</P>
<P>
   And auctions this year included some record prices: $3 million
for the baseball Mark McGwire hit for his 70th home run, at
Guernsey's, and $4.7 million for one of Edward Hicks' ``Peaceable
Kingdom'' paintings, at Christie's, both in January; $684,500 for
an American Indian mask in October, and $11 million for a 1930s
Patek Philippe pocket watch two weeks ago, both at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   At Art Deco auctions, several pieces brought the sort of
six-figure prices usually paid for French 18th-century furniture.
Last month, Barbra Streisand's Art Deco piano by Ruhlmann was sold
for $607,500 at Christie's, and in June, a set of gilded chairs by
Armand Rateau went for $927,000, five times the price expected, at
Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Art Deco also starred at New York's newest art show, the
International 20th Century Arts Fair, held on Thanksgiving weekend.
Organized by Brian and Anna Haughton of London, the five-day
bazaar, the fourth Haughton show now in New York, attracted 12,500
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twentieth-century art is the one area we did not cover in our
fairs,'' Haughton said.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman exhibited at the fair and sold a third of the objects
in his booth. ``It was the best fair for us in a long time _ since
1989,'' he said. ``A lot of people made a lot of money in the stock
market this year and were spending some of it at this fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the style or period, decorative arts and collectibles
seemed to sell well this year at New York's largest auction houses,
both of which expanded: Christie's moved to much larger, more
glamorous quarters at Rockefeller Center, and Sotheby's doubled the
size of its 20-year-old house.
</P>
<P>
   Records were wracked up in sales of decorative arts and
collectibles at both houses. Sotheby's announced that the total for
New York sales _ $180 million _ was its highest ever.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the boom, antiquing in New York, the largest center for
antiques and collectibles in the world, is not always easy. The
sheer abundance makes many collectors ecstatic but frustrates
others, when they have difficulty finding exactly what they seek _
an American 19th-century trotting-horse weathervane, a Gutenberg
Bible, a Ming vase, an 18th-century desk from Versailles or a
Mickey Mouse toy.
</P>
<P>
   These days fewer New York dealers are storekeepers than in the
past. While you can still walk into antiques shops along Lafayette
Street in SoHo and Bleecker Street in Greenwich Village or on and
off Madison Avenue from the 60s to the 80s, they are far less
visible than they once were.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1980s, antiques dealers have followed art dealers out
of storefront galleries to do business instead out of town houses,
gallery buildings, converted factories, warehouses and their own
apartments. Rents are lower, spaces larger and more secure. Many
dealers now see clients by appointment only.
</P>
<P>
   Antiques shops may be less visible, but antiques and art fairs
are on the increase. New York is host to about 60 antiques and art
fairs each year, 10 times the number held in the mid-1960s. Dealers
come from throughout the world to show their wares at the Park
Avenue and Lexington Avenue armories or at the Pier shows.
</P>
<P>
   The International Asian Art Fair, a spring event, is often
described as the best art show in Manhattan, and the reason is
obvious, said the pre-eminent dealer in Asian art, Robert H.
Ellsworth. ``Even if you spent a year going around the world,'' he
said, ``you would never be able to see all the fine Asian art
exhibited here.''
</P>
<P>
   So hot are the fairs and auctions that foreign dealers like
Giuseppe Eskenazi, London's leading dealer in Chinese art, rent
galleries to present private exhibitions. As antiquity collectors
gathered in Manhattan for the auctions a few weeks ago, Robin
Symes, a London dealer, took over a town house to exhibit 30
ancient Greek portraits in stone, bronze, jasper, garnet and
silver, many of which he sold at prices from $800 to seven figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now antiquing is changing again,'' said William W. Stahl, Jr.
an executive vice president of Sotheby's. ``We've added 10,000 new
clients since we began auctioning on the web a few weeks ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
