<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICAN-DAUGHTER-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A NICE WASHINGTON DOCTOR AND HER RUIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The scene is a brunch in an elegant living room in
Georgetown, the upper-class Washington enclave. But Christine Lahti
and a half-dozen actresses and actors are actually filming ``An
American Daughter'' in a home in the upscale Hancock Park section
of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Washington _ the town's hypocrisies, its self-important
journalists and snarky politics _ serves not only as the setting
for the Wendy Wasserstein comedy-drama-turned-television-movie but
also the catalyst for the special personal and professional
pitfalls that face women in and around government.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, television may be the right form for this play
because it's about the television medium,'' said Ms. Wasserstein,
author of ``The Sisters Rosensweig'' and ``The Heidi Chronicles,''
whose Washington drama opened at Lincoln Center in 1997 to mixed,
if not poor, reviews and has since been revised by the author.
``Maybe Monicagate, maybe all the things we've seen in the last two
years in Washington, has given the play a resonance that it never
had before.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama, which explores the corrosive effects of a private
life turned public before the television cameras, is now completing
production in Los Angeles, and is to be shown next spring over
Lifetime. It is the network's first adapted Broadway play.
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime _ with mainstream, if soft-hued, series like ``Any Day
Now'' and ``Oh Baby'' _ may be the No. 1 cable network for women's
programming (now available in 73 million households), but it is
hardly a bastion of feminist sensibility. Despite that, Dawn
Tarnofsky-Ostroff, Lifetime's executive vice president for
entertainment, says the Wasserstein play fits perfectly into the
network's efforts to lure women viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, this is a very contemporary and relevant story that
will appeal to our viewers, who are women from all walks of life,''
said Ms. Tarnofsky-Ostroff. ``Our viewers are hungry for knowledge
and information. We want projects that can teach them.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``The American Daughter'' teaches is, in fact, a fairly
bleak lesson.
</P>
<P>
   The play deals with an eminently qualified Washington physician,
Lyssa Dent Hughes (Ms. Lahti, who lobbied hard to snare the role),
who faces an onslaught of media and political scrutiny after the
president nominates her to be surgeon general. A mistake from the
past _ she once discarded a jury summons _ comes back to haunt her.
</P>
<P>
   Characters in the drama include Lyssa's husband, Walter (played
by Tom Skerritt), a sociologist and author who has affairs on the
side; a gay, conservative pundit (Mark Feuerstein) who easily
betrays her; an arrogant feminist in her 20s who's popular on the
talk show circuit (Blake Lindsley) and a slippery television news
reporter (Jay Thomas) who's seeking a scandal. Many of the
characters are quite despicable.
</P>
<P>
   The play itself was written in the aftermath of the
controversies involving President Clinton's failed appointments of
Zoe Baird, Kimba Wood and Lani Guinier, and was criticized in a
review in The Boston Globe, for example, as ``a smug comedy about
unbearably smug people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wasserstein has reshaped the play in several important ways.
She has sharpened the focus on the Lyssa character, making her
stronger, as well as clarifying her relationship to her husband.
The ending of the drama has changed to make her more resolute. And
the character of the gay Republican pundit has been made less
vengeful; he is now almost bewildered by his own horrific behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, some aspects of the play seem somehow more
timely, especially in the aftermath of Monica Lewinsky and the
humiliation of Hillary Rodham Clinton. At one point, Lyssa
excoriates her husband for betraying her with another woman in
their own home. ``A lot of people then thought, `Oh, come on,'''
said Ms. Wasserstein. ``It has a different resonance now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lahti put it another way. ``The media and public humiliation
of the president and Monica Lewinsky seems to add weight to what
Wendy is wrestling with here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The television film, directed by Sheldon Larry, also stars Lynne
Thigpen, who won a Tony Award for her role as Lyssa's best friend,
Judith B. Kaufman, a black Jewish oncologist desperate to have a
child.
</P>
<P>
   (Ms. Wasserstein, who is 49 and recently gave birth to her first
child, Lucy Jane, said the Kaufman character was a deeply personal
portrayal after years of struggling with infertility. Ms.
Wasserstein, who is not married, has declined to reveal the name of
the father.)
</P>
<P>
   In taking on the role, Ms. Lahti, an Emmy Award winner for the
CBS medical series ``Chicago Hope,'' said the play's themes had
appealed to her and she had actively sought out the part. It began
with a telephone call to the director, Larry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bugged Sheldon,'' she said with a laugh, in her cramped
trailer on a street in front of the house where she had just
completed the scene of a Georgetown brunch. ``I called Wendy. I
made a complete pest of myself. This was one of the dream parts. I
knew they were going after Meryl Streep and somebody else. And I
thought, well, maybe it'll come to me if she doesn't want to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lahti said she had been captivated by the original Lincoln
Center version of the drama. In fact, when the play was not
nominated for a Tony Award, Ms. Lahti said, she sat down and wrote
an Op-Ed piece for The New York Times criticizing the decision.
(The piece was turned down.) But once she was offered the
television role, Ms. Lahti said, she suggested to Ms. Wasserstein
that in one scene she could make the lead character less passive,
less a victim. Ms. Wasserstein agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The play, Ms. Lahti said, resonates with two themes: how
excessive media scrutiny can sabotage the appointment of qualified
public servants and, on a personal level, how feminism has been
afflicted by the generational divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dismayed that so many younger women find the term
`feminism' somehow embarrassing or outdated,'' said Ms. Lahti, who
appeared on the New York stage in Ms. Wasserstein's ``Heidi
Chronicles.'' ``I'm dismayed also by the lack of support that women
have for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether acting on television is different from the stage,
Ms. Lahti shrugged and said no. ``I really believe in what Jimmy
Cagney once said,''she added. ```You stand there and tell the
truth.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lahti, whose film career has included ``Running on Empty,''
``Housekeeping'' and ``... And Justice for All,'' recently
completed a four-year stint as a doctor on ``Chicago Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mutual decision,'' she said. ``I could have gone on
one more season but they wanted to revamp the whole show and bring
in new people and I just felt it was time to move. And as much as I
loved that gig on `Chicago Hope,' and I did, there would be days
where I'd be going, `How many more times can I say, ``Pass the
scalpel and sponge''? And how come I'm not with my kids?''' (Ms.
Lahti is married to the director Thomas Schlamme; they have
boy-and-girl twins, who are 6, and an 11-year-old son.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lahti, who is to start directing her first feature film,
``My First Mister,'' a comedy starring Albert Brooks, in January,
said that except for cable television parts, strong dramatic roles
for women over 40 were difficult to find: ``I get offered a lot of
moms in movies. A lot of doctors. And that's one of the reasons I'm
directing.''
</P>
<P>
   Actresses like Sally Field and Diane Keaton are directing now,
she pointed out. ``It's a fabulous avenue,'' she said. ``I love
acting, but if I'm going to play supporting, underwritten mom parts
in a movie that I can do in my sleep, I may as well be home with my
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Ms. Lahti's trailer, Robert Schwartz, an executive
producer of the film, and Larry, the director, said that as much as
they had yearned to make the movie in Washington, the costs and
complications were prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's issues of permits and what seems like 16 different
police agencies, and it's not easy,'' said Schwartz. The play
itself, he said, has been trimmed considerably by Ms. Wasserstein,
who adapted her 1989 Pulitzer Prize-winning play, ``The Heidi
Chronicles,'' for TNT in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the important Sunday morning brunch scene, where
the characters collide and the play's themes emerge, has been cut
in half.
</P>
<P>
   Larry, a theatrical and television director who has known the
author for 20 years, said that using cameras for a play that is, to
some degree, about television had strengthened the drama. At one
point near the finale, the Lahti character goes before a national
television audience.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is viewed from inside a television studio (it was
filmed at the CBS studios) where Ms. Lahti appears on 30 screens at
once, at various angles. The scene was meant to display the
pervasiveness of the scrutiny that the characters undergo. This
was, of course, impossible onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has an opinion now and feels they have a right to
know about anything,'' said Larry, preparing for his next scene.
``The result is that lives get ruined and we're the losers. And to
some degree I think that's what this play is about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
