<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-KPN-COX     12-14 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-KPN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors unimpressed by BellSouth European deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's the case of the stock that did not rise.
</P>
<P>
   Like the hound that did not bark in the Sherlock Holmes story,
BellSouth's stock price seems to have said at least as much during
several quiet days as it would have by making a lot of noise.
</P>
<P>
   The provocation to howl came late Thursday, when BellSouth
announced a deal that would help Dutch-based KPN Telecom NV buy a
German wireless provider and _ eventually _ give BellSouth a
sizable piece of the Dutch company.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth would spend virtually no money but would end up with
an interest in KPN Telecom that _ at current prices _ is worth
nearly $6 billion more than its current interest in E-Plus, the
German wireless company.
</P>
<P>
   Although complex, the deal won praise for being a clever bit of
maneuvering. Not only would it boost the value of BellSouth's
European business, it would make the company an investor in an
aggressive player with plans to expand.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the deal, Duane Ackerman spoke eagerly of
``unlocking'' the value of BellSouth's stake in E-Plus. He cited
the apparent gain in the value of BellSouth's holdings as nearly
$2.80 per share of company stock. He stopped short of predicting
that the stock would get a ``bump'' skyward by that amount, but
when asked about the company's reputation after the KPN deal, he
suggested that shareholders would be especially pleased.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reacted by calling the deal ``a savvy
piece of financial engineering.'' The Financial Times gushed that
``the math of the transaction shows just how fabulous a deal
BellSouth has struck'' and said that BellSouth ``has pulled off one
of the most extraordinary financial coups in recent times.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Chief Staff Officer Gary Forsee, who is responsible
for strategic planning, said the deal puts BellSouth in position to
dramatically expand its role in Europe as the Continent's telecom
business booms. Without committing to a deeper entanglement or even
a merger, BellSouth can grow as KPN does, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our assumption is that European wireless values will continue
to grow. They will be our partner of choice to expand our footprint
in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly KPN Telecom investors greeted the news with wild
enthusiasm. The Dutch company stock, trading at $61 a share as the
news began to break, has soared since to $84 a share. And KPN was
the company about to shell out $9.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the sound that you did not hear was the cheering of
BellSouth investors. The company stock Friday moved from $47.25 to
$47.52. On Monday, it dipped back to $47.12 1/2 and Tuesday,
BellSouth was up slightly to $47.50.
</P>
<P>
   Woof?
</P>
<P>
   Forsee said BellSouth is willing to be patient, to see the
market value the deal gradually. But BellSouth officials clearly
were disappointed that Wall Street's initial reaction was so
lackluster. But what was the explanation? Had BellSouth overhyped
the deal to the public or maybe oversold itself? Was BellSouth just
caught in some larger market tide? Or were investors passing up
BellSouth for some other, more fundamental reason?
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the deal was just too darned complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard sometimes to pinpoint when something is significant
and what the market is going to think is significant,'' said
Douglas Christopher, analyst for Crowell, Weedon &AMP; Co. ``I am
looking at this and thinking it's a pretty good investment for
BellSouth. I just don't think that this deal is well-understood
here in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst David Burks of Hilliard Lyons said such a deal always
means more to the smaller company _ in this case, KPN Telecom,
which is about one-third the size of $24 billion-a-year BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   He praised BellSouth for becoming more aggressive, calling the
company's recent unsuccessful bid for Sprint ``a watershed event.
The company is becoming more proactive, more aggressive than in
years past.''
</P>
<P>
   But little of that aggressiveness is reflected in the stock
price.
</P>
<P>
   Through 1999, BellSouth stock has been unspectacular, seesawing
between $40 and $51. In contrast, during each of the two years
before, BellSouth stock grew by more than 60 percent in value. Over
three years, BellSouth is up 147 percent, Forsee said. ``That
record speaks loud and clear about our financial performance.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of brokerage houses have recommended buying BellSouth
stock, predicting that shares will rise. Most optimistic is Lehman
Bros., which sets a target price of $61. Maybe BellSouth stock this
year might be suffering by comparison with the market's high-flying
Internet plays, as many investors look for a quick return.
</P>
<P>
   But some telecom stocks have also outpaced BellSouth. AT&AMP;T,
which had slid through the summer, climbed steadily from $41.75 on
Oct. 1 to a high of $60 before pulling back to the mid $50s. In
that same period, U S West, which is merging with Qwest
Communications, has seen its stock climb from about $57 to more
than $70. MCI WorldCom, which outbid BellSouth for Sprint, saw its
stock rise from about $68 to $92, although it slid back to the
mid-$70s.
</P>
<P>
   Some of BellSouth's telecom rivals have also seen erratic
treatment from investors. SBC dropped from $59 in July to $44.25 in
October before rallying back above $50. Bell Atlantic stock has
swung back and forth between a $69.50 high in early October and a
$62 low, closing Tuesday at $65.06 1/4 a share.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth stock had been slowly climbing, rising from below $42
a share in October to $47 before the KPN deal was unveiled. Yet a
series of massive industry combinations has left BellSouth the last
of the seven regional Bells with no major partnership pact. The bid
for Sprint might have reinforced the anticipation of investors that
something big will happen, Burks said. ``They have raised the bar
of expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Marc Bacurin of JC Bradford said BellSouth might have
been caught up in its own excitement, forgetting that the payoff _
when BellSouth gets stock in KPN _ will not come for at least 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may take doing the conversion to see the stock value
reflect that,'' he said. ``It's just unclear how much you could
read the value to be at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for BellSouth, some analysts believe the company's
bid for Sprint was an admission that it must make a dramatic move
to become much bigger _ and those analysts don't think gradual
expansion in Europe will fill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would bet that within the next six months, we will have an
announcement involving BellSouth and one of those two companies,''
Bacurin said. ``The world is moving fast. They are going to have to
do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
