<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN15-COX     12-14 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eagles' defense healthy, unlike last year
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As he prepared his team for last year's Division 1-AA
championship game against UMass, Georgia Southern coach Paul
Johnson knew his Eagles were on shaky ground defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy hitter Daryl Morrell, a sophomore linebacker, had
sustained a career-ending neck injury earlier in the playoffs.
Linebacker Dante Harrow was still slowed by the effects of a torn
knee ligament suffered in the fourth game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   To worsen matters at linebacker, starter Larry Rogers had gone
out with a knee injury in the second playoff game, and the
separated shoulder of Josh Smithers limited his effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The shaky ground on which Georgia Southern's defense stood gave
way as running back Marcel Shipp rushed for 244 yards and three
touchdowns to lead Massachusetts to a 55-43 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, when Georgia Southern (12-2) faces Youngstown State
(12-2) in both teams' quest for a fifth national title at
Chattanooga's Finley Stadium, Johnson hopes to trot out a defensive
unit capable of forcing the opposition to punt at least three
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as beat up and injured going into this championship
game as we were last year,'' Johnson said. ``But more than that, I
don't think it's any question that we've played better on the
defensive side of the ball. We've had a bunch of guys over there
who've stepped up and made plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those guys are three linemen _ seniors Voncellies Allen
and Eugene Phillips and redshirt freshman Fred Pesqueira _ who have
combined for 55 tackles behind the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   At linebacker, sophomore Jason Neese out of McEachern High has
98 tackles, while redshirt freshman Michael Ward has 72. The other
backers are sophomore Jamar Jones of Douglasville, a healthy Harrow
and sophomore Corey Middlebrooks of Riverdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've definitely got better athletes out there than we had a
year ago,'' Johnson said. ``I mean, guys who can run, and are
capable of making plays.''
</P>
<P>
   That was evident in the Eagles' previous two wins _ 38-21 over
UMass and 28-17 victory over Gateway Athletic Conference champion
Illinois State. Take away the 10 points Illinois State scored on
turnovers in Georgia Southern's territory, and the defense the past
two weekends has limited opponents to two touchdowns a game.
</P>
<P>
   The statistic that most impresses Johnson involves the
opposition's rushing. In the rematch against UMass, Shipp and his
teammates were limited to 81 yards on the ground. The Eagles'
defense cut that down to 69 yards against Illinois State.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy in coaching, which is probably dinosaur today,
is that to win football games you have to be able to run the ball,
and you have to be able to stop the run,'' said Johnson. ``There
might be some exceptions somewhere along the line, but it's been my
experience that if you do those two things, you usually win the
football game.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnest Reese writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
