</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HEARINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Samaranch prepares for House grilling
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ International Olympic Committee president Juan
Antonio Samaranch faces his accusers today armed with a reform
package he hopes will deflect any further criticism and protect his
beloved Olympics from Congress' heavy hand.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. lawmakers have no authority over the Olympic movement, but
have held two hearings and have threatened to cut off the flow of
television and sponsorship revenues to the IOC. Such a move would
be a deadly blow to the Olympics, which is bankrolled by U.S.
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch is scheduled to testify before a U.S. House Commerce
subcommittee studying the Olympic site selection process and
considering legislation to revoke tax-exempt status for Olympic
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Olympic chiefs Billy Payne and Andy Young testified
before the same panel in October. Samaranch postponed his
appearance until he felt he could convince lawmakers that the IOC
has enacted substantial reforms.
</P>
<P>
   At the earlier hearing, there was widespread bipartisan
criticism of the bid cities that lavish expensive gifts and favors
on the IOC members whose primary function is voting for future
Olympic sites.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms were prompted by the Salt Lake City and Atlanta bid
scandals that have battered the IOC's reputation and credibility.
In the past year, the IOC has ousted 10 members implicated in the
Salt Lake City affair, set up a quasi-independent ethics
commission, published its financial accounts and opened its
sessions to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we promised,'' Samaranch said before heading for
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Spaniard is expected to testify with the aid of an
interpreter, even though he speaks fluent English. Some of his
loyalists on the IOC expect a grilling from the panel _ an event
they deem unfair and beneath the dignity of Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers could ask Samaranch about his political role during
the Franco regime and the $12,000 trip his wife and friends made to
Charleston, S.C., and Savannah in 1990 at the expense of Atlanta's
Olympic bid team.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch will be followed by former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger, former Senate majority leader George Mitchell and Sen.
Howard Baker. Kissinger headed the IOC 2000 reform panel that
drafted the reforms; Baker serves on the new ethics commission.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the IOC has voted to give up their life terms and
lavish perks, many members think Congress should leave them alone
and take action against bidders in Salt Lake City and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes two to tango,'' said Peru's Ivan Dibos. ``I would
like it if the commission of the U.S. Congress punished the people
in its country that got us involved in this whole affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Dibos is the member who accepted Atlanta's gift of a used MARTA
bus and who hoped to get another 50 promised on the eve of the vote
in Tokyo for the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Mendoza of Colombia says he considers bid city
representatives as ``no longer respectable people for my family.
It's as if they were lepers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza made two trips to Georgia _ one more than alloted under
IOC rules at the time.Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. The Associated Press contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
