<SLUG> BC-HKN-NIGERIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nigerian to bring physical presence
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For those NHL talent scouts who might have missed this
on the usual Red Deer-Moose Jaw-Medicine Hat road swing, we offer
this travel primer:
</P>
<P>
   Zaria, Nigeria, was the capital city of the ancient kingdom of
Zazzau and was named after the daughter of a ruler near the end of
the 15th century. The town lies at the intersection of roads from
Kaduna, Jos, Kano and Funtua. Or, if you're not driving, Zaria is
conveniently located at the rail junction between Nguru and Lagos.
Just in case you're also looking at a goalie in Nguru.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many people back there know about hockey,''
Rumun Ndur said, laughing. ``I don't think I'd see too many skating
rinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumun Ndur (pronounced ROO-muhn EN-dur) was claimed on waivers
Saturday by the Thrashers from the New York Rangers. He is a
6-foot-2, 222-pound defenseman whom coach Curt Fraser hopes will
add a physical presence on defense. Ndur is one of 15 black players
in the NHL and certainly the only one that comes from Nigeria _
though he didn't hang around long enough to develop an accent.
</P>
<P>
   Other than his name, Ndur is as Canadian as back bacon. His
father, a pediatrician, sought a better life for his family in 1976
and moved with his wife and son to Toronto in 1976. At the time,
Ndur was 6 months old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to come to North America, and it was between Austin,
Texas, and Toronto,'' Ndur said. ``If we moved to Austin, there's
no way I'd be sitting here talking to you in a hockey uniform. It
just worked out that I grew up like every other Canadian kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ndur might have ended up in Texas but the Ndurs ran into
problems obtaining visas for the U.S. So came their Northern
Exposure. Five years in Toronto, then even further north to Hearst,
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask people in Canada and even they don't know where Hearst
is,'' Ndur said. ``The only thing to do up there is play hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   The blacks he has seen in the NHL are about a dozen or so more
than he saw growing up. ``It's actually gotten a lot better,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few incidents of racial slurs in the NHL in
recent years, but Ndur said, ``Since I've been in the pros, nothing
really (has been said to me). Growing up, maybe a couple of times.
But we were just kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Ndur allows that he might have been more of a target if he
didn't grow up in Canada. ``My parents speak with a thick accent,
but I don't have it,'' he said. ``It wasn't like I came in and
couldn't speak English.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 24, he is trying to blend into the NHL landscape. He was
drafted by Buffalo in the third round in 1994, and played most of
three years with the Sabres' AHL team in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Finesse is not his game. In games from 1995-98, Ndur totaled
eight goals, 35 assists and 799 penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He played only eight games for the Sabres before being waived
last December and claimed by the Rangers. On the last year of his
contract, Ndur felt he played well for the team down the stretch.
But he ran into problems in negotiations when he sought a one-year
and/or one-way contract, which pays an NHL salary, even if the
player is sent to the minors. New York offered a two-year, two-way
deal.
</P>
<P>
   It was a month into the season before Ndur signed _ at the
Rangers' terms: a prorated salary of $365,000 this year and
$400,000 next, but only $50,000 in the minors. Ndur agreed to a
two-week conditioning stint with Hartford (AHL), but the Rangers
then had to make a decision to keep him or pass him through waivers
before sending him back to Hartford. They chose the latter, but
Ndur didn't clear _ the Thrashers plucked him.
</P>
<P>
   Ndur said, ``It feels good to be wanted again.'' He had hoped to
land here in the expansion draft but the Rangers had him on their
protected list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to have a fresh start,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
