<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-TAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES TRIPP NOT PROTECTED IN TAPING OF LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The last time they publicly spoke to each other,
Linda R. Tripp was playing out the final act of a betrayal for the
ages, luring Monica S. Lewinsky into a trap that would snare the
former White House intern in scandal and forever mark President
Clinton's place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lewinsky may exact some revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years after Tripp handed federal prosecutors the
infamous audiotapes of Lewinsky confiding her sexual affair with
Clinton, Tripp is caught in a legal vise, fighting charges that she
criminally recorded her phone conversations with her former friend.
</P>
<P>
   And Lewinsky is poised to help Maryland prosecutors seek
convictions that could land Tripp in prison for as long as 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that clears the way for Lewinsky's possible testimony,
a state circuit court judge Tuesday ruled that Tripp was not
protected by an immunity agreement when she gave independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr tapes of her secretly recorded phone
conversations with Lewinsky in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's lawyers argued that she gave Starr the tapes on the
condition that she would not be prosecuted for recording them. She
faces two counts of breaking a Maryland wiretap law that prohibits
recording telephone conversations without the consent of both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately for Mrs. Tripp,'' Howard County Judge Diane O.
Leasure said in her ruling, Tripp's immunity deal did not take
effect until a federal judge signed it on Feb. 19, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a nation weary of the Lewinsky saga may face
another chapter repelete with the intimate details of the former
intern's illicit liaisons with Clinton. It was the Tripp tapes that
effectively launched Clinton's impeachment odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Though Lewinsky is on the prosecution's witness list for a
pretrial hearing this week, lawyers said she is unlikely to appear
in court before the trial begins Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, too, has been absent from the pretrial proceedings.
However, she has used her Web site to portray her prosecution as
the product of a vengeful White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for me, they have been able to ensure that retribution is
full and long lasting,'' Tripp said in a message she posted Monday
on her Web site. She claimed that the Clinton administration has
deliberately scaled back her duties at the Pentagon and ``caused me
to amass hundreds of thousands of dollars in legal debt.''
</P>
<P>
   A Maryland prosecutor, Stephen Montanarelli, testified Tuesday
that he helped to build his case against Tripp with her own words.
He quoted Tripp as telling her weekly bridge club that she had
recorded her conversations with a woman named ``Monica,'' but that
she did not fear criminal charges ``because no one ever gets
prosecuted'' under the wiretap law.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Tripp recorded Lewinsky's words, she hinted at the
prospect of enmeshing Lewinsky in her plan to expose Clinton's
extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm sticking a knife in your back,'' Tripp told
Lewinsky in a taped phone call. ``I know at the end of this, if I
have to go forward, you will never speak to me again and I will
lose a good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp had that thought right. When a grand juror asked Lewinsky
last year how she felt about Tripp, she said, ``I hate her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
