<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY YIELDS CLIMB AMID NEW INFLATION CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury yields rose sharply Tuesday as investors
chose to ignore November's moderate consumer price data and instead
focused on stronger-than-expected retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has said it will raise interest rates again
if there is evidence of continuing strong growth, even if the
inflation rate remains tame. For that reason, Treasuries had their
biggest decline in months Tuesday as investors grew concerned that
the central bank would indeed raise rates to try to brake the
economy's growth.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 11/32,
to 97 21/32. The yield, which moves in the opposite direction from
the price, increased to 6.30 percent from 6.20 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in the yield of the long bond was the largest since
August, as buyers moved to the sidelines amid concern that strong
holiday retail sales would bolster fourth-quarter growth and help
build inflationary pressure, increasing the odds that the Fed would
soon raise rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clues of budding wage pressures and potential labor strife are
beginning to build,'' said Donald Fine, chief market analyst at
Chase Asset Management, ``and with gas prices at the pump
continuing to rise amid surging economic growth, the specter of
rising inflationary expectations down the pike is very likely to
translate into higher bond yields.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine said these concerns had not gone unnoticed by the Fed.
While the central bank is expected to leave short-term rates alone
at its next policy meeting Dec. 21 to avoid rocking the boat during
the Year 2000 transition period, he said, another increase is
expected during the first quarter unless there is evidence of a
slackening economy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, long-term interest rates could come under pressure
as the year unfolds, and could weaken stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Treasuries fell Tuesday after the Commerce Department reported
that retail sales rose 0.9 percent in November. Combined with
upward revisions in previous months and reports of stellar
Christmas shopping nationwide, the report suggested that consumer
spending remained extremely strong.
</P>
<P>
   Also leading the bond selloff were investors' liquidation of
their long positions before the end of the year. Although such
selling was relatively small in size, such volume allowed it to
cause large swings in prices, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Cooper, chief economist for Nesbitt Burns Securities,
said early reports suggested no let-up in personal spending in
December. ``The trend in consumer spending remains too hot for the
bond market's liking,'' she said. ``Retailers have entered the
critical Christmas shopping season with considerable momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' Ms. Cooper added, ``is that on balance, the
pervasive strength in retail sales outweighs the good news on the
CPI for bonds, but the mix of a strong consumer and still-tame
inflation is positive for stocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8916 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-2TAKES-     12-14 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSSING BACK TO GOOD OL' COUNTRY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Country music, almost by definition, exists in a convoluted,
almost duplicitous relationship with its history. It's both a
thoroughly reactionary form of cultural Kabuki, making elaborate
bows to the past, and an intensely marketed reinvention, skittering
wildly after the demographic or musical fashions of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Even by country's standards, Nashville finds itself in a
particularly conflicted moment. It is spawning bigger stars with
more mainstream appeal, selling more albums than was imaginable
just a few years ago. Its most successful stars, like Garth Brooks,
Shania Twain and Faith Hill, are mass-marketed pop culture figures
in a way that would have been unthinkable in the past, and the big
Nashville labels are falling over themselves to come up with the
next crossover blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   True, Nashville's other big breakthrough act, the Dixie Chicks,
has developed an intriguing hybrid _ half banjo, fiddle and twang,
half hip chick marketing. But no one doubts that the serious money
is in the ``Friends'' demographic, not ``Hee Haw'''s, so without
the sexiness, the twang will take you only so far.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as if obligated to provide yin to the crossover yang,
there is suddenly a gaggle of performers, ranging from huge stars
to niche artists, competing to out-retro one another, not just
re-interpreting the past but assiduously digging up old bones. And
amid the crossover fever, there's now a backlash boomlet, not just
of traditional music, but of revivals of classic songs. Just as
authentic country music seems on the verge of finally expiring, the
ghosts are ambling around all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether this constitutes a revival, a calculated
marketing move or a nostalgic bow to the past. And the answer is _
yes. The most conspicuous of the bows to the past is Alan Jackson's
``Under the Influence,'' (Arista 07822-18892-2) which finds him not
just under the influence of Merle Haggard, George Jones, Charley
Pride, Johnny Paycheck et al. but redoing their songs. It makes
sense. Jackson has been the most self-consciously traditional of
the new breed of Nashville success stories. If Garth tried this, it
would exceed even his usual chutzpah quotient.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Jackson it rings true, especially since the songs, a
mix of the familiar and the obscure, seem, for the most part, to
come from Jackson's vision, not from some formula. And the best of
it, the rollicking drinking song ``Pop a Top'' or Hank Williams
Jr.'s ``Blues Man'' clearly comes from the heart, not the head.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear how much the world needs Jackson or anyone else
to redo classic George Jones or Merle Haggard songs, especially
when the originals are still around to do them. And there's one
real stinker _ the totally superfluous duet with Jimmy Buffet on
``Margaritaville'' that sticks out as the one totally cynical note.
Jackson doesn't bring much new to the album, but the music is
affecting, the agenda seems genuine, and he could have done worse
than bring new fans to old country.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson's seems more dutiful than magical, Dolly Parton's
``Grass Is Blue'' (Sugar Hill 3900) takes traditional bluegrass and
makes it her own in an utterly luminous way. Bluegrass seems the
favored path for the current wave of retro excursions, as evidenced
by Steve Earle's collaboration with Del McCourey and Jim
Lauderdale's with Ralph Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   This one ranks with ``The Mountain'' by Earle as one of the most
riveting bluegrass albums in recent years, with truly inspired
playing and vocals that seem to come right from Ms. Parton's East
Tennessee roots without the adorable Nashville chirp. There are
some first-rate originals, classics like the Louvin Brothers ``Cash
on the Barrelhead,'' or Lester Flatt's ``I'm Gonna Sleep With One
Eye Open'' even Billy Joel's ``Travelin' Prayer,'' which somehow
sounds like something scavenged off an old Decca 78.
</P>
<P>
   The players include bluegrass aces like the dobro king Jerry
Douglas, Sam Bush on mandolin and Stuart Duncan on fiddle, and
Dolly's singing hasn't sounded as vital in years. She doesn't just
pay her respects to the ancient spirits _ she summons them up.
Dolly's taken a lot of calculated detours into pop-land, but when
she finally hangs it up, she'll look back on this and think it's
one she really got right.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum is LeAnn Rimes' royally
eponymous new album ``LeAnn Rimes'' (Curb D2-77947), a stunningly
crass attempt to sell country classics to the Back Street Boys and
'N Synch constituency. After her dazzling retro debut, ``Blue'' and
a pop foray, ``Sittin' on Top of the World,'' this is Ms. Rimes'
comeback album at 17.
</P>
<P>
   From the cavalcade of come hither, ``Teen Beats'' photos to the
completely predictable array of blockbuster classics like
``Crazy,'' `Your Cheatin' Heart'' and ``Lovesick Blues,'' this
album feels like an attempt to become the Britney Spears of
country. It's not that Ms. Rimes' big, preternaturally mature voice
isn't worthy. Instead, like a French-speaking dog or a
polka-dancing hog, Ms. Rimes shows off her big voice and country
roots to no point or affect whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   This is pop traditionalism of the silliest sort, veering from
Patsy Cline to a hyperventilating Janis Joplin turn without
bringing anything remotely new to the table. Indeed, the most
interesting song is the only new thing on the album, a rockish
``Big Deal'' written by Al Anderson, late of the rock group
N.R.B.Q., now a top Nashville songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to assume Don Walser won't play Ricky Martin to
LeAnn's Britney Spears. Walser, who took up music fulltime at the
age of 60 after a career in the Texas National Guard, dedicates
``Here's to Country Music'' (Watermelon 31074-2) to ``my children,
grandchildren and great-grandchildren.'' And if anyone deserves a
free ride on the retro express it's Walser, who combines the girth
of a retired Texas sheriff and the talents of a champion yodeler
and has become an unlikely cult hero.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If even ``Under the Influence'' seems an essentially
contemporary retro excursion, Walser's album feels like a
comfortably moldy visitation from a lost world. He yodels in fine
form on his own ``My Ride With Jimmie'' (Rodgers that is). He dusts
off old Marty Robbins and Floyd Tillman chestnuts. And when he says
in his notes for ``Oakie Boogie'' that ``I have been singing this
old song since the 1940s,'' you don't doubt it for a second.
</P>
<P>
   His own band sounds like it's been playing this stuff since the
days of Bob Wills, and the fiddler Buddy Spicher joins them for
some virtuoso turns. It's not for everyone, but it's the most
honest mossback music on the lot.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as eccentric is John Prine's ``In Spite of Ourselves''
(Oh Boy OBR-019), a series of classic country duets. It recreates
not the glory days of George and Merle, but the world of George and
Tammy and Conway and Loretta in duets with both contemporary
singers like Lucinda Williams, Tricia Yearwood and Emmylou Harris
and names from the past like Connie Smith and Melba Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   You know there's a retro moment afoot when there are not one but
two remakes of the old weeper, ``We Could, You and I'' out there at
the same time, with Walser's with Crystal Gayle dueling with
Prine's with the peerless Iris DeMent. Prine's raspy jalopy of a
voice has its limits, and when he has to carry most of the load, he
sometimes falls flat.
</P>
<P>
   But the songs are mostly wonderful artifacts of country's
acutely grown-up take on the frustrations of love, and the notion
of duets provides an unexpected twist to the project, making it
more than just another resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   There's something admirable in contemporary country artists
taking time to show they respect to their elders _ or at least
their elders' musical traditions. But redoing the music of the '50s
and '60s _ or further back in Walser's case _ can only take you so
far, as if the Wallflowers or the Foo Fighters decided to crank out
redos of ``Satisfaction,'' `A Hard Day's Night,'' `Purple Haze''
and ``My Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The current retro rage is a reminder how enduring country's
traditions remain, even as the music's face is increasingly that of
some made-for video starlet. And there's something valuable in
having big names fly the flag for the real stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But with the exception of Ms. Parton's, these are more or less
worthy tributes that lead amiably backward when the real trick,
like the best of Jackson's work, for example, is to take the old
and make it new.
</P>
<P>
   And amid the gazillion-selling crossover acts, there are plenty
of examples of traditional music renewing itself in fresh ways.
They may just have to do most of it off the Nashville big label
preserve.
</P>
<P>
   On ``The Pilgrim,'' (MCA 70057), Marty Stuart takes the country
canon apart and artfully puts it back together in 20 songs and
snatches of sound that touch almost all the diverse traditional
country streams. Along with Johnny Cash, George Jones, Earl
Scruggs, Ralph Stanley and other co-conspirators, he retells a true
story from his Mississippi youth in new songs that remind you where
all that hyperbolic country emotion comes from.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Perfect World'' (Tornado TTX 011) by Ed Burleson is a
primal bit of Texas honky-tonk, which sounds as unaffected as the
kind of music you might hear at any roadside joint in the Texas
Panhandle. It's too small bore to be revelatory, but it is a
reminder that plenty of people are plowing new furrows in old
fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruel Moon'' (HighTone HCD8111) by Buddy Miller, a protege of
Emmylou Harris, goes several steps further, taking disparate pieces
of honky-tonk, hillbilly, bluegrass and country and weaving them
together into a propulsive, stripped-down howl. It puts him right
up there with Steve Earle, Jim Lauderdale (both of whom wrote songs
and sang on ``Cruel Moon'') and the other essential voices creating
compelling hybrids from country's roots.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much howl but plenty of impeccable musicianship on
``New Grange,''(Compass 42802), an assemblage of top string-band
musicians including Alison Brown on banjo and Tim O'Brien on vocals
and various instruments.
</P>
<P>
   It mixes bluegrass with the Windham Hill world of tasteful
Americana and might be too arty for some traditionalists _ more
National Public Radio than Louisiana hayride. But it's an evocative
melding of modern and traditional musics and a reminder of how
relevant and adaptable an old form like bluegrass can be.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of others zigging and zagging around kindred,
rootsy orbits. They're a reminder that respectful bows to the past
have their place, but the real action exists in the quirky corners
somewhere between the pop frontier and the classics of twang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
