<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8920 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CANAL-TURNOVER-BOS &LR;      12-14 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANAL-TURNOVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER PRESIDES OVER SYMBOLIC TURNOVER OF CANAL TO PANAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CANAL ZONE _ It was the engineering marvel that opened
the American Century: a 50-mile waterway through the heart of this
tropical country connecting the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Columbus had the vision on his last journey to the
New World in 1502. But it would take another 400 years before a
roughriding United States president, Teddy Roosevelt, would make it
a centerpiece of American foreign policy and a symbol of modern
Yankee ambition.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the steamship Ancon made the first passage through
the Panama Canal on August 15, 1914, the United States had invested
$400 million and the sweat and blood of 75,000 workers enlisted
from 97 countries. About 5,000 died.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, at the twilight of a century that has seen American
triumphs and blunders in every corner of the world, the United
States symbolically handed control of the canal and its surrounding
360,000 acres to Panama, an act which will legally take effect at
noon on Dec. 31 and end 96 years of US control over one of the
world's most important shipping routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're celebrating an event which will lead to a new
relationship betweeen your country and mine,'' former US President
Jimmy Carter, co-author of the 1977 treaty that pledged American
withdrawl from Panama, said in Spanish during the ceremony. Later,
he said Panama could become ``the Singapore of this hemisphere for
education, commerce and tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter led a US delegation made up of two current cabinet
secretaries as well as past and present diplomats. Leaders of six
other countries, including Spain's King Juan Carlos, Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo, and Andres Pastrana of Colombia also
attended.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the absence of President Bill Clinton, Vice President
Al Gore, and Secretary of State Madeline Albright, all reportedly
because of scheduling conflicts, that dominated much of the
discussion here this week. It drew harsh words from Panamanian
officials, who said the decision showed the US no longer cares
about the canal or about Panama.
</P>
<P>
   With the transfer of the canal, Panamanians will finally control
the facility that became their national symbol after they gained
independence from Colombia in 1903. The feeling of pride was
evident from the capital city's high-rise glass buildings to the
narrow streets of the historic Chorrillos section, where Christmas
decorations hung Tuesday alongside Panamanian flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have three independence days,'' said Jorge
Cabrera Diaz, a 34-year-old salesman in a women's clothing store in
Panama City. ``One for our freedom from Spain, another from
Colombia, and the third from the US.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the pomp and promise that rang through Tuesday's
ceremonial speeches, there were also undertones of doubt and even
dread as Panamanians contemplated their future _ along with the
loss of American economic and military support, the challenge of
efficiently managing the canal and its dozens of now-abandoned
military sites, and the question of how this small Central American
country will handle full sovereignty for the first time in its
history.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian officials have gone to great lengths to reassure the
world that the canal and the country will be fine without the
Americans, noting that more than 90 percent of the canal's 7,500
employees are already Panamanian and that the agency overseeing its
operations will be independent of the government and nonpolitical.
</P>
<P>
   They have plans for expanding the waterway to accomodate modern
ships that are too wide and too long to fit into the canal's locks,
which move about 13,000 ships a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our final objective is to guarantee the secure, efficient and
uninterrupted operation of the canal to satisfy our clients and the
wellbeing of our country,'' said President Mireya Moscoso during
the ceremony at the canal's Miraflores Locks.
</P>
<P>
   Canal officials are also heavily promoting development plans for
the hundreds of old military buildings, airfields and schools _
valued at about $3.5 billion _ abandoned by the US.
</P>
<P>
   A contract awarded by canal administrators to a Hong Kong-based
firm to operate two large ports on either end of the passage has
raised worries among conservatives in the US and elsewhere that
communist China will become a growing presence in the canal and the
region. But supporters of Hutchison Port Holdings, which also runs
major ports in England, insist such fears are unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   There are also concerns that without its own armed forces, which
were disbanded after the US invaded the country in 1989 and removed
the dictator Gen. Manuel Noriega, Panama is ill-equipped to
guarantee its own national security and that of the canal. Many
Panamanians are especially worried about the threat of leftist
rebels from neighboring Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such doubts, John Coatsworth, director of the David
Rockefeller Center for Latin American Studies at Harvard
University, called the Carter-Torrijos treaty one of the few
triumphs of American policy toward Latin America in the last 200
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need it anymore, and it's the right thing to do,''
Coatsworth said said by telephone from Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, which Carter signed with
former Panamanian strongman Gen. Omar Torrijos, the two countries
are supposed to sign a pact to address matters such as security.
Although so far no agreement detailing security arrangments has
been reached, it is widely understood that the US would intervene
militarily in the face of any threat to the canal's neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panamanian democracy will be stronger than ever and its
citizens will demand competent politicians,'' Coatsworth added.
``But the United States is acting like security is a unilateral
issue that it will handle without the Panamanians, and that's not
the spirit of the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts believe the canal is simply not as important today
as it used to be. It was a key strategic possession that allowed US
battleships to pass from one ocean to the other during two world
wars and a Cold War, but none of today's aircraft carriers can fit.
More and more trade is being conducted via air, ground and
telephone lines, and the waterway carries less than 15 percent of
US trade that still travels by sea.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the canal continues to be an mechanical and engineering
wonder for many who ride along its curves and lakes _ even for many
of the country's 3 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had this big, impressive thing in our country for years,
but so many Panamanians have never been allowed to even ride
through it,'' said Tania Cantis, a volunteer who helped shuttle
visitors on canal tours this week, while standing on the stern of a
small craft that made its way along a section of the canal known as
the Gaillard Cut. ``This is my first time, and I hope it's not the
last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
