<HEADLINE>
CARTER ON HAND AS U.S. BIDS GOODBYE TO PANAMA CANAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ At the site of one of America's greatest
engineering triumphs, the United States on Tuesday bid goodbye to
the Panama Canal, marking the close of a dominating, century-long
presence on the isthmus.
</P>
<P>
   As a cargo ship moved through Miraflores Locks at the Pacific
Ocean entrance to the canal, former President Carter stood nearby
and called the transfer of the waterway from U.S. to Panamanian
control ``one of the most significant moments that has ever
occurred in the hemisphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Flashing his trademark smile, Carter, who signed the 1977 Panama
Canal treaties mandating the turnover, said Washington now
recognizes ``the total sovereignty of Panama over this region.''
</P>
<P>
   Though emotional, Tuesday's act was largely symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   Under the treaties, the actual transfer of canal operations will
occur at noon EST Dec. 31. The ceremony was bumped up to Tuesday to
avoid conflicts with millennium celebrations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a light drizzle, this tiny nation of 2.7 million was in
the mood to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   A front-page editorial in the Panama City daily La Prensa said:
``Today, a dream that generations of Panamanians have shared since
the beginning of the republic becomes reality.''
</P>
<P>
   At Miraflores Locks, a choir sang Beethoven's ``Ode to Joy,''
and Panamanian President Mireya Moscoso smiled broadly at the 1,500
guests.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to her conversation with Carter moments before,
Moscoso said: ``He told me, ``It's yours.' Thank you President
Carter, because that's what all Panamanians feel today. We are very
happy because at last we have achieved victory. The canal is
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Although President Clinton and other high-level U.S. officials
declined to attend, Panama's long struggle to wrest control of the
waterway from the United States was heralded around Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   In attendance Tuesday were the presidents of Bolivia, Colombia,
Costa Rica, Ecuador, Honduras and Mexico, as well as King Juan
Carlos of Spain. They arrived aboard one of the canal's high-tech
locomotives that pull ships through the canal locks.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-over was a long time in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1903 treaty, Panama granted the United States the right
to build and operate a canal between the Atlantic and Pacific
oceans. It was a monumental task, and thousands of laborers died
during construction.
</P>
<P>
   When the Panama Canal opened in 1914, it instantly became a
symbol of Yankee know-how. The canal helped to make the United
States a naval power on both oceans and allowed ship captains to
avoid making the long, perilous trek around the tip of South
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a source of great pride in my country from the time
when I was a child,'' Carter said. ``But we didn't understand
clearly enough the feelings of many Panamanians that the
arrangement implied an element of colonialism and subjugation.''
</P>
<P>
   The canal treaties, signed by Carter and the late Panamanian
leader Gen. Omar Torrijos, called for the gradual transfer of canal
operations to Panama over 20 years as well as the elimination of
the 10-mile-wide U.S.-run Canal Zone that straddled the canal. The
documents also required the closure of all U.S. military bases in
the zone and the pullout of 10,000 U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso called Carter ``a man of great vision,'' saying that he
did the right thing despite the treaties being unpopular in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my country and in Panama, there were demagogues who made
false statements, exaggerated the problems, and predicted
catastrophe,'' Carter recalled. ``There are still a few of those,
unfortunately, today who are implanting incorrect or false stories
about the security of the canal and how it is being operated.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Republican lawmakers in Washington who have
recently portrayed Panama as a corrupt backwater and claimed that,
due to the U.S. pullout, China could wind up with control of the
canal.
</P>
<P>
   They are especially concerned about the Hong Kong firm Hutchison
Whampoa Ltd, that in 1997 won a 25-year contract to administer
ports at both ends of the canal.
</P>
<P>
   However, canal experts point out that ship traffic will be
controlled by the Panama Canal Authority, an autonomous Panamanian
agency that will replace the Panama Canal Commission, the U.S.
agency that has run the canal since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, under neutrality provisions in the treaties, the
United States retains the right to intervene militarily to protect
the waterway. Even so, many analysts believe that the controversy
and concerns that it could hurt the Democrats in the 2000 election
may have convinced President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to skip Tuesday's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso, who took office in September, pledged that the
transition would be a smooth one.
</P>
<P>
   She also described a $1 billion modernization program to protect
the canal's status as a safe and efficient route for ship traffic.
More than 14,000 vessels passed through the canal last year, paying
$545 million in tolls.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso pledged that the bulk of the canal's profits would be
plowed back into operations and maintenance rather than to cover
government costs.
</P>
<P>
   Current projects include the widening of the Gaillard Cut _ the
narrowest portion of the canal _ to allow for two-way traffic. The
canal authority is also expected to increase the size of the
canal's protected watershed, since each ship passage requires 52
million gallons of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The canal will be a model operation for the continent,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Clinton expressed confidence in Panama's ability
to manage the canal. In a statement, he also pledged that the
United States would maintain a ``continuing commitment to the
security of the canal.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Carter, the U.S. delegation to Panama included Secretary
of Commerce William Daley and Peter Romero, the acting assistant
secretary of state for western hemisphere affairs.
</P>
<P>
   And in a nod to the canal's early history, Panama invited Touni
De Lesseps. She is the granddaughter of Ferdinand De Lesseps, the
French mastermind of the Suez Canal who tried and failed to build a
waterway across Panama in the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
