<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY RUSH INTRUDES ON JINGLE BELLS SPIRIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dashing through the snow, in a one-horse open sleigh, o'er the
hills we go, laughing all the way _ ha, ha, ha.''
</P>
<P>
   You know, I'm really not a cold-weather person, but that sleigh
is sounding pretty good to me right now.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, I thought that cute little Christmas song was about
this happy family gliding along the snow-covered avenues in their
gaily decorated sleigh. There would be a mom, a dad, and two
adorable children snuggled together on the wooden seats with
blankets on their laps and mittens on their hands. Smiles would
adorn their faces as the stars twinkled in their eyes. The horse _
a big, brown, happy horse _ wore a Santa Cap atop his head, the
silver bells on his harness making a lovely melody as he galloped
along.
</P>
<P>
   I always wondered where they were going with all that jingling
and happiness. I'm sure it was a good place, like grandma's house,
which may be part of the lyrics but I never knew the whole song,
just that jingle bell part. Besides, we always drove to my
grandma's house. I did ask my mom to roll down the windows one
chilly day on the way to grandma's because I wanted to get that
open-sleigh feeling. After a mile or two, we closed the windows
because mama's eyes started tearing up and she couldn't see. I was
cold by then anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Well, time has passed and I've celebrated a few of these
holidays as an adult with a growing family. I've acquired a whole
new perspective on that song. All that dashing, ringing, and
laughing is not about going to grandma's. Here's what really
happened:
</P>
<P>
   Some poor mother has just spent three weeks preparing for
Christmas and it's now the night before Christmas. After a royal
battle, the tree is up and decorated. It leans to one side and
several ornaments are broken, but it's up. The side of the tree
facing the front window is beautiful and the rest of the tree looks
terminal, but it's up. Half of the candy canes have mysteriously
disappeared, but who cares?
</P>
<P>
   The gifts still need to be wrapped, and she can't remember where
she hid that video game but it's somewhere in the house. Her
youngest son has just given her a new Christmas list because he
changed his mind about that other stuff and he wants her to call
Santa before he packs the sleigh. She couldn't find any chestnuts
to roast so she has put some pecans in the microwave and realized,
too late, that 10 minutes was a bit long.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, there's an electrical short in the Christmas lights and
half of the strand isn't blinking. The Santa cutout keeps falling
over and someone has hung the wreath upside down again. And let's
not even talk about the Christmas cards that still need to be
addressed and mailed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she's trying to cook a nice, big dinner for
Christmas, but she can't find her meat thermometer for the turkey
because her daughter is using it on her doll that has a fever. And
the lingering odor from those burnt pecans is making her nauseated.
</P>
<P>
   When she hears the sickening thud of her lovely tree hit the
ground for the third time because the cat was climbing it, trying
to escape from the dog, she just snaps. She loses it. She goes
outside, hops in the family sleigh and takes off in a mad dash. She
hasn't gone a mile when the cell phone in her apron starts ringing.
She tosses the phone into a snowbank and laughs and laughs and
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I think happened.
</P>
<P>
   I could be wrong, but if you hear a news story about a woman
skateboarding on the freeway on Christmas Eve, don't say I didn't
warn you.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
