<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PLACE FOR COWBOY DANCIN' LIKE ANSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANSON, Texas _ Fort Worth had its Cowboy Ball at Bass Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Waco had one last week. Tyler was having one Tuesday night. But
the real Cowboy Christmas Ball, the one that started the multicity
circuit, happens this weekend in Anson.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Michael Martin Murphy is the featured entertainer now,
but more than a hundred years ago, New Jersey-born, New York-raised
William Lawrence Chittenden wrote of ``Windy Billy,'' a Swenson
Ranch cowboy who was calling the tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Folklorists say it was 1885 when Chittenden first observed a
bunch of clumsy cowboys dancing with a group of shy country girls.
It was in Anson, out in West Texas, at the Star Hotel. Chittenden's
poem ``A Cowboy's Christmas Ball'' was published in the Anson paper
in 1890. Later, it appeared in several eastern papers for whom
Chittenden served as a correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way out in western Texas, where the Clear Fork's waters flow,
</P>
<P>
   Where the cattle are a-browsin' and the Spanish ponies grow,
</P>
<P>
   Where the northers come a-whistlin' from beyond the Neutral
Strip,
</P>
<P>
   And the prairie dogs are wheezin' as though they had the grippe,
</P>
<P>
   Where lonesome, tawny prairies melt into airy streams,
</P>
<P>
   While the Double Mountains slumber in heav'nly kinds of dreams,
</P>
<P>
   Where the antelope is grazin' and the lonely plovers call,
</P>
<P>
   It was there that I attended the cowboy's Christmas ball ...''
</P>
<P>
   Chittenden's poem appeared in a collection of his works called
``Ranch Verses'' in 1893 (it's gone through 16 printings). Gordon
Graham, a cowboy folklorist, set the poem to music at the Anson
ball in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   The yearly Christmas dance was an event of major note in Anson.
The seriously religious town actually outlawed dancing within the
city limits. The ball was the only festivity where it was legal to
dance a square, a polka, a waltz, two-step or schottische.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on dancing was lifted in 1987, but old habits die hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be mostly people from out of town coming to the
ball,'' said Nettie Lee of the Anson Chamber of Commerce. ``This is
a very religious town, and there's still `no dancin' in Anson.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but Pioneer Hall, built especially to hold the ball, can
handle about 850 people, and tickets for Friday night were sold out
last January. Next month they'll be sold out again.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to test the flavor of the West Texas event,
tickets to the Thursday and Saturday night dances are available.
Jerry Sneed and his Up The Creek Band will perform on those nights.
It's Michael Martin Murphy's performance on Friday night that is
sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``An awful lot of people were not supportive of the Cowboy's
Christmas Ball because of their feelings on dancing,'' said Tom
Isbell, a local historian. ``It was a real challenge to keep that
tradition alive. If you ask the children today, they wouldn't know
who Chittenden was. One of the tragedies of our day is that we lose
touch with our past.''
</P>
<P>
   The townsfolk who do remember Chittenden were probably students
of Lenora Barrett, a teacher and folklorist who helped form a group
of Anson residents who re-enacted the old dance customs. They
performed at the White House in 1938. Barrett made her students
memorize Chittenden's poem.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas ball hasn't changed much over the years. Cowboy
hats can't be worn on the dance floor, and liquor is not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The ball begins with newly married couples leading the ``grand
march'' to The Eyes of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell me `bout cotillions, or Germans, no sir-ee!
</P>
<P>
   That whirl at Anson City jes' takes the cake with me.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Information box
</P>
<P>
   Where: Pioneer Hall, just south of the Anson town square, about
150 miles west of Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   When: 8 p.m. Thursday and Saturday (Friday sold out)
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $5, available at the door
</P>
<P>
   Dress: Western
</P>
<P>
   Information: Anson Chamber of Commerce, (915) 823-3259
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at Art Chapman, (817) 390-7422, or e-mail:
artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
