<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8926 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SHOAH-VIDEO-$ADV19-NY     12-14 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOAH-VIDEO-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOKEN MEMORIES OF THE UNSPEAKABLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Title of video may be italicized)  
 (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHOAH 1985; directed by Claude Lanzmann. New Yorker. Part I: 273
minutes; Part II: 290 minutes. Four cassettes, $299.98. In Polish,
German, Hebrew, Yiddish, French, English and Italian with English
subtitles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time doesn't fly in Claude Lanzmann's monumental film; it melts.
A chronicle of the Holocaust, ``Shoah'' (``annihilation'' in
Hebrew) proceeds deliberately, inexorably, for 9 hours and 23
minutes, set always to the click-clack of boxcars that carried Jews
to the gas chambers and crematoriums.
</P>
<P>
   Released in theaters in 1985 and now back on video after seven
years out of distribution, the documentary focuses primarily on the
death camps in the Polish towns of Treblinka and Auschwitz. In its
meticulously built concentration of detail lies the awful
fascination.
</P>
<P>
   Doing most of the interviewing himself, Lanzmann pulls the story
from survivors and eyewitnesses who lived near the camps. Of
400,000 prisoners in Chelmno, Poland, two survived, and the film
begins with one of them, Simon Srebnik.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, he avoided execution because he sang well and won
foot races with his feet shackled. In the film he sings as he is
poled by a boatman along a river through stretches of countryside
near Treblinka. It's peaceful now, but, as one witness notes, it
was peaceful then, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans did things smoothly. Throughout, the film pauses for
long, silent looks at empty landscapes, leafy and verdant in summer
and bleakly beautiful in winter. Scenes linger but never lag. The
very slowness generates a kind of momentum, as do the contrasts _
and the boxcars.
</P>
<P>
   Bit by bit, witnesses relate what they remember. Stacked in the
backs of trucks, dead bodies got flatter layer by layer. Sacks of
powdery bone ash were emptied in the river. The boxcars began
arriving at 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Treblinka began as a crude operation but was quickly fine-tuned.
``They'd finish off 3,000 people in two hours,'' says a former SS
Unterscharfuhrer. ``It worked well, the production line of death.''
</P>
<P>
   German guards were sworn to secrecy. Prisoners were to arrive
with no realization of what was to happen to them. Lies were told
to get them to undress. Panic would lead to a massacre right on the
train platform. That would be disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   The film's power is in the minutiae: numbers, time periods,
vehicles used, construction techniques. Was the road asphalt? How
far was the road from the burial pits? People were gassed in vans
driven slowly. How slowly? Who drove? The Germans used Poles as
workers, getting them drunk so they would complete their tasks.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, the Poles make matter-of-fact witnesses, responding
candidly and sometimes offhandedly to Lanzmann's aggressive
prodding. As they themselves point out, it was impossible not to
know what was going on. ``At first it was unbearable, then you got
used to it,'' one says.
</P>
<P>
   At one famous point in the film, Srebnik, wearing a faint smile,
stands on the steps of a Catholic church surrounded by Poles who
recall the era. Some even remember the young boy who sang in the
fields for the Germans. They smile and chat excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   Lanzmann asks why this happened to the Jews. ``Because they were
the richest,'' someone says. A man talks about Jews condemning
Christ to death. Of the Holocaust he says, ``It was God's will,
that's all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
