<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE SENATOR TO JOIN DIETARY GUIDELINES BIAS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State Senator Dianne Wilkerson of Boston is expected to
join a predecessor, Bill Owens, and others in a lawsuit against the
federal government, alleging racial bias in US dietary guidelines
because of minorities' difficulty in digesting milk.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, it is ``unethical for the government to be pushing
milk, based on the knowledge that it has about the effects that it
can have on people of color,'' Owens said Wednesday. He will attend
a news conference at the National Press Club in Washington,
Wednesday morning, along with other plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, initiated by the Physicians Committee for Responsible
Medicine, based in Washington, also alleges a conflict of interest
among some members of a government-appointed advisory committee
that is revising the US dietary guidelines. According to the suit,
some members have received dairy or meat industry grants or
otherwise been involved in industry-funded programs.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson, a Democrat, said she is planning to join the suit,
although as of Tuesday she had not yet formally signed on. The
state Legislature has just approved a $50,000 study that she
proposed to assess US-subsidized nutrition programs featuring milk
in schools and elsewhere, and their effects on people who have
difficulty digesting lactose, or milk sugar. Among the symptoms of
lactose intolerance are abdominal cramps, diarrhea and bloating.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of Asians, 70 percent of blacks and Native
Americans, and 15 percent of whites have difficulty digesting
lactose, according to a review of the literature by the Physicians
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy industry representatives, US health officials and some
researchers say people who have difficulty digesting lactose can
comfortably and safely drink a glass of milk a day, or they can use
one of the products with reduced lactose. Milk and other dairy
products are a rich source of calcium necessary for strong bones,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   The US Department of Agriculture reimburses schools for meals
only if they follow USDA recommendations. For elementary
schoolchildren, that means they're required to take milk unless
they have a doctor's note, according to the USDA.
</P>
<P>
   Other plaintiffs in the suit include the owner of a grocery
story in a predominantly minority neighborhood in Chicago, who said
she was cut off from the US food stamp program because she didn't
carry dairy products; parents of children who have difficulty
digesting lactose; and others, according to Mindy Kursban, staff
counsel for the Physicians Committee, a nonprofit advocacy group
made up of 5,000 physicians and 100,000 lay people. The defendants
are the USDA and the US Department of Health and Human Services
(HHS), the two agencies overseeing the revision of the dietary
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   While US officials said they could not comment on the suit
because they have not yet seen it, a spokeswoman from the
agriculture department defended the process by which US dietary
guidelines are made.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the dairy industry criticized the Physicians
Committee for trying to impose a ``vegetarian agenda'' on the
American public, with this suit as well as its other objections
over the prominence of milk in US dietary advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pushing a vegetarian diet,'' said Gary Wheelock, chief
executive officer for the New England Dairy and Food Council. He
criticized the media for continuing to ``overlook the hidden
agenda,'' in reporting on the Physicians Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal Barnard, president of the Physicians Committee, said
his group's support of a vegetarian diet as healthy is no secret.
But it is not demanding that dairy be removed from US dietary
advice, only that milk be made optional, especially when so many
minorities have difficulty digesting lactose, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
