<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-TURNOVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEREMONY MARKS TRANSFER OF CANAL TO PANAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ As a fine mist fell and large ships sailed
by, the Panama Canal became on Tuesday Panama's canal in a symbolic
ceremony that put an end to a troubled U.S. military era that had
partitioned and anguished this Central American nation for most of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   The historic ceremony marked the start of a new chapter in
U.S.-Panamanian relations, a fact that became evident already with
the absence of high-ranking members of the Clinton administration,
who didn't attend the occasion as a debate swirled in Washington
over the transfer and security of the waterway that links the
Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 29-member American delegation was led by former
President Jimmy Carter, who helped negotiate two treaties in 1977
by which the United States relinquished control of the 50-mile
channel _ an emblem of American engineering that remains
state-of-the-art today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a source of great pride in my country until the time I
became president and even now,'' Carter told several thousand
Panamanian and foreign dignitaries who congregated on the banks of
the Miraflor Locks, one of three gateways in the canal that connect
the two oceans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't understand clearly enough that the arrangement
implied an element of colonialism and subjugation, and not an equal
representation of two sovereign countries,'' Carter continued amid
great applause from those in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Although the transfer was conducted Tuesday, the Panama Canal
doesn't become the property of Panama until Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Panama is a strategically located nation of 2.8 million that
also links Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Carter arrived with Panamanian President Mireya Moscoso, King
Juan Carlos of Spain, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo and the
presidents of Colombia, Bolivia, Ecuador and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   As honorary witnesses to the transfer of the canal, they made a
grand entrance aboard one of the electrical locomotives, called
``mules,'' that guide ships with ropes as they make their way
through the narrow locks of the murky channel.
</P>
<P>
   A mammoth cargo ship emblazoned with the Toyota logo waited to
pass as the ceremony concluded. It was one of the nearly 40 ships
that cross the canal daily, slithering from one ocean to another in
a shortcut that bypasses having to navigate around South America.
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever questioned the American resolve and know-how it
took to start building the canal in 1903, a feat compared in scope
to Egypt's pyramids or the Great Wall of China. When it was
finished in 1914, nearly 30,000 people had died trying to build it,
many succumbing to the tropical ailments of malaria and yellow
fever.
</P>
<P>
   But many have questioned the uneasy coexistence of U.S. troops
and Panamanian citizens that came out of the turn-of-the century
accord allowing the United States to build the canal. It was signed
just a few days after Panama became independent of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso, Panama's first woman president, said her country has
sought independence throughout its history. She thanked Carter and
the late Panamanian strongman Omar Torrijos, who forged the canal
treaties despite great opposition to it in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a popular treaty,'' Carter agreed, adding that of
the 20 senators facing re-election and who ratified it at the time,
only seven returned to office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked very closely with Omar Torrijos, in our country and
also in Panama,'' Carter said. ``There was then demagogues who made
false statements, exaggerated problems, predicted catastrophes in
order to upset and disturb the people of my country. There are
still a few of those, unfortunately, in my nation today.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was referring to recent statements made by several
conservative Republican lawmakers that Panama, which has been
running the canal for last decade, was unfit to administer it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they have raised the specter of the Chinese
Communist menace because a Honk Kong-based company was awarded a
concession to run two cargo ports along the canal.
</P>
<P>
   There are also concerns that leftist guerrillas in neighboring
Colombia could pose a terrorist threat to the canal. Carter and
Moscoso said those fears are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas the U.S. Panama Canal Commission has been overseeing
operations, it will become the Panama Canal Authority at the end of
the year. Both nations have been in transition since the treaties
of transfer went into effect 20 years ago, a period that
effectively ends on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Panama and the United States have made great efforts to
realize a transition that would be imperceptible to users of the
canal,'' Moscoso said. ``Our final objective is to guarantee safe,
efficient and uninterrupted operation of the waterway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
