<SLUG> BC-DRUG-DEATHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US AGENCY URGES FDA TO MANDATE ADVERSE DRUG-REACTION REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prompted by estimates that more than 100,000 people die each
year from adverse reactions to prescription drugs, federal
officials have recommended that the Food and Drug Administration
require hospitals to report all serious drug reactions to the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA should also work proactively to more rapidly identify
harmful effects of new drugs, said a report being released
Wednesday by the Office of the Inspector General of the Department
of Health and Human Services. The agency should also encourage
health care providers to pick up the phone and directly call the
FDA with information about drug side effects, said the report.
</P>
<P>
   And, as new drugs are introduced at increasing rates, the FDA
will likely need more resources to protect the public from
hazardous drug side effects, said the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do more to correct the serious problems revealed by
this report,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.), in a statement
Tuesday, referring to shortcomings in the FDA's adverse effects
reporting system. ``Clearly, Congress has a responsibility to give
high priority to these important reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The report was in response to a set of questions posed by
Kennedy in 1998 to the Inspector General's office, which was
preparing to evaluate the FDA's adverse drug effects reporting
system. Kennedy's concerns were raised in part by a study in the
Journal of the American Medical Association, estimating that in
1994, some 2.2 million hospital patients had serious adverse drug
reactions and 106,000 patients died because of them.
</P>
<P>
   The new report noted that the FDA's own records of deaths and
hospitalizations reported to it seem unrealistically low. In 1994,
for example, the FDA said it received reports of 23,890
hospitalizations and 7,127 deaths from adverse drug reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations in the report urge the FDA to encourage greater
voluntary reporting of adverse effects from physicians and
pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that hospitals routinely collect information on
adverse drug reactions and store them in databases. The FDA could
require hospitals to report all serious and unexpected drug side
effects to it ``as a condition for participation in Medicare and
Medicaid,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   A Kennedy health aide said that some of the stronger
recommendations would require new legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
