<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANCE
</P>
<P>
   CASE DROPPED AGAINST MAYOR'S WIFE
</P>
<P>
   Citing a technicality, a court dismissed corruption charges
against Paris Mayor Jean Tiberi's wife, Xaviere Tiberi, who had
been accused of accepting a bogus job as a pretext for a payoff.
The court was scheduled to issue a verdict in the case, but instead
annulled the proceedings. Mrs. Tiberi was said to have accepted
nearly $36,000 for writing a 36-page report on a subject about
which she had no expertise.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIMISM ON CORSICA
</P>
<P>
   The French government hopes that growing separatist violence on
Corsica may end as talks began between Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
and the island's elected representatives. Jospin has dropped his
demand that Corsicans renounce violence as a condition for the
talks. Some Corsicans seemed encouraged but others warned that the
island has no less than 14 political parties or groups and three or
four armed factions.
</P>
<P>
   ANGRY BRITISH WALK OUT
</P>
<P>
   British members of the European Parliament in Strasbourg staged
a walkout during a speech by French President Jacques Chirac,
signaling their anger over France's refusal to import British beef.
In August, the European Commission lifted its worldwide ban on
British beef imports, and the organization is suing France over its
continuing blockade.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: REBELS KILL 23 MARINES
</P>
<P>
   The navy said 23 marines were killed when a unit of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, the country's largest
left-wing guerrilla group, attacked and briefly overran a naval
base and police detachment near the Panamanian border. The rebels
said at least 40 marines were killed and 40 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: DRUG-SPOTTING PLANES
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has bought 55 single-engine planes for use in
reconnaissance flights to spot marijuana and opium fields, and will
buy 18 more by February. The Cessna 182 Skylane planes will replace
72 UH-1H military helicopters donated by the Pentagon, which Mexico
returned this year after a series of maintenance problems.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: TOP GENERALS FACE TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   State investigators called for a trial of top army generals
implicated in human rights abuses in East Timor. President
Abdurrahman Wahid said he would not intervene to protect his senior
minister for security and political affairs, Gen. Wiranto.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: ANWAR TRIAL TO RESUME
</P>
<P>
   The chief judge in the sexual misconduct trial of former Deputy
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said he is ready to resume
proceedings, adjourned in advance of a parliamentary election last
month. The judge, Ariffin Jaka, halted the trial complaining of a
backache.
</P>
<P>
   CYPRUS
</P>
<P>
   U.N. TALKS END
</P>
<P>
   Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders ended talks with United
Nations officials on ways to end the ethnic division of Cyprus,
where U.N. peacekeepers have been stationed between the two sectors
since 1964. The Greek and Turkish leaders, Glafcos Clerides and
Rauf Denktash, did not meet; talks with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and his adviser on Cyprus were held separately. Denktash said
the next round was likely to be held in late January.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   AMNESTY RULINGS
</P>
<P>
   The Truth and Reconciliation Commission refused to grant amnesty
to six former police officers who confessed to murdering four black
activists in 1985. Amnesty was denied because they could not prove
the killings had a political motive. The former police commander,
Eugene De Kock, who did not take part in the murders, was granted
amnesty for failing to report them once he learned of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
