<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8942 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MOTIVE-DELL-COX     12-14 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTIVE-DELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New company to provide online technical support
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One of the founders of Motive Communications
Inc. of Austin is starting a new company that plans to offer online
tech support to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Abel, who helped found Motive two years ago, has started
all.com Inc. and is its chief operating officer. The company, which
has 25 employees, has licensed technology from Motive and is
expected to officially unveil the company today.
</P>
<P>
   While the company is still in its infancy _ it's looking for a
chief executive and venture capital _ it already has a pretty
substantial investor: Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's an excellent group of people with an excellent
product that provides efficient and affordable support,'' said Carl
Everett, senior vice president of Dell's personal systems group.
Dell has invested in numerous small companies in recent years,
ranging from software startups to Internet retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, which is a Motive customer, has made an undisclosed
investment in the company and has devised a certification process
for all.com's tech support workers, who will be employed as
independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   All.com will use the Internet to connect users having computer
problems to tech support specialists, who will attempt to diagnose
and solve the problem online.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the promise of easier-to-use PCs, tech support remains
an expensive headache, with worldwide help desk costs reaching $23
billion last year. Motive has focused on providing software for
diagnosing tech problems to large corporations including Microsoft
Corp., Walt Disney Co. and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   While more and more tech support providers have been utilizing
the Internet, industry analysts said the small office/home office
market, which spent $203 billion last year on technology, has been
left to fend for itself when it comes to tech support, and is ripe
for a solution like all.com's.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going after a major untapped market in an innovative
way,'' said Rich Ptak, an analyst with Hurwitz Group in Framingham,
Mass. ``The challenge will be maintaining a top-quality tech
support staff. They'll only be as good as the people solving the
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   All.com customers will be charged based on the size of the snafu
_ ranging from $3 to $4 for simple configuration questions to $15
to $20 for general desktop support. High-end server problems could
run in the $100 range. A percentage of the fee goes to the
contractor, and all.com collects a commission on each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Blair, an investment representative with Edward Jones
Investments in Austin who has tested all.com's system, said he
doesn't mind paying for fast service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not particularly computer literate. When problems do
occur, I don't have time to mess with them,'' he said. ``When you
call a computer service, you pay $200 or $300 a shot, and you may
wait three hours for them to show up. This way I don't have to wait
for anyone to show up. I can go right to the site and get help
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   All.com plans to make its software available to consumers for
testing at the end of January, and will begin charging for the
service in early spring.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Hawkins writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. W-mail: lhawkins(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
