<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8946 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-RADIO-CITY-CHRISTMAS-     12-14 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-CITY-CHRISTMAS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MORAL OF THE SHOW: BE HAPPY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once my critical colleagues have dispatched
themselves to various ceremonies of carols, the ``Messiah'' of the
day or the latest ``Christmas Oratorio,'' I check to see that no
one is looking and make a beeline for Radio City Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Music in this town has Christmas covered in every direction:
Baroque, medieval, Victorian, Edwardian and Currier &AMP; Ives. The
Waverly Consort offers music from medieval Spain, France, England
and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Lionheart, the male ensemble, brings us ``Tydings Trew: Feasts
of Christmas in Medieval England.'' From the Vox Vocal Ensemble,
``An Italian Renaissance Christmas''; from the Gabrieli Consort and
Players, music by Praetorius.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful may be these sounds, but none have much to do with us
right now. Maybe it is the nostalgia, the historical distance, that
makes us cherish the traditional carol so. Our hearts warm to the
sound of fictitious sleigh bells and angel-voiced carolers in the
snow. A lot of these things never happened but should have, so we
decide that they did.
</P>
<P>
   I like the ``Radio City Christmas Spectacular'' because it tells
me how the season is progressing on Sixth Avenue or around the
corner at Saks Fifth Avenue. I like a Santa not afraid to loosen
his hips to a boogie beat. The Rockettes make my heart beat fast.
</P>
<P>
   There is in this year's show a dance sequence of multiplying
Santas: so many that by the end they barely fit onstage. It's
comforting to know that there will be enough Kriss Kringles
available for every borough and congressional district in New York
City, with some left over for the immediate suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   This is Christmas in the world I understand, the one going on
above my head as I ride the subway every day. I never came across a
wassail cup on 34th Street or haloed Arabs trekking across the
deserts of Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   The only false note in the ``Christmas Spectacular,'' although
it is undertaken with obvious sincerity, is the Nativity scene. Its
mangers, cribs and wise men are like bad illustrations from
children's books brought to life. There is something removed and
neutral, almost lifeless, about it: this in contrast to a two-hour
show that brims with life.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe trying to show Christmas as it originally happened falls
flat because of what our Christmas celebrations are really about.
Through iconography and texts, the details of Christ's birth and
its significance are attached to all the other things we do at this
time of year. But behind a 2,000-year-old religion lies an older
festival: a midwinter rejoicing in plenty and well-being during the
bleakest season of the year.
</P>
<P>
   If the city's churches are telling their stories well, and they
are, the ``Christmas Spectacular'' conveys the rest of the truth
with a refreshing candor. Toward the end of the show we are in
Santa's workshop as Mrs. S. bellows confidently, ``You'll get
yours!''
</P>
<P>
   Despite our stabs of religious sentiment and the genuine joy in
making someone else happy, at the core of our Christmas is
gratification. Christmas exists to make us happy.
</P>
<P>
   I would extend this thought to the most deeply pious of
Christmas music. Victoria and Britten _ or indeed, ``Silent Night''
_ fill us with a sensuous pleasure. They are the ear's equivalent
of good food and drink.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal Church has caused a furor among its members by
trying to replace the old language of its Book of Common Prayer
with 20th-century plain speaking. I don't blame the howlers, but I
don't blame the church either.
</P>
<P>
   For so mesmerized had parishioners become with the beauty of the
old texts that spiritual supplication gave way to sheer pleasure.
The confession, the creeds and the responses rolled off the tongue
with a delight perhaps more appropriate to a musical concert or a
poetry reading.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Christmas Spectacular,'' with its up-front, no-excuses
cheer, does not suffer such problems. Its nine scenes fly like the
wind. Everything is touched on (from ``Swan Lake'' and ``The
Nutcracker'' to the ``Hallelujah'' chorus); nothing is dwelt upon.
This show is not about spiritual growth or serious attention spans;
it's about having a good time, about feeding one's eyes and ears
with the bounty of a harvest safely stowed away.
</P>
<P>
   It is also immensely clever and carried off with astonishing
precision. Given how much is going on, the coordination of music
and dance should be the envy of any stage enterprise anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockettes, bless them, never miss a step; and when they
smile out at us, the orthodontists of Manhattan can be collectively
proud. As toy soldiers, they are a delight; as Santa's reindeer,
they have antlers that light up for takeoff. Such touches could be
vulgar, but the ``Christmas Spectacular'' has the knack of being
amused by its own flashiness.
</P>
<P>
   I hope that none of the above is construed as an attack on
Christmas as Christian enterprise. The church has superimposed its
message on the seasonal urges of primal man and, in the process,
created a beauty and a sensibility that have made their marks on
this ancient celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Radio City Christmas Spectacular'' keeps us honest in its
way. It says that we should remember the events of the Christian
calendar without feeling guilty about overextended credit cards and
unwise ingestion.
</P>
<P>
   The renovated theater is a delight, with infinite care paid to
the details that bring us pleasure. Christmas means us to have a
good time, to let go a little. I can't wait to go back next year
and hear those two big Wurlitzer organs roaring back and forth
across the theater at each other. Gabrieli, eat your heart out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
