<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HUNGARY-ENVIRON-ART-4     12-14 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNGARY-ENVIRON-ART-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE DANUBE, A NATURE RESERVE UNITES OLD FOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOHACS, Hungary _ In the soggy lowlands along the Danube, where
war raged less than a decade ago, biologists and engineers from
three nations are working on an unusual project using nature to
promote peace.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is Central Europe's largest wetland, a great flood
plain formed by the meeting of the Danube and the Drava rivers.
Here, colonies of fish spawn among the reed beds. Wild boar, storks
and otters, whose numbers are dwindling elsewhere, thrive in the
mosaic of forests and lagoons.
</P>
<P>
   The ecosystem is one, but three countries _ Hungary, Yugoslavia
and Croatia _ meet here. The area became a front line in the war of
the early 1990s when Croatia broke away from Yugoslavia. Gun
positions and scores of land mines still lurk among the water
plants.
</P>
<P>
   But even as many border crossings remain closed here and
political tensions persist among the three governments, an
ambitious effort is under way to rehabilitate the area. The program
is environmental, but its implications are political.
</P>
<P>
   After months of negotiations, the three countries have agreed to
create a cross-border nature reserve that will encompass at least
250,000 acres, which is large by European standards. Hungary and
Croatia are to sign a cooperation agreement Dec. 15, the first step
toward joint management. The World Bank and other institutions have
pledged close to $10 million in loans and grants to manage the park
and create tourist facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our big chance to recover,'' said Darko Varga, the
mayor of Bilje, a village on the Croatian side of the border. ``We
can't produce computers, and we have nothing to sell on the world
market. But we have wonderful nature and animals. We want to bring
back the tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, managers of two contiguous parks on the
Hungarian-Croatian border are scheduled to begin to work together.
Yugoslavia has already delineated 25,000 acres to be linked to the
two other parks. But the economic boycott against the country has
until now excluded it from most international funds and regional
plans. But unofficial talks are going on with Yugoslav biologists
and ecologists.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the fighting, communications were cut among more than
20 villages and hamlets that skirt the wetlands. The war deepened
traditional distrust and local rivalries. Large areas are still
blocked off because of unexploded ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   But the communities have been nudged toward reconciliation from
the outside. The U.N. Development Program has run workshops for the
last two years to encourage village mayors to work with one
another. The Worldwide Fund for Nature has mapped the area and
trained local teachers in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now pressing the governments to open more border
crossings,'' said Varga, who coordinates the mayors' group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The planned reserve is part of a broader effort to rethink the
management of Europe's rivers.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a century of straightening and hemming in
waterways to control them, engineers and ecologists want to return
to a more natural approach. They want to reopen blocked flood
plains to serve as outlets and make better use of wetlands, which
can act as filters and cleanse polluted streams. The Danube,
Europe's longest river, is very much a case in point. Almost half
of its 1,800 miles has been lined with levees or concrete. Along
much of the way, it is shackled by dams.
</P>
<P>
   Near Mohacs, 100 miles south of Budapest, where the northern
edge of the nature reserve begins, the Danube becomes an impressive
600 to 1,000 yards wide. Creeks and inlets meander on both sides of
the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the war, some land has been reflooded and we hope
to keep it that way,'' said Philip Weller of the Worldwide Fund for
Nature, an adviser to the project. He said the area was crucial for
wildlife and one of Europe's most important flooded forests.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, parts of the wetlands that were drained in the
past will be restored. Engineers will flush out silted-up channels
and open up old side arms of the river to let the water run more
freely. The river spills into its flood plains here for about three
months each year, creating ideal breeding places for fish and small
reptiles and for the many wading birds that feed on them.
</P>
<P>
   Stands of willows and oaks harbor the shy white-tailed eagle and
black stork. These birds are threatened elsewhere in Europe as
their habitats have disappeared. More than 270 bird species appear
in this region.
</P>
<P>
   As the waters recede, the vegetation attracts mammals like red
deer, foxes and boar, which in turn attract hunters and poachers.
There is illegal logging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to get more protection now,'' said Tibor Mikuska, a
biologist involved in the project. ``We want the authorities to cut
back logging and hunting licenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected support has come from some rich families, who have
offered private land to extend the reserve, provided it remains
protected. ``This is a unique chance to protect the area,'' said
Karl Draskovic, whose family has pledged to donate some of its
forest holdings along the Drava River. ``There are still few roads,
few people, a lot of lakes and a lot of wildlife. It's magnificent
for bird watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The local mayors plan to spend part of the World Bank loan on
tourist projects, such as building observation towers and bicycle
routes and converting some of the century-old farmhouses into inns.
</P>
<P>
   Around Mohacs, on the Hungarian side, the land seems peaceful
enough. Herons and storks wheel overhead and thousands of Siberian
geese have arrived for the winter. On the high ground, farmers have
neatly stacked their wheat and corn harvest.
</P>
<P>
   But across the border in Croatia, lands near Osijek and Bilje
are still off limits and rife with mines, planted by both the
Yugoslav and Croatian armies.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with the hundreds of mines may be the reserve's greatest
challenge. The Croatian Center for Demining estimates that fewer
than 10 percent have been removed so far. Military maps have proved
inaccurate, and experts said that removing mines that have sunk
into the soggy soil will be extremely costly and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clearing the parts we will open to the public, the roads
and the trails,'' said Mikuska, the biologist who is also a project
coordinator. ``Those will be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that this policy, while not without risk, may
inadvertently help to protect the reserve from poachers and
loggers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should just include all the minefields of the area into the
park and warn that they are off limits,'' Draskovic said. ``That's
the best answer. If a wild boar steps on a mine, we'll have one
wild boar less. So be it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
