<HEADER>
A8950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-REACTOR-COX     12-14 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REACTOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University of Texas trying to get nuclear reactor satisfactionBy
Sharon Jayson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Maybe they should have asked about an extended
warranty.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer, in this case, was the University of Texas. The
purchase: a nuclear reactor, now on the fritz after about seven
years in operation. A manufacturer's welding defect is the likely
cause, which is why the factory rep is headed to Austin to take a
look.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have replaced it for free in the first year. Now it's
an out-of-warranty-type item,'' said Tony Veca of General Atomics,
who will visit Austin in the next few weeks from the company's San
Diego, Calif.-headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Veca said his company, which has built 65 nuclear reactors in
use around the world, provides a year's worth of free repairs or
replacement of defective parts in reactors it produces. UT paid
about $2 million for the reactor, which has operated at the J.J.
Pickle Research Campus in Northwest Austin since 1992. UT's
reactor, which is of the type commonly found at colleges or other
research institutions, is referred to as a pool reactor because it
sits submerged in a swimming pool-like concrete vat of water. The
water and concrete absorb the radiation, allowing UT students and
researchers to observe experiments without a safety risk.
</P>
<P>
   The faulty component is the reflector, a graphite ring enclosed
in an aluminum jacket that looks like the drum of a washing
machine. The stainless steel-encased radioactive fuel rods, which
normally stand upright inside the cylinder like pencils in a jar,
have been removed from the core but remain in the 25-foot-deep pool
of water that surrounds the reactor. UT officials say there is no
safety risk.
</P>
<P>
   Although the building that houses the reactor is still occupied,
the reactor itself has been off-limits since October, when
scientists noticed a swelling near its core and traced it to a
pinhole-size welding defect in the donut-shape reflector. Officials
say no radiation leaks occurred; however, a small amount of water
from the pool seeped into the reflector.
</P>
<P>
   During reactor operation, radiation from the core goes into the
reflector but doesn't escape the pool of water, which acts as a
backup radiation shield. The water that leaked into the normally
dry reflector, combined with the radiation, created hydrogen and
oxygen gas. The gas mixture, which produced the bulge in the
aluminum reflector container, exceeded Nuclear Regulatory
Commission limits. That's why an NRC inspector spent last week in
Austin monitoring UT's response.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've concluded there is no present risk to the public or the
students or the staff at this facility,'' said Marvin Mendonca, who
is based at the commission's headquarters near Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Veca said the one-megawatt reactor generates the same amount of
heat as 10,000 100-watt light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   UT researchers, eager to get the reactor started again, are
planning a temporary solution that involves drilling a quarter-inch
hole in the reflector to vent the gases. Once the gases are
released under NRC safety guidelines, UT can reinstall the fuel
rods and restart the reactor. Given the continuing presence of a
hole and seepage of water, the reactor's performance and the
quality of some experimental data may be hindered, said Sean
O'Kelly, associate director of UT's Nuclear Engineering Teaching
Laboratory at the Pickle site.
</P>
<P>
   It's a short-term fix, however. The long-term answer likely lies
with a new part. A new reflector will cost between $100,000 and
$200,000. Considering that a normal reactor's life span is at least
40 years, and that the problem developed in less than a fifth of
that time, UT officials say they're looking for some customer
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something the university has to work out with the
manufacturer, and it relates to who pays for it. That's something
that the lawyers will work out,'' said Ben Streetman, dean of UT's
College of Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   But Veca, whose company has constructed reactors since 1958,
said the defective reflector at UT is a first for his company. The
NRC confirms that claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it left our warehouse, it had been tested. All the
records show it passed the certification tests that we perform,''
Veca said.
</P>
<P>
   UT scientists are stumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not done anything to abuse it,'' O'Kelly said. ``The
manufacturer tested the reflector for leaks before they delivered
it to us, but we have not done anything to cause the leak, so the
question of what happened is still to be determined.''
</P>
<P>
   Red tape aside, the reactor shutdown has implications for
students such as Magdy Abdelrahman, who needed it to conduct
research to complete his Ph.D. in May. Although UT officials have
tried to help graduate students by suggesting computer simulation
and alternative reactors as backups, Abdelrahman said his research
will suffer until the reactor is back on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer simulation is not ideal. It will not produce the
same results,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Jayson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: sjayson(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
