<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-HIRING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISION ELIMINATES RACE-BASED POLICE PROMOTION IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT AND ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Faced with yet another court ruling saying that race
should not be a factor in personnel decisions, the Boston Police
Department will abandon a 19-year practice of bypassing white
officers to promote minorities, a policy that has divided a
generation of officers.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a ruling by Suffolk Superior Court Judge John
Xifaras, Boston Police Commissioner Paul F. Evans said Tuesday he
will no longer skip over white officers with higher Civil Service
scores to promote minority officers with lower scores in order to
meet affirmative action goals.
</P>
<P>
   Evans will also immediately promote about two dozen white
officers who were passed over for promotion to sergeant and
lieutenant in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to appeal Xifaras' ruling, Evans was acknowledging
what a series of court rulings have concluded: that a 1980 consent
decree requiring affirmative action in promotions to address
decades of past discrimination against black officers should be
ended.
</P>
<P>
   While Evans must now adhere to strict Civil Service rankings in
promotions, he wants the right to consider race for promotional
purposes in order to ensure diversity and avoid the situation that
originally prompted the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, when the discrimination case that led to the consent
decree began, black officers were five percent of the force but
there were no blacks among the 222 sergeants. Currently, minorities
account for 30 percent of the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``All things being equal, is race a legitimate criteria?'' Evans
asked. ``I'm for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans has asked a task force to craft a broader procedure for
promotions that takes into account factors besides Civil Service
test scores, such as job performance and management skills.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said he will continue to fight federal court cases where
he has used race as a tie-breaker between officers who scored the
same on Civil Service exams. And, while the consent decree for
promotions has ended, the department is still bound by another
federal court order requiring it to search out minority candidates
for new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Xifaras' decision, in which he affirmed a Civil Service
Commission ruling against the affirmative action promotions, was
the most recent blow to race-based policies in the city. Last year,
a federal appeals court threw out an admissions policy at Boston
Latin School that used race as a factor.
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall, reaction was mixed as officials on both sides of
the issue viewed the ruling as a triumph or a terrible setback.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilor Charles C. Yancey said that while white males
account for just 30 percent of the city's population, they control
the majority of high-level jobs in the police and fire departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This society has a long way to go before we achieve a level
playing field,'' said Yancey, who has been holding hearings this
year to try to prevent a rollback in affirmative action hiring and
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling must be viewed as a setback for those who believe
in any type of justice, in terms of having a police department that
reflects the makeup of the city -- at all levels,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Council President James M. Kelly applauded the ruling as a
proper continuation of the legal mindset that rejected the
race-based student assignment plan at Boston Latin. ``The courts
are clearly sending a message...that the end is near for race-based
hiring and promotions,'' he said. ``I consider it a positive step
towards a colorblind society, where people are judged based on
their qualifications and ability to do the job, rather than the
color of their skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said he will move immediately to promote six white
officers, who were passed over in 1996, to lieutenant, and also do
the same for 25 white officers who would have been promoted to
sergeant that same year.
</P>
<P>
   While Xifaras' ruling only requires the city to promote the
officers, unions representing the men are seeking back pay and
other damages in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Money was not the issue for John M. McLean, who will now be
promoted to lieutenant. ``I think that the decision is good for the
department,'' said McLean, who was bypassed in 1996. ``I think it
gives everybody a fair and equal chance and I think the playing
field is level now. I don't think anybody who is in the police
department who wants to get ahead should be held back because of
the color of their skin.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sgt. William Bradley of the Massachusetts Minority Law
Enforcement Organization, which sought the original consent decree,
said he was ``appalled'' by the loss of affirmative action in
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every minority citizen in the Commonwealth needs to be
outraged over this decision,'' Bradley said. ``We have been doing
race-based promotions for hundreds of years in this city. That's
why we have a Boston police department run by all white males. Now,
all of sudden, there's a problem when you are hiring blacks,
Asians, Hispanics and women.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
