<HEADER>
A8960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AUTONATION-COX     12-14 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTONATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AutoNation stumbled over used-car hurdles
 &HT;    By Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AutoNation may have learned an old lesson: If you
can't beat 'em, join 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Its innovative approach to selling used cars _ no-haggle
pricing, salaried sales people and computer kiosks showing
inventory, all in a mall-like setting _ couldn't overcome the
serious advantages franchised new-car dealers have.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the reason the Fort Lauderdale-based company is
selling most of its used-car superstores and concentrating on its
new-car dealership empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very competitive business, and (new-car) dealers have
the advantage of first crack at cars coming off leases, from
trade-ins and in manufacturers' auctions,'' said Tom Thomson, an
analyst with First Union Securities in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, AutoNation announced that it was closing 23
superstores nationwide, and integrating the rest with new-car
dealerships. Its three other metro area stores either have been or
will be combined with new-car franchises, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of the big box used-vehicle-only superstore is not
dead, but it's certainly lying on its deathbed,'' said Chris
Denove, an analyst in Los Angeles with J.D. Power and Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with 409 new-car dealerships in 19 states, AutoNation is
several times the size of any other dealership group in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts and observers agree that the move was overdue,
because the superstores had dragged down the company's earnings for
years, they differ on how AutoNation went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   First Union's Thomson said AutoNation built stores that were too
large for their markets, didn't merchandise their vehicles properly
and didn't control costs.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, competitor CarMax, a unit of Richmond-based Circuit
City, ``is doing a lot of little things better,'' he said. The
company has focus, the size of the stores is better tailored to the
markets, and it does a better job of customer service, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But like AutoNation, CarMax is turning to new cars to help the
bottom line and bring in inventory for its used-car stores. Many of
its superstores have new-car franchises. As a result, CarMax is
breaking even, but the jury is still out on its ultimate success,
Thomson said.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Power's Denove said AutoNation was having difficulty
selling used vehicles in a booming new-car market where
manufacturers can offer strong incentives to maintain market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price-conscious consumers who start looking for a used vehicle
soon learn that they can purchase a new model with a full warranty
for very little additional money,'' Denove said.
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation populated its inventory with vehicles in what Denove
called the ``nearly new'' segment, which customers often substitute
for new vehicles, J.D. Power has determined from its analysis and
consumer satisfaction surveys.
</P>
<P>
   When manufacturers cut prices through incentives, it makes
nearly new vehicles less attractive. Compared with traditional
dealerships that renew leases and accept trade-ins on new cars, the
superstores have had to buy inventory on the open market at higher
cost and sell in a more competitive environment, resulting in lower
margins.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles are coming into the nearly new market as leases expire
from a peak leasing period two to four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case of bad timing,'' Denove said. ``There's a huge
supply of nearly new vehicles entering the system in conjunction
with heavy new-car incentives. It's a double whammy.''
</P>
<P>
   While traditional dealers say they don't like to see any of
their colleagues fail, James A. Willingham, president of the
National Auto Dealers Association, said he thought AutoNation's
business model ``was wrong from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Salaried sales people, one-price selling _ over the long pull,
it just doesn't work,'' said the Long Beach, Calif.,
Buick-Pontiac-GMC dealer whose store is three miles from a closed
AutoNation superstore. ``They had too much overhead, and their
vehicle reconditioning was way too expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Willingham pointed out that, in spite of AutoNation's size, it
never came close to selling as many used cars as franchised new-car
dealers. ``They had maybe 1 percent of all used cars and were not a
major player.''
</P>
<P>
   The used-car superstores were high-cost operations with no
chance of ever generating profits proportionate to their risk,
Michael Jackson, who joined AutoNation as chief executive in
October after running the North American operations of
Mercedes-Benz, told The New York Times. Even if AutoNation had been
willing to invest heavily, devote a lot of management time and wait
for years, he said, ``the cost structure in those stores would
still have been very high, leading to marginal operations.''
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation shares closed down 18 3/4 cents to $8.81 1/4 on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation's annual sales are near $20 billion, and the closing
of the superstores will pare that by only $1 billion, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that these operations remained strong, but that
their profitability had been eroded by high costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``AutoNation faces a critical juncture,'' Robertson Stephens
analyst Jordan Hymowitz said in a research note. ``We believe that
Mr. Jackson will have to quickly take additional steps to secure
management retention and focus their energies on improving
franchised dealer margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Ritzler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
