<HEADER>
A8962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-HNS &LR;      12-14 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PREPARES FOR RESUMPTION OF ISRAELI-SYRIAN PEACE TALKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After months of secret maneuvering aimed at finally
ending the 50-year-old Arab-Israeli conflict, President Clinton
will play host Wednesday at the White House to a historic
resumption of Israeli-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Although no dramatic announcement is expected at the end of the
two-day meeting, the Clinton-sponsored talks will likely ``fast
track'' negotiations between the two enemies over the next several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is hoping that the sides will reach a deal early next
year that will finally return the Golan Heights to Syria and
greatly reduce Arab military and terrorist threats to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly no expectation that they can reach a broad,
wide-ranging agreement on issues that are quite difficult and
longstanding. But I think what they will do ... is work hard to
find a process that allows them over a period of time to reach a
peace agreement,'' White House press secretary Joe Lockhart told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent Tuesday preparing for the talks, which will run
through Thursday, by holding a series of meetings with his top
national security advisers and Middle East experts. Aides said the
president would open the talks between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Charaa but will not lead
them.
</P>
<P>
   The session is designed to let Barak and Charaa, who will be
acting on behalf of Syrian President Hafez Assad, talk out their
differences and lay out their requirements for resolving such
issues as the timing and security for what will amount to an
exchange of land for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Their one-on-one conversations will be a historic first. The two
sides have never held such high-level political talks before.
</P>
<P>
   The primary purpose of the talks is to decide when and how much
of the Golan Heights _ the hilly territory in southwestern Syria
bordering the Sea of Galilee that was captured by Israel in the
1967 war _ will be returned and what kind of security guarantees
Syria is prepared to give Israel. But the two men will also work on
a framework for normalizing relations between their two countries,
including the establishment of trade ties as well as diplomatic and
cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, along with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
U.S. special Middle East envoy Dennis Ross, will be available to
enter the discussions at any time.
</P>
<P>
   That the two sides are even talking at the moment is a testament
to Clinton's tenacity in trying to establish a comprehensive Middle
East peace encompassing all of the Arab states that border Israel.
The Syrians and Israelis broke off their talks in early 1996, but
Clinton kept pressure on both sides to resume their discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who has been dealing with the ongoing Israeli-Palestinian
peace process, has also been shuttling between Syria and Israel in
an attempt to strike up a peace agreement on that front as well.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Clinton also began a series of phone conversations
with Assad and Barak in an attempt to gauge what each wanted in an
agreement that would finally end 50 years of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while,'' one Clinton aide said Tuesday, ``we began to
get a picture of what it would take from Assad's perspective and
Barak's to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, this official added, decided ``the timing was right''
to get the two sides together. Assad agreed to send Charaa to
Washington during a meeting last week with Albright in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, meanwhile, had been searching for an opening with the
Syrians since he was elected in May. In a move that Clinton
administration officials said ``got Assad's attention,'' Barak
started talking more publicly about pulling Israeli forces out of a
nine-mile-deep buffer zone in southern Lebanon, which they have
occupied for nearly 20 years fighting a war with Islamic guerrillas
tied to the Syrian-backed militant group known as Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Any peace agreement will have to include Syrian promises to
curtail the activities of Hezbollah and implement other security
guarantees that protect Israel's northern border with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But while the situation in Lebanon will be an important issue in
the talks, the main subject will be the Golan Heights, which Israel
captured from Syria during the Arab-Israeli conflict. About 18,000
Israelis have since settled in the Golan, and Assad wants them
removed. He also wants all the territory returned that was taken
during the war, which would the land bordering the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   That demand poses some real problems for Israel because the
Galilee is an important source of fresh water for the Jewish state.
The Israelis have proposed drawing the final boundary line 30 feet
back from the water's edge to allow for access. So any final deal
would also have to include Israeli rights to the water or the
guarantee of a supply from some other source.
</P>
<P>
   The differences are formidable. But White House officials said
they are confident that the two sides can overcome them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they didn't believe their needs could be met, they probably
would not be at the table,'' said one senior administration
official during a briefing for reporters. ``They obviously believe
their needs can be met, but there's still a difference ... between
can be met and actually being met.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, this official said that ``we feel there is momentum
and we are going ... to be building on that momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there's a sense of urgency on both sides. I know
there's a sense of a commitment and a clear determination. But
there are differences,'' he added, citing the high-level of talks
as evidence that both sides ``are serious'' about coming up with a
formula for peace that works.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Barak has talked openly about some of the
``painful'' decisions that will have to be made to finalize a deal
with Syria. One of the most difficult, he said, will be moving
Israeli settlers out of the Golan Heights, where many of them have
called home for 18 years. But what Israelis fear more than anything
is giving up the strategic piece of territory where Israel has
maintained a defensive military positions for 32 years against a
possible military assault from Syria.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Knesset, Israel's parliament, put aside those
concerns Monday to vote its approval of Barak's trip to Washington
in search of peace. In a speech before the vote, Barak acknowledged
that Israel would likely have to pay ``a heavy price'' for an
agreement. But he said failure would only end up costing Israel
more ``in blood'' over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   A senior aide to Clinton praised Barak for reaching out to Syria
at the same time he is trying to implement the peace agreement with
the Palestinians. But he said that ``whatever agreement he reaches
is going to be an agreement that makes Israel stronger, not
weaker.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
