<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING INCREASES CHANCES THAT LINDA TRIPP WILL FACE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLICOTT CITY, Md. _ A Maryland judge ruled Tuesday that the
immunity granted to Linda Tripp by the independent counsel's office
did not apply to state wiretapping charges against her, making it
increasingly likely that she will face trial for the secret
tape-recordings of Monica Lewinsky that led to the impeachment of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Diane Leasure of Howard County Circuit Court, ruled
that the immunity, granted during the special prosecutor's
investigation of Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with Clinton, only
prevented the state from using evidence gathered by federal
prosecutors after Feb. 19, 1998, which she ruled was the date that
the agreement took effect.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Maryland prosecutors disclosed in court that
they had learned that as early as October 1997, Mrs. Tripp had
regaled women in her weekly bridge game in her neighborhood with
the information that she was secretly tape-recording telephone
conversations with a young woman named Monica who was having an
affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing Tuesday, the prosecutor, Stephen Montanarelli, also
told the court that Mrs. Tripp's bridge companions had told a grand
jury that she spoke about the tapings at almost every game and that
she even invited Ms. Lewinsky to a Christmas party at her Columbia,
Md., home so that the neighbors could meet and gaze upon the woman
who was unwittingly being taped.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling on the effective date of the immunity is
potentially devastating to Mrs. Tripp's case. Lawyers for Mrs.
Tripp and the independent counsel's office have said that they
believed her immunity took effect on Jan. 16, 1998, when a lawyer
from the counsel's office told her she had been given protection
from prosecution after handing over the first of the tapes. But
Judge Leasure ruled that the immunity began on Feb. 19, 1998, when
a federal judge confirmed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Since prosecutors must prove that none of their evidence against
Mrs. Tripp was a result of work by the independent counsel's office
after the immunity, the ruling lets them cite the many news
accounts about the tapes that were printed or broadcast before Feb.
19.
</P>
<P>
   Montanarelli, the special state prosecutor bringing the case
against Mrs. Tripp, said he was ``delighted with the victory'' of
Judge Leasure's decision. He lost no time in telling the court how
he learned from several news accounts that Mrs. Tripp may have
violated Maryland's laws against taping someone without that
person's consent.
</P>
<P>
   One notable article, he said, was published in Newsweek on Feb.
2, 1998. Under Judge Leasure's ruling, the Newsweek account as well
as several others that appeared that January could be used by the
state to argue that prosecutors had learned of Mrs. Tripp's actions
independently.
</P>
<P>
   Montanarelli's account of how Mrs. Tripp kept three bridge
companions informed of the taping meant that even if he had been
unable to use the news accounts from Jan. 16 to Feb. 19, he had at
least one other way in which he learned through his own
investigation that Mrs. Tripp had tape-recorded Ms. Lewinsky.
Montanarelli testified that one woman told the grand jury that she
saw Mrs. Tripp changing the batteries in the special machine she
used to record her conversations with Ms. Lewinsky, and that she
asked if the taping was illegal. He said the woman, Kathleen
Manuel, testified that Mrs. Tripp told her, ``Yes, but no one is
ever prosecuted for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Maryland law, prosecutors must prove that Mrs. Tripp knew
that her secret tape recordings were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the week is likely to be taken up with further
prosecution efforts to show that its information used in indicting
Mrs. Tripp on two felony counts of violating Maryland's wiretapping
laws did not come from the work of the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Murtha, Mrs. Tripp's lawyer in the criminal proceeding,
questioned Montanarelli intensively in the hope of demonstrating
that members of the prosecution team relied on the Starr report or
news reports about the independent investigation to help their own
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
