<SLUG> BC-BBO-WINTERMTGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big fish Griffey Jr. still in water as baseball meetings roll on
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ They relocated 38 players in a sequence of 14
trades. A couple of significant free agents _ Greg Vaughn and Todd
Zeile _ found new jobs. A few teams _ the Colorado Rockies, Tampa
Bay Devil Rays and Chicago Cubs _ significantly changed themselves
for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when all the suits filed out of the Anaheim Marriott Tuesday
at the conclusion of the 98th baseball winter meetings, they
encountered the same apparition that greeted them when they arrived
last Friday: Ken Griffey Jr., available yet unattainable.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings' biggest deal was the one that collapsed early
Tuesday morning, when the New York Mets reached tentative agreement
with Seattle to exchange Octavio Dotel, Roger Cedeno and Armando
Benitez for Griffey. The Mets had the notion, but not the devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey rejected the deal by telephone, the tail again wagging
the dog as the Mariners reached another impasse in their
considerable efforts to deal away one of the most desired players
in the game today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, the longer you go, things change,'' Mariners
general manager Pat Gillick said.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 of the 30 major league clubs declined to deal at the
meetings and the Atlanta Braves were one of them. Still, Atlanta
management maintained there was more at stake in their presence
here than frequent flyer miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't talk with every club here because I did that at the
general managers meeting,'' Braves GM John Schuerholz said. ``But
we talked to the clubs that we felt we had a chance to do something
with and one of these still remains a possibility. Another
possibility developed here.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it wasn't fruitless.''
</P>
<P>
   Customarily, Schuerholz refuses to be specific, but with free
agents outfielder Gerald Williams and shortstop Jose Hernandez
poised to leave the team, the Braves' needs are widely known. The
Braves discussed shortstop Alex Gonzalez with Toronto but came away
with stronger impressions for Los Angeles veteran infielder Jose
Vizcaino.
</P>
<P>
   Another target in the Dodgers' payroll purge, Viscount can
player third, shortstop or second base. And with $3.5 million
coming in 2000 salary, he is not cheap but affordable. But L.A.
cannot be certain of his availability until after the Adrian Beltre
ruling later in the week, which could declare the third baseman a
free agent because he was underage when signed.
</P>
<P>
   Scorecard
</P>
<P>
   Trading was up at these winter meetings after eight trades for
22 players last year. But free agents signing were down two big
names (Vaughn and Zeile), compared to eight a year ago (including
Kevin Brown and Rickey Henderson).
</P>
<P>
   This was a function of two conditions. Primarily, it was a poor
free agent crop. Almost as important, a group of available pitchers
is waiting for left-hander Chuck Finley, the most attractive free
agent pitcher to set a market price. Seattle, Baltimore and
Cleveland are pursuing him, but none is willing to sign him at his
asking price for a three-year, $27 million contract. Once Finley
signs, Aaron Sele would probably be the next to sign.
</P>
<P>
   The logjam has been orchestrated by agent Scott Boras, who
represents many of the best of the available pitchers: Kenny
Rogers, Darren Oliver, Omar Olivares and Andy Benes. He is
purposely waiting on Finley's contract before he will negotiate
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the meetings' highlight came when fellow agent Tommy
Tanzer challenged Boras to a parking lot fistfight late Saturday
night over an alleged case of client raiding....Oakland, suddenly a
force in the AL West, continues to push Anaheim for center fielder
Jim Edmonds, who could be had for pitcher Brett Laxton and two
prospects. . . . Appropriately, the ATM located in the lobby of the
Anaheim Marriott was broken as executives checked out Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
