<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-FIGHTER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING UNVEILS ITS JOINT STRIKE FIGHTER JET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Calif. _ At a top-secret plant here in the Mojave
Desert, Boeing on Tuesday unveiled what could be its most important
airplane of the early 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a commercial jetliner, but a futuristic military jet
called the Joint Strike Fighter.
</P>
<P>
   And the competition is not European airplane maker Airbus
Industrie, but U.S. defense giant Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``By any measure, this is a great day,'' Boeing Chairman Phil
Condit told several hundred people who gathered at Boeing's JSF
assembly plant here to salute the company's entry in what could be
a $300 billion sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, its suppliers, its JSF partners and the military all are
involved in a project that Condit said is redefining how airplanes
of the future will be made.
</P>
<P>
   About 700 Boeing JSF workers in Seattle watched the event via
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the future,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Boeing's 777 has been called a 21st Century
commercial jetliner. ``I'm here to tell you the Joint Strike
Fighter, which builds upon what was done on the 777, and improved
dramatically on what was done, is the 21st Century tactical
fighter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prize that Boeing and Lockheed Martin are after could be the
most lucrative military procurement program ever _ upwards of $200
billion for nearly 3,000 Joint Strike Fighters for the U.S. Navy,
Air Force and Marines and the British Royal Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Defense experts estimate potential foreign sales of between
2,000 to 3,000 planes, which could make the JSF contract worth more
than a third of a trillion dollars over the next four decades.
</P>
<P>
   The fighter would not enter service until around 2008 or 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The high-stakes competition will be decided by the Pentagon in
2001, following a six-month flyoff between two concept
demonstration planes built by Boeing and two built by Lockheed
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing demonstration jets are known as the X-32A and X-32B.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had been expected to unveil only the X-32A on Tuesday,
but when a large black curtain was pulled back at the ceremony,
both aircraft, painted white, were parked nose to nose.
</P>
<P>
   The X-32A is about to enter a ground test program, leading to
its first flight in the spring. Construction on the X-32B began
several months later but assembly has gone so well that it has
closed the gap to about six weeks. It is still missing the engine,
the pilot seat and some wiring.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ceremony was not the traditional rollout that Boeing
holds for new models of its commercial passenger jets.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the event was billed as a special salute to what Boeing
calls its JSF One Team in Palmdale, Seattle, St. Louis and around
the world. The unveiling ceremony also was to mark the
``ton'' of the X-32A into the flight test phase of the
program, including initial ground testing.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly building where the two planes were unveiled is a
windowless, nondescript hangar that is officially called the High
Desert Assembly, Integration and Test Center. It is on Site 1 of a
sprawling tract of arid California desert known as Plant 42,
operated by the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing leases the space. A few hundred feet away is the Boeing
Orbiter Major Modification Facility, where NASA's space shuttles
are hauled in on the back of 747s for refurbishing.
</P>
<P>
   Ground testing and first flights of the X-32A and X-32B will
take place here. Then tests will move to nearby Edwards Air Force
Base and eventually to the Navy's Patuxent River test facility in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The X-32A will demonstrate the requirements for the conventional
take off plane to be flown by the Air Force and Navy. The X-32B
will demonstrate the short take off and vertical landing
requirements of the plane needed by the Marines and British Royal
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Although final assembly of the two X-planes is in Palmdale, the
headquarters for Boeing's JSF effort is Seattle. Key sections of
the X-32 were built in St. Louis and Seattle. The one-piece wing
skins were manufactured in Seattle and taken to Palmdale on
military cargo planes. Parts come from suppliers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Long before final assembly began on a hanger floor, the two
planes had been put together by engineers many hundreds of times in
computer simulations in St. Louis and in Seattle. Design flaws were
spotted and fixed. The virtual reality system was developed for
Boeing's 777. With JSF, it has been taken to the next level and
beyond, Boeing says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You folks are going to define how we design, build,
manufacture, assemble, test and qualify aircraft of the future _
because you know how to do it,'' Frank Statkus, Boeing vice
president and general manager of its JSF program, said in opening
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Vavrik, a 33-year-old engineer from Auburn, Wash.,
represented the 700 or so Seattle JSF team members at the unveiling
ceremony. He got to make the trip because his name was pulled from
a hat _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   His job is to help design the cockpit at the Boeing
Developmental Center near Boeing Field in Seattle. Just as Boeing
talked with its customers about what they wanted to see in the 777,
Boeing is talking with fighter pilots about what kind of cockpit
they want for the JSF. The pilots meet with Vavrik and his team
about every six months.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's cockpit concept is to free the pilot to be a
``tactician'' who can concentrate on weapons deployment, Vavrik
said. The pilot would not have to waste time processing data from
the fighter's many sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Boeing needs to beat Lockheed Martin before the full
cockpit design becomes a reality. The demonstration planes do not
have weapons systems installed.
</P>
<P>
   Vavrik and other members of the Boeing team are confident of
winning.
</P>
<P>
   Geographically, at least, the competition is close. Only a mile
and a half of sagebrush and Joshua trees separate Boeing's facility
and Lockheed Martin's famed Skunk Works plant that is home to its
two JSF demonstration aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   JSF could be the last fighter that the United States builds
until well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pentagon insists this is a ``winner take all''
competition, many defense experts and industry analysts don't
believe it. They say both contractors will share production to
preserve the U.S. defense industrial base.
</P>
<P>
   Lean manufacturing practices and cost-cutting initiatives are
driving the JSF competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affordability is the key to the program,'' Statkus said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Pentagon has opted for performance over cost.
The Air Force's new air superiority F-22 stealth fighters now in
flight testing will cost nearly $200 million each.
</P>
<P>
   With JSF, the Pentagon is demanding that Boeing or Lockheed
Martin build a fighter with cutting-edge stealth and capability
that will cost from $28 million to $38 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's about what a Boeing F-18 cost today, and far less than a
Boeing F-15 costs. Both those fighters have been around for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   And the challenges for the two companies just begin there.
</P>
<P>
   The new fighter must be able to fly at supersonic speed. And as
the name implies, it must meet the requirements of more than one
branch of the service.
</P>
<P>
   Marine, Navy and Air Force versions will be nearly identical.
Commonality helps keep the cost down.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and Lockheed Martin were awarded about $700 million each
to build their demonstration planes. Statkus said Tuesday that
Boeing's JSF program is on budget, on schedule and has a surplus in
case of any last-minute snags.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who wins the competition, the production planes
will look different than the concept demonstration jets. In
Boeing's case, the difference is significant.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Boeing redesigned its plane to save weight and
money, and to improve the fighter's stealth and and
maneuverability.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-foot-wide diamond-shaped wing will now look more like a
conventional swept wing. The fuselage has been lengthened by two
feet and a second horizontal tail has been added. Boeing also
changed the huge engine air intake on the front of the fighter from
a forward sweep to a rearward sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Those design changes came too late to be included in the two
concept demonstration planes.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has further evolved its design in the last couple of
months.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is willing to accept computer models that can
predict the flying characteristics of the design without flying the
new wing in the demonstration phase.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing announced last year that should it win the JSF
competition, it will produce the fighters in St. Louis,
headquarters of its military aircraft and missile systems.
</P>
<P>
   Some defense experts and analysts say Boeing is the underdog in
its competition with Lockheed, even if it is found to have the
winning JSF design.
</P>
<P>
   If the competition is close, the thinking goes, the Pentagon
will pick Lockheed Martin because it can least afford to lose. If
Boeing wins, it would become ``America Aerospace,'' said Richard
Aboulafia, senior aerospace analyst with the Teal Group, a market
research and consulting firm in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would be No. 1 for both military and commercial,'' he
said. ``From an industrial base point, that's why Lockheed Martin
probably has the edge. It's difficult for anyone to accept the idea
of a single America Aerospace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
