<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-SLAVE-LABOR-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANS AGREE TO ESTABLISH $5-BILLION FUND TO COMPENSATE SLAVE
LABORERS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ After months of bitter negotiations, German industry
and government officials agreed on Tuesday to establish a fund of
roughly $5.1 billion to compensate slave laborers during the Nazi
regime.
</P>
<P>
   Though important details were still being ironed out,
negotiators on both sides said on Tuesday night that they had
reached an agreement on the central question, the amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the effort could ultimately affect more than one
million surviving victims of Nazi Germany's systematic use of
forced labor, though nobody is yet sure how many people may
ultimately file claims.
</P>
<P>
   American government officials estimate that there are about
240,000 surviving slave laborers, about half of them Jewish, who
were held in concentration camps and forced to work under
nightmarish conditions. The fund would also compensate a much
larger number of ``forced'' laborers, most of whom were not Jewish
and were brought in from the Soviet Union, Poland and other East
European countries to work in German factories. Officials estimate
that this group numbers anywhere from 700,000 to 1.5 million
people. In both cases, compensation would be paid to victims who
were alive as of last February.
</P>
<P>
   Although fewer than 100,000 of the former forced workers are
Americans, the negotiations were driven almost entirely by American
class-action attorneys and Jewish groups, as well as the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   German industry executives have been worried about the suits,
but even more by the prospect of a conflict with American customers
and business partners.
</P>
<P>
   American and German officials said they now hope to finish
negotiating the main elements of the plan on Friday in Berlin.
German corporations will contribute at least half of the money for
the new humanitarian fund, and the German government will
contribute the rest. American companies with German subsidiaries,
including General Motors and Ford Motor Co., are also expected to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   In principle, the fund could provide as much as $7,500 for each
surviving slave laborer and most likely smaller amounts for forced
laborers. But attorneys involved in the talks predicted some
bruising disputes about the rules governing how former workers will
qualify for those payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an agreement, there is absolutely no doubt about
that,'' said Michael Witti, an attorney in Munich representing
former workers. ``But anybody who thinks this will all go through
smoothly is living in a dream world.''
</P>
<P>
   Though about three-quarters of the fund's money will be used to
compensate forced workers, the settlement is also intended to
resolve other unresolved claims arising from the Nazi era.
</P>
<P>
   The fund also will be used to compensate victims of so-called
``Aryanization'' programs _ Jews and other non-Germans who were
forced by the Nazis to sell their property at firesale prices. And
it will be used to handle lingering claims against insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was reached after marathon bargaining over the
telephone between Jewish groups, American class-action lawyers,
German industry and the German government. It was mediated by
Stuart Eizenstat, the U.S. deputy secretary of the Treasury, and
Otto Graf Lambsdorff, a former economics minister of West Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are scheduled to arrive in Berlin on Friday to work out
final details and formally announce an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for contributing to the fund, German industrial
companies, ranging from DaimlerChrysler and Volkswagen to Siemens,
will be given immunity from future lawsuits over the use of forced
labor. German banks will be freed from claims arising from the the
``Aryanization programs.''
</P>
<P>
   All companies will contribute to a common humanitarian fund set
up by an independent German foundation, which will then transfer
money to designated organizations representing surviving workers in
the United States as well as in Central and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can confirm that an agreement has been reached,'' said
Wolfgang Gibowski, a spokesman for the German industry foundation.
``I hope that the money will come relatively quickly to the
surviving victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's agreement on establishing a fund of roughly 10 billion
German marks entailed big compromises on both sides. Attorneys
representing former workers had demanded 20 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
   German negotiators, as well as Chancellor Gerhard Schroder, had
insisted as recently as last week that there would be no money
beyond the eight billion marks proposed last month.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, advocates for former workers said they were
satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a measure of justice for slave laborers who have
waited a very long time,'' said Gideon Taylor, executive vice
president of the Jewish Conference on Material Claims Against
Germany, which has been collecting and distributing funds from
Germany on behalf of forced workers for the past several decades.
</P>
<P>
   Melvyn Weiss, one of the Americanclass-action attorneys
representing former slave laborers, said he was unhappy about
accepting 10 billion marks, but felt he had had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel good about it, but it is a pragmatic decision,''
said Weiss. ``At this point, we don't have a choice because of the
needs of aging victims and the pressure from governments to get
this resolved.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It may be only a matter of days before a new round of bickering
breaks out over how to distribute money to victims. Class-action
attorneys are already incensed over the draft of a German law that
would establish the rules for running the new foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Witti sharply attacked a provision of the draft law that would
prohibit a person who had received compensation from other programs
for victims of the Holocaust from receiving any money from the new
humanitarian fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the agreement will fall apart because of these
issues, but that rule is totally unacceptable and there will be
significant disputes over it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
