<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MONT-DRUGS-400&AMP;ADD-NY     12-14 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONT-DRUGS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTANA SENATE CANDIDATE HITS THE ROAD WITH HEALTH-COSTS CRUSADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FERNIE, British Columbia _ Al Gonder had a heart attack a few
years ago and now takes six different prescription drugs every day.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Blalock is recovering from hip replacement surgery.
Her husband, Luke, recently had heart surgery. Both take several
medicines regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Tombarge needs expensive inhalants. Vince Megaro takes drugs
to lower his blood pressure and cholesterol level.
</P>
<P>
   They were among 35 retired people from Montana, all of them on
Medicare and all with out-of-pocket pharmaceutical bills of well
over $1,000 a year, who took a day-long bus trip Tuesday to buy
medicine in this ski-resort town across the U.S. border with
Canada. Typically in Canada, filling a prescription costs a third
to a half of what it costs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was organized by Brian Schweitzer, the Democratic
candidate for the U.S. Senate from Montana, who has made the high
cost of drugs to uninsured retirees in the United States the
centerpiece of his uphill campaign to unseat Republican incumbent
Conrad Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about embarrassing Congress,'' Schweitzer told the
group, ``so your pharmacist can get drugs for the same price as
pharmacists around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Schweitzer promises, he will fight to repeal the law
that prohibits prescription medicine from being imported into the
United States, and he will work for Medicare coverage of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Schweitzer is the only Democratic Senate candidate to
focus on the issue. But James Jordan, political director of the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, said he expected the cost
of prescription drugs to the uninsured elderly to be a central
campaign issue across the country next year.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, running for a third term, opposes repealing the law
against importing drugs on the ground that Americans could be
subjected to adulterated and inferior medicine. His spokesman, Matt
Raymond, said the senator favored Medicare coverage of prescription
drugs in principle but had not seen legislation he could support.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, President Clinton proposed expanding Medicare to
cover part of the cost of prescription medicine, but the
Republican-controlled Congress never seriously considered the
measure. The Congressional Budget Office estimated that the plan
would cost $168 billion over two years, much more than Republicans
were prepared to spend.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Schweitzer's bus left Missoula before dawn with 10 passengers
and picked up more at small towns all along Route 93 to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Over the bus' loudspeaker, Schweitzer said he understood that
pharmaceutical companies needed to make healthy profits to pay for
their valuable research. Then he added, referring to the fact that
uninsured old people must pay full cost for medications: ``But why
do senior citizens in this country pay 100 percent of the cost of
research and development, and everyone else gets a free ride?''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is the only developed country without a
national health care system. In Canada and the other developed
countries, the government buys American drugs, and puts a fixed
price on them well below the unregulated price in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies in the United States also negotiate lower
prices for their customers. So essentially the only people in the
world who pay top dollar are Americans who do not have insurance
that covers prescription medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The people on the bus, of course, were all on Schweitzer's side.
``I don't know that I'm smart enough to say what needs to be
done,'' said Gonder, who boarded the bus at Polson. ``But it's a
whale of a burden on people who are retired and on a fixed income
to expect them to subsidize the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonder, 72, is a retired merchant marine radio operator who
lives on Social Security and a modest private pension. Here in
Fernie on Tuesday, he paid $280.32 for a three-month supply of each
of six drugs he takes regularly. In Montana, the cost would have
been about $450.
</P>
<P>
   There is no law against bringing prescription drugs into the
United States for one's own use.
</P>
<P>
   To buy drugs in Canada, Americans need a prescription from a
Canadian doctor. Schweitzer's brother, Mike, is a physician in
Billings and a past president of the Montana Medical Association.
He arranged for Dr. Ron Clark here to meet the Americans, look at
their prescriptions and write identical ones.
</P>
<P>
   Clark saw each of the Americans for two to three minutes,
charged them $10 apiece and gave them new prescriptions. They then
walked across the street to the IGS Value Drug Mart, to have their
prescriptions filled.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second bus trip for drugs Schweitzer has organized
this fall, and he is getting from them the kind of statewide
publicity essential for a 44-year-rancher who has never held public
office.
</P>
<P>
   He trails Burns by 2-to-1 in opinion polls, but Democrats in
Washington see this race as one of their best chances to pull an
upset.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
