<HEADER>
A8991 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-ART-NYT &LR;      12-14 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW'S MAYOR FIGHTS ON AGAINST FOES IN HIGH PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Moscow's embattled and combative Mayor Yuri Luzhkov
held a rally at the foot of the Kremlin on Tuesday night, under the
nose of opponents who for weeks have been orchestrating his
political hanging.
</P>
<P>
   With five days to go before an election in which he is running
both as mayor and as a leader of an anti-Kremlin parliamentary
bloc, Luzhkov told tens of thousands of people, most of them city
workers mobilized by pro-Luzhkov trade unions, that he would take
his fight against President Boris Yeltsin and his entourage to the
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are afraid of us because we will call them to account
because they robbed the country and stole our money,'' Luzhkov
roared, stabbing the chilly air with his finger. ``But we are not
afraid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If Luzhkov sounds defensive and angry these days, he has good
cause. For the last two months, he has been the unlucky star of a
Sunday night program on a Kremlin-friendly television channel where
he has been attacked, lampooned, exposed and accused of most crimes
imaginable in Russia today.
</P>
<P>
   The steady barrage of attacks, broadcast by Sergei Dorenko, a
journalist disavowed by the Russian journalists' union for his
attack-dog style and slippery use of the facts, has already cut
into support for Luzhkov's Fatherland-All Russia electoral bloc,
which he heads together with former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   That alliance, once a favorite in Sunday's parliamentary
elections, has now slipped to third place, behind the Communist
Party, the largest bloc in Parliament, and a new pro-Kremlin
alliance headed by Emergencies Minister Sergei Shoygu, according to
several public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The negative publicity has also chipped away at Luzhkov's once
overwhelming lead in the Moscow mayoral race, which he had moved up
one year to ensure himself a solid position ahead of next summer's
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov, who won re-election in Moscow three years ago with more
than 90 percent of the vote, is still by far the most popular
candidate in a crowded field. But some polls suggest that two other
candidates with tacit Kremlin backing _ former Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko and Pavel Borodin, the affable head of the
Kremlin's property management department _ may together get enough
votes to force Luzhkov into a humiliating runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Such an outcome would permanently damage Luzhkov's reputation as
Moscow's can-do political boss, the man who has swept the city
clean, erected thousands of new housing units, and bamboozled
builders and businessmen into backing ambitious schemes that have
changed the city's landscape. The most monumental of these is the
giant Cathedral of Christ Our Savior, rebuilt in record time on a
spot where an original 19th century church was destroyed in the
1930s by Stalin, in the Communist Party's campaign against
religion.
</P>
<P>
   For this and more, many Muscovites remain unquestionably loyal
to Luzhkov. ``He has brought back order to the city,'' said Raisa
Riabova, a pensioner who holds down a part-time job at a city
school. ``Do you remember the dirt there was everywhere before? It
was enough to make you cry.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when he first founded his Fatherland party (All
Russia came later with an alliance with a handful of powerful
regional governors), Luzhkov had clearly set his sights on the
Kremlin itself. But when Primakov, then Russia's most trusted
politician, agreed to join his team last August, Luzhkov willingly
gave Primakov the top spot on the party's parliamentary ticket and
a clear shot at the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Dorenko and financier Boris Berezovsky, a
Kremlin insider and friend of the Yeltsin family, turned their
media guns on the mayor with ORT, Russia's top television channel,
controlled by Berezovsky, which reaches virtually every household
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Brought back on the air for the election campaign, Dorenko has
been merciless, as he examined Luzhkov's use of patronage, his
administration's record for browbeating businesses, his quick
change of political colors (Luzhkov was once a vociferous Yeltsin
supporter) and his alleged involvement in the murder four years ago
of an American businessman, Paul Tatum.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Christ Our Savior Cathedral has come in for blistering
criticism of its use of cheap materials.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as a parting shot, Dorenko _ who delivers his lethal
blows with a light touch of irony _ sent a helicopter flying over
Luzhkov's country estate, with its tennis courts, stables and
riding arena and mansions for his deputies. In the meantime,
Borodin, shrugging off charges that he accepted kickbacks from
Mabetex Project Engineering Group, a Swiss construction firm that
did work in the Kremlin, has been giving sweeping promises to
voters, while Kiriyenko has been methodically critiquing Moscow's
murky finances.
</P>
<P>
   Fumbling to keep pace with Prime Minister Vladimir Putin and his
allies, Luzhkov and Primakov have moved closer to the Communists,
with whom they are likely to unite in an anti-Kremlin alliance in
the new Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But Luzhkov has also been put on the defensive in his own city.
Kiriyenko _ a member of Yeltsin's team of economic reformers and
leader of a new right-wing party _ said recently on a Moscow radio
program that his criticism of the city's administration is sure to
change the way Moscow is run, regardless of who is elected mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov's biggest mistake, some analysts say, was in trying to
supplant the Communists as the chief critic of Kremlin policies,
and in fanning a wave of scandals that last summer enveloped
members of Yeltsin's inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else did Luzhkov expect from the presidential clan,''
wrote Natalya Arkhangelskaya in an article in the weekly magazine
Expert. ``If he set out to wash the Kremlin's dirty linen in
public, he should have been prepared for a public display of his
own dirty linen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
