<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: TURNING POINT FOR THE MIDDLE EAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Israelis do not stand on ceremony or bow to
courtesy.
</P>
<P>
   But, in an exceptional show of support, Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's large, squabbling Cabinet showed up in force on Tuesday to
see him off as he flew here to resume Israel's negotiations with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   There couldn't have been a clearer demonstration of how Israelis
_ like many others in the Middle East _ perceive the import of the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   It is a moment of truth, as they see it, and it can be felt in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   Israel and its neighbors have arrived at a critical turning
point. If, as expected, Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa
shakes hands with Barak at the White House on Wednesday, Syria, the
longtime anchor of Arab hostility toward the Jewish homeland, will
be taking a giant step toward recognizing the state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   With that, whatever its self-interests, Syria will be sending a
signal to the rest of the Arab world about Israel's permanence in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   And Israel, which faces the prospect of simultaneously
relinquishing territory in the Golan Heights to the Syrians and the
West Bank to the Palestinians, will be taste-testing the
bittersweet fruits of those moves: Peaceful relations with all its
immediate neighbors would mean shrinking back into a truly tiny
country.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting with Golan leaders Tuesday morning, Barak sought
in a brief departure speech to embrace the warring emotions that
leave many Israelis feeling guarded: Some are hesitant to believe
that this time will be any different, others are unwilling to pay
the price and most are wary of another internal conflagration in an
intensely fragmented nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a difficult task,'' Barak said Tuesday morning at the
farewell ceremony. ``I carry with me to the negotiations all the
pain of the conflict _ the victims, the graves, the memorial days _
but also all the dreams and hopes of Israelis who wait for the day
when we look from a position of power and strength at a different
Israel, an Israel at peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts see in this juncture an unusual and perhaps
fleeting synchronization of the determination of three
strong-willed political leaders. Syrian President Hafez Assad,
Barak and President Clinton, who is serving as their broker, all
want, for their own reasons, to seize the moment and overcome the
obstacles that previously derailed the Israeli-Syrian peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, the new effort, which is likely to be blistering and
intense, will do little more than get under way this week. After a
ceremony at the White House on Wednesday morning, the Israelis and
the Syrians will retreat to Blair House for two days to pick up
where they left off _ that in itself being the first point of
disagreement _ when negotiations were suspended nearly four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if preliminary, this week's talks are likely to
prove a crucial opportunity for each side to gauge the other's
genuine points of flexibility. At issue are not just land, security
arrangements and water resources but a fundamental mutual distrust
and, on the part of Assad at least, deep-seated enmity.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Assad will not be here for the opening round
starts things off on a lopsided basis. Some think that Assad, who
is 69 and debilitated by illness, is too weak to make a
trans-Atlantic journey. But he is also reportedly unwilling to step
into the negotiations until they are further along.
</P>
<P>
   In al-Sharaa, the Syrian president is sending his highest-level
emissary, but that emissary will sit down with the top leader of
Israel, and the imbalance in their status makes everything
tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak sacrificed something on the tactical level, when he
decided that he would meet with Farouk Ashara,'' Nahum Barnea, a
leading Israeli political columnist, wrote Tuesday morning. ``This
is an asymmetrical meeting: Every word Barak speaks will be
recorded in the Syrian mind as a promise. Every word that Ashara
speaks will await Assad's final ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   On taking office, Barak pledged to withdraw Israeli troops from
Lebanon, which Syria effectively controls, by next July, whether or
not there is a Syrian-Israeli agreement. In so doing, he forced
Assad's hand and showed his own.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Barak would prefer to pull out of Lebanon with Syria's
promise to restrain Islamic guerrilla forces from attacking
Israel's northern border, Syria does not want to lose this
bargaining chip in its decades-long quest to win back the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Assad first approached the negotiating table eight years ago,
and there is a legacy of negotiations on all the issues involved.
That legacy represents not only a historical record of past
positions and compromises but a bank of experience that brings both
sides to the table well informed.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has noted several times that there are ``microscopic''
differences on Syria between him and his predecessors, including
former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who conducted
back-channel talks through an intermediary, Ronald Lauder, an
American businessman.
</P>
<P>
   All apparently agreed that the Golan Heights, a strategic
plateau that is home to 17,000 settlers, not to mention ski resorts
and wineries, would have to be abandoned in the context of such a
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians are ready to get it back, and their president knows it.
He dispatched workers to the streets of Damascus in the last few
days with banners heralding the rebirth of talks: ``We fought
honorably, we negotiated honorably. We will make peace honorably.''
He will guide Syrian public opinion as he has for years.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, facing Israel's restive democracy, will not have it so
easy. For however difficult are the negotiations with his
adversaries in the Arab world, what he faces domestically can be
just as daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have black hair when I dealt only with the Arabs,''
Barak, a former general, said jokingly in a recent interview. ``Now
that I'm beginning to deal with the Israelis too, the gray is
coming out by the day.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
