<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NEWS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RECEIVES RINGING ENDORSEMENT FROM FORMER RIVAL LAMAR
ALEXANDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ When Lamar Alexander was running for
president this summer, he made a point at every stop about his
chief rival, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, Alexander would say in one Iowa hamlet after
another, is not ready for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, that changed.
</P>
<P>
   Using adjectives such as ``steady'' and ``solid,'' the former
Tennessee governor endorsed Bush the morning after the first
Republican presidential debate in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's ready for the presidency,'' Alexander said at a
news conference with Bush standing at his side. ``I think he has a
clear view of the future. He's the only Republican with executive
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, regarded as a moderate Republican, brushed off
questions about what had changed in the months since he abandoned
the race without endorsing a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said a lot of things in the primary,'' Alexander said. ``I
did everything I could to test Governor Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He earned my respect the old-fashioned way. He defeated me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did that despite some tough rhetoric from Alexander leading
up to the Iowa Straw Poll in August. Back then, Alexander often
said of Bush, ``I was a one-term governor once about 15 years ago,
and I'm not sure I was ready to be president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   With a big lead in early Iowa polls and scores of endorsements
from public officials nationwide, the GOP front-runner hardly needs
Alexander's backing. Perhaps buoyed by a stronger showing in the
latest debate, Bush made a bold prediction about how well he'll do
in Iowa. The state's Jan. 24 caucuses rank as the first major test
on the road to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most vote anybody has ever gotten, I think, is 37
percent,'' Bush said. ``I hope to do that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Tuesday's transfer of the Panama Canal, Bush vowed
to use ``whatever means necessary'' to stop other powers, such as
China, from controlling the passageway. ``The Panama Canal is in
our national strategic interests,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   On another subject, Bush said he supported the military's
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy for gay soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it ought to be made to work,'' the governor said. ``I
believe the next commander in chief has got to send one clear
signal: We're not going to tolerate abuse. We expect people to be
treated with respect throughout the military.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9003 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-2NDTAK     12-14 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the day.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday, the Israeli Parliament gave Barak a bare plurality
supporting his initiative. That doesn't mean he doesn't have
broader support. It does mean, though, that in an incredibly
partisan Parliament where many parties represent sectarian
interests, peace carries a price tag.
</P>
<P>
   The internal political considerations are incredibly
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, the opposition is led by the Likud party now run by
Ariel Sharon, the indomitable but aging former general who picked
up the reins that Netanyahu dropped when he lost to Barak last May.
But Netanyahu's negotiations, although the record of what
transpired is secret, will tie his party's hands. And these days
Sharon, determined but slow-moving, is not the most stirring
opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
   Within his coalition, Barak faces three challenges: the National
Religious Party, which represents the settler movement; the Russian
immigrant party of Natan Sharansky, and, as always, Shas, a
17-member, rigorously Orthodox Sephardic party that has the power
to make or break his government.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are spearheading the Golan defense, which Sharansky
explains as a residual mistrust of ``dictators,'' among other
things. About a quarter of the residents of the Golan are Russian
immigrants, but they are not believed to be as adamant as their
leaders. Their roots in the area are not very deep.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Shas has thrown its weight around clumsily, under the
leadership of a relative novice in politics, Eli Yishai. Yishai,
whom Barak has tried with difficulty to groom, replaced Aryeh Deri,
who stepped down following his conviction for corruption last
spring. But Deri remains something of a force behind the scenes,
and a ruling that is expected on his appeal next month could
provoke his party either way.
</P>
<P>
   Shas party members are split in their allegiances to political
leaders, but also to rabbis. While all technically abide by the
rulings of Shas' spiritual leader, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, there is an
aging kabbalist rabbi, Yitzhak Khedouri, who also commands
loyalties. Yosef, who is considered dovish, has not made it clear
where he stands on the concession of the Golan. Khedouri, however,
has stated his opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, Barak has the power to buy Shas' support, literally,
by rescuing its religious school system, which educates some 20,000
children, from huge debts caused by mismanagement and worse. So
far, he has been unwilling to do that, on principle and because he
would then face a backlash from the secular Israelis who elected
him and chanted, ``No Shas'' on the day he won.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Yishai, in a show of good faith, joined the farewell
ceremony at the airport Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Golan settlers themselves are revving up for a fight, but
they too are divided. The radical leadership defiantly dedicated a
new neighborhood this week while a Golan peace camp registered as a
political movement. In the middle are a substantial number whose
hearts are at war with their heads, and they are concerned with the
bottom line: Will they get financial compensation from the
government for their move, and where will they go?
</P>
<P>
   Giving his backing to Barak, President Ezer Weizman has urged
his people not to be carried away by their emotions. He has a
nephew who lives in the Golan Heights, Weizman said, and if he were
opposed to leaving, what would he do? ``Buy a tank? Rent an M-16?
What's this talk of war?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9007 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSIC-LANGUAGE-3TAKES     12-14 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LANGUAGE-3TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A NEW CENTURY, A PROMISE OF NEW SOUNDS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for MUSIC-TECHNIQUE)  
 (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state of classical music now is strangely appropriate for
the turning of a millennium. After a period of rapid change, from
late Brahms to electronic music and John Cage within a lifetime,
music in recent decades has been relatively stable, and the
achievements of composers have been correspondingly solid.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot from the 1990s, in particular, to be carried into
the next century. But there are signs, too, of imminent change.
Economic conditions threaten concert life and the record industry
with a purge that one can only hope will be refreshing; composition
is bound to be affected, perhaps radically again.
</P>
<P>
   The art is ready for a new generation of composers, who are
likely to be dissatisfied with the increasing marginalization
accorded their predecessors of this century.
</P>
<P>
   A musical observer at the start of the 20th century could have
looked around at a number of living composers whose works were
being regularly performed wherever Western classical music was
known. And most of those composers were relatively young.
Tchaikovsky, Bruckner and Brahms had all died within the decade;
Verdi, Dvorak and Grieg were near the end. A generation was
passing, and the newcomers were ready.
</P>
<P>
   Puccini, famous as the composer of ``La Boheme,'' was 41;
Leoncavallo (``Pagliacci'') and Mascagni (``Cavalleria Rusticana'')
were about the same age. Debussy and Richard Strauss, both in their
30s, were well past the works that had brought them into the
international repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Adventurous listeners might even have heard music by composers
still in their 20s: Scriabin, Schoenberg, Reger. And with a
reputation more local, Edward MacDowell, at 39, had written
everything by which he would be known.
</P>
<P>
   We now live in a different world. Most of the composers who are
widely admired today are over 50, and some are over 90. If
Tchaikovsky had lived to Elliott Carter's age, he might have heard
Stravinsky's ``Rite of Spring'' as a young man of 73 and gone on
composing into the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   The fervor that greeted the appearance of the English composer
Thomas Ades a few years ago was due in part to the rarity these
days of a young man writing at full strength within the classical
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of Ades, now 28, spoke of freshness and change _
though still within familiar boundaries, for it seems that one
great age of innovation is over. It began a few years before World
War I and ended a few years after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Once Cage had produced his silent piece, ``4'33'','' in 1952,
there was perhaps nowhere to go but sideways. The only progress
made after that was in electronic music and in the recovery of
large form, whether by former serialists, like Pierre Boulez, or by
the new Minimalists, like Steve Reich. And even in those areas, not
much has changed in the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier excitement stimulated a lot of talent, which has
been harder to motivate since; thus the aging of the population of
composers. And that excitement can still be felt. Where popular
music of the 1980s sounds quaintly retro (Boy George), classical
music of the 1950s can often seem breathtakingly audacious (Jean
Barraque) _ more so than most of the music written since, because
so many composers during the last two or three decades have chosen
to travel not so much sideways as backward.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving aside those who try to imitate Shostakovich, Bruckner or
other earlier masters, advance in musical technique even among the
most progressive composers has stalled or reversed during the last
30 or 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   An example is the nondevelopment of the orchestra. Between 1800
and 1900, and perhaps even more so between 1700 and 1800, the
orchestra changed radically in its constitution, size and social
role, and a generation ago it seemed that comparable change was
being accomplished in the 20th century, with the introduction of
electronic components, the alteration of platform placement, the
addition of new instruments from alien traditions (electric
guitars, ocarinas), the scoring for unconventional groupings and
the presentation of performances in offbeat settings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, most composers write for an orchestra very like
that of Debussy, Strauss or Mahler, playing onstage in a normal
concert hall, the only differences being in the loss of national
schools of instrument building (a homogenization, therefore) and
the increased role of percussion (an expansion pretty much achieved
by 1925, in the music of Stravinsky, Varese and Berg).
</P>
<P>
   One can blame economics. Orchestras today, in Europe as well as
North America, can rarely afford to present such typical works of
the 1970s as Boulez's ``Rituel,'' with its 11 percussionists and
novel layout, or Karlheinz Stockhausen's ``Trans,'' which needs
special staging, electronics and lighting.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, perhaps financing could be found if the
musical necessity were there. Generally it is not. Boulez has
returned to writing for relatively regular, if large, orchestral
forces in his ``Notations'' series, and Stockhausen has come to
prefer small groups, which can give him adequate rehearsal time.
Neither composer seems now to feel that the orchestra, as a
dominant institution, must be carried forward on the wave of
musical advance. Neither (italics)could(end italics) feel that,
because the wave has subsided.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There have been other periods of comparative calm and stability
in the language of music. Nothing too much changed, for instance,
during the quarter-century after Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde''
appeared, in 1865. Life went on, and it continues to go on. But
after a time of such extreme and rapid change as happened between
1908, when Schoenberg began writing atonal music, and the early
'50s _ a period during which music moved forward all the time to
take on new challenges _ composers may well feel the lack of a
driving force, whether they exult in that lack or bemoan it.
</P>
<P>
   The current vogue for religious music is a symptom. With no
arrow from musical history now to point the way ahead, composers
may gain a sense of purpose from God, whose directives, it appears,
are often comfortingly regressive. Certainly there are few
religious composers who emulate Olivier Messiaen in taking it as
their sacred duty to embrace any and every sound.
</P>
<P>
   Other sources of purpose are hard to find. Few composers can
draw strength from a sense of serving an audience, since the
audience, in the main, has shown itself perfectly capable of
getting along without them. Nor is there much support to be had
from political forces. Socialism and nationalism, which once
energized so many composers, do so no longer.
</P>
<P>
   What remains is the domain of the personal, and the widespread
return to the conventions of Romantic music can perhaps be
explained as a searching for means of expression. Especially during
that earlier period of placidity following ``Tristan,'' music had
great rhetorical power, a wide expressive range and the stylistic
breadth to give voice to such diverse personalities as Brahms and
Liszt, Verdi and Tchaikovsky.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the example of a previous reinvocation of the late
Romantic style, in the 1930s, when composers across the range from
Schoenberg to Prokofiev went back to it. Nothing is new in
postmodernism except the name.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot be, though, that means of expression for today are to
be found only in a musical language well over a century old,
understandable though such a return may be in terms not only of the
Romantic style's allure but also of the comparative underselling of
expression by the 20th-century modernists. Stravinsky and Cage, at
an extreme, explicitly disclaimed subjective expression, though
their music argues loudly with their manifestos.
</P>
<P>
   And the composers who emerged right after World War II had their
sights on levels of abstraction that would enable them to write a
new, clean music. Since what had recently happened was
inexpressible, the only appropriate course was to express nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Expression, though, is unavoidable. And especially at a time
like now, when expression has come to the forefront again, one can
hear the anger in Boulez's early music, the fastidious wit in
Milton Babbitt's, the sense of wonder in Gyorgy Ligeti's. From a
modern, expressive viewpoint, too, the music Luigi Nono wrote in
the 1950s has come to have greater importance, for Nono absented
himself from the contemporary drive to theorize, insisting that he
could and must express the sufferings, struggles and hopes of his
time. And he did so not by resurrecting Romanticism but by pursuing
a fiercely modern musical language.
</P>
<P>
   Nono's subjects, if not his means, have become general. Nearly
half a century after his ``Canto Sospeso,'' in which he set
extracts from prison letters by Nazi victims, many composers are
coming to attend to the experiences of war and totalitarianism, not
to pretend, in a new century, that the old century's dangers will
be over.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Werner Henze's recent Ninth Symphony, he has said, ``deals
with the German homeland as I experienced it as a young man during
and before the war,'' and ``portrays an apotheosis of terror and
grief.'' Other composers, lacking Henze's direct contact with
Nazism, have looked to the testimony of two European Jewish poets
who used their writing as a strategy for survival and, when that
failed, committed suicide: Paul Celan (a model and a source in the
work of the Swiss composer Heinz Holliger and the Czech-German
Peter Ruzicka) and Primo Levi (set by the English composer Simon
Bainbridge).
</P>
<P>
   Yet other composers, without referring directly to the events of
the 1930s and '40s, have kept on projecting musical visions
essentially tragic, bleak or constrained. Gyorgy Kurtag is one.
Like Nono, he was writing powerfully expressive music in the '50s,
though it was only in the late '70s and the '80s, with the general
revaluation of the expressive, that he began to gain an audience
outside Budapest, where he then lived.
</P>
<P>
   Indebted to the great tradition, from Bach to Bartok, he is in
some ways the most deep-dyed of the new Romantic conservatives,
except that in his case the Romantic gesture _ the melody or chord
change that speaks louder than words _ is freed from the upholstery
of 19th-century textures and forms to be placed in a new context,
generally in a fragment that seems at once lapidary and vital.
</P>
<P>
   The radiant sense of ruin in Kurtag's music probably has
something to do with his double acquaintance with totalitarian
power, under Stalin as well as Hitler, and there are many other
composers from Communist Europe who felt compelled to give voice:
among them, Galina Ustvolskaya, in whose music religious simplicity
is shocking, not comforting, and Sofia Gubaidulina. The music of
composers like Ms. Gubaidulina, Kurtag and Holliger demonstrates
that modernism is by no means incompatible with expression, as was
earlier hoped by some and feared by many.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one may reasonably feel that only a contemporary musical
language can express the temper of the times, for the changes that
take place in musical style are not arbitrary; they are of a piece
with other changes in life and culture, and they need to be
recognized by composers who are concerned to speak of the present
and of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the present is thin if it does not contain an
awareness of the past. Boulez and some of his colleagues in the
early '50s wanted to create a music without memory, a New Music as
it was significantly called in Germany. Any hint of history _ a
tonal chord, a singable melody _ was to be avoided; some even
thought that the New Music would have to be exclusively electronic.
</P>
<P>
   It did not last. History could not be expunged any more than
expression could; indeed, the two impossibilities are linked,
because history gives the models in music by which we recognize
expression (the yearning interval, the sensuous harmony), and our
wish to make contact with expression urges us to remember the music
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   All this the New Music soon had to recognize. Still, there
remained the ideal of creating music that would not stalely repeat
what had already been done, and it is an ideal that many composers
have refused to abandon. Where Kurtag makes a homage to Schumann,
for example, he does so not just by quoting but also by stretching
the range of his own language. It is a question not of putting on
fancy dress but of reaching out a hand to touch another person,
even a person known only through music.
</P>
<P>
   The best alternative is a multilayered music in which Schumann
might coexist with Central African drumming, Hispanic-Caribbean
dance music and the complex rhythmic canons of Conlon Nancarrow, as
in some of Ligeti's recent work. Kurtag and Ligeti _ both born in
Transylvania and trained in Budapest, both now exiles _ are
outstanding representatives of two notably successful currents
among the bewildering waterways of classical music today.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtag speaks with a single voice and suggests in his music the
authorial presence with which we are familiar in 19th-century
music; Ligeti refracts that presence through levels of allusion and
self-observation.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtag's music maintains the old equation of communication: he
speaks, and we listen. Our experience of Ligeti's music _ or of
Carter's or Luciano Berio's or Harrison Birtwistle's or John Adams'
_ is likely to be more complicated. Though different in so many
other ways, all these composers commonly write in simultaneous
conflicting speeds and meters, so that there is no controlling
rhythmic line, and thus, it seems, no single subjective voice.
</P>
<P>
   There are other similarities. The music of these polyvocal
composers will often be exuberant and playful, sometimes even when
the underlying expressive charge is gloomy, as in the several
pieces Ligeti has recently produced on falling lament motifs.
</P>
<P>
   Where Kurtag and Holliger convey a pessimism that nobody could
avoid, looking back on the last century, Ligeti and Carter offer an
optimism we would all want, looking forward to the next.
</P>
<P>
   As far as music is concerned, optimism is appropriate. There are
many more composers at work today than ever before, in many more
styles, most of them endeavoring to do what composers have done
throughout the history of Western music: make a new sound. They
lack the rapid technical advances that upheld them and their
colleagues 40 or 50 years ago, but they still face the biggest
challenge, which is to find something that speaks from, for and of
them, and that by being personal is unprecedented and commands
attention.
</P>
<P>
   We are reaching, perhaps, the end of an epoch of relative stasis
_ an epoch also of extraordinary achievement. The language of music
will soon be developing again, in younger heads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
