<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9035 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PARSONS-DANCE-ART-2TA     12-14 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARSONS-DANCE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A DAY, THE GREATEST DANCE SHOW ON EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19)  
 (af)  
 Christopher Reardon's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about the choreographer David Rousseve.  
 By CHRISTOPHER REARDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Parsons would love to hole up for a few days
and shake the flu that has vexed him since Thanksgiving weekend.
Instead, with the biggest show of his life just days away, he drags
himself out of bed most mornings and gets to work.
</P>
<P>
   As the choreographer for ``Times Square 2000,'' Manhattan's
round-the-clock salute to the millennium, Parsons is putting the
finishing touches on nearly a dozen new dances by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   The show will go on with or without him, of course. But the way
Parsons has handled his looming deadline and lingering infection
seems to justify the decision to hire him in the first place.
Colleagues say he has kept his part of the program on track _
despite a trip to the hospital to be treated for dehydration _ with
shrewd planning, a lively imagination and undisguised pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor celebration will start around sunrise on Dec. 31 and
continue for 24 hours. As midnight approaches in each time zone, a
cast and crew of nearly 1,000 will set the mood with dance, music,
video, confetti and a cavalcade of giant puppets.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the dancing will take place on an elevated stage to be
erected in the middle of Times Square; the rest, like the puppetry,
will happen in the streets, in emergency lanes kept clear by the
police.
</P>
<P>
   With 1.5 million revelers expected to turn out, and perhaps a
billion more watching on television and the Internet, the stakes
are staggeringly high.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people will see you in this show,'' Parsons told some
dancers at a recent rehearsal, ``than every dance concert I'll ever
give in 50 lifetimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, who turned 40 in October, is known as a can-do
choreographer with a knack for winning over the crowd. He began
working on ``Times Square 2000'' just over a year ago and helped
develop a set of hourly themes with Geoff Puckett, the show's
creative director, and Michael Curry, the puppet designer. But his
contribution ultimately hinges on the single month of rehearsal
time that he and his troupe, the Parsons Dance Company, have carved
out of their heavy touring schedule.
</P>
<P>
   And so the real work began less than three weeks ago, in a humid
studio at City Center. Parsons was there, with a bowl of soup and a
battery of medications at his side, and so was most of his troupe.
</P>
<P>
   Joining them were dozens of aspiring dancers he had picked for
the show in a September audition.
</P>
<P>
   The first rehearsal focused on the big opening number,
``Awakening,'' which uses slow, ritualistic encounters to evoke the
dawn of civilization and time itself. While most of the material
was new, Parsons had no qualms about recycling bits of repertory.
At one point, he gave new meaning to a rhythmic series of gestures
lifted from ``Step Into My Dream,'' his 1994 collaboraion with
Billy Taylor's jazz trio.
</P>
<P>
   In rapid succession, he and the dancers have also adapted an
aboriginal stick dance from Australia, an umbrella processional
from Japan and a Chinese dragon dance that features a 90-foot-long
puppet. Often Parsons would describe a dance in broad outline, then
demonstrate some likely steps. When his energy flagged, he asked a
few of his leading dancers _ most notably Robert Battle, who has
contributed six dances to the company's repertory since 1997 _ to
fill in blanks and smooth out transitions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parsons remains the final authority. ``This is too
complicated,'' he said one day as they worked on ``Ports of Call,''
a Celtic jig that relaxes to a Caribbean beat. ``Remember, you're
going to be wearing rubber boots and big yellow raincoats. It's not
like you can do pirouettes out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting the dancers into a simple swaying motion, he quickly
conjured up a ship at sea. You could almost smell the salt air.
Then, reaching for a mop, he played around with easy swabbing
motions. As others followed suit, the studio came to resemble a
snappy outtake from ``Anchors Aweigh.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Frank Sinatra's and Gene Kelly's characters in that
1945 Hollywood caper, Parsons' dancers will not get any shore
leave. Because of anticipated congestion in Midtown, they are
supposed to stay close to Times Square for the duration of the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Cots will be set up in the Bertelsmann building, and there will
be a heated waiting room underneath the stage, which will sit on a
traffic island between Broadway and Seventh Avenue just north of
45th Street. ( Curry, who has enlisted hundreds of volunteers to
parade his fanciful puppets through the crowd, will work out of a
separate space near 42nd Street.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the pageantry will start 15 minutes before each hour
and finish 10 minutes after. For several of the hours, Parsons has
booked guest artists to perform traditional dances from Bali,
Turkey, Brazil, Hawaii and the Sioux tribes of South Dakota. His
biggest challenge, though, has been creating or adapting dances for
about 12 of the hours.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographing on the fly has become second nature to Parsons,
who routinely creates dances in a span of 10 or 12 days. Because of
that compressed creative process, he often makes extensive
revisions to his work after it reaches the stage. But with ``Times
Square 2000,'' there are no second chances.
</P>
<P>
   After 12 years of taking his repertory on the road, he said he
welcomed the transience of a one-shot performance _ and the
opportunity for his dancers to unpack their suitcases.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason I'm doing this is to get us off the road,'' said
Parsons, whose company often tours more than 40 weeks a year.
``It's that simple. You have to find ways to keep people at home
and still pay them.''
</P>
<P>
   He works his dancers hard, but also offers regular salaries and
reliable health care. ``I've compromised _ I know I have _ to give
my dancers those things,'' he said, explaining that the troupe's
busy schedule cuts into his creative time. ``But I've had one get
hit by a truck and one who has HIV. This may be theater, but I'm a
very practical person. I've always struggled to make sure the
people I work with are taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more troubling aspects of ``Times Square 2000,'' he
said, is the sense that he is asking too much of the 50 walk-ons
who will augment his troupe. For a full month of rehearsals _
including three overnight drills at Times Square _ and a marathon
performance in the dead of winter, they will receive an honorarium
of $100.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the thrill of being seen on television by a billion
viewers is enough for some of the recruits. But many hope to
impress an audience of one: Parsons. He can hardly blame them. As a
teenager, he hung around Paul Taylor's studio for several months
before the choreographer took him on as an understudy. He got his
break when a dancer was injured just before a tour to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   After 12 years at the helm of his own company, Parsons has grown
accustomed to a level of artistic independence that ``Times Square
2000'' cannot match. As a former gymnast, he envisioned using
trampolines to propel performers high above the crowd. But safety
considerations (the trampolines might obstruct fire lanes) and
budget constraints (the gymnasts wanted too much money) squelched
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Parsons said he found it exhilarating to work on such a
large theatrical scale. ``The object is to change the process,'' he
said. ``Maybe it's uncomfortable. Maybe you fail. But you're still
pushing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
