<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRANSIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION LEADERS SAY THEY WILL NOT CALL TRANSIT STRIKE FOR WEDNESDAY
MORNING
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As contract talks continued feverishly on Tuesday,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said leaders of the transit workers' union
had provided assurances that the union would not shut down New York
City's transit system on Wednesday morning, although city officials
predicted rush-hour chaos because of wildcat work stoppages.
</P>
<P>
   After a state judge issued two orders threatening the union with
draconian fines if it went on strike, Willie James, president of
the union representing 33,000 subway and bus workers, told the
Giuliani administration that he would not call for a walkout on
Wednesday morning, City Hall officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, James and other leaders in Local 100 of the Transport
Workers Union have threatened a strike if they did not reach an
agreement with the Metropolitan Transportation Authority by 12:01
on Wednesday morning, when the union's contract expired.
</P>
<P>
   James sent a letter to all members on Tuesday warning that the
huge fines that could be imposed from defying the judge's orders
``will quickly bankrupt the Union making it unable to function on
your behalf.'' But the letter stopped short of saying outright that
he would not call for a strike.
</P>
<P>
   At a City Hall news conference, Giuliani said the letter made
clear that the union's leaders opposed a walkout, which would be
illegal under New York state's Taylor Law, which bars strikes by
transit workers and other public-sector employees.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani added that there was still a small chance that a
large dissident faction in the union could muster the votes to
authorize a strike _ a move that could paralyze the city and create
havoc for 3.5 million people who use the mass transit system each
day.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said some parts of a contingency plan to speed
transportation into Manhattan would go into effect on Wednesday
morning, and that the full plan _ which would restrict motor
vehicle access _ would be ready if needed.
</P>
<P>
   An official close to the negotiations said on Tuesday night that
the two sides had considerably narrowed their differences, with the
union reducing its wage demands to 5 percent a year over three
years, down from its previous demand for 9 percent a year. The MTA,
this official said, had raised its offer to 13 percent over four
years, up from its previous offer of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After four days of attacking the union, Giuliani escalated his
efforts on Tuesday to pressure it not to strike. He had the city's
lawyers go to a judge's house shortly before 7 a.m. to obtain a
restraining order that calls for fining the union $1 million for
the first day of a strike, $2 million for the second day and
doubling again each successive day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, under the judge's order, individual union members,
whose salaries average $39,000 a year, could face fines of $25,000
on the first day of a strike, with the fine doubling on each
successive day.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said, ``We sought an amount of money that would
immediately make it financially impossible for anyone to engage in
this activity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
