</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Dec. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, over a foot of new snow fell in many of the higher
elevations of Washington state as a chilly flow of air directed
abundant moisture inland from the northern Pacific. The damp
conditions will continue across the Northwest Wednesday, though
snow levels will rise to higher altitudes as a warm front sweeps
east across the region. This will cause snow to eventually change
to rain around pass levels.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered snow showers will surround low pressure tracking
slowly through the western Great Lakes Wednesday where several
inches of snow could accumulate in Wisconsin and northern Michigan.
Farther west, a few light rain showers will develop from eastern
Michigan into the southern Appalachians ahead of an advancing cold
front. Later Wednesday night and Thursday, progressively colder air
will circulate over the relatively tepid Great Lakes, setting the
stage for heavier snow showers downwind of the lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Residual moisture in the lower portions of the atmosphere will
bring clouds and spotty showers to portions of New England. Farther
south, clouds will break, yielding intervals of clouds and sun near
the Middle Atlantic Coast. Meanwhile, Florida will stay seasonably
warm amid sunshine and patchy cumulus clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Subsiding currents of air associated with high pressure over the
Southwest will promote ample sunshine from southern California to
Texas. Gusty breezes from the east will impact southern California
and Arizona Wednesday. The offshore winds will bring very mild
conditions to much of the southern California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Absence of Chill
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since there has been a wintry day in
Milwaukee. Every day since March 11, the temperature has risen
above freezing at the lakeside city. The string of 279 days is just
four days shy of the longest period on record during which
temperatures have risen above 32 degrees. The absence of chill in
Milwaukee is part of a persistent pattern that has swept air masses
across the nation that had their origins over the mild waters of
the Pacific. It is unlikely that the record will be broken,
however, since a surge of chill from Canada will reach the upper
Middle West Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
