<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-HEALTH-2NDTAKE     12-14 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-HEALTH-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHARLESTON, S.C.: the courts.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference later, McCain said he would like to see
independent state panels set up to review cases where consumers are
denied care by a health maintenance organization. His aides said
that under his proposal the 48 million Americans in the managed
care plans that fall under federal regulation would be given a
somewhat broader right to sue than they currently have, if they
were unsatisfied with the review. Currently those in such federally
regulated managed care plans are allowed to sue but only for the
cost of denied medical care.
</P>
<P>
   They would be bared from receiving punitive damages. But they
would be allowed to seek unlimited damages for economic suffering
like lost wages. Dan Schnur, the senator's communications director
said McCain would also propose legislation to put a $250,000 cap on
noneconomic damages, such as awards for pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate debated managed care regulation earlier this
year, McCain voted for the Republican bill, which did not include
an expanded right to sue. His aides said he had supported the
legislation because he did not want to see the issue die in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   To extend health insurance coverage to more of the nation's 44
million uninsured, McCain like many Republicans called for an
expansion of medical savings accounts, tax-free accounts that can
be used to cover medical costs, and for a more general tax
reduction to give people more money to buy insurance. He also
called for a more aggressive effort to encourage small businesses
to band together in insurance purchasing pools, as well as a
greater effort to enroll children in a federal program that was
established two years ago for children in families not poor enough
for Medicaid but not affluent enough to buy private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech made him the first Republican to set out a
detailed health care plan. Bush so far has spoken only generally of
extending coverage to more of the uninsured and pointed to the
program in Texas for regulating HMO's.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been more hotly debated in the Democratic
presidential contest because of Bradley's call for a vast system of
subsidies and tax credits that would cost $65 billion a year. Gore
has aggressively picked apart the plan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On another front, McCain on Tuesday defended the military's
``don't ask don't tell policy'' toward gay members of the service,
saying ``this policy has worked.'' He criticized Gore for calling
on Monday for the outright elimination of the program, saying the
vice president should not take a position on the issue without
first consulting with high-ranking Pentagon officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
