<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 12/14/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- Y2K-COX -- The White
House Y2K czar, John Koskinen, told the National Press Club that
because major industries ``are basically done with their Y2K work
... we do not expect to see major national failures'' in key
sectors, such as power generation, telecommunications or
transportation. He went on though, to urge Americans to prepare for
a few days of potential disruptions in business routines. (Rick
McKay/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) -- Undated -- PARTY-STEMWARE-COX -- Time to shatter
another myth: To set a festive dinner table, matching china,
matching glassware and matching napkins are musts. Sometimes,
inexpensive colored glass says ``festive'' as much as anything.
From left, stemware in blue, $3.95, Crate &AMP; Barrel; pink, $6, and
gold, $7, Pier 1 Imports; and ruby red, $9.95, Crate &AMP; Barrel.
(William Berry/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- PORTZAMPARE-ARCHITECTURE-2
-- The nearly competed LVMH Building, also known as the Vuitton
Tower, center, designed by French architect Christian de
Portzampare in Midtown Manhattan. Many critics are calling his
building one of the most successful to rise in the last generation.
``You are making a book on a bookshelf of this city,'' said de
Portzamparc. ``You want your book to be visible and at the same
time belong to the city.'' (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SANTA ROSA, Calif. -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- PEANUTS-RETIRE --
Charles Schulz, creator of the ``Peanuts'' comic strip, at his
studio/ice arena complex in March. Schulz, 77, who has written,
drawn, colored and lettered every one of his comic strips,
announced Tuesday that his last new daily installment will appear
Jan. 3 and his last new Sunday strip will be published Feb. 13.
Schulz was diagnosed with colon cancer last month. ``Although I
feel better following my recent surgery, I want to focus on my
health and my family without the worry of a daily deadline,'' he
said in a statement. (John Burgess/The Santa Rosa Press Democrat)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1999 - BRADLEY-WHITMAN -- Former
U.S. Senator Bill Bradley talks about campaign finance reform on
Tuesday. Nearly losing re-election to the Senate in 1990 against
now Gov. Christine Whitman of New Jersey shook his confidence in
himself and his staff, triggering an intense bout of introspection
that helped change the course of his career, Bradley and his
friends say. (Jack Manning/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) MIRAFLORES DOCKS, Panama -- Dec. 14, 1999 --
PANAMA-CANAL-2 - Dignitaries attending ceremonies marking the
transfer of the Panama Canal from the U.S. wave on Tuesday. From
left are: King Juan Carlos of Spain, Panamanian President Mireya
Moscoso, Former President Jimmy Carter and Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo. Eighty six years of American power and presence
along the shores of the Panama Canal symbolically ended today when
Carter exchanged the notes with Moscoso and said simply, ``It's
yours.'' (Levette Bagwell/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MIRAFLORES DOCKS, Panama -- Dec. 14, 1999 --
PANAMA-CANAL-1 -- Former President Jimmy Carter exchanges
diplomatic notes with Panamanian President Mireya Moscoso on
Tuesday. Eighty six years of American power and presence along the
shores of the Panama Canal symbolically ended today when Carter
exchanged the notes with Moscoso and said simply, ``It's yours.''
(Levette Bagwell/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- PORTZAMPARC-ARCHETECTURE --
The French architect Christian de Portzamparc in his new LVMH Tower
on 57th Street in Manhattan. Many critics are calling his building
one of the most successful to rise in Manhattan in the last
generation. ``You are making a book on a bookshelf of this city,''
said de Portzamparc. ``You want your book to be visible and at the
same time belong to the city.'' (Jeffery A. Salter/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- HAITI-PULLOUT-4-BOS -- A
servant pours expresso coffee for former Haitian President
Jean-Bertrand Aristide in his office earlier this month. Aristide
decided after leaving office to to cloister himself from most of
his country, according to several US officials. ``Haiti is floating
off our radar screen,'' a senior US official in Washington said on
condition of anonymity. ``Aristide's friends in Washington are
dwindling. It's not that Aristide has become the devil, but that he
hasn't become more of a leader.'' (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- HAITI-PULLOUT-3-BOS -- When
Jean-Bertrand Aristide was restored to the presidency in 1994, he
had water spickets installed in this downtown prison so men could
get their own water in plastic jugs. Some 3,000 prisoners in Haiti
are being held without trial. (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- HAITI-PULLOUT-2-BOS -- A group
of Colombian men in a room at a prison in the Haitian capital where
they are awaiting trial on drug trafficking charges. About 80
percent of those in Haiti's jails are still awaiting trial. (Janet
Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- HAITI-PULLOUT-1-BOS --
Jean-Bertrand Aristide in his office earlier this month. Aristide,
46, is expected to run for president again next year, and to win
easily. But his silence on public matters over the past 18 months
has contributed to a growing uncertainty about him, and about
Haiti's future. (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- OLY-SAMARANCH -- Juan
Antonio Samaranch, president of the International Olympic
Committee, during an interview on Tuesday. Samaranch is to testify
before a Congressional panel on Wednesday investigating
improprieties by his committee. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PHILADELPHIA -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- WEB-JOURNALISM --
Deirdre Shaw, 27, has quit the age-old newspaper business for an
exciting new career in internet journalism. ``In the new economy,
if you're smart and confident, you don't have to wait in line. You
can be whatever you want to be. There are no ladders and no
pigeonholes.'' (Jeffery A. Salter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- WORKERS-LANGUAGES -- As
more immigrants pour into the United States, more workplaces are
resounding with the sound of foreign tongues. Walter Suarez, 28,
left, translates the questions from a reporter for Nelson Diaz, 37.
Both are construction workers in Manhattan. Keeping the lines of
communication open among linguistic groups is important in any work
setting. But nowhere is it more critical than in the construction
trade. (Ozier Muhammed/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MOSCOW -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- RUSSIA-ELECT -- Protesters
rally in support of Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov,, whose portrait is
held at center, near the Kremlin on Tuesday. Luzhkov, trying to
bolster support for his opposition movement in Russia's
parliamentary election on Sunday, and for a possible run for the
presidency next year, roared defiance at Kremlin leaders today and
urged voters to reject candidates linked to them. (James Hill/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- KITCHEN-WARES -- Few
nutcrackers are very efficient, some examples, top row, from left:
Biesse, with rubber layers; Rocket, with a beer-tap handle. Bottom
row, from left: Schmidt &AMP; Brendle's rigid cone; Oxo, with zinc
handles; Mono stainless-steel disk; classic Quackenbush. (Tony
Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- NY-TRANSIT-2 -- Police
officers on the platform at the subway station under Grand Central
Terminal on Monday. Some officers said they were deployed in
preparation for a possible strike. As union and transit officials
negotiated feverishly in the hope of averting a shutdown of New
York City's buses and subways, the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority and the administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani obtained
injunctions that would impose draconian fines on the union if it
strikes after midnight tonight. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HAMAT GADER, Golan Heights -- Dec. 14, 1999 -
MIDEAST-HEIGHTS-2 -- Israelis enjoy the hot springs of Hamat Gader
in the Golan Heights. The resumption of talks with Syria on an
Israeli withdrawal from the strategic Golan in exchange for peace,
which are to begin in Washington on Wednesday, has confronted the
settlers with a real prospect of losing homes, orchards and
businesses in which they have invested decades of their lives.
Hamat Gader is part of the region which could be returned to Syria
in a deal. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- PUNCH -- Cranberry orange
tea punch made by Upper Crust caterers in Manhattan. Over the last
two years, caterers around New York City say they have been seeing
something of a punch revivah. The new punch concoctions are less
formulaic because they tend to use ingredients from all over the
world. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MEVO HAMA, Golan Heights -- Dec. 14, 1999 -
MIDEAST-HEIGHTS -- Yonatan Green stands what was once a Syrian
bunker and is now the front porch of his home in Kibutz Mevo Hama,
overlooking the Lake of Tiberias. The resumption of talks with
Syria on an Israeli withdrawal from the strategic Golan in exchange
for peace, which are to begin in Washington on Wednesday, has
confronted the settlers with a real prospect of losing homes,
orchards and businesses in which they have invested decades of
their lives. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- NY-TRANSIT -- Passengers
talk to a subway conductor at a station on Monday. As union and
transit officials negotiated feverishly in the hope of averting a
shutdown of New York City's buses and subways, the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority and the administration of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani obtained injunctions that would impose draconian fines on
the union if it strikes after midnight tonight. (Richard Perry/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GNJILANE, Yugoslavia -- Dec. 14, 1999 - ADV. FOR SUN.,
DEC. 19 --KOSOVO-RETURNEE-COX -- Skender Rahimi, center, with his
mother Bahtie. Looking on are, from right, wife Vahide and daughter
Mertita. At left is Rahimi's father Ramadam. Skender Rahimi and
some of his family members fled Kosovo to a refugee camp in
Macedonia which eventually put him on a flight to Atlanta. But
Rahimi had to return to his village in southern Kosovo for love of
his parents. (Seamus Conlan/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- ISRAEL-EXTREMISTS-COX --
The crowded streets of Jerusalem's Old City will see added police
protection and video cameras as Israeli authorities try to increase
security for the millennium. Nervous about policing an event
unprecedented in the modern age, Israeli authorities are scrambling
to prevent violence in the millennial ground zero -- the land where
Christianity started 2000 years ago. Experts have predicted
everything from a gathering of only harmless, if eccentric,
believers, to violent acts that could start regional wars. (Larry
Kaplow/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 14, 1999 - WALL-STREET-FLOATER --
Illuminated Christmas decorations on Wall Street Monday night. Even
by the inflated standards of high finance, Wall Street is
overflowing with holiday cheer this year. Investment banks have set
aside $13 billion to pay bonuses, 20 percent more than last year,
with pay packages above $10 million no longer a rarity. (James
Estrin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Dec. 14, 1999 -- KRUGMAN-COLUMN-MUG -- The New
York Times' new Op-Ed columnist, Paul Krugman. Krugman is an
economics professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
and an author known for his theories on international trade and
economics. (Diane Barros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
