<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9082 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PANAMA-CANAL-1215-COX     12-14 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-1215-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PERCEIVED U.S. SNUB ASIDE, PANAMA COMMEMORATES TRANSFER OF CANAL
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ Water cannons fired into the air, tugboats
blasted their whistles and a choir sang the ``Hallelujah Chorus''
Tuesday as Panama moved closer to taking full ownership of the
famous canal that bears its name.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter represented the United States at a
ceremony overlooking the 50-mile-long waterway, signing documents
with Panamanian President Mireya Moscoso as Spain's King Juan
Carlos and the presidents of a half-dozen Latin American countries
looked on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is indeed a historic occasion, perhaps the most
significant that has occurred in this hemisphere,'' Carter said.
the canal ``Was a source of great pride in my country from the time
I was a child until I became president.''
</P>
<P>
   The final, legal hand-over mandated by treaties negotiated by
Carter in 1977 won't come until noon on Dec. 31. Panamanian
officials pushed up the ceremony to avoid conflicts with millennium
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last we have reached victory, the canal is ours,'' said
Moscoso, noting the event was a profound moment in her young
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour ceremony marked an important milestone in the
96-year relationship between the United States and Panama _ and
reflected some of the tensions that have beset that relationship.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
declined to attend, leaving many Panamanians miffed at what they
see as a snub of their debut on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Clinton announced he wasn't coming, it was like, 'OK, he
has a domestic political problem,''' said Roberto Eisenmann,
founder of La Prensa, one of Panama's largest newspapers. ``But
when Albright announced she wasn't coming, it was a real slap in
the face. It showed a lack of interest in the whole region.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Clinton said the U.S. remains committed to the
canal's security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's ceremony underscores our confidence in the government
of Panama and the Panamanian people's ability to manage this vital
artery of commerce,'' Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. retains the right to intervene if there is a threat to
the canal's safety. But a dozen U.S. military bases within the
10-mile-wide canal zone have been closed and turned over to Panama,
leaving the country of 2.8 million responsible for day-to-day
security.
</P>
<P>
   American critics of the canal transfer fear that the Panamanians
will let the 86-year-old waterway fall victim to poor maintenance,
corrupt politics, terrorism or influence by foreign governments.
They are particularly upset by a contract giving management of two
ports at either end of the canal to a company they believe has ties
to the Chinese military _ a charge downplayed by current U.S.
military officials, and denied by the Hong Kong-based companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is action by the leadership of Panama and the
U.S. to restore a U.S. military presence here, there's a great
danger this magnificent canal could be threatened within a short
time,'' said Howard Phillips, head of the Conservative Caucus, who
lobbied against the hand-over in the 1970s. ``It will do us damn
little good to send in the Marines after the fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The turnover is a bookend to what many historians have called
``the American Century.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. construction of the canal between 1904 and 1914 marked
America's emergence as a world power, signaling the country's
engineering prowess and financial might while providing a crucial
economic and military link.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also a powerful symbol of U.S. domination of the
hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Slicing through a 500-foot-tall mountain range, the canal also
sliced across a nation that was never comfortable with the
overwhelming presence of its more powerful neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Panama was a part of Colombia until 1903, when a group of
residents declared independence _ under the watchful eye of U.S.
Marines who steamed into a Panamanian port as the revolt unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   The new Panamanian government quickly signed a treaty allowing
the U.S. to finish building the canal _ and also to run it and the
canal zone, which effectively became a strip of U.S. soil within
the midst of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, thousands of Americans lived and worked in the
360,240-acre zone, enjoying subsidized housing and high pay in
exchange for hard work far from home. Panamanian workers were paid
less and subjected to U.S. laws within the zone.
</P>
<P>
   But they also enjoyed higher paying jobs than they would have
found in Panama's native industries.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting emotions many Panamanians feel about the canal,
the turn-over and the United States are still readily evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the Americans in all forms,'' said Fulgencio Bonilla,
53, a Panama City resident. ``We need their experience in running
the canal, and we need their military to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, worrisome clashes have flared along the border
between Panama and Colombia. Just last weekend, the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, attacked a Colombian outpost on
the border, while other unidentified armed bandits _ possibly drug
traffickers _ have crossed into Panama and attacked rural villages.
</P>
<P>
   Panama's army was disbanded in 1989 after the United States
invaded to depose strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega. He was
whisked to Miami, tried and imprisoned for aiding Colombian drug
traffickers. The country now relies on an 18,000-person police
force.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls show 60 to 70 percent of Panamanians wish the
United States would retain a military presence here.
</P>
<P>
   The canal is considered one of the engineering marvels of the
modern age. It carries roughly four percent of the world's
shipping, and earns nearly $600 million in tolls per year. About 12
percent of U.S. shipping passes through the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Carter acknowledged that the hand-over was
unpopular in the United States, but has said repeatedly that it was
``the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who headed a 29-member U.S. delegation that also
included Army Secretary Louis Caldera and Ambassador Simon Ferro,
criticized the doubters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my country and in this one there were demagogues who
exaggerated problems and spoke about catastrophic events,'' he
said. ``There are still some in my country spreading false stories
about security of the canal.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Carter told the crowd, ``We're celebrating a new
relationship between your country and mine. Today we come together
in a spirit of mutual respect acknowledging without question the
complete sovereignty of Panama. It's a very important moment for
all of Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
