<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1215-CO     12-14 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1215-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAEL-SYRIA TALKS TO OPEN WITH MIDDLE EAST PEACE AT STAKE
 &HT;    (650&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Still hoping to broker lasting peace in the Middle
East before leaving office, President Clinton aims to jump-start
long-stalled Israeli-Syrian negotiations on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will host Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa for morning talks at the White
House, followed by planned face-to-face talks after lunch between
the Israeli and the Syrian officials at the historic Blair House.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand will be Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who
has worked for months trying to nurse the tenuous Mideast peace
process back to something resembling good health.
</P>
<P>
   That process _ key to U.S. political and strategic interests in
the oil-rich Middle East _ has been a central goal of U.S.
diplomacy for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching an Israel-Syria accord _ centered on Israeli withdrawal
from the occupied Golan Heights in return for security guarantees
from Syria _ is seen as one key to an overall peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's vital, because Syria has a large army, Syria controls
Lebanon and it has to do with Israel's entire northern border.,''
said Jon Alterman, Mideast analyst with the U.S. Institute for
Peace, a quasi-governmental think tank. ``It's a question of
whether Israel is surrounded with neighbors with which it is at
peace, or has enemies on its northern border.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high stakes, or perhaps because of them, the
Israel-Syria track has been stalled since talks collapsed nearly
four years ago. At issue are complicated territorial and security
concerns that have divided the two neighbors since Israel's
inception in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   After months of intensive U.S. diplomacy, Barak and Syrian
President Hafez Assad agreed last week to resume negotiations under
White House auspices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a pivotal moment in the Middle East peace process,
one that can shape the face of the region for generations to
come,'' Clinton said in announcing the talks last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace has long been within our sight,'' he said. ``Today, it
is within our grasp, and we must seize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad, who is 69 and in failing health, is sending al-Sharaa to
represent Syria. Both he and Barak were scheduled to arrive in
Washington overnight.
</P>
<P>
   No agreement is expected this week. Instead, Sharaa and Barak
are slated to focus on process matters and a road map for another
round of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly no expectation that they can reach a broad,
wide-ranging agreement on issues that are quite difficult and
long-standing,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters.
``But I think what they will hope to do over the next two days is
work hard to find a process that allows them, over a period of
time, to reach a peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, the two officials will return to their
respective capitals after two days of talks here and schedule a
next-step summit in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't predict how long this will take,'' a senior
administration official told reporters at a White House news
conference. He spoke to more than 60 reporters on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we feel there's momentum and we are going to want
to be building on the momentum,'' the official said. ``But I think
the first two days will be much more geared towards organization
and the process than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the Israeli-Syrian dispute is the occupied Golan
Heights, a large and strategically valuable piece of high ground
where Israel's northern border abuts against southwestern Syria.
</P>
<P>
   After Syria joined Jordan and Egypt in attacking Israel in 1967,
Israel countered with a fierce return blow, seizing the Golan
territory _ a strategic prize for armies dating to antiquity.
</P>
<P>
   Control of the Golan has given Israeli troops a commanding
foothold in Syria. It has also provided a valuable listening post
for eavesdropping into Syrian military conversations and for
monitoring the activities of groups such as Hezbollah, regarded as
a terrorist outfit by Israel and its ally, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Golan also contains the Sea of Galilee _ the single largest
source of fresh water in the desert region.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Israel's continuing occupation of the Golan, though, has come at
a price.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, for one thing, remains in a state of undeclared war
against Syria and its army of 400,000 forces.
</P>
<P>
   A deal on the Golan would come with security guarantees for
Israel _ including dramatic reductions in the number of Syrian
forces arrayed near the Israeli borders _ as well as valuable
trade, investment and diplomatic ties with a land bridge linking
Israel to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practical terms, Israelis will be able to drive to Europe,
they will be able to trade with Syrians and Syrians will be able to
trade with Israelis,'' if an accord is reached and relations are
normalized, said Alterman. ``Syria will open up to Israel and
Israel will open up to Syria. Exactly how that works is something
to be negotiated.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel and Syria have been at loggerheads over the issue since
1967. Following that year's Six-Day War, the United Nations called
for the so-called ``land for peace'' formula at the heart of this
week's talks. That appeal, enshrined in U.N. Security Council
Resolution 242, still lies near the epicenter of the complex quest
for Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
   A second component is Israeli-Lebanon relations. Israel
continues to occupy Lebanese territory it seized in 1982 as part of
an offensive against Palestine Liberation Organization operations
in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, which has based troops in Lebanon since 1976, is
effectively in the driver's seat on the Lebanon-Israeli
land-for-peace front. A deal between those two countries would
likely fall into place, Mideast experts agree, once Israel and
Syria reach an accord.
</P>
<P>
   The third and most troublesome part of the equation is the
remaining gap between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat have set a
mid-February deadline for reaching a framework for so-called final
status talks, aimed at addressing the most contentious outstanding
issues between them, including the future of Jerusalem and the
question of Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the two men have committed to winding up final
status talks by next October _ conveniently in time for Clinton to
claim a foreign policy victory on the eve of November's
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The stakes for Americans, however, stretch far beyond politics
and presidential legacies.
</P>
<P>
   Israel remains the staunchest U.S. ally in the fractious Middle
East, supplier of a substantial amount of the crude oil that fuels
the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, nestled between Israel and another U.S. ally, NATO member
Turkey, has the potential to be a bridge or a chasm between
southeastern Europe and the volatile Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   And Israeli security concerns still darkly complicate U.S.
relations with the Arab world, something American diplomacy has
sought for decades to move beyond.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S.-brokered accord that would end half a century of enmity
and bloodshed in the fractious Middle East would bode well not just
for the region.
</P>
<P>
   If there are benefits to the United States, there will most
assuredly be costs as well. Israeli press reports have suggested in
recent days that Barak will ask Clinton for a commitment for what
could amount to more than $10 billion over time to help finance
</P>
<P>
   operations associated with Israel's withdrawal _ if one is
agreed upon _ from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart neither accepted nor rejected those figures on Tuesday,
but he made clear that the White House was prepared to entertain
some sort of assistance request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always stood ready to help our friend, Israel,'' said
Lockhart. ``As we move forward, those questions, I'm certain, will
be discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
