<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-SPEECH-NYT &LR;      12-14 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY ATTACKS GORE AS CARING MORE ABOUT `PRESERVING POWER' THAN
REFORM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a prelude to his cross-party appearance Thursday
with Sen. John McCain to promote campaign finance reform, Bill
Bradley spoke out Tuesday against the influence of money in
politics and attacked Vice President Al Gore for appearing to care
more about ``preserving power'' than reducing the flow of campaign
donations to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seven years in power, Al Gore has not come close to
enacting campaign finance reform,'' Bradley said at Fordham
University on Manhattan's West Side. ``I have profound differences
with Al Gore. He is wedded to the ways of Washington. Not once has
he called out for changes in the campaign finance system. It shows
he doesn't care about reform as much as preserving power.''
</P>
<P>
   At best, Bradley said, Gore, his opponent for the Democratic
presidential nomination, paid ``lip service'' to campaign finance
reform. ``When I called for the elimination of soft money,''
Bradley said, ``Al Gore's campaign attacked me rather than call for
reform. This is an issue they are afraid to touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Bradley is to appear with McCain, who is seeking the
Republican presidential nomination, at a New Hampshire forum where
they plan to present a bipartisan appeal for campaign finance
reform. Both have called for a ban on soft money, or unrestricted
large donations to political parties from wealthy individuals,
corporations and unions, and both have made the issue of money in
politics a central theme in their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to reporters after his speech, Bradley said he agreed
to appear with McCain because ``it shows that this is a different
kind of a campaign and because it is an important symbol that it
will take both parties to make campaign finance reform happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing Bradley running nearly even with Gore among
New York Democrats three months before the primary, Bradley is
striking a theme that has shadowed Gore since 1996. In a 1997
congressional investigation of fund-raising activities in the last
election, Gore came under fire for attending a Democratic
fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple, for making fund-raising telephone
calls from his White House office and for aggressively pursuing
large soft-money campaign contributions for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore called Bradley a latecomer to the campaign finance
issue, saying that he had taken it up only as he was about to leave
the Senate in 1996, while Gore had sponsored legislation in
Congress as early as 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Bradley sat in the Senate over 17 years without
authoring his own campaign finance reform legislation,'' said Chris
Lehane, Gore's press secretary, ``Al Gore has a real record of
action on campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For his speech, Bradley was flanked by several New York
Democratic politicians, including Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
Rep. Jerrold Nadler, whose district includes the West Side, and
City Councilwoman Ronnie Eldridge. The Rev. Joseph A. O'Hare,
president of Fordham and chairman of the New York Campaign Finance
Board, a quasi-independent body that overseas New York's public
campaign finance system, also appeared.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to proposing a soft-money ban, Bradley has proposed
providing federal candidates with free television time and greater
public funding. Such changes, he said, are necessary because
Congress is unable to ``deliver on the hopes and the dreams'' of
ordinary Americans and because money ``drowns out the voice of
ordinary citizens'' in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money sets the agenda in politics; money makes a mockery of
our representative system,'' Bradley said. ``If you reduce money in
politics, the people's agenda has a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The last Congress, Bradley said, failed to enact a patients'
bill of rights because of opposition from insurance companies and
health maintenance organizations, failed to enact measures to curb
gun violence because of opposition from the National Rifle
Association and failed to increase the minimum wage because of
corporate opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Students listening to the speech said they found Bradley's
message appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't decided who I will support, but I like that he
didn't shy away from the big issues, like gun control and attacking
big money,'' said Sara Dawida, a Fordham sophomore. Justin Brennan,
a junior, said that ``definitely campaign finance reform is the
issue people came to hear,'' while Olivia Vaughn, a senior, said
she liked Bradley's ``stand on global issues, and I especially
agree with his emphasis on campaign finance reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
