<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9092 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-GRIFFEY-950(2TAKE     12-14 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GRIFFEY-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY BLOCKED TRADE TO METS BECAUSE OF ANNOYANCE WITH MARINERS'
TACTICS
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Late Monday night, Ken Griffey Jr., the
Seattle Mariners star who is generally considered the best player
in baseball, used his veto rights to quash a possible trade to the
Mets. But the talented center fielder might have been trying on a
New York Mets uniform for size Tuesday if they had begun their
aggressive pursuit of him earlier.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility arose Tuesday with the confirmation by
Griffey's agent, Brian Goldberg, that the Mets were one of the
teams on Griffey's original list of four teams to which he would
accept a trade. But even before the teams negotiated their
contingency deal, Griffey, annoyed at the Mariners' negotiating
tactics, had reduced the list to one team, and it wasn't the Mets.
It was the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the 30-year-old Griffey invoked his status as a
10-year veteran (the last five with the same team) and blocked a
trade, providing a striking example of how players increasingly use
their rights to determine where they play, and for whom. And the
Mets were left contemplating what might have been if they had added
a 10-time all-star who has averaged 52 home runs the last four
years and is a sensational fielder as well.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey drew up the list late in October after meeting with
Mariners officials and telling them he did not plan to remain with
the team after the 2000 season. Since Griffey can be a free agent
after next season and the Mariners faced the prospect of losing him
and receiving nothing in return, they proceeded to initiate talks
in an effort to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Then came word from Chuck Armstrong, the Mariners' president,
about a conversation he said he had with Fred Wilpon, the Mets'
co-owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks into the process,'' Goldberg said by telephone from
his home in Cincinnati, ``Chuck Armstrong told me the Mets were
very lukewarm toward Kenny but that Wilpon had called him and
specifically asked him about Alex Rodriguez's availability.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is the Mariners' shortstop who also can be a free
agent after next season. He has told the club he doesn't want to be
traded but wants to finish out his contract in Seattle. The
Mariners have not tried to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone efforts to reach Wilpon for comment on his
conversation with Armstrong were unsuccessful, but Goldberg's
characterization of it fits what had been the Mets' internal
thinking earlier in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   In more recent weeks, though, their stance on Griffey changed,
heating up to the extent that general manager Steve Phillips seemed
all consumed at baseball's winter meetings in his attempt to
acquire the player whose 398 home runs place him more than halfway
to Hank Aaron's all-time total. Phillips was intent on pulling off
the coup of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was wired all day,'' an acquaintance said of the general
manager's demeanor Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Even after he confirmed that Griffey had rejected the trade,
Phillips could not hide his feelings about almost having pulled it
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean if we got Ken Griffey Jr. your papers wouldn't stop
the presses?'' Phillips, his voice rising an octave or two, asked a
group of New York reporters just before 2 a.m. New York time
Tuesday, an hour when newspaper presses were running down.
</P>
<P>
   But Phillips was too late. Griffey had changed his mind about
the Mets a couple of weeks earlier. It was his change of mind, in
fact, that prompted Goldberg to relate the Armstrong-Wilpon
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might look like two weeks ago that Kenny changed his
mind,'' the agent said. ``It's also a situation that a team can
change its mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips and his aides met with the Mariners at the general
managers meetings in Dana Point, 30 miles south of here, the second
week of November. But, a participant in the meetings said, the
Mariners did not say whom they wanted for Griffey and the Mets
neither asked for names nor made an offer. But the Mets' strategy
was far more aggressive the past four days.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips pursued Griffey relentlessly despite word from the
superstar's agent that he would accept a deal only to Cincinnati,
the city where he grew up and where his father is employed as a
Reds coach and presumptive manager-in-waiting. Shrugging off the
report, Phillips plowed forward and at least came close to an
agreement Monday with Pat Gillick, the hamstrung Mariners general
manager, on a contingency trade.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether or not an actual trade had been agreed
to. Phillips and Gillick both have declined to say. One person who
had participated in meetings between the teams said that four basic
names were on the table. When Armstrong called Goldberg to seek
Griffey's approval, the club president said the Mariners would get
three of them. The four were Armando Benitez, Roger Cedeno, Octavio
Dotel and Dennis Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call about 11 Eastern last night from Chuck Armstrong,
who's in Hawaii,'' Goldberg said, ``and he asked if Junior would
consider a trade to the Mets. He said they needed to know
immediately. There was no time to think on it. I talked to Junior
and he politely declined.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is, in baseball parlance, a 10-and-5 man. That means he
has played in the major leagues for at least 10 years and the last
five with the same team. That status, in turn, means he cannot be
traded without his permission. It does not give him the right to
ask to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who can be a free agent after next season, when his
contract ends, nevertheless gave the Mariners a list of four clubs
to which they could trade him _ the Mets, the Reds, Atlanta and
Houston. But the Mariners strayed far beyond those teams, and their
disregard for the list led to the change of mind that turned out to
be devastating for the Mets.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Despite the list, Goldberg said, the Mariners asked him if
Griffey would approve trades to the New York Yankees, Cleveland,
St. Louis, Tampa Bay and Pittsburgh. The Mariners did not
necessarily have deals completed with those teams, but Gillick was
trying hard to expand his options. Griffey wound up contracting
his.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed his mind 2 1-2 weeks ago,'' the lawyer said. ``The
reason was that he was being asked to go to teams that were not on
the list. He didn't like all the misleading with teams not on his
list. He was very uncomfortable with that. It was never that he had
a deal. It was `we got something we like, something we'd probably
accept.' After a month of that, he just thought it was better to
shut it down. He told the Mariners and I told the Mariners he would
accept a trade to Cincinnati. Other than that he was coming back
for the last year in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's decision not to play for the Mets was not directed at
them, Goldberg stressed. ``It has nothing to do with the team or
the town or anything like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Gillick kept talking to teams not on the list, he explained
that Griffey could change his mind. Just last Sunday, as the
temperature of his talks with the Mets was rising, he said,
``Kenny's a great guy, but basically his mind changes from day to
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Griffey told a baseball executive this week that
Griffey was very upset with the Mariners for comments like that and
for their continuing efforts to trade him places he wouldn't go.
His attitude, the executive quoted the friends as saying, was that
he would play out his contract in Seattle, leave as a free agent
next November and let the Mariners be stuck with two draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   After the Reds terminated talks with the Mariners last Saturday,
the Mets became the team most likely to conclude a deal. They did,
but it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, following his usual practice, refused to acknowledge
that a trade had been completed contingent on Griffey's approval.
``I'm not going to confirm a deal was in place,'' he said before
talking about stopping the presses, ``but I will confirm that he
has said he would not want to come to the Mets in a trade. Seattle
let us know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Phillips feel he had wasted his time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like it was a waste of time,'' he said. ``I think
it was a worthy effort to pursue, an exciting one to pursue. I'm
always willing to leave that door ajar to be revisited. The way it
stands today it's unlikely something will happen, but things
change. We still have some areas we can have some discussion with
Seattle to make it convenient if something were to change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
