<HEADLINE>
SOX DID VERY LITTLE CHRISTMAS SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, who
often is among the last to arrive and first to leave at baseball
gatherings, remained behind here Tuesday when the winter meetings
came to a close and most club executives scattered.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was taking an extra day not because he had the
expectation of closing a deal for a starting pitcher, a lefthanded
reliever, or a power-hitting outfielder. He had other matters to
tend to, though he expressed confidence that by the end of the
week, the Sox will have pitching help and perhaps a productive
hitter (Carl Everett).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a couple of things we're working on that may come
together by the end of the week,'' said Duquette, who in the five
days of meetings here made one minor trade, swapping outfielder
Damon Buford to the Cubs for utility infielder Manny Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said talks with the Astros about Everett are
continuing, even as Houston GM Gerry Hunsicker and his staff left
Tuesday. It appears that if the Sox make the deal they've discussed
with Houston _ trading shortstop prospect Adam Everett and Single A
lefthander Greg Miller _ Duquette will have to do so without first
striking a deal for a contract extension with Everett, who is
eligible to become a free agent after next season.
</P>
<P>
   As things stood, the Astros were not likely to give Duquette
permission to negotiate with Everett, but as the Sox GM noted,
similar circumstances did not prevent him from trading for Pedro
Martinez two years ago, when Martinez could have walked as a free
agent after one season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to balance the talent you have to give up in such a
trade against the risk that the player you're trading for will play
for you just one year,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette indicated that Everett wasn't the only option he was
pursuing to strengthen the outfield, noting that he has also been
talking with the Anaheim Angels. But he conceded that the Angels
are not inclined to trade right fielder Tim Salmon, and while the
Sox also have some interest in Jim Edmonds and Garret Anderson, the
Angels were on the verge of dealing Edmonds to the Oakland A's for
a package of prospects. He also has talked with the Padres about an
outfielder, presumably Reggie Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, according to sources, still would like to deal
Everett to the Sox, alleviating the surplus of outfielders they
have while eliminating one in a host of salary concerns. But if the
Sox do not act soon, the Astros say they have at least one other
club that has expressed serious interest in the switch-hitting
center fielder, who last year hit .325 with 25 home runs and 108
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette all but conceded that when he acquires a starting
pitcher, it will not be of the high-end variety, like lefthander
Chuck Finley. Duquette did not make an offer for Finley here, and
essentially acknowledged that the other teams in the running _ the
Indians, Orioles, and Mariners _ would be willing to pay more.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he has interest in free agent righthander Steve
Trachsel, an 18-game loser for the Cubs last season who nonetheless
is seeking a big payday, and lefthander Jeff Fassero, whom he once
had in Montreal. He also acknowledged that the club has interest in
Graeme Lloyd, the Aussie lefthanded reliever, but there were other
pitchers the Sox are looking at while waiting for the market to
fall into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to get a starting pitcher before we do anything
else,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was unable to match up with the Padres for lefthander
Sterling Hitchcock but continues to talk with the Cardinals about
righthander Juan Acevedo.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette scoffed at the rumors that greeted him upon his arrival
here that the Sox might have interest in Mo Vaughn. The Angels
weren't shopping the former Boston slugger, whom they're expecting
to bounce back from last season's disastrous experience, which led
to the firing of GM Bill Bavasi and manager Terry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were not happy that Vaughn frequently had a couple of
his friends in the clubhouse, though the club admits it was at
fault for not barring the practice until late in the season.
Vaughn's decision to miss a game in Boston so he could attend the
funeral of a close friend's mother also provoked some resentment
among teammates. Typically, the understanding is that a player
misses a game only for the funeral of an immediate family member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
