<HEADLINE>
FIGHT EARNS APPROVAL, BUT RUIZ-GRANT REMAINS UP IN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Ruiz moved one step closer to Michael Grant Tuesday when an
unexpected fax arrived in the office of his attorney, Tony
Cardinale, from the World Boxing Council. But even with WBC
approval of a match between the No. 1-rated Ruiz and the No.
2-rated Grant, the Chelsea, Mass. heavyweight remains a million
dollar signs away from a March 18 fight on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   WBC president Jose Sulaiman's fax fell short of mandating the
fight but said the organization was in favor of it ``to get an
official challenger'' to face undisputed champion Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   But a day earlier, Ruiz's promoter, Don King, met for more than
an hour with HBO officials to discuss a possible June rematch
between Felix Trinidad and Oscar De La Hoya and never mentioned
Ruiz or Grant, who is an HBO fighter.
</P>
<P>
   HBO is willing to put up around $2.5 million to be split between
the fighters, and Grant is willing to discount his share to get a
shot at the No. 1 ranking because that position would insulate him
from the sport's politics when it comes time to negotiate with
Lewis next year.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, HBO would rather make a Lewis-Grant fight
immediately in part because it believes the World Boxing
Association, whose No. 1 contender is entitled to the next title
shot, would let its fighter step aside with an understanding that
Henry Akinwande would get the winner. But if Grant and Ruiz fight
first, the WBA would force an Akinwande-Lewis rematch that no one
wants to see or strip Lewis of the title and hand it over to Mike
Tyson and Showtime, HBO's cable rival.
</P>
<P>
   So Ruiz's fortunes are buffeted on the one hand by the network's
interests and on the other by his promoter's perceived reluctance
to risk the mandatory position in a fight that will gross him only
$500,000. Secondarily, Grant does not want King to promote the
fight, which could be a major stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   While the two camps seem genuinely interested in making the
fight and believe it can be done, mistrust is in the air. Grant
doesn't trust King, and neither does Ruiz. HBO doesn't believe King
will accept a reasonable fee because it doesn't believe he wants to
make the fight; members of both fighters' camps feel the same away
about HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we've put enough money out to make that fight,'' said
HBO senior vice president for programming Lou DiBella. ``Far too
much, frankly. We won't put up 50 cents more. It's up to them how
they divide it, but it's insane money for that fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Insane or not, Ruiz wants the same $1.5 million that
International Boxing Federation No. 1 contender David Tua declined
for a Grant fight, and Grant's people want the No. 1 ranking to
strengthen their position in any negotiations with Lewis's manager,
who is insisting on future options on Grant to make the title
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WBC has told us they will recognize it as an
elimination,'' said Jim Thomas, who handles Grant. ``Don and I are
supposed to talk later this week. Then we'll see if the naysayers
are right. If Don does what he said he'll do, we're not going to
have a lot of trouble agreeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone on our side is in accord that this is an important
step for Michael. If we need to stretch (on the purse), we would.
I'm a long-term thinker. If we win that fight, there's nothing
Lewis's people can do to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Providing, of course, John Ruiz doesn't do something to him
first.
</P>
</TEXT>
