<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETTAX-NETTAX </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Retailers Step Up Drive for Net Taxes  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Some brick-and-mortar merchants yesterday stepped up a multipronged
effort to make sure e-tailers charge their customers sales tax.
<P>
   At a news conference in San Francisco, merchants from Wal-Mart,
the world's largest retailer, to Cody's Books, a Berkeley
independent, called on policymakers to tax all online purchases,
just as they tax goods sold at physical stores.
</P>
<P>
   Those merchants have formed a lobbying group, the e-Fairness
coalition, to ``advocate a level playing field for the new
economy,'' said David Bullington, vice president for taxation at
Wal-Mart, which sells merchandise over the Web as well as in
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Several retailers, including Wal-Mart, will testify tomorrow in
the second day of hearings sponsored by the Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce, a panel that is charged with recommending an
e-commerce taxation policy to Congress next year.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a coalition of California booksellers has
asked the California State Board of Equalization to investigate Web
merchants like Barnesandnoble.com and Borders.com for alleged sales
tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   At issue for both the e-Fairness Coalition and booksellers is a
1992 Supreme Court decision, Quill vs. North Dakota, that requires
merchants to collect sales tax only in states where they have a
physical presence, or ``nexus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Quill decision applies to sales via catalogs and television
shopping channels as well as Web sites. An act of Congress would be
required to force businesses to collect taxes in states where they
do not have a nexus, said Sarah Whitaker, director of government
relations for the National Retail Federation in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern California Independent Booksellers Association
asserts that the Web operations of national booksellers should be
required to collect sales tax on merchandise sold in states where
they operate stores.
</P>
<P>
   The group has requested an investigation into the matter by the
California State Board of Equalization. Members of the state
Assembly are also studying the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But spokesmen for Borders and Barnes &AMP; Noble told The Chronicle
yesterday that their stores do not constitute a nexus for the Web
division because their Internet operations are separate from their
physical-store operations.
</P>
<P>
   Neither bookseller collects sales tax on Web purchases made in
California, even though they both operate stores here.
</P>
<P>
   Barnesandnoble.com is a publicly traded company that is 40
percent owned by Barnes &AMP; Noble. Both firms are based in New York.
Borders.com is wholly owned by Borders Group Inc. of Ann Arbor,
Mich., which also owns the Walden and Borders book chains.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Ross, president of Cody's Books, has sent extensive
evidence to the BOE that he believes shows Borders' and Barnes &AMP;
Noble's physical stores are acting as ``agents'' for their Web
sites. Agents can be considered a nexus that would trigger sales
tax payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just today, I sent (the BOE) photos of Barnes &AMP; Noble stores
and Borders stores with signs urging their customers to shop
online,'' said Ross in an interview yesterday. ``Both continue to
say physical stores are unrelated to their Net operations and this
is clearly not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross operates a Web site, which constitutes about 1 percent of
its sales, as well as two stores in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Horton, a business taxation specialist with the BOE, said
the board continually monitors merchants to make sure they are
collecting sales taxes if they have a nexus in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Horton declined to discuss specific companies but said, ``We're
seeing if we can establish a nexus for these Net companies to get
them to pay tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Using in-store signage and coupons to promote a Web site would
not ``in and of itself be strong enough to establish nexus, but
that in combination with other things could be useful in
establishing if they have nexus in a state,'' Horton said.
</P>
<P>
   Not every retailer likes the idea of more Net taxation, however.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Julian, a vice president with Federated Department Stores,
the parent company of Macy's and Bloomingdale's, maintains that
sales tax collection is ``very burdensome and expensive,'' he told
The Chronicle yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Tax policies among the 46 states that impose a sales tax vary
widely, said Julian. For example, nine states exempt clothing from
sales tax; five consider handkerchiefs clothing and four do not.
Eight of those states consider shoelaces clothing, but Texas does
not, said Julian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology does not exist today to enable a remote seller
to easily comply with those laws,'' said Julian, who will testify
at the hearing tomorrow at the Westin St. Francis Hotel. The
hearing is one of four the ACEC is conducting across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Wal-Mart's Bullington said his company's Web site collects
sales tax in every state. Wal-Mart employs four people full time to
calculate state and local taxes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said states should simplify their tax structures to make it
easier for e-tailers to collect sales tax. Small Web businesses
such as his should also be exempt from paying sales tax in states
where they don't have a nexus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
