<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON  
 GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON  &HT;     Choices Galore for Credit Cards 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: What is the best credit card deal for small-business use, such
as rental cars, hotels, lunches?
<P>
   &QL; 
A: The good news is you have more choices than ever. There are
about 100 credit cards specifically designed for businesses,
compared with only a dozen or so three or four years ago. You
should check out WebCard, which tracks the credit card industry
from Frederick, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some great deals,'' says WebCard CEO Robert
McKinley. To find out who offers what and for what price, go to
www.webcard.com, click ``CardSurveys'' in the left column and then
click ``Business.''
</P>
<P>
   You will find a list of more than 30 issuers, their annual fees,
interest rates and toll-free phone numbers. McKinley tops the list
with four cards that have no annual fee and charge a fixed 9.99
annual interest rate. They are: First USA Business Visa, American
Express Corp. Platinum Optima, American Express Gold Corp. Optima
and Bank One Business Card.
</P>
<P>
   You need to look at what you want from a business credit card.
McKinley, for example, likes rewards programs and has been very
happy with his American Express business card. He racked up more
than 100,000 points and used it to send 18 New England lobster
dinners for two as Christmas presents to employees. Each dinner for
two, which was sent by Federal Express from Martha's Vineyard,
would have cost $150 if purchased for cash.
</P>
<P>
   One of the advantages of rewards programs is that the company
can consolidate and benefit from the buying power of several
employees. Most of the card issuers also have partners in the
airline, hotel and office supply businesses who provide upgrades,
discounts and other benefits to the business cardholders. Some also
provide sophisticated monthly or quarterly billing statements which
break expenses into useful accounting categories like travel, food
and lodging.
</P>
<P>
   You may find some low introductory rates like the 3.9 percent
``teaser'' rates that banks frequently offer new individual
customers for six months. But McKinley suggests that if your credit
history allows you to get a 9.99 percent fixed rate, it may be
better, especially if you are interested in long term relationships
and reward programs.
</P>
<P>
   One thing to watch out for with business cards is that
cardholders of a business could be liable for their colleagues'
charges if their business is unable to pay the bills. Some issuers
offer protection against such a calamity by limiting employee
exposure to $15,000 or so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
More Biz Sites
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are some other good business Web sites besides the Small
Business Administration's (www.business.gov) site you mentioned
last week?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: There are lots of them. The California Society of Certified
Public Accountants in Redwood City recommends the following:
</P>
<P>
   BusinessAthome (www.gohome.com) _ Features financial, marketing
and operating tips for improving your home-based business.
</P>
<P>
   Small Business Supersite (www.smartbiz.com) _ Has articles,
reports and checklists.
</P>
<P>
   Small Business Administration (www.sba.gov) _ Includes
information on starting a business, creating a business plan,
arranging financing, business development and expansion, marketing
and more.
</P>
<P>
   Securities &AMP; Exchange Q&AMP;A (www.sec.gov/smbus/qasbsec.htm) _ Q&AMP;A
on how a business goes public, including regulations and reporting
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Business Resource Center (www.bizwiz.com) _ New site
under development to provide entrepreneurs with information about
financing marketing, registering your business, dealing with the
government and more.
</P>
<P>
   You might also check the California CPA society's own Web site
(www.calcpa.org). It has some new features useful to small
businesses like ``Ask a CPA'' and articles under ``CPAs Can Help.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, CalCPA offers guides to starting a business,
testing your EQ (entrepreneurial quotient), writing a business
plan, choosing the appropriate legal structure, finance options and
other subjects. It also has an online directory to find a CPA by
geography, expertise or language spoken.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRADE LINKS &QL; 
Last week, we mentioned that SBA's upgraded Web site allows users
to tailor a Web page to support their own international trade.
Reader David Rearwin e-mailed to say it didn't work and he was
right. But the SBA has fixed the link. Go to www.business.gov,
click on International Trade and then link to Tradenet Export
Advisor before clicking ``Personalize this site with: My Export.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
