<SLUG> BC-GM-DAEWOO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM WANTS DAEWOO MOTOR BUT NOT ITS BILLIONS IN DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ General Motors Corp. on Tuesday made
official its desire to buy Daewoo Motor Co., but said it was
unwilling to assume any of the Korean automaker's $16 billion in
debt.
</P>
<P>
   GM executive vice president Louis Hughes, who is now in Seoul,
delivered a letter of intent containing the company's investment
plans to a South Korean committee that represents the domestic
creditors of the troubled Daewoo group.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM is interested in all of Daewoo Motor's domestic business
areas and a large portion of its overseas operations,'' with the
exception of the operations most pressed for cash, said Alan
Perriton, the GM executive in charge of expansion plans in the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
   But Perriton said that it was too early to disclose details of
his company's proposal and that it needed more time to study Daewoo
Motor's business.
</P>
<P>
   An acquisition of Daewoo Motor would greatly expand the huge
American automaker's presence in Asia and would be the largest
asset sale so far for the Daewoo group, which was once South
Korea's second-largest conglomerate behind Hyundai.
</P>
<P>
   The Daewoo group has been struggling for months with a debt
burden estimated at nearly $78 billion, and creditors are pushing
for sales of businesses to pay off much of that debt.
</P>
<P>
   Daewoo Motor Co. has been a supplier of parts to GM under a
relationship that began almost 20 years ago. GM's purchase of the
company would almost certainly ensure Daewoo Motor's future. But
GM's refusal to assume any of its debt means that the Korean
automaker's creditors would have to absorb at least some losses on
their loans if such a sale were to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   An auction of Daewoo Motor has not been ruled out. But Perriton
said GM opposed that idea, saying it ``would harm Daewoo Motor by
prolonging the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh Ho Gen, the head of the Corporate Restructuring Coordination
Committee, which represents Daewoo's domestic creditors, said
further negotiations would be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes visited Seoul just a week after General Motors said it
was merely interested in making a substantial investment in the
Korean automaker.
</P>
<P>
   GM has been evaluating Daewoo's passenger car business as part
of an overall expansion plan in Asia, where it aims to double its
market share to 10 percent by 2005. Just last week, it acquired a
20 percent stake in Fuji Heavy Industries of Japan, parent company
of the Subaru automotive brand, for $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting between the GM officials and South Korean creditors
of Daewoo Motor took place against a background of growing friction
between the domestic and foreign creditors of the Daewoo group.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign creditors, owed nearly $7 billion, say they have
been largely excluded from negotiations aimed at easing Daewoo's
debts.
</P>
<P>
   In a proposal submitted to the foreign creditors earlier this
month, South Korean creditors offered to establish a special
company that would buy unsecured foreign debts held by Daewoo
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The debts would be purchased in cash, but at discounts ranging
from 18 percent to 65 percent. Foreign creditors rejected the
proposal as inadequate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
