<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9107 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-THRESH-THRESH_SFCHRON     12-14 1633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THRESH-THRESH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Video Game Champ Creates Web Portal  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Dennis Fong wasn't a hard-core video gamer. Then he won an
international Doom II competition.
<P>
   He's not a car person. But he has a red, convertible Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   And despite landing $11 million from the investment arm of
Internet powerhouse CMGI for his fledgling dot-com firm, Fong, also
known as ``Thresh'' on the game circuit, never really thought of
himself as a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Fong's short life _ he's only 22 _ has been a series of
pleasant, but unexpected twists, beginning in the early 1990s when
he discovered an aptitude for the twitchy world of video games.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he parlayed that talent and the money from scores of
tournament victories into Berkeley's GX Media, which now hopes to
turn its flagship Gamers.com site into the Web portal for any and
all things game related.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game industry right now is really fragmented,'' Fong said.
``We said we need to build something that brings it all together
... let's become an aggregator of all this information.''
</P>
<P>
   In a market as crowded as the game industry, Fong has his work
cut out for him.
</P>
<P>
   Just as game-related revenues soar _ the overall industry is now
worth a staggering $7 billion a year _ so do the number of Web
sites like Happy Puppy (happypuppy.com), ZDNet's GameSpot
(gamespot.com) and IGN.com (www.ign.com). Most offer game reviews,
sneak previews, trend stories, strategy hints and industry gossip.
</P>
<P>
   But Fong is maneuvering on a different level.
</P>
<P>
   While Gamers.com does offer areas for chatting and viewing
user-based ratings systems, it's mostly a network of links to other
sites' news, reviews, etc. Even the site's ``Play Games'' channel
connects to other sites that actually host the games. Instead of
creating the content, Fong wants to be the clearinghouse for it.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Funk, editorial director of Electronic Gaming Monthly and
Expert Gamer, calls Fong's goal of becoming the ``Yahoo'' of the
game world an ambitious one. But if Fong's business model depends
on users spending a lot of time at Gamers.com, Funk isn't sure it
will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   He believes the majority of gamers heading online will go
directly to Web zines offering original content or to sites where
they can immediately jump into a multiplayer match of Doom or
Quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to go to the (Electronic Arts) of the world
because they want to be there to play a game,'' Funk said. ``It's
nice to have a small chat before a game, but people usually have a
limited amount of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Pidgeon, an analyst at Internet research firm Jupiter
Communications, lauds Gamers.com for linking to other sites,
thereby saving overhead on hosting or content production. But he
warns that anyone getting into the game information business online
has to watch out for Sony, MSN.com's Zone and Electronic Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really the top three in this channel,'' Pidgeon said.
``They'll be more likely to offer more game-related information''
though each site will probably focus on their companies' respective
games.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the folks at CMGI of Andover, Mass., think
Gamers.com, which plans to make money through advertising,
e-commerce and community hosting fees, stands a good chance at
taking on some of the big guns.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI is a Boston-area conglomerate that has invested in,
acquired or launched dozens of portals, e-commerce companies,
Internet technology firms and online ad services. Among its stable
of companies are Engage Technologies, which develops software that
helps advertisers tailor offers to Web surfers, and the search
engine AltaVista.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, CMGI's venture capital arm, AtVentures, invested $11
million to help GX Media move into much  &LR; larger offices in Point
Richmond and increase its staff of 40 40-person head count &LR;   &LR; to
around 100.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jon Callaghan, AtVentures general partner, his
group had looked for an investment opportunity in the Internet game
market for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Two things stood out about Gamers.com, Callaghan said: The idea
that it was a site ``built by gamers for gamers,'' and Fong
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every online gamer needs a place to compare notes or
strategize, and Dennis is the best player in the world,'' Callaghan
said. ``He's very in touch with what gamers need and want in the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong says gamers feed on community.
</P>
<P>
   To foster that among hard-core gamers, he's employed a network
of ``game experts'' from around the world who review game, fan and
related sites and post their findings at Gamers.com.
</P>
<P>
   But since Fong believes ``the biggest obstacle to games now is
that it's intimidating, whether because it's too technical or too
edgy,'' he's also tried to make the site friendly for the general
user.
</P>
<P>
   He calls the interface a cross between Yahoo.com and Excite.com.
And he's installed a search engine and shopping channel, both
designed to appeal to a clueless parent looking for the newest
title or console.
</P>
<P>
   All this is designed to capitalize on the exploding number of
people logging on or plugging in to play Sonic the Hedgehog, Tomb
Raider or Twisted Metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games, about a year and a half ago, were what e-mail was five
years ago,'' Fong said. ``Five years ago, only the techies and
geeks had e-mail. Now if you don't have e-mail you're strange. It's
the same with games. People perceived games as this nerdy thing,
but it's shedding that stereotypical image now. As it's accepted
more and more, it will explode.''
</P>
<P>
   Research supports Fong's theory.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jupiter's Pidgeon, the game industry now outstrips
the film industry in annual revenues. And the online component _
revenues from advertising, subscriptions, etc. _ is expected to
reach well over $100 million this year, compared with about $80
million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``As online gaming grows, reviews, ratings, news, previews (are)
going to become even more important,'' he said. ``Anyone who's
offering all those things has a tendency to offer more hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Pidgeon also says Gamers.com provides something that no one else
does _ Fong's wildly successful gaming alter ego _ though he
criticizes the site for not hyping Fong's identity out front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thresh'' came into existence when a 14-year-old Fong first
took up gaming after hearing a series of explosions from his
younger brother's room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I peeked in and said, `What are you doing, Bryant?' He said
I'm playing this new game called Doom.' So I sat down and started
playing. I got my butt kicked. ... But I said, `Man, this is cool.'
From that day, I was hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong chose the name ``Thresh'' because in the macho world of
online gaming a word that means ``to strike repeatedly'' tends to
get noticed.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that Fong, a Los Altos native, showed an almost
uncanny ability to anticipate the future within the virtual
universes of Doom and Quake. Based on the sounds his opponents
would generate picking up a gun or reloading, Fong could tell where
they were in the game and in which direction they were heading.
They didn't stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot like the wild, wild West back then, where you
make a reputation beating certain opponents, and they spread the
word,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fong never realized he was that good.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a news crew from fledgling Cnet accompanied him to an
International Doom II tournament in Redmond, Wash. Both the crew
and Fong were stunned when he won. Shortly after, he enrolled in
the University of California at Berkeley as a business major; but
he left less than a year later to start Gamers Extreme. With its
easy-to-remember URL, Gamers.com, the company created a site for
fans of hard-core, multiplayer games. But the niche didn't expand
the way the Fong brothers expected.
</P>
<P>
   With the company struggling to gain an audience and stay afloat,
Fong continued to play in dozens of game tournaments, including an
Atlanta Quake competition in 1997. This time, he won a red
convertible Ferrari 328 GTS along with sponsorships, book deals and
a column for PC Gamer magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Fong plowed much of the money he made back into the company, but
it was stymied by some strategic missteps. Fong doesn't disclose
the financial details of the privately held company, but he does
say he and other executives (his official title is chief gamer)
sometimes didn't drive a hard-enough bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn, don't be too excited in the first
meeting,'' Fong said, recalling some of GX's initial business
encounters. ``Before, if someone had a pretty cool idea, we were
like, `Yeah, let's do it!' We were too trusting and too sincere, so
that hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half ago, Fong changed the company's name to GX
Media and decided to try to broaden its appeal to include the
entire gamers' spectrum. In March, the company landed about $2.25
million from so-called ``angel'' investors who often provide
capital for very young start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   But GX Media's big break came in Monte Carlo in October at the
European Technology Roundtable Expo. After presenting a speech on
the game industry, Fong met David Wetherell, the founder and
president of CMGI, who referred him to AtVentures.
</P>
<P>
   This time, GX Media found a partner, not an adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Fong has come to view business as one big game, like Doom and
Quake, albeit a bigger one with different rules. As both a
professional gamer and an entrepreneur, Fong has learned that speed
doesn't make up for lack of strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think it's reflexes,'' he said. ``But the way I
look at games is like speed chess, where there's a lot of
analytical, strategic thinking. Yeah you have to think fast, but
you have to think a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
