<HEADER>
A9110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-4     12-14 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA IGNORES EUROPEAN PLEA FOR TRUCE IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAKHACHKALA, Russia _ The Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe's chairman on Tuesday urged Russia and
Islamic rebels to agree to a cease-fire in Chechnya. But his plea
was ignored, and Russia continued its heavy shelling of Grozny, the
Chechen capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have made an appeal for a cease-fire, and if there is an
attack on Grozny, I have not been answered,'' the official, Kurt
Vollebaek, told reporters here in Makhachkala, the capital of
Dagestan, on Tuesday. ``On the contrary, they are doing the just
the opposite of what I asked for.
</P>
<P>
   Vollebaek's visit underscores the dearth of Western influence
over Russian policy in Chechnya. On the first full day of his
three-day visit, he not only had his plea rejected; the Russians
also bluntly informed him that they saw no role for his
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Like Western political leaders, the group has been concerned
that civilians are being put in danger in Chechnya and wants to see
the turmoil in the breakaway republic resolved by negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin considers the organization naive about the
Caucasus and asserts that suspending military operations now would
simply allow the rebels to rebuild their strength and sow disorder
through the south.
</P>
<P>
   Even Vollebaek's visit did not come about easily. The OSCE's
role was hotly debated in November at the European summit meeting
in Istanbul. Eventually an agreement was reached allowing Vollebaek
to travel to the region.
</P>
<P>
   But Moscow has sought to define the scope of his trip. Alexander
Avdeyev, a senior foreign ministry official, said in an interview
that Vollebaek's visit has been organized by Moscow to demonstrate
that much of the Caucasus is stable and that Russia is a good
custodian.
</P>
<P>
   Vollebaek, in fact, did not start his visit in Chechnya.
Instead, the Russians arranged for him to come to Dagestan, to the
east.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Dagestan was invaded by Islamic militants operating
from bases in Chechnya. And Vollebaek and several foreign reporters
were whisked by helicopter Tuesday to the Botlikh area so Moscow
could make its case that it was the militants who were responsible
for the fighting in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The former war zone is a stunning landscape of snow-capped
mountains, sheer cliffs, alpine meadows _ and destruction. One of
Vollebaek's stops _ Tando, a tiny village with a commanding view of
the valley _ was leveled in last summer's fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said that more than 200 militants had seized the town,
proclaiming they were going to drive the Russians out of the
Caucasus. After the villagers fled, Russian troops counterattacked
with artillery and air strikes, demolishing the village. Only a
handful of residents have returned. ``There is no electricity and
nothing to eat,'' said Fatimat Sakhratullayeva, 58.
</P>
<P>
   Vollebaek said here in Makhachkala that the damage made a strong
impression on him. But he added that his goal was to prevent
similar attacks on civilians in Chechnya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That brought a tart response from Nikolai Koshman, the Russian
official in charge in Chechnya, who noted that Russia halted its
earlier military campaign against the militants in 1996 when
Chechnya achieved its de facto independence. The result, Koshman
said, was an expansion of the militants' operations, hundreds of
kidnappings and the rebel attacks on Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   During Vollebaek's tour in Dagestan's mountains, the roar of
Russian artillery fire in Chechnya could be heard in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces have opened two escape routes for civilians
trapped in Grozny, but the corridors are open only for specified
hours, enabling the military to keep up its bombardment, albeit
intermittently. A Russian official said Russian troops had secured
the military airfield in Khankala, on the outskirts of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians appear determined to win the battle for Grozny,
regardless of what the West thinks. This quest has lent an air of
unreality to Vollebaek's peace mission.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday he plans to visit Chechnya and Ingushetia, to the
west. He expressed the hope that his meetings today with the
leaders of Dagestan and his scheduled session with the president of
Ingushetia might encourage a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, however, that the Russians had scant interest
in his proposal to involve the organization in the sort of
mediating role it played in the 1994-96 conflict.
</P>
<P>
   And he acknowledged that the Russians think his group should
confine itself to organizing relief assistance for Chechnya, and
not dispense political advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understand they cannot find a solution without including
the Chechens somehow,'' he told reporters here. ``Where they
disagree with me is the international role. Their view is that this
is something that Russia can solve by itself, that Russia is a
great power, Russia is mighty, Russia can deal with its own
business, and it does not need the international community to
assist them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
