<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER IGNORES GIRL'S COMMENT THAT `MY MOM IS DEAD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI AND DAVID ABEL S  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEABODY, Mass. _ A 7-year-old girl spent a night sleeping in her
dead mother's arms after her teacher apparently did not believe her
when she said her mother had died.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Hanson, a first-grader at the Kiley School, ``told her
teacher, `My mom is dead,' but she had no emotion in her eyes or in
her voice,'' said Mark Standley, a friend of Lydia's mother,
Kimberley Hanson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her teacher said, `You shouldn't say things like that,' ''
Lydia's grandmother, Sharon Tucker, told the Salem Evening News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lydia went to her desk and sat down and went on (with the) day
like nothing happened. And they put her on the bus when it was time
to go home . . . and her mommy was still there in a chair,'' Tucker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia apparently attempted to comfort herself during the lonely
night she spent with her mother's cold body by maintaining the
normal routine she had shared with Hanson, 33.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia later told her grandparents that after school she finished
her homework, then microwaved leftover spaghetti and meatballs for
dinner. She also made microwave popcorn and watched a movie,
because this was a ritual she and her mother followed every night,
Standley said.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia took a quilt from her bedroom, covered both herself and
her mother, and fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``She actually curled up in her mom's lap and went to sleep with
her overnight,'' Richard Tucker, Lydia's grandfather, told WHDH-TV
(Channel 7) in Boston. ``She watched TV for awhile, holding her
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Hanson, a single mother, had diabetes and probably died
of natural causes Thursday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia was unable to call the police for help because she did not
know how to use the household's new cordless telephone. She had
intended to mail her grandparents a letter with news of her
mother's death.
</P>
<P>
   Peabody Schools Superintendent Louis Perullo called the incident
``a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The school made a mistake,'' Perullo said in a written
statement. ``I wish we had done otherwise. This has never happened
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The young child's grandparents are angry that her teacher
dismissed such an alarming and unusual comment. ``I think it was
appalling. If a kid went to school and said, `My mommy hit me,'
they would have DSS down there like that,'' Richard Tucker said,
snapping his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Family friends, however, said they did not want to see
disciplinary action taken against the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so bad for the teacher,'' Standley said, speaking
outside Hanson's wake Tuesday night. ``She had so many kids to deal
with. But she could have done something, and she didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The school has called to apologize to the family.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Tucker found Hanson's body on Friday, with Lydia there,
holding her mother's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Hanson had complained of feeling ill. Her
mother, Sharon Tucker, made soup for her and Lydia, and made Hanson
promise to visit a doctor Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson did not have the chance. Instead, she sat in a recliner
chair in her living room, put her head back, and died Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia apparently did not go to school Friday morning. She made
herself a bowl of cereal for breakfast, Standley said. When her
grandfather arrived and asked her why she was home, ``she just
rubbed her mommy's hand and said, `Bampy, my mommy died.' '' Sharon
Tucker said. ``He walked over and touched her. She was ice cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson was a manager at a Boston publishing company, Sharon
Tucker said. She worked part time from home so she could be
available when Lydia left for school and returned home.
</P>
<P>
   The grandparents, who live in Hamilton, are trying to get
custody of Lydia, and arranging for her to see a counselor. They
say they will not send her back to the Kiley School.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if his granddaughter had cried over her mother's
death, Richard Tucker answered: ``No, she has not, and that is very
bothersome to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The child is sacred,'' Tucker added. ``You just can't take
what a child says for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2153EST &QL; 
