<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9120 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-COX     12-14 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abortion law may face legal challenge
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Secret court proceedings designed to protect
pregnant girls may create legal problems for a new Texas law that
will force doctors to notify the parent of a minor seeking an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Jan. 1, a doctor will have to notify a parent or
guardian 48 hours before performing the abortion, except in a
medical emergency.
</P>
<P>
   But a girl who doesn't want her parents to know about her
abortion can seek a court order certifying that she is mature
enough to make the decision herself, or that she has reason to fear
that telling her parents would put her in danger. The so-called
``judicial bypass,'' which the U.S. Supreme Court has ruled must be
included in parental notification laws, is designed mostly to
protect girls who have been sexually abused at home.
</P>
<P>
   To conceal the girl's identity, the new Texas law says
everything about the judicial bypass proceeding, including the
court's decision and even the judge's name, has to be confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody agrees that the girl's name should be kept secret. But
critics say the Texas confidentiality clause goes too far, cloaking
judges who might rule based on their ideology rather than the
facts. Some also worry that it will make it difficult for judges
and lawyers to know what ``mature and sufficiently well-informed''
actually means.
</P>
<P>
   The secrecy provision may be ripe for a legal challenge: Some
lawyers and judges argue that the judicial bypass rules, which go
far beyond the secrecy rules in other cases involving juveniles,
violate the Texas Constitution's ban on closed court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be shocked if there wasn't a lawsuit,'' said Chip
Babcock, a Dallas media lawyer who headed the Texas Supreme Court
committee that hammered out the procedural rules for the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Florence Shapiro, R-Plano, who sponsored the parental
notification bill, said she wanted to keep judges' names secret to
shield them from electoral intimidation from either side of the
contentious abortion debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suggest that there is no public purpose for judging
the judges in this particular set of circumstances, because they
are not going to be doing their ruling based on their pro-choice or
anti-choice views. They are going to be doing it based on the
mental capacity of the children,'' Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Watler, a Dallas lawyer who used to head the Freedom of
Information Foundation of Texas, said the law's sweeping
confidentiality ``erodes public confidence in the judiciary,
particularly in a controversial area like abortion. You inevitably
give rise to the idea that judges are deciding these cases based on
personal ideology, and not on the rule of law.'' Watler noted that
a Cincinnati newspaper successfully sued to overturn a similar
provision in Ohio's parental notification law.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides of the confidentiality issue point to
Harris County as an example of an overheated atmosphere on the
abortion issue. Anti-abortion rights forces have been particularly
active in local elections, including judicial races. One Houston
judge, state District Judge John Devine, was jailed as an
anti-abortion protester before he took the bench in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro says she wasn't pressured by either side of the abortion
debate on the confidentiality issue. Her claim is bolstered by the
ambivalence of some leading abortion rights supporters and
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Kae McLaughlin, who heads the Texas Abortion and Reproductive
Rights Action League, said national abortion rights activists want
judges' records to be public so they can be held accountable. But
she's afraid that Texas' elected judges who grant the judicial
bypass will be targeted for defeat by abortion-rights opponents.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin also worries that in rural areas of the state, girls
will resort to illegal and dangerous abortions rather than go
before a judge they know has a record of denying the bypass.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Price of Texans United for Life said he's not all that
concerned about the rules for the bypass procedure. He believes
that many girls will tell their parents rather than go before any
judge. Overall, he is convinced that the law will result in fewer
teen-age pregnancies and fewer abortions. In any case, Price said,
evidence from other states suggests that judges award the bypass 90
to 95 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see the same results, and how they write these
rules isn't going to affect that one way or the other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some judges and lawyers, meanwhile, say the confidentiality
clause may make it difficult for them to know how mature is mature
enough. ``It's going to be more difficult than in other areas of
the law to know what the law is and how to apply it,'' Supreme
Court Justice Nathan Hecht said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ann Crawford McClure of the Eighth District Court of
Appeals in El Paso said the secrecy provision will make it
difficult to establish a body of case law that judges and attorneys
can consult. ``It's really going to be like shooting at a moving
target for the time being,'' McClure said.
</P>
<P>
   But not all judges are concerned. District Judge Scott McCown of
Austin acknowledged that the maturity standard is subjective, but
he said it's one that judges already contend with in other juvenile
cases, such as deciding when a juvenile can be tried as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Hecht said the court considered ruling on the constitutionality
of the secrecy provision but decided to wait until it has a case in
front of it. He wouldn't be surprised, he said, if they get that
chance sometime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: sgreenberger(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
