<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: MIXED FORECASTS FOR FUTURE OF GLOBAL AVIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several days before the start of an international aviation
conference in Chicago early this month, the U.S. Transportation
Department released an upbeat report about the future of aviation
and the success of the various Open Skies agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Those agreements between nations permit unrestricted air service
by airlines of each country to, from and beyond the other's
territory, with no limit on the number of flights, the type of
aircraft and the prices they can charge. The United States has
agreements with 38 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department found that from 1996 to 1998, on
routes connecting interior cities in both the United States and
foreign countries, fares fell an average of 17.5 percent where Open
Skies was in effect. In markets without Open Skies agreements, the
average decrease was 3.5 percent. The department also noted that
the global impact of air transport would approach $2 trillion in
2010, almost double that of 1994, and directly and indirectly would
account for more than 30 million jobs, 6 million more than in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``Beyond Open Skies'' conference in Chicago heard a less
upbeat view of the future of aviation from James Goodwin, the chief
executive of United Airlines, the nation's biggest carrier.
Declaring global aviation at a crisis point, he said there was not
enough runway space, terminals or parking space to accommodate the
millions of arrivals and departures and the one billion passengers
projected to fly on U.S. airlines by 2012, up from 680 million
passengers this year. And he laid most of the responsibility at the
door of the nation's air traffic control system.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first such industry warning. Earlier this year,
Carol Hallet, president of the Air Transport Association, made
similar predictions, contending that the air traffic control system
was inadequate to handle the current 21,000 daily flights, much
less the billion passengers expected within the next dozen years.
In addition, the magazine Aviation Week &AMP; Space Technology
primarily cited the United States government for the growing air
travel crisis, a crisis in which ``passenger safety could be
severely compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is rare to hear such forebodings by an airline executive
at a conference intended to celebrate the growth and economic
importance of the aviation industry. Nevertheless, Goodwin warned
that if something is not done soon, air traffic delays would triple
in 10 years, costing passengers both time and money.
</P>
<P>
   A Matter of Service
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday is the deadline for the airline industry to put into
effect its improved customer service provisions. These include
giving passengers notification of cancellations, delays and
diversions; replying within 60 days of receiving written
complaints, and advising of the lowest fare available for each
flight.
</P>
<P>
   But individual airlines have gone beyond that, pledging to
notify passengers by phone (instead of at the airport) of flight
cancellations when known at least two hours before departure (Delta
Air Lines), promising not to keep passengers aboard delayed planes
for more than an hour (Northwest Airlines) and establishing a
consumer advisory board to give advice about the airline's
performance (U S Airways).
</P>
<P>
   U S Airways yesterday vowed to allow passengers to cancel
purchased tickets within 24 hours without penalty and promised to
make prompt refunds. Two days ago, Continental Airlines said that a
so-called Service Planning Center would be installed at each of its
hub airports in Newark, Houston and Cleveland to rebook passengers
on alternate flights, make hotel reservations and generally assist
fliers.
</P>
<P>
   But judging from reaction on the Internet and in trade
publications in recent weeks, the flying public is taking a
decidedly wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger Rights
</P>
<P>
   Passenger rights are spelled out on a Web site recently
introduced by the National Business Travel Association
(www.BizTraveler.org). There are also some 2,000 travel tips,
including how and where to file a travel complaint, warnings about
regions to avoid because of safety or weather threats, what to do
when bumped or delayed, how to travel with a laptop computer or
with children, and what safety precautions to take in hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Those tips were collected from more than 1,400 of the
association's corporate travel managers, and although intended for
business travelers, they should prove equally helpful for all
travelers. The Web site's passenger complaint form will allow the
association to monitor the actual level of service being delivered
in the travel industry, seek a remedy if possible, and, in the case
of air travel, compile a report from the responses and forward it
to the appropriate regulatory body. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
