<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH15-COX     12-14 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former GOP presidential hopeful endorses Bush
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORALVILLE, Iowa _ Facing questions about whether he is ready
for the White House, George W. Bush on Tuesday trotted out just
what the spin doctor ordered _ an endorsement from former rival
Lamar Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, one of the first to declare Bush not ready for the
big time, campaigned with the GOP front-runner and declared him
``presidential,'' an image Bush is working to capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed me last night and he showed me on the campaign trail
that he is steady, that he is strong and that he is presidential,''
Alexander said. ``In other words, when I get up in the morning and
turn on my television set and look into it, I want to see someone
who looks and acts presidential to me. And to me, George W. Bush
does that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who quit the race in August, offered the endorsement
three weeks ago. The Bush campaign announce-- it Tuesday, the
morning after a debate that, by all measures, went better for Bush
than two previous ones.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said Bush's experience as -- big-state chief executive
is a major plus. Seven months ago, however, Alexander was not quite
as impressed by Bush's resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to be a governor,'' Alexander said in May.
``Going from being governor to being president is like going from
the playground to the NBA finals, and the people of New Hampshire
know that.''
</P>
<P>
   When he dropped out of the race in August after a poor showing
in the Iowa straw poll, Alexander declined to endorse anyone. He
bemoaned the system that allowed Bush to become a prohibitive
front-runner by piling up early money and endorsements. At the
time, Alexander said voters, not inside players, should pick the
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Alexander offered a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is nearly over,'' he said, though nobody has voted
yet. ``I came to the conclusion that I'd waited long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's presidential credentials have come under fire as a result
of stumbles on the campaign trail and lackluster performances in
debates in New Hampshire and Arizona. Monday night, Bush was more
aggressive, especially toward top challenger Arizona Sen. John
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was more relaxed and more confident and more
engaged and a little feistier,'' said Bush adviser Mark McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
   McCain tried to score points with his campaign-reform message,
an ace in the hole he uses in relation to many issues. Karl Rove,
Bush's top adviser, said Tuesday that McCain is overrating the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``While campaign finance reform is a worthy goal . . . it ranks
somewhere lower on the scale than education and defense and taxes
and welfare,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Bush said he had no second thoughts about offering
Jesus Christ as the answer to a debate question asking the
candidates to identify the ``political philosopher or thinker . . .
you most identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Des Moines radio interview, Bush said ``some people might
have been offended by the fact that I was willing to express my
faith on public television. But that's OK. I just thought it was
the best thing to say at the time and, as you get to know me
better, you'll find I'm the kind of person that doesn't worry about
a poll or a focus group when asked questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
