<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9126 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLORIDA-LOTTO-COX     12-14 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-LOTTO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lotto odds great - for lottery officials
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ If you miss buying a ticket for tonight's
$77 million Lotto jackpot, don't fret. It will probably hit that
level at least once more within the year.
</P>
<P>
   And if $77 million isn't enough to make you part with a buck,
just wait 2.8 years, by which time it will likely have hit $134
million, according to lottery estimates obtained by The Palm Beach
Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``$100 million jackpots are achievable and statistically
probable within 24 months and statistically possible within 12
months,'' according to a March memo to then-interim Lottery
Secretary Sue Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the new math for the new Lotto, which was unveiled in
October to produce just these sorts of gigantic jackpots to induce
frenzied ticket buying in a public that's grown jaded with prizes
in the $20 million to $30 million range.
</P>
<P>
   How frenzied?
</P>
<P>
   In a week with a $3 million starting jackpot, the lottery
expects to sell about 11 million tickets. This past week, with
jackpots in the $60 million-$70 million range, the agency estimated
it will have sold 101 million of the $1 tickets.
</P>
<P>
   While lottery officials sold ``new'' Lotto as providing players
twice as many chances to win, in reality, according to its internal
documents, the new ``matrix'' was designed to make more players
lose more often _ thereby boosting stagnant Lotto sales from about
$700 million a year to at least $900 million, possibly $1.1 billion
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Going from a game of picking of six numbers out of 49 to six out
of 53, lottery officials worsened the odds of winning the jackpot
by 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old game, a player betting $10 per week _ if he could
have lived so long _ would have won $7 million after 27,000 years.
He would have spent $14 million winning it.
</P>
<P>
   With the new odds, a player betting $10 per week will win $11.5
million after 44,000 years, having spent $23 million to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Yet from the point of view of the lottery, the change in numbers
drastically decreases the chances that anyone will win a starting
jackpot _ from 50 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, the chances of there being a single winner
of a ``triple rollover'' jackpot of about $30 million decreases
from 94 percent to about 77 percent, thereby allowing the lucrative
quadruple and near mythic ``quintuple'' rollover. In the Lottery's
11-year history, there have been only two quadruple rollovers, $106
million in September 1990 and $89 million in October 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Quadruple rollovers are expected to bring in $51 million in
sales per drawing, with an average of three such jackpots each
year.
</P>
<P>
   And the quintuple _ a sort of Holy Grail for lottery officials _
could see a jackpot of up to $134 million, with $100 million in
sales for each such drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery statisticians estimate that such a drawing would take
place every three years. A comparable jackpot under the old Lotto
was statistically possible every 6.6 years, although the game had
not seen a jackpot like that since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   With any major change with a popular Lottery game, though, come
risks. In this case: What if players don't go for the idea of
betting on a game with even worse odds than before?
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials considered that, but ultimately decided to
believe a survey of their ticket vendors: ``Core players would
dislike it at first but that most players do not know or care about
the odds,'' according to an Aug. 19 staff memo sent to Lottery
Secretary David Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   An outside consultant brought in by Griffin to critique the
proposed switch also acknowledged the concern, advising Griffin to
go ahead with the change but have ready ``a contingency action
plan, with an exit strategy for the 6-of-53 Florida Lotto, when and
if the situation arises, including a replacement game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis,'' wrote Virginia gambling industry
consultant Carl Alexoff, ``there are only two ways to increase
sales: 1) have the current player base play more or 2) broaden the
player base. The trick is to do both.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Lottery officials might see their very first
``quintuple'' rollover tonight if no one wins the $77 million
jackpot. The chances of that happening: 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: shirishdate(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
