<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-USED-CARS-ART-2TAKES(     12-14 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USED-CARS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AUTONATION AND OTHER USED-CAR SUPERSTORES, HARD TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Mich. _ The AutoNation operation here looks more like a
gigantic Starbucks than a place to sell used cars.
</P>
<P>
   Acres of parking lots marked by color-coded signs surround a
large, high-ceilinged building of tan brick and glass. Inside,
instead of battered desks and lots of pushy sales representatives,
the office contains curving cubicles of polished wood, with
computers to describe the features of every car on the lot.
</P>
<P>
   But as heavy sleet turned to snow Tuesday morning in this
Detroit suburb, a team of liquidation experts poked through the
cavernous showroom, trying to determine what could be sold and how
quickly, from the cars to the computers. For while AutoNation has
succeeded in creating a cheerful, comfortable place to buy used
cars, it has failed to do so in a way that would earn money.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the century-long history of the auto industry,
selling cars _ particularly used cars _ has been a gritty business.
Profits usually flowed to the hardest-nosed bargainer, the dealer
who negotiated the highest possible price for each automobile while
spending as little as possible on amenities like furniture,
carpeting and salaries.
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation and other big, publicly traded companies captured
Wall Street's fancy three years ago by trying to change all that.
Now they are struggling as the car-sales industry is buffeted by
the rise of the Internet, a fall in used-car prices and a push by
traditional dealers to improve customer services.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these new-wave car sales companies built used-car
superstores that looked like cafes, not junkyards, and employed
computer kiosks and child-care centers to lure customers to immense
lots that offered as many as 1,000 late-model cars. The same
companies, plus a few others, later created big chains of new-car
dealerships that would share ad budgets and back-office staff to
build national brand names at relatively modest cost.
</P>
<P>
   But now the used-car superstores are disappearing almost as fast
as they appeared, while the chains' new-car dealerships try to cut
costs after sometimes lavish expansions.
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation's announcement late Monday that it would close most
of its used-car superstores and slash costs at its headquarters
signals the unraveling of that original vision. To some extent,
investors had already seen it coming: With the exception of Lithia
Motors, the most old-fashioned of the publicly traded auto
dealerships, stocks in those chains had already slumped. Since
early 1997, price-earnings multiples for the dealer chains have
tumbled from as high as 50 to just 8 or 9, as low as the multiples
for auto manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But the troubles are far from over. ``The initial Wall Street
projections were so off-base that you had this land rush into the
industry,'' said George Hoffer, an economist at Virginia
Commonwealth University.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong? The publicly traded dealership chains appear to
have been buffeted by several forces that few anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, the Internet has made car buyers more conscious of
what constitutes a fair price and better able to check prices
without shuttling among dealerships. These informed consumers give
dealers with low costs and little overhead the advantage, because
they can afford to sell cars at rockbottom prices.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, largely because prices for new cars have leveled off,
prices of late-model used cars have fallen recently, hurting the
value of the inventories at used-car superstores.
</P>
<P>
   Long-maligned traditional dealers also seem to have improved
customer service, partly to match the competition and partly in
response to pressure from automakers, including some that are
experimenting with operating dealerships themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, dealers have used their muscle in state capitals to
strengthen franchise laws. Even where the rules have not been
tightened, the laws already make it hard for publicly traded
dealership companies, automakers and Internet companies to expand
their retailing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Super-dealerships, thus, are undergoing a metamorphosis: Auto
executives are replacing the financiers who built the chains and
are moving quickly to reduce costs. In August, Roger Penske, the
car dealer and diesel-engine magnate, took control of United Auto
Group, the nation's second-largest dealership chain, from Marshall
Cogan, a financier. Michael Jackson, former head of Mercedes-Benz's
North American operations, became AutoNation's chief in October,
replacing Steven Berrard, a video-rental executive and friend of H.
Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   It was Huizenga who conferred Wall Street credibility to the
idea that publicly traded corporations could consolidate the auto
dealership industry; Huizenga had already consolidated the
garbage-hauling and video-rental businesses, building first Waste
Management and then Blockbuster Entertainment. In 1995, Huizenga
took control of Republic Industries, a small garbage hauler, and
set about turning it into what is now AutoNation, the world's
largest auto retailer.
</P>
<P>
   He was able to buy hundreds of dealerships with his high-flying
company stock as he reminded investors and analysts of previous
successes. ``We want to build a brand just like we did at
Blockbuster,'' the company's 1995 annual report said.
</P>
<P>
   But brand-building has proved difficult, partly because the
top-performing dealerships AutoNation bought had already built
their own reputations based on loyalty to the original owners. And
AutoNation was often prevented by state laws from getting extra
volume discounts from automakers that might give it a competitive
advantage over other dealers, so the company could do little to
make up for the higher costs associated with building an empire.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is now laying off virtually all 1,800 employees at the
23 used-car superstores being closed and dismissing 225 of 600
employees at AutoNation's headquarters in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he would also sell one of AutoNation's two jets and
even look for ways to trim costs at the corporate dining room. ``We
will create a cost-conscious culture in this company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But AutoNation, which has 409 dealerships in 19 states and
annual sales approaching $20 billion, still has a long way to go.
Compare it, for example, with Lithia Motors, essentially a family
dealership that has grown into the nation's sixth-biggest publicly
traded new-car dealership chain with 41 franchises under one
corporate umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   Lithia is known for its cheapness. Its corporate headquarters
are housed above the parts department of the company's Toyota
dealership in Medford, Ore. When an electric motor opens the garage
door for the loading dock below, the whir is heard in the offices
of the company's top executives. The walls have the original
knotty-pine paneling from 1973, and hallways feature exposed pipes.
</P>
<P>
   An executive dining room? ``I go to Taco Bell or order in
pizza,'' said Jeff DeBoer, Lithia's vice president of finance. ``We
order in spaghetti sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   That austerity has been rewarded: Lithia's earnings and stock
price have risen even as the stocks of the other big public
dealership chains have faltered. Generally speaking, investors have
grown disenchanted with the idea of generating rising earnings
simply by buying bunches of profitable dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   The only surviving publicly traded chain of used-car
superstores, out of five two years ago, is CarMax Inc., which is
also known for controlling its costs and is 77 percent-owned by
Circuit City Stores Inc. While AutoNation said on Monday that its
corporate overhead costs had risen 71 percent in the last 12
months, CarMax's overhead has remained flat even as it has slowly
expanded, said Austin Ligon, its president.
</P>
<P>
   Austin attributed AutoNation's problems to excessive growth:
``There's a limit to how fast you can do this and still be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation's rivals have also tried to give considerable
autonomy to their dealerships' sales managers, reasoning that every
auto market is subtly different and constantly changing. United
Auto Group and AutoNation are now moving in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   Rival dealers say that a lack of feel for local markets hurts
the big chains. James Willingham, a Buick, Pontiac and GMC dealer
in Long Beach, Calif., said he often drives by an AutoNation
used-car superstore and is surprised by what is on its lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the wrong product,'' he said. ``They're very close to
Long Beach University with 30,000 students and they've got big
sport utility vehicles, big Cadillacs and Oldsmobiles when they
should have Toyotas and Nissans.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation now sees its future relying to a great extent on the
Internet. Two years ago, when it was buying dealerships almost
every week, Berrard said that the company had only begun to work on
an Internet strategy. Jackson now considers the Internet a core
part of AutoNation's business, noting in a conference call with
analysts and reporters on Monday that customers who first contacted
the company through the Internet had bought $1 billion in cars this
year.
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation now lists 90,000 cars and their prices on its Web
site, www.autonationdirect.com; it has 900 sales agents to handle
Internet inquiries. ``This is a payoff for economies of scale,
because of the single-site advantage to present a wide selection,''
said Thomas Eggleston, AutoNation's senior vice president for
e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But while its selection may be broad, customers are unlikely to
buy cars at dealerships at the other end of the country and wait
for delivery.
</P>
<P>
   And for all its size and heft, AutoNation has found that it
cannot simply cut margins and try to sell as many cars as possible.
The company tried recently in Denver and learned that the
automakers' systems for allocating new cars _ another feature of
the franchise system _ did not allow dealers to replace cars as
fast as they were sold, Eggleston said. Manufacturers have been
leery of shipping so many cars to a single dealer, concerned that
the dealer will pursue sales across the franchise territories of
other dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The same state franchise laws also make it impossible for
AutoNation to start selling new cars at the used-car superstores
that it is shutting because that would have infringed on the
territories of existing dealers.
</P>
<P>
   A few experts have suggested that publicly traded dealership
chains join with automakers and Internet companies in a lobbying
campaign to overturn the state laws, possibly through federal
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But traditional dealers are masters not only of low-cost selling
but also of using their connections to influence lawmakers. Despite
lobbying by automakers, dealers have already persuaded at least
five states this year to tighten state franchise laws even further.
Even as the public dealership companies stagger, traditional
dealers are still standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were a real fight,'' said one auto-manufacturing
executive, ``it would have been called.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
