<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BLAME MILLER FOR THE STAR THAT GOT AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marvin Miller stood off to the side Tuesday afternoon
in a large room at the All Star Cafe in Times Square. . Moments
earlier, The Sporting News had named its 100 sportsmen of the
century. Pete Rozelle was voted as the most powerful of all. On
hand to honor his memory were the commissioners of the four major
professional team sports: baseball's Bud Selig, football's Paul
Tagliabue, basketball's David Stern and hockey's Gary Bettman. One
by one, they stepped to the podium to reflect on Rozelle, and how
he had distinguished himself in his long run as commissioner of the
National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the news media circled the four men to talk some more
about Rozelle, and about the hot issues facing each sport. Miller,
the former head of the baseball players union, watched the
give-and-take, not feeling particularly attached to the moment. ``I
feel more like history than anything else,'' he said. ``I don't
have any active role to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but his presence was a reminder that the Sporting
News voters got it all wrong. Rozelle was a master at making a game
into something larger than life: the AFL-NFL merger, ``Monday Night
Football,'' NFL Films, NFL Properties. But Rozelle was working for
the owners, using athletes' supple bodies to make the enterprise
larger while keeping the players' share as small as possible,
refusing to even give guaranteed contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Miller gave players the atomic bomb of sports: he
gave them free agency.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest proof of Miller's lasting power came late Monday
night with news that Ken Griffey Jr. had broken New York's heart
and rejected a trade that would have sent him from Seattle to the
Mets. The deal was so tantalizing that even Selig admitted being
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, I think it would be great for Ken Griffey
Jr. to be in New York,'' Selig said. ``From the commissioner of
baseball's perspective, yes, if the world were perfect and you
could order players. But you can't. I think it would be great for
baseball, but I want to be protective of his right to be able to
choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Griffey would have been a Met. Period. But as
a player with 10 years of experience in the major leagues and the
last five with the same club, Griffey had the right to veto the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, the St. Louis Cardinals traded Curt Flood to
the Philadelphia Phillies. Flood balked and, with Miller as his
counsel, went to court seeking the right to become a free agent.
Miller warned Flood that he would probably lose the case; he also
predicted that the suit would initiate a movement that would change
the financial landscape of professional teams. Flood lost, but the
tapestry was changed. A player's talent clearly meant something.
Andy Messersmith picked up the fight following the 1975 season, and
won, challenging baseball's reserve clause and becoming the sport's
first free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty five years later, Miller feels that many of the players
have no idea of where their free-agent rights come from. ``I do
feel a little irked and chagrined when I realize that the players
have no idea that it was the union that changed everything,'' said
Miller, who was the head of the union from 1966 through 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the brightest of the players, a John Olerud, can exalt in
the fact that he's able to pick a team, go back to his roots. But
there's nothing I've read that gives me the faintest idea that he
knows where this came from. What's taken for granted are the
salaries, the perks, free-agency rights, salary arbitration rights,
all of which were tremendous struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Miller added: ``I would like to see more of these players active
in their own union. I don't like to see them have a board meeting
when 12 teams are not represented. That shows a lack of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Selig spoke of a partnership between Major League
Baseball and its players. ``Everybody has to start to think
league,'' Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller is ever wary. Owners are the relentless foe, the
enemy that never stops being an enemy. In his view, the lack of
restraint that prompts owners to spend $80 million on one player is
the same impulse that won't allow them to stop the assault on
player gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't know your history, you tend to relive it,''
Miller said. ``I don't want to see players have to fight this all
over again. During the period I was active, I would say the latter
half was filled with nothing but attempts by the owners to turn
back the clock. I don't believe they've ever given up.''
</P>
<P>
   And so whenever Junior gets a chance, he should call Miller and
thank him for giving him the option to say no to New York.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
