<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-NYT &LR;      12-14 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH'S MESSAGE FOR CONGRESS: `ETHICS COMMISSIONER EQUALS
ENFORCEMENT'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Juan Antonio Samaranch, the president of the
International Olympic Committee, felt jittery about testifying
before a House subcommittee on Wednesday, he refused to show it
Tuesday night. In his corner hotel suite in Georgetown, he sat
serenely on a sofa and sounded certain that the reforms enacted
last weekend by the IOC will settle all congressional doubts about
the direction of the embattled organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nervous,'' he said, flanked by Dick Pound, an IOC vice
president, and Bob Ctvrtlik, an Olympic volleyball player elected
to the IOC last week. ``What do I have to be nervous about? I'm
told there will be very tough questions, and will try to answer
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, a 79-year-old Spaniard, arrived at the hotel with a
small entourage after a meeting about the IOC's new World
Anti-Doping Agency with Gen. Barry R. McCaffrey, the White House
drug policy director, who excoriated the committee's anti-doping
efforts earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pleased,'' said Samaranch. ``It was a very good
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey and Samaranch released a 17-point agreement, but
McCaffrey said it was nonbinding. There were no groundbreaking
proposals, and the agreement basically reiterated ideas that were
generated from the formation of the IOC's anti-doping agency last
month and a meeting between McCaffrey and Pound, the head of the
IOC agency.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has been elusive quarry for Congress since it began
holding hearings last winter into the scandal over illicit cash and
gifts provided to IOC members by organizers of the 2002 Salt Lake
City Winter Olympics. At two Senate hearings and one in the House,
his absence was noted and scorned, as other IOC members testified
in his place.
</P>
<P>
   His agreement to appear Wednesday came with an assurance that he
would not be subpoenaed as a witness in the ongoing Justice
Department inquiry into the Salt Lake City scandal and negotiations
that eventually led to his agreement to speak to the FBI next
month.
</P>
<P>
   But Samaranch wanted to testify only after last weekend's IOC
session in Lausanne, where 50 procedural changes were approved.
``Maybe before the sessions, it could have been dangerous,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes include modified term limits for members, a ban on
members' once-cherished, but abused, visits to bid cities and the
election of 15 active athletes to the IOC
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they will not trust,'' he said of the members of the
House Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations, which is headed
by Representative Fred Upton, Republican of Michigan. ``But we are
speaking not with words, but with facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch refused to accept the notion that a skeptical Congress
_ and American public _ has placed the IOC on probation until it is
clear that the reforms are tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to trust the members,'' he said. ``We have to trust
the bid cities.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pound added: ``We're not on probation. We're embarking on an
exciting new direction. But there are some people who won't be
happy until we sink into the middle of the Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch sidestepped the criticism of IOC members that Congress
was too intrusive, in threats to strip the organization of its
nonprofit status in the United States and halt the flow of domestic
television rights fees to its accounts. Lambis W. Nikolaou of
Greece, an IOC member, cautioned Samaranch not to testify. ``You
are only accountable to the Olympic family,'' Nikolaou said.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, ever the diplomat, said Tuesday: ``I've said many
times before that the Olympic Games belong to the world. The
president of the IOC is accountable to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Wednesday's hearing, he will be accountable to Upton's
panel. He expects questions about the reforms and about a $12,000
trip that his wife took to Atlanta in 1990 at the expense of that
Olympic organizing committee before it was awarded the 1996 Summer
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was invited,'' he said. ``I told her she had to accept the
invitation. These people are friendly, they're nice.'' He said the
trip, including a side trip to the Olympic yachting site in
Savannah, Ga., posed no ethical problem because he ``has nothing to
do with choosing bid cities.''
</P>
<P>
   He rifled through his leather briefcase to find a letter his
wife received after her trip from Vice President Dan Quayle. ``I
hope you were able to sample the warm hospitality for which the
American South is famous,'' Quayle's letter read.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch also sought to clarify confusion about the mandate of
a new eight-member ethics commission. Last weekend, some members
said it would not initiate future investigations of wrongdoing
without a written complaint or that it would not revisit past
violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cases that are judged are finished,'' he said. ``But if new
facts come from the past, they will be reopened. If no old facts,
it's done.'' He said credible evidence of wrongdoing _ delivered by
letter or verbally _ would be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Had the commission existed several years ago, would it have
rooted out corruption within the Salt Lake City organizing
committee? After all, the scandal was not disclosed to the IOC
through a letter, a personal visit by a whistleblower or a
telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' he said. ``I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, a message was passed to Samaranch from a press
aide. It read: ``Ethics commissioner equals enforcement.'' It
reminded him that an ethics commissioner, reporting to the
commission, is to be hired to police future violations.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Samaranch folded the note into a paper airplane and
rested it on a coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch will deliver his opening statement in English. He will
try to persuade the House subcommittee that the IOC has delivered
on its promise to reform itself. Then he will answer questions in
Spanish through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can say the Olympics are not up to date,'' he said.
``The structures were not the best ones, and we used this crisis to
change many things, no?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
