<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECON-REPORT-350&AMP;ADD-N     12-14 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER PRICES BARELY ROSE IN NOVEMBER, U.S. REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite booming retail sales and strong consumer demand, the
Consumer Price Index barely rose in November, the Labor Department
reported Tuesday. Even gasoline prices did not make their usual
contribution to inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Prices rose in a few scattered areas _ like long-distance
telephone tolls, airline fares, prescription drugs and housing
costs _ but the index, reflecting a great variety of goods and
services, was up only 0.1 percent, the smallest increase since
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is too much competition and too much deregulation, and
as a result companies are finding it virtually impossible to raise
prices,'' said Ed Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Banc Alex.
Brown, offering an explanation why rising inflation, widely
expected on Wall Street, fails month after month to show itself in
the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The weak November inflation number should have sent stock prices
soaring, with its suggestion that the Federal Reserve's
policy-makers will refrain from raising interest rates when they
meet next week. Stable prices and interest rates encourage
investors to remain in stocks rather than shift to interest-bearing
securities.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of focusing on the bland inflation data, investors
responded to two other government reports that reflected the
economy's strength and for that reason seemed to portend higher
interest rates, if not next week then soon enough. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 32.42, to 11,160.17, and interest rates on
Treasury securities rose slightly.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department, in one report, said retail sales jumped
by a robust 0.9 percent, a result of holiday spending and a surge
in auto purchases in a strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the second report, the nation's current-account deficit, a
measure of what Americans owe to foreign lenders, rose in the third
quarter to $89.95 billion, up 11.2 percent from the second quarter.
Higher interest rates, in Wall Street's view, would cut into these
trends by raising the cost of credit. Spending would slow not only
for domestic goods but also for imports, the main reason for the
rising foreign debt.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Yardeni attributed the mild inflation numbers to
competition and deregulation _ of the telecommunications industry
in the mid-1990s and banks and financial services companies this
fall _ others said the stock market might be playing a dual and
somewhat contradictory role.
</P>
<P>
   Rising stock prices encourage spending and demand, trends that
could in time produce inflationary shortages. But notoriously
unprofitable Internet companies are using money raised from
investors to subsidize discount pricing. Amazon.com, for instance,
floats shares in a rising market, and the money it raises covers
huge annual losses. Meanwhile, the company maintains its discount
pricing. And the discounts, in turn, keep prices down in
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar is happening in other industries, says Sung
Won Sohn, chief economist at Wells Fargo in Minneapolis. ``Many
people check toy prices on the Internet and ask toy stores to match
them,'' he said. ``Or they see the merchandise at a store and go
home and buy it for less on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices would have fed into the inflation rate,
producing a higher price index, if the Bureau of Labor Statistics
had continued its price surveys for another week instead of ending
them Nov. 22. The bureau followed its usual practice of shortening
the surveys to three weeks from four in November and December, to
interfere as little as possible with holiday shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices dipped in late October, and ``there was not
enough of a rebound by the time we had finished our pricing,'' said
Patrick Jackman, a senior economist in the office that handles the
price index. The December report is likely to reflect the rebound,
perhaps adding as much as one-tenth of a point.
</P>
<P>
   With energy excluded from the November report, the price index
rose only 0.2 percent. That was also the case when both food and
energy prices were excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Economists focus on this restricted figure because they consider
energy and food prices volatile _ subject to sharp fluctuations
that can distort the overall ndex. With those exclusions, the index
increased 2.1 percent for the 12 months ending last month. By this
measure, the annual inflation rate has fallen from 2.4 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The overall index is another matter, rising 2.6 percent over the
last 12 months, a full percentage point more than the annual rate
as of last December. Rising petroleum prices accounted for all of
the increase, particularly as it shows up in gasoline, aircraft
fuel and heating oil. Elsewhere, petroleum has not affected the
prices of other products yet, although it is a major building block
for plastics used in toys and many other products.
</P>
<P>
   Toy makers and others who use plastics may simply be absorbing
the higher cost, at the expense of profits, or offsetting the cost
through greater productivity _ in effect getting more production
from employees for the same wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Productivity would have to rise at an accelerating rate to
maintain this balance, and that is questionable,'' said Richard D.
Rippe, chief economist at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite strong sales last month, the prices of new vehicles were
unchanged, on a seasonally adjusted basis, and over the last 12
months they fell 0.3 percent. Apparel costs fell in November,
reflecting discounting that usually precedes Christmas. But rents
and the cost of owning a home rose _ each by a strong 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of demand for housing,'' Jackman said, ``and
that is affecting monthly costs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
