<SLUG> BC-NY-TRANSIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY, TRANSIT WORKERS REACH TENTATIVE DEAL, APPARENTLY AVERTING
STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for updated top and general rewrite) 
 (mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City's transit workers and the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority agreed on the outlines of a tentative deal
Tuesday night, a union spokeswoman said, apparently averting a
strike that was threatened for Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 p.m. Tuesday, Carlean Williams, a spokeswoman for Local 100
of the Transport Workers Union, said that Willie James, the union's
president, had just reached an agreement that would cover the
city's 33,000 subway and bus workers. But union officials said a
few final details were still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams said she did not immediately have details of the
tentative agreement because James had not yet presented the
agreement to the union's board and staff.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the two sides were moving closer to an agreement on
Tuesday, city officials warned of the possibility of disruptions
Wednesday from wildcat actions by disgruntled transit workers..
</P>
<P>
   City and state officials said Tuesday night that the MTA and
union sides were close to a deal, but it was not quite clinched.
Michael McKeon, a spokesman for Gov. George Pataki, said the
governor was heading from Albany to his New York City office to do
what he could to help resolve any loose ends in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative agreement came on a day when James was under
intense pressure from a large dissident faction to take a tough
stance and from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to avoid a strike. The two
sides reached the tentative deal on a day when a state judge issued
two orders threatening the union with draconian fines if it went on
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that leaders of the transit workers' union had
provided assurances that the union would not shut down New York
City's transit system Wednesday morning, although just hours before
the agreement was reached, city officials were preparing for
possible rush hour chaos because of wildcat work stoppages.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the tentative deal was announced, an official
close to the negotiations said that the two sides had considerably
narrowed their differences. This official said that the union had
reduced its wage demands to 5 percent a year over three years, down
from its previous demand for 9 percent a year. The MTA, this
official said, had raised its offer to 13 percent over four years,
up from its previous offer of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, James and other leaders in Local 100 of the Transport
Workers Union had threatened a strike if they did not reach an
agreement with the Metropolitan Transportation Authority by 12:01
Wednesday morning, when the contract expired.
</P>
<P>
   James sent a letter to all members Tuesday warning that the huge
fines that could be imposed from defying the judge's orders ``will
quickly bankrupt the union, making it unable to function on your
behalf.'' But the letter stopped short of saying that he would not
call for a strike.
</P>
<P>
   At a City Hall news conference, Giuliani said the letter made
clear that the union's leaders opposed a walkout, which would be
illegal under New York state's Taylor Law, which bars strikes by
transit workers and other public-sector employees.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani added that there was still a small chance that a
large dissident faction in the union could muster the votes to
authorize a strike, a move that could paralyze the city and create
havoc for 3.5 million people who use the mass transit system each
day.
</P>
<P>
   Before the tentative deal was announced, Giuliani said that some
parts of a contingency plan to speed transportation into Manhattan
would go into effect Wednesday morning, and that the full plan,
which would restrict motor vehicle access, would be ready if
needed. The city has spent $3 million preparing for a strike.
</P>
<P>
   After four days of attacking the union, Giuliani escalated his
efforts Tuesday to pressure it not to strike. He had the city's
lawyers go to a judge's house shortly before 7 a.m. to obtain a
restraining order that calls for fining the union $1 million for
the first day of a strike, and $2 million for the second day,
doubling each successive day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, union members, whose wages average $39,000 a year,
could face fines of $25,000 on the first day of a strike, with the
fine doubling on successive days.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said, ``We sought an amount of money that would
immediately make it financially impossible for anyone to engage in
this activity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
