<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ISRAEL AND SYRIA SPEAK OF PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Dec. 15:
</P>
<P>
   History beckons in Washington on Wednesday, as Israel and Syria
open peace talks that could bring an end to an era of conflict in
the Middle East. The Israelis and Syrians appear eager to resolve
their differences quickly, and they will have the assistance of
President Clinton in trying to do so. The major issues facing the
lead negotiators, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk Shara, involve control of the Golan
Heights, the restoration of peace in Lebanon and the safeguarding
of Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the narrow margin of approval Israel's Parliament gave
Barak's negotiating plans Monday, the moment is promising for a
settlement with Syria and the Israeli leader should be bold in
seizing it. Peace with Syria and Lebanon would mean that for the
first time since its creation in 1948, Israel would no longer face
armed hostility from any of its immediate neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli governments have tried to negotiate with Syria before,
without success. This time chances seem good that a deal can be
worked out in which Israel would return most of the Golan Heights
in exchange for a Syrian commitment to peace, recognition and
normal trade.
</P>
<P>
   The talks will probably move quickly to the details of defining
Israeli withdrawal lines in the Golan and establishing safe
conditions for Israel's promised troop withdrawal from Lebanon.
Before Israel took control of the Golan's strategic high ground in
1967, Syria used it to launch attacks on Israeli civilians below
and to threaten vital water supplies. The Golan also provides a
vantage point overlooking military traffic from Damascus to the
border, giving Israel time to mobilize in the event of Syrian
attack. New ways will have to be found to provide Israel with the
information it now gets from monitoring stations atop the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   One plausible proposal would place international or U.S.
observers at the Golan monitoring stations now manned by Israelis,
with Israel retaining access to information directly affecting its
security. There might also be agreement to demilitarize a swatch of
territory on either side of the newly established border.
</P>
<P>
   The issues concerning Lebanon are in particularly urgent need of
resolution because of Barak's promise to withdraw Israeli forces
from that country by next July. Even if Syria agrees to rein in
Lebanese Hezbollah fighters from launching new attacks against
Israel, Damascus may not be able to guarantee that Hezbollah's
Iranian sponsors will show equal restraint. Yet it is hard to
imagine a Golan solution that does not include Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's Israeli parliamentary vote is significant, since Barak
has promised that any deal he reaches with Syria will be submitted
to Israeli voters in a referendum. But if Syria is reasonable about
addressing Israeli security needs, a peace agreement can still win
broad public support. It is now up to Barak and Syrian President
Hafez Assad to produce such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
