<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STROLLER-CASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY REJECTS DANISH MOTHER'S CLAIM OF FALSE ARREST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a case that set off a trans-Atlantic debate about
child-rearing practices, a federal jury in Manhattan rejected a
Danish woman's claim Tuesday that New York City police officers had
falsely arrested her outside an East Village restaurant after she
left her baby daughter in a stroller on the sidewalk to go inside
for a drink.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member panel, however, did award the woman, Anette
Sorensen, a total of $66,400 in compensatory and punitive damages
for events after her arrest, including what the jury called the
``widespread practice'' by the police of failing to advise
foreigners who are arrested in New York of their right to
assistance from their consulate.
</P>
<P>
   But the repudiation of the false arrest claim made by Ms.
Sorensen, who contended that in Denmark parents often leave their
babies in strollers on the sidewalk, was seen as clear vindication
by the city and the police officers who had arrested her that night
in May 1997 and who were named in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Gregory O. Ajose, one of those officers, said: ``It shows
that police officers can act in good faith and not fear that their
actions will be misunderstood and they'll be held to a standard
that's unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We acted in good faith that evening,'' he went on, ``to try to
protect the life and interests of a 14-month-old child, and to be
dragged through this lawsuit was pretty sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Ms. Sorensen's lawyer, Michael Q. Carey, denounced
the verdict as possibly the result of ``jury nullification'' _ when
a jury ignores the evidence before it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have been a cultural question,'' he said, adding, ``A
little xenophobia was at play here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorensen, who weathered a blistering cross-examination in
the trial that raised questions about whether she had been drunk
and ignored her child's welfare that night, said afterward: ``I
have to lean up against the truth. That's what I've done all the
way along. The truth hasn't changed.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the six members of the jury would discuss the verdict.
The forewoman, who did not give her name, said only that the jurors
focused on the facts and saw the case as a serious one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing that makes it here is frivolous,'' she said as she
left U.S. District Court in Manhattan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In reaching its verdict, the jury also rejected a false arrest
claim by the baby's father, Exavier Wardlaw, 52, who lived in
Brooklyn and was with Ms. Sorensen that night at the restaurant, a
Dallas BBQ at Second Avenue near St. Marks Place.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that although both Wardlaw and Ms. Sorensen, 32,
had been strip-searched by the police, they were each entitled only
to nominal damages of $1.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorensen was awarded $6,400 in compensatory damages for the
failure of the police to advise her of her right to have the Danish
Consulate notified. Her lawyer, Carey, had offered evidence that
the police failed in tens of thousands of cases a year to provide
such information.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant corporation counsel, Patricia Miller, said that the
city would seek to overturn the $60,000 in punitive damages awarded
in the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the law is very clear that punitive damages may not be
awarded against the city,'' she said, ``and I suspect that that
particular amount will be set aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Wardlaw, whose total award was $1, left the courtroom fuming.
``What's wrong with New York City?'' he asked. ``Where is humanity
of the people?
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Danish customs had resonated throughout the trial,
which was attended by many Danish television and newspaper
journalists. In court, Ms. Sorensen testified that she had always
been able to see Liv, who was bundled in blankets in the stroller,
through a window in the restaurant, but that she had gone inside
herself because it was chilly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
