<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON MEETS WITH JEWISH GROUP TO DEFLECT CRITICISM ON ISRAEL
TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Moving to ease strains with some Jewish groups,
Hillary Rodham Clinton met privately with Orthodox Jewish leaders
for more than an hour Tuesday, as she sought to deflect criticism
of her November visit to Israel while signaling her agreement on a
number of issues raised by the group, including opposition to
physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to express my deep commitment for the security and
well-being of Israel,'' the Democratic candidate for U.S. Senate
told reporters after the meeting at the downtown headquarters of
the Union of Orthodox Jewish Congregations of America. ``I was able
to discuss the role that I believe the United States should rightly
play in supporting Israel as it takes risks for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Mrs. Clinton used the meeting to recount, if
in unusually great detail, what have become familiar views on
U.S.-Israeli relations and other issues of concern to the group.
</P>
<P>
   However, in one emotional moment, Mrs. Clinton assured Stephen
Flatow, whose daughter was killed in a terrorist attack in the Gaza
Strip in 1995, that she supported his efforts to collect a $247.5
million in damages he won in a suit against Iran. A U.S. District
Court made the award under the 1996 Antiterrorism Act after finding
that Iran had promoted the terrorist group that claimed
responsibility for the blast that killed his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts by Flatow, who was one of 100 people who attended
the lunch with Mrs. Clinton, to collect by seizing diplomatic
property owned by the Iranian government in the United States have
been strongly opposed by the State Department, which has argued
that diplomatic property is sacrosanct. Mrs. Clinton used the
meeting to signal her disagreement with the State Department's
stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that the State Department would negotiate with
you in good faith and there could be some way of resolving this
that would stay true to the principle that you pursued and the
meaning of the legislation that was signed,'' Mrs. Clinton said,
according to notes taken by someone who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also signaled that she supported the groups'
attempt to curb physician-assisted suicide, though she stopped
short of endorsing legislation in Congress, supported by the
Orthodox Union, that would outlaw it.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's meeting with the group came at a time of growing
concern among her advisers about her standing among Jewish voters,
a critical group in her expected campaign against Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani. Giuliani has always had strong relationships with Jewish
leaders in New York, particularly the more religious and
politically conservative leaders who made up the bulk of Mrs.
Clinton's audience Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady was accompanied to the meeting by Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., an Orthodox Jew who is a member of the board of
directors of the group.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting view of the two candidates became clear after
Orthodox Union president Mandell Ganchrow was asked, after a
question-and-answer session with the first lady, if he viewed Mrs.
Clinton and Giuliani as friends of the Jewish community. ``Mayor
Giuliani has been a friend,'' Ganchrow said. ``Mrs. Clinton has
been a friend in her circles. We do not know her as well, because
she has not run for office. And that was the purpose of this
meeting, to really find out where she stands on some of these
issues. Some of these issues we agree with, some we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has been criticized by this group, and others in
New York, for sitting silently as the wife of Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat used a public awards ceremony to suggest that Israel
had been poisoning Palestinian children with toxic gases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
