<SLUG> BC-HERNDON-OBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENABLE HERNDON, PLAYWRIGHT AND SCREENWRITER, DIES AT 72  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Venable Herndon, a playwright and screenwriter who
taught dramatic writing at New York University's Tisch School of
the Arts, died on Dec. 8 at Mount Sinai Hospital in Manhattan. He
was 72 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was acute leukemia, said Louise Bernikow, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   His best-known screenplay was his 1969 collaboration with the
director Arthur Penn on ``Alice's Restaurant,'' a film inspired by
the hit recording by Arlo Guthrie and starring Guthrie. His plays
included ``Until the Monkey Comes,'' which was produced Off
Broadway in 1966 and revived earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Herndon was also the author of a book, ``James Dean: A Short
Life'' (1974), and was the founding editor of the literary journal
Chelsea Review in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Philadelphia on Oct. 19, 1927, Herndon graduated from
Princeton in 1949 with a degree in French literature and received a
master's degree in comparative literature from Harvard in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   From 1951 to 1966, he worked in advertising with clients
including Gimbel's and Beefeater gin.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the faculty at New York University in 1975, becoming
an associate professor in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Sharon Anson, and a daughter,
Isabelle Molinaro of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
