<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-2000-HOTELS-335&AMP;AD     12-14 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-2000-HOTELS-335&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHATTAN HOTELS EXPECT THIS NEW YEAR'S EVE TO SET RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some cities have scaled back their expectations for
New Year's now that they have no illusions that holiday visitors
will have to camp outside overflowing hotels. In Manhattan, rooms
are available at many hotels for New Year's, and events like the
star-studded $1,000-a-person Celebration 2000 party at Jacob Javits
Convention Center have been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Manhattan's hotel industry remains on track for a
record New Year's holiday. About 85 percent of Manhattan hotels
will be completely sold out during the holiday, compared with 70
percent occupancy for a typical New Year's Eve, according to a Dec.
6 estimate by the PricewaterhouseCoopers hospitality and leisure
consulting practice. And revenues from room rates and the New
Year's Eve packages wrapped around them will average 21 percent
more than usual for this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   New York room rates are already the highest in the nation,
averaging $178.60 a night this year, well above the runner-up, San
Francisco, where the average is $135.01 a night. Yet to judge from
the occupancy rates and waiting lists at many hotels, many visitors
who descend on New York to usher in 2000 are untroubled at having
to add a hefty premium for New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Hefty but apparently not extortionate, since few New York hotels
are charging more for rooms than the posted price, or rack rate,
according to Sean Hennessey, director of the PricewaterhouseCoopers
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, hardly any hotels are charging less than the
posted rate, which, throughout the hotel industry, seldom bears
more relationship to reality than the sticker price on new cars.
And almost 90 percent of the city's hotels require a three- or
four-day stay over New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   But a sizable number of Manhattan hotels that put together
expensive packages for the New Year have not sold out, Hennessey
said. While some of them have recently lowered the price of their
packages, ``the difficulty now,'' he said, ``is finding time to get
the word out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rather than end up with even a single empty room on New Year's
Eve, many of those hotels have recently discounted those rooms
heavily. Last week, for example, Central Park Inter-Continental New
York listed its available rooms with Priceline.com, dropping its
posted $389 daily rate to $250.
</P>
<P>
   For $550 a night based on a two-night minimum stay, some rooms
are still available in the Crowne Plaza in Times Square; for an
additional $550 per person, the hotel's Samplings restaurant on the
second floor offers a six-course meal with champagne, as well as a
ringside seat of the ball descending from atop the building at 1
Times Square. Hotel Reservations Network and other consolidators,
which buy blocks of rooms in many cities and sell them at discount,
still have some rooms available in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the Inter-Continental at 48th Street and Lexington Avenue,
which is charging $449 a night for a two-night minimum, is
virtually sold out. So is the 1,946-room Marriott Marquis Hotel,
despite charging $2,000 for a four-night stay.
</P>
<P>
   More foreign guests than usual for this time of year are booked
at the Marquis, in the heart of Times Square, which this year,
according to the New York Convention and Visitors Bureau, will be
the site of the biggest party in the square's 95-year history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
