<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LOUIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JUSTLY HARSH PUNISHMENT FOR VOLPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Dec. 15:
</P>
<P>
   Short of murder, it is hard to imagine a crime more vicious than
the torture Justin Volpe inflicted on Abner Louima. The corrosive
effect of Volpe's crimes on trust between New York City police and
many communities may take years to mend. The suffering he caused
Louima and his family cannot be fully measured. The 30-year
sentence imposed by Federal District Judge Eugene Nickerson will
not heal those wounds, but it sends a strong message to law
enforcement officers that police brutality will face severe
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Volpe admitted to violating Louima's civil rights by
sexually assaulting him with a stick in a Brooklyn precinct station
bathroom. Nickerson's decision to sentence him to 30 years, though
less than the life sentence recommended by the federal probation
department, seems a sound application of the complex federal
sentencing guidelines. It has been accepted by the federal
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The offense level of Volpe's crime, as calculated by probation
officers under federal sentencing rules, was high enough to warrant
a life sentence. That was based, in part, on the crime involved,
the brutality and sexual nature of the attack, the fact that Volpe
was a police officer and that Louima was under arrest and
handcuffed at the time of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   But Nickerson removed from consideration an
obstruction-of-justice element, which was based on Volpe's threat
to kill Louima shortly after the attack. The judge ruled that
obstruction could be counted as an aggravating factor in sentencing
only if the obstruction took place during the investigation or
prosecution of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The judge further reduced the offense level, and therefore the
sentence imposed, because Volpe is likely to be held in harsh,
segregated prison conditions to protect him from abuse by other
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Three other officers, Charles Schwarz, Thomas Wiese and Thomas
Bruder, will face a second trial next month for allegedly
conspiring to obstruct justice in attempting to cover up Schwarz's
role in the assault. Schwarz, who was convicted in June of
violating Louima's civil rights, plans to appeal because Volpe has
belatedly said that Schwarz was not in the bathroom during the
assault. These questions will be played out in further court
actions. The Volpe sentencing does not end the case, but does show
that a measure of justice has been achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
