<HEADLINE>
HULL, KYL, MC CAIN DECRY MONUMENTS `BY DECREE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Gov. Jane Hull and members of Arizona's
congressional delegation are blasting proposals to create two
national monuments in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But their objections may be too late.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton hinted Tuesday, Dec. 14, that he likely will
sign an executive order soon that would protect 1 million acres
northwest of the Grand Canyon and 70,000 acres north of Phoenix
from uranium mining and urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving these lands national-monument status would ensure they
would be passed along to future generations, healthy and whole,''
Clinton told a gathering of environmental leaders in the Roosevelt
Room of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The setting was significant. The room is named for President
Theodore Roosevelt, who pushed through Congress the 1906
Antiquities Act, which gives the president the power to declare
national monuments to protect any land that has historic,
scientific or archaeological significance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton described the proposed Grand Canyon-Parashant National
Monument _ nearly the size of the adjacent 1.1-million-acre Grand
Canyon National Park _ a place of ``stunning canyons and lonely
buttes, shaped by the hand of God over millions of years.''
</P>
<P>
   And the president called the proposed Agua Fria National
Monument - in the rolling hills east of Interstate 17 between Black
Canyon City and Cordes Junction - ``a desert region in the shadow
of rapidly expanding Phoenix.'' &QL; 
In an exclusive interview Sunday, Dec. 12, with The Arizona
Republic, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said that Clinton likely
would act on his recommendation to create the two Arizona
monuments, and two others in California, within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Dec. 13, Hull called a press conference to denounce
Babbitt's proposal, saying that the plan bypasses the involvement
of Arizonans and could harm the state's economy by reducing the
amount of productive land in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Dec. 13, Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., said he is writing
a letter urging Clinton not to go forward with the proposal, saying
it amounts to ``government by decree.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was voicing support for Babbitt's recommendation,
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. and a leading GOP candidate for president
in 2000, suggested that Babbitt is breaking his pledge of
``cooperation and commitment'' to work with Congress and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``His recent statement indicates that he is deliberately taking
into his own hands a decision that should be made by the state and
the Congress, with support of the Arizona people,'' McCain said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at &QL; 
steve.yozwiak(at)arizonarepublic.com &QL; 
or at (602) 444-8810. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
