<HEADER>
A9267 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ELLIOTT-CHRISTMAS-COL     12-14 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIOTT-CHRISTMAS-COLLECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCK ELLIOTT JR., THE MAN WHO COLLECTED CHRISTMAS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DINITIA SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is a man obsessed with Christmas. Jock Elliott
Jr., 79, retired chairman of the advertising firm of Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather, has been collecting Christmas books and mementos for more
than 40 years. He now has 3,000 objects, most of them the first of
something: the first printed picture of Santa descending a chimney,
from The New-York Mirror in 1841; the first Christmas card, from
1843; the book in which the words ``Merry'' and ``Christmas'' first
appeared together, in ``An Itinerary,'' a travel book by Fynes
Moryson Gent, in 1617.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Elliott keeps them all in his country house in Cross
River, N.Y., but now other fans of Christmas can see about 150 of
his objects, through Jan. 29, at the Grolier Club, a club for book
collectors, at 47 East 60th Street in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But why the obsession? Maybe it is because Elliott, who has no
children, is on a Proustian journey to recapture the Christmases of
his own childhood.
</P>
<P>
   There was more snow in those days, Elliott said as he gave a
recent tour of the exhibit. His family's house, at 220 East 62nd
Street, was ``a fairyland,'' he said; the lights on the Christmas
tree reflected brilliantly off the mirrored walls in the second
floor hallway. When he and his baby brother Osborn, who grew up to
become editor of Newsweek, woke up, there were ``early morning
presents'' at the foot of their beds to keep them quiet, Elliott
said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's father was an investment counselor, and his mother
sold real estate. It was the Depression, but so plentiful were the
presents he and his brother received when they were boys, Elliott
said, that they were displayed for a week afterward. Elliott
remembered how he and his brother worried about the ``old family
retainer,'' his mother's maid, not having presents. So they used
their pocket money to buy rubber bands and paper clips to stuff
into her stocking.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a mystery at the heart of Jock Elliott's
Christmas: that his mother, who ``grew up in a broken family,''
never talked about her own childhood Christmases. There was no
mention of ``the secret presents, the carol singing, the bulging
stocking, the glittering tree,'' Elliott writes in the exhibit's
catalog. ``She must have been a lonely little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's Christmas collection is a social history of the
holiday in England and America. It reminds one that Christmas is an
invented occasion. Elliott points out that pagan cultures had
festivals at the time of the winter solstice. The Romans had the
Saturnalia, in honor of Saturn, the harvest god, during which there
was much drinking and rowdiness. Most scholars agree that Jesus was
not born on Dec. 25, 1,999 years ago; some think it was more like 4
or 5 B.C. The Christian holiday developed as an incentive for
converts who were reluctant to give up winter revelries.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest item in Elliott's collection is a leaf from a Book of
Hours from 1430, before the invention of movable type, showing the
Adoration of the Magi. There is also a leaf from a book printed by
William Caxton of the story of the Nativity, and a volume of
Milton's poems, from 1645, probably a first edition, including
``Hymn on the Morning of Christ's Nativity.''
</P>
<P>
   The English Puritans put a damper on Christmas. In 1644, Oliver
Cromwell banned the celebration. Elliott's collection includes
books and tracts attacking and defending the holiday. One, written
in 1647, by someone who dared use only his initials, ``T.H.,''
reads: ``This very good time of Christ's birth some men do not
greatly desire to have this day sanctified with thanksgiving, nor
yet their poor kindred and poor neighbors treated with Christmas
mirth and love, but I hope these men will change their judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Christmas as it is in America, a time of familial togetherness,
did not come into being until the middle of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Nissenbaum, a historian, has written that in New York
City, there was originally little distinction between Christmas and
New Year's celebrations. In his book ``The Battle for Christmas''
(Alfred A. Knopf, 1996), he writes that immigrants, workers and
members of the lower classes were noted for their rowdiness during
the Christmas week. The modern Christmas, Nissenbaum said, was an
invention of the upper classes, to curb those excesses.
</P>
<P>
   A milestone in its beginning, he said, was Clement Clarke
Moore's ``Visit From St. Nicholas'' (``The Night Before
Christmas''), published in 1823. Elliott has several books
containing the poem, including an 1844 collection by Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Around the time of Moore's poem, the first Christmas card
appeared, in England. It was commissioned in 1843 by Henry Cole, a
founder of the Victoria and Albert Museum, and illustrated by John
Calcott Horsley. The card is a triptych. In the center is a scene
of a family celebration, with everyone, including the children,
drinking a toast. On either side are panels showing the poor being
given food and clothing. Elliott's card is the only one inscribed
and dated by Horsley still in private hands, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of the 19th century, Christmas had become a craze
on both sides of the Atlantic. But Christmas trees became popular
only after 1848, when The Illustrated London News published a
drawing of Queen Victoria, Prince Albert and their children
gathered around a tree hung with ornaments. That image was
transformed for New World consumption when it appeared in Godey's
Lady's Book in 1850, democratized with the removal of the Queen's
coronet, and Albert's mustache, sash and royal insignia.
</P>
<P>
   The political cartoonist Thomas Nast created the modern image of
Santa Claus, and Elliott's collection contains several examples of
illustrations of Santa as a roly-poly figure with a long white
beard.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott also has five first editions of ``A Christmas Carol in
Prose. Being a Ghost Story of Christmas'' by Charles Dickens, from
1844, with illustrations by John Leech. One book, Elliott said, is
notable for its ``defective'' title page, which has no title,
author's name, place of publication or date. ``In the United
States, it was pirated,'' he said. ``He didn't get a penny for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of Dickens' book prompted Christmas books by William
Makepeace Thackeray, Hans Christian Andersen, Wilkie Collins and
Horatio Alger. Elliott rounds out his collection with a grab bag of
books, including ``The Cultivation of Christmas Trees'' by T.S.
Eliot and ``Christmas Holiday'' by Somerset Maugham, with an
inscription to his lover and adopted son, Alan Searle. There are
also copies of Edna St. Vincent Millay's ``Ballad of the
Harp-Weaver,'' and Elliott's favorite piece of prose, ``A Child's
Christmas in Wales'' by Dylan Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   For Elliott, standing in the midst of it all, life seems just a
continuation from one Christmas to the next. He and his brother
still exchange ``early morning presents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott says he still has a Christmas stocking and it is six
feet long. ``My wife fills it up with socks and underwear,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott also wears Christmas suspenders, Christmas socks and a
nightshirt. Every Christmas, he reads his wife, Eleanor, ``The
Ballad of the Harp-Weaver.'' Afterward, Elliott said, ``we go to
sleep with a warm heart and a moist eye.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
