<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-WHITMAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS AND FOES AGREE: NEAR LOSS IN '90 WAS PIVOTAL EVENT FOR
BRADLEY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lede graf to make it `walk,' stead of `lark')  (jt) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It once seemed that the word failure was not a part
of Bill Bradley's lexicon. He had been a Rhodes Scholar, Olympic
gold medalist, two-time NBA champion and, on his first foray into
politics in 1978, the winner of a Senate seat from New Jersey. In
1984, during the Reagan landslide, he won re-election in a walk.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1990, when Bradley came within 3 percentage points of
losing his once safe bastion to an unknown, poorly financed
Republican named Christie Whitman, he was devastated. For weeks, he
wandered the state in a sullen funk, asking friends what had gone
wrong. Over coffee, Michael J. Breslin, a Hackensack, N.J., lawyer,
summed it up for him in one word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `the public thought you were arrogant,''' Breslin
recalled, referring to voters' anger with Bradley for not taking a
position on a $2.8 billion state tax increase that year. ``He
looked at me as if he was startled. Because he can't stand arrogant
people. I said, `Nobody's told you that?' And he said, `No, you're
the first guy to mention that word, arrogant.'''
</P>
<P>
   To many of his critics and supporters alike, the disastrous 1990
campaign _ both sides use the adjective _ represents the most
important event in Bradley's political life. Almost no one had
expected the race to be close, Bradley had widely been touted as
presidential contender and he outspent Whitman by 12-to-1. Yet he
nearly lost.
</P>
<P>
   The election he later called ``a terrible blow'' shook his
confidence in himself and his staff, triggering an intense bout of
introspection that helped change the course of his career, Bradley
and his friends say.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, he revamped his Washington staff and cut his ties
with some of his oldest political advisers. He removed his name
from the list of 1992 presidential contenders. His interest in the
Senate waned, and he began work on a memoir, ``Time Present, Time
Past,'' that eventually consumed more of his time than legislating.
By 1995, he had decided to retire, announcing in a now famous
speech that ``politics is broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, after two lucrative years of consulting, teaching and
lecturing, Bradley returned to the political arena as a candidate
for the Democratic presidential nomination. Yet as much as ever,
the 1990 race continues to color his view of politics, and his
critics' views of him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Bradley says, he relied too much on expensive pollsters
and consultants who failed to notice the electorate's fury. ``The
lesson of 1990,'' he said recently, ``is you can have too much
money in a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the race also helped him understand the importance of
listening more directly to voters, of speaking from his heart and
not worrying about the advice of handlers, of being bold. All are
lessons he claims to have incorporated into his current race, where
he has campaigned against conventional politics and made campaign
finance reform a central issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would never be where he is today if not for 1990,'' said
Michael Kaye, Bradley's media adviser in 1990. ``He had to fail. To
see that that could happen, and that he could be humiliated. And I
think 1990 totally liberated him. He said to himself, `From this
point on, I'm going to do it the way I want to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans say they took a somewhat different lesson from
1990. To them, Bradley's refusal to distance himself from Gov. Jim
Florio's tax plan _ the issue Whitman built her campaign around _
simply proved that he was too aloof to understand the anger of
average voters and too regimented to adjust when he finally did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting him to blow me out of the water any day, which
he could have done with just a couple of sentences distancing
himself from that tax hike,'' said Whitman, who is now in her
second term as New Jersey's governor. ``But the fact that he didn't
became a bigger issue. If you are going to represent the people of
New Jersey, you have to respond to their concerns, you have to
listen to them. He just never responded.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``The impression I got was that once he locks onto a
game plan, he won't change it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Though Whitman entered the Senate race in January 1990, the
campaign really began in March, when Florio, a first-term Democrat,
unveiled his plan to close a yawning state budget gap with a $2.8
billion tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, coming in the midst of a spreading economic
downturn, touched off a storm of protests. Angry homeowners rallied
outside the statehouse, ``Impeach Florio'' bumper stickers spread
like brush fire and radio talk shows devoted hours to railing
against the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Florio released his proposal, Whitman's campaign
strategists had mapped out a plan for attacking Bradley as an
out-of-touch Washington insider more concerned about global affairs
and presidential politics than his home state. The tax plan
provided more fodder than they ever had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, Whitman began demanding that Bradley take a
position on the tax increase, which was in the news almost daily as
Florio pushed it through the legislature. To their delight, he
refused time and time again, saying that it was a state issue that
had no place in a U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this self-styled tax expert to say, `I have an opinion but
I'm not going to say it, I'm not going to tell you,' well, people
thought that was unbelievably arrogant,'' said Willliam Palatucci,
a New Jersey lawyer who was Whitman's principal political
consultant then.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, the tax issue raised some very difficult political
and personal problems. His aides say he really believed that it was
improper for him to weigh in on a state issue, even though he told
them privately that he thought the tax increase was ``too much, too
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   But more than that, Bradley felt deep loyalty to Florio, who had
bucked Democratic Party leaders by supporting Bradley in 1978 over
the state organization's favored Senate candidate. ``Some people
said we had to answer these Florio questions,'' said Bob McHugh,
Bradley's campaign press secretary at the time. ``But Bradley just
wasn't going to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, one of Bradley's closest political advisers, Douglas
Berman, his 1984 campaign manager, was Florio's state treasurer and
an architect of the tax increase. It would have been hard for
Bradley to criticize the plan without appearing to repudiate his
old friend, now the chief strategist for Bradley's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that a number of relatively inexperienced consultants
were running Bradley's 1990 campaign instead of Berman was an
indication to many people that Bradley was not too worried about
Whitman. Nicholas Donatiello, Bradley's 30-year-old Senate press
secretary, was the manager, though he had never run a campaign
before. Kaye, the media consultant, spent much of the year in Santa
Fe, N.M., and Los Angeles. And Joseph Peritz, a pollster, was a
specialist in consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a campaign people were anxious to run, because
expectations were sky high,'' Donatiello said in a recent
interview. ``You couldn't beat 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Bradley's friends also say he seemed to be more
interested in the 1992 presidential campaign than in his
re-election. Leading up to the 1990 campaign, he had spent $1
million on polling voters around the country and buying computer
equipment to analyze the data. He also raised much of his $12
million Senate war chest outside of New Jersey, particularly in
California, an indication that he was trying to create a national
base of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   All of those things fit neatly into Whitman's line of attack.
Yet by the fall, polls showed Bradley still leading her by 20
points or more. So his advisers maintained their cautious strategy
of refusing to engage Whitman and running positive advertisements
about Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin Optional material)
</P>
<P>
   But even those commercials seemed to fall flat. One spot
featured Bradley in his Senate office, kicking his sneaker-clad
feet up onto his desk; another showed him sinking a basketball shot
before cheering students. In both cases, the ads seemed oddly out
of sync with the bad mood of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked frivolous,'' Kaye said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also often seemed slow or ineffective at responding to
Whitman's repeated thrusts on issues, ranging from his campaign
contributions to his environmental record. When she challenged him
to take a position on flag burning, he spent two weeks studying the
matter before announcing that he considered it a constitutional
right.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional material)
</P>
<P>
   By the last two weeks of the campaign, Bradley, who had been in
Washington for Senate votes during much of the fall, finally
returned home for full-time campaigning. For the first time, he
heard voters' anger in person. Soon after, his campaign ran its
first negative ad against Whitman, accusing her of supporting taxes
as a Somerset County freeholder. He defended the ad with a line he
still uses today, ``Get an elbow, give an elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   By and large, however, Bradley did little to alter his strategy
down the stretch. Yet more and more voters were switching their
allegiances to Whitman every day, and Bradley had no knowledge of
it. His own campaign had stopped doing tracking polls in October,
confident that their big lead would hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing, but no one smelled the coffee,'' McHugh said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Following the election, Bradley became withdrawn, his friends
and former aides say. He blamed his advisers, himself and even
voters. ``For many months to come,'' he wrote in ``Time Present,
Time Past'' (Knopf, 1996), ``I looked at each person who approached
me as if he or she had voted against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, as his disappointment lifted, he came to look at the
1990 election as ``the best thing that ever happened in my
political career,'' he wrote in his memoirs. ``It forced me to face
up to what I needed to change, both organizationally and
personally. It forced me to go deeper into my emotions and to speak
from values and convictions in ways I had avoided before.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's friends say they think Bradley has become more playful
and unbuttoned now as a result of 1990, doing little things like
grabbing the glasses off Larry King's face or asking Sam Donaldson
whether he ever smoked marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   But some also wonder whether he completely understands what
happened in 1990, and whether he has accepted his own role in his
poor showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt betrayed,'' said one friend. ``And he blamed everyone.
He saw how vulnerable he was to people giving him advice. I felt
bad for him because I saw how wounded he was. But in the end, he's
the boss. They gave him bad advice, but he's the one who took it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
