r s BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     12-14 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH STATE FOCUSED ON VOLLEYBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ They are young, attractive, athletic, bright and
brimming with energy.
</P>
<P>
   They are in one of the storied vacation spots in the world, an
idyllic paradise where there are all sorts of alluring diversions.
</P>
<P>
   They have been staying at a hotel in Waikiki for a week, and you
would figure that by now they would have sampled the hip night
spots and at least paid homage to that shrine on the beach, Duke's.
</P>
<P>
   But forget it.
</P>
<P>
   The women on the Long Beach State volleyball team haven't
partied, danced, or engaged in the kind of frenzied fun those in
their late teens or early twenties are known to routinely do.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they haven't even gone out at nights except on those
two notable occasions last week when they took care of business in
the NCAA Regionals against Colorado State and Texas A &AMP; M.
</P>
<P>
   They have been eating their dinners early and by 8 o'clock have
been in their rooms studying for their final exams, which they've
taken here the past few days under the watchful eye of a Long Beach
State proctor named Armando Contreras.
</P>
<P>
   Their coach, Brian Gimmillaro, doesn't even impose a curfew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never have had to have one,'' says Gimmillaro proudly. ``I've
never once had a bed check. There's not a person on this team who
would go out and fool around.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just not in these athletes' makeup. And they make a lot
of the rules themselves. They are able to govern themselves. From
the time they get at Long Beach, I instill in my players the
importance of being responsible and trustworthy. One of the things
I've been most proud about our program has been the discipline of
the players. And I think this discipline is reflected in the way
they play on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a mild surprise that the defending NCAA champion 49ers
have reached the Final Four for the seventh time in 11 years,
especially since Gimmillaro lost his Player of the Year setter,
Misty May, and two other stalwarts, Jessica Alvarado and Benishe
Dillard, from his 1998 team.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers struggled early in the season with the heralded 6-1
newcomer from Colorado, Brittany Hochevar, as the setter, and
Gimmillaro, reluctantly, turned to the 5-7 sophomore academic
scholar, Keri Nishimoto.
</P>
<P>
   The insertion of Nishimoto into the starting lineup turned the
Long Beach season instantly around.
</P>
<P>
   Nishimoto started gathering assists in bushels as her deft
passes began resulting in a steady stream of kills by teammates
like Cheryl Weaver, Tayyiba Haneef, Brandy Barrett, Anja Grabovac
and Veronica Walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people didn't think we'd be here,'' says
Gimmillaro, whose team faces the unpleasant task of playing No.
2-ranked Stanford Thursday evening. ``But we've just been getting
better and better and better. I just wish we had more time. If we
could be together for one more month, I don't think anyone would be
able to beat us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Keri Nishimoto could run this team, but I didn't know
if she could be physical enough to take us where we now are.
Obviously, she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Gimmillaro says his team will face its greatest challenge of the
season against the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think Stanford should have been the No. 1 seed
because it beat more teams in the Top 10 than Penn State did,''
says Gimmillaro. ``Stanford is a very tall and talented team. It
beat UOP easily, and you know UOP beat us twice. So there's no
doubt we're going to have our hands full.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can the 49ers beat Stanford?'' I asked Gimmillaro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to be at our best,'' he said. ``We're
going to have to play as we did against Texas A &AMP; M, which I
thought was our best match of the season. We're going to have to
make good passes and not make many errors. It's going to be
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these 49ers have had it tough the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have had to had to live in the shadow of last year's
undefeated team that I think is the best to ever play college
volleyball,'' says Gimmillaro. ``It's been difficult for this team
to develop its own identity. The expectations at Long Beach have
become so great, but I think this team now, finally, has its own
identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his team, Brian Gimmillaro has not remained in Honolulu
the entire time.
</P>
<P>
   He and wife Dania returned to Long Beach on Saturday to spend a
couple of days with their son and daughter, and then he flew back
here on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't worried that his players might stray during his
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so focused both on their studies and on volleyball
that they don't really have time for anything else,'' says
Gimmillaro. ``Oh, they did go to the mall for a couple of hours
over the weekend. They also were going to go snorkeling, but it
rained and the event was canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   There are so many differences between women and men athletics
aside from the physical contrasts.
</P>
<P>
   The women don't posture shamelessly and finger-point after
making positive plays.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do they fail drug tests, or get involved in robberies or
petty theft or other such shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think you would have no curfew and bed checks if your
team was comprised of men?'' I asked Gimmillaro.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Gimmillaro laughed heartily, thought a moment and said
firmly, ``No way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
