<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-HEALTH-1STLD-W     12-14 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-HEALTH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(890)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN UNVEILS HEALTH PLANCALLING FOR MODEST CHANGES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 4th and 5th grafs to correct and clarify cost of McCain's
health plan)  By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Calling the nation's health care system ``too
costly, too inaccessible and too bureaucratic,'' Sen. John McCain
on Tuesday set out a plan of ``tailored reforms'' ranging from a
federal program to help the low-income elderly pay for prescription
drugs to a limited right to sue health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech to the Charleston Rotary Club was part of an
effort by the Arizona Republican to capitalize on his surge in New
Hampshire by fleshing out his positions on issues. Health care _
and most particularly the soaring costs of prescription drugs _ has
emerged as one of the hottest topics on the campaign trail this
year, and until now it has been a policy arena largely dominated by
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our health care system today often fails to reflect our
values,'' McCain said, as he began two days of campaigning in one
of the key early primary states where he is hoping to upset the
Republican front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. ``Too many
Americans go to sleep at night desperately fearing illness or
injury to themselves or a family member because they are without
health insurance to pay their bills.''
</P>
<P>
   But even while he identified access to affordable, quality
health care as one of the most pressing problems facing American
families, McCain stopped well short of the kinds of more
far-reaching legislation that Vice President Al Gore, former Sen.
Bill Bradley and congressional Democrats are running on. Aides were
still calculating the cost of his program hours after his program.
On Tuesday night, they said his entire health care plan would cost
$7.6 billion when fully in effect in its fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   His plan for regulating health maintenance organizations would
extend a limited right to sue to consumers in managed health care
plans regulated by the federal government. But that would not
include allowing suits for punitive damages. His prescription drug
plan would offer federal funds to states that choose to participate
and match the amounts instead of making it a new benefit for all
Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed nothing resembling Bradley's call for a vast system
of subsidies and tax credits to insure all children and provide
access to affordable coverage to all adults, allowing anyone to buy
private insurance through the program that insures federal workers,
the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting there does not require some grand experiment in social
engineering,'' McCain said, ``or a death-by-a-thousand-cuts,
gradual government takeover of the health care system. We need only
to consult our values and enact tailored reforms that build on the
strengths of the current system.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's attempt to find an ideological middle ground was most
clear in his proposal for alleviating the spiraling costs of
prescription drugs to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has called for a broad expansion of the
federal Medicare program to add prescription drug coverage for up
to 39 million elderly and disabled Americans. Under his plan,
Medicare beneficiaries would pay a total of $110 billion in
premiums for drug coverage over the next decade, and the government
would put up $118 billion. Both Gore and Bradley have advocated a
Medicare benefit for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, by contrast, called Tuesday for a far more modest block
grant that would cost the federal government $5.1 billion across
five years, with matching funds put up by those states that choose
to participate in the program. Currently 14 states provide some
kind of drug cost assistance to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   While Medicaid currently covers most prescription drug costs for
the elderly poor, McCain's aides said his plan would help an
estimated 10 million of the near-poor elderly with incomes of up to
two times the poverty level of $8,240 for an individual and $11,060
per couple.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said that he would create regional pilot projects
costing $1 billion over three years to test regional programs to
provide assistance to the elderly regardless of income when they
face catastrophic drug costs ``that can cruelly snatch away a
life's savings.
</P>
<P>
   The speech gave McCain a new opportunity to tie his signature
issue _ the overhaul of the campaign finance laws _ to broader
social concerns. ``Taking the $100,000 special interest checks out
of politics is the gateway through which all other reforms
including the reform of our health care system must pass,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed both parties' fidelity to special interests for
congressional gridlock on regulating managed care. ``Republicans
want to protect the insurance companies from lawsuits,'' he said.
``The Democrats want to let the trial lawyers sue anyone for
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain found a middle ground, on regulating managed care,
calling for more protections than Republican legislation that
passed the Senate, but stopping short of the right to sue contained
in a bipartisan bill that the House passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you or a loved one is sick or injured and wrongfully turned
away for care, you must be assured the ability to resolve that
problem rapidly through a fair and independent review process,'' he
said. ``But if you're not satisfied, no American should be denied
the ability to seek redress through the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference later, McCain said he would like to see
independent state panels set up to review cases where consumers are
denied care by a health maintenance organization. His aides said
that under his proposal the 48 million Americans in the managed
care plans that fall under federal regulation would be given a
somewhat broader right to sue than they currently have, if they
were unsatisfied with the review. Currently those in such federally
regulated managed care plans are allowed to sue but only for the
cost of denied medical care.
</P>
<P>
   They would be bared from receiving punitive damages. But they
would be allowed to seek unlimited damages for economic suffering
like lost wages. Dan Schnur, the senator's communications director
said McCain would also propose legislation to put a $250,000 cap on
noneconomic damages, such as awards for pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate debated managed care regulation earlier this
year, McCain voted for the Republican bill, which did not include
an expanded right to sue. His aides said he had supported the
legislation because he did not want to see the issue die in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   To extend health insurance coverage to more of the nation's 44
million uninsured, McCain like many Republicans called for an
expansion of medical savings accounts, tax-free accounts that can
be used to cover medical costs, and for a more general tax
reduction to give people more money to buy insurance. He also
called for a more aggressive effort to encourage small businesses
to band together in insurance purchasing pools, as well as a
greater effort to enroll children in a federal program that was
established two years ago for children in families not poor enough
for Medicaid but not affluent enough to buy private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech made him the first Republican to set out a
detailed health care plan. Bush so far has spoken only generally of
extending coverage to more of the uninsured and pointed to the
program in Texas for regulating HMO's.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been more hotly debated in the Democratic
presidential contest because of Bradley's call for a vast system of
subsidies and tax credits that would cost $65 billion a year. Gore
has aggressively picked apart the plan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On another front, McCain on Tuesday defended the military's
``don't ask don't tell policy'' toward gay members of the service,
saying ``this policy has worked.'' He criticized Gore for calling
on Monday for the outright elimination of the program, saying the
vice president should not take a position on the issue without
first consulting with high-ranking Pentagon officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
