<DOCNO> NYT19991214.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-COLEY-NY     12-14 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-COLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA AND COLEY STAR IN THE LATEST BOXING SOAP OPERA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oscar De La Hoya and Derrell Coley sat on stage at
the Theater in Madison Square Garden Tuesday surrounded by the set
from ``A Christmas Carol.'' The two fighters were there to promote
their bout at the Garden on Feb. 26, but they are also players in
another drama that has been unfolding since De La Hoya lost his WBC
welterweight title to Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   The latest soap opera in boxing can be called ``As the
Welterweights Turn.'' By the time the run of it is complete, De La
Hoya and Coley may not meet in the ring in February, and Coley may
actually be a pawn in a bigger game to get De La Hoya and Trinidad
back in the ring for a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's news conference, Dan Goossen, Coley's promoter,
had his lawyer send threatening letters to the promoter Bob Arum,
the president of Top Rank Inc.; to De La Hoya's promoter; to HBO,
which will televise the De La Hoya-Coley bout, and to Madison
Square Garden. The letters said to stop the fight or expect to be
sued.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen contends that Arum is interfering with his exclusive
promotional contract with Coley by signing him to an agreement to
fight De La Hoya. Goossen said Arum went behind his back and dealt
directly with Coley to get him signed to fight De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Arum has done as it relates to Coley is tantamount to one
baseball owner tampering with another baseball owner's player,''
Goossen said. ``In our industry we don't have a commissioner to
uphold someone's rights. Arum knew we had an exclusive contract
with Coley. Coley knew it; his manager Barry Linde knew it and his
attorney Milt Chwasky knew it and HBO knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chwasky said that Goossen was not acting in the best interest of
Coley and had dragged his feet on negotiating a deal for Coley to
fight Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Coley is the mandatory contender for the WBC title that Trinidad
holds. Chwasky said that Goossen was also slow in trying to work
out an agreement for Coley to fight De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way he'll win his lawsuit,'' said Chwasky, who
became Coley's attorney two weeks ago when Coley's manager, Linde,
called him. ``How can he win when he's exploiting the fighter?''
</P>
<P>
   Chwasky said that Goossen was offered $250,000 to allow Coley to
fight De La Hoya. Goossen turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about money,'' Goossen said. ``This is about right
and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Goossen had negotiated a contract with promoter Don King for
another one of his clients, David Reid, the WBA superwelterweight
champion, to fight Trinidad. But that fight was postponed when
Coley insisted that he would not step aside and relinquish his
right to challenge Trinidad for the welterweight title in order for
Reid to fight Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen had his lawyer, Jethro Eisenstein, file a lawsuit in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan Tuesday against HBO on behalf of
Reid, asking that a judge stop HBO from saying that it has the
right of first refusal on the Trinidad-Reid bout. Eisenstein said
that because Goossen is not the lead promoter for that bout, HBO's
contract with Reid is not in effect for Trinidad-Reid. King,
Trinidad's promoter, is the lead promoter for that bout.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen's actions came on the heels of a failed meeting between
Arum, HBO executives, King, Trinidad and his advisers to reignite
negotiations for a De La Hoya-Trinidad rematch. Arum said King and
Trinidad were insisting that the De La Hoya-Coley match come after
a rematch between De La Hoya and Trinidad. But Arum refused to go
along with that and the meeting ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goossen did this at the behest of King for whatever Byzantine
reason,'' Arum said regarding Goossen's threats to stop the De La
Hoya-Coley bout.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, all the participants involved in De La
Hoya-Coley were putting on a happy face at Tuesday's announcement.
It will be De La Hoya's first fight in New York since he knocked
out Jesse James Leija in a lightweight bout on Dec. 15, 1995. De La
Hoya drew 16,000 fans for that fight.
</P>
<P>
   Coley was beaming at the opportunity to fight De La Hoya, who
had ducked him for almost two years when De La Hoya had the title.
It didn't seem to matter to Coley that De La Hoya doesn't have a
title anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for this opportunity for 19 months; is this
really Oscar?'' Coley asked looking over at De La Hoya. ``Somebody
should check his ID, because I haven't seen the guy in 19 months.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya flew from Miami where he is recording a record album.
Although he was still glum about having lost his title to Trinidad
on Sept. 18, De La Hoya promised to be more aggressive in his fight
against Coley. He said the Trinidad fight had forced him to change
his way of thinking and his way of training.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be an action-packed event,'' De La Hoya said.
``I'm going to come out with such anger. No more boxing on my toes.
It's sad that no one appreciates that skill of boxing anymore. If
it pleases the fans, I will go back to my old style and just duke
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
