<SLUG> BC-NY-TERRORISM-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS JAIL ISOLATION CAUSED SUSPECT'S DECLINE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (rk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Harvard Medical School psychiatrist who specializes
in the effects of solitary confinement on prisoners has concluded
that a defendant accused of having links to suspected terrorist
Osama bin Laden has been so mentally devastated by his imprisonment
that he may not be able to assist meaningfully in his own defense,
newly disclosed records show.
</P>
<P>
   The examination of the defendant, Wadih el-Hage, which was
conducted at the request of his lawyers, comes as a federal judge
in Manhattan has shown increasing concern about the impact of the
highly restrictive jail conditions under which el-Hage and five
other terrorism suspects are being held.
</P>
<P>
   The government, which asserted that el-Hage and the others might
still be involved in planning acts of terrorism, had invoked a
rarely used rule to hold the suspects in isolation, barring them
from virtually all contact or communication with outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Stuart Grassian, who examined el-Hage for four hours on
Sept. 3 in the Metropolitan Correctional Center in lower Manhattan,
said that more than one year of virtually complete isolation has
taken a devastating mental toll on el-Hage, who last lived in
Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``His day is almost entirely empty of structure or variety,''
Grassian wrote, ``and when he thinks, he finds himself endlessly
ruminating on the injustice and indignities he must endure.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor's 18-page report, made public on Monday, cited
repeated strip searches and constant surveillance of el-Hage by
guards, his inability to remain in touch with his family or to
practice Islam, and the ``continual ringing of the telephone near
his cell and the flashlights shining in his face at night.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, federal prosecutors, who have resisted
relaxing the terms of the suspects' confinement, made an unexpected
concession, telling Judge Leonard B. Sand of U.S. District Court in
Manhattan they were willing to allow el-Hage to move to a larger
cell and to have another defendant in the terrorism case as a
cellmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suggestion of not requiring isolation of the defendants,''
Sand said, ``which I am hearing for the first time today, is
something that should be explored. It seems to be a constructive
notion.''
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatric report on el-Hage is part of a mammoth bail
application newly filed by el-Hage's lawyers. The application was
released after Sand unsealed several pages that contained grand
jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The filing, totaling more than 400 pages, offers a wealth of new
detail about el-Hage, whom prosecutors say was a former personal
secretary to bin Laden, who is blamed for the bombing of two
American embassies in Africa in August 1998. Prosecutors have
charged that el-Hage helped bin Laden set up front companies in
Africa, and participated in his broad terrorist conspiracy to
attack American citizens abroad.
</P>
<P>
   El-Hage has been charged with perjury, in addition to the
conspiracy charges. He has not been accused of a direct role in the
embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania, which killed more than 200
people and wounded thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The new filing shows that el-Hage, who has pleaded not guilty,
admitted going to work for bin Laden _ ``It was bin Laden's idea,''
he testified before a grand jury on Sept. 24, 1997 _ but only in
what he contended were legitimate business ventures.
</P>
<P>
   El-Hage's lawyers, Sam A. Schmidt and Joshua L. Dratel, argue in
their papers that the available evidence contradicts the
government's assertions that el-Hage was involved in violent acts
that prosecutors have previously cited as a basis for holding him
before trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the government comes out with something, whether sealed
or in public, to show otherwise,'' Schmidt said Tuesday, ``I think
there's no basis for the judge to find that he's presently a danger
to the national security, or to the community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
