<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-14 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-FUNDRAISING-HUANG-1ST     12-14 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-HUANG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL TO QUESTION DEMOCRATIC FUND-RAISER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd graf to correct name of congressional committee)  (rk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of investigations, partisan vitriol and
accusations of stonewalling leveled at the Clinton White House,
Republicans in Congress will at last get what they have long
sought, a hearing on Wednesday to publicly question a Democratic
fund-raiser at the epicenter of the 1996 campaign fund-raising
controversy: John Huang.
</P>
<P>
   Protected by a grant of immunity, Huang is scheduled to begin
three days of testimony at the House Government Reform Committee
led by its Republican chairman, Rep. Dan Burton of Indiana _ an
event that Republicans hope will prove uncomfortable for President
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans may be disappointed. In Huang's opening statement, a
copy of which was provided to The New York Times, the former
fund-raiser said he knew of no wrongdoing by either Clinton or
Gore. Huang said he might have escaped ``the terrible ordeal'' had
he implicated them, but, he said: ``I never had a basis upon which
to do so. In fact, I maintain very high regard for each of these
dedicated men.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Huang pleaded guilty to engaging in a conspiracy to
defraud the Federal Election Commission by arranging for employees
of the Lippo Group, an Indonesian-based conglomerate run by the
powerful Riady family, to be reimbursed for contributions in the
1992 and the 1994 elections. He was sentenced to probation and
agreed to cooperate with the federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Huang played a significant role in the 1996 campaign. Of the
$2.8 million in improper contributions that the Democrats were
forced to return after the 1996 election, almost 80 percent were
raised by Huang and Yah Lin Trie, both of whom were longtime
friends of Clinton and raised large sums based on their personal
relationships with the president. In 1997, when the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee began its investigation, Huang
refused to testify, invoking his constitutional right against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, White House officials repeated their frequently
expressed skepticism about the objectivity of Burton's panel and
questioned its impartiality in questioning Huang. Jim Kennedy, a
White House spokesman, said: ``Three things in life are certain.
Death, taxes and partisan hearings chaired by Dan Burton.''
</P>
<P>
   But Huang's testimony _ re-examining the frenzy of Democratic
fund-raising in 1996 _ comes at a time when campaign finance issues
seem to be catching fire in the presidential race and could help
sharpen demands for changes in the country's system of raising
money for federal candidates and parties.
</P>
<P>
   Those demands are already central issues for insurgent
presidential candidates such as Bill Bradley, the former Democratic
senator of New Jersey, and John McCain, the Republican senator from
Arizona. In an unusual step, Bradley and McCain have scheduled a
joint appearance on Thursday in New Hampshire to pledge that if
nominated, they would call on their parties to refuse unrestricted
contributions for party-building activities known as soft money.
Many of the large contributions raised by Huang in 1996 flowed into
the Democratic National Committee in soft-money checks.
</P>
<P>
   In his written testimony, Huang does not suggest that he will
add important new details to his activities, which have been the
subject of lengthy Senate, House and Justice Department
investigations. Last month, Burton's committee released lengthy
notes taken by FBI agents in their investigation of campaign
finance matters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in his prepared remarks, Huang, who once worked at the
Commerce Department and later at the Democratic National Committee,
portrayed himself as a victim of partisan politics, a rising tide
of anti-Asian sentiment and grossly unfair news accounts, including
reports of lawmakers who falsely accused him of economic espionage.
``People seeking publicity have lied about me repeatedly in the
press and even before this committee without consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted that he had made mistakes. ``Embarrassed and
saddened though I am by the unfortunate attention my conduct and
notoriety brought upon my community, the dated and isolated
offenses, which I have openly acknowledged, will not deter me from
my careerlong efforts to promote understanding between the citizens
of the United States and those of China, Taiwan and the rest of
Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY CAN HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Investigations have found that Huang first met Clinton in the
1980s, through a mutual friend, James Riady, the head of the Lippo
Group. By 1992, when Huang was employed by Lippo Bank in
California, he began to raise money for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's election, Huang used his contacts to get a job
at the Commerce Department. In 1995, as the president's re-election
campaign began, Huang left Commerce to begin fund-raising for the
Democrats, although some party officials had reservations from the
start about whether Huang might be raising money from contributors
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout 1996, Huang organized fund-raising events, some
attended by foreign contributors and Clinton. Huang and another
fund-raiser, Maria Hsia, organized one such event on April 29,
1997, at the Hsi Lai temple in Hacienda Heights, Calif., that was
attended by Gore, whose shifting statements about his knowledge of
the purpose of the event dogged the vice president for many months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
