<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOARING OIL PRICES AREN'T SLOWING ECONOMIC GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most gratifying developments of 1999 has been the
failure of soaring oil prices to slow U.S. economic growth or
weaken the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Although oil prices have generally more than doubled compared
with this time last year as a result of OPEC's decision last spring
to curb output, the world's economic system hasn't showed any
appreciable sign of distress. Unlike during the 1973 and 1979
shocks, there has been no sign of incipient hyperinflation or any
hint of decelerating economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Americans have seen substantially higher petrol
prices at the pump, but not nearly high enough to force the sort of
consumption trade-offs that hurt a consumer-driven economy. In
fact, as one industry analyst recently noted, the
inflation-adjusted price of gasoline is still below its level of
the early '80s, after the second oil shock.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's Consumer Price Index report illustrated the relatively
benign effect of higher oil prices. The index rose only 0.1 percent
in November, and the price of gasoline actually showed a decline.
So far this year, the index is rising at a rate of 2.7 percent.
While this is higher than last year's 1.6 percent consumer
inflation rate, it's still relatively mild by postwar U.S.
experience.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? For one thing, according to a recent analysis by
The Economist, crude oil costs for most countries now account for a
much smaller share of overall petrol prices. The biggest
inflationary force when it comes to gas prices in recent years has
been tax increases, which have diluted the effect at the pump of
even large crude price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor, the analysis said, is the diminishing dependence
on oil in the world's richest countries. Energy conservation,
increased use of other fuels and a decline in the presence of
energy-intensive industries have led to reduced oil consumption.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development shows that if the average cost of oil in 1999 is double
1998's average cost, it will only increase the oil import bills of
the richest economies by 0.5 percent, or less, of gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   Another dynamic is the financial condition of the oil-exporting
countries. During the previous two oil shocks, they banked much of
their windfall profits because they had more money than they could
spend. Nowadays they're not so flush, and recycle their increased
income into the world economy by spending most of it.
</P>
<P>
   Last but not least, previous oil shocks occurred in tandem with
soaring worldwide commodity prices, which intensified the
inflationary potential. The Economist, however, says its commodity
price index is generally unchanged over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say the world is out of the woods when it comes to
energy costs. Rather, it's to put the situation into perspective.
While the generation that survived the gas lines and hyperinflation
of the '70s has been conditioned to dread oil price increases, the
world has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Rising petroleum costs are still an inflationary factor, but not
nearly the destructive force they were a generation ago. Meantime,
we may have more to fear from government's revenue enhancers on
this score than we do from OPEC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
