<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-ROCKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS ROLL OVER ROCKETS, 101-90 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For a while, the interchangeable Knicks looked on in
half amazement tonight as Patrick Ewing stepped onto the floor as
if he were slipping into a time machine.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was not the struggling, huffing vision he had been for the
first two games of his return. He was the Ewing of his youth as he
prowled around the paint and produced points by the handfuls in the
first quarter against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ewing stepped aside, and allowed younger players like
Latrell Sprewell to take over. After Ewing scored 14 of his 20
points in the first quarter, Sprewell delivered 11 of his 22 in the
third period to form a New York combination that overwhelmed the
depleted Rockets, 101-90, at the Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston added 20 points in a well-rounded Knick victory.
It was the Knicks' sixth victory in their last seven games, and
their third in a row since the return of Ewing. After shutting down
the easy 3-point attempts the Rockets (7-16) had early in the game
to remain annoyingly close, the Knicks (14-9) grabbed a 15-point
lead midway through the fourth quarter and rolled from there.
</P>
<P>
   By a twist of lockout season scheduling fate, the Knicks last
season did not have to face a Rockets' team that had three players
selected among the top 50 in league history _ Scottie Pippen,
Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   By injury and insult, the Knicks did not have to play that
talent-loaded team on Tuesday night either. After what amounted to
a verbal food fight with Barkley, a disgruntled Pippen was traded
to Portland before the season. Then, the Rockets lost Olajuwon and
Barkley to injury.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Knicks playing a Rockets team that looked like a
car on blocks and short on parts. But they still had a team Knicks
Coach Jeff Van Gundy considered dangerous because of one simple
reason: the Rockets can run and push the ball, with rookie Steve
Francis providing the nudge.
</P>
<P>
   They can also shoot the 3-pointer, which allowed the Rockets to
stay within 48-45 of the Knicks at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Knicks had certain advantages. Ewing, for one. It was
as if he had taken a dip into a jar of wrinkle-free cream. He
looked 10 years younger and fresher as he posted up the chunky
Thomas Hamilton and arched shots over the reserve center, Kelvin
Cato. Ewing's 14-point first-quarter effort belied the struggles he
had in the two previous games of his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   After missing 14 shots in a row and only making 3 of his first
19 since returning to the team last Friday, Ewing began Tuesday
night's game by putting down 5 of his first 6 shots This wasn't the
same Ewing at all. His touch was soft, his movements were sharp and
his reflexes were quick enough to push the Knicks to a 28-23 lead
at the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks could not keep the momentum going, though. Their lazy
perimeter defense allowed the Rockets to close the gap on some
timely 3-point jumpers. Matt Bullard delivered back-to-back 3's _
one in front of Larry Johnson and another in front of Kurt Thomas _
to tie the game at 30-all with 4 minutes 29 seconds left in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A brief flurry by Houston ended the Rockets' run. Ewing, who
took a long breather after playing the entire first quarter, scored
just 2 more points before leaving the flo the Knicks ahead
at the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
