<SLUG> BC-NY-TRANSIT-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY, TRANSIT WORKERS DRAW CLOSER TO DEAL TO PREVENT STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for updated top and some rewriting. Lede backs off from
certainty of tentative agreement.) 
 (mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City's transit workers and the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority drew close to a deal Tuesday night on the
key issue of wages, union officials said, but the two sides were
still struggling over the final details of an agreement to head off
a strike Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   As a midnight deadline approached, several union officials said
a tentative pact had been reached that would cover the city's
33,000 subway and bus workers. But the president of Local 100 of
the Transport Workers Union, Willie James, said management was
still balking. ``We were very close to a deal, but management
backed off that deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the two sides were moving closer to an agreement
Tuesday, city officials warned of the possibility of disruptions
Wednesday from wildcat actions by disgruntled transit workers.
</P>
<P>
   City and state officials agreed Tuesday night that the MTA and
union sides were close to a deal, but it was not quite clinched.
Michael McKeon, a spokesman for Gov. George Pataki, said the
governor was heading from Albany to his New York City office to do
what he could to help resolve any loose ends in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides drew close to a deal on a day when James was under
intense pressure from a large dissident faction to take a tough
stance and from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to avoid a strike. The two
sides neared agreement on a day when a state judge issued two
orders threatening the union with draconian fines if it went on
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said leaders of the transit workers' union had provided
assurances that the union would not shut down New York City's
transit system Wednesday morning, although city officials were
preparing for possible rush hour chaos because of wildcat work
stoppages.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, an official close to the negotiations said that
the two sides had considerably narrowed their differences over
wages. This official said that the union had reduced its wage
demands to 5 percent a year over three years, down from its
previous demand for 9 percent a year. The MTA, this official said,
had raised its offer to 13 percent over four years, up from its
previous offer of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Calhoun, the union's secretary-treasurer, said Tuesday
night that the two sides were very close on wages, an issue that
both sides said would be the biggest hurdle to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, James and other leaders in Local 100 of the Transport
Workers Union had threatened a strike if they did not reach an
agreement with the MTA by 12:01 Wednesday morning, when the
contract expired.
</P>
<P>
   James sent a letter to all members Tuesday warning that the huge
fines that could be imposed from defying the judge's orders ``will
quickly bankrupt the union, making it unable to function on your
behalf.'' But the letter stopped short of saying that he would not
call for a strike.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with more than 1,500 union transit workers Tuesday
morning, Gil Rodriguez, a union vice president, urged the union
members to respect the court orders.
</P>
<P>
   At a City Hall news conference, Giuliani said the James letter
made clear that the union's leaders opposed a walkout, which would
be illegal under New York state's Taylor Law, which bars strikes by
transit workers and other public-sector employees.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani added that there was still a small chance that a
large dissident faction in the union could muster the votes to
authorize a strike, a move that could paralyze the city and create
havoc for 3.5 million people who use the mass transit system each
day.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a strike, Giuliani said that some parts of a
contingency plan to speed transportation into Manhattan would go
into effect Wednesday morning, and that the full plan, which would
restrict motor vehicle access, would be ready if needed. The city
has spent $3 million preparing for a strike.
</P>
<P>
   After four days of attacking the union, Giuliani escalated his
efforts Tuesday to pressure it not to strike. He had the city's
lawyers go to a judge's house shortly before 7 a.m. to obtain a
restraining order that calls for fining the union $1 million for
the first day of a strike, and $2 million for the second day,
doubling each successive day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-14-99 2358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
